<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0001 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8385 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-LAKERS-HNS &LR;      05-24 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-LAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Lakers are built on glitz and
high-profile glamour, but Sunday afternoon they went the way of all
flash.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Antonio Spurs completed their four-game sweep of the
Western Conference semifinals, pounding the Lakers 118-107 before
17,505 in the last game at the Great Western Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shut down the Forum, baby!'' shouted the Spurs' Mario Elie.
``That's all I wanted. We'll be the answer to a trivia question one
day: `Which team won the last game on the Forum floor?' It was the
Spurs, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, who move into the Staples Center next season, might
be the answer to another trivia question: ``What is perhaps the
most talented team not to win the NBA title in 1999?''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, baby. And that's just how the Lakers played much of
this season, like babies. Like immature children, the Lakers spent
most of the season refusing to play well together or share the
basketball. And like children to the end, they apparently were
anxious to get on with their summer vacation as soon as possible,
not even bothering to put up much of a fight Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs advance to the conference finals for the first time
since 1995 and will play the winner of the Utah-Portland series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as emotional as I was years ago (in 1995) in this
situation,'' said Avery Johnson, who finished with 19 points and 10
assists Sunday. ``It's good to go back, and I'm excited, but I'm
not as excited as I was a couple of years ago because that was my
first time (in the conference finals).
</P>
<P>
   ``But now the goals are a lot higher. We're thankful to be here,
but we have a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   As do the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence of three All-Star-caliber players _
Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Glen Rice _ the Lakers were swept
aside by the Spurs, who are all meat and potatoes _ or carne y
papas, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been so many great Lakers teams over the years, so
this is kind of sad in a way, too, that they won't be playing here
again,'' said the Spurs' Jerome Kersey, who scored all nine of his
points in the fourth quarter. ``There are a lot of ghosts here.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, and if you listen hard enough, beyond the pulsing Laker
Girl dance beats and the pounding O'Neal rap rhythms, you can
almost hear those spirits of Lakers past having a good, long laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers thought they had exorcised all those recent playoff
ghosts with a purge that began after getting swept by Utah in last
season's conference finals. Gone from that team _ which won 61
regular-season games _ are Nick Van Exel, Eddie Jones, Elden
Campbell and coach Del Harris, and they must be enjoying a good,
long laugh at the Lakers' expense.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps so is Dennis Rodman _ if he's even paying attention,
which he didn't do during his 23-game stint with the Lakers this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The home crowd made sure the Lakers remembered, taunting the
team with chants of ``Eddie, Eddie,'' recalling Jones, who, along
with Campbell, was dealt to Charlotte for Rice.
</P>
<P>
   All that maneuvering, and the Lakers still are reading headlines
that no doubt will scream, ``Four-gone conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   And those superstars were knocked out not only by Tim Duncan's
33 points and 14 rebounds, but by Jaren Jackson, who scored nine of
his 20 points in the fourth quarter, and Kersey's big final period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge team effort,'' Duncan said. ``People kept coming
off the bench and doing things for us that we needed them to do.
People just stepped into their roles and did the things that they
needed to do throughout the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers closed the third period with a 12-0 run that cut a
14-point San Antonio lead to 86-84 entering the final quarter. But
instead of staggering, the Spurs staged a clinic, scoring the first
13 points of the period, going ahead 99-84 with 8:26 remaining on
Jackson's 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   It was a jog to the finish line from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set a certain tone for this team all season,'' said David
Robinson, who had 12 points, seven rebounds and two blocks. ``It's
not luck. You just go out there and execute and get it done. But
that's the way we've been playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the game was close down the stretch, well, we've won
every close game down the stretch. You just believe in yourself,
and you begin to understand that we can win every one of these
games.''
</P>
<P>
   It's starting to look as though O'Neal is destined to lose every
one of these games. Sunday marked the fifth time in six playoff
seasons that O'Neal has been sent home via sweep, and he wasn't any
happier this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like feeling like this,'' said O'Neal, who finished
with 36 points and 14 rebounds but missed 11 of his 23 free throws.
``Right now, I'm very upset and very disappointed. It's very
embarrassing. Every time I get sent home, I get embarrassed. I hate
saying, `Well, we played hard.' No, now it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's over for the Lakers, and it was accomplished by a team
that was built, not bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``That feels great,'' said Elie of knocking off the Lakers'
high-priced talent. ``I thought (Spurs coach Gregg) Popovich did a
good job of putting the right guys here. I felt that with the
Spurs, it was never talent with them _ it was just the mental
(toughness). And he brought in some guys _ myself, Jerome Kersey
and Steve Kerr _ who have been here before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a special group here. These guys like each other. We
have no egos, and nobody worries about the stat sheet. Everybody
just worries about wins and losses on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder if the Lakers worry about the same things. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
