<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8400 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BLUEJAYS-B     05-24 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX STRIKE NICE BALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BLUE JAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ OK, it's a little early to put these Red Sox on a
pedestal. But you have to admit the Olde Towne Team earned some
bragging rights with series victories in the last six days over the
Yankees and Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox exploded for 13 hits Sunday at Fenway Park and
closed out a 5-1 homestand with a 10-8 victory and a sweep of a
youthful and talented Toronto team. Although he worked only six
innings, Pedro Martinez won his ninth game in 10 decisions as the
offense picked him up for a change.
</P>
<P>
   Boston won for the 14th time in its last 17 games with hitting,
pitching, and defense. Besides Martinez, Tom Gordon picked up his
50th straight save, and home runs by Damon Buford and Jason Varitek
accounted for four runs in the fifth inning to break a 3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez prevailed despite a shortened pitch count imposed by
the Red Sox (he threw 96). He allowed three runs on eight hits,
struck out six, and walked one. Manager Jimy Williams was tossed
from a game for the first time this season, but it didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well against two tough teams,'' said Williams. ``Of
course, we have a long way to go. We pitched good overall and we
played good defense. We got some timely hits. That's what it takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids compete good together. They pull for each other. It
really doesn't surprise me that Damon had the game he did today. Or
Trot Nixon or John Valentin had the games they had on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   It must have come as a surprise to a crowd of 28,559 that
Toronto was able to overcome deficits of 2-0 and 3-2 to tie
Martinez. Boston's ace had averaged 130 pitches in his previous
five starts and 10.8 strikeouts. So after the Sox took a 7-3 lead
in the fifth, they had Martinez work one more inning and turned it
over to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The pen struggled, but the Sox won anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't expect him to throw a shutout and strike out 15
hitters every game,'' said Williams. ``They have professional
hitters on the other side. We've asked Pedro to pitch a lot of
pitches in many consecutive starts. I think we got him under 100
this time. To me, it just tells you how good he is when he can go
out and compete like that and get a win.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Martinez's streak of at least one strikeout
in 33 consecutive innings was halted. The early exit cost him a
chance to extend his 10-plus strikeout streak to eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to give the team a chance to win,'' Martinez said.
``And today I did a little bit less than the other times and they
pulled it out. I wasn't struggling. They made some adjustments and
had some good at-bats. I still made some good pitches. I wasn't
concerned about the number of strikeouts I have in a game. I'd
rather get two ground balls and a popup. That'll help me somewhere
along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Buford's homer came off former Cy Young Award winner Pat Hentgen
(4-2) with two out in the fifth. Troy O'Leary hustled down the line
and just beat the throw on a hard grounder to third, a play on
which Toronto's Tony Fernandez was charged with an error. Mike
Stanley singled past short, then Buford jumped on an 0-1 fastball
for the homer to left and a 6-3 lead. Moments later, Varitek hit
homer No. 4 to put Boston ahead, 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox got three more runs in the eighth, but Toronto scored
two in the seventh and three in the ninth. The tying run was at the
plate when Gordon came on. Three pitches later, Homer Bush flied to
right and the Sox had a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to hit a home run,'' said Buford. ``There were
people on base and I just tried to drive in some runs. I'm just one
person. We have a lot of good players on the team. It's not
something we talk about as a team. But we know we've played well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good team,'' said Martinez. ``We're getting used to
winning and competing, doing the little things. That's going to
help us. I don't see any big hero. It's always somebody (different)
who sticks out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
