<HEADLINE>
LIGHTNING BOLT KILLS FIREFIGHTER IN OWN BACK YARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT   AND CHARLES F. BOSTWICK 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMDALE, Calif. _ A U.S. Forest Service firefighter was struck
and killed by lightning as a pair of rare spring thunderstorms
pummeled Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Culbertson, 47, was in the back yard of his home in
Palmdale, 62 miles north of downtown Los Angeles, about 7 a.m. when
lightning struck a nearby cottonwood tree. The bolt burned an
entrance hole into the man's shoulder, and left him with electrical
burns on his chest, back, side and arms, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was probably out there watching the lightning, but nobody
really knows,'' said Los Angeles County sheriff's Sgt. Steve
Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning bolts continued to strike nearby as paramedics worked
on the stricken man, who was moved into a garage and out of the
rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a couple strikes _ probably within 100 feet _ in some
of the vacant fields around there,'' firefighter-paramedic Scott
Clark said. ``He had a viable (heart) rhythm, but by the time we
got him to the hospital he was pronounced dead after about 10
minutes of them working him up.''
</P>
<P>
   The power-packed thunderstorms also knocked out electricity at
thousands of homes as they swept across Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The pair of storms rumbled out of the area's High Desert
beginning about 3 a.m. and rolled from the northeast to the
southwest and then off the coast.
</P>
<P>
   The rain contributed to more than 300 crashes on Southern
California highways Sunday morning, more than double the number
reported for the same period a day earlier, said Officer Frank
Sansone of the California Highway Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest rain was reported in Glendale, nine miles north of
downtown L.A., where 0.45 inch fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty unusual. We don't see them too often, especially
strong ones like these, over our area. These were pretty big
storms,'' said Stuart Seto, weather specialist for the National
Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the (spotters) said if you look at the calendar you
wouldn't think it was time for rain anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The storms were generated by a low-pressure area that moved west
from the California-Nevada border and became unstable, lifting
moisture and generating clouds and thunderstorms, Seto explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
