<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOVEL APPROACH BY KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Knicks aren't a soap opera. Uh-uh. They're a
full-blown Gothic novel.
</P>
<P>
   With eight games left in the regular season they were 21-21 and
in very legitimate danger of missing the playoffs. More than one
local scribe was suggesting that Latrell Sprewell was bored and
thoroughly disinterested. The coach was said to have the job
security of an Italian premier.
</P>
<P>
   Jump to the playoffs. If Allan Houston doesn't get the bounce of
his life last Sunday they would have lost to Miami and Jeff Van
Gundy would have been an ex-coach. But his last-second jumper hit
the rim, bounced up off the glass, and fell through the net. New
York 78, Miami 77. Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Where are we now? Well, we are, in all likelihood, one game away
from a sweep of the Atlanta Hawks. Next Sunday the Knicks will meet
the Pacers for the fifth year in a row, this time for the right to
represent the Eastern Conference in the NBA Finals. The Knicks made
it three straight Sunday with an authoritative 90-78 dispatch of
the outmanned Hawks. But was that _ is that _ the big story in New
York today? Noooo. That would be too simple.
</P>
<P>
   The story is that someone in a position to know has admitted
that stories Sunday claiming that the Knicks had been holding
secret talks with Phil Jackson before the season was over were
accurate. Madison Square Garden president Dave Checketts, a devout
Mormon, does not attend Sunday games, but MSG public relations
representative Barry Watkins confirmed that the Knicks had been
conversing with Jackson, Doc Rivers, and Dave Cowens, as well.
What? Whoopi Goldberg's not interested?
</P>
<P>
   All this raises Van Gundy to about an 11 on the sympathy meter,
at least in the eyes of the local media. The sad-eyed mentor, who
always has had major support within the team, now is being
portrayed in terms that would have made Mother Teresa blush. About
all this, he, of course, says nothing.
</P>
<P>
   But Lenny Wilkens wasn't afraid to speak up when asked what he
thought of the controversy swirling about his coaching rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he shouldn't worry about it,'' Wilkens said, ``and I
don't think he is. When your captain (Patrick Ewing) comes out and
says he's behind you 100 percent, you just go out and do your
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people are less forgiving. They want to know why it took
Van Gundy so long to recognize what Sprewell and Marcus Camby could
do for the team. These two have become The Story. When this pair
enters the game, everything changes. The Knicks get friskier,
quicker, more athletic, and more energetic. They actually become
something of a transition team (three straight second-period fast
breaks, if you can believe that). More importantly, they have
become a winning team.
</P>
<P>
   They are, at present, precisely the type of team departed
general manager Ernie Grunfeld hoped they'd be when he a) signed
Sprewell and b) traded Charles Oakley for Camby. But he lost his
power struggle with the coach, who was very cautious with Sprewell
and openly critical of Camby. Wherever Ernie is, and when last seen
he was scouting European talent, he must be smirking. The truth is
that he was right and the coach was wrong. Now he's out of a job he
has been proven to have done well and the coach looks secure.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happens when the ultimate stakes are a $1 million
net for every playoff home game. The suits get very itchy.
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly is going on here? How have the Knicks, almost a
textbook dysfunctional family with less than three weeks remaining
in the regular season, moved to within a game of the conference
final?
</P>
<P>
   ``We just started to play better,'' offered Van Gundy.
``Sometimes people try to make it more complex than it is. We've
become more unselfish. And, let's face it, we've had some breaks
along the way. If that ball had not bounded in last week, we
wouldn't be talking about this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I'm surprised,'' said backup center Chris Dudley,
whose 14 points and 12 rebounds were both playoff highs. ``But I
wouldn't have predicted it. We knew coming into the season that we
had talent. But, as you know, in the middle of the season we
weren't jelling. We had new faces. We had limited practice time.
Latrell was hurt in the beginning and couldn't practice. You just
didn't know when it was all going to click in.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were 21-21, we knew we had to win six of eight to make
the playoffs. We had a couple of days off, and we worked hard. We
won those six of eight, and that helped pull us together. That was
the beginning of our playoffs, and we've been playing well since
then.''
</P>
<P>
   At many junctures during the season people said this abundance
of talent thing was a myth. As Van Gundy pointed out Sunday, Ewing
hasn't been truly healthy for two years. Larry Johnson has been
transformed from a rugged low post player into a dainty spot-up
3-point shooter. Charlie Ward isn't very good, period. Houston and
Camby were said to be soft. Dudley is an offensive liability.
Sprewell didn't give a damn. Kurt Thomas was a flake. Chris Childs
was a $4-million-a-year backup. Have I left anyone out?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, Herb Williams is so old he gets a senior discount at
the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   And now? It's one-for-all and all-for-one. It's all lovey-dovey,
and can I open the door for you? The bench is now a huge asset, and
we're told it's all because they're such selfless people. ``The
four guys who come off the bench regularly (Sprewell, Camby,
Dudley, and Childs) have all sacrificed,'' Van Gundy said.
``They've all started in this league, and they're making huge
sacrifices.''
</P>
<P>
   Pass the Kleenex. What's happening is that in the short run the
Knicks are winning, and these people are (usually) keeping their
mouths shut. Fine. But this is New York, and this is corporate
America, and you never know where and when you need the pooper
scooper. How convenient that double Oscar winner William Goldman
sits right behind the basket. Watching this team should keep him in
screenplay ideas for the next 10 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 0024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
