<HEADER>
A8403 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HOLLEYCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-24 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGING PRAISES OF BIRD 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Larry Bird is unlike any coach in the NBA. That's
not to say he is the best. He's just different. There are many
reasons for that. One of them has to do with a word that will cause
any coach to rant. We are talking about ``distractions.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as Bird remains in Indiana and has ``Coach'' before his
name, he never will have to worry about distractions. Ever. That's
why it shouldn't be surprising that his Pacers are undefeated in
the playoffs _ 7-0 _ after Sunday's 89-86 Eastern Conference
semifinal win over the 76ers. The Sixers have existed for 36 years
and never had been swept out of a seven-game series. If they want
to talk with a peer group about their historic problems, they can
call the Bucks, who also were swept by the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Bird has the Pacers thinking and winning like no other team in
the franchise's 23-year history. This is the first time the Pacers
have won seven straight playoff games. It is the first time they
truly believe they belong in the Finals, rather than the
(conference) finals. Bird is constantly putting things in
perspective for his players, even when he isn't directly speaking
to them.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, a reporter asked Bird about Reggie Miller's
focus. Bird said that his shooting guard was special. The
questioner, obviously not having a good mental day, asked the coach
if he ever has seen a player focus like Miller. That's crazy, isn't
it? Bird easily could have said, ``Yep. I look at him in the mirror
every day.'' He didn't. He paused long enough for the obvious to
emerge.
</P>
<P>
   If you are enjoying this rare Bird, I would advise you to tape
the Pacers' remaining playoff games and freeze these memories. If
this team wins the NBA title, I am convinced that Bird will walk
away, peacefully, from coaching. Forget about the three-year
contract he signed in 1997. He can stay with the Pacers, in any
capacity, as long as he wants. But it is obvious that all he wants
to do is win one championship. With no distractions, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked us last year if we wanted him to come back,'' Antonio
Davis said Sunday. ``We looked at him like he was crazy and said,
`Yeah we want you to come back. We want you to lead us one more
time and see if we can win a championship.' ''
</P>
<P>
   They have made it clear that they like the way he leads. They
like the fact that he can talk basketball with Pat Riley, Jerry
Sloan, and Chuck Daly. They also like it that he could stop talking
and take all of those coaches to any of the nation's asphalt hoop
courts and dominate them in a pickup game. Even more important, if
all the league's coaches went on a silent retreat, you can be sure
Bird would be the last one to speak.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers went through an awful, 10-minute scoring drought in
the third and fourth quarters Sunday. They watched their 12-point
lead with two minutes left in the third become a 1-point deficit
with two minutes to play. The 20,844 fans here sensed a win. Bird
didn't. He may be from Indiana, but he didn't want to go back there
for a fifth game. So what if the Pacers probably would have gone on
to win the series, four games to one? Another game would have meant
another round of practices, another round of interviews, and
another delay in what the Pacers ultimately want. Those, friends,
are also known as distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really not a hollerer or a screamer,'' said Mark Jackson,
who had 14 points and 13 assists Sunday. ``A lot of coaches _ with
the fourth quarter the Sixers put on _ probably would have called
12 timeouts and cursed us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird talked strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have to be screaming all the time,'' Chris Mullin
said. ``It may be a little different style than what guys are used
to, but it's probably more effective. Larry was like that as a
player. He wasn't always a guy you heard in the paper, but I know
he was a guy you heard in practice. He talked to you through
action, by busting your butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, I have no problem telling you that when I look at the
Pacers on paper, there is no excitement. Miller is a great shooter.
Jackson makes terrific passes. The people who are supposed to
rebound usually do it. But the only sexy thing about this team is
that 7-0 playoff record.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at us and it's pretty much like that girl at the club
who doesn't look good initially, but does at about 2, 3 in the
morning,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   A fashion editor from GQ magazine is not going to call the
Pacers Tuesday and ask for a player to be part of a photo shoot.
Sunday, Rik Smits stepped on the court with knee-high black socks.
You haven't seen anti-fashion until you've seen a 7-foot-4-inch man
in shorts with black socks pulled to his knees. You won't see many
Pacers on MTV or BET. Travis Best and Miller had roles in Spike
Lee's ``He Got Game,'' but they had minimal parts.
</P>
<P>
   Bird and his team share the same basketball soul. They speak
only when necessary. As straightforward as Bird has been during
these playoffs, I have a feeling he will have a lot of interesting
things to say when his book, ``Bird Watching'' _ authored by former
Globe writer Jackie MacMullan _ is released in September. Certain
members of the Celtics' organization (are you reading this, Paul
Gaston?) should be nervous about the book's contents.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Pacers, they answer all criticisms about their style
by winning. If they beat the Knicks in the conference finals, they
will set a franchise record for playoff wins (11). Sunday, the
chalkboard in their locker room read ``NEXT!!!'' Beneath it,
someone wrote, ``8 Mo','' a reference to the number of wins they
need for a title. Before they left the court, they caught the
glimmer of Ron Harper's championship ring. The Bull was sitting
near their bench. A fan asked, ``Ron, can I see your ring?'' Harper
held up his hand and said of the Pacers, ``I don't know who will
win the championship, but they should.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, we'll be talking about former Pacers coach
Larry Bird.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 0025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
