<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8404 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-GIANTS-HNS     05-24 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-GIANTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN FRANCISCO _ Jeff Bagwell should come with a warning label:
Handle with care.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe that would have kept rookie reliever Joe Nathan from
setting off an explosion Sunday at 3Com Park. Bagwell's three-run
homer in the seventh inning broke open a tie game and sent the
Astros on their way to a 4-1 victory over the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's blast provided the requisite run support for Jose Lima
to become the National League's first eight-game winner. It also
kept the Astros from getting swept in the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess this is why they say baseball is a funny game,'' said
Bagwell, who was 1-for-4. ``I had a really bad day and basically
(was) hurting our club. I guess you can say I'm relieved to be
having the day I was having and end up hitting a three-run homer in
a game we win 4-1.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his clutch homer, it was clear Bagwell wasn't satisfied
with his performance _ particularly the fact he failed twice with
runners in scoring position and less than two out.
</P>
<P>
   But that was an aberration. Bagwell has been money with runners
in scoring position, hitting .362 in those situations this year. He
has 44 RBIs in the Astros' 42 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were 3-3 on the road trip, but it is scary to think
where they might have been without Bagwell, who hit .400 and drove
in nine of the Astros' 25 runs on the six-game jaunt to Los Angeles
and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Lima extended his major-league-best winning streak to eight
games and improved to 24-9 since Astros manager Larry Dierker put
him into the starting rotation last season. The Astros have a .690
winning percentage in games started by Lima over the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old righthander has evolved into quite a pitcher
since his days with the Detroit Tigers, with whom he was 8-16.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Houston Astros got kind of a find when they brought Jose
Lima into the organization,'' Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Lima has become the closest thing to a sure win that the Astros
have.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest difference in what has happened to me is that they
gave me opportunity,'' Lima said. ``I got a chance, bro. That's the
biggest difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima made sure the Giants didn't have a chance. After giving up
a leadoff homer to Marvin Benard in the first inning, Lima allowed
only one runner to reach scoring position for the remainder of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Lima retired 11 of the last 14 batters he faced, and Billy
Wagner pitched a scoreless ninth inning for his 12th save. It was
Wagner's first save since May 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really needed to get this win,'' said Astros second baseman
Craig Biggio, who hit his National League-leading 19th double in
the game. ``We had some tough games on this trip, and we haven't
always had the best of luck on the West Coast. Any time we can go
3-3 on this trip, I'll take that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros drew six walks in the game, none more crucial than
the back-to-back free passes Nathan issued to Lima and Biggio to
start the seventh inning. After Nathan struck out Russ Johnson,
Bagwell took him to a 3-2 count. Instead of pitching around Bagwell
_ Derek Bell (0-for-4) was on deck _ Nathan decided to challenge
the Astros slugger.
</P>
<P>
   As Bagwell's Astrodome theme music says: ``Tick, tick, tick,
tick _ boom!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at 3-2 three times before that,'' Bagwell said. ``I
struck out twice and walked. If the guy pitches around me and walks
me, it's bases loaded with one out. Nathan throws 95, 96 mph. When
you throw that hard, you challenge people.''
</P>
<P>
   Benard's homer was the second Lima had allowed in a span of
three innings, dating to his last start. Prior to that, Lima had
pitched 37 innings without allowing a home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lima got the best of us today,'' Giants manager Dusty Baker
said. ``He wasn't 7-1 for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros put runners in scoring position with fewer than two
outs in each of the first three innings, but Giants starter Shawn
Estes held them off each time. Estes retired seven consecutive
batters at one point but found himself in trouble again in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Bagwell drew back-to-back walks to lead off the
inning, and Johnson scored from second on Richard Hidalgo's
broken-bat single over shortstop Rich Aurilia's head. It was a
breakthrough hit for Hidalgo, who had not driven in a run since May
12.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros tied the score but missed a chance to claim the lead
after Estes walked Carl Everett to load the bases with one out.
Baker signaled reliever Jerry Spradlin into the game, and the
hard-throwing righthander proceeded to strike out Tony Eusebio and
coaxed a weak liner from Tim Bogar to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Giants, that was the last bullet they
would dodge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
