<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-GALAXY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY'S STARS PROVE TOO MUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ If Major League Soccer expects to survive, it
will have to do better than this. The Los Angeles Galaxy continued
to struggle offensively and at the gate, but performed well enough
to take a 1-0 win over the Revolution Sunday &UR;  &LR; night before an
announced crowd of 7,581 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere around a Galaxy game has changed drastically as
the team has discarded Hispanic stars, and its attack has
floundered. The relationship between the Galaxy and fans seems to
have been critically altered, and the attendance was so small that
the spectators could not possibly hope to duplicate the festive
feeling of previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
   They did cheer the third-minute goal by Steve Jolley, who was
unmarked as he headed in a corner, but the stadium soon became
eerily silent.
</P>
<P>
   After the goal, the Galaxy retreated into a defensive posture, a
tactically-sound maneuver but hardly exhilarating for spectators.
</P>
<P>
   And the Revolution, though hobbled by injuries, displayed some
spirit but no scoring touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We created enough chances to win the game,'' Revolution
midfielder John Harkes said. ``But we are giving up early goals,
and we've got to eliminate that straight away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not discouraging, because we didn't lose in the run of
play. We have to take responsibility for what happens because we
are letting in too many easy goals. But we understand what the
problem is. If we had lost by three or four goals, then we would
have a problem. We can build on this for the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkes, recovering from a sprained right knee, made his first
Revolution start since joining the team from D.C. United via
Nottingham Forest in England. He engaged in a spirited midfield
battle with the Galaxy's Mauricio Cienfuegos and directed the
Revolution offense.
</P>
<P>
   But Harkes tired in his first full game in three months, both
defender Richard Goulooze (calf cramps) and midfielder Jair (back
strain) departed in the first half, and defender Dan Calichman
(shin bruise) limped through the second half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
