<HEADLINE>
BUFORD PROVIDES A LITTLE THUNDER 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BUFORD-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mother Nature provided the rain that fell softly on
Fenway Park Sunday afternoon, leaving it up to Red Sox center
fielder Damon Buford to chip in with the lightning.
</P>
<P>
   The bolt off Buford's bat _ a 374-foot three-run job off Toronto
starter and loser Pat Hentgen _ came in the fifth inning, breaking
a 3-3 tie and giving the Red Sox a lead they never quite would
relinquish en route to a 10-8 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Buford, who went 1 for 4, also had a second-inning sacrifice fly
and his four runs batted in equaled a personal best for the former
Oriole, Met, and Ranger, who hit a career-high 10 homers last
season for Boston but waited until Sunday to connect for his first
of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not bad,'' said Buford with a smile and a shake of the head.
``One home run in 100 at-bats (the total when he came to the plate
was actually 93). ``Seriously, you don't want to wait too long for
that first one, so it felt good. I knew it was gone. Now I don't
have to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Buford was aware of the stiff wind that was blowing from right
field to left and he also was aware that Hentgen was one pitch away
from being in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to think of the situation and what he might
throw,'' said Buford. ``Playing in center field, I knew the rain
was coming in behind me, but the wind was blowing out. I mean, I'm
not a weatherman, but I could tell a storm was coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Hentgen hadn't exactly owned Buford before Sunday. Buford, who
had four RBIs against the Blue Jays last July 23, had been 4 for 9
(.444) with a home run and a pair of walks in their previous
confrontations and while Hentgen struck him out with one out and a
man on in the fourth, Buford broke open the game an inning later.
</P>
<P>
   And don't let that 1 for 4 fool you.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of swinging for the Green Monster in the seventh,
Buford, with Mike Stanley on base with a leadoff double, did his
job by hitting a grounder to the right side, advancing Stanley to
third. While Boston didn't take advantage of the situation, Buford
had executed a fundamental play to go along with his sacrifice fly
and homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had some quality at-bats,'' said manager Jimy Williams.
``Plus the big hit.''
</P>
<P>
   It all added up to what Buford termed, ``a real good day. Pedro
(Martinez) didn't look like he had his best stuff, but he went six
for us and gave us another quality start and that's all you can
ask. He's been picking up the team every time he pitches, so today
it was a good time for the offense to help pick him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Buford, who has been encouraged by Williams and hitting coach
Jim Rice to hit to all fields since his arrival last season, has
taken the cue. He had a 10-game hitting streak earlier this season
(14 for 41, .341) that ended May 9 and has been getting more
playing time against righthanded pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   There was never a question, however, about his defense. Buford
is tied for the team lead in outfield assists (3), with two of them
leading to double plays.
</P>
<P>
   And he nearly made the defensive play of the day Sunday when he
raced to the warning track in a vain effort to haul in former Red
Sox farmhand Pat Lennon's two-out double that just eluded his lunge
in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I got there,'' said Buford, who is batting .281.
``When I went to stab at it, I just missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   But when it came to that Hentgen pitch in the fifth, Buford made
no mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hung the pitch and I just got good wood on it,'' said
Buford. ``I'm sure he'd like that one back.''
</P>
<P>
   But on a day when the Red Sox needed every run they could
muster, Buford and his teammates were happy to take the home run
and not look back as they headed for New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
