<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-LEGISLATURE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TEXAS HOUSE PASSES BILL TO INCREASE PAY OF TEACHERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By JOHN W. GONZALEZ
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After one of the longest debates of the year,
the Texas House late Sunday approved a $3.8 billion school finance
plan for 2000-2001 that would increase every public school
teacher's pay by $3,000 a year while requiring all school districts
to reduce their property tax rates slightly.
</P>
<P>
   The 150-member body tentatively approved the bill without major
changes on a voice vote. Yet, member after member had attempted to
use the funding proposal as a vehicle to keep afloat dozens of
other education initiatives dealing with testing, benefits, class
size and taxation.
</P>
<P>
   One concept that could have prolonged the dialogue _ state-paid
vouchers for private school students _ was not pursued. Advocates
determined that floor support was insufficient to win approval of
even a pilot voucher program.
</P>
<P>
   The version of Senate Bill 4 that the full House approved was
close to the version that the House Committee on Public Education
had approved.
</P>
<P>
   The House committee had totally revamped the Senate-approved
bill that Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, had sponsored. The
Senate-approved bill had sought to boost teacher compensation by
focusing on retirement and other benefits, thus allowing districts
to contemplate reducing their tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   House members dumped the Senate plan out of fear that districts
would choose not to reduce tax rates, even if their income was
boosted by state contributions for retirement programs. The plan
the House was considering would send the $3,000 directly to
full-time teachers, counselors and nurses, while forcing districts
to reduce tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not control local tax rates, nor do we control the value
of property. But what we can do is control the amount of money
available to drive down tax rates,'' said House Education Committee
Chairman Paul Sadler, D-Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   He said the pay raise, while not everything that teachers
deserve, was the Legislature's long-overdue effort to recognize
their hard work. The last across-the-board pay raise for teachers
was in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, Senate Bill 4 recognizes the efforts of
our teaching professionals over the last decade in improving our
classroom performance _ including our student performance _ student
by student, classroom by classroom, campus by campus, throughout
this state,'' Sadler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It adopts a $3,000 pay increase for every single teacher in
every single district,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which requires a final vote today before returning to
the Senate, also provides money to curtail social promotions and
improve Head Start, prekindergarten, kindergarten and 9th-grade
learning programs.
</P>
<P>
   The tax relief element would produce an average property tax
reduction of 6 cents per $100 in valuation. In the Houston
Independent School District, for example, the tax rate would drop
from $1.49 per $100 in valuation to $1.43. State financial analysts
estimate that the local tax relief generated by the bill would
approach $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Before debate on the funding proposal began, the House finished
work on a measure that rewrites Texas' open records law to make it
easier for the public to obtain government documents. Senate Bill
1851 by Sen. Jeff Wentworth, R-San Antonio, was returned to the
Senate for further consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The open records bill would streamline the process that the
attorney general must follow to decide whether a governmental body
must grant an open records request.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than having 60 days to decide, the attorney general would
have 45 days. Limits on the types of financial information that
could be withheld were narrowed.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also provides for posting of notices to help the
public understand their right to information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
