<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-76ERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS TIDY THINGS UP WITH SWEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The 76ers have a team meeting Monday at 1. Before
they attend, they should announce the ban of one literary item.
It's called a stat sheet. In some communities, such a ban would be
seen as censorship. Not here. What we are talking about is
self-preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's not to say the fourth and final game of their
best-of-seven series with the Pacers was not close. Indiana won,
89-86, at the First Union Center, to advance to the Eastern
Conference final against the Knicks or Hawks (New York leads, three
games to none).
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers erased a 17-point first-quarter deficit and had a
chance to win in the final minute. They won't know what an
opportunity they missed until they look at the stat sheet. That's
because late in the third quarter and for most of the fourth, the
Pacers couldn't make a shot. That's not an exaggeration. For 10
minutes, the Pacers did not make a field goal. They missed 13
straight.
</P>
<P>
   Pacers coach Larry Bird was asked how many games you can win
with droughts like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not very many,'' he said of the dry spell that began with 2:12
remaining in the third and ended with 2:02 left in the game. Bird
added, ``We got absolutely nothing out of our second unit. The
second unit let a good lead evaporate and eventually Philly went up
by 4 (83-79). The starters played well all game long.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird's team is 7-0 in the playoffs for a reason. It knows how to
win. It had a 12-point lead when the drought began and trailed,
83-82, when it ended.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers certainly didn't punish Indiana for not being able to
score. When the game was over, someone asked Philly's Allen Iverson
(25 points) if Rik Smits fouled him with 41 seconds left. He said
yes. He also said, ``But it shouldn't have come down to all that.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. The Sixers got their 4-point lead when Matt Geiger
hit a short baseline jumper over Smits with 3:17 to play. But then
they got silly. Point guard Eric Snow threw the ball away on
consecutive possessions, the last of which led to a Chris Mullin
drought-snapping 3-pointer. After Iverson missed a jumper, Reggie
Miller made a difficult, 15-foot runner with 1:31 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to pull up for a three,'' said Miller, who finished
with 23 points, ``but I had missed two in a row and you have to
know clock and score.''
</P>
<P>
   That would have been good advice for Snow. Not known as a great
shooter, Snow pulled up for a 26-footer. Fifteen seconds remained
on the shot clock. Snow's shot wasn't even close. Smits followed
the miss with a layup and the Pacers would not trail again. The
game was over and the 20,844 fans here knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People knew it was over, but no one left,'' Iverson said of
the Philly fans. ``It means so much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers, who lost 51 games a year ago, have excited this town
again. But now they and their rejuvenated fans will not be able to
play again until next season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's sweep made history. It is the first time any Sixers
team has been swept in a seven-game series . . . Jalen Rose was a
miserable 1 of 11 from the field. ``It was probably the worst game
he's played all year,'' Bird said . . . Sixers president Pat Croce
reminisced about '97 when, ``I went after Rick Pitino real hard
during March Madness.'' Croce also pursued Phil Jackson and Larry
Brown. He settled for Brown when he couldn't land Jackson and ``it
looked obvious that Rick was leaning toward Boston or staying in
Kentucky.'' He said he's glad he chose Brown. ``God works in
mysterious ways,'' he said. ``It was a blessing that we got
Larry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
