<HEADER>
A8416 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-BOS &LR;      05-24 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NY DOES BENCH PRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fact: It's over. Formality: It can't end until Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, the Atlanta Hawks could pull themselves together and
somehow avert a sweep at the hands of the New York Knicks. And
someone from ``Save Fenway'' will be invited to throw out the first
pitch in the new ballpark four years hence.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-0 series lead is a submission hold in the NBA, and that's
what the Knicks have on the Hawks following Sunday's convincing
90-78 triumph at Madison Square Garden. Before this messy thing was
over the crowd was calling for both the sweep and geriatric center
Herb Williams. They also were saluting that well-known scoring
machine Chris Dudley, who fouled out with 1:06 remaining to a
standing ovation after playing the best playoff game of his career
(14 points, 12 rebounds).
</P>
<P>
   With Indiana already into an Eastern Conference final that will
begin Sunday, the Knicks would like to avoid a Game 5 by wrapping
up the series Monday night. ``We don't want to return to Atlanta
and allow Indiana to have all that rest while we're in a war,''
Dudley said.
</P>
<P>
   A what? The closest Atlanta got in the final 23 minutes was 9.
The Hawks shot 31 percent for the game and 21 percent for the
second half. If this was war, it was the USA vs. the Grand Duchy of
Fenwick.
</P>
<P>
   ``One problem we've had in the whole series is that we haven't
shot well,'' lamented Atlanta coach Lenny Wilkens. ``It's hard to
win when you're shooting in the 30s. The low 30s.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks followed their new game plan perfectly. In other
words, they constructed an early lead and then called on the firm
of Sprewell &AMP; Camby to put the game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell and Marcus entered the game in tandem with the Knicks
leading, 15-12. They proceeded to score 20 of the next 28 New York
points. Sprewell hit his jumper _ Steve Smith simply could not stay
with him _ and Camby rammed home second shots and easy post flips.
In the second half, Camby teamed with Dudley to control the inside,
allowing the hobbled Patrick Ewing (24 painful minutes) to spectate
in peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two guys who hurt us were Camby and Sprewell,'' confirmed
Wilkens. ``When they come in they are fresh. Without (the injured)
Laphonso Ellis and Alan Henderson, we can't replace Grant Long, and
we have no answer for Camby.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta hung around for a half like some sort of Loyal
Opposition whose sole function is to dignify the system (think
Massachusetts Republicans). But the Hawks only scored 24 points in
the first 26 minutes of the second half, by which time the Knicks
had a 76-60 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It's over, of course, but New York coach Jeff Van Gundy can't
say that. ``I'm just worried about getting one more win in this
series,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If that's really true, he's the only one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
