A8421 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-BOS &LR;      05-24 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA SEEKS TRINIDAD 
</HEADLINE>
 LA HOYA-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Oscar De La Hoya wants more knockouts. Felix
Trinidad wants more money. They both may find what they're looking
for Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   A newly, and at times unwisely, more aggressive De La Hoya
emerged Saturday night in his 19th title fight, a defense of the
World Boxing Council welterweight championship that ended with De
La Hoya knocking out game Oba Carr with a long left hook that
exploded off the challenger's face and sent him spinning like a
felled tree to the floor moments into the 11th round.
</P>
<P>
   When Carr whirled sideways and then backward before falling
face-first to the canvas, it was evident he was destined to fight
no more this night, which he did not after getting up on legs so
wobbly that referee Richard Steele immediately stopped the bout at
the 55-second mark to give De La Hoya his 31st win without defeat
and the knockout he said had been his goal.
</P>
<P>
   While Carr was falling in Las Vegas, International Boxing
Federation welterweight champion Trinidad's father, Felix Sr., and
promoter Don King were fighting in Puerto Rico. The issue was
whether a purse offer of $10.5 million guaranteed plus a
well-hidden $500,000 and an upside of pay-per-view sales was enough
to match the IBF champion with De La Hoya this fall at the same
Mandalay Bay Events Center where Carr was sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   Logic and business sense tell King, Trinidad's promoter, the
deal is a good one. As good, in fact, as it gets for Trinidad, who
until he made $3 million to fight Pernell Whitaker in his last
fight never had earned more than $1 million from King.
</P>
<P>
   But Trinidad's father, who long has been at odds with King,
claims the deal he rejected last week stood to pay his son $8
million and King $2 million and the additional $500,000 that came
in a later counteroffer was all going to the promoter under the
present terms. Bob Arum, De La Hoya's promoter and the lead man in
the negotiations, insisted that was inaccurate and the deal would
be worked out because ``King and I have a signed deal. The rest of
them are just fighting. It'll work out.''
</P>
<P>
   That's probably so, in part because of Carr's courageous outing
against De La Hoya. While Trinidad knocked Carr out in eight rounds
after Carr dropped him early when they met several years ago, De La
Hoya nearly was taken the distance by Carr and ended up with a
split left cheek (the result of an intentional head butt, according
to Steele), sprained left hand, and swollen left eye before he
finished off Carr.
</P>
<P>
   So the Trinidad camp may have taken some solace in what it saw
Saturday night, believing its power puncher can get to De La Hoya
with lead right hands and left hooks more consistently than Carr
did, and with far more power. If they do believe it, they will grab
the money on the table and forget arguing for $8 per home for every
pay-per-view sale over 850,000, as Trinidad's father was demanding
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The original deal agreed to by Arum and King called for Trinidad
to receive $10 million guaranteed plus $6 per home for every sale
over the first million. Since De La Hoya never had topped 760,000
that seemed a bit much, but Arum argued if Trinidad wanted a
smaller guarantee he would get more of the upside. But Trinidad's
father always has favored guarantees over possible pay-per-view
sales and seldom looked for opponents who might pressure his son,
which is why some people believe he would rather see this deal go
away despite the huge pot of gold if he takes it and the larger one
later if his son wins.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, Trinidad's signature on the contract seems
as inevitable as Carr's back on the floor Saturday night because of
the numbers De La Hoya can write into an opponent's contract.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya gets what he wants because he can pay what you want
and what he wants now is a unification fight with Trinidad that
would cement him as the best welterweight of his era and allow him
to move on to the 154-pound division to create another
mega-millions fight with another former Olympic gold medalist,
World Boxing Association champion David Reid.
</P>
<P>
   First, however, De La Hoya must survive this new ``style'' he
revealed against Carr. In the opening minutes it was indeed a more
stalking, aggressive, pressure-creating attack that overwhelmed
Carr with hand speed and power. But after he dropped Carr for the
first time with a left hook after having wobbled him with a jab, De
La Hoya seemed to drift off into an unfocused approach that was
sometimes warrior and other times waltzer.
</P>
<P>
   That still allowed him to dominate Carr for most, but not all,
of the night. But it left co-trainer Gil Clancy wondering when his
young fighter would simply go fight, because when he does, Clancy
believes, guys like Oba Carr go away quickly and guys like Felix
Trinidad go, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He convinced himself what he would do and he did it in the
first round,'' Clancy said. ``Then he stopped. It becomes a chess
match with him instead of a fight when all he has to do is fight
because his hand speed is so much faster (than his opponents) and
he punches so hard he can get you out at any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single round he opened up against (former WBA champion
Ike) Quartey he won the round. You need a psychiatrist to figure
out why (he doesn't always do that). When I had Emile Griffith I
was happy when he got hit with a good shot early in a round. Then
he'd go kill the guy. Who knows why?''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy believes if De La Hoya approaches Trinidad throughout
their fight the way he did the first and last round of the Carr
bout, the outcome will be clear and quick, because just like De La
Hoya beat Trinidad to the negotiating table to sign a contract he
also will beat him to the punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felix is a bomber, so the idea is to hit him before he hits
you,'' Clancy said. ``He's not a puzzle. Trinidad is very
dangerous, but he's a little slower than Oscar.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Trinidad has been slow to sign to fight De La Hoya. If
that difference in hand speed between them follows each into the
ring Sept. 18, Oba Carr won't be the only guy Oscar De La Hoya has
knocked to the floor at the Mandalay Bay Events Center, just the
first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
