A8423 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-SOCAL-2Takes     05-24 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-SOCAL-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVAR REFUGEES SAMPLE CALIFORNIA LIVIN'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE AND ROBERT MONROE 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They fled from explosions, executions and the
politics of war in the poorest region of Europe. They set foot in a
new world last week, thousands of miles away from the horrors they
left behind in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And by Sunday, the grim faces of 28 Albanian refugees
transplanted to Los Angeles took new form as their first weekend in
America came to a close. Their memories of ruin seemed to wash away
in the excitement of discovery and adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   Their excitement came from beaches, the desert, buffet lines,
grocery stores, movie houses and tourist spots. They took crash
courses in using microwaves and washing machines. With the help of
homemade language charts, they did their best to communicate with
their host families.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've been beyond Serbia,'' 55-year-old
Nuhi Vlashi said through an interpreter. His family of eight has
taken up residence at a host home in Simi Valley in neighborning
Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the men have traveled, but nowhere as far as America.
It's nice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, the Vlashis, staying with Lloyd and Joan
Martin, woke to a breakfast of banana nut bread baked by the
Martins' neighbor. The Martins took four of the Vlashis' six
children to their Catholic church, but the children, Muslims, chose
not to go inside. They waited in the car.
</P>
<P>
   By 10:30 a.m., Almas Rexhepi, who had helped translate for the
Martins and their guests, brought doughnuts and told them about
their uniquely Southern Californian next destination.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, the two families were piling out of the Martins' Ford
Explorer at Malibu's Zuma Beach.
</P>
<P>
   For the Vlashis, the experience of sand between their toes and
the sight of eight-foot waves crashing before them was as foreign
as their host country. Rexhepi didn't come along to translate for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on our own,'' Lloyd Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Nuhi Vlashi and his wife, Muradja, walked with care toward the
ocean. But their children had already made a beeline toward the
surf, their faces fixed in awed smiles. The mushy sand moistened by
the tide is easy to write in, daughter Emrije, 22, discovered. She
wrote the word ``Kosovo'' in it with her finger. The tide washed it
away. She wrote it again.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Martin stayed with the parents while the children threw a
football among themselves _ underhand and sidearm despite Lloyd's
example. Lloyd showed them how a Boogie Board works. The Vlashis
cheered when daughter Mirvete caught a small wave. Lloyd held the
13-year-old aloft in his arms, jumping just as a wave splashed past
them.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Martin has been trying to gauge what food the Vlashis like.
Definitely Cheerios. Absolutely not pork. Eggs, maybe some other
time. The Martins have hosted nine foreign exchange students over
the past 22 years, but never a family. After two days, she
concluded that some things are universal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They act out. They fight. They talk. They're a normal
family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Martin was learning about Albanian culture as fast as
Emrije, the second-eldest daughter, and Sufete, the Vlashi's
12-year-old son, picked up English words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people here think they're pretty primitive,'' said
Lloyd Martin, gesturing toward the Vlashi children. ``They have
extreme respect for their parents, but we've advanced way past
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The two families communicated without their English-to-Albanian
language chart. It took work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Want a towel to dry off, dear?'' Joan asked Mirvete as she
returned dripping from the ocean. Mirvete grabbed a jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Towel? No?'' said Joan, her voice trailing off.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Martin said he prefers excursions to natural places like
the beach though he and Joan might take Knott's Berry Farm up on an
offer of free tickets for their guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have mixed feelings about Knott's Berry Farm and
Disneyland,'' he said. ``It's our American version of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Vlashi children had jumped into the white Ford
Explorer and set off on an adventure to Vasquez Rocks with Lloyd
Martin behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ate pancakes this morning before we left. I think they
liked them,'' Joan Martin said, describing how they experimented
with syrup. ``Maybe we'll try to find an Albanian restaurant for
them in the San Fernando Valley. That would be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Once inside the park, the six youths jumped out of the Explorer
and stood on the running boards and bumpers, riding outside the
vehicle as they drove toward Vasquez Rocks' famous peak _ most of
them in the same clothes they wore as they stepped off the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Martin stepped out of the car, pointed to the peak, and within
120 seconds the group scaled their way to the top, barely stopping
to take a breath.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar with the terrain, their clunky heels and Nike tennis
shoes with two-inch soles didn't hold them back.
</P>
<P>
   They posed for photos. They waved to passers-by. They laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Sufete Vlashi rested his head in his arms and began to cry. His
sister Nurije, 24, wrapped her arms around him and gave him
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' Emrije Vlashi, 22, said in broken English as
they descended.
</P>
<P>
   How about the food? American lifestyle?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very good. We like (it),'' Emrije said, referring to her
English-to-Albanian language chart.
</P>
<P>
   Next on the agenda was a trip to Barstow, where Lloyd Martin
would introduce them to his father. Then dinner _ at Denny's.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way they can see the pictures of the food,'' Joan Martin
joked.
</P>
<P>
   Rexhepi, one of the only Albanian immigrants living in Simi
Valley, had met the Vlashis after they arrived and greeted them
with hugs and comfort, being the only local who can speak the
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see them happy. They seem well,'' Rexhepi said.
``I ask myself: What have these people done to deserve this? This
war is all about greed, about men who are not satisfied with what
God gave them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at them now. They have some peace.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the refugees now in Los Angeles are extended relatives of
Hajrush Vlashi and his wife, Renee, of suburban West Hills. They
sponsored their family members as immigrants and, with the help of
the Valley Jewish Federation, were able to rescue them from the
war-torn Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Six families agreed to house Vlashi's relatives for several
weeks. Four other family members remain in Macedonia and were
expected to arrive later.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the refugees have said they are enjoying their
time in America, most hope to return to Kosovo when the conflict
ends. The Federation plans to move the refugees into their own
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Federation spokeswoman Bonnie Somers said Sunday that the
organization has established a fund for the refugees. The Kosovar
Refugee Resettlement Fund will pay for security deposits on
apartments and other necessities incurred as the refugees establish
their own residences in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
