u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYCLING-ATLANTICCUP-B     05-24 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYCLING-ATLANTIC </SLUG>
 CUP-BOS  
 McCORMACK RIDES ON  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ There's no way a bicycle race with more than
100 riders should give anyone a home advantage. But try telling
that to Mark McCormack of North Easton, who Sunday came from the
middle of the pack to bolt to a sprint finish win in the sixth and
final day of the Atlantic Cup Classic in Harvard Square. Last fall
he was another local hero when he won the national cyclocross
championship at Devens.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Monahan, a top category amateur racer from Wyckoff, N.J.,
defended his title as overall winner in the series. He won only one
of the races, but placed in the top four every day and took home
$500 as overall winner, plus another $1,500 for his finishes over
the past five days.
</P>
<P>
   The streets bordering Harvard Yard were closed to traffic for a
few hours Sunday, and orange plastic mesh fences were put up on the
sidewalks, but other than that it seemed like just another Sunday
in the square. Chess players matched wits in Holyoke Center, mimes
danced near the MBTA subway stop, and homeless people asked for
change.
</P>
<P>
   All the while master of ceremonies Dick Ring was giving nonstop
commentary from the podium as the 123 racers blew around the
.7-mile course 50 times in the 35-mile criterium. The riders, who
removed their helmets when the national anthem was played at the
beginning of the race, put them back on and locked their shoes in
their pedal clips when the race was counted down at 12:30.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next hour, the competitors, riding at 40 miles per
hour, became a blur of multicolored jerseys as they zipped down
Massachusetts Avenue, took a left on Quincy Street past the Fogg
Art Museum, another quick left on Broadway, then through the
underpass back to Mass. Ave. About 5,000 spectators lined the
route, according to race director Paul Salvucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``After six days of racing, it's not so much what the course is
like, but what everyone's legs are like,'' said Monahan, 27. The
criterium series began with a race in Northampton Tuesday, then
moved on to New Bedford, Providence, Salem, and Somerville before
Sunday's race. Monahan won the race in Somerville.
</P>
<P>
   So as wearer of the leader's yellow jersey, he knew he was a
hunted man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the defensive, because I had a 9-point lead, and all
I needed to do was just stay close,'' he said. Sylvain Beauchamp of
Canada finished second overall, and McCormack was third.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack sat in with the pack for most of the race until about
15 laps to go, when he started thinking about how he'd make his
move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I didn't want to be leading going up that hill, because
there's so much of a headwind,'' he said, referring to the uphill
climb as the pack emerged from the underpass and headed toward Out
of Town News. So he waited until the pack rounded the corner and
the finish line was in sight. ``I was probably 20 guys back, but I
made a charge on the left, and Robbie Ventura came on the right
when we were on that bend and then it was just a drag race.''
</P>
<P>
   McCormack raised his hands in victory as he crossed the line in
1 hour 18 minutes 26 seconds. Just behind him was Saturn teammate
Ventura and 20-year-old amateur Charles Dionne.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack, 28, said the past week has been tiring not just
physically but emotionally. He learned that his older brother,
Frank, was involved in a crash while racing the Tour of Japan last
week. He is hospitalized with broken bones in his hand and a
damaged left kidney.
</P>
<P>
   So Sunday was especially sweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've been racing my heart out all week, but I've
had a lot on my mind, and my results haven't really shown it,'' he
said. ``For me, this was a great way to cap out the week of
frustration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
