</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD TURNS GET BUHL IN 
</HEADLINE>
 500-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Still smoldering over the mistake he made
Saturday when he crashed his primary car in Turn 1 _ on the warmup
lap of his initial qualifying attempt, no less _ Robbie Buhl said
he felt immensely relieved but hardly redeemed after finally making
the 33-car field Sundy for Sunday's 83d Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   After wrecking his primary car Saturday, then blowing the engine
of his one and only backup Sunday, Buhl jumped into a loaner
provided by A.J. Foyt and qualified with a four-lap average of
220.115 miles per hour. Mother Nature also did Buhl a good turn
when he bumped his way into the field for his fourth consecutive
Indy 500 start by bettering Mike Groff's four-lap average of
220.066 m.p.h., just before the rains came and brought an abrupt
halt to Bubble Day activities at Indianapolis Motor Speedway at
2:03 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   About 2 1/2 hours later, Speedway officials declared
qualifications complete and closed the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, when we took the car back (after the engine blew)
and started busting it apart, we figured with the weather, `This
isn't going to work,' '' said Buhl, a 35-year-old native of Grosse
Pointe, Mich., and a 1986 graduate of New England College in
Henniker, N.H., who came to Indy as the primary driver for Sinden
Racing Services. ``So, we kind of scattered around to see what
other people had. Somebody talked to A.J. So, I went to see him and
it was a pretty casual conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A.J. was kind enough to say, `Hey, I've got two cars. See
which one works best for you,' '' Buhl added. ``Our two teams just
pulled together and made a couple of calls that were right. I think
we timed it just right.''
</P>
<P>
   Just after Buhl came across the start-finish line and took the
checkered flag, ominous rain clouds overhead finally burst and
stranded Marco Greco in the pits as he was preparing to take the
track for his qualifying attempt. It also dashed any hopes Groff,
Scott Harrington, Stephan Gregoire, Jaques Lazier, and Lyn St.
James, who was the slowest among the record 33 first-day qualifiers
Saturday and first bumped Sunday, from bumping their way back into
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime car owner Dick Simon was also left out in the cold when
his driver, Gregoire, failed to qualify, marking the first time
since 1982 that Simon will not be at the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   They were all shut out by one of the tightest fields in the
history of the race. To wit: the margin in qualifying times between
pole winner Arie Luyendyk and rookie Wim Eyckmans, the slowest
qualifier, was 3.695 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the range of emotions he felt, Buhl said, ``The
biggest emotion I feel is that I'm still angry and mad at myself
for what I did Sunday. I was probably too confident in the race
when I went in that first time by and hadn't taken the green. I was
trying to wind things up too quickly and that was a mistake I made
and I should've known better. So I'm still trying to get over the
screwup I made.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhl attempted Saturday to bring his tire temperatures up to
speed on the first of two warmup laps when he bobbled it in Turn 1,
did a half-spin, and hit the outside retaining wall, causing heavy
damage to the left side of his car. Buhl was not injured,
physically _ just psychologically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can understand how bad you feel as a driver
when you do what I did,'' Buhl said. ``I mean, the day before
qualifying, the guys were back in the shop and up until five in the
morning putting a motor in the backup car, just in case. Then I go
out, you know, and make a mistake. You just don't understand how
that feels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it makes it more rewarding when you don't have five
cars sitting there and you're busting your butt with the one car
you have. And it does make it satisfying with A.J. offering up his
car and his crew guys and you go out and do five or six laps in it
and you go out and you're able to qualify. There's some
satisfaction in that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
