<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8429 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-SHOW-SPI &LR;      05-24 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-SHOW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEELING AND DEALING AT GUN SHOWS COMING UNDER INCREASING
SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LISA STIFFLER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKEWOOD, Wash. _ The single-shot pistols and rifles are neatly
aligned on the Asian rug covering the folding table. Some of the
metal on the old German guns have subtle, marble coloring and
multiple triggers that designate which barrel fires.
</P>
<P>
   These are features their owner, Larry, appreciates. His array of
firearms are meant for collecting more than for hunting or to use
in self- defense. In fact, ammunition is not even available for
many of the guns, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   The adjacent table is lined with hand-made knives for fishing
and hunting. The perfect blades curve toward exotic hard-wood
handles. Two tables down, 19th-century hand-woven baskets from
Northwest Indian tribes are decorated in whale motifs.
</P>
<P>
   Across the aisle a collector has a hodgepodge of handguns and
pre-ban semiautomatic rifles and a few patches and buttons from the
Civil War for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the all-American gun show, touted by some as a
celebration of U.S. history and the weapons that made it; to others
it's a Tupperware party for criminals.
</P>
<P>
   But as sensational crimes are linked to gun shows as a weapons
conduit to criminals, the all-American pastime of wheeling and
dealing firearms in a flea-market-style forum is coming under
increased scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday a youth violence bill passed the U.S. Senate, and,
thanks to a tie-breaking vote by Vice President Al Gore, an
amendment was added to the bill that tightens restrictions on
transactions at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, now in the House, would require all buyers at
gun shows to undergo a background check before taking home their
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, background checks are done only for firearms
purchased from licensed gun dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms reports that
licensed dealers make up 50 percent to 75 percent of the sellers at
gun shows; the rest are non-licensed vendors, most of whom are
collectors buying, selling and trading guns as a hobby.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address, President Clinton Saturday cited
attacks on students in Colorado and Georgia and urged the House to
pass the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call on the House to take immediate action,'' Clinton said.
``I hope the House of Representatives will pass every one of these
common-sense efforts that the Senate has passed to protect our
children from guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite criticism by the government and public, collectors and
dealers met this weekend in the Tacoma, Wash., suburb of Lakewood
for the monthly Pacific Arms Society gun show _ one of the 4,000
guns shows held annually in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Parents with children, war veterans and young couples circulated
the tables that mostly filled the former Ernst hardware store
behind the Lakewood Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Gary has pieces of his collection on display at a table near the
front of the show. A glass case holds German handguns worth
hundreds and even thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Gary's love of German Lugers began when he sent away for a $2
toy gun advertised in a comic book. He now owns nearly 100 guns and
has a Luger from every year they were made, from 1900-1945.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all history,'' Gary said. If you know the background of
the weapons they can reveal a wealth of information. ``If you read
the right books, the darn things will talk to you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hobby, like collecting stamps or baseball cards,'' he
said. Except gun collecting ``isn't politically correct.''
</P>
<P>
   The political incorrectness of guns worries those those who love
them.
</P>
<P>
   They worry about bad press, the increased pressure to reduce the
number of firearms people own, ever more legislation they say could
violate their constitutional right to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of the government and criminals coming to take their guns
compels the collectors to withhold their last names.
</P>
<P>
   Collectors such as Larry and Gary, who made up the majority of
vendors at the Lakewood show, sell guns without filling out
paperwork and aren't required to inquire about a buyer's identity
or criminal background.
</P>
<P>
   Antique guns and firearms deemed ``curios'' because of
particular unique features are exempt from background checks when
sold by dealers and collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Gottlieb, director of Bellevue's Citizens Right to Keep and
Bear Arms, said the problem with background checks is they are slow
and gun shows are short, usually lasting only a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington state, shotgun and rifle sales are called into the
FBI's National Instant Background Check System, known as NICS, for
approval, which can take days. Background checks for handguns are
done by local law enforcement and can take up to five business
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had an instant check system that was really instant,
it'd be workable,'' said Gottlieb. ``No one would oppose (the
legislation).''
</P>
<P>
   Those lobbying for background checks for all buyers say the
legislation closes loopholes that allow illegal purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of regulation on gun sales by collectors makes these
transactions appealing to criminals, said Bruce Gryniewski,
director of Washington Ceasefire. Criminals ``are going to try to
find the easiest way to get a weapon without a background check.''
</P>
<P>
   But gun show participants say many of the sales are between
collectors who know each other. Criminals don't patronize the gun
shows _ they steal their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association cites Justice Department research
that found only 2 percent of guns used in crimes were obtained at
gun shows, about 25 percent from stores, and the rest were stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Larry said he sometimes sees the same gun traded from dealer to
dealer, just circulating around the gun show regulars. He questions
the sense of doing a background check every time the trades are
made.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the new legislation wouldn't deter the criminals
from getting the guns and would not have prevented the recent
school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crook is still going to have the black market for guns,''
he said. ``None of this (new legislation) would have prevented any
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary said it would make more sense to enforce laws already on
the books covering firearms violations, but ``it's easier to make
new laws rather than enforce old ones.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the gun shows will continue as they have, bringing gun
lovers together for the weekend, to browse each other's collections
and swap history. And a fraction of America's 223 million firearms
will continue to pass through the hands of people without
background checks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
