<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8430 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      05-24 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S OWNERSHIP TESTING PUBLIC INDEBTEDNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ To fully comprehend the breathtaking display of guts
required by the Mariner owners to inquire about more public money
for their new stadium, the Guilty Pleasure, it's helpful to review
a couple of statements.
</P>
<P>
   Both occurred in the second week of December, 1996, and help
explain how the park's cost has grown so much: A much larger room
at the new yard is needed to store the hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   Four members of the King County Council, Ron Sims (now King
County Executive), Pete von Reichbauer, Cynthia Sullivan and Larry
Phillips, signed a letter asking that the ballpark construction be
slowed down because the schedule and a variety of legal challenges
put the county bonds for the project in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The letter stated in part: ``Frankly, we think the public would
be better served if the Public Facilities (District) were to adopt
a more realistic schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Provocative stuff, eh?
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent events have proven the caution was more than
warranted. At the time of the letter, the public was on the hook
for a proposed $295 million.
</P>
<P>
   It subsequently ballooned to $417 million. The price tag for the
park swelled to a pornographic $517 million _ and the owners are
now sniffing about attempting to recover as much of the $100
million difference as public foolishness will allow.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for the cost inflation was the incredibly
compressed work schedule for the stadium _ at 26 months, the
fastest in modern American history for a sports park with a roof.
The owners insisted on a 1999 opening, even if it meant bidding out
the work based on a drawing on a cocktail napkin.
</P>
<P>
   But once the slowdown request reached ownership, its lawyers saw
a great opportunity to kibosh the entire deal, sell the club and
blow Dodge before they actually had to be responsible for a
half-billion dollar white elephant.
</P>
<P>
   Within a couple of days, Mariners CEO John Ellis, whimpering
before the TV cameras, announced that they were pulling out of the
stadium deal and putting the club up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Because King County allegedly was going back on its commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regard the council members' letter,'' said Ellis, ``as a
clear decision by the political leadership of King County to
abandon their oft-repeated promises.''
</P>
<P>
   What?
</P>
<P>
   Where?
</P>
<P>
   How?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in the letter, or any other council action, amounted to
more than throat-clearing about imminent financial disaster. The
council members, and most every policymaker and staffer in county
government as well as the owners, knew that costs would explode and
that the Mariners were looking for any pretense to cut and run.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Slade Gorton (R-Nintendo) rode in and blistered so many
political behinds so ruthlessly that all opposition to the Mariner
timetable melted away and transformed into one of the sweetest
leases in major league sports.
</P>
<P>
   The one financial commitment that the owners were forced to
accept was responsibility for all cost overruns. As each overrun
story surfaced, the Mariners renewed the pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Now the story is that Ellis and owner Howard Lincoln have
quietly engaged in what had long been anticipated _ a campaign to
grab the surplus generated by taxes used to build the park. That
money was pledged to retire the public debt earlier.
</P>
<P>
   So now who's ``abandoning their oft-repeated promises''? None
other than our own little high-tech baseball cabal, which accused
the county of same 2{ years ago. If the owners could teach this
much hypocrisy to pitch a baseball, the AL West race would be over
by Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   The PFD has long been aware the Mariners have their own lawyers
and construction consultants scrutinizing the stadium work, looking
for mistakes and excesses that will make a case in either a court
of public opinion or a court of law.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an unsolicited tip, owners, free of retainer fee: Stick
to a court of law. Because with public opinion, only Saddam Hussein
has a worse case than the Mariner owners.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, these guys helped save baseball here. Yeah, it was on
their watch when the game peaked in Seattle in 1995. Gratitude has
been plentiful and often expressed.
</P>
<P>
   But the October, 1995, decision to make the public the primary
partner in the stadium changed the equation.
</P>
<P>
   For all the Mariner whining about annual losses, the public now
has more invested in this franchise than the ownership. And the
public has no way to recoup its investment, whereas the owners will
come out more than whole when they sell the club _ as every
baseball franchise seller always has.
</P>
<P>
   The owners don't see it that way. Once they recognize their
coercion campaign is a non-starter, they will take the case to
court and sue us.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, it's the (begin italics) Public (end italics)
Facilities District. But it has no money of its own. The Mariners'
partner, thee and me, are the folks with the money.
</P>
<P>
   And if we don't pay up, we will be told its our fault that Ken
Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez are wearing different uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8432 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      05-24 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTING GIVES WAY AFTER M'S RALLY LATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ To the highlight shows, it was just another
blooper. Base runner trips between first and second, flops and
crawls to the bag, much too late.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing funny about it to Charles Gipson. The Mariner
outfielder left his blood and sweat on the Kauffman Stadium base
paths Sunday. He kept in the tears, but not his dejection.
</P>
<P>
   Gipson was on base as a pinch runner in the ninth inning of
Sunday's 5-4 Mariners loss to the Kansas City Royals. With one out
and Russ Davis batting, Gipson took off for second. He saw that
Chad Kreuter's throw would be high, and he was just about to start
his slide when his ankle turned.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of having a man in scoring position, the Mariners had
two outs. Moments later, Davis struck out to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tore ligaments in the ankle a few years back, and when it
gets to the point where it's going to roll, it just gives out,''
said Gipson, who had scrapes on his knee, wrist and knuckles and
wore an ice pack on his ankle after the game. ``I guess it just
gave out on me. You can't do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it cost us our momentum. I know I had that bag stolen.
It's just a mistake you can't make. It can't get any worse than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had won their past six games to reach .500 for the
first time in a month. Seattle heads to Minnesota today to face a
Twins team they swept last week.
</P>
<P>
   The M's will be glad to be through with Kansas City for a while.
They split six games with the Royals over the past two weekends,
but Kansas City rarely was out of any game and is one of baseball's
surprise teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played hard, they played well,'' said Mariners manager
Lou Piniella. ``We played hard, we played well.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. Handcuffed by Royals ace Kevin Appier for seven
innings, the M's scored three times in the eighth to take a 4-3
lead. But Mac Suzuki, who had not relieved in a close game all
year, walked the leadoff batter in the bottom of the inning,
forcing Piniella to call on Jose Paniagua for the third straight
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to stay away from using (Paniagua), but Suzuki just
didn't come close,'' Piniella said. ``He threw the first pitch over
and missed home plate by wide margins.''
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua got a ground ball that advanced Mike Sweeney to second,
then Jermaine Dye bounced one to third. The ball took what Piniella
called a ``side hop'' on Davis, and it went for a hit. Kreuter
popped up for the second out, but singles by Mariner-killer Carlos
Febles (13-for-22) and Rey Sanchez brought home the tying and
go-ahead runs.
</P>
<P>
   Davis may have lost Dye's ball in the white shirts behind home
plate at Kauffman Stadium, where the screen now extends all the way
to the ground and there is no wall in front of the fans. This was
the Mariners' first day game here in the new configuration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played it just right, and I kind of lost it,'' Davis said.
``You take your eyes off the ball on a day like today with a
backdrop like that, for one instant, you're done. By that time, the
infield was baked, and it was hard. But that's no excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua (2-4), who pitched two innings Friday and 11/3
Saturday, had not worked three straight days all year. But he said
he didn't feel any less sharp Sunday than he'd been earlier in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to me and said, `If we need you in the game, will
you be ready?''' Paniagua said. ``I said, `Yeah, I'll be ready.' I
threw in the bullpen, and I said I felt OK.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a game that turned wild as soon as the bullpens came
on. Freddy Garcia allowed two first-inning runs, then permitted
five hits (three to Dye, who was 4-for-4) and one run over the next
five innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw someone up in the bullpen in the second inning, and I
said, `Whoa,''' Garcia said. ``I just had to keep the game close.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Royals, the 31-year-old Appier was a departure from the
parade of inexperienced starters Seattle had faced in its win
streak. He held the M's hitless until David Segui's leadoff single
in the fifth. With Appier's contorted delivery and on a bright day,
the Mariners struggled to pick up the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it seemed like the ball was glowing, like a big
snowball up there,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Appier got help from Kreuter, who threw out Tom Lampkin trying
to steal in the third and Segui trying to steal in the fifth,
ending both innings on strike-'em-out/throw-'em-out double plays.
</P>
<P>
   But against reliever Scott Service, the Mariners tied it 3-3
when David Bell ripped a slider for a two-run homer in the eighth.
Alex Rodriguez followed with a double off the wall, and Ken Griffey
Jr. lashed a single to left off the left-handed Matt Whisenant,
giving the M's a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's 13th homer of the season broke Bret Boone's club record
for homers by a second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's single extended his hitting streak to 12 games, tying
a career high accomplished four times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
