<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8435 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACING-PIGEONS-2Takes     05-24 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACING-PIGEONS-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN'S RACING PASSION FOR THE BIRDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Flying nearly 60 mph over hundreds of miles, Rusty
Hemsath's racing pigeons dodge hawks, power lines and storms with a
single goal: getting home.
</P>
<P>
   Some soar in like a jet with wings locked.
</P>
<P>
   Some come in just happy to be back, circling on the approach and
flapping their wings with joy.
</P>
<P>
   They all made it back to the San Fernando Valley community of
North Hills one recent Sunday after a 245-mile flight from Merced,
and mere seconds separated the winners from the losers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a thrill just watching them come home,'' said Hemsath,
one of Southern California's top fliers after more than 60 years in
the sport.
</P>
<P>
   His birds fluttered into traps and walked across a computer
scanner that read their leg band and registered the time, number
and sex.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, Hemsath's best bird did not win. But his birds are
the pride of the Sepulveda Racing Club, with two placing in the
national hall of fame.
</P>
<P>
   He once won a $5,000 purse in Snowbird, the prestigious race the
Fernando Valley Racing Pigeon Club hosts during the fall young bird
season; he raised a baby that won $36,000 for another flier and
produced offspring that won $28,000.
</P>
<P>
   The hobby of bringing the best out of these powerful and proud
descendants of European racing stock nevertheless remains the main
attraction for Hemsath and most of the Valley's fliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The birds are the key to the whole thing. I just try to keep
them trained and healthy,'' Hemsath said.
</P>
<P>
   With four active clubs, pigeon racing is alive and competitive
in the San Fernando Valley. Clubs from Simi Valley, Thousand Oaks
and Ventura, as well as Orange and Riverside counties, often enter
the same races, sending 4,000 to 7,000 birds into the same flight
and pushing the best birds to the front.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this once-treasured pastime of men and sons faces an
uncertain future in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The first recorded U.S. race was a 500-mile flight ending in
Philadelphia in 1878.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak more than a century later, there were some 12,000
fliers across the nation. The number has dipped to 10,000 as the
fliers get older and fewer newcomers take up the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've grayed, we've matured and there's been no outreach.
We're a very well-kept secret,'' said Rick Phalen, executive
director of the American Racing Pigeon Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma City-based union is developing its first outreach
program to promote the sport, which is notable given the
organization was established in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few clubs have done that. We're looking at what kind of
tools we can put in the hands of people at local clubs, a spark of
creativity perhaps, what kind of financial support we can share,''
Phalen said.
</P>
<P>
   To attract future fliers, the Devonshire Racing Pigeon Club has
placed newspaper advertisements. It was the idea of Phil Ball, who
said the club must add to the dozen or so active fliers in its
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need membership, people to keep a club going and more
birds flying. The more birds you have, the more competition,'' Ball
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hemsath was just 15 when he bought his first bird. ``I went down
and bought a couple of pigeons for 25 cents apiece.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 77, he still loves the challenge of a race. ``When the bird
comes sailing in, I get the same thrill as I did then.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemsath's best bird was fourth among nearly 2,000 in the recent
race from Modesto. His best this season was first in a similar size
pack two weeks earlier in the Fresno race, a notable achievement
given a late spring storm that slowed the winning speed to 35 mph
and knocked down a few dozen birds.
</P>
<P>
   Hawks and power lines are other obstacles. But the vast majority
of racing pigeons learn to fly high enough and fast enough to enjoy
careers that can last some five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``These birds are meant to fly all in a day,'' said Clay
MacBeth, a Granada Hills flier who also trains racing pigeons for
other area fliers. ``Anything under 400 miles is a straight fly
home. Anywhere from 400 to 600 miles, they will stop for a drink of
water and then come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's usually just a quick pit stop if they're going to be a
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   The pigeon racing bug bit MacBeth when he was 14 and looking for
something that needed care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the competitiveness started to take over,'' he recalled.
``I think I would have gotten bored with it and dropped it if it
hadn't been for the sporting activity.''
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Omni and Fernando Valley clubs, MacBeth is still
racing 35 years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want friendly competition, it's there. If you want to
bet a little money on your bird, it's there,'' he said. ``You
strive to get your birds in condition to come home and then you
strive to get them into competition to win.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   With three birds in the state hall of fame, two of them also
earning national hall of fame honors, MacBeth's rank with the best
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   MacBeth has recorded a win so far on the spring season. His best
bird averaged 60 mph in taking the Delano race.
</P>
<P>
   So how does a racing pigeon get from there to here?
</P>
<P>
   Pigeons come home mostly on instinct, sensing direction, aided
by strong vision and hearing, fliers explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``The homing pigeon is a very apt name for these birds. That's
why our pigeons aren't the ones people see bumming around the park,
hanging out on the library or even the next-door neighbor's
garage,'' explained Phalen. ``There's one place they're comfortable
and want to be, and that's home.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all racing pigeons are created equal, requiring experience
in breeding and skill in training.
</P>
<P>
   Fliers might spend $3,000 to $5,000 a year on feed, medication
and travel costs.
</P>
<P>
   Hemsath starts each winter with 24 pairs of breeders, typically
culling and adding several new pairs each year. Like most American
fliers, he buys from Europe because domestic racing pigeon stock
has gone out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   Born in January, babies will remain in a loft for a month before
they are allowed out to walk and begin flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more they fly, just like a kid exercising, the stronger
they get,'' Hemsath said. ``After a few days of this they will get
a little more adventurous. When they get a little confidence, they
will start roaming around.''
</P>
<P>
   Distance training lasts into the sixth month, as Hemsath carts
dozens of birds to release points farther and farther away from his
North Hills home. The final training flight begins in Bakersfield,
some 90 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   MacBeth, a Chevron tanker truck driver, trains racing pigeons
for other fliers twice a week. He hauls hundreds of birds in his
specialized truck to release points 50 to 100 miles beyond the San
Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``These pigeons are like any athlete, they need work,'' he said.
``They have to work out during the week to get ready for the event
on the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   The races to Los Angeles range from 115 miles from Delano on
opening day to 600 miles from near the Oregon border in the final
week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In a race, the birds are all released at once, not long after
sunrise. Weather conditions at that time feature relatively cool
temperatures and, ideally, a tail wind.
</P>
<P>
   Homing instincts will get birds back, but fliers use lures to
bring them home sooner. Mates and babies awaiting their arrival are
powerful attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the homes.
</P>
<P>
   Hemsath's six lofts, for instance, are elaborate wooden
structures with boxes for each bird, heating and ventilation, even
plush grass for walks outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fliers create what they win and what they lose with.
You've got to find out all their qualities, and you have to bring
it out of them,'' Hemsath said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8443 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-24 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS CAN'T BANK ON SHAQ IN PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ All you really need to know about the Los
Angeles Lakers is this: In a game they needed infinitely more than
their next paycheck, they never led.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers could have used a money player Sunday in Game 4 of
their Western Conference semifinal against San Antonio. Their
superstar center Shaquille O'Neal may be built as square as a
vault, but there's no banking on him in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In the postseason, when teamwork and team defense are an
essential combination, he's an easy safe to crack. O'Neal
contributed 36 points and 14 rebounds Sunday, but that wasn't
golden for the Lakers. Not even close.
</P>
<P>
   He has done this five times now in his seven-year NBA career ...
that is, led a team into the playoffs so it can exit under the
force of a broom.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan scored the first basket Sunday, over O'Neal, and
those two points sent the Spurs off and sprinting to a 118-107 win
and a four-game sweep in front of a Forum sellout crowd that, like
O'Neal, didn't seem to get it.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the 17,505 spectators booed third-year player Kobe
Bryant as he dragged himself off the court, as though he was the
reason all the hope and dreams they invested in this season were
now so much worthless currency.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Bryant had a few missteps. He took some wild shots, was
slow rotating to his man on defense more than once and fouled out
with a minute left, with 16 points, eight rebounds and three
assists.
</P>
<P>
   All those numbers, though, are dwarfed by this one _ 20. That's
how old Bryant is. He's still so young. Think about it; how many
kids his age would you trust to drive your car, much less the lane
at the most critical point of the season?
</P>
<P>
   The thing you must believe about Bryant is he is not selfish,
just a little clueless. He has character and he cares. That's the
important stuff. The mistakes he makes can be traced to youthful
exuberance and inexperience, and both of those are correctable with
age.
</P>
<P>
   But what of O'Neal's shortcomings? At what point do you stop
looking at them as correctable and see them as character traits?
</P>
<P>
   He had only two assists in the four games against the Spurs,
which makes you wonder why his teammates bothered moving at all
when he had the ball. You couldn't have blamed them for wanting to
conserve their energy for the other end, knowing they'd have to
cover for O'Neal, who is downright phobic when it comes to
defending the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   His reluctance to move his feet at all once he staked out a spot
in the paint led to three illegal defense calls against the Lakers
in the first half. When he didn't have the ball in his hands,
O'Neal looked out of sync. Not surprisingly, the Lakers couldn't
find any rhythm; they trailed the Spurs 65-41 at the midway point.
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room afterward it would have been music to our
ears to hear O'Neal blame himself for one of those open jumpers
David Robinson hit.
</P>
<P>
   Or promise to seek a hypnotist, an acupuncturist and/or Rick
Barry to help him with his free-throw shooting. (He converted 47.5
percent of his free throws for the series.)
</P>
<P>
   We gladly would have settled for any acknowledgment that maybe
he would have kicked more balls out to his teammates if the Spurs
hadn't been so quick to hack him. O'Neal might even have made a
joke at his expense _ gallows humor, you know _ and said something
like, ``Hey, they're no dummies. They were playing the
percentages.''
</P>
<P>
   As the team captain _ indeed, as a veteran player _ O'Neal
should have been the one to shoulder some of the blame, at least
publicly. (He could chew his teammates out in private as he saw
fit.)
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, though, isn't one to look hard in the mirror, unless
it's to admire his threads and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old man-child doesn't see much need to raise his
voice, even if it's to rally the troops before a do-or-die game.
Asked before the game if he planned to do something to pump up the
energy level in the room, he said, ``Talk to Rambis. He's the
expert. Not me.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Kurt Rambis, the interim coach with the uncertain
future. O'Neal already has been heard making disparaging comments
about Rambis behind the coach's back, which isn't a very cool thing
to do when you're supposed to be setting an example for your
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   If O'Neal isn't behind him, it doesn't bode well for Rambis.
Just ask Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell, two players the Lakers
could have used in this series but were traded to Charlotte in
mid-March after O'Neal lost patience with them.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Del Harris. O'Neal denigrated Harris' coaching
style and we all know what happened to him. As much as we like
Rambis, he might as well update his resume and send it to the
printers.
</P>
<P>
   Unless ...
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal has a clause in his $121 million contract that allows him
to opt out this summer. Let's hope he'll act on it. That would save
owner Jerry Buss and team executive Jerry West the hassle and
heartbreak of having to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   After firing Harris, signing Dennis Rodman and sacrificing Jones
and Campbell for Glen Rice and J.R. Reid, all on O'Neal's
recommendation, it's the only move Buss has left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 0123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8444 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-24 0886
