<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8451 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-SPURS-LADN     05-24 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SPURS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS SWEPT BY SPURS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ A Los Angeles Lakers season in which
anything and everything was subject to change ended abruptly Sunday
_ proving that in the end, nothing changed at all.
</P>
<P>
   No coaching change, no mix-and-match, throw-it-in-the-Cuisinart
blending of new faces and names, no number of experiments could
avert a repeat of past disappointments. The Lakers' season stopped
dead in another playoff sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Only the round and the opponent were different. The San Antonio
Spurs took the place of the Utah Jazz and, with a 118-107 rout,
sent the Lakers out of the Western Conference semifinals, four
games to none.
</P>
<P>
   It was an ironic and bitter conclusion to a thoroughly
disorienting season in which every desperate Lakers transaction to
win, now, at all costs, netted just another empty feeling.
</P>
<P>
   As the game wound down, television cameras panned across the
six, aging championship banners hanging above the Great Western
Forum floor, but the final game in the venerable old building's
history would not add anything to the legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very embarrassing,'' Shaquille O'Neal said of the Lakers'
second straight sweep out of the playoffs. ``Every time I get sent
home, I get embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was the Western Conference finals. The Lakers were
supposed to step forward, to a championship. Instead, a step back _
despite the addition of sharpshooter Glen Rice and the maturation
of young stars O'Neal and Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to deal with,'' said Derek Fisher, ``because each
year you set goals and you want to get better. And we really didn't
get better this season. That's what makes it so hard to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, even though we got swept in the conference finals,
we felt like we had taken that next step in becoming a championship
team. So coming into this season, we planned on winning. And the
lockout pushed all of that back, and the changes made it even more
difficult. So, right now, it's disheartening, but it's real and
it's life. So we have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Lakers may simply have conceded to the will and
the power of a more soundly constructed team. After losing Games 2
and 3 with a lack of composure in the waning minutes, the Lakers
were denied the chance to blow another late-game lead. The Spurs
made certain of that, leading from wire to wire.
</P>
<P>
   Only once in the second half did the Lakers threaten to extend
their season and make a return trip to San Antonio. After trailing
by as many as 17, they put together an impressive charge to end the
third quarter, using a 12-0 run to pull within 86-84.
</P>
<P>
   The run was a little bit O'Neal muscle, a pinch of Bryant's
will, some Rick Fox determination and part Tyronn Lue youthful
exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   But the season ended there. The Spurs, too veteran and too
fundamentally sound to be rattled, answered with a 13-0 run to open
the fourth quarter, and, minutes later, the first several hundred
fans began heading early for the Forum exits for the last time.
(Though not before offering a a few boos and a few sarcastic
``Ed-die'' chants in honor of traded guard Eddie Jones.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be embarrassed,'' Rice said. ``There's no way in the
world we should have gotten swept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we did everything we could to prevent getting
swept. We didn't play our best basketball, probably not one of the
games. The execution just wasn't there, and we paid for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a year ago, when the Jazz ran the Lakers off, there would
be no questioning of players' hearts and souls. Last May, O'Neal
bellowed that anyone without those qualities should ``get off my
team.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Lakers credited each other for playing hard, if
not always unselfishly or intelligently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried, guys tried,'' O'Neal said. ``Every time we made a
run, they just came down and hit a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys played hard. So I'm proud of the guys for playing hard
and not giving up.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Lakers simply were no match for Tim Duncan (33
points) and a surrounding cast of role players _ including Jaren
Jackson (20 points) _ who fed off of him. The Spurs were always a
step ahead of a Lakers defensive rotation, resulting in 39 Lakers
fouls and 54 free-throw attempts by San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had very sporadic moments of putting (scoring) strings
together,'' said rookie coach Kurt Rambis, his ``interim'' label
hanging over him, his future unclear. ``I thought Ty (Lue) gave us
a nice little lift. We put a few things together now and again, but
we couldn't sustain anything for any length of time offensively.
Defensively, that's where we kept breaking down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give yourself absolutely no chance to win when you let the
other team shoot 60 percent, 58 (percent) from the 3s, go to the
line 54 times, turn the basketball over 15 times for 27 points; you
have no chance. Unless you're shooting 100 percent, you've got no
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Lakers team that survived a lockout-shortened, 50-game
irregular season, the firing of coach Del Harris, a brief stopover
by Dennis Rodman and the trade of Eddie Jones for Rice now
contemplates another offseason of alterations.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, however, will compare to the insanity the Lakers just
packed into the last 108 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season, in particular, wasn't conducive to making
changes,'' Rambis said, ``and we made a lot of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only team that made all these major changes in the
middle of the year ... and with no practice time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not an environment to get everybody on the same page.
That's something we were fighting all season long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 0142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
