<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8458 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN     05-24 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOND FORUM MEMORIES COME FLOODING BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ A few minutes after the final buzzer sounded
_ probably the last final buzzer for an official NBA game in Forum
history _ Los Angeles Lakers public-address announcer Lawrence
Tanter thanked the fans for three decades of great memories.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like the big ashtray,'' longtime Lakers fan
Jack Nicholson said of the Forum. ``It's a great basketball arena.
I'll miss making the drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson has visited the Staples Center, set to open next
season, but it was in the daytime and he couldn't gauge the
atmosphere or traffic patterns. Good or bad, it won't be the Forum.
For Nicholson, nothing will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in Inglewood when I first came to California,'' he
continued. ``I walked to Hollywood my first time, along the route I
drive now. I walked all the way up La Brea. There were huge bushes.
It was scary when it was dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson has seen the great players and the championship teams,
but his most vivid Forum memory was an obscure incident a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always remember when Magic (Johnson) tried to teach Elden
Campbell how to run,'' he said. ``We got a big laugh out of that.
Running instructions, right there in the middle of the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Chick Hearn, the voice of the Lakers since they moved from
Minneapolis, gave an easy smile and quick answer when asked for his
fondest memory of the Forum, which opened Dec. 30, 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when Jerry West hit that 63-footer to put the game
in overtime against New York,'' Hearn said of Game 3 of the 1970
NBA Finals. ``They were ready to play the overtime and no one could
find Wilt (Chamberlain). They didn't know where he was, so I said,
`Go look in the locker room,'' because Wilt liked to eat chicken
after games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went in and there was Wilt, eating chicken. They told him
to dry off his hands and go out there for the jump ball. I don't
know why he left the court. He must have thought there was a
3-point line or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside the Lakers locker room after their 118-107 loss
to San Antonio on Sunday, West managed a faint smile while
recalling his favorite Forum moment: the team's 1972 NBA title _
his only championship as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly would not be today,'' he said. ``Maybe we should
schedule the Harlem Globetrotters or the Washington Generals to get
a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people have seen more Forum games than Tanter, the P.A.
announcer for 16 of the past 17 years. He recalled the vicious
rivalry with Boston and James Worthy diving out of bounds to tip
the ball to Magic against Detroit in the 1988 Finals. But like
Nicholson and Hearn, Tanter's most vivid memory has nothing to do
with victory or defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the 1983 NBA All-Star Game, and Marvin Gaye came down
the steps one minute before he was supposed to sing the national
anthem,'' Tanter recalled. ``He handed us a cassette of the audio,
and we put it on. At first, we thought it was the wrong thing. But
he had created his own background music. Then he sang, and it was
awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   So are the memories.
</P>
<P>
   Note: The Lakers are scheduled to play at least one exhibition
game at the Forum in the fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
