<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERANS RICE, HARPER CONTEMPLATING FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Derek Harper arrived in January, bringing to
the Los Angeles Lakers his 15 years of NBA wisdom. Glen Rice came
in mid-March, bringing his deft shooting touch as the supposed
final piece of a championship team.
</P>
<P>
   But as both veterans watched their title hopes die in a
conference semifinals sweep Sunday, they shared doubts about the
team's future and their own.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old Harper might retire rather than finish out his
two-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers could exercise a one-year, $7.1 million option on
Rice or give him a new deal, but he says it has to be on his terms.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, frequently frustrated playing third fiddle to Shaquille
O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, said he ``won't be mad'' if he's back, but
said the team needs to change to fit him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I pretty much tried it their way. It didn't work. So
now I think we gotta focus more on doing it a different way,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   That means a more movement-oriented offense catered to Rice's
skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be,'' he said. ``They got me here for a reason, and
that reason was not to go around and stand on the court and not do
anything. Put me to use, I like hard work. I tried to explain over
and over that when you run me off screens and post me up, things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper's role was defined in training camp, when he was named
co-captain shortly after being introduced. But he found it
difficult to get through to the young superstars around him; he
also discovered that his leadership was undermined when Kurt Rambis
replaced Del Harris as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Said Harper, ``I would have liked to have contributed more to
help this team be successful, but it didn't work out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The best example of the lessons he preached was found on the
opponent's bench Sunday. The San Antonio Spurs played as a team,
not a collection of individuals, and trusted everyone right down to
the 12th man, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Harper said, ``is how you have to play the game _ with
one agenda to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The brash young Lakers don't understand that yet?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't think we do,'' Harper said. ``I have banged my
head against the wall. But it's OK. My head is perfectly fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he can earn $1.1 million if he returns, Harper _ whose
playing time diminished to the point he didn't even play Sunday _
is contemplating retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early for me to make a decision on that, to be
honest,'' he said. ``I've been (in the NBA) for 16 years. Believe
it or not, I've never gone through a year like this. It's been the
most interesting year that I've ever encountered.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran words: The Spurs' Mario Elie said the Lakers needed to
go to Shaquille O'Neal more often and need to let Kobe Bryant
develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great talent,'' he said of Bryant. ``There's no way
(fans) should boo him when he's coming off the court. That's weak.
When I retire, I'm going to pay for tickets to see him play.''
</P>
<P>
   History: Lakers forward Travis Knight set an NBA playoff record
by fouling out in just six minutes of play.... Lakers rookie Tyronn
Lue scored the final NBA points in Forum history, on a driving
layup with 25 seconds left.... In franchise history, the Lakers
have been down 0-3 on five occasions and have been swept each time;
in fact, no NBA team has come back from an 0-3 deficit to win a
playoff series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 0150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
