<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8477 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LAD     05-24 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA ON THE MEND, EXPECTS TO FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Oscar De La Hoya's injured left hand probably won't
stand in the way of his long-awaited mega-matchup against Felix
Trinidad on Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays on the hand _ injured in the second round of Saturday's
11-round knockout victory over Oba Carr, De La Hoya said _ were
negative, according to his doctor, Tony Daly.
</P>
<P>
   The hand was sprained just above the wrist, Daly said. He said
it was swollen after the fight, during which De La Hoya apparently
fought nine-plus rounds in pain.
</P>
<P>
   However, the WBC welterweight champion should have enough time
to heal. The fight is in four months. The earliest he would begin
serious training is mid-July, which leaves almost two months for
the healing process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' Daly said when he was asked whether he thought
De La Hoya would be able to fight in September. ``It's four months
away.''
</P>
<P>
   The hand was put in a splint and he won't be able to use it for
a month.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming De La Hoya's hand was really injured and a factor in
the fight _ we can only take his word for it _ his performance was
both gutsy and outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   First, De La Hoya is almost exclusively a left-handed fighter.
That means he won the bout even though his principal weapon was
damaged. Second, Carr is talented, well-schooled and very tough.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya landed 46 percent of his punches, while Carr
connected on only 21 percent of his, according to ComuBox
statistics. And the champion had two knockdowns, the second of
which ended the fight. That's a not a bad night.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, De La Hoya was extremely pleased afterward, even though he
desperately wanted to give a spectacular performance after a series
of tentative efforts the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad, the IBF welterweight champion, knocked out Carr in
eight rounds in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The scoring: De La Hoya (31-0, with 25 knockouts) would've won
the fight had it gone the distance. He led by five points and seven
points on two cards and three points on the third.
</P>
<P>
   However, it wasn't that one-sided. Carr lost two points in the
seventh round because of repeated low blows and head butts.
</P>
<P>
   Take that away and Carr was in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   A cut below: A cut on De La Hoya's left cheekbone, the apparent
result of a head butt, required stitches; it was inconsequential in
the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Fight hype: Promoter Bob Arum, of course prone to hyperbole,
said the De La Hoya-Trinidad fight will be the biggest
non-heavyweight matchup since Sugar Ray Leonard outpointed Marvin
Hagler in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he might be right.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Oscar De La Hoya is the biggest draw in boxing
outside of Mike Tyson. And Trinidad, while not a household name, is
widely recognized as one of the top-five fighters in the world.
</P>
<P>
   However, the bout could never rival the energy of the
Leonard-Hagler-Tommy Hearns-Roberto Duran era of the 1980s. Each of
those great fighters had built tremendous reputations _ largely on
free television _ during an era void of popular heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   The public bought into their rivalry because all four were
extremely compelling, while only De La Hoya has such appeal today.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, no lower-division matchup is more exciting
today. Very rarely do the very best agree to fight the very best,
and this is one of those times.
</P>
<P>
   The Las Vegas Hilton has made De La Hoya a 7-5 favorite in the
fight, which is a virtual tossup.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the bout is not a done deal. Trinidad has yet to
sign off on it. However, those close to negotiations say only
last-minute details must be worked out and an official announcement
will be made soon.
</P>
<P>
   If Trinidad !ital!doesn't take the fight, he's crazy. He might
never again be in a position to make the more than $10.5 million
he's been offered.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy watch: De La Hoya, who said last week that he would no
longer work with Gil Clancy, now says the veteran trainer will be
back in camp for the Trinidad fight.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy works with head trainer Robert Alcazar in the final
stages of De La Hoya's training.
</P>
<P>
   Mayweather follies: Floyd Mayweather, who stopped Justin Juuko
on the undercard Saturday, was typically outspoken afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time,'' he said at the post-fight news conference,
``Oscar was the main event, but I thought !ital!I was the main
attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Not the way he's been fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The WBC super featherweight champion was hardly spectacular
against Juuko, a last-minute replacement for Goyo Vargas, before he
finally knocked him out in the ninth round. Juuko was greatly
overmatched, yet Mayweather _ more interested in showboating than
punching _ had difficulty putting him away.
</P>
<P>
   It was his second straight mediocre performance. He was only
able to outpoint little-known Carlos Rios in February.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's return: Mike Tyson, due to be released from prison no
later than June 4, is expected to fight before the end of the year,
said Shelly Finkle, his manager.
</P>
<P>
   No opponent has been named, although Europeans Axel Schulz and
Brian Nielson are the names that pop up most. Finkel said he is not
near a deal with any possible opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis-Holyfield: The Las Vegas Review-Journal reported that the
Lennox Lewis-Evander Holyfield rematch on either Nov. 6 or Nov. 13
will be at the new Mandalay Bay Events Center, the site of
Saturday's bout, citing unnamed sources close to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The first fight, in March, was at Madison Square Garden in New
York. It ended in a controversial draw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
