<HEADLINE>
THIS WEEK'S TV HIGHLIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TODAY: Clay is what kids use to make Mother's Day presents, what
cowboys rub on snake bites and what credit dentists use for
fillings. So what brilliant minds decided it would make a pretty
swell surface for a Grand Slam tennis event? The French, of course.
Here's a better idea: Why not just use linoleum with some sawdust
and peanut shells thrown on top? Maybe then, Pete Sampras would
have a chance. French Open first round, USA Network, 7 a.m. (three
hours each weekday live; NBC has weekend coverage Saturday at 9:30
a.m. and Sunday at 9 a.m.)
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY: Why do sporting events cause normally law-abiding fans
to go berserk and start destroying property? It's Jim Lampley's
subject to police. ``Real Sports With Bryant Gumbel,'' HBO, 10 p.m.
(replays this week Wednesday at 6 a.m., Thursday at 11 a.m. and 8
p.m. and Sunday at 11:30 a.m.)
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY: The Western Conference finals move back to the new
Hockeytown, Denver, where the replay machines actually show when
goals have been scored in the Avalanche's favor. NHL: Dallas at
Colorado Game 3, ESPN, 4:30 p.m. (ESPN has Game 4 Friday at 4:30
p.m. and Fox Channel 11 has Game 5 Sunday at 11 a.m.)
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY: Let's see if the Leafs leave this Eastern Conference
final in four without having to be embarrassed by Dominik Hasek.
NHL:Toronto at Buffalo Game 3, ESPN, 4:30 p.m. (ESPN has Game 2
Tuesday at 4:30 p.m. and Game 4 Saturday at 4:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY: Chicks may dig the long ball, but the Dodgers will dig
it more if either Glavine or Maddux make it into this series based
on how they've been pitching. Meanwhile, here's a way to keep the
Wrigley Rowdies awake: Pelt them with home runs. Dodgers at
Atlanta, Channel 5, 4:30 p.m. (KTLA also has Saturday's game at 4
p.m. and Sunday at 10 a.m.); St. Louis at Chicago, WGN, 12:10 p.m.
(WGN also has Saturday's game at 11:10 a.m. and ESPN has Sunday
night's game at a special time of 4 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY: ``Let's get it on _ it will be the fight of the
century,'' Oscar De La Hoya said of his fight tentatively scheduled
with Felix Trinidad in September. Hey, Oscar, by that time, there
won't be much of a century left. And the way things have been
going, it'll get pushed back anyway. Besides, Trinidad has to tie
up some loose ends. Felix Trinidad vs. Hugo Pineda, HBO, 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY: Jay Leno has been hired as the warm-up act for this
year's Indy 500 _ but only to drive the pace car. Check out the
chin strap on that helmet. Indianapolis 500, Channel 7, 8 a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
