<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-REVOLUTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY WINS, STARS SIT IN SECOND HALF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Los Angeles Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid had seen
enough midway through the second half.
</P>
<P>
   While his strikers continued to miss opportunities as if they
were firing at a hockey goal, he pulled striker Clint Mathis in the
60th minute in favor of defender Ezra Hendrickson.
</P>
<P>
   Then he pulled Welton, the Galaxy's leading scorer last season,
in favor of rookie Marvin Quijano (69th minute), who made his MLS
debut.
</P>
<P>
   It was more of a statement than anything else, since Los
Angeles' 1-0 victory over New England on Sunday in front of 7,581
at the Rose Bowl was decided in the opening minutes off a header
from Galaxy defender Steve Jolley.
</P>
<P>
   But the statement was clear. Through 10 games now, forwards Cobi
Jones, Welton and Mathis have accounted for three goals
collectively, meaning it was time for some of these guys to sit.
</P>
<P>
   Post-up striker Carlos Hermosillo finished his season Saturday
in Mexico and should join the team following a week off, but for
the time being that's no consolation to Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly I'm frustrated, but they're growing frustrated,
too,'' Schmid said of his forward trio. ``I didn't think Welton was
dangerous, and Marvin has been training well. As far as the other
two subs I made today, Clint and Joey (Franchino), I just didn't
think they had good games.''
</P>
<P>
   Schimd pointed to the help on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Necaxa's (Hermosillo's team in Mexico) finished, so
maybe the cavalry's on the way. And maybe things will get resolved
for Seth George (Galaxy's unsigned draft pick) next week as well.
They will both provide reinforcements. We could also be making a
trade that involves forwards. We'll see, a lot is yet to be
decided.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy's lone goal ended a two-game 146-minute scoring
drought in the third minute following a nice finishing header from
Jolley.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Vanney sent a corner kick to the far post, timing it
perfectly for Jolley, who easily beat New England goalkeeper Walter
Zenga to the near post for a 1-0 victory and the Galaxy's sixth
goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jolley, part of Los Angeles' league-leading defense, isn't ready
to blame the Galaxy's sluggish start on the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not them,'' Jolley said. ``It's a long season. We're
doing our part right now, but there are going to be times when
they're going to be covering our butts. We've been fortunate
(defensively), but we're not saying we're carrying the team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now teams are defending us and not going forward, so it
makes us look good. We didn't play extremely well, but a win's a
win.
</P>
<P>
   The victory improves the Galaxy to 5-5 and moves it into fourth
place in the Western conference. New England fell to 3-6.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles had a chance to go in front 2-0 in the 24th minute,
but midfielder Clint Mathis missed a one-on-one opportunity with
Zenga, spraying his shot over the New England goal.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution midfielder Ivan McKinley broke free down the
left-side in the 28th minute. He sent a perfect cross to Giovanni
Savarese in front of the Los Angeles net, but Savarese couldn't
finish from five yards out, heading his cross away from the near
post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
