<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8482 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     05-24 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS FULFILL EXPECTATIONS OF FUTILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At long last, the Los Angeles Lakers have finally fulfilled
expectations. It was in a 118-107 loss, of course, but that should
count for something.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to meet any of the positive-minded expectations the last
three years, their own or those of their fans and often adoring
media (like NBC), the Lakers can take solace that they did Sunday
what most everyone anticipated and put the final brush strokes on a
sweep at the hands of the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' Game 4 effort was flawless. They fell behind early
with a superb lack of teamwork, closed the third quarter with a
rush to create false hopes, and then gloriously crashed in the
fourth quarter as the Spurs outscored them 13-0 in the first four
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Riveting stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look at things this way: While other teams move on towards
a mere NBA title in June, fans here will have all summer to argue
whether the Lakers or Dodgers are Los Angeles' biggest
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the Lakers win the debate. Sweeps are very
definitive indicators of a team's underachievement, and this is the
second year in a row that the Lakers have exited the playoffs
zero-for-four.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, there's all the dramatic effect. The Lakers made sweeping
changes (sorry) this half-season in an effort to not finish the
season with a playoff bagel, and yet that's what happened again.
Thus, from now until they do otherwise, the word ``sweep'' will
accompany the Lakers wherever they go.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true for the big fella, Shaquille O'Neal,
whose teams have been swept out of the playoffs in five of six
tries (Orlando three times, Lakers twice). The only time he didn't
bagel was 1997, when the Lakers went 1-4 against Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq has seen more brooms than Mickey Mouse in ``Fantasia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very embarrassing,'' Shaq said while staring at his
shoes. ``Everytime I get sent home, I get embarrassed. This year
was a step back.''
</P>
<P>
   How true. It doesn't help that the Lakers have an uncertain
future to go with their unsatisfying past. Sunday's loss
underscored all of the Lakers' pressing issues, and they're
numerous.
</P>
<P>
   There's the defense. With Eddie Jones in Charlotte, the Lakers
have no one who plays it. The Lakers were stingy with Jones and
generous without him. And the Shaq paradox is that while he attacks
on offense, he is flat-footed on defense.
</P>
<P>
   There's the talent issue. The Lakers presumably have oodles of
it. But if so, then why do they have glaring personnel weaknesses
at point guard and power forward? With Elden Campbell and Dennis
Rodman gone, the Lakers had no one to guard Charles Barkley in the
Houston series or Tim Duncan in the Spurs' series.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did they expect? J.R. Reid? Robert Horry? Rick Fox?''
said the Spurs' Mario Elie, naming names of Lakers who couldn't
guard future MVP Duncan, who scored 37 and 33 points in the two
Forum games.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Lakers are so immensely talented, then why does
everyone on the roster save Kobe Bryant and Shaq look expendable?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have talent,'' said Lakers general manager Jerry West after
the carnage. ``But we don't know how to win the games we need to
win. They (the Spurs) played smarter. They seemed more committed
(to their game plan).''
</P>
<P>
   That leads to the teamwork issue. The Lakers have three players
who need to see the ball a lot to be effective, and the NBA only
allows them to play with one. A share-the-wealth policy sounds
better than it plays. Shaq and Kobe had difficult co-existing, and
that was before Glen Rice showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Rice has complained since his arrival that he needs to see the
ball more. Sunday, he was 4-for-10 from the field in 45 minutes of
play. ``We got back into not passing the ball around,'' said Rice.
</P>
<P>
   But from another precinct, Shaq said, ``We got away from what we
did against Houston. The pieces all fit in the first round. When
you have a go-to guy (meaning Shaq), you have to run everything
through him.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, Kobe said, ``The Spurs did what all good teams
do, make adjustments. We make adjustments, but our (offensive)
spots are always changing.''
</P>
<P>
   This leads to the coaching issue. Kurt Rambis' effort after Del
Harris was waxed was sincere, but he's overmatched, not so much by
opposing coaches as by his own players.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, perhaps trying to regenerate the Celtics-Lakers '80s
rivalry, egged Magic Johnson on Sunday about his interest in the
coaching job. Maintaining a longstanding tradition, Magic didn't
say no. For the rest of the day, NBC viewers saw more reaction
shots of Johnson than they did Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to West, who deferred questions about Rambis to
his boss, Jerry Buss, and who short-circuited questions about his
own future with ``enough has been said about my situation.''
</P>
<P>
   He tried instead to serve as the voice of reason. ``I want to
try not to make too much out of an awkward season,'' he said. ``We
put a lot of pressure on ourselves. We made a lot of changes that
we thought we needed to make in a very short season. Kurt was
handed one of the most difficult situations a coach has ever had.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I fear most is that the players will lash out (at each
other). Should we have made (those changes)? Should we not have? We
always push the envelope, and we always second guess ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   No more so than any of their fans. One wouldn't expect anything
less.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
