<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 03:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8494 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     05-24 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REAL-LIFE PHANTOM MENACE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking refuge from the violence and chaos of the real world, I
ducked into a theater for a couple hours of soothing make-believe
violence and chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Light-saber battles, wall-shaking sound, flying objects and
crazy characters from strange worlds! Then the movie started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' is good, and not just for the gimmicks. There
are lessons of hope. If our species manages to survive, evolve and
develop its innate intelligence and technology, some day our
ancestors will kill one another in much cooler ways than we do now.
</P>
<P>
   I'm no ``Star Wars'' expert, so I was plot-lost in space. The
cute kid star of ``Phantom Menace'' is, I assumed, the future Luke
Skywalker.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong! I'm told that the boy, so full of lofty ideals, is
destined to choose a murkier path. In the next movie he becomes
Richard Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   Also to come, Yoda mates with Poppin' Fresh to produce E.T.,
inventor of the cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   The movie does inspire contemplation of spiritual themes. Like,
despite our seeming insignificance in the vast sea of the cosmos,
one person, one teensy flyspeck in the galaxy, truly can make a
difference, can provide hope. I'm referring to my neighbor Ed, who
let me cut into the ticket line.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is lifelike. Viewers gave a huge cheer to Yoda, the
wise and kindly whatsit. We all wish our country had a leader who
was a Wookie instead of Nookie.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to separate the ``Phantom Menace'' from the menacing
phantom, Darth Milosevic. Like the bad guys in the movie, Milosevic
is unreasonable, power-crazed, won't negotiate. Dirty politics are
involved on both sides, and much violence ensues, including the
displacement and slaughter of entire ethnic populations.
</P>
<P>
   George Lucas should sue NATO and Milosevic for plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   One difference: NATO bombs keep falling on wrong targets. Or are
those really mistakes?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know who NATO would be if it was a former baseball
pitcher?'' asks a caller named The Old Homeboy. ``Ryne Duren.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. Ryne Duren had a hellacious fastball, Mr. Magoo
eyesight and a drinking problem. Duren's first warm-up pitch
invariably whistled 10 feet over the catcher's head. Batters
trembled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intimidation,`' says Homeboy. ``It's, `You can't trust us
because we don't know what we're doing, either. We don't know what
we might hit by accident.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton wants NATO to send 50,000 troops to Kosovo as
``peacekeepers.'' What peace? Why not send 50,000 ``peacefinders''?
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Star Wars'' galaxy, there is no gun control, and how
will Dianne Feinstein and Barbara Boxer handle this? Both are pro
gun-control but anti any attempt to rein in Hollywood violence.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be because both senators were elected with Hollywood
money?
</P>
<P>
   Recent headline: ``Gun bill votes reflected NRA contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is misleading because it could just as well be
flip-flopped: ``NRA contributions reflected gun-bill votes.''
</P>
<P>
   What's the cause and effect? In the end, both sides vote their
wallet.
</P>
<P>
   I support gun control because I'd rather be attacked with a
light saber than an assault weapon. The gun lobby says citizens
need military weapons because our government might attack us. But
our government has nuclear weapons, so we all need to upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   In a bar in L.A. last week, S.F. guy Lee Houskeeper found
himself chatting amiably with Charlton Heston, until Lee asked,
``How would you feel about every citizen owning a nuclear bomb?''
</P>
<P>
   Happy hour ended abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the ``Phantom Menace'' villain whose photo is on
this column was correctly identified by reader Alex Elko. No, it's
not Java the Putz. It is Ginko Biloba.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
