<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 09:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8605 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TA     05-24 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
(The Week in Review) 
(dw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New Furor Over an Old Whaling Tradition
</P>
<P>
   The gray whales that migrate from Mexico to the Bering Sea were
driven to the edge of extinction by commercial whaling by the
1920s. That is when the Makah Indians, who live at the very
northwestern tip of the lower 48 states and had relied on the
whales for a large part of their diet for centuries, stopped
hunting the grays.
</P>
<P>
   But the whale population recovered and now numbers at least
25,000, so the Makah decided to revive their tribal tradition of
whaling, around which many ceremonies, legends and songs were
built. Last week the Pacific Ocean near Father and Son Rocks, just
off Olympic National Park in Washington, turned red when tribal
hunters harpooned and then shot a 30-ton female whale with a
.50-caliber assault rifle.
</P>
<P>
   The Makah are likely to conduct more hunts: Under an
international pact, they can kill up to 20 whales over the next
four years for ``subsistence or ceremonial purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some environmental groups, torn between a desire to protect the
whales and respect for the ancient Indian traditions invoked by the
Makah, took no position on the hunt, while others said the whales'
real enemy was not the Makah but commercial whalers in other parts
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   But other groups expressed outrage. ``We're obviously very upset
that the Makah went ahead with killing an innocent sentient
creature in such a bloody and untraditional way,'' the Sea Defense
Alliance said.
</P>
<P>
   Makah leaders were jubilant about what they called a cultural
revival but also angered by the criticism. ``Why don't people
question other cultures?'' asked the tribal chairman, Ben Johnson
Jr., who said the rifle was used only to hasten the whale's death.
``They're going over us with a fine-tooth comb.''
</P>
<P>
   _ SAM HOWE VERHOVEK
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin Gambles and Comes Out Ahead
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin won impressive tactical victories on two
fronts _ not bad for an unpopular leader who just a few months ago
was being written off as an ailing and erratic figurehead. First
came the fizzling of a long-threatened impeachment drive headed by
his Communist-led opposition, followed a few days later by the easy
approval of his new prime minister, Sergei Stepashin, in the
Communist-dominated Duma.
</P>
<P>
   Having regained the initiative, Yeltsin now has to get back to
governing. His first move was to pointedly remind Stepashin that
all Cabinet appointments must be cleared with the Kremlin. His
second was to head south to the Black Sea for a two-week vacation.
</P>
<P>
   _ CELESTINE BOHLEN
</P>
<P>
   Guilty Plea by Fund-Raiser
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department got a lift in its campaign finance
inquiry when a Democratic fund-raiser and Arkansas friend of
President Clinton pleaded guilty in federal court to two political
fund-raising charges. Yah Lin Trie, a Taiwan-born naturalized
American citizen known as Charlie, also agreed to cooperate with
the department in its investigation into the financing of Clinton's
1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The plea came three days after a federal appeals court
reinstated five of six charges against another fund-raiser, Maria
Hsia.
</P>
<P>
   Another Drop in Crime
</P>
<P>
   For the seventh consecutive year, crime in the United States
fell sharply in 1998, according to preliminary data from the FBI.
Violent crimes and property crimes each fell 7 percent, declines
criminologists attributed to several factors, including an
expanding economy, a larger prison population and a lower demand
for crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Gandhi Roils Indian Politics
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party, once India's dominant political force,
appeared to be poised to make electoral gains in general elections
this September, but the abrupt resignation of the party's
president, Sonia Gandhi, has thrown all political calculations into
disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi, who married into an Indian political dynasty, quit
after three rebellious leaders in the party openly opposed her
candidacy for prime minister because she was born in Italy. The
leaders were expelled from the party later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ CELIA W. DUGGER
</P>
<P>
   New Deal on Korea Sanctions
</P>
<P>
   Since the Korean War ended in stalemate in 1953, Washington's
approach to North Korea has been pretty straightforward: Isolate
the place, and hope it will collapse in Stalinist rubble. But
somehow it has held together, starving but building missiles and
aspiring to build nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes former Defense Secretary William Perry, who arrives in
Pyongyang this week with a new deal as the first-ever presidential
envoy: Give up your long-range missile program, stop exporting arms
and forget about the nukes. In return, Washington would start
lifting its economic embargo.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal would require the world's most isolated country to
open up, a move it has always resisted.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   Indictment in Terror Case
</P>
<P>
   A former U.S. Army sergeant was charged with collaborating with
Osama bin Laden in a worldwide terrorist conspiracy against
Americans abroad. A federal indictment described Ali Mohamed, 46,
as a crucial aide to bin Laden, the Saudi exile who has been
accused of masterminding two embassy bombings in Africa last year.
Mohamed's lawyer said he planned to fight the charges.
</P>
<P>
   _ BENJAMIN WEISER
</P>
<P>
   Round One to Katzenberg
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Katzenberg came out ahead in the first round of his
acrimonious legal battle with Walt Disney Co.. The referee
overseeing the case ruled that Disney had breached its contract
with its former studio chief. So Katzenberg is entitled to a bonus
plus interest based on the profits of movies he made while at
Disney.
</P>
<P>
   The next phase of the trial, which has captivated Hollywood,
will determine exactly how much he gets.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANDREW POLLACK
</P>
<P>
   The Hype Was With Them
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace,'' playing at 2,970
theaters, often around the clock, set an opening-day record. (On a
school night, yet!) To be exact, $28,542,349, or nearly $7 million
more than ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park'' took in two years ago.
Armed with galactic hype, ``The Phantom Menace'' didn't need any
raves, and its reviews were indeed mixed. But here's the real
question: If you stumble to a movie at 3:30 a.m., are you staying
up late or getting up early?
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Breaking Up a Vitamin Cartel
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a decade, executives at the world's leading producers
of vitamins would plot in secret to control the prices, production
and distribution of nutrients and additives used to enrich food
products.
</P>
<P>
   That cartel came to an abrupt end when Hoffmann-LaRoche Ltd.,
the Swiss pharmaceutical giant, pleaded guilty in federal court to
violating the Sherman Antitrust Act and agreed to pay a $500
million fine, the largest criminal penalty ever imposed by the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   A second company, BASF AG of Germany, agreed to pay $250
million. Executives of both companies, along with others, remain
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEPHEN LABATON
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
