<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, May 30) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending May 15, at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. SUMMER SISTERS, by Judy Blume. (Dell, $7.50.) Two
</P>
<P>
   young women from very different backgrounds come of
</P>
<P>
   age on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE PILOT'S WIFE, by Anita Shreve. (Back Bay/Little, Brown,
</P>
<P>
   $13.95.) After learning that a plane flown by her husband
</P>
<P>
   has exploded, a woman tries to unravel the secret life
</P>
<P>
   he led.
</P>
<P>
   3. GENUINE LIES, by Nora Roberts. (Bantam, $7.50)
</P>
<P>
   A biographer has a problem: to reveal or conceal the
</P>
<P>
   secrets of a glamorous film actress.
</P>
<P>
   4. SECRET PREY, by John Sandford. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Davenport pursues the killer of a corporate
</P>
<P>
   chairman who was on a hunting trip.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE MIDNIGHT CLUB, by James Patterson. (Warner
</P>
<P>
   Vision, $6.99.) A New York journalist finds herself
</P>
<P>
   threatened by a psychopathic killer.
</P>
<P>
   6. YOU BELONG TO ME, by Mary Higgins Clark. (Pocket,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A radio talk-show host attempts to expose a
</P>
<P>
   killer who targets lonely women.
</P>
<P>
   7. HOMEPORT, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.50.) An art
</P>
<P>
   expert's troubles, personal and professional, lead
</P>
<P>
   her to seek help from a seductive art thief.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE ELUSIVE FLAME, by Kathleen E. Woodiwiss.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $7.50.) An artist, destitute in Georgian
</P>
<P>
   London, returns to her native America.
</P>
<P>
   9. NOW YOU SEE HER, by Linda Howard. (Pocket, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of a young painter takes a strange turn.
</P>
<P>
   10. MEMOIRS OF A GEISHA, by Arthur Golden. (Vintage, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of a young woman growing up in Kyoto who has
</P>
<P>
   to reinvent herself after World War II begins.
</P>
<P>
   11. I KNOW THIS MUCH IS TRUE, by Wally Lamb. (Regan Books/
</P>
<P>
   Harper Perennial, $16.) A troubled man must care for his
</P>
<P>
   schizophrenic twin brother.
</P>
<P>
   12. LEGACY OF SILENCE, by Belva Plain. (Dell, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Her past haunts a woman who fled to America at the
</P>
<P>
   beginning of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE READER, by Bernhard Schlink. (Vintage, $11.)
</P>
<P>
   A German high school student falls in love with a
</P>
<P>
   former Auschwitz employee.
</P>
<P>
   14. ``N'' IS FOR NOOSE, by Sue Grafton. (Fawcett, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Kinsey Millhone investigates the sudden, strange death
</P>
<P>
   of a police officer in a California town.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE STREET LAWYER, by John Grisham. (Island/Dell,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A young lawyer discovers his
</P>
<P>
   prestigious firm's dirty secret.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. REAL BOYS, by William Pollack. (Owl/Holt,
</P>
<P>
   $13.95.) A clinical psychologist discusses the
</P>
<P>
   emotional development of boys.
</P>
<P>
   3. A PIRATE LOOKS AT FIFTY, by Jimmy Buffett. (Fawcett,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Traveling from Florida to the Amazon, the singer-
</P>
<P>
   songwriter reflects on his life.
</P>
<P>
   4. OUR DUMB CENTURY, edited by Scott Dikkers. (Three
</P>
<P>
   Rivers, $15.) Newspaper headlines making fun of great
</P>
<P>
   events of the past century.
</P>
<P>
   5. UNDER THE TUSCAN SUN, by Frances Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) Life in the Italian countryside.
</P>
<P>
   6. A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   7. GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance to
</P>
<P>
   geographical advantages.
</P>
<P>
   8. FALLING LEAVES, by Adeline Yen Mah. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $13.) From a cruel childhood in China to life as a
</P>
<P>
   California physician: an autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   10. OCTOBER SKY, by Homer H. Hickam Jr. (Island/Dell,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) A memoir of Coalwood, W.Va., where the author
</P>
<P>
   learned to build rockets.
</P>
<P>
   11. (x) THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Paperbacks, $6.99.) The story of the
</P>
<P>
   nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a single crew.
</P>
<P>
   12. ADVENTURES OF A PSYCHIC, by Sylvia Browne and
</P>
<P>
   Antoinette May. (Hay House, $12.95.) A psychic tells
</P>
<P>
   her life story.
</P>
<P>
   13. (x) INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor/Doubleday,
$7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest season in
</P>
<P>
   history.
</P>
<P>
   14. TALKING TO HEAVEN, by James Van Praagh.
</P>
<P>
   (Signet, $6.99.) A ``world-famous medium'' discusses
</P>
<P>
   communication with the other side. (b)
</P>
<P>
   15. TENDER AT THE BONE, by Ruth Reichl. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $13.) A memoir by the former restaurant critic for The
</P>
<P>
   New York Times.
</P>
