<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: HARDCOVER BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, May 30) 
(Eds: The word AT in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for hardcover
books. See BESTSELLERS-HARD-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list and where
the book stood the previous week.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales for the week ending May 15, at almost
4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 50,000 other retailers
(gift shops, department stores, newsstands, supermarkets),
statistically weighted to represent all such outlets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) indicates that a book's sales are barely distinguishable
from those of the book above. A (b) indicates that some bookstores
report receiving bulk orders for a book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. STAR WARS: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace, by Terry
</P>
<P>
   Brooks. (Lucas/Ballantine, $25.) How it all began for
</P>
<P>
   Anakin Skywalker (a k a Darth Vader).
</P>
<P>
   2. WHITE OLEANDER, by Janet Fitch. (Little, Brown, $24.)
</P>
<P>
   The ordeals of growing up as experienced by a teen-age girl
</P>
<P>
   whose single mother murders a lover.
</P>
<P>
   3. WE'LL MEET AGAIN, by Mary Higgins Clark. (Simon &AMP;
</P>
<P>
   Schuster, $25.) A woman struggles to free herself of the
</P>
<P>
   suspicion that she murdered her husband.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE GIRL WHO LOVED TOM GORDON, by Stephen King.
</P>
<P>
   (Scribner, $16.95.) When a girl gets lost in the
</P>
<P>
   woods, she is saved by her spiritual association with a
</P>
<P>
   relief pitcher for the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   5. CERTAIN PREY, by John Sandford. (Putnam, $24.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Davenport pursues a woman who is a longtime
</P>
<P>
   successful paid killer.
</P>
<P>
   6. EAST OF THE MOUNTAINS, by David Guterson. (Harcourt
</P>
<P>
   Brace, $25.) A man with cancer returns to the eastern
</P>
<P>
   Washington of his youth to commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   7. BITTERSWEET, by Danielle Steel. (Delacorte, $26.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman copes with a midlife crisis: Should she continue
</P>
<P>
   to raise a family or should she pursue her old career?
</P>
<P>
   8. A NEW SONG, by Jan Karon. (Viking, $24.95.) A clergyman
</P>
<P>
   and his wife move 600 miles from home, creating new friendships
</P>
<P>
   and maintaining old ones.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE TESTAMENT, by John Grisham. (Doubleday, $27.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A reclusive billionaire, a burned-out lawyer and a
</P>
<P>
   young woman who works as a missionary in the jungles
</P>
<P>
   of Brazil are brought together by a startling secret.
</P>
<P>
   10. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE, by J.K.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling. (Levine/Scholastic, $16.95.) A British
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school of witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   11. (x) JOINING, by Johanna Lindsey. (Avon, $24.) In 13th-
</P>
<P>
   century England, a woman gradually changes her feelings
</P>
<P>
   about her partner in an arranged marriage.
</P>
<P>
   12. OH, THE PLACES YOU'LL GO! by Dr. Seuss.
</P>
<P>
   (Random House, $17.) The problems of finding your way
</P>
<P>
   through life; in verse and pictures.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE WHITE HOUSE CONNECTION, by Jack Higgins.
</P>
<P>
   (Putnam, $25.95.) Tracking an assassin who threatens
</P>
<P>
   the stability of the British and American governments.
</P>
<P>
   14. BEYOND THE GREAT SNOW MOUNTAINS, by Louis L'Amour.
</P>
<P>
   (Bantam, $16.95.) Ten short stories ranging from
</P>
<P>
   the Old West to Hollywood to Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   15. CRYPTONOMICON, by Neal Stephenson. (Avon, $27.50.)
</P>
<P>
   From World War II to the World Wide Web: a tale of
</P>
<P>
   code making and code breaking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE GREATEST GENERATION, by Tom Brokaw. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $24.95.) The lives of men and women who came
</P>
<P>
   of age during the Depression and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   2. TUESDAYS WITH MORRIE, by Mitch Albom.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $19.95.) A sportswriter tells of
</P>
<P>
   his weekly visits to his old college mentor,
</P>
<P>
   who was near death.
</P>
<P>
   3. YESTERDAY, I CRIED, by Iyanla Vanzant. (Simon &AMP;
</P>
<P>
   Schuster, $22.) A counselor recalls how she turned
</P>
<P>
   painful experiences into feelings of hope.
</P>
<P>
   4. BELLA TUSCANY, by Frances Mayes. (Broadway, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   An American writer recalls a spring and summer spent
</P>
<P>
   in the romantic sections of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   5. EVERY MAN A TIGER, by Tom Clancy with Chuck Horner.
</P>
<P>
   (Putnam, $27.95.) The novelist and a retired Air
</P>
<P>
   Force general examine the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   6. ALL TOO HUMAN, by George Stephanopoulos. (Little,
</P>
<P>
   Brown, $27.95.) The former adviser to President Clinton
</P>
<P>
   recalls his years in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE CENTURY, by Peter Jennings and Todd Brewster.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $60.) An account of the 20th century,
</P>
<P>
   complete with photographs and first-person narratives.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE ART OF HAPPINESS, by the Dalai Lama and Howard
</P>
<P>
   C. Cutler. (Riverhead, $22.95.) What Buddhist doctrines
</P>
<P>
   and common sense tell us about dealing with everyday
</P>
<P>
   problems.
</P>
<P>
   9. BUSINESS (AT) THE SPEED OF THOUGHT, by Bill Gates with
</P>
<P>
   Collins Hemingway. (Warner, $30.) The chairman of
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft discusses how new technology is changing the
</P>
<P>
   ways business is done. (b)
</P>
<P>
   10. THE MAJORS, by John Feinstein. (Little, Brown, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist's account of the 1998 Masters, U.S. Open,
</P>
<P>
   British Open and PGA golf tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   11. (x) THE LEXUS AND THE OLIVE TREE, by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $27.50.) A journalist explains
</P>
<P>
   the instant electronic global economy.
</P>
<P>
   12. COMFORT FROM A COUNTRY QUILT, by Reba McEntire.
</P>
<P>
   (Bantam, $19.95.) The country music star tells how she
</P>
<P>
   balances the demands of her career and her family.
</P>
<P>
   13. (x) FEEL THIS BOOK, by Janeane Garofalo and Ben Stiller.
</P>
<P>
   (Ballantine, $22.95.) The comedians discuss
</P>
<P>
   self-empowerment, spiritual supremacy and sex.
</P>
<P>
   14. (x) WAKE UP, I'M FAT! by Camryn Manheim. (Broadway, $23.)
</P>
<P>
   The memoir of a television actress who has long contended
</P>
<P>
   with obesity and its stigmas.
</P>
<P>
   15. (x) BLACK HAWK DOWN, by Mark Bowden. (Atlantic Monthly,
</P>
<P>
   $24.) The bloody battle between American forces and Somalia
</P>
<P>
   street fighters in Mogadishu in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   16. (x) RAISING CAIN, by Dan Kindlon and Michael Thompson
</P>
<P>
   with Teresa Barker. (Ballantine, $24.95.) The emotional
</P>
<P>
   life of boys and what can be done to benefit it.
</P>
<P>
   17. (x) BETRAYAL, by Bill Gertz. (Regnery, $27.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A reporter charges that the Clinton administration
</P>
<P>
   has undermined America's security. (b)
</P>
