<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8615 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN-COX     05-24 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Help, I'm being held prisoner in a . . .
 &HT;    For release May 26, 1999.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a private message to the State Department:
</P>
<P>
   I know you are quite tied up with that Kosovo stuff, but I also
know you have the best interests of American citizens at heart and
would want to be informed about this.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Americans are being kidnapped daily in foreign
cities, notably in the Mediterranean rim.
</P>
<P>
   As you typically post warnings to Americans about traveling to
places such as North Korea, Libya, Iran and, now, the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade, you might consider a foreboding about these
kidnappings, temporary as they are and, thankfully, with no
fatalities to date.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, these kidnappings are not at the hands of terrorists
but they are of note nevertheless. In the last three weeks, I was
kidnapped in Mallorca, Marrakech and Tunis. Last year, I was
kidnapped in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   Please do not attach any political patterns to this, it's all
got to do with the Big Hustle. As American tourists travel to
foreign destinations they most likely will buy what is called a
tour. Part of that package usually is the half-day tour of a
principal city, and that's where the kidnapping takes place.
</P>
<P>
   The tour guide, often operating under the pretense of being a
college professor with a specialty in archaeology or religion,
typically has a brother-in-law who sells carpets.
</P>
<P>
   As you exit an historic site and your gasping, mostly aging,
group trails the guide through the winding narrow streets of souks,
bazaars, casbahs or medinas, you suddenly are bewilderingly herded
into a carpet-laden establishment and made to climb one or two
flights of steps into a large room with rolls of carpeting stacked
on end. There, a cadre of swarmy-looking persons stand by, awaiting
the moment they are turned loose on you.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you have been through this before, you have no idea of
what is about to happen. You are made to sit on benches along the
outside perimeter of the room while an English-speaking person asks
if you would prefer mint tea or Coke. (I ask you, what would you
rather drink: a narrow glass of clear liquid with a huge leaf of
something in it, or a Coca-Cola?)
</P>
<P>
   As you squirm uncomfortably on your bench, usually drinking
whatever that mint tea is because you feel if you order a Coke, you
will be seen as an ugly American, the prime salesman is telling you
how many knots are woven into the carpet as the others begin
rolling out the various samples.
</P>
<P>
   It is there and then that you realize you have been had and the
Big Hustle is on. You look for an exit but it is blocked by
salesmen. When the presentation is completed, you are further held
against your will by those same people who now try to isolate you
into small groups, asking which carpet you want to purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes ago, I was looking at some breathtaking Arabic
architecture, totally unaware that in a short time I was going to
be forced down a narrow alley, up several flights of stairs and
waylaid by carpet salesmen every bit the equal of used car
salesmen, if not better.
</P>
<P>
   The inexperienced, those who never have been kidnapped before,
make the mistake of asking a question about the carpet _ something
like, ``What's it look like on the back?'' -- and it's like
bleeding just ahead of a shark.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us, freed by our own resilience, have squirmed away
from the room only to be beset upon by shawl, fez, religious object
and stuffed camel salesmen on the lower floor while we await the
release of our besieged friends above.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three or four-hour whirlwind of the city, more than an
hour of it is taken by this involuntary visit to the carpet shop.
(In other places, it might be the pearl or cameo factory or the
diamond cutters.)
</P>
<P>
   I thought you people in State ought to know about it. The next
time I am kidnapped in such a manner, and after I am released, I
would like you guys to tell the Pentagon to bomb the place. But,
please, just the carpet place.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
