<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8618 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-DULL-POLITICS-REVIE     05-24 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-DULL-POLITICS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DULL CAN CUT BOTH WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
(dw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Poor Al Gore. As if President Clinton's keening
that his loyal No. 2 needs to unbend were not enough, now the
Republicans have made Gore a punch line.
</P>
<P>
   Even Steve Forbes, a Republican presidential candidate not known
for flair, gets big laughs cracking wise about Gore's lack of
flair. ``Concerning Gore, I won't be giving him any advice today,''
Forbes deadpanned last week. ``He seems to be getting enough from
the White House.'' He then referred to the vice president's ``rigor
mortis.'' Both lines drew more cheers than anything Forbes said
about his new Social Security proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon used to advise his proteges not to worry if they
were loved or despised. ``The worst sin in politics,'' he once
said, ``is being boring.''
</P>
<P>
   From money to the entire White House infrastructure to
on-the-job experience, Gore has more advantages than any candidate
for president today. Yet polls show that his support in the
primaries is less than enthusiastic, and that he would get
clobbered in a general election by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas or
Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Why? The vice president is boring. The American people, in
polls, say so. Leno and Letterman say so. Even his mentor, Clinton,
says so. Gore tried to turn his weakness into a strength, by making
self-deprecating jokes, but the boring schtick was boring.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's fate will depend on a question that is as yet
unanswerable. After the vertiginous, long-running Clinton sitcom,
will Americans want more presidential high jinks? Or will they want
a respite from it all? Will voters want a leader focusing intensely
on them, or will they just want to be left alone to play the stock
market? No one, after all, is more gratifyingly boring than Alan
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Podesta, a Democratic strategist, said that after sampling
years with Clinton, voters may want calm. ``People go to amusement
parks and like roller coasters,'' he said. ``At the same time, they
appreciate the straight and narrow.''
</P>
<P>
   If America wants bland, Al Gore is the man. Many of the hottest
politicians these days are the coldest. The appropriately named
Gray Davis chastised reporters last year for wanting a candidate
``who could be a replacement for Jay Leno.'' Three months later,
Davis, a Democrat, was elected governor of California. Now he calls
himself Gore's ``charisma adviser.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, the determinedly dull governor of New York,
George Pataki, who invites critics to compare him with his
predecessor, Mario Cuomo, the compelling Democratic orator.
``There's a big difference between glitz and substance and rhetoric
and reality,'' Pataki said. ``If you look at my predecessor, there
was nobody who was better able to give a speech. But he was not as
able to change a government.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's friends still respond, perhaps reflexively, to queries
about the very vertical vice president with a query of their own:
``When were you last out with him? He's changed.'' They insist that
the dullness quotient is way overstated. They say Gore can be
surprisingly engaging, even robust, in small settings when the
cameras aren't around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't Al Gore's people understand?'' asked Mandy Grunwald,
a media consultant who is advising Hillary Rodham Clinton.
``Instead of bemoaning the fact that he's not Clinton, celebrate
it. People want the substance of the Clinton-Gore years without the
soap opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Gore's advisers are beginning to agree. ``Boring is good
because it means reliable,'' said Marla Romash, a Gore adviser who
for years has defended Gore's campaign skills. ``It means someone
who's going to get the job done. It means someone who's going to
stay focused.'' Gore's advisers argue that he has been so
overshadowed by the president that people have not had a chance to
get to know him.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, blandness comes in as many flavors as Ben &AMP; Jerry's.
In Gore's case, it means a candidate who is uninspiring and
sometimes awkward with voters (a telltale sign _ he doesn't know
quite what to do with a baby.) His lone rival, former Sen. Bill
Bradley, has some provocative ideas, but can be prone to deliver
them in a lifeless monotone. He almost seems to dislike
interruptions for applause.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the mix of fizz and bland policies is a winning
combination. One explanation for why Bush is the early favorite for
the Republican nomination may be that he knows how to charm voters.
(A recent Washington Post/ABC News Poll found 56 percent of voters
viewed Gore as somewhat or very boring; only 23 percent said that
of Bush.) But on policy matters, Bush has tried to sit on his lead
and appeal to the widest electorate possible by being
nonprovocative.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, despite Clinton's piquant reputation, some of his
best points came when he tried to make politics and ideology as
bland as possible, as when he pressed for school uniforms in the
1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to say to me _ I'm not sure to my face _ that I
was kind of dull,'' said Michael Dukakis, the Democratic
presidential nominee in 1988 and three-term governor of
Massachusetts, who sympathizes with Gore. ``I would say, `You don't
get re-elected three times because you're dull.'''
</P>
<P>
   Noting the extraordinary oratorical skills of Presidents Reagan
and Clinton, he added, ``If you're going to judge the rest of us by
these two guys, then we'll all be in sad shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes blandness comes in cycles. In New York, voters picked
the peppery Ed Koch as mayor. Then they opted for David Dinkins
(bland) and then Rudolph Giuliani (highly spiced).
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rise of politicians like Pataki and Davis, there
still is some appetite for sizzle. In the contest for Minnesota
governor last year, the professional wrestler Jesse ``the Body''
Ventura defeated Hubert Humphrey III who, unlike his father, is
hardly a live wire.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over personality is important because voters often
look to politicians, specifically presidents, to inspire and to
lead. This is the television age, after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Straightforward is OK but boring is never in,'' said Patrick
Caddell, a pollster for President Jimmy Carter. ``We're talking
about the presidency. They don't want Bill Clinton back, this wild,
out-of-control thing. But to say if you're a wooden Indian that's
OK, that's overstating it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview in Austin, Texas, Bush, who has the
raffish charm of Bill Clinton, declined to discuss Gore's political
skills. Yet he made the case for a president who connects with
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to know you care,'' he said. ``People want to know
you relate. People want to see you in action. That's really
important, particularly in early states where retail politics can
affect the outcome of the election. People know if you're
uncomfortable around them. People know if you don't like them.
People are smart.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even if Gore buys the idea that bland is beautiful, he should
not expect it to carry him to the White House. Sen. Richard Lugar,
R-Ind., who was considered so bland that he was passed over for Dan
Quayle as George Bush's running mate in 1988, tried to turn his
seriousness into an asset in the 1996 presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his commercials, Lugar spoke earnestly as a photograph
of Clinton, Gore and Jim Belushi, in sunglasses and fedoras,
mugging as the Blues Brothers, flashed on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidency is serious business,'' Lugar said, very
seriously. ``The president is not entertainment. The president is
commander in chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters, however, did not take Lugar seriously at all. He was
soon out of the race, saying he had no interest in ``competing
endlessly with no prospects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
