A8621 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLSENDOLPH24-COX     05-24 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLSENDOLPH24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Security First raises Atlanta's financial profile
 &HT;    By Ernie Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time was, back in the 1970s, Atlanta was the banking capital of
the Southeast, partly by virtue of Mills B. Lane, the legendary
chairman of Citizens and Southern Bank. The bank, later best known
as C&AMP;S, was a powerhouse that fueled much of the economic
development, and Lane's progressive style helped to set the tone
for what we called the New South.
</P>
<P>
   Happenstance, some elements of history and other factors have
shifted the mantle of financial leadership away from Atlanta,
mostly toward Charlotte _ even though Atlanta remains the leader in
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   We were reminded recently that quietly but surely Atlanta is
regaining some financial distinction. This time it's in the new
realm of electronic communication and the new public appetite for
banking at home, or from the desk at the office, or rapid
transactions between companies.
</P>
<P>
   Security First Technologies, a name that does not trip off the
tongue like NationsBank or SunTrust, announced a $1.4 billion deal
last week that could solidify the company's position as an
important supplier of software and technology that helps banks
extend electronic service to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Both residential and commercial customers benefit from the
programs, fueling the gradual tilt toward banking by computer
rather than the traditional ways. From all appearances, it is the
wave of the future in the world of finance.
</P>
<P>
   Security First, subject to approval by all concerned, has moved
to buy competitors FICS and Edify. The company is adopting the name
S1. Furthermore, Intuit is purchasing a 2.5 percent stake in S1 for
$50 million, enabling both companies to deploy Intuit's commercial
systems for tax filing, as well as handling payroll and tax
payments.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it a big deal is not the dollar figure of $1.4
billion, though even today that is certainly substantial. What is
big is that, in the words of Security First Chief Executive Officer
James S. Mahan III, the deal ``rounds out our product offering and
takes our strongest competitor out of the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if you want to do electronic transactions, very
soon the chances will be that S1 might be the supplier of the
technology that makes it happen. Who knows _ banks may soon carry a
seal on the window, ``S1 Inside.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Security First is making itself a fundamental force
in the world of electronic finance much as Microsoft did in the
world of computers. Microsoft chose to master the operating systems
of computers and left the vicissitudes of the marketplace to the
computer hardware developers like Compaq, Hewlett-Packard and
others. It turned out to be a good choice.
</P>
<P>
   In somewhat the same way, Security First is supplying the muscle
to electronic banking and leaving the shape and presentation,
marketing and capitalization of the services to the style of the
companies.
</P>
<P>
   S1 is not dominant. In fact it competes against a giant called
CheckFree Holdings, as well as smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   But it has increased its power and reach, and according to some
analysts, now becomes more of a competitive force overseas.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this a true Atlanta story is that the basic
underlying technology that launched Security First as we know it
was developed in the early 1980s by SecureWare, a company spawned
by the Georgia Tech incubator program.
</P>
<P>
   It is that technology that is really driving the growing
business now enjoyed by S1 and its big customers, which include a
dozen major banks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
