<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSIDE-LINE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    INSIDE LINE
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By John McCosh
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hill to be on time to push Northern Arc
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Hill vows he'll be on time for the big Northern Arc
showdown this week. The chairman of the Gwinnett County and the
Atlanta Regional commissions got stuck in traffic earlier this
month when a planning committee debated a blueprint for the
region's future and decided to try to kill the Northern Arc.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday the transportation plan goes before the full ARC board
and Hill, an ardent Northern Arc supporter, says he'll be there for
the lobbying, as well as the voting. The board is set to select a
group of projects that its staff will test for air quality over the
next several months with the aim of adopting a final transportation
plan in March.
</P>
<P>
   Success will mean metro Atlanta is in compliance with federal
air pollution limits and road building can commence. Hill says the
new Georgia Regional Transportation Authority is likely to build
the 59-mile arc across the northern suburbs even if it's left out
of the ARC plan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back at the Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce,
members say the Northern Arc and the whole transportation plan
ought to be shelved until the kinks are worked out. In a letter
sent to the ARC last week, chamber members complain the current
plan anticipates spending lots of money on transportation fixes
over the next 25 years with little hope for improved mobility in
the region. Better to delay the vote and create a plan that at
least forecasts an improvement, the letter says.
</P>
<P>
   The business group wants specific proposals, such as the
Northern Arc, taken out of the group of projects that will be put
through the air quality test. And it wants the ARC to come up with
a comprehensive and cost-effective transportation system for the
region before adopting a plan.
</P>
<P>
   Contested roads continue to grow
</P>
<P>
   While the lawyers negotiate, the asphalt keeps spreading,
bringing 11 contested roads in eight metro Atlanta counties closer
to completion. Environmentalists and road builders are extending
until June 21 a deadline to settle a lawsuit over roads that were
grandfathered through what government officials hope are loopholes
in the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Environmental Law Center, on behalf of
environmental groups, is targeting 11 roads in progress in an
effort to coerce governments to spend more money on alternative
transportation such as rail lines, bike paths and sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   It's $140 million worth of projects, including the widening of
Peachtree Industrial Boulevard in Gwinnett and a new 6-mile road in
south Fulton County.
</P>
<P>
   $50 oversight sends Air Touch to court
</P>
<P>
   For want of $50, Air Touch Cellular is having to make a federal
case out of a proposed cell tower in Forsyth County. In 1998 the
company applied to the county for a tower along Ga. 400 to meet
growing demand in the corridor, sending in its $200 fee. Problem:
The fee was $250. According to Air Touch's recent U.S. District
Court lawsuit, a county staffer said not to worry, simply pay the
$50 when picking up the permit. Problem: The county declared a
moratorium in February before Air Touch picked up the permit. Last
month the county sent Air Touch a check for the $200, with an
explanation that the fee was insufficient and the site needed
rezoning, which wouldn't happen during the moratorium. The county
has until next month to respond to the cellular company's charges.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: horizon(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   You can reach John McCosh at 770-263-3866.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
