<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    INSIDER TRADING
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Executives have many reasons to sell stock in their companies.
</P>
<P>
   For John R. Alm, who last month was promoted to executive vice
president and principal operating officer of Coca-Cola Enterprises,
it's to help disadvantaged and troubled youths.
</P>
<P>
   Alm, 53, who previously was chief financial officer, sold 60,000
shares on April 28 at between $36.13 and $36.38 each, totaling
$2,171,830.
</P>
<P>
   That's after he exercised an option entitling him to acquire the
shares at $4.63 each, totaling $277,800.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sale was to fund the construction of a summer camp in
Wyoming for disadvantaged and at-risk youth,'' said spokeswoman
Laura B. Asman. ``It's his own individual initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   Alm, one of two principal operating officers, still holds
1,039,209 shares directly and indirectly, worth $36,632,117 at
Friday's price of $35.25 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Lowry F. Kline, chief administrative officer, exercised an
option for 29,000 shares on April 28 at $4.63 each, totaling
$134,270. He then sold them at between $36.13 and $36.38 each,
totaling $1,048,020. Kline now holds 542,080 shares directly and
indirectly, worth $19,108,320. G. David Van Houten, president of
the Central North America Group, exercised an option for 22,500
shares on April 28 at $4.83 each, totaling $108,675. He then sold
them at between $36 and $36.13 each, totaling $810,260. Van Houten
now holds 338,859 shares directly and indirectly, worth
$11,944,779.
</P>
<P>
   Among other Georgia companies:
</P>
<P>
   At American Business Products, Lawrence L. Gellerstedt III,
chairman, president and chief executive, bought 12,550 shares from
April 26 to 29 at between $15.38 and $15.88 each, totaling
$196,612. He now holds 45,142 shares directly and indirectly, worth
$553,109 at Friday's price of $15.75 on the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   At AFLAC, Daniel Paul Amos, president and chief executive,
exercised an option for 108,600 shares on April 27 at $9.42 each,
totaling $1,023,012. To cover expenses of the transaction, he
turned in 50,400 shares to the company at $55.47 each, totaling
$2,795,688. He now holds 3,392,328 shares directly and indirectly,
worth $174,916,910.
</P>
<P>
   Kriss Cloninger III, chief financial officer, exercised an
option for 112,096 shares on April 28 at between $9.42 and $15.83
each, totaling $1,177,388. He then sold 60,000 shares at $54.75
each, totaling $3,285,000. Cloninger now holds 119,347 shares
directly and indirectly, worth $6,153,830.
</P>
<P>
   E. Stephen Purdom, executive vice president of insurance
operations, exercised an option for 140,140 shares from April 12 to
29 at between $4.90 and $15.83 each, totaling $1,584,808. He then
sold 120,000 shares at between $51 and $55 each, totaling
$6,520,000. Purdom now holds 110,776 shares directly and
indirectly, worth $5,712,042.
</P>
<P>
   At Centennial HealthCare, Alan C. Dahl, chief financial officer,
bought 13,300 shares from April 15 to 17 at between $3.75 and $4.06
each, totaling $50,278. He now holds 72,792 shares directly and
indirectly, worth $404,906 at Friday's price of $5.56 1/4 on
Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Kent C. Fosha Sr., executive vice president of operations,
bought 1,000 shares on April 15 at $3.75 each, totaling $3,750. He
now holds 8,970 shares, worth $49,896.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence W. Lepley Jr., president of the Paragon Rehabilitation
unit, indirectly acquired 26,500 shares from April 16 to 19 at
$4.31 each, totaling $114,215. He now holds 109,725 shares directly
and indirectly, worth $610,345.
</P>
<P>
   Bertil D. Nordin, director, bought 6,000 shares on April 22 at
$4.63 each, totaling $27,780. Nordin now holds 7,500 shares, worth
$41,719.
</P>
<P>
   At Georgia-Pacific, James E. Bostic Jr., senior vice president
of environmental, government affairs and communications, exercised
an option for 10,000 shares on April 27 at $51.68 each, totaling
$516,800. He then sold 7,235 shares at $90.16 each, totaling
$652,308. Bostic now holds 16,808 Georgia Pacific Group shares,
worth $1,568,397 at Friday's price of $93.31 1/4 on the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   Donald L. Glass, president and chief executive of Timber Co.,
exercised an option for 23,400 shares on April 28 and 29 at $51.68
each, totaling $1,209,312. He then sold them at $93.88 each,
totaling $2,196,792. Glass now holds 10,446 shares directly and
indirectly, worth $974,742.
</P>
<P>
   James F. Kelley, senior vice president of law and general
counsel, exercised an option for 12,000 shares on April 26 at
$51.68 each, totaling $620,160. He then sold them at $90.63 each,
totaling $1,087,560. Kelley now holds 827 shares directly and
indirectly, worth $77,169.
</P>
<P>
   Clint M. Kennedy, executive vice president of pulp and
paperboard, exercised an option for 16,500 shares on April 27 at
$51.68 each, totaling $852,720. He then sold them at $90 each,
totaling $1,485,000. Kennedy now holds 11,104 shares directly and
indirectly, worth $1,036,142.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Terrell, vice president and controller, exercised an
option for 5,300 shares from April 23 to 26 at $57.29 each,
totaling $303,637. He then sold 8,350 shares at between $90 and
$90.75 each, totaling $755,475. Terrell also indirectly sold 225
shares on April 14 at $90 each, totaling $20,250. He now holds
3,400 shares directly and indirectly, worth $317,263.
</P>
<P>
   At John H. Harland, Richard C. Blum &AMP; Associates, beneficial
owner, indirectly acquired 253,000 shares from April 1 to 15 at
$13.25 each, totaling $3,352,250. It now holds 6,286,000 shares
directly and indirectly, worth $111,183,620 at Friday's price of
$17.68 3/4 on the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   John H. Weitnauer Jr., chairman, bought 5,000 shares on April 29
at $16.50 each, totaling $82,500. He now holds 24,359 shares, worth
$430,850.
</P>
<P>
   At Maxim Group, Joseph J. Jillson, director, bought 10,000
shares on April 9 at $8.13 each, totaling $81,300. He now holds
110,000 shares, worth $776,875 at Friday's NYSE price of $7.06 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Richard A. Kaplan, director, sold 426,048 shares from April 7 to
27 at between $7.75 and $9.21 each, totaling $3,531,950. He now
holds 219,252 shares, worth $1,548,467.
</P>
<P>
   John Michael Nixon, director, bought 20,000 shares on April 14
at $10 each, totaling $200,000. He now holds 140,000 shares, worth
$988,750.
</P>
<P>
   At Rock-Tenn, Edward E. Bowns, executive vice president, sold
79,200 Class A shares on April 23 at $14.50 each, totaling
$1,148,400. He now holds 8,047 Class A shares directly and
indirectly, worth $111,652 at Friday's price of $13.87 1/2 on the
NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   At Roper Industries, Larry K. Christensen, group vice
president-industrial controls, exercised an option for 1,900 shares
on April 19 at $3.75 each, totaling $7,125. He now holds 15,052
shares directly and indirectly, worth $494,835 at Friday's price of
$32.87 1/2 on the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   At Shaw Industries, Thomas Grady Cousins, director, bought 600
shares on April 29 at $20 each, totaling $12,000. He now holds
43,325 shares, worth $774,434 at Friday's price of $17.87 1/2 on
the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   At WestPoint Stevens, Robert J. Gehm, executive vice president
of sales, sold 6,000 Class A shares on April 19 at $36.81 each,
totaling $220,860. He now holds 56,785 Class A shares directly and
indirectly, worth $34.62 1/2 at Friday's price of $1,966,181 on
Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission requires insiders
(officers, directors, persons with policy-making roles) to report
their transactions within 10 days after the month in which they
took place. Beneficial owners, or those owning 10 percent or more
of any publicly held company, also must report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
