<HEADER>
A8624 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLSTREET24-COX     05-24 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLSTREET24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech's market model signals `sell'
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Serrvice
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stock market model at Georgia Tech recently registered a
``sell'' signal.
</P>
<P>
   That alone would be something to think about. It becomes even
more thinkable when you consider that it's only the fourth sell
signal from that model in more than a decade, and the previous
three were in 1994, 1990 and 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Just to refresh your memory, 1994 was a turbulent year of rising
interest rates. Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 1.5 percent
for the year, and the Dow Jones industrial average gained only 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 fell 6.6 percent in 1990 due to a Saddam
Hussein-inspired stock sell-off that everybody agrees was a ``bear
market.'' The Dow fell 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And who needs to be reminded of 1987, the year of the greatest
crash in stock market history?
</P>
<P>
   Why does the stock market model register sell again?
</P>
<P>
   Because bond yields are high, explains Fred C. Allvine.
</P>
<P>
   Allvine is the ubiquitous Georgia Tech professor who is also
director of Tech's Stock Market Project, monitor of the market.
</P>
<P>
   A reading of 50 on Tech's zero-to-100 model is a ``buy'' signal,
and a reading of 20 is a ``sell.'' At the moment, says Allvine, the
model stands at 11.6.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't the model signal a sell last summer, when stock
prices were clearly headed for the cellar?
</P>
<P>
   Before that correction was over, the market had tanked in its
worst sell-off since 1990. The Dow fell from 9,338 on July 17 to
7,539 on Aug. 31, or just over 19 percent (other indexes declined
further).
</P>
<P>
   But there was no sell signal because bond yields also fell.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year Treasury yield dropped from 5.92 percent on May 14
to 4.71 on Oct. 5, or 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of the correction, the stock market has rallied
vigorously _ astonishingly might be a better term.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow is up about 3,500 points since early October to its
recent high of 11,108, or almost 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the 30-year Treasury yield has also moved higher, from 4.84
percent in October to a recent high of 5.92 _ a gain of 25.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Explanations for the rising bond yields vary, but the basic idea
is that bond traders are increasingly worried about inflation.
That, in turn, would lead to higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The parallel rise in stock prices and bond yields is similar to
earlier situations when the stock market model signaled a sell.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists are concerned that the rise in bond yields at a time
when stocks are under pressure could lead to the next stock market
correction. Rising yields make bonds highly attractive to investors
as an alternative to stocks.
</P>
<P>
   A scary event is all it would take to trigger such a sell-off,
according to this thesis.
</P>
<P>
   Bearish analysts contend that stocks are under pressure largely
because of their high valuations as measured by price-to-earnings
and other ratios.
</P>
<P>
   Stock market bulls argue, however, that the market really isn't
overpriced, when you consider how low inflation is.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the Federal Reserve to suggest that inflation could
become a problem again. And Fed members said last week they
``lean'' toward an interest rate increase to ward off inflation _ a
sentiment that could keep bond yields from falling very far.
</P>
<P>
   It may be getting difficult for an individual investor to decide
what to do as Wall Street's big names debate the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Allvine has a suggestion. ``The market may go up from here,'' he
said, ``but the prudent investor should be cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
