<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 10:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8629 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KASICH-$ADV30-COX     05-24 2169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASICH-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KASICH FOLLOWING HIS HEART, MAYBE TO THE WHITE HOUSE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories for release
Sunday, May 30.
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DERRY, N.H. _ The Ford Explorer rips through hilly streets while
passenger John Kasich shuffles papers looking for the outline to
tomorrow morning's commencement speech. He's got the full text, but
he needs the outline.
</P>
<P>
   The outline, man!
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go from a prepared text,'' he said, ``and these things
are becoming more and more important. Now we've got 1,200 people
tomorrow and I haven't spent 10 seconds thinking about it. Of
course, if I think about it for 10 seconds or 10 hours, it doesn't
really change things much.''
</P>
<P>
   He has just left an evening meeting with GOP leaders in
Goffstown and is on his way to a wine-and-cheese in Derry and he's
been invited back to the local television station at 11 p.m. to do
one more live shot for the day. Naturally, he can't say no to TV so
he's fretting about when he can work through his speech to the
graduating class at New Hampshire Community Technical College.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse is that even when he's crunched for prep
time, Kasich alone decides how he's going to say what he wants to
say. He will not simply read a speech. Or he can't. Or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read,'' he said, ``it just doesn't come from the
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a single word to explain why this modestly
well-known congressman from Columbus, Ohio, is campaigning for the
Republican nomination for president, this is it. Heart.
</P>
<P>
   You've heard the phrase ``fire in the belly'' to be president?
Well, Kasich's whole abdomen is fully involved. Belly, lungs, bones
and heart.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich is the antithesis of Gov. George W. Bush, the anointed
Texan who so far has been aloof and unavailable to campaign for
president even while the GOP establishment has lined up behind him.
Where Bush is financially secure, in command of the polls and
building unparalleled party support without leaving Texas, Kasich
is hustling for every buck, nearly invisible on TV and wearing out
shoes trying to meet every man, woman and child in New Hampshire
and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich tells you this doesn't intimidate him, and his friends in
Washington and Columbus tell you he means it. Kasich believes he
should be campaigning for the presidency right now, and that's all
there is to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When John believes,'' said longtime friend Rep. David L.
Hobson, R-Ohio, ``he believes.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in 1978 Kasich was a 26-year-old staffer in the
Ohio Senate who believed he should be a state senator. So he quit
his job and began a door-to-door-to-door campaign that 13 months
later culminated in his unseating a prominent Democrat whose family
name adorned a large funeral home and the local landmark dam.
</P>
<P>
   It was such a long shot even local Republicans didn't want to
put their stamp on his candidacy, barely bothering to endorse
``shaggy John,'' the recent Ohio State University graduate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shocker,'' said Bob Blair, who was the Republican
Party's other Senate staffer. ``We said, `You can't do this!' It
was an upset for all time.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, while in Columbus, fellow Republicans asked Kasich to do
something he didn't believe in _ raise taxes. So at 28 he protested
by writing his own budget for the state of Ohio. Today he refers to
that as the event that ``unleashed John Kasich.''
</P>
<P>
   From the state legislature, Kasich went on to believe he should
run for Congress, which led to the nation's only Republican victory
over a Democratic incumbent in 1982. And since he believed in
greater fiscal restraint than he was seeing from Washington
leaders, he wrote or co-wrote his own version of the federal budget
in 1989, 1990, 1991, 1993 and 1994. He maneuvered them all to the
House floor for votes, but none came close to passing.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1995, Republicans were in the majority and Kasich was
chairman of the Budget Committee _ a job he won by outworking a
senior lawmaker from North Carolina. Suddenly, Kasich's obsessive
drive to balance the federal budget matured from a quixotic
adventure to a rational goal. Buoyed by a roaring economy that
dramatically raised the government's income, the Kasich-negotiated
spending plan became America's first balanced budget in 30 years
when President Clinton signed it in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Now Kasich debates with himself, and sometimes his presidential
exploratory committee staff, about how much of the Budget Committee
wars he should include in his stump speeches in New Hampshire and
Iowa, home of the first two presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of why I need to talk about what I've done in the past is
to show them that I'm the one guy who actually has moved
mountains,'' he said from the Explorer's front seat. ``A lot of
what I say, people might think is too idealistic. But, boy, I've
been able to get a tremendous amount done in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a budget speech for commencement? Naw, he thinks. A
recounting of his effort to abolish the B-2, which led to a
reduction in the number produced? No, these kids don't want that,
man.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, bigger than the question of what to say to technical
college graduates is the looming, seeping, pervasive issue of
whether Kasich's tenacity can move this biggest mountain of all:
the presidential nomination of the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a quirky campaign with a quirky candidate who has
absolutely no chance to be elected president of the United States
in 2000,'' said Washington political analyst Stuart Rothenberg.
``No chance.''
</P>
<P>
   What's quirky about Kasich is that he loves (and knows)
contemporary rock n' roll, campaigns in Iowa against federal
subsidies for a sacred local product called ethanol or against the
Lakers in Los Angeles, and is happy to speak at a Democratic
fund-raiser if a close friend and Democrat asks.
</P>
<P>
   The picture of the sedate, sober, cautious politician doesn't
apply to Kasich. You hear the term ``boyish'' around him a lot,
which some observers, like Rothenberg, say is the root of his
problem. The knock on Kasich is that he's too energetic, too eager,
too undisciplined to read a prepared speech, for heaven's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is 47, he looks 37 and he acts 27,'' Rothenberg said. ``He
lacks the maturity that people want to see in their president.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kasich, and those close to him, say critics like Rothenberg
are missing the big picture. They say it's a mistake to confuse
enthusiasm and energy with immaturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's his freshness,'' Hobson said. ``I'm not quite sure
why that happens, because he's very mature in his thinking, he's
very conservative about money, which are attributes of a mature
person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as his views go, and as far as his emotions go , I can
tell you he's a very mature person. I've seen him in major
negotiations with White House people where he was the strongest one
in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Kasich: ``It's good that they underestimate me. ... When
you're thinking about being president of the United States and
people look at you and think you're boyish, you have to work extra
hard. On the other hand, it means that I can do 18 more events than
anybody else, so I wouldn't trade it.''
</P>
<P>
   As an indelible function of his personality, Kasich's speaking
style is boisterous to the point of nearly being fervent. When John
believes, he believes out loud. He delivers a message of broad
populism that says returning authority and taxes to people will
raise their feelings of control, heighten their sense of
responsibility for the world, and restore a spirit of hope.
</P>
<P>
   And he says it with a delivery that most closely resembles the
blam-blam football commentary of John Madden. A Kasich speech is
filled with ``You know whats?'' and ``I'll tell you whys!''
</P>
<P>
   On religion in politics: ``A lot of people say they're of faith,
but they're not. It's like me standing in my garage and saying I'm
a Ford Escort. I mean, just 'cause I say it doesn't make it so.''
</P>
<P>
   On schools: ``Public education is not going to improve without
competition (in the form of tax-funded vouchers that let parents
pay for private school). The fear of opening it up is really a
comment on how much we trust mothers and fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   On making faith in God a feature of his campaign: ``I'm not into
this to be a preacher; if I wanted to be a preacher I would have
gone to seminary. But at the same time, I think it's appropriate
for me to reflect the fact that I think faith is important to a
great society. And also, I tell people because I think it's a good
tip. It's like giving a guy a tip on how to hit a golf ball. I
think it's an important part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   On George W. Bush: ``I don't underestimate the challenge, but
you know what, everybody has a tough challenge. He has a long way
to go. He can't get the green jacket (of the Masters tournament
champion) until he plays all 18 holes, and it's just amazing what
can happen in one round of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   And he isn't alone in his thinking. For every Rothenberg who
doubts, there's a Charles Cook, whose Cook Political Report in
Washington rivals Rothenberg's publication, who finds Kasich to be
too forceful a personality to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an interesting person,'' said Cook, who saw Kasich in New
Hampshire recently. ``He's got a magnetic personality and you kind
of feel good listening to him. You see a lot of ordinary people
nodding their heads a lot when he's speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook's view is that the Bush juggernaut is likely to steam
unimpeded into the nomination for president, but there's a chance
Bush, still a novice campaigner, will stumble long enough to give
the trailing pack a chance.
</P>
<P>
   And in a group that includes Elizabeth Dole, Dan Quayle, Sen.
John McCain, Steve Forbes, Patrick Buchanan, Lamar Alexander,
Christian activist Gary Bauer, Sen. Bob Smith and Baltimore radio
personality Alan Keyes, Cook sees Kasich as a fresh face with the
potential to break through and fill the gap a Bush mistake could
create.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it's a long shot, but I wouldn't rule him out,'' Cook
said. ``There's just too much talent (in Kasich) and too many
uncertainties about the race to rule him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Cook said Kasich has drawn together a highly respected
campaign team that includes veterans such as communications
strategist Ed Gillespie and pollster Ed Goeas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If John Kasich had no chance, you wouldn't have the type of
people in the Republican Party signing up to work with him,'' Cook
said. ``Either these guys aren't as smart as their reputations, or
this isn't crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kasich strategy is simple. He knows he can't match Bush's
reported $50 million (he'll be happy to collect $18 million,
although so far he hasn't filed reports with the Federal Election
Commission because he formed his exploratory committee in Ohio.)
But with the primary season condensed into a few key days in
February and March, Kasich is hoping heavy publicity generated by a
surprisingly strong showing in New Hampshire and Iowa will catapult
him into contention in primaries in California and New York weeks
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was a nationwide primary, right off the bat it would be
beyond my reach,'' Kasich said. ``But the fact is there are three
launch sites in America: Cape Canaveral, Iowa and New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   But first he must overcome the notion in his own party that Bush
is the only choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party tends to almost honor the divine right of kings,''
Kasich said. ``Frankly, the inability of my party to have an open,
raucous, tumultuous debate of ideas and people limits the ability
of the party to excite. The question is, can we get out of that
habit in this election?''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate question is, what is he going to say to the
graduating class of New Hampshire Community Technical College in
Nashua? An enormous tent has been pitched on the lawn this Saturday
morning and Kasich is inside now working through his philosophy on
how to succeed in life.
</P>
<P>
   He squeezes a little of his Budget Committee history into the
part about perseverance, but only a little. He talks about
believing in your dreams, in loving yourself, in loving your
neighbors, in finding time to laugh, in sharing your gifts with
others.
</P>
<P>
   He never mentions that he's running for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``And maybe at the end,'' he says in closing, `` people will be
able to say the world is a little better because we came this
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, the audience rises into a sustained ovation. A man, up
out of his folding chair, volunteers with raised eyebrows, ``Good
speaker!''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Cote of Nashua had never heard of John Kasich and had no
idea he was exploring a run for the presidency. Cote just came to
see his 27-year-old daughter getting her life back on track with a
degree in massage therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll do well,'' he said of Kasich. ``He has a good
sense of direction about him.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
