<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8632 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BRAZIL-OUTLOOK-REVI     05-24 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BRAZIL-OUTLOOK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS PANICKED, BUT BRAZIL DIDN'T 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
 (DW)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
traveled to the United States early this month, and everywhere he
went the same people who four months before were worrying about an
Asian-style meltdown of Brazil's economy praised him for his astute
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton led the chorus, expressing
relief at ``the substantial progress'' Brazil had made in
recovering from the fiscal crisis, which led to a 40 percent
devaluation of its currency in January.
</P>
<P>
   During his tour Cardoso also stopped in New York, where he was
peppered with questions about Brazil's implementation of a $41.5
billion economic rescue package backed by the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Left unaddressed, however, was a more fundamental issue: To what
extent did the crisis reflect genuine deficiencies in the Brazilian
economy and to what degree was it a self-fulfilling prophecy,
brought on by panic and myopia in the global capital market itself?
</P>
<P>
   At this juncture, no one denies that Brazil's currency, the
real, had become overvalued against the dollar and needed to be
adjusted. Throughout his first term, Cardoso's main policy goal had
been to bring inflation, traditionally the country's biggest
bugaboo, under control; that made him eager to avoid any sharp and
sudden devaluation and the surge of higher prices that would follow
it.
</P>
<P>
   But Brazilians, from officials to the average citizen, are
increasingly convinced that a series of ``simplistic comparisons''
and ``undue generalizations,'' as Minister of Finance Pedro Malan
put it in a recent interview, made the situation last January worse
than it might have been and overlooked the country's underlying
strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the world's eighth-largest economy has begun to right
itself, for example, all the talk about ``global contagion'' seems
particularly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Except in the estimation of some traders abroad, Brazil was
never really comparable to Indonesia, where a family dynasty
enriched itself at the country's expense. Nor was it equivalent to
Russia, where the collapse of a communist state has allowed a mafia
to seize control of the economy, or even Mexico, where one corrupt
and ossified political party has wielded power for 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street needs a geography lesson,'' Marcus Vinicius
Pratini de Moraes, a former Cabinet minister who is now president
of the Brazilian Association of Exporters, said recently. ``A bank
goes bust in Moscow and they sell their Brazilian shares? They
should go back to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Too late for Brazil and its 165 million people, who have had to
endure lost jobs and recession since January, stock markets around
the world seemed to recognize that error this month.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, speculative pressure on Argentina and its currency last
week generated some turbulence here and in other Latin American
countries. But Boris Yeltsin's dismissal of Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov in Russia caused barely a ripple.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the announcement was being made in Moscow, the Sao
Paulo stock market rose to an 18-month high, fueled largely by the
return of foreign money, and the Brazilian government was able to
announce the sixth cut in interest rates in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
   Other measures of Brazil's strengths are, if anything, more
revealing. In contrast to the traumas that have wracked Russia and
the Asian tigers recently, Latin America's largest country has in
just 15 years successfully made the transition, without violence or
social trauma, from military dictatorship to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Its democracy is often raucous, as is demonstrated by a current
congressional investigation into insider trading that took place at
the time of January's devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   But even though Cardoso has to work within a system of checks
and balances more restrictive than the systems facing his Asian,
Russian and Mexican counterparts, he has time and again delivered
on promises to restructure the Brazilian state and economy.
</P>
<P>
   After the agreement with the IMF was signed last November,
investors and officials abroad immediately began to view a
reduction of Brazil's often-generous social security benefits as a
test of Cardoso's resolve. Though the Brazilian Congress dithered
for two months, it eventually passed the legislation, which
requires a constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   As political leaders here have noted, none of the countries that
have been hectoring Brazil on this matter _ not Germany, not
France, not Italy, and certainly not the United States _ have
themselves begun to come to grips with the issue at home.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the steps Brazil had taken to modernize its economy
even before the January crisis were substantial, more than what
many other countries have done in decades. When he took office in
1995, Cardoso inherited a highly protectionist economy. But he
quickly lowered tariffs, allowing trade and competition to surge,
and sold off one inefficient state-run monopoly after another:
ports, electricity, mining, telecommunications, railways, banks and
more.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso maintained that course, showing unusual political
courage, even when a harsh recession set in after the eruption of
the Asian crisis in 1997, threatening both his re-election and
efforts to stabilize both prices and the real. Brazilian voters
were mature enough to resist opposition blandishments of short-term
relief in favor of what they saw as the long-term payoff that would
make their country an economic power: stability and growth.
</P>
<P>
   The late Carroll Quigley, the Georgetown University professor
whom Clinton has cited as his most influential teacher, used to
define capitalism as ``a system of accounting that ignores social
costs.'' Judging from Brazil's recent experience, the converse is
also true: market-driven philosophies are unwilling to grant credit
for social gains that cannot immediately be measured.
</P>
<P>
   To Riordan Roett, an expert on the Western Hemisphere at Johns
Hopkins University, Cardoso's most significant achievement may be
that during his first term ``more Brazilians were lifted from
poverty than in the past 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   That feat, a result of the same inflation control and currency
stabilization program that came under speculative pressure in
January, has turned millions of poor Brazilians into consumers and
makes the country more attractive to foreign investors hunting for
new markets.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the crisis, a new study appeared here showing
that between 1994 and 1998, high school enrollments in Brazil
increased 37 percent, as parents realized that they no longer
needed to yank their children out of classes and send them to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are extraordinary numbers for so short a period,'' a
``gigantic leap,'' Claudio de Moura Castro, an economist who is the
co-author of the study, wrote in the news magazine Veja.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5357 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BRAZIL-OUTLOOK-REVI     05-24 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BRAZIL-OUTLOOK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS PANICKED, BUT BRAZIL DIDN'T 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
 (DW)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
