<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8636 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-ISRAEL-POLITICS-REV     05-24 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ISRAEL-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S NEXT LEADER PICKS UP RABIN'S MANTLE AND ALTERS IT TO FIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
 (dw)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A month before he was resoundingly defeated last
Monday by Ehud Barak, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu explained
in an interview that attacks on his personality reflected one key
thing: the Israeli left's continuing need to blame somebody for the
assassination of Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed at the time to be a curiously outmoded interpretation.
What? It had nothing to do with his galvanizing personality as
prime minister, the way he alienated and divided even his Cabinet?
Was everyone really harkening back to 1995, when Netanyahu, the
opposition leader, was accused of legitimizing an atmosphere of
incitement against the prime minister, Rabin?
</P>
<P>
   On the night of Barak's victory last week, when tens of
thousands of young Israelis burned memorial candles for Rabin in
the square where he was assassinated, it was clear that Netanyahu _
``Bibi,'' as Israel called him _ had a point.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that the Rabin assassination was an undigested
trauma for many Israelis, and that Barak's victory allowed a kind
of public catharsis of repressed grief over a national martyr whose
death at the hands of an extremist Jew changed the way many
Israelis felt about being Israeli.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bibi is still being held responsible and he probably has to be
retired for the country to get beyond Rabin's murder,'' Yaron
Ezrahi, a political scientist, said several days before Netanyahu's
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Barak understood this, too. He is skillfully navigating his way
through the lingering images of Rabin, his own military and
political mentor. On election night, to declare his victory, he
joined the huge crowd that had converged on Rabin Square in Tel
Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   It was his night, but he celebrated amid huge banner pictures of
the slain prime minister. He stood beside Rabin's widow, Leah. He
looked into the sky and he talked directly to Rabin. He effectively
dedicated to him his electoral triumph, a landslide by Israeli
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Barak's first act as prime minister-elect was
to visit the Rabin grave, as if to lay to rest once and for all the
great sadness before taking his first steps into the future.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as prime minister, Barak's challenge will be to diverge
from the model of his mentor, to emulate Rabin and, having learned
from his political mistakes, to move beyond him. He quickly made
clear that he intends to do so. He moved instantly to start
negotiating a broad coalition government, rather than rely on a
razor-thin majority as Rabin did.
</P>
<P>
   If Rabin's life was ended by the blood passions in Israeli
society, then successfully following in his footsteps means healing
Israel. It means being slightly less of a commander, and more of a
consensus builder.
</P>
<P>
   Like Rabin, Barak, 57, represents the old Israel. He is the very
model of the Zionist pioneer man. His mother lost nearly her whole
family in Treblinka. His father grew up an orphan after his family
was killed in a pogrom in Lithuania. He was born on a kibbutz
before Israel was born as a state. He spent his life defending the
dream of Israel, rising steadily through the elite military ranks
to become army chief of staff. He is Ashkenazi, a descendant of
Europeans; he plays classical piano; he is resolutely secular.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a typical representative of the species of new man the
fathers of the Zionist movement tried to create in Israel,'' Tom
Segev, an author, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate insider, Barak is coming to power at a moment when
kibbutzim are aging, or turning into shopping centers, and when the
supposed outsiders _ the Sephardim, who came from Middle Eastern
countries; the Russian immigrants, the ultra-Orthodox _ are
redefining what it means to be Israeli.
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis who voted for Barak said they would have much
preferred to see a new breed of political leader arise, to see
citizen-candidates rather than generals. After all, the era of the
great wars is fading. Barak's classic acts of heroism _ leading a
unit that liberated a Sabena airplane from hijackers at Tel Aviv in
1972, for instance _ happened a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe, they said last week, Israel is not ready for
political normalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week I wrote about Barak that he is a somewhat outdated
portrait of Israel,'' Ofer Shelah, a columnist for the newspaper
Maariv, said last week. ``But we are lucky that is the case: We
need someone who can take us back a little, to the days when being
Israeli was an aspiration and not something accursed.''
</P>
<P>
   As a peacemaker, Barak is no radical. He does not talk, as did
Shimon Peres, his predecessor at the helm of Labor, about forging a
new Middle East in which Israelis and Palestinians live in a
harmonious political and economic integration. He aspires to
separation from the Palestinians; they have their land, Israel has
its land, and everyone goes about their business.
</P>
<P>
   It is the ideology of the pre-state kibbutzniks.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians, in the wake of their gloating enthusiasm about
Netanyahu's loss, started listening more carefully to Barak's
oratory and getting depressed about the hard line he took. But
Barak is very different from his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   He does not consider himself to be the reluctant inheritor of
international peace agreements he'd just as soon renege on, as
Netanyahu did. Instead, he is determined to build on the existing
agreements, establish professional diplomatic relationships with
the Arab world and move expeditiously toward final settlement with
Israel's neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   In a documentary film by Claude Lanzmann, Barak, who is
interviewed, says he sees Jewish history as a struggle between
fanaticism or extremism and pragmatism.
</P>
<P>
   The purists, he says, have ended up dead, like the zealots who
killed themselves at Masada. Barak is not a zealot _ just as his
mentor Yitzhak Rabin wasn't. Unlike Rabin, though, he comes into
power at a time when the right wing has withered.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin trod a path for him, and Netanyahu, a reluctant
peacemaker, nonetheless continued down the same road.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is a time when pragmatism, at least on the issue of
peace, has a better chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
