<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8638 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CHINA-HONGKONG-REVI     05-24 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CHINA-HONGKONG-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG SEEKS ITS OWN CHINESE WALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(dw) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ China's newest city is crowded, expensive, polluted
and mired in its worst recession since World War II. Yet to listen
to Hong Kong's leaders, every person in mainland China with the
slightest claim to live here would scramble across the border if
the gates were opened.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, Hong Kong has been in a lather over the prospect
that it is about to be inundated by Chinese immigrants. The fears,
which began after a court here granted residency to mainland
Chinese who have at least one parent in Hong Kong, escalated into
near-hysteria when the government estimated that more than 1.6
million people would be eligible for residency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that Hong Kong cannot bear the burden of these
1.67 million people,'' said Tung Chee-hwa, the territory's chief
executive, in a typically charged response. ``The consequences are
unimaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Tung asked Beijing, in effect, to overrule the court
by reinterpreting a part of Hong Kong's constitution that deals
with residency rights. Pro-democracy leaders accuse Tung of
flouting the rule of law, which has been the cornerstone of Hong
Kong's economic success and was supposed to survive the transition
from British to Chinese rule.
</P>
<P>
   That Hong Kong would put its legal system at risk to keep out an
influx from the mainland shows how vulnerable this enclave still
feels. Nearly two years after Hong Kong reverted to Chinese
sovereignty _ in a grand experiment known as ``one country, two
systems'' _ people here regard Hong Kong as a Xanadu that could be
spoiled by the masses from the vast Chinese hinterland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a typical immigrant mentality that says `I got in, now
close the door behind me,''' said Martin Lee, the leader of Hong
Kong's Democratic Party. ``This whole debate has brought out the
worst in people.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Hong Kong's woes, there is no disputing its allure. It
generates a gross domestic product of $25,200 per person, 33 times
that of the rest of China. It has more Rolls-Royces per square mile
than any city in the world. In a country of 1.2 billion people,
half of whom have not made their first phone call, Hong Kong has so
many cellular phones that movie theaters ask patrons not to talk on
them during love scenes.
</P>
<P>
   It may be one country, but measured by almost any economic
yardstick, it remains resolutely two systems.
</P>
<P>
   David Tang, founder of the Shanghai Tang boutiques in Hong Kong
and New York, speaks for many here when he asks: ``Do we want
millions of immigrants coming into a stable and bourgeois society?
Our starting point is different than 150 years ago, when this place
was a barren rock.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate has put Hong Kong's residents in an awkward spot.
Most are the children or grandchildren of Chinese refugees who came
in waves after the communist takeover in 1949 or during the
Cultural Revolution. While many still distrust the regime, the
motherland evokes genuine patriotism. Protesters mobbed the U.S.
Consulate here to denounce the errant bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, pelting it with tomatoes rather
than rocks, as protesters did in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to sharing their schools or neighborhoods with
mainland Chinese, Hong Kong's citizens wrinkle their noses. In a
survey of residents conducted shortly after the hand-over in July
1997, the words they most used to describe mainlanders were
``ignorant,'' ``impolite,'' ``dirty'' and ``greedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of this has to do with changing demographics. Many of the
mainland Chinese who poured into Hong Kong after 1949 were members
of the commercial elite. Those who came during the Cultural
Revolution tended to be scholars and intellectuals. The latest
batch, from neighboring Guangdong province, are mostly young, male
and uneducated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a form of class discrimination,'' said a 40-year-old
woman from Guangdong province whose husband lives in Hong Kong.
``Many people in China have not had the chance to receive an
education.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who identified herself as Mrs. Siu, is trying to gain
residency for her 16-year-old daughter. Mrs. Siu's husband migrated
to Hong Kong in the 1970s, returning to China in 1981 to find a
wife. After the couple had their daughter, they discovered that
Hong Kong's immigration laws barred her from moving here. So Mrs.
Siu stayed with the daughter in China, while her husband moved
back.
</P>
<P>
   Attitudes toward mainland Chinese have also hardened in the wake
of the Asian economic crisis. With Hong Kong limping through its
second year of recession, blue-collar workers here worry that more
newcomers could crowd them out of the job market. Policy-makers
fear that an influx of unskilled people would make Hong Kong less
competitive than Taiwan and Singapore, both of which have
immigration policies that favor highly skilled applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say Hong Kong has exaggerated the projected number of
immigrants to scare the public and win support for reversing the
court ruling. ``It's probably the grossest misuse of numbers I've
ever seen by a government,'' said Michael DeGolyer, the director of
an academic project that conducts surveys on public attitudes about
Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
   DeGolyer said some realities of Hong Kong life _ like its
stratospheric real estate prices _ would keep mainlanders away. In
fact, he said, some locals stay only because of its hospitals and
schools. ``If Hong Kong opened its border 24 hours a day,'' he
said, ``and if it built schools and medical facilities near the
border, at least 200,000 people would move out immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5364 &Cx1f; var-z
