<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8652 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MACEDONIA-SCENE-BOS &LR;      05-24 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACEDONIA-SCENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FASHIONS   AMID OLD FEUDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ In heart of the city, pounding with a disco
beat, the party was in full swing on a recent weekend night.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes away by car, meanwhile, busload after busload of
newly arrived ethnic Albanians were settling down for their first
night in the tents that were now their homes. Blankets were
distributed. Rain was forecast.
</P>
<P>
   But downtown life went on, and life was good. For many of the
weekend partiers, dancing at nightclubs, enjoying ice cream sundaes
at one of the cafes in the mall, the Kosovar refugees were out of
sight, out of mind. Mention of them brought grimaces. Mention of
NATO brought groans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People did stay inside the first night of the NATO airstrikes
because we were all scared,'' said Ljupco Atanasov, a 25-year-old
unemployed engineer who was on a double date. ``We are scared now,
too _ that the refugees will stay in our country, that NATO will
keep making war on Yugoslavia from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Added his friend, college economics major George Alexov, also
25: ``NATO has no job here. It's Kosovo where they should be. We
can keep our own security.''
</P>
<P>
   With hundreds and sometimes thousands more Kosovars arriving
daily and the United States advocating a rapid buildup of NATO
troops in Macedonia, many of the young adults who live in Skopje
and who largely seem unable to find jobs here said over the weekend
that they feel attacked on all fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Hot spots in the capital city, cosmopolitan by Balkan standards
despite the bland, Communist-era architecture, were crowded with
people wearing up-to-date designer knockoffs but holding to
centuries-old feuds.
</P>
<P>
   Young people sat at cafe tables jammed close together, or stood
in lines outside bars blaring music from the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Few whose families were not originally from Albania expressed
anything but contempt for the 50 or so Kosovar women who have given
birth in a nearby refugee camp. Images of Kosovar children
separated from their parents seemed not to move them. All but a
handful refused to condemn the ethnic cleansing campaign by
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, instead blaming Western
forces and the refugees themselves for amassing in Macedonia at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Milosevic is a good man who maybe did a bad thing, but
Serbian babies are dying, too . . .,'' said Elena Markovska, a
15-year-old high school student who was out at midnight eating
sweets with three girlfriends. ``We like the American people very
much. We like their ways. But we don't think what they're doing
here is right. It won't help anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with NATO's commander, General Wesley Clark, calling for
the military alliance to assemble as many as 50,000 troops on
Kosovo's borders _ almost double the previously agreed number _
that sort of angry talk from even teenagers is threatening to
disrupt Macedonia's delicate ethnic balance and to create an
anti-American backlash.
</P>
<P>
   Before ethnic Albanians started streaming across the border,
before the North Atlantic Treaty Organization began its air
campaign eight weeks ago, Macedonia was a nascent and divided
Balkan democracy. Overwhelmingly Slavic, 23 percent of its
population is Albanian by heritage, with a variety of ethnic
backgrounds making up another 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Jakub Ramushi, an ethnic Albanian translator who speaks a
half-dozen languages but was unable to find work until the latest
crisis brought scores of journalists and relief workers to town,
went so far as to compare the majority's treatment of the minority
to the pre-civil rights era in the US South. He said he favors both
a NATO buildup and its bombing campaign, as well as the ground war
which President Clinton has yet to rule out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can really make you feel bad for being Albanian,'' said
Ramushi, 27, who was born in Skopje after his parents moved to the
capital from Kosovo. He emphasized that he considers himself as
much Macedonian as Albanian. ``We did get a lot more rights after
Macedonia became independent _ high school in our own language, an
Albanian university _ but the ones who didn't like us before like
us less now that all of this is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Comments by more than two dozen Macedonians around the same age
would seem to bear out his concerns. Sasha Milosevic, no relation
to the Yugoslav leader, called Macedonians brothers of the Serbs,
enemies of the Albanians. The 27-year-old government security
worker added that NATO is now on the way to becoming his enemy,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not good to have so many soldiers here,'' said Gordana
Trajkoska, 30, who works part-time jobs when she can find them.
``You can notice them during the day and the night. It is an
internal problem in Yugoslavia, and it is not good for some outside
force to try to do something. Every country has its problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But Errol Khazovic, a 21-year-old Bosnian store clerk now living
in Macedonia, said that NATO's presence made him feel safer, and
that he would welcome more troops to his adopted country if it
would lead to peace. ``It's for our protection and the protection
of Macedonia, for every people, all of the Balkans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed buildup in both Albania and Macedonia, which not
all NATO allies endorse, is intended in part to pressure Milosevic
into accepting NATO's settlement terms. But as a condition for any
settlement, Yugoslavia on Friday called on NATO to cease its
airstrikes and to withdraw troops already stationed on the borders
of neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good thing to have these NATO troops and I don't
want them here,'' said waitress Tanya Lazarevska, 22, preparing to
serve another round of beers at a downtown bar serving desserts as
well as drinks. ``What does this have to do with us? I don't know
anyone who is happy about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
