<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8655 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-VIOLENCE-BOS &LR;      05-24 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT DETAILS PSYCHOLOGICAL TOLL OF ULSTER VIOLENCE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ The standard way of taking the toll of the
``Troubles'' here is to cite the more than 3,000 killed and 40,000
wounded in 30 years of clashes between Protestants and Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   But an equally disturbing measure of what has been lost is due
out this week. The first report to analyze the psychological legacy
of the conflict describes residents of violence-ridden
neighborhoods who suffer nightmares and flashbacks, who feel guilty
for living when relatives have perished, who take drugs and drink
to numb the ache, and who are certain that nothing and no one can
help heal their emotional scars.
</P>
<P>
   Coming as negotiations over self-government are entering a
make-or-break phase, the study helps to explain why all of Northern
Ireland seems to be in a nail-biting state of anxiety over whether
the stalled peace process can be reenergized _ and whether
psychological as well as physical recovery can commence in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   ``What our report suggests is first of all that the impact of
the armed conflict is long-term,'' said Marie Smyth, director of
the Cost of the Troubles Study, the charitable organization that
conducted the analysis. It is to be made public Thursday and is the
last in a series of reports on the violence here.
</P>
<P>
   ``In physical terms it's very clear that if someone has a leg
blown off in an explosion, clearly the leg will not grow back,''
Smyth added. ``But in emotional terms, while some people have been
able to make some kind of recovery, there are a significant number
who have not . . . 20 years later they're still living with the
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie Close knows all about the impact of sectarian violence
that has been widespread here since 1969. It claimed her husband 16
years ago. Since then one nephew has been shot, while another was
beaten and later died. Her brother-in-law was killed and her
brother still has the bullet in his brain from another shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has come through without being scarred,'' Close said.
``For people like us it's too late for help. We're getting on with
our lives the best we know how.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, have been asking for help, especially since the
cease-fires in 1994 and the Good Friday Agreement of last year.
Much the way soldiers who fought in Vietnam and World War II held
in the hurt until the fighting ended, mental health workers say,
many touched by the violence here responded to its cessation by
acknowledging their pain and seeking counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Their problems fall into four general groups, the therapists
say: a nervousness, or ``hyperarousal,'' that makes them sense
danger even when it is not there; avoidance that keeps them away
from certain parts of the city and that often leaves them
housebound; flashbacks and other ruminations about violent episodes
they witnessed; and a ``dissociation'' that leaves them numb to
nearly everything around them.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the problems affected a single individual; more often
they touched an entire family, leading to a surge in spousal abuse
and other home-centered troubles. Sometimes it was adults who were
stricken, but often it was children, many under 13, who felt they
somehow were responsible for violence that killed or wounded a
parent or sibling.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the psychological troubles have been described mainly
through anecdotal experience _ with nearly everyone here able to
offer a new and disturbing twist _ or through case files of health
care workers. But the study to be released this week, based on a
survey of 1,346 adults across the country, offers the first
in-depth look at what is wrong and what could be done.
</P>
<P>
   One in four respondents from neighborhoods where
Troubles-related deaths were highest reported having nightmares,
compared with one in eight in neighborhoods where the frequency of
deaths was more moderate. Likewise, the rates at which people
experienced disturbing flashbacks, or felt guilty for having
survived the violence, was nearly three times as high in the
high-violence areas.
</P>
<P>
   What did they do to deal with their guilt and other woes? One in
four who lived in high-violence areas took some form of medication
to help, while almost as many said they were drinking more alcohol.
And when they sought counseling, 40 percent of those living in
these areas said they couldn't find it, compared with 29 percent in
neighborhoods with moderate or little violence.
</P>
<P>
   The most disturbing finding of all involved despair:
Eighty-three percent of those in high-violence areas said they felt
nothing could help them, compared with just 4 percent in areas with
moderate violence and 12 percent in places with few killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``On every single count, areas of high intensity violence show a
quantum difference. It's like you're talking about two different
countries,'' said Smyth, an adjunct professor at Smith College in
Massachusetts. She and her colleagues are calling for government
policies that target assistance to the worst-hit neighborhoods,
recognize the critical role the family plays in providing support,
and address the way in which drugs and alcohol are easy fixes for
so many victims.
</P>
<P>
   Therapists and others dealing with such matters say change
already is happening, especially since the flood of new cases began
several years ago and since more funds became available as a result
of the April 1998 peace agreement. They're hopeful even more will
happen if Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain succeeds in bringing
the various parties together in ongoing talks that focus on
power-sharing arrangements for Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   More funds are being spent, victims have a more effective voice,
and a government minister has been made responsible for handling
trauma-related health issues, says Sir Kenneth Bloomfield, who
served as Northern Ireland's Victims Commissioner and produced a
mammoth report on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a long time for this society to work a lot of
this out of our system,'' he added, ``but at least a start is being
made.''
</P>
<P>
   Arlene Healey also is hopeful, especially since her new Family
Trauma Center opened in March with funds from the Good Friday
Agreement. ``I think we needed a culture of denial to be able to
cope,'' she said, but now people are beginning to come forward,
acknowledge their psychological problems, and seek treatment
ranging from individual counseling to family therapy.
</P>
<P>
   While many of her patients suffer syndromes that look like the
post-traumatic stress experienced by Vietnam veterans, Healey
added, ``there's nothing `post' about our situation. It's much more
like South Africa, where's there a continuous traumatic stress
disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are less sanguine about the help professional counselors
can offer, and less confident that victims of violence will seek
that assistance. That is why Close and people like her formed
Survivors of Trauma, a group through which victims of violence help
one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's people who have been there,'' she said. ``It isn't
bringing in counselors who have never been through it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
