<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-STARWARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STAR WARS' ROCKETS INTO BOX-OFFICE HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bar has been set high, very high, and America has been
waiting with bated breath. Will ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace,'' the most-hyped movie in history, set a box-office
record during its five-day opening? Will it sink ``Titanic?'' Will
it stomp ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, according to estimates given by Tom Sherak, chairman of
20th Century Fox's domestic film group, the movie's distributor.
Its total gross from last Wednesday through Sunday at 1 p.m.
anyway, was estimated at $102.8 million. Figures are usually
calculated over a three-day period, or four days if a Monday
holiday is involved. Sherak said ``Titanic'' grossed $28 million on
its first weekend and perhaps a total of $40 million over its first
five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' which set an
opening day record by bringing in $28.5 million, grossed an
estimated $61.8 million over its first weekend, the largest figure
for a non-holiday opening. (The holiday champ is ``The Lost World:
Jurassic Park,'' which opened Memorial Day weekend two years ago
and took in $72 million.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phantom Menace'' is showing at 2,970 theaters _ many of
them featuring it on multiple screens _ across the country, and has
averaged $20,819 per location. It has become the fastest movie to
reach the $100 million mark (five days, vs. six days for ``Lost
World'').
</P>
<P>
   Is everyone happy?
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is we're always happy,'' responds Sherak. The
better news is this is the good side of the force. We're thrilled.
Next weekend, the holiday, it will be like a shooting star: You
just hold onto it.''
</P>
<P>
   This prediction, of course, comes amid critical reaction which,
by and large, has rated the movie somewhere between tepid and
plot-free to barely adequate. On May 16, Washington Post writer
Tony Kornheiser predicted, ``By this time next week the crowds are
going to be so meager that if you want to see this piece of junk,
George Lucas will drive you personally. Nobody is going to see this
. . . This puppy stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   But the crowds are out there. This one seems to be critic-proof.
``That's the one great thing about the movie business,'' says
Sherak. ``Everyone has an opinion, and nobody's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas's three other ``Star Wars'' movies are in the all-time
top-10 grossing movies. ``It's not a contest,'' George Lucas told
Newsday recently. ``I really don't have any desire to be No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is.
</P>
<P>
   Movie analysts have predicted a total gross when all is said and
done of between $1.2 billion and $1.5 billion worldwide in
theaters. ``Titanic'' grossed $600.8 million in the US, and $1.01
billion worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
