<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8710 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV30-NY     05-24 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DEFENSE OF THE QUEEN'S ENGLISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 30)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In her annual address to her subjects, Queen Elizabeth II
updated the ``out of the mouths of babes'' idea with this
observation: ``The young can sometimes be wiser than us.''
</P>
<P>
   T.R. Reid, London bureau chief of The Washington Post,
commented: `` &UR; Than us &LR; ? I wondered: Is this proper English? So I
dug out the Oxford Guide to English Usage and found that Her
Majesty was wrong. No one was more dismayed than I.''
</P>
<P>
   Here we go again in the great battle between the Concerned
Conjunctionites and the Proper Preppies. The crucial question: Is
 &UR; than &LR;  a conjunction that must be followed by a pronoun in the
nominative case ( &UR; I &LR; ,  &UR; we &LR; ,  &UR; they &LR; ) or is  &UR; than &LR;  a preposition that
must take a pronoun in the objective case ( &UR; me &LR; ,  &UR; us &LR; ,  &UR; them &LR; )?
</P>
<P>
   Reid and his conjunctionite buddies have not only the Oxford
usagists behind their stiff-upper-lip stand. Erik Wensberg, reviser
of Wilson Follett's Modern American Usage, says, ``In the queen's
construction,  &UR; than us &LR;  is at best colloquial and at worst simply
wrong.'' Then he adds: ``But as she rightly sensed,  &UR; than we &LR;  is
annoyingly starchy. The answer?  &UR; Than we are &LR; . It maintains strict
grammar and achieves better rhythm as well.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a cop-out; in this scrap, you gotta choose up sides (he
averred colloquially). The New York Times stylebook is
conjunctionite, demanding that  &UR; we &LR;  follow  &UR; than &LR; , no matter what
most New Yorkers say. Jack Kilpatrick, ``The Writer's Art''
columnist who is more prescriptive than me (whoops!), says: ``I
think the queen was wrong in her use of  &UR; wiser than us &LR; . It should
have taken the nominative.  &UR; Us &LR;  sounds awkward, doesn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Not to me. I am a Proper Preppie. To my ear, keenly attuned to
the actions and passions of my time, it's  &UR; wiser than we &LR;  that
sounds stuffy, stilted and strained, not to mention cribbed,
cabin'd and confined. And speaking of Shakespeare, how about ``a
man no mightier  &UR; than thyself or me &LR; ,'' said by Cassius about
Julius Caesar? Or what of John Milton's use, in ``Paradise Lost,''
of `` &UR; than whom &LR; , Satan except, none higher sat''?  &UR; Whom &LR;  is
objective, ain't it?
</P>
<P>
   There are those who believe that the combined judgment of the
firm of Shakespeare, Milton &AMP; Safire cannot stand up to the
 &UR; diktat &LR;  of the legion of Conjunctionites. I will grant that famed
writers make mistakes; even Homer noodled. But we who dare to treat
 &UR; than &LR;  as a preposition have our authoritative defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regularly hear  &UR; than I &LR;  and  &UR; than me &LR; ,'' writes Kenneth G.
Wilson in The Columbia Guide to Standard American English. ``Some
commentators think that the conjunction is currently more frequent
than the preposition, but both are unquestionably standard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would allow  &UR; wiser than us &LR;  because it is perfectly normal
English usage,'' says Robert Burchfield, retired editor of the
Oxford English Dictionary and most recent reviser of Fowler's
Modern English Usage, from his home in Oxfordshire. ``In British
English we use both standard forms. The queen was right,'' he says,
adding loyally, ``She always is.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Fowler himself noted in an earlier edition: ``The
prepositional use of  &UR; than &LR;  is now so common colloquially (He is
 &UR; older than me &LR; ) that the bare subjective pronoun in such a
position strikes the reader as pedantic.'' (By  &UR; subjective &LR;  he uses
a synonym for  &UR; nominative &LR; , the case required by the  &UR; conjunctive &LR; .
That's what St. Henry thinks is pedantic and to be avoided.)
</P>
<P>
   Now let's review the bidding. On formal occasions, like an
address from the throne, most authorities would advise royal
speechwriters to stiffen the sinews, stretch the nostrils wide and
treat  &UR; than &LR;  as a conjunction, followed by  &UR; I &LR; ,  &UR; we &LR;  or  &UR; they &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   But even as they once more fling their bodies unto this breach,
the Conjunctionites seem uncomfortable because they can feel the
tectonic plates of language shifting under them. That's why they
all say, ``But the prepositional way is OK in colloquial speech,''
in a plaintive, real-life-is-passing-us-by tone.
</P>
<P>
   By choosing the proper prepositional in a formal address, the
queen decided the time was ripe to eschew pedantry even at the risk
of being criticized as grammatically incorrect. Because royalty is
trying to escape rigidity and adopt a common touch, she preferred
on this formal occasion to adopt the informal usage of commoners,
which is sometimes called common usage.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are hip will hooray. All hail the prepositional
 &UR; than &LR; ! Long Live the Royal  &UR; Us &LR; !
</P>
<P>
   FOR SHAME
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Shameless &LR; ,  &UR; reckless &LR;  and  &UR; indefensible &LR;  were adjectives used
in first reports of a censure resolution early this year. When Sen.
Dianne Feinstein submitted her resolution (which was never voted
on), a key word was changed:  &UR; shameless &LR;  became  &UR; shameful &LR; . What's
the difference?
</P>
<P>
   The difference lies in the word that is modified. If it is the
agent who lacks shame _ who observes few constraints of modesty or
morality _ then that person is  &UR; shameless &LR; . If the word being
modified is the action itself rather than the person, then the
action is filled with shame, or is  &UR; shameful &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   If I danced drunkenly through Times Square in the nude on
Millennium Eve, I would be  &UR; shameless &LR; . You, if you were clothed
and sober, might find my celebration  &UR; shameful &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
