<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     05-24 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SENS. HATCH AND SESSIONS SLEEPWALK THROUGH HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once again the Senate has passed a deeply flawed juvenile crime
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Senate wanted to allow juveniles to be jailed in
the same facility with adults, despite the horrors that arose from
such a practice.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., shilled
for that one and pushed the current racist juvenile crime bill (S.
254) through the Senate. It was passed May 20 by a 73-25 vote with
two senators abstaining.
</P>
<P>
   The troubling part of this juvenile crime bill is that it
eliminates the requirement forcing states to address the
disproportionate confinement of juveniles from minority groups. In
1988, Congress amended the Juvenile Justice and Delinquency
Prevention Act of 1974 to include a mandate for states to study and
attempt to correct the problem of disproportionate minority
confinement (DMC). Forty-six states have completed their studies
and identified the problem in their law enforcement systems. Forty
states are developing plans to address DMC.
</P>
<P>
   The DMC mandate does not require arrest quotas or that any
minority juvenile be released from jail. The mandate requires
states to look at the problem. The Hatch-Sessions bill totally
discards that federal mandate.
</P>
<P>
   In California, for instance, minority youth consistently
received more severe punishments and were more likely to receive
jail time than white youth _ for the same offense. Six times as
many blacks are put in state juvenile facilities for crimes against
persons than whites who commit the same crimes.
</P>
<P>
   National figures show that approximately the same percentage of
white juveniles use drugs as black juveniles. Yet a study done by
the National Center on Institutions and Alternatives showed the
marked racial disparity in waging the drug war in Baltimore. In
1980, only 18 white juveniles were arrested in Baltimore and
charged with drug sales compared to 86 black juveniles arrested for
the same crime. By 1990, the disparity leaped enormously. Only 13
white juveniles were arrested for selling drugs, but 1,304 black
youths were arrested for the same crime.
</P>
<P>
   A black kid in Baltimore had 100 times more chances of being
arrested for a drug crime as his white counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   That's what is meant by disproportionate minority confinement.
It's a national problem. It's real and it's based upon racial
fears. Racism has been a growing specter in the juvenile justice
system since the turn of the century. The DMC mandate is a step to
dealing with the problem.
</P>
<P>
   One should note that there are no members of the Senate who are
black.
</P>
<P>
   The only member of a minority is American Indian, Sen. Ben
Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., who voted against S. 254.
</P>
<P>
   But Hatch doesn't believe the disproportionate arrest rates for
minority juveniles is due to racism _ he stated on the Senate floor
that those are the kids who are selling drugs to ``our'' children
and they should be convicted. ``Our'' obviously means ``white'' in
Hatch's prejudiced parlance.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., hit the heart of the problem in
his response to Hatch: ``This is all about race. I cannot believe
that I have heard on the floor of the Senate an argument that race
is not the critical consideration. When the police are out there in
the streets, and we get to which kids are searched on the streets
and which are not, you don't think that has anything to do with
race? When we get to the question of which kids are arrested and
which kids are not, you don't think that has anything to do with
race today in America? ... When we get to the question of
sentencing, you don't think that has anything to do with race? You
are sleepwalking through history.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony of this sad debate is that this juvenile crime bill is
loaded with anti-gun provisions and congressional hysteria because
of the recent school shootings of teens by teens _ the shooters all
white juveniles, by the way, and some of them from wealthy
families.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional hysteria (We must do something!) shows in the
senators' cry of a rising juvenile crime wave. Not so. Hatch and
Sessions used 1994 as the reference year for the presumption that
juvenile crime is on the rise, but neglected the latest data from
1995, 1996 and 1997 which show that juvenile crime has dropped
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   A letter dated May 10 to the Senate signed by 36 prominent
criminologists and crime policy experts pointed out the senators'
error: ``The Justice Department's Crime in the United States
reported last November that the juvenile homicide arrest rate had
dropped again for the fourth straight year _ by more than 45
percent since 1993.'' The letter goes further: ``Today, the
percentage of violent crime arrests attributed to juveniles is
lower than it was in 1975.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Senate version of the juvenile crime bill reaches
conference committee with the House version which still contains
the DMC mandate, the Congressional Black Caucus will play a pivotal
role in demanding that the DMC mandate remain in the final bill.
The caucus sent a letter to Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., pointing out that an overwhelming majority of House
members endorsed the retention of DMC in the House juvenile justice
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch and Sessions ignore the clear evidence of the widespread
disparity in the treatment of minority juveniles in this nation's
law enforcement system. If the Hatch-Session's bill becomes law
without the DMC mandate, it will by that omission create a Jim Crow
justice system for minority children. Not a step forward, but a
long step backward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
