<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Speak up, tell A&AMP;E which bio you want
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   How often has this happened: It's 8 p.m., you realize ``The
Nanny'' is a rerun and the Braves are on the West Coast. You flip
to the A&AMP;E channel for relief only to find it's ``Accounting Giants
Week'' on ``Biography.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, A&AMP;E is giving you a chance to have a hand in the occasional
program selection. ``Biography'' is getting interactive.
</P>
<P>
   Until June 1, people can type www.biography.com into their Web
browser and have a say in what they see. Viewers will pick the bios
shown over the next several months. The by-demand hour-long shows
will start airing Monday, July 12, on the 8 p.m. A&AMP;E channel
series.
</P>
<P>
   Bio By Demand has five categories: Hollywood Superstars
(including Jim Carrey, Harrison Ford, Tom Hanks), TV Celebrities
(including Carol Burnett, Kathie Lee Gifford and Della Reese),
Great Entertainers (such as Patsy Cline, Frank Sinatra and
Liberace), Empire Builders (such as Bill Gates, J.C. Penney and
Colonel Sanders) and Anything Goes (Sonny Bono, J. Edgar Hoover and
Princess Diana).
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy traders could reap real cash
</P>
<P>
   You've read all about the guys who quit their jobs to spend
their days playing the stock market. They're called day traders.
Now ETrade, one of the more popular online stock-trading sites, and
Individual Investor magazine are holding a contest to find the best
one.
</P>
<P>
   The prize is $20,000 and it starts May 31. It runs through the
close of trading June 30. A playoff round starts in September.
</P>
<P>
   You start with $500,000 in imaginary cash. The goal is to build
your portfolio. At the end of each month, the person with the
biggest portfolio gets $10,000. The winner for the month and the
499 runners-up are eligible for the playoff round. The winner of
the playoff round gets the grand prize.
</P>
<P>
   The grand prize winner will be profiled in the February 2000
issue of the magazine, which hits newsstands in January.
</P>
<P>
   Register online at www.iioftheyear.etrade
</P>
<P>
   .com. After registering, players can select, manage and track
their fantasy stock portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Headphones deliver Dolby, but at a price
</P>
<P>
   Sony Electronics has released the first headphone capable of
reproducing Dolby digital sounds. But it will cost you.
</P>
<P>
   The cordless headphones, which come with an AC power adapter,
batteries, battery charger, cable, decoder and digital processor,
will retail for about $550.
</P>
<P>
   The headphones weigh 10 ounces and can be used anywhere in the
home, from in front of or behind the source, in 90-degree, 33-foot
range. More than one headphone can be used with the transmitter.
</P>
<P>
   The MDR-DS5000 comes with an infrared transmitter that measures
7 inches by 7 inches. It has a digital device that decodes the
digital Dolby source.
</P>
<P>
   Now mattresses available via Web
</P>
<P>
   First it was books and CDs, then couches and cars. Now you can
buy a mattress on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   A site at www.emattress.com bills itself as the first one where
you can buy a bed and have it delivered.
</P>
<P>
   The site carries mattresses from Serta, Simmons and King Koil,
as well as pillows and frames.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
