<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8735 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHNOBUDDY25-COX     05-24 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As prices drop, once-fancy gadgets become the norm
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was thinking about pocket calculators the other day. I
remembered, back in the 1970s, saving up about $400 to buy a
Hewlett-Packard calculator. It was an amazing device then. It could
add, multiply and divide, as well as do all sorts of math problems
that would have made my high school trig teacher proud.
</P>
<P>
   It was a marvel of the time _ all that power packed into a gizmo
small enough to fit into my jacket pocket. Nowadays, of course, you
can find more powerful pocket calculators for $4 hanging in those
little shrink-wrap packages as you stand in the grocery store
checkout line.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the real marvels of technology _ how prices drop
so fast. Think of any gadget you care to mention _ microwave oven,
VCR, color television _ and, if you are old enough, you'll be
struck by how expensive it once was and how cheap it is now. While
prices for cars, houses and T-shirts have zoomed up over the years,
gadget prices invariably have dropped.
</P>
<P>
   That's what's happening now with PCs. Sure, I know it's been
going on for a while, but, I promise, you haven't seen anything
yet. As the technology is refined, as the size of the market grows,
and as manufacturing costs drop, PC prices will follow the same
script as my pocket calculator. Someday soon, PCs will be so cheap
that even people like me with ordinary incomes won't think twice
about buying a new one on a whim.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, AMD _ a big competitor to Intel in the
microprocessor market (those are the chips that are the brains
behind a computer) _ announced price cuts of up to 45 percent. AMD
had to do it because it is the sort of company that stakes its
fortune on selling chips for less than Intel. And Intel has dropped
prices itself, as well as doing a great marketing job with its
excellent but lower-priced Celeron chip.
</P>
<P>
   The price drops alone are a big deal and worth marveling about.
But I think the real impact of all this is going to be the way it
changes how we use computers. When the world changes, it seldom is
because of just one event. It's usually a combination of related
events. And as prices for PCs have dropped, using the Internet has
become easy and affordable, too. Most of us have Internet
connections at work and at home, and, without really thinking about
it, we've shifted a lot of our ordinary lives (ordering books,
chatting with friends, checking the weather) to the Net and to PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Those of you who know me as a techno-dinosaur, a man afraid of
some of the ways the Internet and computers have muscled in on our
lives, may be surprised by what I think about this coming change.
</P>
<P>
   I think that, as computers and the Internet become as ordinary
as clock radios and the morning news on TV, we may finally put it
all in perspective. Up to now, we have treated the cyber-world as a
magical place with different rules. Just as earlier social critics
worried television and radio would tear apart the fabric of
society, we've had the same worries _ me especially _ about this
new cyber-world.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying, by the way, that the worries were foolish.
Remember how Orson Welles' ``War of the Worlds'' broadcast created
panic? When the public puts magical belief in a medium, the power
of it becomes real. It has been the same with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But I believe that as technology becomes a routine part of life
_ as radio did _ we may begin to treat cyberspace and the Internet
as we treat television and radio. The message will become the
important thing, not the medium that carries the message. The magic
will go away, but the power will stay.
</P>
<P>
   So while the good news is that prices are dropping, I think the
even better news is that computers and the Internet are poised to
become just another excellent way of dealing with information.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Bill appreciates hearing from you but cannot respond to all
e-mail. Personal home page:
http://www.mindspring.com/(tilde)bhusted/bills.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
