<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH25-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHOOL VIOLENCE
</P>
<P>
   Teen wounds 6 students
</P>
<P>
   A student opened fire in a Georgia school last week, exactly one
month after the attack at Columbine High School in Colorado. Police
said a 15-year-old boy wounded six of his classmates at Heritage
High School in Conyers, about 20 miles east of downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The student brought two guns into the school and began shooting
before the first bell. Friends said he was upset because his
girlfriend had broken up with him. He was charged with aggravated
assault and will probably appear in court today.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was the sixth mass shooting at an American high
school or middle school since October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL
</P>
<P>
   New leader elected
</P>
<P>
   Israelis last week elected Ehud Barak to be their new prime
minister. Now he has 45 days to bring together members of the
Israeli parliament to support his programs. The members who agree
to support Barak's policies will make up his multi-party, or
``coalition,'' government.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said he wants a coalition ranging greatly in beliefs.
``When there is a broad government, the public can more easily
accept decisions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has pledged to make peace in the area. Israel is a Jewish
nation, which has fought for years with surrounding Arab countries,
whose residents are mostly Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   MOTORCYCLE MANIA
</P>
<P>
   Daredevil jumps canyon
</P>
<P>
   Motorcycle daredevil Robbie Knievel jumped 228 feet over a
sliver of the Grand Canyon last week. He broke his own world record
for a motorcycle jump by 5 feet. Fireworks erupted and a crowd of
several hundred cheered as he soared over the 200-foot-wide gorge
at 90 mph on an ordinary 500cc motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   If he failed, Knievel could have plunged 2,500 feet to the
canyon floor.
</P>
<P>
   Knievel was going to attempt the jump on April 29, but it was
canceled at the last minute because of wind and cold. Knievel said
his daredevil father, Evel Knievel, had wanted to jump the Grand
Canyon but never got the chance.
</P>
<P>
   LIVING HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   Trees with a past
</P>
<P>
   Kids across the country can own a descendent of one of the last
trees planted by Johnny Appleseed.
</P>
<P>
   Appleseed, whose real name was John Chapman, planted many trees
in the early 1800s. He died in 1845 at age 71.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Meyer took cuttings from the wood and roots of an Ohio tree
planted by Appleseed before its recent death. In his greenhouse, he
grew thousands of saplings from the cuttings.
</P>
<P>
   You can get one of the saplings for $35, plus shipping, by
calling 800-320-TREE or by surfing to www.americanforests.org. The
proceeds go to American Forests, a nonprofit group that promotes
tree planting and preserves historic trees.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
