<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8748 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-GENEALOGY25-CO     05-24 1798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-GENEALOGY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Software, Internet make tracing family tree easier
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gene and Janice James of Riverside, Ohio had been interested in
the histories of their families for years, but Gene said they never
got deeply into the genealogy hobby until he retired around 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get started once or twice, but the record-keeping
and paper pushing was just horrendous,'' Gene James said. ``I
didn't have the time and patience for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Gene James is a dedicated hobby genealogist who has traced
his direct ancestry to the 17th century. And the tool that cut out
enough hassles for James to pursue the hobby is his home computer.
</P>
<P>
   James said the computer does two things that make genealogy
simpler, more fun and more efficient: It organizes records, and it
links hobbyists through the Internet for the exchange of ideas and
information.
</P>
<P>
   But unfortunately, the Internet is not the genealogy panacea
that some people believe. Genealogy experts like James and Carole
Medlar, genealogy librarian for the Dayton and Montgomery County
Public Library, say nothing can substitute yet for the hours people
spending looking through paper records for data about their
ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who come in thinking they can find their
entire family tree on the Internet, but that's not usually true,''
Medlar said. ``That doesn't happen unless you stumble across
someone online who has gone to all the trouble before you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gathering information
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in tracing your roots, a good place to
start is with your family members, according to James and Medlar.
And a key bit of information you need to have is where people
lived.
</P>
<P>
   James, for example, said his father left him a family tree with
names and dates relating to his ancestry. ``When I was starting out
I brought it to a woman who had been doing research, and she said
the things my father left me were exciting, but they weren't all
that useful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   James was a civilian employee in the flight dynamics laboratory
before he retired, and he worked with computers 15 or 20 years
before retiring. He now writes a monthly column on computer
research for the newsletter of the local chapter of the Ohio
Genealogical Society.
</P>
<P>
   To get authoritative information on who was related to whom, a
researcher has to get to local records in the places their
ancestors were born, exchanged property, died and so on. In the
United States, most of the important records are kept at the county
level.
</P>
<P>
   A birth certificate on file in a county office with the names of
the parents and the child is an example of the kind of primary
source material that is tapped to produce a well-documented family
tree. Also important are marriage and death certificates, church
records, deeds and wills and old federal Census records.
</P>
<P>
   Medlar said only a fraction of that kind of information is
accessible directly through the Internet, but the Internet
computers at the public library are still a great resource for
genealogical research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Researching genealogy has grown to be one of the top three
hobbies in the United States and the Internet does offer marvelous
support for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Medlar said library patrons can log on to one of the library's
Internet computers to access databases with research information.
</P>
<P>
   One such database is the Social Security death benefit index,
she said. The online resource allows researchers to find the names
and dates people died and the names of people who received death
benefits after the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Medlar said the library provides free access to some premium
reference databases. These are reference tools that normally carry
a subscription or per-use price, but the library pays the fees for
its patrons.
</P>
<P>
   If you're doing research on the Internet from home, the place
most people start is at cyndislist.com. Cyndi's List is a free site
managed by genealogist Cyndi Howell, and it contains links to
41,700 sites and archives.
</P>
<P>
   The sites include thousands of links to hobbyists who have
researched their family trees, and there's a chance you'll find
someone with common ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet resources, though, generally only provide clues
that point researchers to more traditional research avenues such as
county records.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is all secondary data,'' James said. ``You can't
trust any of it as absolute.''
</P>
<P>
   The public library is a great source for noncomputer records.
For example, the Dayton library has microfilm Census records for
all Ohio counties through 1860 and for Montgomery County through
1920.
</P>
<P>
   The main branch of the Dayton library downtown has a genealogy
research section, and Medlar is on duty in the area from 2 to 6
p.m. Wednesdays. She's available at the reference desk on other
days.
</P>
<P>
   Medlar said even if researchers can pinpoint where to look for
old records, they usually have to review such records themselves to
get information. ``Usually county workers are busy doing county
work,'' she said. ``Going through old county records is not what
they're paid for.''
</P>
<P>
   James said he and his wife gather much of their information
while traveling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't build our vacations around places we want to go to do
research,'' James said. ``But it's not unusual for us to stop for a
day on the way to going somewhere or on the way back.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizing information
</P>
<P>
   James said that where computers really shine is in compiling
data in a convenient form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working with the same piece of genealogy software
for the last nine years, and I still don't know all the things it
can do yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   James said he keeps his genealogy records using a software
program called Brothers Keeper, but he said most of the programs on
the market cost about $15 to $45 and do basically the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   He said some popular programs include Family Tree Maker,
Ultimate Family Tree and Personal Ancestral File. To find reviews
of these programs and others, you can check the Genealogy Software
Springboard site at toltbbs.com/(tilde)kbasile/software.html.
</P>
<P>
   There are two basic types of interlinking records kept in
genealogy research.
</P>
<P>
   One is the ancestor shet that starts with an individual then
names that individual's parents, and the parents' parents, and the
grandparents' parents, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The other type of record is a family group sheet. It lists a
husband, wife and their offspring along with some details about the
family's personal history.
</P>
<P>
   James said genealogy software allows the researcher to enter
data in a simple format. The software maintains the links between
people that have been entered into the system, and it helps the
researcher manipulate the data into useful forms.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the software packages allow the researcher to enter
notes on the people whose names are listed. Some also store photos
connected with records.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people go back a few generations and they stop trying
to go further and further back,'' James said. ``Instead they get
into researching details about their ancestors' lives. They're more
interested in what their ancestors did day to day than in anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   James said he's primarily been interested in tracing his direct
ancestors back as far as possible. So far he's traced his line back
eight generations to a man named David James who was born in 1660,
probably in Cardiff, Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Just including direct ancestors only going back eight
generations involves recording information on 256 people. And
James, who is still filling gaps in his direct lineage, also has
records of siblings and multiple marriages that make his database
even more complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never would have been able to keep all this straight without
a computer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When James goes to a county office, cemetery or library to look
up information about his family, he doesn't take a notepad and
pencil like old fashioned genealogists. He takes a laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   Online exchanges
</P>
<P>
   In addition to record-keeping, James said computers are most
useful in linking researchers to other researchers via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days before the Internet your chances of finding
somebody else working on your family tree would be almost nil,'' he
said. ``Now it happens all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   James said his wife's maiden name was Allenduff and in 1800,
there were records for only two people with that name in the United
States. ``Nobody knows where they came from,'' he said. ``They
could have been dropped out of a spaceship.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with such a small family, James has found four people
online researching the Allenduff ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   He's found even more people researching the James lineage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The further you go back, the more direct ancestors you have,''
James explained. ``And the more direct ancestors you know about,
the better the chances are that some other direct descendant is
doing research, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Resources like Cyndi's List provide a way for people doing
research on their family trees to let the world know what they're
doing. And it's common for researchers to cross paths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standard greeting is 'Hi, Cousin!' when you hear from a
relative you didn't know you had,'' James said.
</P>
<P>
   He said researchers do more than chat when they meet on line;
they also exchange data.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, James said if he found a relative working on
James family history he and the relative would print out their
family tree records and send them in a big envelope.
</P>
<P>
   Now he said it's possible to send records electronically. Most
genealogy software programs are able to convert information into a
standard format that can be shared by other software programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just in the last week a relative sent me an e-mail that had
data on 200 people in an attachment,'' he said. ``Every year you do
more exchanges and you send more data electronically.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, James doesn't just dump information from other
researchers into his own database without checking out the new
information first. ``It's source material just like everything
else. It gives you new information to look into.''
</P>
<P>
   James also said exchanging information via e-mail has its
drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be careful with the information you send on living
people,'' he said. ``Things like mother's maiden name, for example.
Do you realize how often mother's maiden name and information like
that is used as a security check? You don't want to spread
information that someone could use to steal someone else's
identity.''
</P>
<P>
   CONTACT James Cummings at 225-2395 or by e-mail at
jamescummings(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
