<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, May 24, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-IOWA (Washington) _ In planning a presidential campaign, a
serious candidate must plot the ascent of Mount Yepsen. Gov. George
W. Bush is no different. Sometime during Bush's first, brief
campaign visit to Iowa next month, it's a good bet that the Texas
governor will seek to find time to make the climb. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-STATION (Undated) _ Shuttle astronauts lift off for the
international space station this week, prepared to break new ground
as they dock with the fledgling outpost for the first time.
Discovery's delayed mission is set for launching at 6:48 a.m. EDT
Thursday from NASA's Kennedy Space Center in Florida. By MARK
CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   LAWMAKERS-WAGES (Albany, N.Y.) _ The new law that withholds New
York legislators' salaries until they approve a state budget has
been declared unconstitutional by a Brooklyn judge. But lawmakers,
who by now have missed their third paycheck, still will not see
their state wages until Gov. George Pataki has finished appealing
the court ruling. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITAL-MERGER (San Francisco) _ The 1997 merger of the medical
centers of the University of California at San Francisco and
Stanford University was supposed to save them from financial ruin,
but a stream of bad news has left many questioning the sales pitch
used to justify the deal. It has not shielded the hospitals from
the fiscal distress felt by academic medical centers nationwide. By
ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   SUTURES (San Francisco) _ A medical manufacturer retrieved only
2 percent of about 3.6 million surgical sutures it recalled after
the products allegedly were contaminated with infectious bacteria,
according to the Food and Drug Administration. Rep. Pete Stark,
D-Calif., says the FDA's handling of the nationwide recall of the
Ethicon Corp.'s trademark Vicryl surgical sutures _ and the low
return rate _ have made him fear that ``the system may have failed
to protect the health of patients.'' By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   ROCKWELL-OBIT (San Francisco) _ Alvin John Rockwell,_ a
prominent San Francisco lawyer who played a key role in shaping
Germany's new democratic government after World War II, died here
last week of coronary artery disease. He was 90. By The San
Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS (Undated) _ For those who like simple, elemental
furniture, check out the table in peopleplacesthings, one of
several catalogs put out by the J. Jill company. The table,
available in three styles, is a solid block of plantation-grown
Costa Rican cypress. It's primitive and purposeful _ proudly a
place to set stuff. By STEVE BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   ART-DISABLED (Oakland, Calif.) _ Regina Broussard is known for
her distinctive drawings resembling ancient wood carvings. Judith
Scott's fiber art has been acquired by a museum in Paris and is the
subject of a book. Both artists are disabled and do their artwork
at Oakland's Creative Growth Art Center and Gallery. By ROBERT
SELNA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-BUSINESS (San Francisco) _ Electronic commerce still may
be in its infancy, but there are already scores of cheerleaders and
skeptics on the subject. Two of the latest voices heard come from
Thomas Siebel, founder and chairman of San Mateo-based business
software maker Siebel Systems Inc., and Pat House, executive vice
president and co-founder of Siebel Systems. The two have written
``Cyber Rules: Strategies For Excelling at E-business.'' By WENDY
TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   McKESSON-LAWSUITS (San Francisco) _ Barely one month after
McKesson HBOC Inc. admitted to improperly recording its revenue,
the nation's largest drug wholesaler is fighting off lawsuits,
allegations of financial fraud and questions from federal
regulators. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEOPHONES (San Francisco) _ Back in the '50s, visionaries knew
that global citizens would talk to one another on gleaming
videophones. But the fancy devices have never caught on. That may
be changing soon. The Kyocera Corp., based in Kyoto, Japan, has
announced the newest version of the device _ a mobile unit called
the Visual Phone VP-210, to be marketed initially in Japan. By JOHN
BERGER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BOOKS (Undated) _ If you haven't experienced books on
the Internet, check out Web locations sites where ``virtual books''
appear and may be downloaded to any computer. These sites have been
a boon to authors who, for whatever reason, eschew the traditional
road to publication in favor of (almost) instant gratification and
the opportunity to reach millions of readers. By JUDYTH RIGLER.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INDOOR-GRILLS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Summertime and the livin' is easy
... time to relax with books and barbecuing. But don't fret if you
live in an apartment and don't have room for an outdoor grill. A
New Jersey company has designed smokeless indoor grills to make
barbecuing a timeless convenience. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   SUSHI-HEALTH (Albany, N.Y.) _ A New York statute that requires
the servers and preparers of uncooked food to don gloves is a
recipe for a culture clash. Sushi chefs claim compliance with the
health code inhibits their ability to create their edible art to
perfection. By LINDA TRISCHITTA.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBL-PITCHER (Boston) _ The Boston Red Sox's Pedro Martinez has
grown into the most overpowering pitcher on the planet. By STEVE
CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Lately we've been reading about
police profiling and DWB, or Driving While Black. If you fit the
profile of being African American, or Latino, the cops pull you
over on any pretext _ especially if you're driving in a white
neighborhood. I want to talk about something that hasn't come up
before: DWW, Driving While White. What happens if you're DWW? By
ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Offering people advice on how to
raise their kids is touchy. They tend to get annoyed.``Yeah, what
do you know about it?` they demand. So, up front, let me just say
this: I raised two kids. I wasn't perfect at it. The kids weren't
perfect, either, believe me. They turned out pretty well, though.
By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Please don't misunderstand. I
am definitely not against progress. In many ways, the new
technologies which are nosing their way into everyday lives are
welcome and helpful. Still, all is not peaches and cream. Take, for
one example, the phone calls we get of an evening, usually after
supper. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I have seen many advertisements
that missed the mark so badly they should have been classified as
``friendly fire.'' A new, three-page ad for Nolvadex, the
anti-cancer drug tamoxifen, is one of them. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
