<HEADLINE>
JUNGLE FEVER: CUBA GOODING JR. PLAYS BY `INSTINCT' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Cuba Gooding Jr. with Anthony Hopkins in
a scene from ``Instinct.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Don't show him the money.
 &HT;    Just show him to a quiet table, a quiet back room, even a quiet
back door so Cuba Gooding Jr. can get away from the people who want
to hear The Line.
 &HT;    ``Say it,'' begs a teen-age boy in baggy jeans. ``You must say
it, man!''
 &HT;    ``Please say it,'' says a young woman on Michigan Avenue in
downtown Chicago. ``My friend over there is sick, and she would
feel better if you said it just once.''
 &HT;    Even at a local hamburger joint, the request swells to a general
chorus that even a determinedly low-profile Gooding can't ignore.
 &HT;    And give him this much, when the actor does anything, it's in a
big way.
 &HT;    Suddenly, he catapults up from a booth, his hips swiveling and
his head grooving to some imaginary beat.
 &HT;    ``Shoooow me the moonnn-aaaaay!'' he shrieks, and his fans burst
into applause,
 &HT;    Sure, a few older patrons look at him and clearly write him off
as another young guy who's obviously snapped. But everyone else
knows beyond a doubt that Cuba Gooding Jr. is in town.
 &HT;    Actually, Gooding says later as he relaxes in a luxury suite at
Chicago's Four Seasons Hotel, that was his character in ``Jerry
Maguire'' (1996). The actor himself doesn't need to be shown the
money.
 &HT;    ``I actually drive my agents crazy,'' he says, ``because they'll
want to negotiate a bigger salary for me on projects that I really
want to do. But if I get any resistance from the studio, I just
immediately go, `OK, fine. I'll take whatever they're offering me.'
 &HT;    ``The studios are willing to pay me big bucks to do an action
movie,'' Gooding adds, ``but I turn those down all the time. I
don't want the people who follow my movies to leave the theater
going, `He did that one for the cash!'''
 &HT;    So you know that it wasn't for the money that he signed on to
film ``Instinct,'' opening nationwide on June 4. Based on Daniel
Quinn's book ``Ishmael,'' the film casts him as a psychiatrist
assigned to evaluate a famous primatologist (Anthony Hopkins)
accused of ``going native,'' living among the gorillas he studies
and ultimately murdering two park rangers.
 &HT;    The money didn't enter into it, Gooding says. More important was
the chance to work with the Oscar-winning Hopkins ... and to redeem
himself in the British actor's eyes.
 &HT;    Wincing, he recalls their first meeting, at a 1997 industry
showcase.
 &HT;    ``It was so embarrassing,'' Gooding says, shaking his head.
``All I saw was the back of this bald head. Someone says to me,
`That's Tony Hopkins.' And I said, `Oh, no it's not. It's Lester
from the `Addams Family.'''
 &HT;    At which point, the man turned and gave him all the frost that
you'd expect from the eye of Sir Anthony Hopkins.
 &HT;    ``I gasped and said, `Oh, hello, Mr. Hopkins, nice to meet
you,''' Gooding adds. ``He wasn't mad for a moment, so I
impulsively wrapped my arms around him and gave him a big hug. Tony
then whispered to me, `So, kid, you're going to do that movie,
aren't you? The movie with the apes?'
 &HT;    ``I had no clue what he was talking about at the time.''
 &HT;    At that moment, the script for ``Instinct'' was lying amid a
pile that had flooded into his office since he had won a Best
Supporting Actor Oscar as football player Rod Tidwell in ``Jerry
Maguire.''
 &HT;    ``The Oscar was like this sonic boom,'' Gooding says. ``I went
from, `Oh, look, it's that guy from ``Boyz N the Hood''' to `Hey,
Cuba my man!'''
 &HT;    Since collecting his statuette, Gooding has put Jack Nicholson
in his place as a gay art dealer in ``As Good As It Gets'' (1997)
and toured heaven and hell with Robin Williams in ``What Dreams May
Come'' (1998), almost certainly the only film in which he'll ever
play Williams' son. He was even able to raise enough cash to
produce his first feature, ``A Murder of Crows,'' a thriller
starring Eric Stoltz that's due for release later this year.
 &HT;    And he's having fun, which should come as no surprise to anyone
who saw his exuberant acceptance speech at the Oscars. No one could
call him inhibited.
 &HT;    ``Cuba has no fear,'' Williams said during a ``What Dreams''
interview. ``What I love about him the most is that at the drop of
a hat he'll drop his trousers.''
 &HT;    Actually, yes. Even when the script calls for nudity, though _
as it does in one of his upcoming films _ Gooding can manage to
surprise people.
 &HT;    ``I had to do this really passionate love scene,'' he recalls,
bounding to his feet to set the scene. ``So I said, `Can I get the
whole crew in here, please?' I was really serious. I adjusted my
robe and I said, `Listen, this is a very big day. I don't want any
laughing.'
 &HT;    ``Then I dropped the robe,'' he says, deadpan. ``My assistant
had made this prosthetic penis _ he stuffed a stocking with
cellophane. Well, the whole crew cracked. The tension evaporated.
Afterward it didn't matter how long we were naked that day, it just
didn't matter.''
 &HT;    Gooding was 23 when he dazzled audiences in ``Boyz N the Hood''
(1991). He expected a major career to ensue, but few offers
appeared, and most of them were highly derivative of ``Boyz.''
 &HT;    ``I was offered dozens of inner-city movies, but I passed,'' he
says. ``I also didn't want to play the villain or the good-bad guy
_ I always wanted to be a leading man.''
 &HT;    Roles in ``Lightning Jack'' (1994) and ``Outbreak'' (1995) led
to an audition for ``Jerry Maguire'' _ opposite Robin Williams, who
briefly considered the title role that later went to Tom Cruise.
 &HT;    A year later, Gooding was thanking the Academy and his wife, a
teacher named Sara. The Goodings live in Los Angeles with their
sons, 5-year-old Spencer and 2-year-old Mason. They also have three
Great Danes _ Pitch Black, Woodrow and Lollipop.
 &HT;    A self-described ``homebody,'' Gooding says he isn't one for the
Hollywood circuit of parties and premieres.
 &HT;    ``A big night is Pay-Per-View,'' he says.
 &HT;    The other night, he adds, he even caught ``Jerry Maguire'' on
cable.
 &HT;    ``I immediately got caught up in it,'' the actor says. ``But
then I had to turn it off, because I started thinking, `That's the
best you're ever going to be.' I had to stop looking at it.''
 &HT;    He sighs.
 &HT;    ``Winning the Oscar is tricky,'' he says. ``It starts you off on
having internal dialogues you never thought you'd have.''
 &HT;    And besides, it can make you crazy after a while.
 &HT;    ``The only bad part of winning the Oscar,'' he adds, ``was that
I went home that night and my nanny had Spencer waiting on the
driveway. The minute I stepped out of the limo, the nanny was like,
`OK, say it to Daddy.' Spencer yawns and says, `Show me da money,
daddy.'
 &HT;    ``I looked at my nanny like, `I'll kill you!''' Gooding says,
laughing. ``I'm standing in my driveway screaming, `No, no, no!'''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
