<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-SINGERS-THE-DIXIE-CHICKS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHISTLING DIXIE: HOW THE DIXIE CHICKS RUFFLED NASHVILLE'S
FEATHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Martie Seidel, Emily Erwin and Natalie
Maines, the Dixie Chicks. 
 By BOB PAXMAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    They're three women who dress like alternative-rock stars but
play a mixture of straight country, pop and bluegrass. They go by a
slightly tongue-in-cheek name, the Dixie Chicks.
 &HT;    In a word, they're so un-Nashville, yet the Dixie Chicks find
themselves ruling the country roost, and the Nashville
establishment has been forced to pay attention to them, like it or
not.
 &HT;    The Dixie Chicks _ fiddle player Martie Seidel,
multi-instrumentalist Emily Erwin and lead vocalist Natalie Maines
_ burst practically unknown onto the country scene in January 1998.
In little more than a year they've managed to ruffle the feathers
of normally placid Music Row _ which isn't that hard, but the
Chicks have gotten away with it, which is much rarer.
 &HT;    Their escape hatch, of course, has been popularity, which
translates into one thing that even Nashville can't ignore: money.
 &HT;    Their debut album, ``Wide Open Spaces,'' recently reached the 5
million sales mark. Its first single, ``I Can Love You Better,''
soared into the top 10, and the followups, ``There's Your Trouble''
and the album's title cut, both hit No. 1 on the country charts.
Country Music Association Awards and two Grammy Awards were simply
icing on the cake.
 &HT;    All this from virtually nowhere, leaving the country world
scratching its head and asking, ``Who are these women, and how are
they doing this?''
 &HT;    The look and the sound are both part of it, Erwin says.
 &HT;    ``Three women doing what we do is just so different in itself,''
says the tallest of the trio, who plays banjo, guitar, dobro and
mandolin. ``The fact that we play our own instruments has a lot to
do with our signature sound. People probably look at us playing
fiddles and banjos or whatever and think, `What are they doing up
there?'
 &HT;    ``But it's fun for us, and I think we are breaking a lot of
stereotypes.''
 &HT;    They've also latched onto a particular audience, mainly women in
their 20s _ as all three Chicks happen to be _ looking for feisty
role models. ``I Can Love You Better'' and ``There's Your Trouble''
embody a certain edginess without giving way to the anger that
seems to drive some other female pop acts.
 &HT;    ``We are a little partial to songs like that,'' Erwin agrees.
``There's a psychology behind it, you know, `You're seeing the
wrong one, buddy!' But we're just calling it like it is. People
like things in plain English.''
 &HT;    She laughs.
 &HT;    ``It reminds me of a lot of Tammy Wynette's songs,'' she adds.
``She was always saying, `Girl, get your head out of your
you-know-what,' and I loved her for that reason.''
 &HT;    Once you establish yourself in that vein, of course, you get
pitched similar songs by everyone with an ax to grind. And, yes,
the Chicks are getting more than their share.
 &HT;    ``We're getting piles and piles of `attitude' songs,'' Erwin
reports, chuckling. ``Guess there's an awful lot of 'tude out
there.
 &HT;    ``But that's not our M.O. at all,'' she says. ``The song `Wide
Open Spaces' has a lot of depth to it. `Once You've Loved Somebody'
is a great ballad. So there's no formula for a Chicks song _ if we
like it and we think we can put our harmonies to it, that's all we
need.''
 &HT;    Incidentally, the Chicks aren't really from Dixie. All three are
Texas natives, actually. Seidel and Erwin are sisters who were
already veterans of the music business by the time they _ and two
since-departed partners, Laura Lynch and Robin Macy _ founded the
Chicks in 1989.
 &HT;    The sisters got their first experience in six years of touring
the country as members of Blue Night Express, a teen bluegrass
group. The Chicks were officially hatched in an informal way, when
the four _ Seidel then 19 and Erwin 16 _ took their instruments to
a Dallas street corner and started playing for tips.
 &HT;    It wasn't meant as the start of something big, Seidel recalls,
but something clicked.
 &HT;    ``We knew there was something magical _ or at least lucrative _
about women playing music together,'' she says. ``The only problem
was we didn't have a name.''
 &HT;    Finding one wasn't easy, as the performers struggled for a tag
that they'd all go for. One morning, though, the answer came out of
thin air _ literally, since it was on the radio that they happened
to hear the Little Feat song ``Dixie Chicken.''
 &HT;    One syllable-extraction later _ Seidel didn't like the idea of
being a chicken _ they had a name.
 &HT;    But though they found ample bookings at clubs and dance halls
around Texas, the Chicks couldn't get any record companies
interested. It took six more years for the missing ingredient to
arrive, in the form of Maines.
 &HT;    The daughter of producer/musician Lloyd Maines, she'd heard the
band several times during her days as a college student in Lubbock,
Texas. Liking their style, she sent the sisters a demo tape in 1995
_ as it happened, just when the search was on for a replacement
Chick.
 &HT;    Seidel and Erwin admired not only Maines' voice, but also the
somewhat brazen personality she brought to her singing. Blonde and
brassy with a lilting soprano, Maines brought a Marilyn Monroe
spark to the Chicks' country style.
 &HT;    ``Our music evolved to this point once Natalie came in,'' Seidel
says. ``It took finding Natalie to make us say, `We've got
something.' That was the best thing that ever happened to Emily and
me.''
 &HT;    The band, now a trio, clicked almost immediately. And in 1997,
when Sony Music Entertainment decided to relaunch Monument Records,
former home to Roy Orbison and other country-pop legends, the first
act it signed was the Dixie Chicks.
 &HT;    The rest is, if not history, at least yesterday's news. Leaving
the obvious question, is there anywhere to go but down?
 &HT;    Unsurprisingly, the Chicks think their ride is only beginning.
 &HT;    ``One of our biggest goals is to write more of our own
material,'' Erwin says. ``Not long ago we went on a songwriter's
retreat outside Nashville and worked with all these great writers.
It was important for us to learn more about the craft of writing,
because we are new songwriters in relation to a lot of other
people.''
 &HT;    If you're wondering what sort of tunes the Chicks would write on
their own behalf, you won't have to wait long to find out.
 &HT;    ``We already have a handful of songs that we'll be recording for
our next album,'' Erwin reports.
 &HT;    That album, as yet untitled, is scheduled for release Aug. 31.
And the country-music world, which was generally skeptical about
the Chicks' chances as recently as a year ago, is predicting great
things.
 &HT;    Apparently the Dixie Chicks _ name, look and all-girl status
intact _ aren't the marketing problem that they once seemed.
Country audiences have a wider range of interest than many
observers had predicted, and the Chicks aren't ``too different'' to
succeed.
 &HT;    ``We heard a lot of that,'' Erwin admits.
 &HT;    In the end, she says, the marketing strategy wound up to be a
simple one _ let the Chicks be what they are.
 &HT;    ``We are not something that's been manufactured,'' she explains.
``We're real, we play our own instruments, which is kind of bizarre
to a lot of people. Maybe we were considered different or odd or
something _ but, you know, people who take the greatest chances
often make the greatest gains.
 &HT;    ``We tried to reinvent the wheel a million times, before
realizing what the essence of Dixie Chicks really is,'' she
concludes. ``Now we are definitely going to do this on our own
terms.''
 c.1999 Bob Paxman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Bob Paxman is a Nashville-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on The Dixie Chicks, consult the
