<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
May 25. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   FM: Those low-band FM stations are still an issue before the
FCC. The feds want the smallest to be 1,000 MHz, much larger than
the small outfits in Lawrence or on KC's West Side. The little guys
say the government is leaning toward the big guys in the biz. The
FCC has extended public comment before they rule. Kevin Murphy. 30.
</P>
<P>
   FALL: Investigators probe what caused the fatal plunge of WWF
wrestler Owen Hart. We examine the history of the stunt, the
equipment involved, etc. Checking whether the cable snapped or Hart
jumped before being hooked in. He reportedly practiced three times
Sunday but had misgivings up until the stunt. Checking police and
WWF investigations; Truman Medical Center and medical examiner for
cause of death; whether city's Kemper staff had any
responsibilities, any violations city codes, etc. Ruth Igoe, Lynn
Horsley and Steve Penn. 30. Graphic. Photo
</P>
<P>
   FRAUD: U.S. Attorney's Office files civil suit Monday alleging
Medicare and Medicaid fraud in care of pregnant indigents. Mark
Morris. 20.
</P>
<P>
   CREEK: Federal agency releases the first-ever comprehensive
study of the health impact of the former Amoco oil refinery on
Sugar Creek, Mo., residents. Mike Mansur. 25.
</P>
<P>
   PIPE. Holdover. 36. Far away in Alaska, when the pictures show
oil-soaked birds and a tanker leaking crude into the ocean, an
environmental disaster such as the Exxon Valdez will easily capture
the national limelight. Much closer to home, however, the potential
for another kind of petroleum disaster lurks underground, along
150,000 miles of pipelines that transport hazardous liquids through
such places as rural Atchison, Kansas. Ruptured lines can occur
anywhere, from Coffeyville, Kan., to Glasgow, Mo., to just outside
the nation's capitol in Washington. They may not get the publicity
of an Exxon Valdez, but pipeline breaks caused $54 million in
property damage last year in the U.S., and by one count spilled 7.7
million gallons of oil and other substances. The Environmental
Defense Fund calls that the worst toll in eight years, and charges
that federal regulators don't do nearly enough to prevent such
incidents. Pipeline companies say they still offer the safest way
to transport oil, and they're doing what they can, including the
use of ``smart pigs,'' instrument-laden devices that travel through
a line to detect possible problems. John L. Dvorak. Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   VANGUARD _ A look at how tiny Vanguard Airlines made its case
against American Airlines, and what it means for the airline
industry. By Randolph Heaster
</P>
