<HEADLINE>
NEW FASHION MAGAZINE AIMED AT CHRISTIAN WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEATHERFORD, Texas _ Michelle Toholsky, a former model and
Christian talk-show host, is publishing a new Christian women's
fashion magazine called Shine.
</P>
<P>
   ``From boot-scootin' to Bass Hall _ Fort Worth Has It All'' and
``30 Days to Swimsuit Lean'' are featured articles in the inaugural
edition of Shine, scheduled to appear in Christian bookstores this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping romance in a marriage, fashion advice, hair and makeup
tips, cooking innovations, a fitness column and devotional essays
about Christian life round out the first edition, according to
publisher Toholsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our magazine will focus on both inner and outer beauty and
show the joy of Christian living,'' said Toholsky, a mother of four
children.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Walsh, a former co-host on Pat Robertson's ``700 Club,''
is featured on the cover of the first issue. Walsh will be a
regular contributor to the magazine. Nancy Stafford, a former Ford
model who was a co-star of the ``Matlock'' television series, is
contributing a column on inner beauty.
</P>
<P>
   The original ``Doublemint Twins,'' chewing-gum commercial stars
Linda Ryan and Lisa Winters, will write about their Christian
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord has brought together some incredible people,''
Toholsky said. ``I couldn't have done it by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Toholsky said her goal was to find everyday women with everyday
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get women who were real, very down to earth and
could relate to all women,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Toholsky met Walsh several years ago on the ``700 Club''
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``She interviewed me because I was a Christian model who
wouldn't do certain things, such as appear in lingerie ads or
commercials for alcoholic beverages and cigarettes,'' Toholsky
said.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, David, an oil company representative based in Fort
Worth, said the magazine involves many of her family members. Other
family projects include a Christian retreat center in Springtown
and a program to feed the homeless in Fort Worth and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   One of the magazine's features, ``The Mom Connection,'' will be
written by Toholsky; her mother, Sandy Hormillosa; and her
grandmother, Ila Barnett.
</P>
<P>
   The three formerly hosted a radio talk show called ``The Mom
Connection'' on KTCY//104.9 FM. Efforts are under way to put the
program on local television, Toholsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents always tried to instill Christian values and a
sense of giving in all of my family members,'' Toholsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Toholsky says her father, Tony Hormillosa, has headed a program
called Heart for the Homeless on Dallas streets for 11 years. He
recently expanded the ministry to Fort Worth. Hormillosa collects
food from area restaurants and other sources and travels in a van,
giving out food.
</P>
<P>
   Single copies of the bimonthly magazine are $2.95. An annual
subscription is $17.95. More information can be obtained by calling
(817) 613-0188 or writing to Box 2493, Weatherford, TX 76086.
</P>
<P>
   Toholsky says most of the proceeds from the magazine will be
given to area charities, including the street ministry run by her
father.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
