<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8873 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     05-24 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAT TWO COOKIES, AND CALL ME AN OLD LADY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be, doctors told you to take two aspirin and call in
the morning. My doctor suggested I eat a couple of cookies.
</P>
<P>
   No kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Signed in with the receptionist. Verified my address and
insurance carrier and took a seat in the waiting room. Nice waiting
room.
</P>
<P>
   You could twiddle your thumbs or read People magazine. I went
for the pamphlet on diabetes. Just the day before, I'd conferred
with the family hypochondriac and, medical manual in hand, decided
that's what I had. Not only does my sister Nancy suffer from it, so
does my mother's only surviving sibling, Aunt Eunice.
</P>
<P>
   I just wanted the doctor to confirm it and get rid of the sudden
dizzy spells I'd been experiencing.
</P>
<P>
   The nurse comes to the door and calls my name. I get up and
proceed to the scale. If ever there were a guarantee for bad news,
this is it.
</P>
<P>
   I weigh in at more than I ought to and head to the examining
room. It's nice, too. Cold. Bright. Sterile. I've already written a
check to cover my $10 co-pay. This is my room. I own it and the
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The nurse takes my blood pressure. It's perfect. I'm a bit
surprised because this is the other ailment common to my family.
</P>
<P>
   Because I don't want to even think about being pregnant again,
that leaves just one thing. Diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Doctor comes in and I describe my symptoms. I've been dizzy with
a little tingling in my lower extremities.
</P>
<P>
   He asks me if I had breakfast. I tell him I don't do breakfast.
Never have. Learned a long time ago that there were too many
wonderful foods to waste my time with breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   He tells me to eat something, anything, even if it's just a
couple of cookies, because if I'm waiting until lunch, it takes my
body about an hour to realize it's been at the trough.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, I'm paraphrasing here.
</P>
<P>
   But these are his exact words. ``You're not as young as you used
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   What's this! I give him 10 bucks, he gives me five minutes,
insults me and leaves.
</P>
<P>
   I sulk until the nurse returns and draws blood. Just to be sure,
she tells me, they're going to check for a few things. That was on
Friday. Monday, the nurse tells me my glucose level is fine, even
my good and bad cholesterol are fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's perfect,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   I'm dumbfounded. Can't even get sick. And I'm old.
</P>
<P>
   I call the family hypochondriac and share my humiliation. She
repeats the symptoms noted in her medical journal. She suggests
getting a second opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Back at work, people are suspicious because I'm not going for
the chocolate. They think my radar is off. I explain I haven't been
feeling well and I thought I should cut back. Besides, I'm
overweight.
</P>
<P>
   They look at me in disbelief and ask where. I whisper my weight.
They still want to know where. I ask for sympathy. They laugh in my
face.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not what I used to be. The doctor says so, and hardly a day
passes that my daughters don't remind me how old I am.
</P>
<P>
   But what do they know? When I was 8 years old, I thought 41 was
ancient, too. Only I didn't automatically think that someone had
one foot in the grave because of it.
</P>
<P>
   My baby does. The other day she asked me if I missed my mother.
I told her yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, don't worry, Mommy,'' she says. ``You're old. You'll
probably be in heaven with her soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, and I'm going to eat chocolate chips all the way there.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
