<SLUG> BC-MELROSE-NEXT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE HEATHER COULD SHARPEN HER CLAWS NEXT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having been a regular on ``Dynasty,'' ``T.J. Hooker'' and
``Melrose Place,'' as well as the lesser-known ``Going Places,''
Heather Locklear is fast becoming the feminine answer to Robert
Urich: a woman who can always find a TV show that will have her.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Melrose'' giving itself a big kiss-off Monday night,
Locklear is once again be free to explore her options. Here are
some shows we'd like to see her appear on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal'': The obvious choice. Heather shows up and tries
to outdo Ally in the micro-mini competition (no-weight division),
and makes life rough for Georgia, because she's played by
``Melrose'' alum Courtney Thorne-Smith and she's romantically
involved with a guy named Billy _ just like she was on ``Melrose!''
</P>
<P>
   ``General Hospital'': Heather wakes up from a coma to discover
that all seven seasons on ``Melrose'' were a dream, in an episode
that features the return of Frisco Jones (''Melrose's'' Jack
Wagner).
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files'': Fox Mulder begins to suspect that Heather is a
siren with some sort of paranormal power over cheesy rock stars
such as Tommy Lee and Richie Sambora, leading them to fall for her.
Heather also tries to exert control over Dana Scully by giving her
some fashion sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of the Hill'': Heather appears as Hank's long-lost
city-girl cousin, who settles down in Arlen as a Mary Kay
saleswoman and stirs previously dormant longings in Bobby Hill. In
a lengthy subplot, Heather and Boomhauer begin dating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawson's Creek'': Heather shakes things up as a new
schoolteacher who makes life interesting for the guys, miserable
for the girls, and nightmarish for her faculty colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends'': Heather threatens Chandler and Monica's
relationship when she takes a job as a waitress at Central Perk.
Joey and Ross also take an interest, but Joey's dumbness reminds
Heather too much of ``Melrose's'' Billy Campbell, and Ross' hair
gel reminds her too much of all the ``Melrose'' women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frasier'': Heather does a series of L'Oreal commercials for
KACL (so it's radio, and these are hair commercials. Work with us,
OK?). Frasier, charmed by the symmetry of his ``I'm listening'' and
her ``I'm worth it'' begins a romance with Heather, can't believe
his luck, and then blows it with some ridiculous nitpick about how
her roots are showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'': Heather strikes up a romance with
the mayor of Sunnyvale, unaware that he's an invincible demon.
Buffy goes after her, mistakenly thinking that Heather is a
vampire. Alas, she's only a vamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diagnosis Murder'': Heather shows up on a show where the lead
is more than twice her age, and gives him a heart attack, in effect
canceling the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Touched by an Angel'': The angels, having seen Heather's
antics on ``Dynasty'' and ``Melrose,'' try to make a better person
out of her. Encountering their first truly lost cause, they retire.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot writes on pop culture for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-T.MDNM/elegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
