<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8882 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIOLENCE-LYRICS-COX     05-24 1500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-LYRICS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can Music kill? Debate rages over roll of music in teen deaths
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can a rock band be blamed for the deadly actions of fervent
fans? Of course. The finger-pointing has happened time and again.
But does that mean there's a provable cause-and-effect relationship
when a young fan goes over the edge?
</P>
<P>
   The courts keep saying no.
</P>
<P>
   Few people would deny that music influences those who listen the
closest, particularly teen-agers looking for life's answers amid
the emotional tug-of-wars of peers, parents and school.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, Beatles lover Charles Manson told police the foursome's
``Helter Skelter'' inspired the Tate-LaBianca murders. In 1999,
everything that Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold listened to fell
under societal scrutiny after they shot to death 12 classmates and
a teacher at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., and then
killed themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle of the controversy this time was Marilyn
Manson (no relation to Charles). Already Public Enemy No. 1 in the
eyes of conservative family organizations, the ghoulish,
breast-clad shock-rocker's name came up repeatedly after the
Littleton shootings on talk shows, in newspaper editorials and on
the evening news. His ``Irresponsible Hate Anthem,'' with the lyric
``I am so all American, I'd sell you suicide,'' was cited as an
example of the messages being sent to teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Manson defended himself in a tersely worded statement two days
after the tragedy: ``The media has unfairly scapegoated the music
industry and so-called Goth kids and has speculated _ with no basis
in truth _ that artists like myself are in some way to blame. This
tragedy was a product of ignorance, hatred and an access to guns.''
</P>
<P>
   He canceled the last five concerts of his tour, including one in
Denver, but that didn't stop conservative organizations from going
after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you can't put the blame entirely on him,'' said Martin
Belforte, a representative from Austin's chapter of the American
Family Association. ``On the other hand, you can't ignore that he
glorifies suicide and hatred and endorses the idea that life has no
meaning. Everyone knows that music does have an influence on
teen-agers' attitudes, so what kind of an influence do you think he
has?''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Littleton tragedy, it appears that Manson had
very little, if any, influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus seems to be that (Harris and Klebold) didn't
even like Marilyn Manson,'' said Michael Mehle, pop music critic at
the Rocky Mountain News in Denver, citing the extensive work of
other reporters at the newspaper to verify a link. ``We stopped
mentioning him a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the campaign against the singer continues, as does
criticism of two lesser-known acts that the boys in Littleton did
like _ German industrial-rock bands KMFDM and Rammstein.
Investigators found scrawled lyrics from the bands that one of the
boys had written down.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Manson, whose lyrics are vaguely demonic and nihilistic
but rarely make any sense, KMFDM and Rammstein's songs are clearly
angry, aggressive and, yes, occasionally violent. One line in the
KMFDM song ``Piggybank'' goes, ``If I had a shotgun, I'd blow
myself to hell.'' Rammstein taped an MTV video full of shooting
scenes similar to the movie ``Reservoir Dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hitler-admiring gunmen apparently were attracted by the
bands' German heritage, although the musicians disavow any neo-Nazi
support.
</P>
<P>
   An art form
</P>
<P>
   ``KMFDM are an art form, not a political party,'' the group's
founder Sascha Konietzko said on the band's Web site. ``From the
beginning our music has been a statement against war, oppression,
fascism, and violence against each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Rammstein, meanwhile, didn't deny the violent overtones of its
music and especially its pyrotechnic-laden stage shows. The band's
statement read, ``We only show violence during our gigs and we make
it the subject of our lyrics. But we definitely refuse to practice
violence ... .'' Proving or disproving the influence of particular
bands in the Littleton shootings won't resolve the long-standing
debate over how to rein in music's powerful effect on young people.
With every new school shooting, like the one in the Atlanta suburb
of Conyers last week, questions will be asked about what kind of
music the gunman favored. (The recordings of the late rapper Tupac
Shakur was singled out in this latest case.)
</P>
<P>
   A similar critical crescendo sounded nine years ago over the
English heavy metal band Judas Priest. The band was sued by the
families of two fans, high-school dropouts who made a suicide pact
using a shotgun in Reno, Nev. One died and the other lived for
three years, but with facial deformations.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy-metal youth culture was put on trial. It was argued in
court, however, that the boys had seriously troubled upbringings.
Despite histories of drug abuse, physical abuse, clinical
depression and other signs of familial dysfunction _ plus, one of
the boys had just broken up with his girlfriend _ the parents
blamed Judas Priest for the suicide pact. The band's ``Stained
Class'' album was on the turntable at the time they shot
themselves, and it was said to include the subliminal message, ``Do
it! Do it!,'' recorded in a barely audible technique. The judge
left open the possibility of such subliminal messages being
considered harmful, but he didn't fault the band or the ``do-its''
in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Ozzy Osbourne, another English rocker, has fought three lawsuits
in which parents said his song ``Suicide Solution'' caused their
sons' suicides. The judges also sided with Osbourne in each case,
saying his music was protected under the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Bands not guilty
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hemphill, a First Amendment lawyer in Austin, said it would
be difficult for any of the bands mentioned in the Littleton case
to be found guilty in a court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the proper court debate is whether or not music,
or art of any kind, can help cause a disturbed person to go over
the edge,'' said Hemphill. ``It can, we've all seen that. The
question is whether a band should be held responsible because a
disturbed fan does something tragic. So far, the court has said it
shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Hemphill helped represent Tupac Shakur and Interscope
Records, who were sued by the family of a state trooper killed near
Victoria by an 18-year-old man. The teen had been listening to
Shakur's ``2Pacalypse Now'' in his car before the shooting, and
claimed in his own criminal trial that the tape inspired him to
kill. The rapper and label, however, won the suit in a summary
judgment by U.S. District Court Judge John Rainey. Jurors in the
criminal trial gave the shooter the death penalty, deciding music
wasn't a mitigating factor in the murder.
</P>
<P>
   In the civil case, Judge Rainey wrote, ``At best, the recording
(`2Pacalypse Now') reveals that weak-willed individuals may be
influenced by Shakur's work. As the Supreme Court (has) explained,
swaying the weak-willed does not remove constitutional protection
from speech. ... The defendants cannot be responsible for
determining the mental condition of each and every potential
listener.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hemphill, ``All these cases, including the Colorado
shootings, are incredibly unsettling, so it's only right that
people try to find out what the heck is going on. ... But blaming
(the music) seems to be an overly simplistic solution to way more
complex problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Belforte at the American Family Association agrees, but he said
that doesn't mean Marilyn Manson and other rock acts shouldn't be
stopped, either through censorship or, more likely, through
boycotts.
</P>
<P>
   What do teens think?
</P>
<P>
   ``We still think parents should send the message that we don't
want this kind of dangerous music being sold to kids,'' Belforte
said. ``Like it or not, there are more and more teens with a
penchant for violence these days, and this kind of music simply
causes much more harm than it does good.''
</P>
<P>
   The oft-forgotten factor in this ongoing debate is what teens
themselves think. Among a dozen interviewed at the WherehouseMusic
store in South Austin last week, many were ambivalent to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't listen to any of those bands, so I don't really care
whether I can buy their CDs or not,'' said 17-year-old Trey
Crocker.
</P>
<P>
   The one shopper who did seem to care likes Manson's music. Tony
Melendez, 18, who owns two of Manson's CDs, said the singer and
others like him are getting a bad rap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just rock music, you know,'' Melendez said. ``I know lots
of people who listen to it, and they've never gone out and shot
people. But then I've never known any kids who keep shotguns and
pipe bombs in their bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Chris Riemenschneider at
criemenschneider(at)statesman.com or call 445-3607.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
