r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELROSE-CONFESSIONS-T     05-24 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELROSE-CONFESSIONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFESSIONS OF A `MELROSE' FAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a certain point, ``Melrose Place'' was perfectly in sync with
the Zeitgeist. That point came in a mid-'90s ``Seinfeld'' episode
in which Jerry was revealed to be a closet ``Melrose'' watcher. It
led, as such things tended to on ``Seinfeld,'' to the downfall of a
relationship, but Jerry acknowledged that he had to watch because
he couldn't believe that the characters on ``Melrose'' did things
that were so stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry's disclosure came as comfort to many of us closet
``Melrose'' watchers. We're an odd lot. Many of us are reasonably
intelligent, artistically inclined, the type who think it's pretty
cool to live in an area that gets movies with subtitles. And yet
``Melrose,'' a show that featured mediocre-at-best actors playing
great-looking but shallow people doing incredibly stupid things ...
well, the show was addictive.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, anyway. Like most soap operas, ``Melrose''
eventually hit a point where it was chasing its creative tail. It
got to a point where it seemed that Heather Locklear's character,
Amanda Woodward, had dated every guy on the show except for Matt,
the gay character with a lousy love life. The show even made a joke
out of the serial romances in a recent episode, in which Thomas
Calabro's scheming Michael Mancini expresses his love for his
newest infatuation and then gives props to his wives, listing each
as an afterthought: ``Nothing against Jane ... or Sydney ... or
Kimberley ... or Megan ... or Jane again ... ''
</P>
<P>
   It was that self-aware sense of humor that kept us watching,
guilty as we felt about doing so. Calabro, probably the show's best
actor, playing Michael, its best character, once called the show a
comedy. Although the show had a certain hit-the-organ-chord
melodrama to it, he had a point _ ``Melrose'' often winked at the
viewer. It was stupid, but it had us hooked, even though we
couldn't figure out why nobody ever closed their Venetian blinds on
the show, why people always jumped to the worst possible
conclusions and why characters often married people who had once
tried to blow them up.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, jokes run out of gas if you tell them enough, and
``Melrose,'' like ``Seinfeld,'' told its jokes a few times too
many. Those of us who once watched it as a guilty pleasure drifted
away, only to come back out of curiosity as the show peters to its
end. You could call the show influential. You could say that
without it, we wouldn't have ``Ally McBeal,'' ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' or ``Charmed.'' You could say that, but ``Melrose'' never
meant itself to be taken even that seriously. And that's why we
watched.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot writes on pop culture for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
