</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SITCOMS-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPARTURE OF `HOME IMPROVEMENT,' `MAD ABOUT YOU' LEAVES VOID IN
SITCOM LAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How ironic that the series most likely to solve family squabbles
neatly and lovingly will leave the air in the midst of a
professional family falling-out. Viewers who have stayed with
``Home Improvement,'' which concludes its eight-year run Tuesday,
will find it odd that co-star Jonathan Taylor Thomas isn't there.
</P>
<P>
   Why the actor decided to skip the final episode depends on
whether you're reading The Star, watching ``Inside Edition'' or
listening to co-star Patricia Richardson, who seems to spread the
blame across a number of quarters, including the actor's advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me if this sounds unsympathetic, but this was exactly the
sort of friction this syrupy little series needed to change its rep
from the Mariah Carey of sitcoms _ a comedy that wouldn't be so
artificial had it borrowed even a bit from real life. (Judging from
the finale, however, it made little difference.)
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``Mad About You,'' the other series survivor
checking out this week after seven years, has come full circle,
delivering a final note that love and marriage is as glorious as it
is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional theory that the two sitcoms started out as
opposites _ ``Mad'' as the edgy, urban romantic comedy, ``Home'' as
the formulaic, suburban family sitcom _ and ended as dorky family
comedies doesn't really ring true.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, complaints that ``Mad'' had grown weary and repetitive
usually came from people who didn't seem to be actually watching
the show on a regular basis anymore.
</P>
<P>
   I know. I was one of them. But after watching a number of this
year's shows, I saw that the series had picked up steam rather
nicely, peaking with a few episodes that could stand with this
romantic comedy's best.
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell exactly where these sitcoms fall within the
lexicon of television culture, whether they said something of
significance or merely dissolved into the wasteland that's series
television.
</P>
<P>
   What's clear is that ``Home'' and ``Mad,'' both based on the
adage that you can't live without men and you can't kill them, seem
to be the last of their breeds.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, ``Home'' was a family show that played
shamelessly to everyone in the family. That made it an instant hit
with viewers and a complete bore to TV critics, many of whom found
its elements too easy to assemble. (In our cynical world, we now
consider ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' a family show, although the
kids are merely props.)
</P>
<P>
   Tim Allen's Tim Taylor was a master of macho madness, hammering
through 2-by-4s on his cable show and bantering with partner and
buddy Al (Richard Karn), always ridiculed because of his
``sensitivity.''
</P>
<P>
   At home with wife Jill (Richardson), and sons played by Thomas,
Taran Noah Smith and Zachery Ty Bryan, Tim was an aggressive
goof-up whose masculine pride frequently got him in trouble,
particularly with Jill, who wanted her boys to live a more cultured
life. (Thankfully they seemed to have turned out more like Jill
than Tim.)
</P>
<P>
   Next-door neighbor Wilson (Earl Hindman) appeared like clockwork
to mop up each Taylor mess. The running gag was that his character
never showed his entire face, always being blocked by the high
fence or other perfectly placed objects. It's the one area in which
``Home Improvement'' refused to kowtow to audience yearning.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's character was merely a domesticated version of his ``Men
Are Pigs'' stand-up act, about a modern man so confused about women
that he's reduced to beating his chest and making grunting noises.
I never could figure if those sounds were a gorilla flexing
territorial muscle or a baboon stuck in a trap.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Home'' was a clever vehicle for Allen's talents, partly
because he offered us a jerk we could enjoy guilt-free.
</P>
<P>
   But signing on Richardson was the clincher. Jill served as the
female counterpoint to Tim's male world. She was the intellectual
of the two, someone who looked beyond Tim's fascination with
machinery and the power that propels it.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Richardson said that it was always
important to her (though not necessarily to the writers, she noted)
that the relationship be balanced. It was Richardson who tried,
usually in vain, to take apart gender-related cliches, to show the
real ups and downs of marriage with children.
</P>
<P>
   She admits that far too many times, Tim got away with murder as
her character was asked to grin and bear it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this is also what ``Home'' shares with ``Mad'' _ female
co-stars talented enough to mask the shortcomings of their comedic
husbands.
</P>
<P>
   Much like Jill and Tim, Jamie (Helen Hunt) and Paul (Paul
Reiser) played yin off yang. The only difference was that they
often switched positions. The impulsive, neurotic Paul could be
driven insane by some trivial matter, only to be soothed by
cautious, calm Jamie. Later, Jamie is the neurotic impulsive being
consoled by rational Paul.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
