<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8892 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SITCOMS-2ndTake-TE     05-24 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SITCOMS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: rational Paul.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Hunt got to do what Richardson yearned for: To play half of
a wrinkled, flawed, real couple at a time when television considers
three episodes a long-term relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Each season we have another romantic comedy contender (at least
three come up this fall), but none has been able to do it right. I
don't know if that has more to do with characters, writing and
execution, or a shift in viewer tastes preferring legally
unattached love.
</P>
<P>
   But some of ``Mad's'' best scenes were those when Jamie had had
enough, when Paul was pushing her buttons and she'd storm around
the apartment growling or dash out of the place altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Jill wouldn't dream of doing that.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Mad'' had to evolve to that point. The series started out
as yet another talky urban sitcom about young, bagel-eating yuppies
populating the streets of Manhattan. Its search for laughs in the
little things of life made it seem too ``Seinfeld'' for its own
good.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the exploration of the offbeat details gradually revealed a
relationship that was intensely intimate and candid and
realistically fragile.
</P>
<P>
   The cliff-hanging story arc during the 1996-97 season framed
this truth especially well. When Jamie kissed a co-worker, Paul
went into an emotional tailspin. Although it seemed almost silly to
think that the two would actually break up (and become, what, ``No
Longer Mad About You?''), the writing showing a relationship at a
crossroads was effective. That it was Jamie, not Paul, who strayed,
was also an attempt to roam the seldom-used road.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the nasty things critics have said about the series
since the baby arrived, the best episode of the entire run was the
one-shot, real-time episode when the couple stood outside their
door listening to daughter Mabel cry herself to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides of the independent-baby debate were well-represented
and executed with great care and sensitivity. Their decision to let
her cry _ and Jamie's last words of ``We broke her heart'' _ still
rings with me.
</P>
<P>
   Neither series could promote feminism without making fun of it,
which I think is a direct result of men dominating writing staffs.
But both series advocated equality for women while showing how
difficult equal partnerships can be.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the abilities of Hunt and Richardson often came
in, as their roles carried the burden of delivering value-laden
messages.
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite ``Home'' exchanges begins with Tim saying to
Jill, ``Why do you bug me during football games? Did I bother you
during childbirth?'' and Jill responding, ``No, but you bothered me
during conception.''
</P>
<P>
   That verbal jousting is played back during the season finale. In
fact, flashbacks are a part of both season-enders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mad About You,'' which aired Monday night, was the most
ambitious, and most successful. Janeane Garofalo plays a grown-up
Mabel talking about her parents, and the results are surprising and
touching.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Home,'' airing Tuesday, Al is getting married while
Jill and Tim contemplate a move to Indiana to follow Jill's career.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. Even with Thomas a no-show, it manages to go out
the same way it came in: safe, reassuring, comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
