<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8898 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCULPTURE-TEX     05-24 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCULPTURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOW REVEALS LIMITLESS POSSIBILITIES OF SOMETIMES DISDAINED ART
FORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Sculpture, critic Charles Baudelaire said in
the mid-1800s, is something you trip over when stepping back to
look at a painting.
</P>
<P>
   Baudelaire considered sculpture boring and the work of
uncivilized people. Having little use for it, he likely would shun
_ assuming he were alive, that is _ a new Fort Worth exhibition
called ``House of Sculpture.''
</P>
<P>
   Opened Sunday at the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth, ``House of
Sculpture'' features about 30 works by about 30 artists _ and nary
a painting. The earliest work on view is the Modern's classic
Joseph Cornell box, ``Untitled (Medici Boy)'' of 1953. A couple of
the most recent are 1998-99 works by Rachel Whiteread, one of the
YBAs (Young British Artists) who have taken the world by storm, and
Joseph Havel, a Houston artist known for his poetic castings of
such improbable items as shirt collars and (in this show)
bedsheets.
</P>
<P>
   This is a nervy show for the Modern to present. Baudelaire
wasn't (and isn't) the only member of the art elite to disdain
sculpture. Snobbery isn't the only reason sculpture shows are
scarcer than hen's teeth, though.
</P>
<P>
   Sculpture is difficult to display to advantage. Insensitively
installed, sculpture tends to look and feel as if it's in the way _
like something you'd, well, bump into. Too, the cost of shipping
sculpture is enough to discourage many a museum.
</P>
<P>
   So why _ apart from the fact that it surely can afford to pay
for shipping _ is our Modern Art Museum presenting this show?
(Which, by the way, is exclusive to Fort Worth.)
</P>
<P>
   Michael Auping, the Modern's chief curator, has a ready answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sculpture of the last 30 years is literally all over the
place,'' Auping says. ``You could argue that the most radical
developments in the art of the past 25 years have been in
sculpture. Since the end of World War II, sculpture has been
remarkably aggressive in staking out new territories, in adapting
new and changing ``Zeitgeists.''''
</P>
<P>
   That's another way of saying that many of the most significant
artists of the past several decades have been involved with
sculpture. Artists like Cornell, Dan Flavin, Eva Hesse, Robert
Irwin, Donald Judd, Bruce Nauman, Claes Oldenburg, Richard Serra
and David Smith _ all of whom are represented in this exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   With pop art and minimalism in the '60s, sculpture stepped down
from its pedestal: Andy Warhol made what might be called a
sculpture _ it occupied space, after all _ that was a simulation of
a Brillo box. Californian John McCracken made tall, narrow,
immaculately finished slabs that stood on the floor and leaned
against the wall. And they hardly were alone.
</P>
<P>
   Then came artists like Hesse, Nauman and Lynda Benglis. They
made objects that dangled from the wall, that drooped or appeared
to be oozing, or that lay abjectly on the floor. From there,
Nauman, Irwin and others explored the sculptural possibilities of
light and sound as defining or occupying space.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with such endless possibilities, Auping says he took
a relatively conservative tack in choosing this show. Initially, at
least, he looked at sculpture in terms of something that stands in
space, and he seemingly stretched out from there. What he ended up
with is an installation that encompasses many of the above
sculptural possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   To make a bit more sense of it all, Auping has grouped some
works according to when they were made, as well as according to
themes like figuration and minimalism.
</P>
<P>
   Installing it, he effectively assumed the role of some of the
sculptures, standing where they would stand, considering their
relationships with other nearby works or pieces within range of
vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with sculpture forces you to think differently,''
Auping says. ``Installing paintings is about continually looking.
Establishing transitions with sculpture involves different
instincts. It's more about walking and standing. You almost have to
pretend to be the sculpture.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting exhibition flows gently, rather than making
grandiose statements. It lets people figure out quite a bit on
their own. And that's really the best way of getting to know art.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``House of Sculpture,'' through Aug. 8
</P>
<P>
   Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   1309 Montgomery St.
</P>
<P>
   (817) 738-9215
</P>
<P>
   Admission: Free
</P>
<P>
   Hours: 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesday-Friday, 11 a.m.-5 p.m. Saturday,
noon-5 p.m. Sunday
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You
can call her at (817) 390-7679, or e-mail:
vizart(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
