NYT-05-24-99 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8907 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-24 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO LESSONS IN SAVING FOR RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I would like to retire in 28 years at age 60 with
inflation-adjusted income that matches our current level of
$85,000. Maybe I'm an optimist, but I believe Social Security will
exist for us. Currently we have $25,000 in a 401(k) plan, to which
we contribute 3 percent of our income, and there is an employer
match of 25 percent of the first 6 percent. This is invested 10
percent each in Fidelity Overseas and Fidelity Worldwide, 20
percent each in Fidelity Magellan and Blue Chip Growth, and 40
percent in Fidelity Contrafund. Our general savings, to be used for
nonessential living expenses, possible college expenses beyond a
program we have established for our two children, or retirement,
amount to $10,000 in three mutual funds. We add to these accounts
irregularly, depending on how fruitful the year was. Will we
achieve our goals with this investment plan?
</P>
<P>
   M.B., Londonderry, N.H. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Alas, my friend, you're not even likely to come close.
</P>
<P>
   The big stickler is that phrase you used: inflation adjusted. If
we presume inflation averages 3.5 percent during the next 28 years,
you will need $222,714 to buy what $85,000 buys today.
</P>
<P>
   If you keep up with your current savings plan and you achieve 10
percent average annual growth, you'll have a little in excess of
$800,000.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you get raises during all those years and continue
your contributions as a percentage of salary, the accumulation will
be greater, but probably nowhere near enough to meet your target.
</P>
<P>
   I would begin by correcting the most obvious mistake, which is
your failure to take fullest advantage of your employer's matching
program.
</P>
<P>
   If you went up to 6 percent contributions to the 401(k), the
match would double, to a level of $1,500 a year. This would also
bump your expected accumulation in the 401(k) to a little in excess
of $1.4 million _ still not enough to take you to your goals, but a
whole lot better.
</P>
<P>
   There's no problem with your selection of investments, but if
you indeed want to have a comfortable retirement, you're going to
have to take the whole business of saving more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   So what would it take to support your plan for retirement? You
might come fairly close if you moved your 401(k) savings level to
10 percent of your salary, and kept it at that level every time you
got a raise.
</P>
<P>
   Ten percent contributions, plus the maximum employer match,
would take you to a figure just shy of $2 million, again assuming
10 percent investment returns. And as your salary and contributions
increased, so would employer matches, taking the pool even higher.
</P>
<P>
   And a more disciplined approach to your other savings program
would also help, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are 30 and 34 years old, respectively, and
have worked to save fairly aggressively. We are now trying to
determine if what we have saved is in the right vehicles and
determine if we're on the right course to finance a comfortable
retirement (very far off), a new home, and a vacation home purchase
within three years. We make about $200,000 annually and have
accumulated $137,000 in retirement savings. We have no credit card
or auto loan debt, and owe $195,000 on our home, which is appraised
at $249,000. We are both donating the maximum allowed by our 401(k)
plans. We also have $20,500 invested in a mutual fund and four
common stock accounts with dividend reinvestment programs, and we
add $900 a month to these five accounts. Finally, we have $146,300
in other savings, of which $33,000 is in a money market fund and
the rest in mutual fund and common stock accounts. Do you have any
suggestions on how we're investing?
</P>
<P>
   B.M., Acton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You are certainly on the right path for a very comfortable
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   You don't mention how much you contribute to your 401(k)
accounts, but if each of you is contributing 10 percent of your
salaries, or a total of $1,666 a month, your accumulation would be
in excess of $5.8 million in 30 years, presuming 10 percent average
annual portfolio growth.
</P>
<P>
   Your portfolio is nicely diversified, and although you don't
give details of how your husband's 401(k) is invested, if he is
following your lead his will also be well diversified.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing I worry about is how you're going to finance the
purchases of a new primary residence and a vacation home within the
next three years.
</P>
<P>
   You will probably need more cash than that $33,000 in the money
market fund, so you might either consider selling some of the stock
positions _ after examining the tax consequences of the potential
sales, of course _ or diverting some of that $900 in monthly
savings that's going into nonretirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Three years is a short savings time frame, and putting
short-term money in stocks is pretty dangerous. I suggest you tally
up the amount of cash you will need for these purchases, and set up
the nonretirement savings accounts so that you will have it on hand
in liquid accounts.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you diverted the $900 monthly savings to your
money market fund, that $33,000 would amount to a little more than
$73,000 over the next 36 months, here presuming 5 percent average
annual returns from the money fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
