<SLUG> BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
  
 ART ADV.: Photos with NH-LOEB and ARRANGED-MARRIAGES are being
transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BELGRADE-SCENE (Belgrade) _ Belgrade's defiance in the early
days of the bombing has been replaced by something more like groggy
resignation that the war will continue indefinitely. By Kevin
cullen. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   MACEDONIA-SCENE (Skopje, Macedonia) _ With hundreds of Kosovars
arriving daily and the United States advocating a rapid buildup of
NATO troops, young Macedonians feel attacked on all fronts. By
Lynda gorov. 1000 words. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-VIOLENCE (Belfast) _ First study of its kind examines
the impact of 30 years of violence on ordinary Irish citizens:
nightmares, flashbacks, drug use. By Larry Tye. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SHAS (Jerusalem) _ Political power of the ultra-Orthodox
is surging. Their belief that Israel should be a theocracy poses a
threat to the 70 percent of Israel that would define itself as
secular. By Charles M. Sennott. 1290 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NH-LOEB (Manchester, N.H.) _ After decades with a Loeb at the
helm of the Union Leader Corp., the torch is being passed from
Nackey Loeb to Joe McQuaid, who takes over as publisher of the
arch-conservative paper. By Jill Zuckman. 1200 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   NH-MCQUADE (Manchester, N.H.) _ It's likely Joseph McQuaid and
the Union-Leader will be scrutinized for any hints of which
presidential candidate will receive the paper's blessing, and which
ones will feel its wrath. By Jill Zuckman. 445 words.
</P>
<P>
   MEMOIR-PERSEUS (Cambridge, Mass.) _ An acrimonius battle has
developed over charges of espionage against one of the nation's
most revered scientists. By David L. Chandler. 1245 words. (a and i
coding) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEAD-DRIFTER (Pensacola, Fla.) _ Mark Bailey has become, in
death, a symbol of the misery that can grow from a brief spasm of
violence in prison. By Curtis Wilkie. 935 words.
</P>
<P>
   ARRANGED-MARRIAGES (Undated) _ Young immigrant professionals _
aware that half of the marriages in America end in divorces _ are
holding onto one of their most sacred faiths: arranged marriages.
By Tasha Robertson. 1230 words. PHOTO (a and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ In New Hampshire, the candidacy of
presidential hopeful Bill Bradley in 1999 is looking more like the
candidacy of Paul Tsongas of 1991. By Robert A. Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Concord, N.H.) _ In the center of the
school-finance debate. By Thomas Oliphant.
</P>
<P>
   JACOBY-COLUMN (Undated) -- Ray Shamie's last campaign. By Jeff
Jacoby.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Martin F. Nolan's and Diane White's columns are
unavailable today.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH/SCIENCE (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NONCOMPETE (Undated) _ Non-compete contracts, common in
business to protect trade secrets or a customer base, are a new and
alarming wrinkle in the health care industry. By Dolores Kong. 1130
words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-QUESTIONS (Undated) _ What causes headaches? By David
Ropeik.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-TALK-SHOWS (Undated) -- The late-night talk show universe has
gone to a more segmented system. Four who divide up the alt
late-night kingdom. By Don Aucoin. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-SPRINGS (Undated) _ With her Kentucky pedigree and
plain-spoken ambiguities, Bobbie Ann Mason was one of the American
writers who emerged in the 1980s under the unruly rubric of
minimalism, though she didn't really belong there. By Gail
Caldwell. 1260 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-RUN (Undated) _ Christopher Tilghman has chosen a gem of a
title for his second collection of stories: ``The Way People Run.''
By Matthew Gilbert. 1025 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-THOREAU (Undated) _ Henry David Thoreau, determinedly
individualistic, has suffered an interesting fate in the tag end of
the 20th century. He is become Everyman. By M.R. Montgomery. 1230
words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TIPS (Undated) _ What's hot on the just-published list.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-STARWARS (Undated) _ ``Star Wars'' appears headed for its
