<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADS SEND THE WRONG MESSAGE ABOUT BREAST CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ IN 50 years on Earth, I have seen many
advertisements that missed the mark so badly they should have been
classified as ``friendly fire.''
</P>
<P>
   A new, three-page ad for Nolvadex, the anti-cancer drug
tamoxifen, is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Printed in mainstream magazines, not medical journals, the ad is
aimed at women who are afraid of developing breast cancer _ which
is to say practically every woman alive. It features a large photo
of the back of a slim, young-looking woman in a black lacy bra and
black panties. She sits like a statue amid bed sheets.
</P>
<P>
   The ad copy headline: ``If you care about breast cancer, care
more about being a 1.7 than a 36B.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1.7 refers to the breast cancer risk assessment test.
</P>
<P>
   Score 1.7 or above and you are considered high risk by the
medical profession. Your chances of getting breast cancer are
almost double the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing your number gives you power, and knowing about
Nolvadex should give you hope,'' the ad soothes. ``Because even if
you are at high risk, Nolvadex has been proven to significantly
reduce the incidence of breast cancer in women at high risk.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll talk about that ``proof'' later. Look at the ad's overt
message.
</P>
<P>
   Black lacy underwear, bed sheets and a babe signal one thing,
right? Gotcha! Then you get hit with a truly insulting implication:
If you're not too vain or obsessed with the size of your breasts,
you'll be scared enough to check your risk for breast cancer.
(``You owe it to yourself to find out.'') If you're high-risk, be
smart and ask your doctor for Nolvadex. (``There is something you
can do.'')
</P>
<P>
   Nolvadex may indeed turn out to be the miracle prevention drug
that its manufacturer and the National Cancer Institute have touted
it to be. Since 1973, tamoxifen has been a highly effective
treatment for diagnosed breast cancers. Raking in about $500
million in annual sales, Nolvadex has made its British-Swedish drug
manufacturer AstraZeneca Plc, a major player on the global
pharmaceutical stage.
</P>
<P>
   But in April 1998, the results of a National Cancer Institute
study of 13,388 high-risk women catapulted AstraZeneca into a new
universe of potential earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Although the study was interrupted 14 months before its
scheduled completion, NCI researchers pronounced tamoxifen a breast
cancer ``preventive'' for high-risk women. Tracked for an average
of three years, 6,600 of the women took tamoxifen while 6,000 took
placebos. In the tamoxifen group, 85 developed breast cancer
compared to 154 in the placebo group.
</P>
<P>
   The actual difference is only 69 cases, but that translates into
a powerful sounding ``45 percent decrease'' for the tamoxifen
users.
</P>
<P>
   British researchers quickly blasted the National Cancer
Institute for basing its conclusions on such a brief study: 10
years is considered a better indicator for any such trial.
</P>
<P>
   Further, tamoxifen is supposed to be taken for five years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, three European studies found little difference
between tamoxifen-placebo groups.
</P>
<P>
   None of that mattered. Despite Novadex's side effects _ a 2-3
times greater risk of uterine cancer, blood clots, strokes,
cataracts and hot flashes _ women at high risk for breast cancer
inundated doctors with demands for the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Two months before the U.S. Food and Drug Administration gave
tamoxifen a very qualified OK as a preventive, AstraZeneca and
Europe's fifth largest drug company, Roche Holding AG, announced
they would jointly promote Nolvadex in the United States. The drug
is available in generic form elsewhere, but AstraZeneca has
exclusive manufacturing rights here until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the American Society of Clinical Oncology gave
tamoxifen another lukewarm thumbs-up as a prophylactic.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors should offer the drug to high-risk women, said the
group, but not recommend it.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half of the Nolvadex ad, you learn that the drug
``is not for everybody.'' Tamoxifen's side effects are listed along
with an 800 number for a free video. Nowhere do you learn some of
the most important numbers about breast cancer and high risk.
</P>
<P>
   While breast cancer strikes every age group, more than
three-fourths of the cases are diagnosed in women over age 50.
</P>
<P>
   Merely reaching your 60th birthday automatically qualifies you
as high risk.
</P>
<P>
   In the NCI study, tamoxifen prevented 20 breast cancers in every
1,000 women over 50 who still had a uterus. It also caused
life-threatening side effects in 22 per 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The size and mainstream placement of the Nolvadex ads aggravates
a growing American phobia: Being a woman means you'll probably get
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, the average U.S. woman stands a 12 percent chance
of developing breast cancer in her lifetime. Most high risk women
(20 percent of the female population) have not an 80 or 90 percent
chance but a 24 percent shot.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, whether they care about being a 36B or not, more U.S.
women are killed by heart disease than by all other cancers
combined.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
