<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY RUN AMOK 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Please don't misunderstand. I am definitely not
against progress, not even if it's spelled with a capital ``P,'' or
for that matter if its rendered as PROGRESS.
</P>
<P>
   I write on a computer and use e-mail daily. Research is abetted
by access to the Internet. Voice mail often permits life to proceed
more smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the new technologies which are nosing their way
into everyday lives are welcome and helpful. You can shop for a
yacht by phone, for all I know, and be perfectly happy with the
result.
</P>
<P>
   Still, all is not peaches and cream.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for one example, the phone calls we get of an evening,
usually after supper. On the other end is what the speaker
obviously hopes will be considered a solicitous voice, asking to
speak to Mr. Rosenfield. Being swift of mind, I immediately sense
that this is not exactly an intimate of mine. Sometimes the hopeful
voice at the other end is seeking a Mr. Rosenford. This puzzled me
for a while, until I figured out that when I hurriedly print my
surname it could, conceivably, if you want to be picky and
difficult, be read as Rosenford instead of the
what-should-be-plain-to-everyone Rosenfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Upon confessing to my identity, I am barraged with a flow of
words so rapid and ill-spoken that I find it difficult to grasp
just what is being said. I do make out that this is a call from a
phone system or a credit card company, of which I am reassured by
the voice, I am a treasured customer. I further decipher that
because I am such a fantastic client _ one in a thousand, if not
better _ they are offering me a fabulously new and larger and
better arrangement that will make my existence on Earth a heck of a
lot pleasanter, even though my costs might possibly go up a teensy
bit.
</P>
<P>
   Being unsure just exactly what blessing is being proferred, and
not wishing to forego such a potential benefit, I ask for their
proposal to be sent to me in writing so that I might study it and
render a competent decision.
</P>
<P>
   There follows a pause on the other end of the line. After a
momentary hesitancy, the voice again takes up the sales pitch. When
I interrupt to say that I insist on a written offer, the
exasperated reply is ``But we have nothing in writing.'' No
kidding. Nothing to be had in black and white, to be able to review
and think about. Instead, the people who unleash these pitchmen
want an on-the-spot decision on the basis of an incomprehensible
phone call made by people who clearly have not specialized in
elocution.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, poor enunciation is not the annoyance your
experience when you place a phone call these days to many a
business enterprise. Awaiting you at the other end is a perfectly
distinct voice that for all its comprehensibility has a certain
deadly quality to it.
</P>
<P>
   You hear from this voice a recitation of the multifarious
activities that transpire, apparently with regularity, under this
office's roof, in which you were seeking human contact with just
one single soul out of the multitudes apparently rattling around in
there.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that you have merely to listen and evaluate a myriad of
choices, at the end you have to remember which of the options
offered approximates your needs the best.
</P>
<P>
   It helps to have a pad and pen handy, so that you could rapidly
take notes on the catalog that is being recited. If you are, say,
``discomfited'' by this, think how many more pennies are moving to
the bottom line of the business that has substituted mechanical
intelligence for the human kind.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, your valuable time has been chewed up accommodating
yourself to their peculiar idea on how to make friends and
influence people.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of abuse goes on and on. The guise is that better
service is being delivered; the actuality is that it makes a sham
of service.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the people who run the subways not only cleaned up
the cars, which themselves have been updated. They have also
installed a loudspeaker system that is designed to inform riders of
the station which they have reached as well as the name of the one
coming up next.
</P>
<P>
   What a splendid idea, especially for a city to which tourists
flock. The problem is that the crackles that emanate from the
system are useless because they cannot possibly be understood. To
the avidly listening straphanger, it is not apparent whether it is
the fault of the speaker or of the system or both.
</P>
<P>
   Here a perfectly good idea is wasted because it doesn't begin to
deliver the goods reliably.
</P>
<P>
   So many of the contemporary applications of technologies require
more than a second look, both by those who purport them as an
improvement for our way of life, and by all of us who are being
afflicted by innovations that have run amok or gone awry. Enough,
already.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
