<HEADER>
A8958 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEAD-DRIFTER-BOS &LR;      05-24 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAD-DRIFTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY SEEKS JUSTICE FOR DRIFTER WHO DIED ON JAILHOUSE FLOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENSACOLA, Fla. _ Mark Bailey was a Penobscot Indian who drifted
down from New England years ago in search of a place in the sun,
only to wind up dead at the age of 39 on the floor of the Escambia
County Jail on a winter morning a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Unheralded in life, Bailey has become the center of controversy
in death and a symbol of the misery that can grow from a brief
spasm of violence in a combustible setting where prisoners and
guards gnaw at each others' emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Bailey's family and inmates at the jail say he was
beaten to death by a gang of corrections officers after he struck a
woman jailer. After nearly five months of inquiries and multiple
autopsies, the state has reached no conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting on the medical examiner's report, and then
we'll proceed,'' said Michelle Kiefer, public information officer
for the Florida Department of Law Enforcement. She said Sheriff Jim
Lowman and other officials had been instructed by county
supervisors not to discuss the case with the press.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bailey, the 20-year-old son of the victim, said: ``He died
with a little help from them in jail. I'm sort of confident about
what's going on, but it's aggravating how slow it's been.''
</P>
<P>
   After Dr. William Bell, an associate medical examiner for
Escambia County, quickly concluded that Bailey did not die at the
hands of the officers, lawyers representing Bailey's family
retained Dr. Ronald Reeves, a former official in another Florida
county who calls himself ``the people's medical examiner'' and
offers his services to trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves declared the officers responsible for Bailey's death. But
because of his controversial position, he was replaced with a Miami
pathologist who is studying the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Department of Law Enforcement intervened by bringing
in a medical examiner from Pinellas County to conduct a third
autopsy. The FBI has also entered the case, according to Bailey's
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, sworn statements have been collected from
several inmates who said they saw Bailey beaten to death. The
accounts differ, but O'Gwen King, one of the lawyers involved in
the case, said, ``Anytime you take statements from that many
people, you're going to get some discrepancies. These are
remarkably similar stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey had never amounted to much since coming here more than 20
years ago _ from Vermont, the family's lawyer believes. Divorced,
with two sons, he worked as an itinerant house painter. Much of the
time, he drank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he could drink heavy,'' said his son. ``Other times,
he didn't drink at all. He started realizing he had a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   He went through a treatment program for alcoholism in late 1998,
then in the first week of the new year, something snapped. Fueled
by liquor, Bailey had an argument with his girlfriend, Tanya
Thomas, and bolted from her rural home a couple of hours before
dawn on Jan. 5. After he pounded on the door of a nearby mobile
home, the sheriff's office was called.
</P>
<P>
   According to the deputies' report, Bailey gave conflicting names
and dates of birth, then ``assumed a fighting stance and began to
yell.'' A big man weighing more than 200 pounds, he was wrestled to
the ground and booked at 5:50 a.m. on charges of resisting arrest
and assaulting an officer. He was put in Cell Five by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Around 7 a.m., Mary Durell, taking a roll call, entered Bailey's
cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, this lady officer was backing out real fast,
holding her mouth,'' said James Cook, a 47-year-old who was in jail
at the time, in a sworn statement. ``Two or three officers grabbed
Mr. Bailey and pulled him out of the cell, and by that time two of
them were on the radio calling `Code Red.' ''
</P>
<P>
   According to Cook's statement, and testimony given by other
inmates in an adjacent cell, a number of officers rushed to the
scene, subdued Bailey and began pummeling him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officers was coming from everywhere but except the sky,'' said
Robin Ball, who said she witnessed the fracas on her way to the
jail infirmary. ``They was just kicking him with boots like army
boots that you're wearing for a war. He was already dead when they
took him around the corner and beat him some more. About 10 of them
was beating him, and some was kicking him every which way but
loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook said: ``They threw him flat on his face and handcuffed him
. . . One of the officers stood on Mr. Bailey's head and just
jumped up and down on his head and also on his back. . . . I
haven't never seen a man get beat like that in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has suggested a racial motive.
</P>
<P>
   When Bailey no longer struggled, Holland said, one of the
officers uttered an expletive and said: ``Call 911.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey was pronounced dead at 7:22 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Photos of Bailey's corpse show a body wrecked. His face and arms
were bruised, his foot gashed. A medical examiner's incisions left
wounds like bright red ceremonial flowers on his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man was tore up,'' said his daughter-in-law, Kristen
Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   After several weeks in the morgue, the body was finally turned
over to the family. ``I guess you could say he was put to rest,''
said his son. ``I know part of him's in the ground, but I didn't
like the way it had to be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8960 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TALK-SHOWS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     05-24 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALK-SHOWS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... an interview.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Letterman-like, O'Brien is willing to bite the hand that feeds
him. Visiting a new NBC merchandise store, he pronounced it a
``rip-off'' and tore up a T-shirt. After sampling food cooked by
Martha Stewart, he fell to the ground, gasping ``Constricting air
passage!'' as a nonplussed Stewart looked on.
</P>
<P>
   The bits on ``Late Night'' have an endearingly cheesy,
let's-put-on-a-show-in-the-garage quality. My favorite is when, on
a darkened stage, O'Brien and Richter hold flashlights under their
chins to create a ``spooky'' aura while they take hilarious
glimpses into the distant future, ``all the way to the year 2000.''
With any luck, O'Brien will be a fixture all the way to the year
2030. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DENNIS MILLER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The host's sardonic voice _ literally and figuratively _ defines
this show.``Dennis Miller Live'' builds toward ``The Rant.'' The
stage goes dark until only Miller is visible _ eyes glittering,
mouth twisted in a grin that tells you he is ready for takeoff _
and Miller mutters ``Now, I don't want to get off on a rant here .
. .'' And then he does. His verbal tempo accelerating with each
sentence, Miller careers across the contemporary landscape,
inveighing against the collapse of the culture on a dozen different
fronts.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, here is Miller in high rant last February on the
loss of privacy: ``You've got a better shot at hearing Charlie
Sheen deliver the keynote address at a Promise Keepers rally than
you do at maintaining anything that even vaguely resembles a
private life.'' With a healthy complement of four-letter words to
punch home his points, Miller takes full advantage of the greater
license afforded by HBO. Because his show is only a half-hour, the
interviews don't drag on, and Miller is unusually willing to
slam-dunk a guest. ``I don't want to hear the mushroom story,'' he
snapped at one fellow who was about to indulge in a drug tale.
</P>
<P>
   Miller takes viewer calls during his interviews, a seldom-seen
gambit that allows the host to showcase his ad-lib celerity. When
one young caller asked what college Miller wanted to go to when he
was 18, he shot back: ``I always thought that I'd go to the College
of Cardinals, 'cause I'd look the most limber.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with Miller there is always the smugness factor. Most
of the time, he seems mighty pleased with himself and his brand of
high-IQ comedy. But then again, most of the time on ``Dennis Miller
Live'' he has reason to be. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CRAIG KILBORN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not so Kilborn. He always had his detractors when he hosted
``The Daily Show'' _ chiefly they objected to his smirk _ and so
far (he took over for Tom Snyder on March 30) he seems bent on
proving them right.
</P>
<P>
   Long on self-congratulation, short on laughs, ``The Late Late
Show'' needs better writers, pronto, because many of Kilborn's
jokes fall with a thud. As an interviewer, Kilborn has lost the
sure-footedness that characterized his stint on ``The Daily Show,''
resulting in conversations that are insipid even by the lax
standards of late-night chat. Kilborn to Heather Locklear: ``You're
beautiful, and you've been a hit for so long on three shows.''
Locklear: ``OK.''
</P>
<P>
   With bits like ``Let's Enjoy My Hair'' and a segment where he
stands near a window and ``reflects on a job well done,'' Kilborn
strives for self-aware irony but often comes up empty. He is
capable of a certain spacy likability, and the ``Five Questions''
routine _ Kilborn queries guests along the lines of ``Which
20th-century philosopher had the best table manners?'' _ is a
winner. He should build on that, jettison the rest, and hope for a
Conan-style recovery from a disastrous debut. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHRIS ROCK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With his screechy voice and a willingness to say anything,
anything at all, Rock has the clearest point of view of the
late-night talk-show hosts.
</P>
<P>
   His comic style is to aim for, and often achieve, a state of
constant uproar. The more touchy the topic _ such as race relations
_ the more Rock likes it. Here is Rock's take on gang warfare in
New York: ``Officials say the increase is the result of the Bloods
trying to compete with the two most violent gangs in New York City,
the Latin Kings and the NYPD.''
</P>
<P>
   Guests, too, had better come prepared to defend themselves. Rock
needled Vivica A. Fox for her role in ``Booty Call'' (``When you
saw the script that says `Booty Call,' what was going through your
mind? `I got a booty'?'') and twitted Bryant Gumbel for enjoying
golf, observing ``Golf is very white.'' Shrewdly, Rock doesn't
spare himself from the general raillery, as when he described his
sex-starved teenage years: ``I was 30 pounds lighter, I had braces,
I had glasses. (Expletive,) I was birth control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chris Rock Show'' returns to HBO in September (he
alternates with Miller, whose show runs from January through
August). &QL; 
 &QL; 
JON STEWART &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since he succeeded Kilborn as anchor of ``The Daily Show'' in
January, Stewart hasn't exactly had to hunt for material, since the
show is structured as a mock newscast and current events provide no
shortage of comic fodder.
</P>
<P>
   The format _ news footage punctuated by wisecracks from the
anchor desk _ lends a topicality and immediacy to the show, and the
jokes are usually pretty good, though Stewart sometimes leans on
obvious targets: British cuisine, Boris Yeltsin's drinking habits.
The four-minute limit on interviews keeps the show moving along, as
does Stewart's deadpan way with an out-of-left-field question. He
caught Angelina Jolie by surprise by saying: ``You've done a lot of
love scenes, but oddly enough, none with Jon Stewart. Does that
hurt?''
</P>
<P>
   But the best part of ``The Daily Show'' (which airs weeknights
at 11 p.m. on Comedy Central) is the taped segments, an
increasingly common feature of late-night comedy shows. The ``Daily
Show'' correspondents have a real knack for finding oddballs: a man
who is running for president while dressed as a lobster; some
survivalists gathered at a Y2K convention (``God wouldn't permit me
to kill anybody,'' one woman said solemnly. ``But I've prayed about
it, and I think I could maim somebody''); and a guy who is selling
real estate on other planets.
</P>
<P>
   Back here on earth, as viewers of Conan, Chris, and Company can
attest, some of television's choicest real estate can be found on
late night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
