<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8966 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-MORTALITY-BOS &LR;      05-24 1808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-MORTALITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAYS'S SEARCH FOR REASONS TO BELIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the beginning of his one-man play about the Middle
East, ``Via Dolorosa,'' David Hare declares that he recently
realized, ``almost without noticing, that for some time my subject
as a playwright has been faith. My subject is belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Hare's mission may be to seek out true believers, but that
hardly makes him a missionary. He envies the Arabs and Israelis
their fervor while being too aware of its destructiveness to adapt
any such passions himself. Conversely, all around him in England he
sees the rigor mortis of a life without that passion. That's the
horrible irony of Western civilization at the millennium, as he
tells the audience:
</P>
<P>
   ``People always say in England we lead shallow lives. Our lives
must be shallow because we live in a country where nobody believes
in anything any more. My whole life I've been told: `Western
civilization? An old bitch gone in the teeth.' And so people say,
go to Israel. Because in Israel at least people are fighting. In
Israel, they're fighting for something they believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   That quest for something to believe in hovers over all the new
Anglo-Irish plays on Broadway, a quintet of plays that asks
questions about living the meaningful life in a world seemingly
without meaning. It isn't a new question, by any means. In fact,
the godfather of all such plays is winding down its run on
Broadway: the great British adaptation of Eugene O'Neill's ``The
Iceman Cometh,'' with Kevin Spacey.
</P>
<P>
   The protagonists of ``Via Dolorosa,'' ``Amy's View,''
``Closer,'' ``The Weir,'' and ``The Lonesome West'' are all, in
their way, trying to find something to believe. Rooting for them
can be as hard as rooting for the Red Sox, and ultimately just as
productive. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Via Dolorosa'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of all of them, Hare's one-man show is the most heartfelt and
intriguing, even if its subject matter makes it the least likely to
stand the test of time. The passions that fire the Middle East
conflict won't abate anytime soon, but the specifics will shift
enough to undermine the play. Still, one doesn't hold that against
``Fires in the Mirror,'' so there's no point in lamenting the
limitations of ``Via Dolorosa.'' Hare comes across, in fact, as a
combination of Anna Deavere Smith and Spalding Gray. Though he is a
less accomplished stage presence, he does combine Smith's ability
to bring polarized passions to life and Gray's irony of the
outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the riveting tour of the area's strange politics,
there is the haunting sense that we would kill for a taste of the
meaningfulness of life in the Middle East, even if we wouldn't
dream of actually giving up our comforts for such a dangerous
environment. Hare's sense of humor keeps most of the audience with
him, even those in New York whose sympathies are more likely to be
with Israel than are Hare's.
</P>
<P>
   At a Q &AMP; A in Israel, Hare laments how Tony Blair has come to
symbolize the lack of passion in British life: ``What does he
believe? Nobody knows. What will he do? Whatever is popular. Where
is he heading? He never tells us. At once, an Israeli actor
interrupts, `Oh please, please, send us your Tony Blair.' '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Amy's View'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The occasion of that interchange was a performance in Israel of
``Amy's View,'' a play that Hare wrote for Judi Dench and is almost
certain to give her a Tony to go with her Oscar this year.
Unfortunately, it is not a play remarkable for anything other than
Dench's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Dench plays Esme Allen, an actress whose faith and belief are in
the power of art, theater specifically, and if she's the flag
bearer of a dying cause, then she's prepared to go down fighting
against the pop-culture barbarians at the gate. Chief among those
barbarians is Dominic, the son-in-law who has wrested her daughter,
Amy, away from her.
</P>
<P>
   Had Hare invested Dominic with a fraction of the intelligence or
articulateness that he gives to both the Arabs and Israelis,
``Amy's View'' might have something to say about what makes Tom
Stoppard, for example, more worthy of attention than Quentin
Tarantino, a filmmaker in whose footsteps Dominic will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Hare not do that, he also fails to square the
circle between the political and personal. That is, whenever the
confrontation between high art and pop art starts to percolate,
Hare disconnects and switches to a rather tedious domestic drama.
There is a connection, but Hare doesn't make it worth the effort to
find it _ meaning that when Esme declares at the end, ``So we're
alone,'' it doesn't have the force it should.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, seeing great actors in the service of their
art is reward enough for many _ witness Julie Harris and Charles
Durning in ``The Gin Game.'' And there's no doubt that Dench is as
good as they come these days. But as Hare proved in ``Plenty'' with
Kate Nelligan and ``Skylight'' with Michael Gambon, there's nothing
like a great performance in the service of a fine play. For that
matter, even though Hare himself will never be confused with a
great actor, ``Via Dolorosa'' proves that the play is so much more
the thing than the player. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Closer'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the sense that today's Britain (and, by extension,
America?) is a spiritual wasteland stronger than in Patrick
Marber's second play, ``Closer.'' It is the best pure play of the
five, though whether Marber makes his case convincingly enough is
hotly debated by audiences when the curtain goes down.
</P>
<P>
   The implications of ``Closer'' are thoroughly depressing _ sex
makes the world go round, be it on the Internet or between the
sheets. The perfect life is the search for the perfect poke. All
four of the characters in ``Closer'' believe that to some extent,
even if the two women _ played by Anna Friel and Natasha Richardson
_ try to invest their lives with something more. Friel's young
waiflike character, in particular, will come to symbolize a quest
for a life in which matters like sacrifice and honor might still be
possible. In that sense she and Marber are reminiscent of Hare in
``Via Dolorosa.'' The quest for something to have faith in is not
limited to religion and ideology, though it isn't at all clear what
might take their places.
</P>
<P>
   Marber's gifts as a humorist and linguist are even sharper than
in his first play, ``Dealer's Choice,'' as is his ability to make
his work seem fresher than the latest hip movie. And it doesn't
hurt to have a great cast (better than the one I saw in London) at
your service. Ciaran Hinds (``Persuasion''), Friel, and Richardson
are terrific, though Rupert Graves seems a bit too placid as the
least sympathetic member of the foursome. I'm still not sure Marber
makes the case, but it's certainly an experience watching him try
to get there. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``The Weir'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moving across the sea, Conor McPherson is the third of the hot
Irish playwrights of the moment, along with Sebastian Barry (``The
Steward of Christendom'') and Martin McDonagh. The search for
meaning isn't as cosmic in ``The Weir'' as in the above sons of
``The Iceman,'' which makes its simpler sense of story more widely
enjoyable. There's a lightness of being represented, but it isn't
at all unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, ``The Weir'' owes more to ``The Iceman Cometh''
than any of the other plays. We're in an Irish bar where a group of
people will exchange stories that gradually strip away their
illusions. Set in a rural part of Ireland, ``The Weir'' starts out
with ghost stories that might be the Irish equivalent of ``Tales
From the Crypt'' or the old TV series of the paranormal ``One Step
Beyond.'' The atmosphere and the accents lend a pleasant creepiness
to the proceedings, but as the night wears on, the stories get more
real and, ironically, more haunting. That McPherson doesn't ask
bigger questions gives ``The Weir'' a pleasant enough taste to roll
around on one's lips, but after it's digested there's the
unpleasant question, ``Is that all there is?'' (The production of
another McPherson play, ``This Lime Tree Bower,'' opened this
week.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lonesome West'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McPherson takes it for granted that life, as depressing as it
sometimes might be, is worth living. If Hare concludes ``So we're
alone,'' McPherson sees hope in the comfort of community.
</P>
<P>
   To which Martin McDonagh would say, ``Give me a break.''
(Actually, he would insert a trademark adjective before ``break''
but we won't get into that.) If McDonagh had written ``The Weir,''
the denizens of the bar would have so frightened themselves with
ghost stories that there'd be as much blood as beer flowing by the
end of the play.
</P>
<P>
   McDonagh makes Samuel Beckett look like a cockeyed optimist. If
Beckett's credo is ``I can't go on, I must go on,'' McDonagh's is
``I can't go on, I might as well blow Da's brains out.'' And he's
more successful commercially than Barry and McPherson because,
among other things, his writing is hysterically funny.
</P>
<P>
   The key to black comedy is to leave the audience laughing so
hard that there's no room to complain. This doesn't work in all
cases, as could be attested to by a chorus of boos rising at the
end of the play. And though I was laughing as hard as anyone,
particularly in the first act, I wasn't altogether unsympathetic to
the boo birds.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for meaning by any of the above playwrights is a
fool's errand to McDonagh. It's symbolized in ``The Lonesome West''
by a priest whose kindhearted ineffectualness would be chilling if
McDonagh didn't have us in stitches. (This is the third part of
McDonagh's Leenane trilogy; the first, ``The Beauty Queen of
Leenane,'' will be coming to Boston next season. Jon Platt and
Pace/SFX have money invested in ``The Lonesome West,'' so that
could tour here as well. An unrelated McDonagh play, ``The Cripple
of Inishmaan,'' is currently at the ART in Cambridge.)
</P>
<P>
   Father Welsh is the parish priest in Leenane, where ``murder,
mayhem, and miserliness'' are the rule of the day. (So much for
McPherson's comfort of community.) At the center of the action are
two brothers whose abilities to get under each other's skin will
leave the priest's attempt to find faith, belief, or any kind of
order in a shambles.
</P>
<P>
   McDonagh can seem like the most scathing critic of contemporary
life we have. He can also seem like a Howard Stern for the
intelligentsia, something of a one-trick pony. I have a feeling
that the best is yet to come for both McDonagh _ ``The Cripple'' is
a better play than ``Lonesome West'' _ and Marber (and for Yasmina
Reza, whose ``Art'' is also in New York). But then I have a sense
of hope that none of the characters in ``The Lonesome West'' or
``Closer'' would be caught dead contemplating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
