<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT CAUSES HEADACHES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What causes headaches?
</P>
<P>
   T.S., E.P., Mattapan, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It depends on what kind of headache you have. Scientists
don't understand the causes of tension, the most common, or
cluster, the most excruciating. But they're starting to make some
big discoveries about the causes of migraine.
</P>
<P>
   In all three kinds of headaches, we do know what hurts. Dr.
Michael Moskowitz, Professor of Neurology at Harvard, says it's the
pain-sensing nerves woven through the blood vessels in your head,
and through the meninges, the three-layered sac that contains your
brain. Brain cells themselves have no pain sensors.
</P>
<P>
   The most common kind of headache is the tension headache.
According the Dr. Michael Cutrer, Director of the Partner's
Headache Center at Brigham and Women's and Mass General Hospitals,
as many as eight people in ten will suffer tension headache at one
time or another. It's a moderate intensity bilateral (both sides)
squeezing that lasts from minutes to weeks. There's no throbbing to
a tension headache, and no nausea or aura, the visual perception
that accompanies migraines. This is the kind of headache that
responds to over-the-counter medication.
</P>
<P>
   Least common are the cluster headaches. Men get them six times
as often as women. They cause extreme pain in and around one eye,
like a boring or searing through the eye for 15 minutes to three
hours. They are usually accompanied by red eye or tearing or
nostril dripping or sweating on the forehead, all on the same side
as the pain. They come in clusters of one or more per day over a
period of weeks or months, then disappear for months or years, then
recur. They're called ``the suicide headache'' because they're so
ferocious.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say there are three great pains in life,'' Dr. Cutrer
says. ``Childbirth, kidney stones, and cluster headaches.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-most common headache is migraine. Between 12 and 15
percent of the population suffers migraine headaches. Women have
migraines three times more than men. Two thirds of women migraine
sufferers experience them around menstruation.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Cutrer says migraine is a unilateral (one sided) throbbing
headache with moderate or severe pain that can last from a couple
hours to three days. It is usually accompanied by nausea, vomiting,
and/or abnormal sensitivity to light or smell. Known triggers, in
addition to menstruation, include certain foods (aged cheese,
chocolate, caffeine, citrus fruits), exercise, and changes in
weather or season.
</P>
<P>
   Migraine usually follows some kind of anticipatory symptoms. 15
percent of migraine sufferers report a visual aura 20 to 40 minutes
before the pain starts, a shimmering sparkling image or a small
blind spot that spreads slowly to obscure half the field of vision
of each eye. Other anticipatory sensations include a tingling in
the hand and lower arm that jumps to the face, mouth and tongue,
motor weakness in the muscles on one side of the body, a craving
for certain foods, mood change, even the inability to recall words.
</P>
<P>
   The visual aura is providing neurologists with their first big
clues about the root causes of migraines, and possibly all
headaches. Dr. Margarita Sanchez and Dr. Nouchine Hadjikha of Mass
General Hospital have studied patients whose migraines have
specific triggers. They put them in a functional magnetic resonance
imaging (fMRI) machine, which can ``see'' blood flow in the brain
and tell which cells are active. It's literally like watching the
living brain at work. Then, with the patient's patience and
permission, they trigger a migraine.
</P>
<P>
   The fMRI reveals brain activity that's never been seen before,
an unusually slow spreading of activity across the parts of the
brain known to be the centers for vision, at the same speed the
patients say their visual aura spreads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know of nothing in the human brain that fires slowly this
way,'' Dr. Moskowitz says. ``The brain usually sends signals at
meters per second. This is millimeters per minute.''
</P>
<P>
   The brain activity causes the release of chemicals including
hydrogen ions, potassium, serotonin, histamines, and arichidonic
acid. Released in measured ways they don't create pain. But when
something triggers the unusually slow brain activity that's been
recorded in migraine patients, the release of these chemicals
becomes unmeasured, and they build up, Says Dr. Moskowitz.
</P>
<P>
   They have to be cleaned out of the system. That's what the blood
vessels do. When this particular mix or soup of chemicals builds
up, it's enough to stimulate the pain-sensing nerves in the blood
vessels and the meninges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout the body the pain system is a natural warning
system. When it goes off it's telling us that something's wrong,''
Moskowitz explains.
</P>
<P>
   It's no different in the head. Dr. Moskowitz thinks migraines,
and possibly other headaches, may be our body's way of warning us
that we're doing something harmful to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the very early stages of defining these events and
trying to classify them,'' Dr. Moskowitz says. ``We've only had
tools like fMRI for a little while. But I'm confident we'll know
what causes migraine headaches, and maybe the other types, within
the next ten years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8972 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEMOIR-PERSEUS-BOS &LR;      05-24 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMOIR-PERSEUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMOIR'S SPY CHARGES SPUR DEBATE AMONG SCIENTISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ It was supposed to be a kind of detective
story, the clever unmasking of the identity of a former Manhattan
Project scientist who may have passed atomic secrets to the Soviets
during World War II. Instead, it has turned into an acrimonious
battle to preserve the reputation of one of the nation's most
revered scientists, MIT's Philip Morrison, after charges of
espionage were leveled against him by a respected public-interest
activist and author.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the story especially odd and poignant is that the two
men were longtime friends. They are unlikely to be again.
</P>
<P>
   The story exploded with the publication last month of a memoir
by Jeremy Stone, son of the crusading independent reporter I.F.
Stone and, for the last 30 years, president of the Federation of
American Scientists. In the book's next-to-last chapter, he details
a series of conversations and visits with a scientist he calls
Scientist X, who he comes to believe was a Soviet spy, code-named
Perseus.
</P>
<P>
   But Scientist X was easily identified as the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology's Morrison, who then sent Stone a letter
detailing clear-cut discrepancies that show he could not have been
Perseus. Stone responded with a terse letter acknowledging the
discrepancies, and saying that ``I can only accept your denial that
you are Perseus.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Stone's failure to apologize for his allegations or to
change the book, some members of the federation are debating
whether stronger remedies may be appropriate. Documents summarizing
the tale were sent to members of the federation's governing board
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just outraged'' by the unsubstantiated charges in
Stone's book ``Every Man Should Try,'' said Priscilla McMillan, a
professor at Harvard University's Russian Research Center and
secretary of the federation. Despite Stone's attempts to conceal
Morrison's identity, she said, ``anybody who knew anything about
the history of the Manhattan Project would know who it was.''
</P>
<P>
   While both men are held in high regard, several scientists and
historians contacted by the Globe who know them both expressed
dismay at Stone's actions and unreserved support for Morrison. ``I
think Phil is unscathed by this,'' said Frank von Hippel, chairman
of the federation's nonprofit foundation.
</P>
<P>
   As for Stone, von Hippel said, ``some people would like him to
apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   It began with the 1991 publication of a series of articles by
Colonel Vladimir Chikov, and then a 1994 book by Pavel Sudoplatov,
both former KGB officials who mentioned Perseus as having been one
of a half-dozen scientists who they claim provided secret
information about the development of the atomic bomb to Soviet
agents during the war.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there were obvious discrepancies between Morrison and
the Perseus described by Chikov, making it clear that Morrison
could not have been that spy _ if, indeed, such a person ever
existed.
</P>
<P>
   But if Perseus was real, the articles make it clear that
Morrison was not the one. They refer to Perseus having been
recruited by the KGB during a visit to his ill parents in New York,
whereas Morrison's parents lived in Philadelphia at the time. And
they say that Perseus was fighting with the International Brigades
in Spain, whereas Morrison, as he pointed out in his letter to
Stone, ``was never plausible infantry material.'' Morrison,
stricken with polio as a child, always walked with a severe limp
and a cane.
</P>
<P>
   If the discrepancies were so clear, what led Stone to make his
identification in the first place? It all appears to have been
based on a turn of phrase and on interpretations of body language.
</P>
<P>
   The first clue, Stone says in his book, was a few sentences
attributed to Perseus in the Chikov article, describing his
motivations for providing atomic information to Russia. Unlike more
recent spy cases, there was no financial motive here; Perseus
apparently believed that for the United States alone to have the
bomb would be a dangerous and unstable situation, and that it was
important for the Soviet Union to join the nuclear club as quickly
as possible to restore a balance of power. Stone thought the
sentiments and one particular phrase sounded like the voice of his
friend Morrison _ even though, as he acknowledged, the quote had
been translated from English to Russian and back again and then
edited.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison not only denies the identification, he strongly eschews
the sentiments ascribed to the wartime Perseus. ``No, I didn't feel
that way,'' he said in an interview Friday. ``I think it's simply
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting this hunch that Perseus might be Morrison, Stone
recounts that in 1994, he visited Morrison and his wife twice to
try to sound them out. But, as he makes clear in the book, he never
actually stated what was on his mind, instead talking in broad
terms about Perseus and about trying to get that person to tell his
story.
</P>
<P>
   In those meetings, Stone says Morrison became so fearful that
his knees shook, and that Phylis Morrison's reactions seemed to
confirm his suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response to written questions from the Globe, Stone
summarized his reasons for going ahead: ``The chapter was written
only because, in conjunction with everything else . . . during a
discussion of Perseus between myself and the Morrisons, Phylis
seemed to have actually identified Phil as Perseus by throwing a
fit, pointing at him, and urging me to reach a `tacit agreement'
with him while he sat there silently. I felt entrapped by this.''
</P>
<P>
   But Morrison says that in pointing to him during that
conversation, Phylis was merely recognizing and reacting to the
still-unstated accusation by Stone against Morrison. And the
recalled quote is simply wrong, he says. The shaking knees,
Morrison said, were the result of aftereffects of his childhood
polio.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Morrison has been a long-term member of the
federation that Stone heads, and was instrumental not only in
hiring him, but in heading off an attempt to oust Stone from that
position years ago _ all of which Stone acknowledges.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in his written responses, Stone says that ``I have
always loved and admired Philip Morrison . . .'' His goal, he says,
is to persuade those people who participated in wartime espionage
to come forward and share their stories, in the interests of
history and to allow Americans to judge their motives for
themselves. And he acknowledges that ``it is entirely possible that
Perseus does not exist at all,'' and that ``obviously, Phil may
well be innocent of any violation of law whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether such statements will be enough to stave
off any attempt by the federation's board to demand further
response. Robert Park, a physicist and director of the American
Physical Society, although not a federation member, said he has
spoken with some members and that ``if there has not been already,
I would be astonished if there were not calls for his
resignation.'' In the meantime, he said, some members have already
talked about resigning in protest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
