<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS SEND THE WRONG MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Offering people advice on how to raise their kids
is touchy. They tend to get annoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, what do you know about it?'' they demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, what business of it is yours?''
</P>
<P>
   So up front let me just say this: I raised two kids. I wasn't
perfect at it. The kids weren't perfect, either, believe me. They
turned out pretty well, though. In the context of the times in
which we live, guess what: That makes me an expert.
</P>
<P>
   Also, like it or not, how your kids behave has an impact on
other people _ on the community in which you live. If parents want
to go off on some mountaintop somewhere, live like hermits and
raise their kids to live on nuts and berries and shun the rest of
humanity, that's one thing. But if they're going to send those kids
off into the world to inflict themselves on other people, then
those parents have an obligation not only to their kids but to the
world they share with others.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, permit me to offer my humble opinion on the
conduct of two sets of parents _ and on the messages they're
sending both their own kids and the kids of other people:
</P>
<P>
   In the first case, a 12-year-old kid in the comfortable Albany
suburb of Guilderland was charged last May with showing up at
school with an M-16 ammunition clip. According to the cops, he'd
brought in the clip, which he'd stolen along with some live
ammunition rounds from a National Guard firing range, to convince
the other kids in the school that he was serious when he threatened
to kill some teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the school went nuts. The kid was suspended for the
rest of the year. He ended up in juvenile court charged with a
misdemeanor. The adjudication of that case is secret. That's
routine in juvenile court. Now the family is suing the school
system and the cops for $850,000. Yeah, The family's lawyer admits
that the kid stole the M-16 clip and the ammunition. But he alleges
that the kid never threatened anybody and that the cops and the
school slandered him.
</P>
<P>
   In the second case, a 19-year-old senior at
Ravena-Coeymans-Selkirk High School in the southern Albany suburbs
went to class the other day with his hair fashioned into 18-inch
spikes, dyed bright red. The school decided that was disruptive and
sent him home. The family told me that the school has no right to
tell their kid how to wear his hair and that he's going back with
the same fetching tonsorial affectation.
</P>
<P>
   So what are we left with here? We seem to be left with two sets
of parents pulling out all the stops to communicate to their kids _
and to everybody else's, by the way _ that they can do any loony
thing they please, and that their parents will wage total war
against any non-family authority figure who finds their conduct
objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   Now nobody understands more vividly than I do just how tough it
is to raise kids. Few people realize, when they take on the job,
how huge a chore it'll be to get their progeny properly launched
into the world, socialized and civilized to function in it
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   But you either raise kids who understand that the larger society
has a reasonable right to object to stunts like ammunition clips in
school, and that there are rational rules that must be followed. Or
you raise kids who get the message that anybody who disapproves of
anything they might do can just go to hell, or, if they annoy you
sufficiently, be sent there by force.
</P>
<P>
   Given recent events, which message seems louder?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
