<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVING WHILE WHITE: THE WAY TO GET AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lately we've been reading about police profiling
and DWB, or Driving While Black. If you fit the profile of being
African-American, or Latino, the cops pull you over on any pretext,
or none at all _ especially if you're driving in a white
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   I want to talk about something that hasn't come up before: DWW,
or Driving While White.
</P>
<P>
   What happens if you're DWW? Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why white people don't know about it.
</P>
<P>
   As long as I stick close to traffic laws, I drive all over the
place in my bland Honda and never get stopped by the cops. I don't
even consider the possibility. Talk about different black and white
worlds. One world involves a black-and-white in the rearview
mirror, the other doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with us white people _ make that heterosexual,
middle-class white males _ is that we don't notice all the things
that aren't happening to us.
</P>
<P>
   We hardly notice that we're not excluded from corporate glass
offices, newspaper front pages or network sitcoms. We expect to be
excluded from jail and unemployment lines.
</P>
<P>
   This came to me at a newspaper meeting on diversity last week. I
realized it's hard to get people, especially white males, to talk
about race or gender politics in mixed company.
</P>
<P>
   Sex and money are much easier topics. We have huge national
conversations on sex and money, while Clinton's national
conversation on race never got past the first talking point.
</P>
<P>
   Let me tell you, I have little white guilt. I'll tell a black
person where to get off, and I do about twice a week to San
Francisco Mayor Willie Brown. Not because he's black, but because
he's the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   I have suffered enough in life to know you should enjoy your
advantages. But know those advantages, and don't deny them.
</P>
<P>
   Many middle-class white men think they have overcome the same
kind of obstacles women and blacks have to overcome. Blacks and
women don't exactly see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   A long time ago, Eddie Murphy did a great ``White Like Me''
segment on ``Saturday Night Live.'' At one point, Murphy, in
whiteface, went to a bank and the teller whispered, ``How much
money do you want?''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that easy, but in my time, 1,000 white men graduating
from Harvard faced exactly that question at job interviews. And I,
like an idiot, said, ``None, thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the noise about minority hiring, white privilege and
class privilege still exist.
</P>
<P>
   I first learned about Driving While White back in the late '60s,
although in those hippie times I thought it was DWN, Driving While
Neat.
</P>
<P>
   I had a friend who believed if he kept his hair short, dressed
well and drove a boring car, he could do anything. He also was
white. One night in rural Connecticut a cop pulled us over for a
minor infraction. The cop looked us over and sent us on our way.
</P>
<P>
   A mile down the road, my friend flipped open the glove
compartment. There was a bag of marijuana and a gun he had borrowed
from the Colt factory, where he worked.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson one: Never trust a friend not to be an idiot and get you
sent to prison as an armed drug smuggler.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson two: If you're an idiot, be white and middle-class and
you might get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Whites can't understand what it's like to be black in America _
that's the cliche and the truth. But white people also have to work
hard to understand what it's like to be white in America. We take
our membership in that big club for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the insight comes in a rush, like when a friend went
to the Department of Motor Vehicles and found he was the only white
man in line wearing a tie. The clerk moved him to the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was I supposed to do, say, `No, treat me badly, too?'''
my friend said.
</P>
<P>
   Usually we white, middle-class males don't see what we have _
and resent what little we think we're losing. We have to be put at
a huge advantage or disadvantage before our eyes open.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, sometimes a white male can be at a disadvantage. We see the
world from above. That's not a view that provides perspective.
</P>
<P>
   You have to get down to earth, or the road. Take a few drives
through rich, white neighborhoods and see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing happens, good for you. Think about it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
