<HEADLINE>
WRITERS DEBATE THE ROLE OF BOOKS IN THE WEB ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDYTH RIGLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writers Kurt Anderson (``Turn of the Century'') and Jon Katz
(``Running to the Mountain'') recently held a literary debate on
line. The choice of venues was appropriate, given that the debate
focused on the future of the ``traditional'' novel as books
proliferate on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't experienced this phenomenon firsthand, check out
Web locations sites www.1stbooks.com, www.sansip.com and
www.upublish.com, where ``virtual books'' appear and may be
downloaded from the Internet to any computer. These sites have been
a boon to authors who, for whatever reason, eschew the traditional
road to publication in favor of (almost) instant gratification and
the opportunity to reach millions of readers.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and Katz addressed some tough questions springing from
this growing trend: Does the book have a future in cyberspace? And
_ certainly an even larger question _ does the text-based novel
have a future at all?
</P>
<P>
   These guys weren't a couple of Luddites bemoaning what
technology has done to the artiste; Andersen, co-founder and editor
of the cutting-edge Spy magazine, says he abandoned his typewriter
nearly two decades ago for the computer, he e-mails a couple of
dozen times a day and he couldn't have completed the research for
his new novel without the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Katz, a contributing editor for Rolling Stone, writes on the Web
for Slashdot.org and is a confirmed Internet user.
</P>
<P>
   The two made a lot of good points. Andersen stressed that,
counter to popular opinion, the novel isn't dead; and if it's
wounded, ``the microchip isn't responsible.'' But he added that, at
least so far, what he's seen on the Internet _ with the exception
of on-line bookselling _ won't have any lasting impact on our
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is an important on-line literary (or cinematic or
musical) work?'' Andersen asks. ``Where's a hypertext masterpiece?
When does the renaissance begin. ... If I find it almost impossible
to be moved watching television, how on earth are streaming video
images on a monitor screen ever going to shake or enlighten or
entertain me in a deep, satisfying way?''
</P>
<P>
   Katz countered that members of the ``Holy Circle'' of publishing
houses, trendy magazines and other cultural insiders are merely
feeling threatened by the accessibility of the Net, where anyone
with a message can find an audience, where you don't need an agent
or a track record to get published. He sees the Internet as a
``barrier buster.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the established avenues through which we receive our
culture, Katz added, the Internet is an unknown. The institutions
are hidebound and uninspiring; the Internet is vibrant and
unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   There's more food for thought within the debate _ which you can
find at www.randomhouse.com/atrandom/kurtandersen/ _ but perhaps
most intriguing is Katz's final salvo: ``Publishing will almost
certainly survive the Internet, but a fairer question might be
whether it really deserves to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
