<HEADLINE>
A MUST-HAVE CATALOG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We like simple, elemental furniture and thus were delighted with
a table in peopleplacesthings, one of several catalogs put out by
the J. Jill company. The table, available in three styles, is a
solid block of plantation-grown Costa Rican cypress. It's primitive
and purposeful _ proudly a place to set stuff. Weighing 80 pounds
and standing 17 to 21 inches high, the table comes in barrel,
concave or classic pedestal shapes. Even in you're not up to paying
$210 for the table, be sure to call to receive a copy of
peopleplacesthings, which is one of the classiest catalogs we've
seen. It's a perfected Pottery Barn, with cool items like metal
candleholders with small stones slipped in their hollow bases and a
remarkable, $2,300 hammered-tin armoire. Call 800-295-4378.
</P>
<P>
   PANDA TOASTER: Just what everyone needs: An $80 toaster that
bakes the face of a panda onto a piece of toast. Now, we understand
that people can feel strongly about their toasters _ we know
someone who likes to show off his new toaster at parties, and
Williams-Sonoma is selling a ton of those $400 retro-chrome
toasters _ but really, now. A panda on every slice of toast? Surely
a zeal for the cute critters from China has its limits. We'd
understand better if the toaster came with three or four
interchangeable elements that would allow you to switch to, say,
lizards, porcupines and koalas, depending on mood. Eighty bucks
seems like an awful lot to spend on a two-slice box of whimsy,
although whoever buys it for a $10 at a garage sale in 20 years
will be delighted. We found the toaster among the oddities in a
catalog called Lifestyle Fascination. Call 800-669-0987.
</P>
<P>
   OLD TUNES: As aurally impressive as they are, compact discs lack
the nostalgic appeal of records, especially the heavy old 78-rpm
platters. And there's no better way to play them than on a
gramophone. Lifestyle Fantasies catalog found an stash of old
gramophones, dating from the 1920s to the '50s, and had them
completely reconditioned, with some parts restored and others
recast. The brass horn is new, but most of the mechanicals and
casework are original, meaning no two are exactly alike. Each
features a side crank, chrome arm and felt-covered turntable and
comes with both a 78 record and a supply of needles. Curiously, the
catalog is a bit evasive about the origin of the gramophones,
saying only that they're from ``the British Colonies.'' Order the
$400 gramophone by calling 800-669-0987.
</P>
</TEXT>
