<HEADLINE>
ALVIN ROCKWELL, PROMINENT LAWYER, DIES AT 90 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Alvin John Rockwell, a prominent San Francisco
lawyer who played a key role in shaping West Germany's democratic
government after World War II, died May 19 at Mount Zion Hospital
of coronary artery disease. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rockwell, a partner in the firm of Brobeck, Phleger and
Harrison, held a lifelong interest in international affairs. His
career led him from making radio addresses to the postwar German
public to honoring Soviet Premier Nikita Khrushchev during his
controversial visit to America in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Mr. Rockwell was president of the World Affairs
Council of Northern California. Khrushchev had just been denied his
request to visit Los Angeles and Disneyland when he was honored by
the council in a San Francisco dinner. Mr. Rockwell's reasoned
speech at that event was credited with helping to defuse the
tension that had built up around Khrushchev's U.S. tour.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rockwell's introduction to foreign affairs came in 1945,
when he moved to Berlin to serve as legal adviser to the commander
of the American forces occupying a portion western Germany.
</P>
<P>
   His assignment was to rebuild the German legal system, employing
aspects of German tradition and Western democratic principles.
</P>
<P>
   On several occasions he spoke directly to the people of Germany,
in public appearances and on the radio. His work is credited with
helping to shape what is now that nation's legal structure.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Kalamazoo, Mich., in 1908, Mr. Rockwell attended Albion
College in Michigan and DePauw University in Greencastle, Ind.,
where he served as student body president and a member of Sigma Nu
fraternity. He graduated Phi Beta Kappa in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   After a postgraduate year at the London School of Economics, Mr.
Rockwell attended Harvard Law School. He graduated in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rockwell practiced law in Boston for a brief time, then
moved to Washington to serve in the solicitor general's office as
special assistant to the U.S. attorney general and as attorney for
the National Labor Relations Board. He argued many cases for the
government in defense of labor activity, and appeared several times
before the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   After service in Germany, Mr. Rockwell came to San Francisco to
join Brobeck, Phleger and Harrison. His clients included United Air
Lines, the Matson Navigation Co. and the Homestake Mining Co. He
also served on Homestake's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   His wife of 50 years, Anna Hayward Rockwell, died in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rockwell is survived by a sister, Gladys Osborne of Delray
Beach, Fla.; a son, John Rockwell, and a granddaughter, Sasha
Rockwell, both of New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
