<HEADER>
A8986 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-NONCOMPETE-BOS &LR;      05-24 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NONCOMPETE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVIDERS, PATIENTS LAMENT CONTRACT RESTRICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a Boston-area mental health counselor was forced late last
year to stop seeing nursing home patients she'd worked with for
five years because of a contract restriction, a woman in her 80s
who had come to depend on her was devastated.
</P>
<P>
   ``She turned her back to me and she wouldn't speak to me. There
were tears coming down her face,'' said the counselor, who did not
want to be named for confidentiality reasons. The patient, who was
bedridden and had no family, refused to eat and died a few months
later, in February.
</P>
<P>
   The contract restriction, known as a non-compete clause, was
required by the private mental health agency that initially
employed the counselor. When she switched agencies, she was forced
to stop seeing the elderly patient and others in that nursing home
_ even though officials there wanted to retain her services through
her new employer.
</P>
<P>
   Such restrictive covenants strike at the very heart of the
patient-provider relationship and the freedom of patients to follow
a trusted health care provider, say officials from organizations
representing health care professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Non-compete clauses were initially created by businesses to
protect trade secrets or a customer base. But they are increasingly
being used across the country by health care firms in an ever-more
competitive and profit-minded industry.
</P>
<P>
   If a car maker uses a non-compete clause to restrict employees,
``the cars don't suffer, nor do the customers who purchase the
cars,'' said Russ Newman, the executive director for professional
practice with the American Psychological Associaton.
</P>
<P>
   But in health care, he said, ``when you begin to prioritize
business interests over health care interests, who suffers is the
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   The clauses typically stipulate that health care employees agree
not to take patients with them if they move to a different
employer, for a period of a year or two, even if the patients want
to maintain the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   But nowhere, perhaps, is the patient-provider relationship more
important than between an elderly nursing home resident and her
mental health provider, say health care professionals.
</P>
<P>
   While some nursing homes have their own mental health staff or
allow private practitioners to come in and bill for their services,
many Massachusetts facilities contract with outside private
agencies to provide mental health services. These agencies, like
the one the Boston-area mental health counselor worked for, are
increasingly requiring non-compete clauses.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest maneuver in the field, for-profit Arbour
SeniorCare bought the competing MHM/Bay Colony agency in December.
The acquisition made it the largest such mental health agency in
New England, providing services to about 300 nursing homes. As part
of the deal, about 75 employees of MHM/Bay Colony were asked to
sign non-compete clauses with Arbour as a condition of continued
employment.
</P>
<P>
   But one Boston-area social worker refused to sign the
non-compete clause, which was a condition of continued employment.
She had just two days around Christmas to end relationships with 35
elderly and disabled patients at one long-term care facility, and
about a month to break off with another 65 patients at three
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these patients don't have families, or have families
who abandoned them long ago. It was really a horrible time of year
for this to have occurred,'' said the social worker, who also did
not want to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Arbour SeniorCare has sued psychologist Peter Janney for trying
to rescind a non-compete clause a few days after he signed it, but
the agency unsuccessfully tried to get a court injunction against
him, according to court documents. The firm also alleged Janney
tried to talk nursing homes he worked at out of signing contracts
with Arbour.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing home officials submitted documents in support of Janney,
saying they had no intention of signing with Arbour anyway,
according to court files. Janney has filed countercharges against
Arbour. The case is pending in Plymouth (Mass.) Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the state attorney general has been asked to
investigate possible violations of anti-trust laws and patients'
rights by Arbour, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Hoch, chief executive officer of Arbour SeniorCare and a
certified clinical nurse specialist by training, declined to
comment on legal matters, but said that the agency was willing to
allow mental health workers to stay as long as needed to end
patient relationships gradually.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, owned by Universal Health Services in Pennsylvania,
is part of a Massachusetts system that includes Arbour Hospital, a
psychiatric facility in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Ending relationships abruptly ``was not our policy and was not
our intent,'' said Hoch, who was surprised to hear about the
termination of 35 patients in two days at one facility. ``We gave
everyone the choice of how they wanted to make the transition or
termination with their patients. This is very upsetting.''
</P>
<P>
   She defended the agency's use of non-compete clauses to protect
its patient base and business interests, while at the same time
saying that ``patient care is paramount. There is no question about
that.'' Hoch added, ``I like to think we balance it very well.''
</P>
<P>
   While such clauses have been a way of doing business in many
fields, Massachusetts last year prohibited TV and radio stations
from requiring non-compete clauses of employees, whether they be
news anchors, disc jockeys or technicians.
</P>
<P>
   And the state is one of the few, if not the only one, to
prohibit employers from requiring such clauses of physicians and
nurses, under laws that were put on the books more than 15 years
ago to protect patient choice, according to attorneys from the
Massachusetts Medical Society and the Boston law firm Stoneman,
Chandler &AMP; Miller, which represents health care employers.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no similar protection for psychologists, mental
health counselors and social workers, who have arguably one of the
most trusted relationships with patients.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Harris, psychologist and legal counsel for the
Massachusetts Psychological Association, who was not speaking on
behalf of the association, said he favors a state law extending the
protection to mental health workers, but there is currently no such
bill pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of agreements are not in the public interest,''
said Harris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
