<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE CENTER OF THE SCHOOL   FINANCE DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CONCORD, N.H. -- &UR;  &LR; Give New Hampshire a little time, and you
start thinking about Israel or Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The factions, feuding, fulminations, and fighting over public
school finances have been going on so long that the prospect of a
settlement can seem more jarring to the politicians than more of
the debilitating same.
</P>
<P>
   In an atmosphere dominated by the poles of opinion the wishes of
ordinary people clearly reflected in the polls of opinion are easy
to forget. From each pole comes the same message: wrecking a
settlement is justified because, after all, we're right.
</P>
<P>
   One month, a more or less bipartisan majority of the Legislature
is cobbled together to enact a hodge-podge of revenue measures
built around a statewide property tax in response to a state
supreme court ruling almost two years ago that the public school
financing system is illegal. Now the Legislature is now mired in
its budget process that has to produce the final chunk of money for
the new system so that it can pass constitutional muster.
</P>
<P>
   You can smell what's ahead _ delay, inaction, stalemate,
building toward legislature-manufactured crisis as the next fiscal
year looms in July. Then come continuing resolutions, fiscal chaos,
injury to the ordinary operation of government, recourse to the
courts, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The simple solution _ just finish the stupid job _ has yet to
occur to the feuding factions. Each is convinced that its way,
backed by a constituency that confuses decibel level with support,
must be the only way.
</P>
<P>
   With an $825 million package already in hand, the Legislature
first must enact an agreed-upon (in principle) 25-cent increase in
the cigarette tax. Then it must fill a fiscal hole left between the
package enacted this spring and what is required to complete the
reform (you get an argument over how large it is).
</P>
<P>
   The current inaction stems from an ideologically driven effort
in the Republican-led House to find the money exclusively with deep
cuts in the rest of state government; in the newly Democratic
Senate, the root of the problem is the still-driving dream of the
state's progressives to have a state income tax.
</P>
<P>
   In the eye of the impending storm sits the state's remarkable
governor, Jeanne Shaheen _ fiscally conservative, otherwise mostly
progressive but also committed to the Third Way of thinking that
you find in such places as California or Britain. She also has been
elected in two landslides on a vow not to approve a state income or
sales tax, which she has had the temerity to stick to as she drove
the process of responding to the court decision.
</P>
<P>
   In conversation in her office, she is content to lay back and
allow the Legislature to confront its duty to go the last mile
responsibly, quietly confident that in the end it will do so if the
alternative is more chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she is also freshly armed with perspective from
attending the Education Commission of the States in Kentucky, one
of many states that has successfully gone through a court-ordered
reform of public school financing.
</P>
<P>
   Every time Shaheen has opened her mouth during this crisis, she
has reached the solid majority of citizens who both like her and
approve of her approach.
</P>
<P>
   One of the facts often forgotten in the midst of the yelling
matches is that New Hampshire doesn't have bad public schools; in
fact, it has pretty good public schools. And, as conservatives have
taught, education excellence is not a function of some magical,
per-pupil spending number.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the state's package _ if the last holes are filled _
comes in above some other states' responses in similar situations
that had no difficulty passing court review of what is termed
``adequacy.'' New Hampshire, under Shaheen, is also moving well
within the mainstream of the national movement to use performance
and accountability standards to spur further reform.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, a court challenge to New Hampshire's looming
solution is inevitable. It's one thing if it comes only from the
minority of so-called property-rich towns where taxes would rise
under a statewide system.
</P>
<P>
   But it's something else if it comes as well from the towns that
brought the state lawsuit in the first place and decide that going
for even more money is better than helping make the reform work.
</P>
<P>
   Legal or legislative, and don't forget the added poison from a
name-calling commentariat up here, the misimpression is of total
polarization.
</P>
<P>
   But that misses the dynamism of the center. It is not
difference-splitting, but problem-solving: more resources for most
schools in need against a background of substantial property tax
reform.
</P>
<P>
   The right and left poles, opposing a state solution on the one
hand and advocating an income tax on the other, share the need to
block a legislative solution by any means to advance their cause.
By definition that makes the schools a pretext.
</P>
<P>
   But for the governor, the schools are the cause. This is one
case where the polls are more reliable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
