<HEADER>
A8998 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOURIST-RESTAURANTS-L     05-24 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURIST-RESTAURANTS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANK FRED HARVEY FOR TOURIST RESTAURANTS AND SOUVENIR SHOPS
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of tourists on train buying souvenirs
 By ANDREA IBANEZ 
 c.1999 Andrea Ibanez 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone has had the experience. Sitting in a car, humming along
a smooth highway on a long trip. Bored beyond conversation, looking
out the window at the same landscape hour after hour. The only
thought is, ''When are we going to stop and eat?''
</P>
<P>
   We haven't much choice in where we eat anymore with chain
restaurants to be found even in the smallest towns in America. It
is a sad comment on the state of our available options that there
are books published about the location of ``real'' road food.
</P>
<P>
   But if we bemoan the lack of choice today, imagine for a moment
the state of travel out west about a hundred years ago where the
alternatives were few and miserable. The lucky traveler of that day
with a railway ticket faced hours of monotony staring out at the
bleak landscape. The journey was broken by two things at its end _
the long awaited meal and perhaps the sight of Native Americans
selling trinkets at the station.
</P>
<P>
   These two distractions from the tedious trip were to provide
fame and fortune to Fred Harvey, the father of the modern chain
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The Fred Harvey restaurants were part of a brilliant marketing
plan. The target: the typical traveler on the Atchison, Topeka and
Santa Fe Railroad who sat for hours or days on horsehair-stuffed
leather banquettes, dreaming of a decent meal when the jostling of
the train stopped.
</P>
<P>
   All too often, however, that meal was a disaster. When the train
stopped for fuel and water, passengers scrambled into the local
eatery, ordered food and hoped it arrived quickly enough to be
gobbled down before the train pulled out of the station. The usual
fare _ a stringy piece of meat, some eggs and a cup of coffee _ was
served by proprietors ill-equipped to handle the sudden and
overwhelming throngs of passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Harvey hit upon the idea of a restaurant chain as a result
of his own miserable experience riding the rails. Born in England
in 1835, Harvey emigrated to the United States at the age of 15 and
worked his way up in the restaurant business until a partner
absconded with the profits.
</P>
<P>
   Thrust by necessity into a new career as a freight and cattle
agent, Harvey looked out onto the western horizon and saw his
future. He believed that a fine eating establishment with
reasonable prices would be a success.
</P>
<P>
   How right he was.
</P>
<P>
   In 1876, he opened the first Harvey House in Topeka, Kan. The
Santa Fe Railroad supplied coal, ice and water, transportation for
furnishings, food, supplies and personnel all without charge to
Harvey in exchange for a reliable meal. And this Harvey delivered.
His standard breakfast consisted of cereal or fruit, steak and
eggs, hash browns, six hotcakes, apple pie and coffee. All for 50
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey's second great idea was to recruit women to serve the
food. Waitresses added another layer of refinement to his
operations and diminished lingering fears of travel in the Wild
West. Newspapers throughout the East and Midwest ran the following
advertisement:
</P>
<P>
   ''Wanted - Young women, 18 to 30 years of age, of good
character, attractive and intelligent, as waitresses in Harvey
Eating Houses on the Santa Fe Railroad in the West. Good wages,
with room and meals furnished. Experience not necessary. Write Fred
Harvey, Union Depot, Kansas City, Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   Clad in black dresses with crisp white aprons, hair pulled back
demurely, the Harvey Girls, as they came to be known, were models
of efficiency and cheerfulness and reassured customers in
unfamiliar territory. The Harvey Girls had the privilege in working
in fairly elegant surroundings with Irish linen on the tables,
china, and Sheffield silver.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Harvey graduated from lunchroom to restaurant and finally
to hotels. The Santa Fe Railroad latched onto the glamour and
mystique of the Southwest by naming their trains the ''Chief'' and
''Superchief'' and using the thunderbird motif on their tableware.
Harvey named his hotels the Casta$eda, El Navaho, La Fonda,
Alvarado, Fray Marcos, La Posada, The Montezuma, The Havasu and
Sequoyah.
</P>
<P>
   Furnished in the what the company advertised as ''Indian
Style,'' they were an understated and modern presentation of Native
American and Hispanic influences _ not today's turquoise howling
coyote.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey's success was phenomenal and for the final coup, he
created a thriving souvenir trade. Travelers were besieged at the
railroad station by Native Americans selling pottery, blankets or
jewelry and it wasn't too long before the artisans became savvy _
utilitarian water jugs became smaller and rugs took on the popular
decorating hues of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvey Company, anxious to cash in on the booming souvenir
market, regularly wrote to Lorenzo Hubbell, owner of a famed
trading post on the Navajo reservation, and specified which colors
and motifs of rugs would sell best.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvey Company credited itself with reviving Navajo weaving
as well as rekindling an interest in the nearly extinct craft of
basket weaving. They trumpeted, ''Fred Harvey has done more for all
the Indian tribes in the Southwest than the thousands of people who
have written books, people in Congress, humanitarian committees,
etc. because we have created a market for their goods....'' The
Harvey Company didn't make out so badly in the deal, either.
</P>
<P>
   The souvenir trade begat the sacred American tradition of the
gift shop thereby linking the Harvey markets together. A train
passenger alighting in Albuquerque, N. M., for instance, was
quickly surrounded by Native Americans showing off their goods. The
colonnaded arcade of the Alvarado housed the Indian Building, with
its museum and a demonstration room where artisans created items
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   One had to pass through the salesrooms on the way back out to
the train or in again for dinner. With limited entertainment
available, is it any wonder that the tourist wandered back into the
gift shop and bought and bought?
</P>
<P>
   The tradition lives on. We travel more than any generation
before us. And spend more, too. And whether we go by car, train or
plane, we can be sure that at the beginning, the end or anywhere
along the route there will be a chain restaurant and a gift shop
nearby. Thank you, Fred Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrea Ibanez lives in Tucson, Ariz., and frequently writes
about the Southwest.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
