<HEADER>
A8999 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      05-24 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; 111 &LR;  ``Dancemaker'' Matthew Diamond takes his look at Paul
Taylor a step beyond most dance documentaries. He charts
dancer-choreographer Taylor's evolution and endurance, but devotes
just as much screen time to the anxieties of the hard-working and
devoted dancers whose bodies are Taylor's tools, and whom he isn't
above manipulating to arrive at his elegant, athletic dances with
their frequent emphasis on solitariness. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   (FU)  &UR; 11 &LR;  1/2 ``Endurance'' The quiet, self-contained dignity of
Haile Gebrselassie, the Ethiopian gold medalist in the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics' 10,000-meter run, translates into a compelling screen
presence in this docudrama in which he plays himself. But you can't
help feeling there's more complexity to him and his story than this
simple straight-line narrative is equipped to convey. (G)
</P>
<P>
   (FU)  &UR; 111 &LR;  ``Get Real'' Smart, realistic portrayal of a gay
16-year-old who falls in love with the school hunk. The film feels
familiar without being hackneyed, and in this movie year packed
with adolescent angst, ``Get Real'' easily emerges as the best of
the bunch. (R) (Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 111 &LR;  ``The Love Letter'' A charming screenful of amiable
mischief set in a New England seacoast town (played by Rockport).
Everybody knows everybody else's business, or thinks they're
entitled to, especially when one after another finds an unsigned
love letter each is convinced is addressed to her or him. Kate
Capshaw's frazzled bookshop owner is warm and simpatico, and the
others are engaging, too, especially Tom Selleck as Capshaw's
feelingful but inarticulate old flame and Julianne Nicholson as her
spunky young summertime clerk. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 111 &LR;  ``A Place Called Chiapas'' Although there is little doubt
about where her allegiances lie, filmmaker Nettie Wild presents a
fascinating, even-handed examination of the bloody acrimony between
Mexico's government and Mayan Indians waging a guerrilla war for
improved education, health care, and rule over their ancestral
lands. (Unrated) (Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 11 &LR;  1/2 ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' A world
apart from ``Star Wars'' _ and a notch below. It'll satisfy the
fans, but only just, and mostly because of snazzy visuals. The film
is unmistakably aimed at the young. Character and personality take
a back seat as this story focuses on Liam Neeson's Jedi Knight; his
pupil, Ewan McGregor's young Obi-Wan Kenobi; and his even younger
discovery, Jake Lloyd's Anakin Skywalker, the Tom Sawyer kid who
grows up to become Darth Vader but who at this point is more
interested in hot-rodding. (PG)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 111 &LR;  ``Trekkies'' Making fun of ``Trekkies,'' those folks
obsessed with all things ``Star Trek,'' has always been rather like
shooting fish in a barrel _ it's just too easy. So it says a lot
about Roger Nygard's often-hilarious documentary on the Trekkie
phenomenon that he spends as much time laughing with devotees as he
does laughing at them. (PG) (Renee Graham)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
