<HEADER>
A9000 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SPRINGS-BOS &LR;      05-24 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SPRINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK HOME IN KENTUCKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
CLEAR SPRINGS 
A Memoir 
By Bobbie Ann Mason. Random House. 298 pp. Illustrated. $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With her Kentucky pedigree and plain-spoken ambiguities, Bobbie
Ann Mason was one of the American writers who emerged in the 1980s
under the unruly rubric of minimalism, though she didn't really
belong there. Like other contemporaries trying to capture the
cloverleaf cruelties of the New South, she wrote about K Mart
stores and scattered families and empty rooms with Jerry Falwell
preaching from the TV _ but these were outcomes of history, not
personal failures, and her fiction contained too much heartsore
loss to qualify for the bleakness of minimalism. Throughout her
stories and novels ran a theme of disconnection and returning _ of
leaving home only to grieve for it, of feeling the earth under your
feet even when the world seemed capable of ejecting you from its
orbit. It may have already disappeared under the rubble of history,
but there was still that sense or promise of the land: a place that
either held you in memory or that you couldn't go on without.
</P>
<P>
   This palpable absence is revealed and explained in ``Clear
Springs,'' which is Mason's first effort at autobiography _ a
painstaking exploration of her Kentucky family and the farm they
owned, and of the paths leading outward from that lodestone that
would bend the author's course. At the center of the story is
Mason's mother, Christy Mason, who dreamed of going north to
Detroit, but instead stayed home, raised four children, and helped
her husband run their dairy farm on the outskirts of the little
town of Mayfield in western Kentucky. A few years ago, widowed and
in her 70s, she gave in to her children's requests and moved into
town. Most days, she still drives out to the farm to go fishing at
the pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clear Springs'' is a tender but uneven story about memory and
family and the costs of progress; it is also Mason's attempt to
capture her own equivocal legacy as both a loyalist and a wanderer.
In this regard, the work follows a classical arc, one that's become
familiar in the current memoir: early innocence and fidelity, the
far-flung, roaming bluster of youth, the redemptive reckoning of
the return. These constructs shape the chronology of the narrative.
Spanning Mason's first few decades, from her birth in 1940 through
graduate school and marriage in 1969, ``Clear Springs'' then skips
to 1990, when Mason returned to Kentucky with her husband to buy
their own piece of land. Woven throughout are the stories of her
predecessors: the brief, ill-fated marriage of her mother's
parents; the Mason family who, related by marriage, took in Christy
as a child, then watched her fall in love with a distant cousin;
the ceaseless, rewarding partnership of Christy and Wilburn Mason,
who between them worked hard enough to feed a family of six from
the garden and livestock they raised.
</P>
<P>
   That's a bone-deep American tale, and you can feel the emergence
of a young literary imagination, counting bugs and reading Nancy
Drew novels there in the pastoral stasis of Kentucky. When Mason
was 10 or 11, she started writing her own mystery stories, where
``the pleasure of writing was discovering what might pop out of my
mind unbidden.'' As she would come to realize, this free-fall
consciousness was one of the necessities of a fictional
sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   The laws of class are different in the rural South: Mason's
family wasn't poor, but every dollar counted, and they didn't have
indoor plumbing until after the Second World War. The days were
about plowing and weeding and hog butchering and selling
blackberries for a dollar a gallon; the dinners in between,
courtesy of Christy Mason, were about chicken and ham and biscuits
and tomatoes and damson pie. It's a romantic life in print and an
exhausting, insular one in reality, and Bobbie Ann did what
millions have done before her: She left the farm and headed for the
bright lights. Entranced by the wildfire promises of rock 'n' roll
and literature, she hit New York in 1962 _ whereupon she traded in
her sundresses and high heels for an earnestly sophisticated
mantle. It seems to have taken, but it didn't fool Mason herself,
who longed for the South and suffered a culture shock that any
immigrant to the Northeast will find poignantly familiar. Graduate
school didn't help. She went to Binghamton, N.Y., to study English
Lit, and found a well-meaning professor who encouraged her to read
the Greeks. ``I read Plato's Republic to my wife on our
honeymoon,'' he told Mason, who was flabbergasted at the idea. ``I
had the wrong gear for this venture,'' she remembers thinking. ``I
was like one of those catfish that can sort of walk on land _
awkwardly, using their whiskers like elbows.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the Beatles and Vietnam, the rest of America was
enduring a greater systemic shock, and those forces, too, would
influence Mason in ways she couldn't have known at the time _ in
the cultural lightning-bolt references of her fiction, in her
wonderful Vietnam novel, ``In Country.'' But almost none of her
life as a writer is included in ``Clear Springs,'' whether for
reasons of modesty or focus. Instead Mason has chosen to remember
the formative, smaller world that made her who she was, even though
she would have to leave there to recognize its dominion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clear Springs'' has odd failings, and the story is so full of
honorable intention that those shortcomings feel distressing. But
Mason was hardly the ruthless self-editor in this book. Devoted to
her family, intent upon capturing the force and beauty of life in
rural Kentucky and its changing face over the decades, she is
indiscriminate in what she has chosen to include _ with very little
of the synthesis or retrospective analysis that makes for brilliant
memoir. Mason has always been an unabashedly straightforward
writer, and that has worked to great advantage in works such as
``Shiloh and Other Stories'' and ``In Country,'' both of which paid
scrupulous attention to form. When it comes to the story of her
family, though, she has been less unsentimental; as with her
mother's cluttered farmhouse on moving day, Mason simply didn't
know what to throw out.
</P>
<P>
   This makes for dull reading sometimes, either uncensored (must
we know the cartoons the Mason kids watched, or the color and
texture of Mason's childhood phlegm?) or unprocessed (can't she
comment on her grandfather's hitting her, or the animal fatalities
that broke her heart?). And such irritations deflect from the very
real power of what is best about ``Clear Springs.'' That
distinction encircles Christy Mason, who is clearly the heroine of
her daughter's story; by the end of the book, it's easy to see why.
The last chapter of ``Clear Springs'' contains a stunning narrative
about a day in the life of Christy Mason that elicits the finest
stuff imaginable from two different women: the older one passionate
and cussedly stubborn, the younger one _ the writer-witness _
resolute and beautifully loyal. One carries a fishing rod and the
other a No. 2 pencil; in the hands of the Mason women, those are
both formidable tools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
