<HEADER>
A9003 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-RUN-BOS &LR;      05-24 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-RUN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT FROM THE SAD PAST, TOWARD EPIPHANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE WAY PEOPLE RUN 
By Christopher Tilghman 
Random House. 209 pp. $21.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christopher Tilghman has chosen a gem of a title for his second
collection of stories: ``The Way People Run.'' The phrase has a few
fine gradations and facets to it, as it yokes together how people
generally operate with the way they leave _ as in run away, and
turn away. And indeed, for many of the characters in Tilghman's
stories, most of whom are men, to live is to avoid. You wind up
these husbands and fathers and sons, and they proceed to take a
step back, away from the conflicts and compromises and commitments
of their lives. Like the lost soul in the story ``A Suitable
Good-bye,'' they are forever ``looking for the exit.''
</P>
<P>
   But it would be a mistake to characterize Tilghman's second
collection by the cleverness of its title. Like ``In a Father's
Place,'' which quickly established Tilghman as an extraordinary
short-story writer in 1990, the six new pieces are better than
clever. They are cleverly designed, but carried forth with such
naturalness and emotional flow that you don't think much about
authorial wit as you read. Despite the anomie and distance that
trips up his characters' heels, Tilghman's world is a sensual,
organic, and spiritual place in which men are interconnected with
the family members from whom they run, and the American landscapes
through which they run. His world is richly drawn with memory-laden
locales _ from Montana and Mississippi to the Chesapeake Bay region
_ and with the sort of family back stories that give each piece an
almost novel-like feel.
</P>
<P>
   While the stories are quite distinct, they're constructed on a
situation that recurs almost rhythmically throughout the book.
Tilghman returns again and again to people who are facing unwanted
feelings as they revisit a family home _ the old cottage on the
Rappahannock in the first story, ``Something Important,'' for
instance. During a stay at the mildewed house filled with memories
of Aunt Eliza on her wicker settee, a teacher named Peter Ramsey
learns just how successfully he's been running from the awful
truth: He and his wife are so distant that she's actually asked his
brother to tell him their marriage is finished. It's as though
Peter must take a Thomas Wolfe-ian trip home again, in order to
move forward. Likewise in ``Room for Mistakes,'' when a Newton man
travels back to his Montana childhood home for a lesson in the
power of forgiveness _ toward his mother, who has just died, toward
his stepfather, and toward himself. In a single moment, he fathoms
the meaning of mercy.
</P>
<P>
   More than his first collection, ``The Way People Run'' showcases
Tilghman's intuitive sense of pacing, the speed at which human
feeling moves. The emotional shifts that shape each of these dramas
feel entirely true, even fated, no matter how small they may be. He
doesn't manufacture revelations, or pop them like surprises to
create a sense of closure. In the book's saddest piece, ``Things
Left Undone,'' a young couple heals from the death of their son,
but slowly and tentatively, after seasons of alienation between
them. Their reconciliation ``will be enough, not perhaps for every
man and every woman, but for her, and for him, for now.'' The
haunting title story is similarly incremental, as a man on a
job-seeking road trip in the West becomes like an outlaw on the run
from his wife and children, wandering into a prairie town where his
grandfather once lived, sleeping with a strange woman. He is a
father, but he's also a son in need of a guiding light.
</P>
<P>
   The only rigged story of the six is ``The Late Night News,''
about a recently divorced man living a lonely life in ``one of
those big ancestral arks along one of those Chesapeake Bay
rivers.'' A ghostlike confrontation with a burgler shakes him out
of his retreat: ``You know man, you're a mess,'' the burglar tells
him. ``You sitting here in this big house drinking all alone.'' In
a less graceful collection, the schematic, ``Christmas Carol''
setup of this story might not jar as much.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the stories build beautifully to their moments of
relief and understanding _ moments that arrive in their own good
time, frequently unwelcome. What people run from, in some cases, is
freedom from pain. In ``A Suitable Good-bye,'' a depressed New
Yorker named Lee fights off the consolations of family ties. He
takes a train journey to Hattiesburg with his mother, to help her
track down the grave of her father, a suicide. But he can't wait to
run back to his empty New York life, and he finally succumbs to his
profound dodginess and abandons his mother. ``I thought if we stood
on my father's grave, you could see what despair leads to,'' his
mother cries at him before he splits. On the plane back to his
rootless urban life, though, he has a vision of his own
self-annihilation in the person of a hollow businessman drinking
bourbon. For an important moment, he thinks about breaking his
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Tilghman's language is deliberate and straightforward, but with
lovely, knowing flourishes throughout, particularly in the passages
about nature. About the Montana climate in ``Room for Mistakes,''
he writes: ``That was what real cold was, something the cattle
could see, a kind of recognition one could find in the black ice of
their eyes in the morning. In Massachusetts, people liked to talk
about the temperature as if it were a contest; on the Plains, the
cold was private information, like love.'' That's the kind of wise,
visual description you come to expect from Tilghman in ``The Way
People Run,'' a strong collection that grants us access to the
quiet, dignified, and gradual world of ``private information.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Matthew Gilbert writes about television and books for the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
