<SLUG> BC-TV-TALK-SHOWS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GENERATION OF HOSTS LIVENS UP THE LATE SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even the most casual television viewer knows that mornings on
the tube are talky, afternoons are soapy, evening time is prime,
and each day ends with a choice between the local news and sleep.
</P>
<P>
   But there are 24 hours on the TV clock, and many night owls are
still looking for laughs during what noted funnyman Johann Wolfgang
von Goethe called ``the mournful midnight hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this is a pretty good time to be an insomniac, because
a host of youngish comedians are revving up the venerable
late-night talk-show genre and driving it a few places David
Letterman and Jay Leno haven't gone.
</P>
<P>
   On the major networks, a pair of treetop-tall 36-year-old comics
are vying for viewers at 12:35 a.m.: NBC's exuberant Conan O'Brien,
who has surpassed Leno and Letterman as the new gold standard on
late night, and Craig Kilborn, whose CBS show has been more tin
than gold so far but can't yet be counted out.
</P>
<P>
   On cable's Comedy Central, still another 36-year-old comedian,
Jon Stewart, deftly meets the challenge of satirizing TV newscasts,
even though they already do a pretty good job parodying themselves.
On HBO, Dennis Miller _ the group's graybeard at 45 _ unleashes his
pet peeves each Friday night in a polysyllabic, rapid-fire rant
that evokes Lenny Bruce and Mort Sahl. And this fall, 33-year-old
Chris Rock will return to HBO with his own scorching brand of
take-no-prisoners comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Even though these hosts largely adhere to the
monologue-plus-interview format perfected by Johnny Carson, and
they too must feign interest as actors plop down on the couch to
flog their latest projects, make no mistake: These are not your
father's late-night talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   This quintet is more daring, more willing to challenge the
audience, and generally more plugged in to contemporary culture
than Carson ever dreamed of being. In part, that is because
late-night television now seeks demographically correct niches (in
other words, young, educated, free-spending viewers) rather than
trying to please everyone, so hosts aren't automatically blanded
out for a mass audience.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to picture Carson introducing a make-believe kids'
show titled ``The Embryonic Rockabilly Polka-Dotted Fighter
Pilots,'' as O'Brien has done, or featuring performances by rap
artists the way Rock does, or tossing in &QL; 
 &QL; 
references to ``Waiting for Godot'' while complaining about ``the
sprawling, impersonal ganglion'' of hospital rooms, as Miller
recently did.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it's also hard to picture Carson being so cruel as
to wisecrack, as Stewart did upon the death of former child actress
Dana Plato, ``There's got to be an easier way to get on the cover
of People.'' That no-limits ethos is the downside of the new
talk-show hosts.
</P>
<P>
   While pushing envelopes and hot buttons, they sift through
contemporary life and pop culture for one-liners or throwaway
allusions. O'Brien will riff on Ralph Malph, B. L. Stryker, or T.
J. Hooker; Miller will interrupt a rant on modern medicine with a
nostalgic reference to Bones McCoy of ``Star Trek,'' or will greet
a whooping crowd with ``I'm having deja Arsenio vu'' (a line that
inadvertently underscores how much, with the exception of Rock,
late night remains the domain of white males).
</P>
<P>
   Speaking as they do directly to younger viewers, the post-Carson
generation of comics can assume a certain level of fluency in the
language of kitsch. Also in keeping with that youthful skew, the
guests booked on these shows tend to be up-and-comers rather than
established stars _ the likes of Reese Witherspoon, Vivica A. Fox,
Julianne Moore, Angelina Jolie, or Paula Cale of ``Providence.'' In
the interviews, the hosts usually don't dig any deeper than Carson
did: The priority is keeping it fast and funny.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the monologues, let's just say that whatever
their differences, all five hosts are very, very glad that Monica
Lewinsky chose to work at the White House and that Dan Quayle chose
to return to politics. Celebrities in general get roughed up when
the comedians' eyes turn, as they often do, to current events.
</P>
<P>
   On ``The Daily Show With Jon Stewart,'' Billy Joel's retirement
was greeted derisively by Stewart with the observation that the
announcement left ``not a dry bulging eye in the house'' and the
question: ``Billy's gone. Will elevators and supermarkets go
silent?'' On ``Dennis Miller Live,'' Miller cracked that ultrathin
Calista Flockhart's ``20/20'' interview went awry when she
``slipped through the molecules on the couch and got stuck in a
subatomic space,'' and mocked Bill Gates for wearing glasses that
``would be too big for the Teddy Roosevelt statue on Mount
Rushmore.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``The Late Late Show With Craig Kilborn,'' Kilborn said the
premiere of the new ``Star Wars'' movie featured ``none other than
Mark Hamill, who said through a plate-glass window: `That'll be
$8.50, sir.' '' On ``Late Night With Conan O'Brien,'' on the night
before the presidential impeachment vote in the US Senate, O'Brien
predicted: ``By 1 o'clock tomorrow, President Clinton will be
reclaiming his old table at Hooters.''
</P>
<P>
   But if they share a glee at deflating the famous, there are
distinctions as well among the new voices of late night. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CONAN O'BRIEN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For sheer high spirits and inventiveness, O'Brien outruns the
late-night pack. A former writer, he's got a great comic mind and
is exceptionally quick on his feet; his throwaway quips are more
clever than some comedians' scripted monologues. Six years after he
got off to a very rocky start as Letterman's successor, O'Brien now
hosts the most consistently funny and original show on late night.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien has clearly been influenced by Letterman's absurdist
sensibility, with pseudo-interviews of a randy Clinton bellowing
``Yee-ha!'' and asking ``Do you want to get high?''; segments where
Conan learns to drive a truck and dance in hip-hop style; and bits
featuring characters like Triumph the Insult Comic Dog and Pimpbot
5000 (an android that, in O'Brien's words, ``combines the classic
sensibilities of a 1950s robot with the dynamic flair of a 1970s
street pimp'').
</P>
<P>
   But O'Brien goes Letterman one better by actually seeming happy
to be there, with a nicely unforced style of self-deprecation.
Opening his fifth-anniversary special last year, O'Brien noted that
``it's also the fifth anniversary for the `I Can't Believe That Guy
Has a Show' club.'' He boasted that the special was being simulcast
in Times Square; then a camera panned the square to reveal that the
simulcast was not on the famous giant screen but on a tiny TV in a
hole-in-the-wall store.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien also gives his sidekick, Andy Richter, more running room
than any late-night host ever has, even Letterman with Paul
Shaffer. And the 32-year-old Richter delivers with killer ad-libs
and physical comedy, such as when he was ``tricked'' into
blundering naked onto the set of the ``Today'' show, where Matt
Lauer was preparing an interview.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
