<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9007 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SOUTHIE-BOS &LR;      05-24 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SOUTHIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOUTHIE' LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `This movie should have died a million deaths,'' says
``Southie'' writer-actor Jimmy Cummings. ``But it didn't. Because
it was a story that wouldn't die.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, the General Cinema screening room in Boston
was packed with people from South Boston for a special screening of
``Southie,'' a tough yet sensitive tale of growing up in that
Boston neighborhood. At the screening are Phil Barrineau, the
neighborhood guy who scouted locations, and Eddie Eaton, who's
spent his whole life in the neighborhood. There's the owner of the
Quencher Tavern and a couple of firemen. This isn't a Hollywood
event, overflowing with celebrities and money men. It isn't about
fame and money. And neither is the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it, man,'' says Cummings, 31, who was born on
Vinton Street in South Boston and began writing the script nearly
six years ago. Producers came and went. Another co-writer came and
went. Actors came and went. Financing came and went. A title came
and went. The release date came and went. The only element holding
it all together was Cummings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't agree to play Danny because of the script,'' says
Donnie Wahlberg, a few weeks later on a sunny afternoon at Suffolk
Downs. ``I agreed to play it because of Jimmy. I just knew he'd get
it done. This movie should have died but it didn't. Because it has
heart _ Jimmy's heart.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Jimmy's heart beat?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bulldog,'' says co-writer-director-actor John Shea,
who's best known for his starring role in Costa-Gavras's
``Missing'' and for playing Lex Luthor on television's ``Lois and
Clark.'' ``He'll do anything to achieve his goals. Anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Cummings wasn't born to make movies. He seemed born to make
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always on the edge and sometimes in the middle of bad
stuff,'' says Cummings, who credits his time at Westwood's Xaverian
High with turning him around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in one day and I had a fight with another kid who had
been humiliating me and I got him down on the ground and punched
him,'' recalls Cummings. ``When I came inside the school, my
homeroom teacher, Mr. Balashi, grabbed me and told me that you
never hit somebody when they're down. It was that sort of thing
that straightened me out. That's why, at the end of the movie, I
have a short list of people I thank. And none of them had anything
to do with the making of the movie. But they had a lot to do with
making me.''
</P>
<P>
   After high school, Cummings moved to New York with some vague
notion that he wanted to act. But it was tough, and he wound up
supporting himself as a doorman and a carpenter, among other jobs.
Things went so badly on the acting front that he decided to write
himself a role. Buoyed by friends' reception of his stories of his
younger days in Boston, he began sketching out a deeply felt tale
of a kid growing up in _ and out of _ his hometown. After making
notes and a rough draft, he approached his pal David McLaughlin,
who was writing a book about New York's Covenant House, to help.
Together they pieced together a story called ``The Big Brass
Ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, after working and reworking the script, Cummings got it
to actor and Springfield native Shea, who was then involved in the
``Lois and Clark'' series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was making the transition from just acting to directing and
acting,'' says Shea, who also plays a policeman in ``Southie.''
``And I really liked the idea of a movie set in South Boston and
written from the inside out. But it needed work.''
</P>
<P>
   And work it got.
</P>
<P>
   Draft after draft. Shea writing and editing on the red-eye back
and forth from Los Angeles. Cummings doing the same in New York.
McLaughlin dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, through promises kept and promises broken, talent
found and lost, financing appearing and disappearing, Cummings
persevered.
</P>
<P>
   The real Rocky
</P>
<P>
   ``I never give up, man. Never,'' says Cummings. ``I'm from
Boston. I mean, I didn't even know what I was doing but I knew I
was doing something right. I'd see these movies that were terrible,
and I knew mine was better. I mean, when I saw `Rocky' I thought it
was me. I know I can go 15 rounds and it didn't make no difference
whether I lost the first 14. I knew I could knock them out in the
last round. And that's exactly how it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked Jimmy's enthusiasm,'' he says. ``And I liked
the idea that it was basically his story. It meant something to
him. And I liked the characters, especially Donnie's.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Southie,'' Donnie Wahlberg plays Danny, a young adult who
returns to South Boston for a wedding. He had left town to shed the
entanglements of family and neighborhood. In order to find himself,
he needed to be alone _ free of being the family caregiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my own story,'' says Wahlberg, who first read the
script in the summer of 1996. ``My heart was in it right off the
bat. I got parts in `Ransom' and `Body Count,' but I wanted to
shoot `Southie.' ''
</P>
<P>
   They shot the film on a shoestring budget. Wahlberg, for
example, paid for a three-room trailer and a hair and makeup person
out of his own pocket. After a 26-day shoot featuring 12-hour days,
the film was finished.
</P>
<P>
   Because there was a rumor that a studio was making a movie from
Orson Welles's script called ``The Big Brass Ring,'' they changed
the title to ``Southie.''
</P>
<P>
   But it still wasn't finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is really bad for independent films,'' says
``Southie'' producer Bill McCutcheon. ``It's getting harder and
harder. But Lion's Gate (the distributor) agreed to open it in
Boston and on the West Coast _ presumably in Seattle, where it did
very well at the Seattle Film Festival _ and we'll go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Cummings is happy. He got out of the movie what he
put into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get that feeling that it's a different world,''
says Cummings, who plays a two-bit, ultraviolent punk in the
picture. ``It's a world you need to leave but can't. It's a
dangerous place, and a loving place.''
</P>
<P>
   During last June's Nantucket Film Festival, Cummings's dreams
came true when the line to see ``Southie'' stretched around the
block at the island's aptly named Dreamland Theater. It was just a
week after the film won the best picture jury prize at the 24th
annual Seattle Film Festival. ``Southie'' was hot.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpected delay
</P>
<P>
   So why did it take so long for the film to hit theaters?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the business,'' says Cummings. ``It happened when it
happened because that's when it happened. Only in the movie
business does that make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Lion's Gate was tied up promoting ``Affliction'' and ``Gods and
Monsters,'' two Oscar-nominated films, so ``Southie'' had to wait.
Finally, the local film that finished shooting before ``Good Will
Hunting,'' ``Monument Ave.,'' and ``Next Stop Wonderland'' even
started filming will open.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of ``Southie,'' in a pivotal moment, Danny picks
up a picture of his father. But it's not a photo of his father,
it's a portrait of Jack Cummings, Jimmy's father. An inside homage
to a man who, at 55, was hit by a car and killed in Andrew Square
when his son was 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father lost his job at the newspapers'' _ he worked in the
press room at both the Globe and the Herald at different times _
when I was 6,'' says Cummings. ``He started to drink. That left us,
as a family, in bad shape. He left us with bills. It wasn't good.''
Cummings pauses. ``Did you ever stand in line with those coupons
and watch people watch you? It's humiliating. Then you eat that
awful peanut butter. Man, you can never get the taste of that crap
out of your mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's precisely that taste that flavors ``Southie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day,'' concluded Cummings. ``I made it for
my family.''
</P>
<P>
   A movie where no one makes any money. No one gets any fame. And
everyone's happy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
