<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9008 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-RYAN-BOS &LR;      05-24 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RYAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RYAN' IS GUNNING FOR VIDEO VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan,'' last
year's highest-grossing film, storms the home-video beachhead,
generating anticipation from fans and some anger from video
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The World War II drama was the winner of five Academy Awards,
including best director for Spielberg and best cinematography for
Janusz Kaminski. Retailing for $110, it's a hefty price for many
small video-store owners who need to buy a substantial number of
copies in order to compete with the chains. Each home-video
distributor decides whether to price a tape at $20 for sell-through
to the general market, or to price it for the rental market, in
which case the home-video dealers pay a premium and profits are
generated through renting the tape to consumers. Last year, 20th
Century-Fox and Paramount's ``Titanic'' went directly to the
sell-through market.
</P>
<P>
   But DreamWorks is taking the pricier route, and they don't seem
worried. The orders have come in very strong, and even though the
studio wouldn't confirm the number of copies shipped to stores this
week, a spokesperson said it was a record number. That would put
it, at least, over the 1.1 million copies record established by
20th Century-Fox Home Video when they released ``There's Something
About Mary'' earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Independent video-store owner John Hunt of Hunt's Video Hut in
North Kingstown, R.I., feels the squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for a small store owner because they offer deals if
you buy more than a certain number of copies,'' says Hunt. ``For
`Private Ryan,' if you buy four at the standard rate, they'll sell
you six more at a reduced rate and then buy back the bargain copies
after 90 days. But what if you don't need 10 copies? I bought six,
which is a lot for us, but a lot of customers have been asking for
it. We paid less than $20 for `You've Got Mail' and we can't keep
it on the shelves. There should be more like that to help the
independents.''
</P>
<P>
   The dealer price doesn't affect consumer anticipation. If a
sampling of customers at a variety of Cambridge video stores is any
indication, ``Saving Private Ryan'' may make everyone happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it should have won best picture,'' said Henry
Sasantzky, outside Hollywood Express near Porter Square. ``I'll
rent it and, when it runs its course, I'll buy it as a pre-viewed
copy for $10 or so. Just like `Titanic.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan'' has already won the 1998 battle for the box office with
just over $210 million, even though it lost the Academy Award for
best picture to ``Shakespeare in Love.'' According to calculations
provided by DreamWorks, it was listed as the year's best picture by
more than 70 critics and organizations such as the New York, Los
Angeles, Chicago, and London critics' associations.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Goldberg, who plays Private Mellish, the guy who taunts the
Germans, wasn't sure what to expect when the film was originally
released last July. While Tom Hanks is the star, the supporting
cast, including Edward Burns, Tom Sizemore, Dennis Farina, and Matt
Damon, is what gives the film its depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything about the film was a little unusual,'' says
Goldberg, from his home near Los Angeles. ``Even when I read for
it, we read from another script from a film called `A Midnight
Clear.' It felt foolish and pointless but, a few weeks later, I was
in the movie. I didn't even know who I was playing. During the
shooting we would make up lines and situations. Spielberg and
everyone was very open to that. The entire script was in flux.
While we were shooting we'd all contribute, then they'd call in an
assistant and the writer and they'd transcribe and we'd shoot.
There was a lot of improvisation and I think he cast everyone
because he thought we'd fit together. He allowed us a lot of
freedom. The only question I had was whether or not it would
cohere.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Goldberg surprised when he saw the finished film?
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that it would be graphic,'' said the Sarah Lawrence
graduate. ``There were entire scenes cut out. But it's hard not to
be overwhelmed by it. I also thought it would be maligned for being
too graphic or people wouldn't like it because it wasn't pro or
antiwar. It wasn't simple. But I was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Most actors explain that they take certain roles because of the
great script or a director they'd like to work with, describing the
decision in artistic terms. Not Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only asked my agent one question,'' recalled the actor, who
played Eddie on the hit series ``Friends'' and went on to play
Matthew McConaughey's best friend in Ron Howard's ``EDtv.'' ``Can I
do it in exchange for finishing funds for my movie?''
</P>
<P>
   When the answer came back yes, Goldberg signed on.
</P>
<P>
   That movie is the now-completed ``Scotch and Milk,'' a festival
favorite without a distributor that was written, directed,
produced, and co-edited by Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   It's at the opposite end of the movie spectrum from the
big-budget ``Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's black-and-white, nonlinear, and it's pure and honest,''
he said. ``It wasn't made to be a calling card to something else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
