 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, May 25:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans two pages on the continuing crisis in
Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Developments on Kosovo from NATO
headquarters as the alliance's political body, the North Atlantic
Council, prepares for a major meeting on Tuesday to consider the
role of ground forces. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ Military developments on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ Widespread blackouts and loss of
water are seriously disrupting the lives of people in the Yugoslav
capital. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PROTESTS (Belgrade) _ Mothers' antiwar protests, thought
to have been quelled, resume. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Dateline to kum, Macedonia) _ Tensions between
the United Nations and Macedonians over the handling of refugees
increase as thousands more cross into Macedonia and many are bused
away to Albania. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   And this related story:
</P>
<P>
   MAP-AGENCY (Bethesda, Md.) _ The National Imagery and Mapping
Agency, source of the outdated maps in the bombing of the China
embassy in Belgrade, holds a forum on its plans to make its images
and data available to the public. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-POLITICS (New Delhi) _ A look at the enigmatic Sonia
Gandhi. On Tuesday, Congress Party leaders will make a last-ditch
plea to her to return as president of party as they prepare for
elections in the fall. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DAM (Beijing) _ In an implicit admission that severe
problems bedevil the giant Three Gorges Dam project, Prime Minister
Zhu Rongji has announced a major change in strategy for resettling
at least 1.3 million people who will be driven from their homes. By
Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HARASS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules, 5 to 4,
that school boards can be sued for student-on-student sex
harassment. Associate Justice O'Connor, in the majority opinion,
notes that sex harassment in schools is serious, and that when a
school district is on notice that a student's education is impaired
and does nothing it can be sued. In the view of the minority, this
decision opens the way for the federal government to get involved
in such things as student desk assignments. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MEDIA (Washington) _ Police violate the 4th Amendment
when they bring the media along to a home for a search and arrest,
the Supreme Court rules. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ A roundup of other high court action: a
disability case, suits against employers, a takings case and a case
on the FTC's jurisdiction over non-profit groups. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-CHILD (Milwaukee, Wis.) _ Ten years old but going on 21,
Tremayne Franks is the neighborhood's youngest corner grocer. With
both parents missing from the scene, Tremayne, who lives with his
grandmother, briefly found a shelter working at the now-closed Fast
Deal Supermarket and in his relationship with its owner, a
Palestinian immigrant. A look at fatherless boys, strained race
relations and the plight of families dropped from the welfare
rolls. By Jason DeParle. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-COLLAR-VICTIMS (Undated) _ The victims' rights movement,
which two decades ago began demanding recognition and help for
those who have suffered from violent crimes, is now turning its
attention to those injured by white-collar crime. Their advocates
have already succeeded in changing a federal law to allow money
from a special crime victims fund to be used to help those injured
by economic crimes, and the first federally financed pilot programs
began last year. Fueling the movement is the fact that the numbers
of such victims are surging at a time when violent crime has
plummeted. By Leslie Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVETTI-DEUTSCHE-TELEKOM (Frankfurt, Germany) _ What Olivetti's
victory in the battle for control of Telecom Italia means for
Deutsche Telekom. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   CADBURY-COKE (Undated) _ Cadbury-Schweppes and Coca-Cola scale
back their $1.8 billion worldwide deal because of regulatory
opposition in Europe. The new $1.1 billion sale by Cadbury now
excludes European Union nations other than Britain, Ireland and
Greece. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   LAW-FIRM-MERGER (New York) _ The New York law firm Rogers &AMP;
Wells and Clifford Chance, Britain's biggest law firm, vote to
merge. By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:30 p.m., stocks were lower: The Dow
Jones industrial average was down 93 points, the S&AMP;P 500 down 14
and the Nasdaq composite down 45. Many European markets, Germany
and Switzerland among them, were closed for a holiday and in
London, which was open, the FTSE 100 was little changed. In Asia,
Tokyo's Nikkei ended up 0.6 percent, while Hong Kong's Hang Seng
rose 1.34 percent. At midday in New York the yield on the 30-year
Treasury bond stood at at 5.74 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   GM-DELPHI (Detroit) _ Looking ahead at the General Motors
spinoff of Delphi Automotive. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   THERMO-REORG (Undated) _ Three days before its annual meeting,
Thermo-Electron will announce some restructuring steps. This comes
two weeks after it received a letter from the Franklin mutual funds
calling for an overhaul. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE-HOURS (New York) _ The New York Stock Exchange says it will
accelerate its timetable for extending trading hours. By Diana B.
Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   AVIS-CENDANT (Undated) _ Cendant sells its automobile fleet unit
for $1.8 billion to Avis Rent a Car, raising Cendant's stake in
Avis to 34 percent from 19 percent. Cendant also says it intends to
sell a handful of units as it completes a major overhaul aimed at
focusing its core operations on travel, real estate, direct
marketing and car rentals.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-DEBT (Sao Paulo) _ A plan to swap $1 billion of overseas
corporate debt for government-backed debt has been abandoned. By
Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
