<HEADLINE>
N.Y. LAWMAKERS STILL WAITING FOR THEIR PAYCHECKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARA JAKES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The new law that withholds legislators' salaries
until they approve a state budget has been declared
unconstitutional by a Brooklyn judge.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawmakers, who by now have missed their third paycheck,
still will not see their state wages until Gov. George Pataki has
finished appealing the court ruling, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   In a 10-page decision Friday, state Supreme Court Justice
Richard Huttner ruled that the law ``coerced'' legislators into
making fiscal decisions and could lead them to ``sacrifice (their)
consciously held beliefs'' in order to avoid personal financial
woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This strikes at the very heart of our republican form of
government wherein all legislative power is derived from the
people,'' Huttner said. ``To place any legislator, or anyone in any
branch of the government, under undue economic pressure in
exercising his or her judgment while expecting that person to act
in accordance with his or her oath of office is illogical, unsound
and unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   The pay-withholding measure was approved overwhelmingly by the
legislature during a special session in December as part of a deal
to hike lawmakers' salaries by 39 percent to $79,500 annually. It
requires lawmakers, but not the governor, to go without pay until a
state budget, which is nearly eight weeks late, is passed. The
state's fiscal year began April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after they began missing paychecks, 14 Democratic
legislators _ all but one from New York City _ sued the state. The
lawsuit charged that the measure gives too much power to the
executive and could put legislators in a position where they might
be inclined, or perceived to be inclined, to acquiesce on budget
issues out of personal interest.
</P>
<P>
   Huttner's decision does not order the state to release
legislators' withheld pay.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Health Committee Chairman Richard Gottfried, a
Manhattan Democrat who led the court battle against the measure,
said, ``I felt from the start that the purpose of this law is to
use personal financial pressure to try to bludgeon legislators into
caving into the governor's budget cuts. I'm happy the court agrees
that this is unconscionable in a democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   After learning about the court's decision, Comptroller H. Carl
McCall, a Democrat, ordered his office to release the paychecks
from the vault where they have been stored since the legislature's
first missed payday. The comptroller's office issues paychecks. But
the state treasurer, whose office is part of the governor's
Republican administration, is actually responsible for distributing
them. And that won't happen until Pataki has exhausted his appeals
options, said spokesman Patrick McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their paychecks will continue to be withheld if they would
rather sue for their paychecks rather than work for them,''
McCarthy said, adding that the governor was not surprised at the
judge's ruling. Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, a Democrat who is
defending the state in the matter, said an appeal would be filed
within days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
