<SLUG> BC-CYBER-BUSINESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE IS FOR EVERYONE, AUTHOR SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Electronic commerce still may be in its infancy,
but there are already scores of cheerleaders and skeptics on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the latest voices heard come from Thomas Siebel, founder
and chairman of the business software maker Siebel Systems Inc.,
and Pat House, executive vice president and co-founder of Siebel
Systems. The two have written ``Cyber Rules: Strategies For
Excelling at E-business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cyber Rules'' explains how e-commerce will change the way
companies do business in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Siebel, who helped Larry Ellison get the Oracle Corp. off the
ground in the 1980s, said all companies should conduct at least
some of their business over the Web. He spoke about e-commerce in a
recent interview:
</P>
<P>
   Question: In your view, how exactly will the Internet change the
way we do business?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: This is a total paradigm shift. This is one of the
inflection points in history. Most businesses will shift their
business model to incorporate e-business and make that part of
their distribution mix.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will traditional businesses fall by the wayside?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. The Internet is just one of the ways we're going to do
business.
</P>
<P>
   In a lot of transactions there's no substitute for human
interaction. If you're going to get a new ad campaign for
Coca-Cola, you're not going to do this just over the Internet. You
have to meet with ad people and plan.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of these discussions imply the Internet replaces sales
people and stores. That's just a bunch of bunk. Storefronts will
continue to exist.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What types of jobs will e-commerce eliminate?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't see any jobs being eliminated. I just see more jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The jobs aren't that different from non e-commerce jobs. You
still have marketing, sales, human resources. The jobs are
essentially the same. Just the distribution channel changes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There has also been a lot of talk about how e-commerce will
reduce companies' operating costs. How will this happen?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not about reducing costs. It is about applying
information and communication technology to establish and maintain
customer relationships and provide much, much higher levels of
service.
</P>
<P>
   Companies will have to deal with razor-thin margins, and they'll
have to deal in volume.
</P>
<P>
   The market is global. Innovative, visionary companies see the
future. Those people who don't make this transition will cease to
exist.
</P>
<P>
   Q: This assumes that all companies need to take a global
approach to business? Is this possible or necessary?
</P>
<P>
   A: When you go to Europe, the borders are gone. To not take
advantage of large market opportunities is not rational for the
business person.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are there any industries that cannot take advantage of e-
commerce?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't see any industries that won't be totally changed by
this.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers can use (the Internet) to buy fertilizer and sell
cattle. The family farm is going to buy and market its products
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There are companies that will take advantage of this paradigm
shift and be the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   There are companies that won't and will get wiped out. For
example, those companies that didn't make the transition to
computer-aided manufacturing in the '70s and '80s got wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Despite all the interest in doing business over the Net, few
e-commerce companies are making money. How and when will these
businesses turn profits?
</P>
<P>
   A: Right now, these companies are getting their valuations from
things other than profits. It's their ability to aggregate users.
</P>
<P>
   One of these days we're going to have a crisis in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Some leading company like Oracle will announce their stock has
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Then the market will drop by some crazy number. Then these
Internet stocks will drop. Then they're going to start focusing on
their profits.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com could make a profit, but their board's not telling
them to make a profit. The board is telling them to spend.
(Seattle-based Amazon.com, the online book seller, recorded a loss
of $61.7 million on sales of $293.6 million for the quarter ended
March 31.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: When will profits become more important to Internet
businesses?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'd be amazed if this doesn't happen in the next 24 months.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There are so many Internet startups in our midst. How many
will survive?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ninety-five to 97 percent will fail. There's a market excess
here.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets don't know how to deal with this revolution
yet. Valuations are 100 times more than they deserve. Right now,
they're valued on unbridled enthusiasm. That's a temporary
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   When these markets collapse, it won't be the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Companies will just get reasonable valuations, but the
underlying effect to the economy will be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you respond to e-commerce naysayers who say the
industry is mostly hype?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are a lot of people that contended for many, many years
that the Earth was flat. Some of them used to be experts in their
field. They were wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
