<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9110 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORAAA0525-COX     05-24 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORAAA0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't expect top quality at a cut-rate price
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A guy brought his car back to a tire dealer complaining that the
tires were only six months old and already worn out. Sure enough,
the mechanic confirmed both front tires were worn down to the cord
on the inside while the outer edges showed almost new tread.
</P>
<P>
   The customer's receipt validated the mechanic's suspicion. A
wheel alignment had been recommended when the tires were purchased,
yet the customer had declined the work. The customer's disgruntled
explanation was, ``Yeah, I know how you guys operate. They wanted
to charge me another $300 for parts they claimed were worn out
before they would even align it. I found this other guy who would
do the work for less than half of what your shop wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you taken the car back to the guy who did the work?''
asked the mechanic. ``The tire wear is due to improper alignment,
not defective tires.''
</P>
<P>
   The customer replied, ``Yeah, sure I took it back! He claims the
tires are faulty and should be replaced free of charge.''
</P>
<P>
   The mechanic saw an argument brewing and decided a direct
explanation wouldn't work. He suggested putting the car on the rack
so they could determine the reason for the tire wear. A quick but
thorough inspection of the front end revealed excessive looseness
caused by several worn components. It was also apparent that no
parts had been replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did this guy say he fixed on your car?'' queried the
mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't know exactly. He said he put on a couple of
good, used parts. I told him just to patch it up 'cause I was going
to sell it. Say, can't you just tighten up some of this stuff and
align it close?''
</P>
<P>
   The mechanic's patience faltered.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Every time the vehicle moves, the alignment changes
because the parts are worn out. I'm sure an intelligent fellow like
you can now understand that trying to patch this car together with
used parts wasn't a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what are your options now? You can take the car back to the
guy who worked on it and give him a chance to make it right. You
can try to sell the car the way it is, or you can get the front end
fixed and chalk your losses up to experience. In any case, you're
going to have to buy new tires. Alignment wear is not the tire
manufacturer's fault.''
</P>
<P>
   All of us have probably had an experience similar to this. We
budgeted for a specific purchase only to be unpleasantly surprised
by unforeseen problems. Our first instinct might be to try to find
someone to patch it up just until we can afford to get it fixed
right.
</P>
<P>
   But that usually gets us in more trouble than we started with.
Most reputable repair shops avoid patch jobs because they always
come back with an angry customer in tow. Here are some suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   Don't be afraid to ask questions. Reputable shops encourage
questions. Questions convey your interest in what is happening with
your vehicle. It also gives you a chance to form an opinion about
the shop. Nobody expects you to understand every nut and bolt in
your vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't understand an answer, ask them to repeat it in
plain English. Sometimes service people forget and slip into
technicese without realizing it.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the service adviser or mechanic to explain the exact nature
of the problem including the consequences that might be incurred if
the repair isn't performed immediately. Don't ask, ``How long can I
drive it this way?'' or ``How many miles before it breaks?''
</P>
<P>
   No one can estimate the actual time and place of total failure.
When there are several problems, ask for a prioritized list so you
can budget accordingly. If possible, ask them to show you what
needs to be repaired.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget to inquire about parts and labor guarantees,
warranties and the mechanic's qualifications. Get it in writing.
</P>
<P>
   You always have the option of a second opinion. Don't expect
comparable price or quality between a reputable shop and a shop
that uses cut-rate or used parts. You should expect to pay a
diagnostic fee as you would if you were getting a second opinion
from a doctor. Beware of freebies. Those ``get you in the door''
techniques are rarely free.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you actually find a shop that agrees to patch up
your car (just long enough for you to sell it), you're in the wrong
place.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
