<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer-loving Jeep Wrangler a guilty pleasure
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you ever noticed that sometimes in life you find that you
like things that common sense tells you are not necessarily good
for you?
</P>
<P>
   They're usually relatively harmless _ like pizza and cotton
candy, platform shoes or acrylic fingernails _ and all that matters
is that we like them.
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said of the Jeep Wrangler. It's everything that
a vehicle shouldn't be and at the same time everything that a
sport-utility should be.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because it began as the pure utility vehicle commonly
known as the jeep during its original days serving the U.S. armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Wrangler, while a bit more gussied up than the military
issue, is truly a world apart from the truck-based luxury liners
that most people refer to as sport-utilities. Even its corporate
cousin, the elegant Jeep Grand Cherokee, has to be a very distant
cousin.
</P>
<P>
   My test vehicle was equipped with a canvas top and
zip-in-and-out plastic windows. As I kept up with traffic on the
interstate, the windows would blow out.
</P>
<P>
   Entry and exit were not exactly graceful. True to its heritage,
the Wrangler side body extends four or five inches above the floor
surface. It quickly becomes an up-over-and-down entry maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   The front windshield is a real novelty in today's automotive
market. It's flat, and the Wrangler's headlights are round.
</P>
<P>
   By today's standards, the Wrangler is pretty basic. It also
happens to be a supremely ``happy'' vehicle. It makes you feel good
every time you get in.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the enigma. There is really nothing about the
Wrangler that, by all of today's standards, should make it
endearing, but it is.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that it is about as close to driving an adult
version of your kiddie pedal-car as you can get? Does it allow you
to revisit your first, second or perhaps even third childhood?
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that the spirited performance of the 4.0-liter
engine coupled to a five-speed manual transmission is a relatively
light package that gets your adrenaline flowing? Or could it be
that sometimes less truly is more?
</P>
<P>
   The Wrangler Sport has the contemporary necessities such as dual
air bags (passenger-side with a shutoff switch) and a cupholder,
but the experience of driving is not marred by a host of gizmos.
</P>
<P>
   While a tux and a prom dress might be a bit uncomfortable in the
Wrangler's bucket seats, cutoff jeans, wet swimsuits and the wind
in your hair and the sun in your face are made to order for this
summer-loving vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Write Linda Sharp in care of Wheels, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
