<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, May 25:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BLACK-HOLES (Undated) _ The sudden, random and faraway
flashes of gamma radiation, known as gamma ray bursts, seem to be
cosmic birth announcements of a phenomenon of awesome power, one
predicted by Einstein's general theory of relativity but shrouded
in mystery because no light can escape the dark clutches of its
consuming gravity. If current hypotheses are correct, Dr. Tsvi
Piran of Columbia University said at a recent four-day symposium at
the Space Telescope Science Institute, ``each gamma ray burst is
signaling the creation of a new black hole.'' By John Noble
Wilford. (1975 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WEIGHT-FAT (Undated) _ For three decades now, Americans have
been bombarded with advice to eat less fat for the sake of their
hearts and their waistlines. But now a growing number of nutrition,
health and obesity specialists maintain that in trying to squeeze
some of the heart-damaging grease from our high-fat diets, they
have sent Americans the wrong message. It's not fat per se that's
the problem, the experts now say, but the kinds of fats Americans
eat and the other kinds of foods they fill up on when they cut back
on appetite-satisfying fat. By Jane E. Brody. (1900 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RESEARCH-REVIEW (Undated) _ Duke's recent problems with a
Federal review board illuminates the increasing stresses on that
hospital and university review boards face and the new
aggressiveness by the Federal agency that oversees them, the Office
of Protection from Research Risks. The review boards, which check
the safety and efficacy of experiments on humans, generally work on
their own time with little or no staff and virtually no training.
By Philip J. Hilts. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SMALLPOX (Undated) _ The Doctor's World: Smallpox, an
ancient disease, was eradicated 20 years ago. Smallpox, the virus,
is on death row, frozen in two highly protected laboratories in the
United States and Russia. Like lawyers filing last minute briefs,
American scientists recently found new arguments for public health
research requiring use of the virus in future laboratory
experiments. Last week, with the U.S. and Russia reversing earlier
decisions to destroy the smallpox virus, the World Health
Organization granted the virus yet another stay. It is good for at
least three years beyond the June 30 date that had been set for its
destruction in ovens. By Lawrence K. Altman Jr. (1750 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FLAG-PRESERVE (Undated) _ Using technology as new as space
age fabrics and as ordinary as the chemicals from the corner
dry-cleaning shop, scientists and historians here have taken on the
job of cleaning and preserving the Star-Spangled Banner, the flag
that flew over Fort McHenry in Baltimore in 1814, so that it might
last at least another 185 years. By Irvin Molotsky. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Items on decoding backward speech sounds,
winds on Jupiter and storms on Mars. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WEIGHT-MORPH (Undated) _ The software in a body morphing
machine shows users what they might look like if they lost 15
percent of their weight or, show a 30 percent gain. Then it tells
details users' chances of contracting various weight-related
maladies _ heart disease, diabetes and high blood pressure _ worsen
and improve with the changes. By Eric Nagourney. (425 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ONLINE-FITNESS (Undated) _ On-line training: The Internet is
awash with gymnasts and fitness competitors, body builders, coaches
and trainers willing to sign up clients for online fitness. The
system has its advantages, including the anonymity. This writer
emerged 17 pounds lighter, capable of sleeping through the night
for the first time in her life, energetic, fit and strong. By
Marion Roach. (1375 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health: In the early '70s,
celebrity dieters and wishful thinkers propelled Dr. Robert C.
Atkins's self-styled ``diet revolution'' into a national phenomenon
that sent shivers of despair through the promoters of sound
nutrition and public health. Despite warnings of a possible heart
attack on every page, ``Dr. Atkins' Diet Revolution,'' a book that
promoted a high-fat, high-protein diet and spurned all
carbohydrates, was bought by 10 million Americans whose growing
reliance on labor-saving devices and fast foods had spawned thunder
thighs and rendered their waistlines obsolete. But the Atkins
scheme was neither new nor revolutionary then and is really no
different from his ``new diet revolution,'' published in 1992 and
now enjoying a resurgence of popularity among countless
weight-conscious women and carnivorous men seeking a quick and
painless route to a slimmer summer. By Jane E. Brody. (1450 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WEIGHT-PILLS (Undated) _ In their eagerness to take pills
that will help them slim down, people may conveniently overlook
something that doctors remember all too well: weight-loss drugs
have had an alarming history. By Denise Grady. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WEIGHT-REBOUND (Undated) _ It is a depressing article of
faith among the overweight and the professionals who treat them
that 95 percent of people who lose weight regain it _ and sometimes
more _ within a few months or years. That statistic has been quoted
widely over the last four decades, from Congressional hearings to
diet books to research papers and seminars. And it is the reason so
many people approach dieting with a sense of hopelessness. But
there is a problem with that piece of conventional wisdom: There is
no scientific basis for it. In fact, obesity researchers say that
no one has an accurate idea of what percentage of the population
can maintain a weight loss over the long term. By Jane Fritsch.
(1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Though it has been well established that most peptic ulcers
are caused by a bacteria called Helicobacter pylori, or H. pylori,
and can be effectively treated with antibiotics, recent studies
show that that information has not gotten out to ulcer sufferers,
and a large number of doctors were continuing to treat with
standard acid blockers only. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Many teen-agers experience stress, but the patterns of stress
girls encounter may leave them more vulnerable to depression than
the patterns of stress boys experience according to the results of
a study that appears in the current issue of the journal Child
Development. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: Pluto sometimes
crosses the orbit of Neptune, suggesting to me that they might
collide at some point. Should I worry? (300 words)
</P>
