<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-MERGER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITIES' HOSPITAL MERGER LEADS TO NEW PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The 1997 merger of the medical centers of the
University of California at San Francisco and Stanford University
was supposed to save them from financial ruin, but a steady stream
of bad news from the hospital system has left many questioning the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of streamlining services and getting better prices on
drugs and supplies, the merger added 1,000 employees, a new set of
executive offices and, some say, distractions from the hospitals'
core missions.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, it has not shielded them from the financial distress
being felt by academic medical centers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The merger was supposed to help protect the hospitals _ UCSF
Mount Zion and UCSF Medical Center in San Francisco and Stanford
Hospital and the Lucile Salter Packard Children's Hospital in Palo
Alto _ from projected loss of revenue from cuts in Medicare,
Medicaid and from lower private insurance payments.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents claimed the merger would improve the combined bottom
line by $256 million between 1997 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, UCSF Stanford Health Care officials say they will run
up a $135 million debt by next year if they don't immediately slash
the budget and eliminate 2,000 of the system's 12,500 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The system also announced recently that it must find yet another
$100 million _ either through cuts or increased revenues _ to make
it comfortably through 2001. That could mean closing in-patient
hospital care and perhaps the emergency room at Mount Zion.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of mounting losses and resulting cuts on patient care
remains to be seen. Unions and faculty members say the future looks
grim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to continue to spiral the system into the ground,''
said Karen MacLeod of the University Professional and Technical
Employees union. ``We cannot keep making cuts like this and not
believe it's going to have serious, permanent effects on the
hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Claims that the merger would lead to a more cost-effective
operation ``proved to be absolutely and totally incorrect,'' Frank
W. Clark Jr., a longtime opponent of the merger, told fellow UC
regents last week.
</P>
<P>
   Several other regents, who voted to transfer UCSF's hospitals to
a private corporation owned jointly with Stanford, also expressed
unease with the results.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and employee unions, who opposed the merger, are beating
the drum for its dissolution. Even those who continue to support it
agree it hasn't turned out as they had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, we failed badly in the management of the
operation,'' UC President Richard Atkinson told regents last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite widespread grumbling, momentum for a divorce does not
appear to be sweeping the campuses. Some doctors believe the merger
could lead to fruitful collaborations at the two affiliated medical
schools, but those opportunities are being overwhelmed by the
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ills of the world have been blamed on the merger,'' said
Ken Melmon, chairman of the academic senate at Stanford Medical
School. ``I think the faculty at Stanford is sort of wishing for a
divorce to some extent, but the fact is that divorce in the long
haul probably isn't going to impact these problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``UCSF Stanford Health Care's president and CEO, Peter Van
Etten, still insists that the merger will prove worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 20 months into this. Nobody said it would be easy.
Nobody said it would be quick,'' Van Etten said. ``I continue to
believe that the two organizations are much more able to deal with
our core problem, which is the changing external environment, by
continuing to operate as a merged entity.'
</P>
<P>
   UCSF Stanford financial woes are due in large part to federal
budget cuts that have sharply reduced payments to academic medical
centers everywhere. Those cuts were expected and were a key
justification for merging.
</P>
<P>
   Van Etten said the revenue shortfalls simply came faster than
expected, and UCSF Stanford failed to act quickly enough to cut the
staff and expenses.
</P>
<P>
   He also admitted that officials should not have hired as many
people as they did. Half of the new hires were in patient care,
partly a result of increased business at the hospitals. Most of the
rest were in finance and computer technology, to put in place
expensive but crucial upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   The organization spends $150,000 a month renting executive
offices near Candlestick Park, considered neutral ground between
the two institutions. Officials defend the expense, saying several
employees formerly located at both campuses have moved there,
freeing needed space.
</P>
<P>
   But many question whether projected savings from the merger were
ever realistic. Faculty members at both campuses also have
expressed doubts about management, and some have called for top
executives to step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't clear to me that good administration wouldn't cure
this whole problem,'' Melmon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
