<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9194 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-McKESSON-LAWSUITS-HNS     05-24 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-McKESSON-LAWSUITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG WHOLESALER FACES RAFT OF LAWSUITS OVER ACQUISITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Barely one month after McKesson HBOC Inc.
admitted to improperly recording its revenue, the San Francisco
company is fighting off a barrage of lawsuits, allegations of
financial fraud and questions from federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson, the nation's largest drug wholesaler, shocked
investors April 28 when it said a year-end audit found $42 million
in sales that were improperly recorded by HBOC, a health care
software company in Atlanta that McKesson bought in January.
</P>
<P>
   In its bombshell announcement, McKesson said the accounting mess
would force the company to restate its earnings over the past four
quarters and lower its profit outlook for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news crushed McKesson's healthy stock, which plunged 50
percent to $35. Within hours, the Fortune 100 company lost $9
billion in stock market value _ one of the most devastating one-
day losses for a company in Wall Street history.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, dozens of shareholders have filed lawsuits in
federal court in San Francisco and San Jose against McKesson.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action suits allege that top executives knowingly or
recklessly manipulated the company's finances and software sales
figures.
</P>
<P>
   One suit charged that McKesson Chairman Charles McCall, the
former chief executive of HBOC, and McKesson director Jay
Gilbertson, HBOC's former president and chief financial officer,
schemed to ``deceive the investing public'' by inflating revenue
figures. That led to the artificial boosting of HBOC's stock price
before McKesson bought the company, the suit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Because the merger was a $14 billion stock transaction, the two
shareholders ``had a motive to misstate the company's financial
results,'' says the lawsuit filed by attorney Justice Reed of
Schubert &AMP; Reed in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In November, shortly after the deal was announced, McCall owned
4.6 million shares of HBOC stock and held options on 3.6 million
HBOC shares that could be cashed in when the merger was completed,
according to the lawsuit. Also in November, Gilbertson bought
384,000 HBOC shares to be exercised as stock options, the suit
says.
</P>
<P>
   Several securities attorneys said the legal storm for McKesson
will worsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, the accounting shenanigans are rising to the
level of securities fraud,'' said William Audet, a San Jose lawyer
who represents investors in one lawsuit. ``When they admit they
`improperly recorded' revenue, those are industry buzzwords for
``Oops, we screwed up, and someone may have been cooking the
books.'''
</P>
<P>
   McKesson executives declined to comment on the fraud
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson _ founded as a drugstore in New York City in 1833 _
also faces the scrutiny of regulators. The U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission recently contacted the company to discuss the
accounting problems, a McKesson executive confirmed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received inquiries, and we're responding to their
questions,'' said Larry Kurtz, vice president of corporate
communications for McKesson.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz would not confirm or deny the precise details of the SEC's
inquiry. But legal and government sources close to the SEC said
that regulators have met with attorneys from Skadden, Arps, Slate,
Meagher &AMP; Flom, the high-powered New York law firm that represents
McKesson.
</P>
<P>
   The sources, who requested anonymity, said the SEC asked for
corporate financial papers, merger documents from McKesson's
acquisition of HBOC, audits of HBOC by Arthur Andersen &AMP; Co. and
audits of McKesson by Deloitte &AMP; Touche LLP.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Pacific Exchange in San Francisco is
investigating the options trading in McKesson stock during the
weeks prior to the McKesson/HBOC merger, said Dale Carlson, a
Pacific Exchange spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, McKesson is conducting its own investigation.
The company has hired Skadden Arps and forensic accountants at
PricewaterhouseCoopers to go over its books and accounting
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson hopes its internal investigation will be done by June,
but it could easily stretch beyond that date, Kurtz said.
</P>
<P>
   It would take a lot to shake McKesson. The corporate behemoth
posted $31 billion in sales last year and employs 20,000 people
worldwide. The company does business with thousands of hospitals,
pharmacies, doctors' groups and medical manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There appeared to be few danger signs in the deal McKesson-HBOC
deal. Wall Street analysts were high on McKesson's earnings outlook
and stock performance.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson had enjoyed several strong fiscal quarters. McKesson's
financial adviser, Bear Stearns, and HBOC's advisers, Morgan
Stanley and Arthur Andersen, all signed off on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in our due diligence for the merger suggested there
were any problems,'' Kurtz said. ``We were assisted by investment
bankers, accountants and legal counsel, and we were satisfied the
due diligence we conducted was appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one research firm, though, flagged problems at HBOC
well before the merger. The Center for Financial Research &AMP;
Analysis Inc. in Rockville, Md., warned investors in 1998 and 1997
that HBOC was using a legal but risky accounting method of posting
cash receipts from customers before HBOC actually got paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were booking revenue on software sales when they hadn't
collected the cash yet,'' said Christopher Teeters, the center
analyst who followed HBOC. ``And they were getting more and more
aggressive at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and securities lawyers also said that McKesson had been
dying to make a big acquisition that would strengthen its dominant
position in the health care services field. And HBOC, a
fast-growing software vendor and a high-flying stock on Wall
Street, seemed to fit the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``McKesson is a pretty conservative company with a sound
reputation, and they acquired a company in the health care software
industry, where there's a lot of fast and loose accounting,'' Reed
said. ``It's a cultural clash, and it really blew up in their
faces.''
</P>
</TEXT>
