<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      05-24 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Outdated Views on Ulcers Hinder Cures &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Though it had been well established that most peptic ulcers were
caused by a bacteria called Helicobacter pylori, or H. pylori, and
could be effectively treated with antibiotics, recent studies
showed that the information had not gotten out to ulcer sufferers
and that a large number of doctors were continuing to treat with
standard acid blockers only.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lack of awareness among physicians and consumers,''
Dr. Benjamin D. Gold, a professor at the Emory University School of
Medicine in Atlanta, said at the annual meeting of the American
Gastroenterological Association in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A study by Dr. Gold and other researchers for the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention found that more than half the 5,436
adults surveyed believed that ulcers were caused by stress and not
by a curable infection. This belief, the study concluded, may deter
people from seeking proper medical care for peptic ulcers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Cindy R. Friedman, a researcher with the CDC, said that even
though most doctors knew that H. pylori caused most ulcers, they
continued to prescribe acid-blocking therapy for first-time
patients. In one study, only 25 percent of the doctors prescribed
antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC estimates that about 10 percent of Americans suffer from
ulcers. Experts are not certain how H. pylori is spread. The
National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases
explains that the bacteria weakens the protective mucous coating of
the stomach and duodenum, and that weakening allows acid to get
through to the lining beneath. Both acid and the bacteria irritate
the lining and cause a sore or ulcer.
</P>
<P>
   Dull, gnawing pain is the most common symptom.
</P>
<P>
   More information on ulcers can be obtained from the CDC at (888)
698-5237.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What Stress Can Mean to Teen-Age Girls &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Many teen-agers experience stress, but the patterns of stress
girls encounter may leave them more vulnerable to depression than
those boys experience, according to a study that appears in the
current issue of the journal Child Development.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers interviewed 88 youths, ages 8 to 18, who were
receiving treatment at several mental health clinics in an effort
to link stressful experiences to depression. Their parents were
also interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gathered information regarding the events that caused
stress or problems in the children's lives over the last year,''
said Dr. Karen D. Rudolph, an assistant professor of psychology at
the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champagne and the lead author
of the study. ``We asked about peer and family relations, school
adjustment, health related problems and other stressful
circumstances. We then rated how stressful the events were.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that children between 13 and 18
experienced more stress than those between 8 and 12. Though boys
and girls experienced the same overall amount of stress, boys were
more likely to complain of stressful situations like doing poorly
in school, getting sick, moving to a new town, getting arrested for
stealing or other events unrelated to interpersonal problems.
</P>
<P>
   Girls, on the other hand, experienced most of their stress from
relationship problems, including fights with peers, siblings or
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls may have more intimate and close relationships than boys
do,'' Dr. Rudolph said. ``When something happens, it can be very
stressful and disruptive.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final phase of the study, researchers interviewed the
children to see whether they were experiencing anxiety or
depression.
</P>
<P>
   Girls reported more symptoms of depression in response to stress
than boys did. Girls' symptoms included feeling sad, feeling like
crying and feeling alone. Some also felt that nobody loved them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adolescents are faced with a lot of challenges they aren't
faced with earlier in life,'' Dr. Rudolph said.``Girls may be
socialized into a more nurturing role and may be more likely to be
involved with problems in their families or close relationships
with friends. This can lead to depression when these roles are
disrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
