<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE PANEL URGES CITIES TO PREPARE FOR Y2K WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a move to prepare cities and towns for the
century date change and potential computer glitches, President
Clinton's Council on Year 2000 Conversion launched a nationwide
campaign Monday aimed at government and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our greatest domestic risks for Year 2000-related failures are
at the local level,'' said John Koskinen, chairman of the council.
</P>
<P>
   Two communities, San Antonio and Clearwater, Fla., were cited as
examples of how business and government leaders can work to prevent
Year 2000, or Y2K, computer glitches that could affect utilities,
medical care and banking.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Barton, director of the Y2K compliance office with Frost
Bank in San Antonio, said the primary goal in that city's campaign
has been to build public trust that institutions and government are
prepared for potential problems on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts fear that computers and other devices
containing microchips programmed to recognize only the last two
digits of a year will fail or malfunction beginning year, when the
machines may assume it is 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Barton was one of seven business leaders who participated in a
news conference urging communities to plan for the Year 2000
conversion with a tool kit and information that is available from
the council at 888-USA-4-Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   ``From power and phone companies to banks and water utilities,
Americans want to know how the important local services upon which
they rely may be affected by computers' ability to process the
century date change,'' Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 national associations representing utility and
service providers are working with the council to help mid-sized
cities and smaller towns prepare for potential computer glitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many communities, service providers have been working hard
to keep citizens informed of their progress and the work that
remains,'' Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is not to cheerlead or create a false sense of
security,'' he added. ``Our goal is for participants to share
factual information about what's been done, what remains to be done
and what additional actions a community should take as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks and financial institutions appear prepared for Y2K
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, John Hawke Jr., the U.S. comptroller of the
currency, told the House Banking Committee that the banking
industry would come through the changes ``with flying colors.''
</P>
<P>
   The House passed the Year 2000 Readiness and Responsibility Act
to protect businesses from legal damages over any Y2K problems.
Similar legislation is pending in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, backed by the computer industry and business
groups, would limit punitive damage awards to $250,000 and make
plaintiffs wait 90 days after a Y2K failure before a lawsuit can be
filed.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups oppose any legislation that would protect
businesses against legitimate Y2K claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
