<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-IMPROVEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME IMPROVEMENT CLOSES ITS DOORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
HOME IMPROVEMENT 
Starring: Tim Allen, Patricia Richardson, Richard Karn 
On: ABC 
Time: Tuesday at 8 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Why do you bug me during football?'' Tim Taylor asks wife Jill
in a flashback scene from Tuesday's ``Home Improvement'' finale.
``Did I bother you during childbirth?''
</P>
<P>
   A sensitive fella, Tim. In an age of neo, he was defiantly and
unrepentantly paleo, the kind of guy who, his wife once observed,
``thinks that PBS is something a woman gets once a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet though Tim was not what you would call a '90s guy, ``Home
Improvement'' was indisputably one of the most popular sitcoms of
this decade. Tim Taylor, the not-quite-handyman host of ``Tool
Time'' and father of three played by Tim Allen, became a kind of
Everydad for our time. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was because ``Home Improvement'' was one from the
heartland in an era when every other show seems to be set in
Manhattan or Los Angeles, or because Allen played Taylor as a guy
who usually managed to do the right thing by his family while also
remaining true to his Neanderthal essence. It also helped
enormously that Jill, played by Patricia Richardson, was so quick
with a field-leveling comeback. (Her rejoinder to the football
remark was ``No, but you bothered me during conception.'')
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute finale is chockablock with clips that remind us
that, within the formulaic limitations at which even Richardson
admits she chafed, ``Home Improvement'' could be as good as it
gets.
</P>
<P>
   It also flexed a lot of ratings muscle over the years: In fact,
in 1993, a certain NBC sitcom named ``Seinfeld'' moved to Thursday
nights after it proved unable to compete with ABC's ``Home
Improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   The clips are sandwiched around a final episode that poses some
questions: Will the family move to Indiana so Jill can take a great
new job? Will Al Borland (Richard Karn) go through with his
wedding? Will we finally get to see the face of Wilson (Earl
Hindman), next-door neighbor and dispenser of Zen-like wisdom to
the Taylors?
</P>
<P>
   After eight years during which ``Home Improvement'' won 10
People's Choice awards, many viewers may have trouble letting go,
but Richardson was more than ready to see it end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely the time,'' she said during a conference call
with TV critics. ``We had taken that family where it was going to
go. ... The writers were still finding things to write about, but
it was getting harder and harder.''
</P>
<P>
   That was apparent to viewers. Still, we never looked to ``Home
Improvement'' for cutting-edge, state-of-the-art comedy. It never
had the cachet of ``Frasier'' or ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   As the finale reminds us, the humor of ``Home Improvement'' was
broader. It painted in big, cartoony strokes that fit Allen's
outsize personality. We could laugh at his obsession with cars
(``I'm addicted to cars,'' Taylor confessed. ``I'm thinking of
checking into the Henry Ford Clinic''), the mishaps he caused on
``Tool Time'' with his misplaced confidence in his abilities, or
his mangling of the advice imparted by Wilson, the sage neighbor
whose face was always partly obscured by the backyard fence.
</P>
<P>
   The husband-wife scenes between Tim and Jill edged close to
emotional truth at times, as when Jill had a hysterectomy this
season, but the show was careful never to stray too far from its
laughs-first formula. ``Tim evolved over the years, but he can't
get too evolved or there's no more show,'' observed Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Improvement'' was among the most successful of the '90s
sitcoms based on the persona of a standup comedian, a genre that
also included ``Seinfeld,'' ``Roseanne,'' and ``The Drew Carey
Show.'' But in an era where ``edgy'' is the most coveted of
adjectives, ``Home Improvement'' was never that, which meant fewer
Emmy nominations and less critical approbation than it deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pigeonholed into a family entertainment,'' said
Richard Karn, who played Al Borland, Taylor's sidekick on ``Tool
Time.'' ``We were never taken seriously'' by the entertainment
industry. The upside, Karn said, is that ``There was definitely a
connection with the audience right away. They got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Richardson and Karn are disappointed by some aspects of
their experience on ``Home Improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson made it clear that she wishes Jill had had more room
to grow rather than remaining Tim's foil, and said she had to
constantly pressure the show's mostly male writers to give Jill her
due. Pointing to Helen Hunt on ``Mad About You,'' Richardson said:
``It became her show equally. That didn't happen in my case.'' But
she said there were also satisfying episodes, such as ``the
wonderful show where I was attracted to the other guy.''
</P>
<P>
   While emphasizing that she had ``a really good experience doing
the show'' and that it has ``given me many gifts,'' Richardson said
she wishes the show had been ``more real'' in depicting family
tensions, like ``Roseanne'' or ``Everybody Loves Raymond.'' ``That
was what I wanted our show to be more of,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some have fretted that the end of ``Home Improvement'' signals
the demise of the family sitcom genre, but Richardson isn't buying.
She says family programs will continue to thrive if, like
``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' their humorous takes on family life
are grounded in complicated reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad family shows are in trouble, and they should be,''
said Richardson. ``Shows that present family life as something like
vanilla are on their way out, because they're not what people know
family life is like and they're boring to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Karn said that Al's character development was shortchanged by
the show's writers. ``He really did become the whipping boy. It got
to the point where he was there for fat jokes and slams on his
mother,'' he said. ``I felt a strong need to keep the character's
dignity and rise above that if I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen was not available for an interview, but in January, he
told TV writers in Pasadena, Calif. he wanted to leave the show
while it was still popular and of high quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``When is it ever the right time to shut the door on something
that has this much love and care?'' said Allen. ``I watched Michael
Jordan, and I watched `Seinfeld,' and I realized there's just no
good time to move on. But it's our show, and this is when we want
to call it quits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
