<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WEIGHT-PILLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIET PILLS POPULAR DESPITE A TAINTED PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Pa.)   (af)  
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The weight-loss drug Xenical, approved last month, had barely
reached the market when Web sites selling the drug sprang up to tap
into the intense consumer demand that accompanies the debut of
anything marketed to make people lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   But in their eagerness for pills to help them slim down, people
may conveniently overlook something that doctors remember all too
well: weight-loss drugs in general have have a rather alarming
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very checkered past,'' said Dr. Steven Heymsfield,
deputy director of the obesity research center at St. Luke's
Roosevelt Hospital in Manhattan. Although Heymsfield does prescribe
weight-loss medications for some of his patients, he said, ``I
believe we should use these drugs judiciously. If you forget the
past you're doomed, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the popular drug combination known as fen-phen
was blamed for damaged heart valves, and two drugs that had been
part of it were taken off the market. (A third, the appetite
suppressant phentermine, is still available.)
</P>
<P>
   During the 1930s, about 100,000 Americans took a chemical,
dinitrophenol, which prevented food energy from being turned into
fat. ``The energy is just liberated as heat,'' Heymsfield said.
``You sort of become a firefly.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, dinitrophenol was poisonous, causing blindness
and even death.
</P>
<P>
   ``In days gone by, thyroid hormone was very common,'' said Dr.
Jules Hirsch, an obesity expert and senior physician at the
Rockefeller University Hospital in Manhattan. It boosted
metabolism, and made people lose weight. But the excess hormone
disrupted heart rhythm and caused muscle weakness. ``It became
discredited, as it should have been,'' Hirsch said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Albert Stunkard, director emeritus of the weight and eating
disorders program at the University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia
said, ``The first drugs that were used that turned out to be
effective were amphetamines.'' These stimulants, introduced in the
1950s, suppressed appetite and may have boosted metabolism.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were used, and then abused,'' Stunkard said. ``But
they're actually very effective, and you can lose a lot of weight.
Long, continued use had bad effects, however, like making people
paranoid. And when they stopped, they became depressed and regained
the weight. Congressional hearings on amphetamine abuse were held
in the 1960s, and after that you weren't allowed to use them for
weight loss.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the strangest weight loss crazes was human chorionic
gonadotropin, a hormone produced by pregnant women. During the
1960s, injections of the hormone were said to stimulate rapid
weight loss _ if they were combined with a strict, low-fat,
low-calorie diet. Some patients were also told that if they cheated
on the diet, the hormone would actually cause rapid weight gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a scam,'' said Heymsfield.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of past debacles, he said, weight loss drugs are
studied longer and tested more carefully, and doctors tend to have
more confidence in them. The only ones on the market besides
phentermine are Xenical and Meridia.
</P>
<P>
   Xenical, also called orlistat, blocks the intestine from
absorbing about 30 percent of the fat that a person eats, and
studies have shown that people who take it may lose from 5 percent
to 10 percent of their body weight in a year. Meridia, or
sibutramine, is an appetite suppressant approved in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Both drugs are supposed to be used along with a reduced-calorie
diet, and only by people who meet the technical definition of
obese, meaning that they weigh 30 percent more than they should, or
20 percent more, with complications like diabetes or high blood
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Both drugs have side effects. Meridia can raise blood pressure,
and Xenical can cause diarrhea or even fecal incontinence if a
person eats too much fat while taking it.
</P>
<P>
   But people still clamor for them, and Heymsfield said he
prescribes them if he cannot talk a patient out of the idea, or if
diet and exercise have simply not worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do help people under certain circumstances,'' he said.
But, he emphasized, the drugs do not work well without diet and
exercise, and researchers do not know whether people who are helped
by them will be able to keep the weight off in the long run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1641EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9223 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOUSEKETEER-BANDLEADE     05-24 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOUSEKETEER-BANDLEADER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CHILD STAR JOHNNY CRAWFORD HEADS  TIMELESS  ORCHESTRA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL BIDWELL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's as if you'd stepped back into another era.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen musicians with slicked-back hair, splendid in white
dinner jackets, are playing the bouncy dance music popular during
the tough years of the Depression, when the poor grew poorer and
the rich ... well, the rich continued to party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever see a dream walking? Well, I did,'' croons the
orchestra leader through a megaphone, wearing tails and top hat.
``Did you ever see a dream talking? Well, I did...''
</P>
<P>
   The pages slide off your mental calendar, just like the
flashbacks in those old black-and-white movies ... 1937 ... 1934
... 1928 ...
</P>
<P>
   You've fallen under the spell of former Mouseketeer, former
child actor Johnny Crawford, who in the past decade has become one
of the premier society crooners and orchestra leaders in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can play any kind of music the people who hire us want,''
said Crawford, 53, who seemingly carries an encyclopedia of musical
knowledge in his head. ``But my favorite is the music of the '20s
and '30s. It's music not everybody knows, but once they hear it,
they seem to like it.''
</P>
<P>
   They do, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Crawford's Dance Orchestra was chosen to evoke a 1923
atmosphere at the Regal Biltmore Hotel's 75th anniversary last
fall, then picked to give vintage glitter to Gov. Gray Davis'
inaugural ball in January.
</P>
<P>
   So sought-after for celebrity parties and benefits it's booked
six months in advance, his orchestra will play a Fourth of July
concert of between-the-wars music at the Los Angeles County Museum
of Art for the fourth year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The what-era-is-it uncertainty Crawford's music evokes is what
won the orchestra a featured spot in Sony-TriStar's ``The
Thirteenth Floor,'' a sci-fi adventure flick scheduled to hit
theaters Friday. In the film, directed by Josef Rusnak, a computer
guru time-travels back to 1937 via computer chip, then turns up
dead. It's up to his assistant to go back to that era to look for
clues to the murder.
</P>
<P>
   For the film, Rusnak used lots of digital manipulation to make
present-day Los Angeles look as it did in the late '30s. So getting
just the right music to evoke the era _ an elegant dance orchestra
playing at a ritzy hotel, a smaller swing group playing
down-and-dirty for a dance marathon _ added just the right
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get an almost-documentary-style atmosphere; that
was very crucial,'' Rusnak said. ``And Johnny is the most authentic
guy doing this music. It's like a time warp to listen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusnak said Crawford not only suggested the songs used in the
movie and provided the arrangements, but also offered
'30s-appropriate advice on everything from the demeanor of the
waiters and chorus girls to helping choose authentic period dancers
for other scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me so much background information about the style of
the era, how people behaved,'' said Rusnak. ``He became a very dear
friend and adviser for me. I got an expert on this movie without
even knowing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Swing dancers can strut their stuff to Crawford's tunes on the
movie's soundtrack CD, which also will be released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to sit still when Crawford's orchestra is playing,
said Bill Vestal, producer of the Fourth of July concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our audience gets very frustrated because there's no place for
them to dance,'' he said. ``But we're all dancing backstage.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a reaction Crawford relishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This music is so old, it's new,'' the orchestra leader said.
``It's fresh, it's happy, it's melodic and a lot of other things
that young people aren't used to hearing. When people hear it, they
want to dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I love most when I'm conducting is turning around and
seeing the dance floor packed. That's what this music was written
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, whose grandfather was a Tin Pan Alley song plugger and
music publisher in the 1920s, said he was born with a love of
vintage music, but it took him a long time to parlay that interest
into a career.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take him long to get on stage, though. His father was
an actor at Columbia Studios, and both his parents were active in
community theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get on stage with them,'' Crawford recalls. ``I
loved the curtain calls, the people clapping.''
</P>
<P>
   He played a number of roles in movies and on TV, but fame really
began with a song.
</P>
<P>
   An imitation of tearful '50s crooner Johnny Ray won Crawford a
spot as one of the Mouseketeers on ``The Mickey Mouse Club'' in
1956. He left to take the role of young Mark McCain on ``The
Rifleman,'' a 1958-63 TV western.
</P>
<P>
   While he played roles in 15 movies and a dozen plays, he always
seemed to return to his first love: music and dancing.
</P>
<P>
   But because it was the early '60s, the time of the teen idol, he
became a singer. Signed by Del-Fi Records in 1961, he had hits with
``Cindy's Birthday,'' ``Rumors'' and ``Patti Ann.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Hollywood High School in 1964, he
continued to appear in shows ranging from ``Bonanza'' to ``The
Donna Reed Show.'' Armed with riding and roping skills learned on
``The Rifleman,'' he rode the professional rodeo circuit for two
years until he was drafted into the Army, where he spent two years
making training films. Discharged, he returned to acting and
continued his singing career between movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But every once in a while, I'd pull out one of the old 78s and
listen to Al Jolson and Paul Whiteman,'' Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   He met Playboy magazine founder Hugh Hefner, and, on his first
visit to the Playboy Mansion, discovered Hefner had a similar love
for old movie musicals and pre-big band music.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, there were these old, scratchy records of
dance bands from the 1920s playing,'' Crawford said. ``A light went
on in my head! It was like I had stumbled onto an abandoned gold
mine. I was so excited!''
</P>
<P>
   Another acquaintance suggested that he go to New York, where
band leader Vince Giordano needed a tenor to front for his
Nighthawks Orchestra. Crawford took the job and discovered a whole
new career, which included singing at President George Bush's
inaugural ball.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano played the same music Crawford had heard in all those
'30s musicals _ the same music for which his grandfather had left
him trunkfuls of arrangements. After two years in New York,
Crawford returned to Los Angeles in 1988, determined to form his
own orchestra and play the kind of music he loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like the '40s music, which is a little too mellow,''
Crawford explained. ``It's syncopated, a little too exuberant.
Mellow bands really didn't want people to dance to their music;
they wanted people to sit and listen. But the bands that lasted
were dance bands.''
</P>
<P>
   He hoped others would fall in love with the music, too, but the
first people he had to win over were the musicians he auditioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them were used to playing `cool,' to improvising,'' he
said. ``They were afraid of being too corny. This music was corny,
but it was sincere. In those ('30s) days, musicians used to play
with more feeling, more style. I didn't want my guys to do it like
they were making fun of the music. I had to find musicians who
would play it like they meant it.''
</P>
<P>
   Every good dance band had a singer, and Crawford fills that
spot, as well as conducting and writing arrangements. His pleasant
tenor voice _ which occasionally dips into baritone range _ is a
perfect match for the music the band plays.
</P>
<P>
   On stage, the former child actor becomes a character again, an
amalgam of a handful of dapper leading men: part suave Fred
Astaire, a dash of ``Thin Man'' detective William Powell, a bit of
mammy singer Al Jolson, a soupcon of French romanceur Maurice
Chevalier.
</P>
<P>
   The character, and the orchestra, soon made a name for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Even charging $8,000 a night, Crawford found himself so in
demand he was turning down gigs. So, he began putting together
smaller groups for weddings, bar mitzvahs, retirement dinners and
other events, forming Johnny Crawford Music Inc. to act as a sort
of clearinghouse for bookings for local musicians. His wife,
Charlotte, helps run the business from their Hollywood Hills home.
</P>
<P>
   With a touch of gray at the temples but the same boyish grin,
Crawford's come a long way from a little kid wearing mouse ears.
And he sees no end in sight to his success, as long as people like
to dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so lucky to be doing this,'' he said with a wide grin.
``I got to know a period of music that comes from maybe the peak of
craftsmanship. And I'm actually making a living in show business in
a way that nobody else is. I've provided my own acting job, and it
just gets better and better.'' &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
