<HEADLINE>
DELAYED MISSION TO DOCK SHUTTLE WITH SPACE STATION FOR FIRST TIME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shuttle astronauts blast off for the U.S.-led international
space station this week to dock with the fledgling outpost for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's 10-day mission will launch at 6:48 a.m. EDT Thursday
from NASA's Kennedy Space Center in Florida. It was delayed a week
so hail damage to the shuttle's fuel tank could be repaired.
</P>
<P>
   The flight is the first to the unstaffed outpost since shuttle
astronauts joined the first two components, the Russian Zarya and
American Unity modules, last December. This mission was added to
station assembly plans a year ago and symbolizes the difficulties
that Russia's financial problems added to the six-year construction
effort.
</P>
<P>
   The station, at this stage of assembly, was never intended for a
shuttle docking.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia's funding problems stalled production of the
station's 21-ton, 43-foot-long crew compartment. Known formally as
the Russian service module, the compartment is scheduled to be
launched in late November from Central Asia. It is 19 months behind
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The first resident crew initially was scheduled for May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   With launch date for the Russian module slipping last May, NASA
altered plans to wait until after the service module's arrival at
the new station to launch a shuttle supply mission.
</P>
<P>
   Station managers decided to add a shuttle flight ahead of the
crew compartment. The mission would lighten the cargo loads on
subsequent missions, allow visiting astronauts to make repairs and
use the shuttle's propulsion system to boost the station to a
higher altitude if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   It also forced a major change in mission planning to permit a
shuttle docking without the massive service module and its more
sophisticated flight control systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the biggest deals we had to decide on this
flight, ... exactly how to attach the shuttle to the station,''
said NASA's Wayne Hale, the mission's lead flight director.
</P>
<P>
   On paper there were two options.
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery crew could rendezvous with the new station, then
extend the shuttle's 50-foot robot arm to grab the eight-story
outpost and position the docking mechanism on the Unity module for
a linkup. In December, shuttle astronauts caught up with the
previously launched Zarya module and used the robot arm to link it
with the Unity module.
</P>
<P>
   The second option was to adjust their procedures and dock
directly, relying on the less-sophisticated propulsion and flight
control systems of the Zarya module to hold the complex steady.
</P>
<P>
   Mission planners chose the latter option after an engineering
analysis revealed difficulties stabilizing the 68,000-pound Zarya
and Unity modules in the robot arm's grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Several changes have been made in the flight control system
aboard Zarya as well as to the shuttle's rendezvous procedures.
</P>
<P>
   First, Russian engineers have developed a computer software
patch that will prevent Zarya's more powerful steering thrusters
from firing during the linkup. An inadvertent discharge by a large
jet during the initial docking operation could jolt Discovery out
of its berth.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Zarya module's low thrust jets, which will be
activated to hold the station in position for the docking, must be
quickly deactivated after the linkup with commands issued from a
Russian ground control station. The unfinished service module is
designed to handle that task automatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have analyzed this to death. It became clear very early
that the better way to approach this was to dock,'' said Hale.
``With the small thrusters we don't have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of rising slowly toward the station from below for the
docking, the shuttle crew will descend gradually toward the station
from several hundred feet above. The flight path was altered so
that the shuttle would not block antennas on the station awaiting
the crucial commands from the ground that will switch off Zarya's
thrusters after the docking.
</P>
<P>
   Timing will be crucial because of the need to execute the linkup
over a Russian ground station, a constraint shuttle pilots mastered
by docking nine times with Russia's Mir space station between 1995
and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery commander Kent Rominger and co-pilot Rick Husband will
have four minutes to maneuver through the approach in order to dock
on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be a very interesting rendezvous and docking,''
said Rominger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of our training is for the problems that could
occur. In some of our training, when we didn't dock, we bounced off
very late in the game,'' Rominger said of the elaborate ground
simulations involved in the preparations. ``Part of the reason is
that (Zarya) was never intended to be the motion control system to
support the docking. Knock on wood. I hope we won't have to use any
of that bounce off training,'' Rominger said.
</P>
<P>
   With Discovery docked, astronauts Tammy Jernigan and Dan Barry
will do a seven-hour spacewalk, primarily to install cranes on the
outside of the outpost. The hand-operated cranes will be used by
future station crews to move and install large storage batteries
and electronics boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts plan to move nearly two tons of cargo, including
laptop computers, printers, cameras, clothing, medical supplies,
oxygen canisters, drinking water and sound-dampening insulation
from Discovery to storage areas on the station. The gear will be
needed by the first resident crew expected to arrive early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Two high-priority repair efforts are planned as well.
</P>
<P>
   Working inside the Zarya module, the shuttle crew will replace
18 faulty ampere meters that are causing a half-dozen storage
batteries in the station's electrical power system to slowly
degrade.
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery crew will also attempt to restore full use of a
U.S. satellite communications system that allows NASA mission
control teams to monitor station activities directly from mission
control facilities in Houston. A degradation in the signal was
detected in March.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
