<HEADER>
A9231 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-24 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LEGISLATURE REACHES BOREDOM, FRENZY STAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Anticipation, disappointment, frustration,
anger, humor, even (occasionally) elation. All are emotions that
quickly become familiar to people on and around the legislative
roller coaster.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is boredom, mind-numbing boredom, a condition that
often consumes all others and can almost make statehouse veterans
temporarily forget whether their programs are up or down.
</P>
<P>
   The recent Senate showdown that saw the death of the hate-crimes
bill was riveting drama. But those moments in the legislative
process are rare. Much more common, particularly this late in a
session, are days like the one last week, when senators, with
little or no debate, approved legislation to stiffen the penalty
for fleeing from a police officer _ and 50 other bills.
</P>
<P>
   All this was done in the space of about five very long hours. It
was not the place to be for someone who had stayed up a bit too
late the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the bills _ on subjects as varied as injured workers,
air conditioning contractors and outboard motors _ were passed with
little discussion, let alone debate. Deals, if necessary, had been
privately worked out in advance, as they are on most bills that
pass through the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   There was a great deal of trust, on the part of the bill
sponsors, in the House members or lobbyists who had brought them
the bills and also on the part of the other senators in the bill
sponsors. Legislators don't have time to read most of the thousands
of bills and amendments they vote on each session, although many of
those measures contain hidden time bombs that occasionally explode
during a re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer volume of legislation also hides numerous special
interest provisions that most Texans could very well do without.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the bills that passed through the Senate that day still
won't clear all the necessary hurdles and become law. Many probably
shouldn't. Does anyone, for example, really think that a felon who
has just held up a convenience store will worry about an extra slap
on the wrist if he thinks he can outrun the police car in his
rearview mirror?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that bill, if it were to become law and if anyone actually
learned about it, would discourage an occasional speeder from
trying to outrun the blue lights and jeopardizing the safety of
other motorists. But for most practical purposes the measure
probably belongs in the it's-the-thought-that-counts category.
</P>
<P>
   A few bills actually had major statewide significance.
</P>
<P>
   One was a constitutional amendment, which will be on the
November ballot, to clarify how the offices of governor and
lieutenant governor would be filled if Gov. George W. Bush is
elected president next year.
</P>
<P>
   There really wasn't much mystery that Lt. Gov. Rick Perry would
be the next governor. The real question was who would succeed Perry
in the No. 2 job. If voters approve the amendment, the 31 state
senators will pick one of their own to complete Perry's lieutenant
governor's term.
</P>
<P>
   Senators also voted to send another _ and probably more
controversial _ constitutional amendment to the voters. This one
would allow a former spouse's wages to be garnisheed for overdue
alimony.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people may be surprised, but, yes, Texas does allow
alimony now, but only under very limited circumstances. The
Legislature approved it four years ago as part of a welfare-reform
package, and voters will soon get to decide whether to give it some
new teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Although only two senators voted against it, the alimony-related
measure sparked the only semilively debate of the day, which ended
with this quip from Sen. Royce West, D-Dallas: ``Do you remember
that song, It's Cheaper to Keep Her?''
</P>
<P>
   About the only other measure to attract any significant
attention was a bill by Sen. Mike Moncrief, D-Fort Worth, to allow
that city to use a portion of its local hotel and motel tax to
finance a luxury hotel near its downtown convention center.
</P>
<P>
   Some Houston senators, fearing some language in the measure
could hurt Houston's new baseball stadium project, raised enough
questions to prompt Moncrief to postpone a vote on his bill for a
few hours. That gave the Houston senators time to call home and be
assured the bill didn't affect their stadium _ and jeopardize their
political futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Fort Worth thank you,'' Moncrief said after the
bill was revived and senators routinely approved it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not all the people of Fort Worth. The community
leaders and developers who supported the bill, however, were very
grateful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
