</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By C.CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cosmic Collision
</P>
<P>
   Q. Pluto sometimes crosses the orbit of Neptune, suggesting to
me that they might collide at some point. Should I worry?
</P>
<P>
   A. No, in the opinion of Dr. Bryan G. Marsden, associate
director for planetary sciences at the Harvard-Smithsonian Center
for Astrophysics in Cambridge, Mass. Their closest approach is not
that close, he said, but about as far as the distance between
Uranus and the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   One reason they cannot pass any closer is that Neptune goes
around in its orbit three times in the time that Pluto goes around
twice, he said. This exact relationship is called a resonance.
</P>
<P>
   Another such relationship, called the Kozae resonance, provides
an added protection, Marsden said. The orbit of Pluto is not in the
same plane as Neptune's but is inclined to it at an angle of about
17 degrees. When Pluto is closest to the Sun, it is about as far
away from Neptune's orbital plane as it can be, and there is close
to the maximum separation when the two planets are crossing at the
same distance from the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the planets didn't have these protections, a collision
would have happened long ago and we would never have known about
Pluto's existence,'' Marsden said. ``Perhaps over hundreds of
millions of years they could get out of resonance, but that is a
long enough period that we wouldn't have to worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Pluto is not alone in the Kozae resonance; at least 50 other
objects in orbit around the Sun, called Plutinos, enjoy the same
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by postal mail to
Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to:
Question(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9238 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WEIGHT-MORPH-ART-     05-24 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WEIGHT-MORPH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODY COMPUTER SHOWS SHAPE OF THINGS TO COME 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ERIC NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have seen the future _ and I prefer the past. Or is it the
other way around?
</P>
<P>
   The glimpses of what was and what could be came courtesy of a
recent visit to a ``body-morphing station.'' The computerized gizmo
is not unlike a fun-house mirror that distorts your image until you
appear ridiculously thin or grotesquely fat. But here the goal was
not idle amusement but education (OK, it was really a way to help
shill a new product, but we'll get to that later).
</P>
<P>
   The morphing station, which is available only at news media
events, may eventually find its way into malls. To use one, you
start by having someone else enter your weight and height to
determine your body mass index _ or BMI, a measure of weight in
relation to height _ while a camera records your image.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the fun part. The software allows you to shrink your
image to show what you might look like if you lost 15 percent of
your weight or, if you dare, expand it to show a 30 percent gain.
Then it tells you how your chances of contracting various
weight-related maladies _ heart disease, diabetes and high blood
pressure _ shift with the changes.
</P>
<P>
   Being a person of moderation (whatever else my BMI, described as
borderline problematic, might suggest), I opted to be blown up by a
mere 20 percent. In a flash, the screen showed what the future
might hold if I were to make too many trips to the ice cream parlor
and not enough to the gym.
</P>
<P>
   My cheeks swelled, my jowls seemed to droop and the stripes on
my shirt looked like they were trying to escape from one another.
More unsettling, all my disease-risk rates shot up significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Then I had them shrink the original me by 10 percent, and
listened as the dietitian noted with approval the improvement in my
disease statistics. I was too busy, though, watching the thinner,
vaguely familiar figure from the past looking out at me from the
screen. It looked like someone I went to school with.
</P>
<P>
   The machines are being used by the pharmaceutical company
Hoffmann-La Roche to help promote its new weight-loss drug,
Xenical.
</P>
<P>
   I may be taking the wrong attitude to the whole thing. The
dietitians say they generally use the machines to show people how
they would look if they lost weight, not gained it. It is an
incentive, in other words, not a threat. So that slim fellow I was
looking at could well be my future.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the morphing station will print out pictures of both. I
know which one I am more likely to hang on the refrigerator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
