<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IOWA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA REPORTER WILL BE BUSH'S PRIMARY OBSTACLE AND TEST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In planning a presidential campaign, one of the
first steps for a serious candidate is ascending Mount Yepsen.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush is no different.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime during Bush's first, brief campaign visit to Iowa next
month, it's a good bet that the Texas governor will seek to find
time to make the climb.
</P>
<P>
   As chief political reporter for the Des Moines Register, Iowa's
dominant newspaper, David Yepsen is a towering figure on the road
to the Iowa caucuses, traditionally the first important test for
White House aspirants.
</P>
<P>
   He is _ the candidates, their counselors and media mavens agree
_ a singular journalistic figure in the early presidential
contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anyone who comes close,'' said Cheryl
Arvidson, senior writer at the Freedom Forum and an acquaintance of
Yepsen's since their days at the University of Iowa 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``David is really recognized as the most knowledgeable, most
perceptive Iowa reporter when it comes to the presidential
caucuses,'' said Eric Woolson, who was once a competitor while
covering politics for the Waterloo Courier and then a source as
press secretary to recently retired Gov. Terry Branstad. Woolson is
now spokesman for Bush in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Even before their anticipated sit-down, Yepsen has assessed the
monumental expectations for Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a little too early for the governor to be writing
his inaugural address,'' Yepsen said in a recent column. ``There
are things about Bush that bring to mind President John Connally,
President John Glenn and President Edward Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yepsen recalled former President Bush's intimate attention to
Iowa in his first White House run in 1980 and his victory in the
caucuses that year over front-running Ronald Reagan, who barely
deigned to fly over the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son, you better remember that the next time one of your
high-paid consultants says you can win this thing sitting on your
behind in Austin,'' Yepsen wrote in his characteristically
down-to-earth style.
</P>
<P>
   It was not lost on Bush and his advisers that through the six
sets of caucuses that Yepsen has covered, he has often been the
first person to publicly point out weaknesses in campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Yepsen, however, wears his stature and quadrennial celebrity
modestly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certainly other reporters around here who cover this
game,'' Yepsen said.
</P>
<P>
   The only name, however, usually offered as a runner-up to Yepsen
in journalistic influence is Mike Glover, the highly regarded Iowa
capitol reporter for The Associated Press. He and Yepsen often
appear together on a public-affairs program on Iowa public
television.
</P>
<P>
   Yepsen takes a matter-of-fact approach to his position and the
consequent dealings with candidates and their staffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a job to do. I have a job to do,'' Yepsen said. ``I
cover this game, and so they want to be covered, and they also want
to get their message through.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't me. If anybody else was sitting in this job, it would
be them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yepsen does have the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just so uniquely dominant because the Register is
uniquely dominant,'' said Mike McCurry, who before his recent stint
as White House press secretary handled a string of losing
Democratic presidential contenders (then-Senator Glenn in 1984;
Arizona Gov. Bruce Babbitt, now the Interior secretary, in 1988;
and Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska in 1992).
</P>
<P>
   Local television coverage of presidential politics in Iowa is
generally spotty and superficial.
</P>
<P>
   More intense local television coverage traditionally doesn't
kick in until the campaign moves on to New Hampshire, where
Manchester-based WMUR is the only network-affiliated station in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   WMUR's Scott Spradling this week offered a cautionary
Yepsen-esque assessment of possible weaknesses in Bush's campaign,
including his trouble so far getting his school voucher and hefty
tax-cut plans through the Texas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Yepsen's view is also valued by newspaper and magazine
journalists from around the country and the world who troop to
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the guy whom everyone turns to make an assessment of the
candidates,'' McCurry said. Over the years, Yepsen has been quoted
in a number of Chronicle articles about Iowa politics.
</P>
<P>
   Yepsen is most sought after, however, by the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The approach was always the same,'' McCurry said. ``To haul
him down to the Savery (Hotel) coffee show and get him there and
have coffee and eggs with the guy running for president of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just sits there and pulls out his notebook and listens to
the future leader of the free world try out his stuff,'' McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
