<HEADER>
A9258 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLANCY-HORNER-TEX     05-24 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLANCY-HORNER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENLISTED MAN: CLANCY LENDS BESTSELLER STATUS TO A HERO'S STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Tom Clancy's admiration for military heroes is genuine.
</P>
<P>
   The bestselling author's novels and nonfiction books celebrate
men who believe in decisive action when American shores and/or
foreign interests are threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence also can be seen in his own back yard, literally.
</P>
<P>
   The man owns a tank.
</P>
<P>
   But the real passion is revealed when Clancy, 52, talks about
retired Air Force Gen. Chuck Horner, co-author of ``Every Man a
Tiger'' (Putnam, $27.95), the current Clancy bestseller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a minstrel, and I write about warriors,'' Clancy croons,
his usually clipped, harsh voice suddenly turning soft. ``That man
is a real warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Knock it off,'' orders Horner. The trim, 63-year-old is seated
on a low couch on the other side of the living room in a luxurious
suite at The Mansion on Turtle Creek where the duo has paused
momentarily during a whirlwind national tour promoting ``Every Man
a Tiger.'' ``Don't listen to this guy. He doesn't know what he's
talking about,'' quips Horner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crap,'' Clancy snaps, stubbing out one half-smoked cigarette
and lighting another. ``You're a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So you say,'' Horner says, sighing and rolling his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn right, that's what I say.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy and Horner are a bit more agreeable when the subject
turns to how they teamed up to write the book, which uses Horner's
distinguished Air Force career as a framework to teach readers
about problems and changes in the military approach to national
defense in the past four decades. Horner, who concluded his
military service designing and directing the Coalition air assault
during Desert Storm, wanted to write his memoirs focusing on how
lessons learned in the Vietnam debacle enabled the Coalition to
crush Saddam Hussein's Iraqi forces. Like most fledgling authors,
though, he didn't know how to get published.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard that he was working on a book, so I got him in touch
with my agent,'' says Clancy, adding that he and Horner had not yet
met at the time. ``They talked, and then my agent calls and tells
me I ought to get involved in the project.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy, with a long string of fiction bestsellers, already had
written six nonfiction books about military history and strategy,
including one with retired Army Gen. Fred Franks. He said he is
occasionally moved to write military history, ``because the public
schools are crap. They don't teach history there anymore.
Geography, either. You can't find a kid in a public school who can
find Belgium on a map. Me, I've been a historian since I was 8, 9
years old. So I try to put it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Horner and Clancy got together. Within 10 minutes, Clancy
claims, he knew they were friends for life and would write a great
book together.
</P>
<P>
   They disagree, again, on how the book was written. Clancy says
he simply served as editor, asking Horner questions and, sometimes,
forcing the much-decorated fighter pilot to relive moments he'd
sooner have forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not true at all,'' Horner insists. ``Tom Clancy is a genius.
He crafted the whole thing. My concern was that the book should be
entertaining, not boring. It wouldn't be a good book if people
glanced at a page or two and put it down.''
</P>
<P>
   From the opening scenes, when Iraq overruns Kuwait and Horner is
summoned by Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf to brief President George Bush
on U.S. air readiness for response, ``Every Man a Tiger'' brings
readers into planning sessions and bomber cockpits from peacetime
Lakenheath Air Force Base in England to the Vietnam jungles.
Clancy's third-person narration links first-person recollections
from Horner. The Horner/Clancy team doesn't spare criticism for
military blunders, and it emphasizes Horner's personal faith in
God, country and family without lathering on too much emotional
treacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because this is history,'' Clancy notes. ``We had to
put a lot of Chuck in here. Readers need to understand that most of
our military leaders are gifted, solid men. But Chuck is always
honest. When you read this book, you know it's for real.''
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Horner wanted an entertaining book, Clancy says he has
his own yardstick for whether ``Every Man a Tiger'' is a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how much it sells,'' Clancy snaps. ``That's why you
write books, so a lot of people will read them. I've learned
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In light of his own success, it's hard to recall that Tom Clancy
was an absolute unknown just 15 years ago. The owner of an
independent insurance business, the military-obsessed Clancy _ who
never served in the armed forces _ managed to churn out a novel in
his spare time. Based on a failed 1975 defection attempt by a
Soviet naval officer, ``The Hunt for Red October'' was eventually
published in 1984 by the tiny Naval Institute Press. Someone,
however, gave a copy to President Ronald Reagan, who loved the book
and touted it during press briefings. ``Red October'' rocketed up
the bestseller list and eventually was made into a hugely
successful movie. Clancy gave up the insurance business.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't take bestseller status for granted. Fans who
write to Clancy in care of his publisher often receive personal
replies, especially if they have technical questions about one of
his books.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta respond to the fans,'' Clancy says. ``You interest
somebody enough for him to ask a good question, well, maybe it
deserves a good answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Clancy and Horner hope readers find questions in, and get
answers from, ``Every Man a Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is about leadership,'' Horner says. ``It's about
how common sense, planning and valuing the people working with you
can bring about good results. Leadership is leadership, whether
it's in the military or a tire store. Too often, the military or a
business tries to invent artificial mumbo-jumbo. Well, human beings
operate best on steady principles; the courage to tell the truth,
attention to personal appearance, responsibility for one another.
Informed chain of command, too. If I'd dropped dead during Desert
Storm, our strategy still would have worked because people were
ready to step in as needed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It ought to be a simple lesson,'' adds Clancy. ``The good
companies like Disney or Microsoft know they have to take care of
their people. A lot of other companies have crap for policy.''
</P>
<P>
   After another week of book signings and interviews around the
country, Clancy and Horner head home _ Maryland for Clancy, Florida
for Horner. If ``Every Man a Tiger'' is successful enough, they
might team up for another book.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even if we don't, we'll always be in touch,'' Clancy says,
lighting his seventh cigarette during a 45-minute interview. ``I've
got a lot more to learn from this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Crap,'' Horner says, laughing, co-opting Clancy's favorite
word. The two men grin at each other.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
