<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9282 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUSHI-HEALTH-HNS &LR;      05-24 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUSHI-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSHI CHEFS SEE A RAW DEAL IN NEW YORK HEALTH LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LINDA TRISCHITTA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ A state law that requires the servers
and preparers of uncooked food to don gloves is a recipe for a
culture clash. Sushi chefs claim compliance with the health code
inhibits their ability to create their edible art to perfection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe sushi is an art,'' said Minoru ``Mino''
Kawaguchi, owner of Mino's Sushi House in Saratoga Springs. ``It's
a very old discipline. Japanese traditions are misunderstood.''
</P>
<P>
   Kawaguchi was cited twice and fined $1,000 for bare-hand contact
with raw food, a violation of the state sanitary code. State health
officials say sushi chefs should follow the same regulations as
other restaurant workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make this citation almost daily in every type of restaurant,
and bare hand contact almost always goes to legal actions,'' said
State Department of Health Sanitarian Joe Curatolo, who levied the
fine against Mino's.
</P>
<P>
   Sushi chefs are part of a centuries-old, pre-refrigeration
culinary tradition. In Japan, apprentices can spend three years
working only with rice before being allowed to cut fish. They rely
on their bare hands to feel for parasites, filet fish properly and
reveal patterns in the flesh that appeal to the eye and signify the
tender cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Sushi masters say they can accurately guess the number of rice
grains within their palms, a skill that along with speed is
celebrated in contests back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very good sushi chef washes their hands a lot to keep them
very cold and prevent hand oils from tainting the flavor of the
fish,'' Kawaguchi said. ``We don't hold the fish long.''
</P>
<P>
   The code does not require donning gloves for a full shift but
the accessories are mandatory when the preparer uses both hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sub shop, gloves should be changed every two sandwiches
or so,'' Curatolo said.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that food preparers' dexterity would not be
impaired. ``Surgeons wear gloves that allow them to do many
tasks,'' he said. ``Hands in the water all the time is a negative.
We're talking viral and bacteriological problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Susumu Omiya, owner of Mari Japanese Cuisine in Burnt Hills who
said his chefs wear the gloves ``most of the time,'' has not been
fined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chefs need to feel if the fish is spoiled and for the
level of oil. It's a judgment (they need to make) and that's the
last chance before it goes to the customer,'' Omiya said. ``With
gloves we're missing that. Gloves take the technique out of the
program. And it's hard to go fast. The human hand is better.''
</P>
<P>
   Kawaguchi, 43, came to the United States 18 years ago and owned
eight restaurants in Greenwich Village, Albany and California
before settling in Saratoga Springs. He said the fine, which he
negotiated down to $250, was not an ethnic or cultural insult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my lawyer that it's not fair, but he said I'm lucky. I
have to obey the regulations,'' he said. ``If I had a big chain of
restaurants, I might appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Omiya said his chefs understand sanitary conditions but he feels
sushi is a special case. ``If we cut a finger we wear gloves to
protect the public,'' Omiya said. ``It's common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ruben, a former resident of Japan who teaches the
cuisine _ without gloves _ to hundreds of students at six cooking
schools in Manhattan, said he does not understand the logic of the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wearing a latex glove, well, if they push their hair back or
sneeze, the glove is just as contaminated as a bare hand,'' Ruben
said. ``The sandwich maker who wears that vile glove all day long
is also an offender.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruben, calling Kawaguchi's case ``a travesty,'' said the
precautions seemed excessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York City, I have never seen a sushi chef wear
gloves,'' he said. ``I would love to see them go into every sushi
restaurant here. It would cause an uproar.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We're a paranoid nation, especially in light of
e-coli.''
</P>
<P>
   Kawaguchi could be closed down if he is caught without gloves in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not to penalize people. It's a training process,''
said Curatolo, who is working with two Japanese restaurateurs to
open places in Saratoga Springs. ``Sushi chefs are within their
right to go to the state Legislature to have the code changed. They
have to demonstrate scientific proof that they won't endanger the
public with bare hand contact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1716EDT &QL; 
