<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9285 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIXIECHICKS-CLONES-TE     05-24 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIXIECHICKS-CLONES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE NOT THE CHICKS, BUT THESE NEW GIRL GROUPS DO BEAR A
RESEMBLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What hath the Dixie Chicks wrought?
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at the photos that accompany their media handouts: A
trio of new groups, all featuring cute young blond women singing
songs full o' sass and heartache with sweet, airy harmonies.
</P>
<P>
   The field is not so crowded with young girl-group hopefuls
bearing at least some resemblance to Dallas' Chicks that we need a
score card (not yet), but let's get the players straightened out:
</P>
<P>
   SheDaisy: Sisters Kristyn, Kelsi and Kassidy Osborn from Magna,
Utah. The debut single from their new ``The Whole SheBang'' CD,
``Little Good-Byes,'' is at No. 26 on the national country singles
charts.
</P>
<P>
   Redmon &AMP; Vale: Pals Allison Redmon and Tina Vale, who came from
Lilburn, Ga., and Elko, Nev., respectively, to form a duo in
Nashville and record a CD, due for release in July. All that's
available right now is the single ``If I Had a Nickel (One Thin
Dime),'' which is picking up some airplay.
</P>
<P>
   Mulberry Lane: Sisters Heather, Jaymie, Rachel and Allie
Rizzuto; they're from Omaha (specifically, a street called Mulberry
Lane), their sound is folk-pop with more R&AMP;B-smart rhythmic
touches. Their debut CD, ``Run Your Own Race,'' was released this
month, and the flagship single, ``Harmless,'' is, as they say,
climbing the charts.
</P>
<P>
   No, SheDaisy, Redmon &AMP; Vale and Mulberry Lane do not all sound
alike _ and none of them sounds exactly like the Chicks; Mulberry
Lane is a far more straight-ahead pop group, with country touches
well to the back.
</P>
<P>
   But the musical similarities (especially with SheDaisy and R&AMP;V)
are clearly there, and the look and basic sound of all three are
eerily familiar and fairly scream Emily, Natalie and Martie.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Released in January 1998, the Chicks' ``Wide Open
Spaces'' has sold more than 5 million copies, won the trio two
Grammys (including Best Country Album) and earned them a spot both
opening stadium shows for George Strait and playing numerous dates
on this summer's edition of Lilith Fair.
</P>
<P>
   What's not to emulate?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync _ like all the cute
Texas guys, the hat acts that came out a couple years ago,'' says
Linda O'Brian, music director for KSCS. ``It's a fad. It always
happens. Some people in the industry are calling SheDaisy the
Disney Chicks, because they're signed to Lyric Street, a Disney
label.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories of these three acts, too, share a common thread: All
these women, we're told, grew up in small towns, went to Nashville,
toughed it out awhile, and finally hit on the perfect combination
of harmonies and songwriting. SheDaisy came to Nashville a decade
ago, performing first as the Osborn Sisters and then the Violets
before signing with Lyric Street.
</P>
<P>
   And all three, of course, have released a CD with a lot of
breezy, accessible music _ but also, let's note, songs about women
not taking any nonsense from any menfolk, darn it.
</P>
<P>
   The theme runs most strongly through SheDaisy's debut, ``The
Whole SheBang''; in addition to ``Good-Byes,'' there is also ``I
Will ... But,'' in which the narrator refuses to be her sweetie's
dirty secret, cure-all pill, Friday paycheck, Barbie doll or Martha
Stewart (?) _ but she will be your ``everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmon &AMP; Vale's ``Nickel,'' too, is all about empowerment: ``If
I had a nickel for every time I wished your love was still mine/I'd
have one thin dime,'' they chime.
</P>
<P>
   Best breakout potential of the three? At present, the smart
money's on SheDaisy; they have the best songs (which come from
Kristyn), a pleasing sound, and a 13-minute profile film that's
been shown to radio and retail. And because of all this,
``Good-Byes'' is doing fairly well on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   And lest we think this is all cynical timing on the part of
record labels, well, at least one country expert doesn't see it
that way. Janine Matteson, country editor at ``Gavin,'' strenuously
defends SheDaisy, saying that she ``doesn't see a slew of Dixie
Chickettes coming out.'' Country listeners _ and journalists _ need
to look beyond the surface similarities and dig a little deeper,
she says, and give each group a chance based on its own merits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labels want to find a unique sound,'' she says. ``The Chicks
proved that different isn't bad. I think country has a tendency to
pigeonhole _ if we have one of anything, we don't think we need any
more. We have a narrow vision.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
