<HEADLINE>
FOR DISABLED ARTISTS, CREATIVITY HAS NO BOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SELNA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Regina Broussard is known for her distinctive
drawings resembling ancient wood carvings or hieroglyphics. Judith
Scott's fiber art _ sculptures wrapped in string and other
discarded materials _ has been acquired by a museum in Paris and is
the subject of a book.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many artists, Broussard and Scott have attained critical
acclaim and financial success. But these women, and other artists
at their Oakland studio, are exceptional in another way: They are
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Oakland's Creative Growth Art Center and Gallery is
celebrating its 25th year as a haven where physically and mentally
disabled adults learn, create and showcase their talents. A gala
earlier this month attracted hundreds of supporters and collectors
eager to see the gallery's latest additions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This artwork defies conventional wisdom,'' said Irene Brydon,
the center's executive director. ``Disabled artists do work that
trained artists can't imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Brydon said the center, which was the first of its kind in the
United States and has produced close to 500,000 pieces of art, has
seen an enormous increase in visiting collectors over the last five
years, due in part to the popularity of ``outsider art.''
</P>
<P>
   Outsider art, Brydon said, has its roots in ``brut art,'' a name
given to late 19th-century work produced by artists in mental
institutions. Today, Brydon said, the term defines art produced
outside mainstream galleries by those ``ignored, isolated or
marginalized by society.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal labeled outsider art a trend in the
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, outsider art is characterized by its raw, direct
themes and style, which are being emulated by more and more
mainstream artists.
</P>
<P>
   But to the 90 or so artists preoccupied with their creative
pursuits on any given day at Creative Growth, labels are
insignificant. They would rather create art than talk about it,
said instructor Stan Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   In flashes of inspiration, Louie Estape dreams up abstract
gorillas and other creatures, and later carves the shapes out of
wood, adorning them with repetitive geometric designs, circles and
brilliant colors.
</P>
<P>
   Autistic artist William Tyler uses colored pencils and ink to
produce precise, linear renderings with social themes. Carl
Hendricksen, who has cerebral palsy, constructs a multifeatured
wooden chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of their work is nontraditional and obsessional, with
the same theme repeated over and over again _ as if they need to do
it,'' Brydon said.
</P>
<P>
   Most participants come to the center on referral from social
service workers or other caregivers, although some learn of it on
their own, Brydon said.
</P>
<P>
   The artists' disabilities include a spectrum of mental and
physical challenges, but to get into the program, an individual
must demonstrate a real interest in art.
</P>
<P>
   Started with a grant from the National Endowment for the Arts,
the licensed day care program receives 70 percent of its funding
from the state Department of Developmental Services. The center
must raise money through grants and gallery sales to supplement its
funding.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's cultural arts department also contributes some money,
and 13 part-time teachers are provided by the Oakland Public
Schools adult education division. Some instructors teach classes
that focus on independent living, while other artists/mentors with
master's degrees teach and supervise creative arts, including
drawing, painting, print making, ceramics, wood sculpture, rug and
furniture making.
</P>
<P>
   The Creative Growth gallery is filled with the participants'
artwork and puts on exhibits every six to eight weeks. Brydon said
the gallery, which attracts more than 4,000 visitors a year, earns
about $100,000 a year, with half going to the artists.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for artwork range from $12 to $1,000, Brydon said. All of
the center's 125 clients are given some compensation quarterly,
regardless of whether their art sells.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, a wood sculptor who has been teaching at Creative
Growth since 1985, said he works more individually with the artists
than he would in a conventional program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You move from student to student, each with different skills
and disabilities,'' Peterson said. ``Some have problems with speech
or deafness, others are not able to use their hands or feet ... it
is a really interesting environment to teach in. It keeps you on
your toes at all times.''
</P>
<P>
   Another difference, said Peterson, is the reward and inspiration
he receives from his students.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are very appreciative of any assistance you give
them, and they are very self-motivated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reanne Estrada, a sculptor and performance artist who teaches
rug making, said that like all artists, those at Creative Growth
are inspired by their lives outside the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a sense of humor and are interested in pop culture
like contemporary music and television ... their lives very much
inform their art.''
</P>
</TEXT>
