<SLUG> BC-SUTURES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECALL OF SURGICAL SUTURES UNDER FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A medical manufacturer retrieved only 2 percent
of about 3.6 million surgical sutures it recalled after the
products allegedly were contaminated with infectious bacteria, the
U.S. Food and Drug Administration said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., said the FDA's handling of a
nationwide recall of the Ethicon Corp.'s trademark Vicryl surgical
sutures _ and the low return rate _ made him fear that ``the system
may have failed to protect the health of patients.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter last week to Stark and Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif.,
Associate FDA Commissioner Melinda Plaisier said Ethicon had
managed to retrieve only about 76,000 of 3.6 million boxes of
sutures that were processed in a problem-plagued sterilizer at a
Texas factory and then shipped to hospitals and surgeons in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The other 3.5 million sutures presumably had already been used
by the time the recall began, an FDA official said.
</P>
<P>
   An Ethicon spokeswoman said the company believed the FDA may
have misinterpreted its data, contending that about 25 percent _ or
about 900,000 of the sutures _ had been returned in the recall. But
the FDA insisted the numbers were accurate.
</P>
<P>
   In lawsuits and complaints to the FDA, more than 100 patients in
California and eight other states have blamed contaminated Ethicon
sutures for a nationwide outbreak of fierce, debilitating
post-operative infections in 1994 and 1995. The company has denied
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for victims have said they fear that many other people
may also have become infected by the sutures, which in lawsuits
were alleged to have been contaminated with staphylococcus and a
rare bacteria that is related to tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   Stark and Waxman last month wrote a tough letter to the FDA
asking pointed questions about the incident and the agency's
supervision of it.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Plaisier for the first time reported the return
rate, 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In her letter she also said Ethicon had destroyed all the
sutures that were returned in the voluntary recall.
</P>
<P>
   Stark and other critics said that will make it far more
difficult to investigate the role of the sutures in the infection
outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the low return rate on the recall and the destruction of
the returned sutures, Plaisier defended the conduct of the company
and the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1994, the FDA issued a warning letter to Ethicon,
faulting the company for continuing to sell sutures after it
discovered its sterilizer unit was malfunctioning. Because of the
sterilization failures, the FDA said it regarded the sutures as
``adulterated'' under terms of federal pure-products laws.
</P>
<P>
   But Plaisier wrote last week that there was no proof sutures had
actually become contaminated, saying the ``FDA considered the
deficiencies to constitute a lack of assurance of sterility, not a
lack of sterility.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, there was no proof the sutures were responsible for
the infections, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Odenthal, a spokeswoman for Ethicon, said the FDA letter
supported what the company has said all along _ that there is no
evidence that the sutures caused the postoperative infections the
lawsuits alleged. She said Ethicon was working with the FDA to iron
out the disagreement over the correct number of sutures returned in
the recall.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records and FDA documents, the sutures
problem began in March 1994, when Ethicon, a $1.2 billion Johnson &AMP;
Johnson subsidiary, noted that a new high-tech system for
sterilizing sutures at a plant in San Angelo, Texas, was
malfunctioning.
</P>
<P>
   In May of that year, Ethicon stopped using the equipment. But no
recall was ordered until September, after prodding from FDA
inspectors who had discovered the problem during a routine
inspection. In the meantime, 3.6 million suspect sutures were on
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ethicon recalled the sutures, it contended the risk of
infection was so slight that there was no reason for doctors who
had used the sutures to warn patients, a company memo shows.
</P>
</TEXT>
