r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FALL-COMMENT-SFCHR     05-24 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-COMMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS PLAY IT SAFE AGAIN IN FALL LINEUPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Them who has, gets.
</P>
<P>
   The adage applies to nothing so much as network TV. To get a
series on the air, it seems, you have to have a series on the air.
</P>
<P>
   So when the network fall schedules were released last week, the
stars' names weren't always familiar, but the producers' names
were.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Wolf, producer of ``Law &AMP; Order,'' has a new show and,
surprise, it's a chip off of ``Law &AMP; Order.''
</P>
<P>
   David E. Kelley, may we kneel and cross ourselves when we say
his name, has two new shows. One is ``Ally,'' ground like sausage
from old ``Ally McBeal'' footage.
</P>
<P>
   It goes on. ``ER'' executive producer John Wells, whose
``Trinity'' was such a smash nonhit last year, has two new shows of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite is Aaron Sorkin. He got ``Sports Night'' on ABC last
fall. It's a good show but still wobbly as a newborn colt. Still,
he and Wells will be producing the new ``West Wing'' this fall for
NBC.
</P>
<P>
   These are talented individuals. But will ``The Practice'' be
better because Kelley is overseeing the production of ``Snoops''?
Doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's because so few people do so many shows, or because
network programmers are basically jackasses, the fall season once
again looks, on paper at least, like any other TV season. And in an
era of hemorrhaging ratings, that doesn't bode well for the old
networks.
</P>
<P>
   There will be 38 new series on ABC, CBS, Fox, NBC, UPN and the
WB. Five are direct spin-offs of existing shows. Four are cop
shows. At least three are lawyer shows. I gave up trying to count
how many will be about young people afoot in New York. Let's just
say too many.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be expected to remember that ``Now &AMP; Again'' is CBS and
``Once &AMP; Again'' is ABC. Neither is to be confused with Jane
Pauley's ``Time &AMP; Again'' on MSNBC. But go ahead anyway, if you
must.
</P>
<P>
   There's ``Grown Ups'' on UPN and ``Oh Grow Up'' on ABC, and I'm
making a wild guess that neither show is especially for grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is to say, the networks are repeating themselves
more than a burping babe. The same old same-old.
</P>
<P>
   One trend is more promising, dramatically. Three new shows are
set in high schools; interestingly, the networks finalized their
schedules in the immediate wake of the Columbine High School
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   It's not simply that ``Freaks and Geeks,'' ``Popularity'' and
``Manchester Prep'' will be centered in high schools. It's that
they may be poised to tackle the sorts of teen issues that erupted
in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   More early indications for the fall season:
</P>
<P>
   _ Business plans do change at UPN. Last year its executives
argued that they were standing forthrightly for the principle of
general, broad-based entertainment, and damn the demographics. In
the fall UPN will program for adolescent males, with pro wrestling
leading the way.
</P>
<P>
   _ African Americans have been slighted again, as badly as in the
1950s. Only UPN continues to take a stab at this increasingly
neglected audience. The bigger networks are snow-white for the
fall. And even Fox has put ``The PJs'' into storage until midseason
next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ It may be tougher for NBC to hold Thursdays together. ABC,
Fox, UPN and the WB are showing signs of a fighting spirit, and
they might smell blood. ``Friends,'' ``Frasier'' and ``ER'' will be
one year older. ``Jesse'' will be one year dumber, and ``Stark
Raving Mad'' will be new. Take NBC down on Thursday and the peacock
is stew meat.
</P>
<P>
   _ All the networks except CBS will ignore anyone whose physical
age is past 49 and whose mental age is beyond 15. And doesn't CBS
seem a mite arthritic? You just can't win.
</P>
<P>
   _ Half-hour sitcoms have become so stale that even the networks
are sick of them. Fewer than half of the new shows are comedies, a
big reversal from past seasons. By year's end some of us will be
complaining that we just can't digest another TV drama.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where are the risk-takers? Hiding in the bushes, waiting until
midseason. Practically every delicate se ries in development has
been held off the air until after the annual autumn slaughter. More
and more, it's evident that September is the most dangerous time to
put a new show on the air.
</P>
<P>
   _ Care for an interesting time slot? Personally, I like 9:30
p.m. Wednesdays, when new shows will be on four of the six networks
_ and CBS will be running a movie.
</P>
<P>
   _ These titles might say something malicious about the times.
Consider: ``Harsh Realm,'' ``Cold Feet,'' ``Odd Man Out,''
``Smackdown!,'' ``Get Real,'' ``Shasta McNasty,'' ``Oh Grow Up,''
``Wasteland.'' Geez, it's enough to make someone adore ``Safe
Harbor,'' if only for its name.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of titles, no way should ``Ryan Caulfield'' be a cop
show. It sounds way, way too much like ``Holden Caulfield.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
