<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MANDELA-REVIEW-NYT     05-24 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MANDELA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LONG WALK': NELSON MANDELA A MAN, LEADER AND LEGEND 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(ms) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title ``legend'' is generously handed around these days,
used especially in television as a synonym for the hour's
celebrity. So calling Nelson Mandela a legend is an inadequate
tribute. Careful though he is of his image, he also guards his
privacy and is too aloof to pander to the tabloids. Even many who
acclaim him as an authentic hero of our time know little about him
other than that he was held as a prisoner of apartheid for almost
three decades and that on his release in 1990 instantly became his
nation's pre-eminent politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Long Walk of Nelson Mandela,'' Tuesday night's two-hour
offering from ``Frontline,'' digs into his character, particularly
as revealed by his behavior on Robben Island during his
imprisonment. His warders and his comrades agree on the commanding
position that he assumed despite being cut off from the struggle
that was taking place in South Africa's black townships. When the
time came for negotiations, it was Mandela who was recognized as
the most credible negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   Born into a royal house of a tribal clan, the young Mandela was
recruited into the black cause by Walter Sisulu, a rising figure of
the African National Congress. Given his imposing stature, his
aristocratic mien and his defiant attitude, Mandela was tapped as a
leader among the black elite. He was also something of a ladies
man, and his rocky love affair with Winnie Madikizela, who became
his wife and a controversial political figure, is reported in
considerable detail. It would prove an excruciating embarrassment
for a man who so valued his privacy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961 Mandela moved from his advocacy of nonviolence to
sabotage. His bombs brought him the title of ``Black Pimpernel.''
When he was captured, he used his defense to attack the system. ``I
am a black man in a white man's court,'' he announced, and was duly
sentenced with other underground leaders to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   On Robben Island, largely cut off from the outside world, he led
what a fellow prisoner calls ``a war of nerves'' against the
authorities. As the prisoner described it: ``Mandela made the
point, if they say you must run, insist on walking. If they say you
must walk fast, insist on walking slowly.'' He protested against
every indignity, and over time, restrictions were relaxed, his
status affirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations between the increasingly embattled white
rulers, who found themselves unable to contain the violence in the
townships, and Mandela, who was accused by some comrades of selling
out, makes for an especially illuminating part of the program. His
canny analysis of the whites' predicament and his autocratic
negotiating style carried the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Long Walk'' ends with a description of the 1995 Rugby
World Cup final in Johannesburg, where tens of thousands of white
fans greeted their country's new leader with shouts of ``Nelson!''
For Mandela, wearing a team jersey, it was a moment of triumphant
reconciliation. As for the problems facing South Africa under his
successors, they are left for future reports.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   FRONTLINE
</P>
<P>
   The Long Walk of Nelson Mandela
</P>
