<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9341 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-RESEARCH-REVIEW-A     05-24 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RESEARCH-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TESTS ON PEOPLE, WHO WATCHES THE WATCHERS? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Texas)  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PHILIP J. HILTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In H.G. Wells' novel ``The Time Machine,'' a flourishing, modern
civilization is maintained by an unseen underground tribe that
carries out its work behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   While the parallel is inexact, the story has similarities in the
real world of medical research, where the visible edifice of
university and medical center laboratories is supported by
committees with an unassuming title but a crucial responsibility.
The committees, institutional review boards, are the people charged
with insuring the safety and ethics of experiments on human beings.
</P>
<P>
   In large part, these boards are a legacy of the revelations of
science run amok in Hitler's Germany and the widespread disgust at
the Tuskegee syphilis study and the like. The committees' job is
not only to prevent this kind of ethical disaster, but also to
protect human experimental subjects in more mundane ways, like
insuring that they understand their rights and that they have
formally consented to experiments.
</P>
<P>
   As the pace of pharmaceutical development increases, these
boards are finding their work increasing. And the federal agency
that oversees them, the Office of Protection from Research Risks,
is moving with new aggressiveness to monitor IRB performance.
</P>
<P>
   The members of these boards _ scientists, ethicists and
patients' representatives _ are unpaid and work several hours a
week, plus attend monthly meetings that may run four to six hours.
They have little staff to help them. Their work is highly technical
and specialized, but for the most part they must train themselves.
And, according to various estimates, they are expected to review
300 to 2,000 proposed experiments per year, with each experiment
documented in hundreds of pages of material.
</P>
<P>
   But should something go wrong in the basement rooms where these
committees meet, the whole multimillion-dollar research enterprise
can come to a humiliating, expensive halt, as Duke University
Medical Center discovered this month when federal regulators
briefly suspended the university's license to conduct human
experiments _ all 2,000 of them _ because it had violated ethics
and safety rules.
</P>
<P>
   Duke was the third major research institution in six months to
have its work suspended, and the director of the federal ethics
office, Gary Ellis, said in an interview last week that half a
dozen other university research programs were under investigation.
At least a couple of the inquiries had turned up serious problems,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Korn, senior vice president of the American
Association of Medical Colleges, which represents major research
universities and medical centers, saidthe Duke case showed the
heightened concern, at least in Washington, about experiments on
humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is talk that new legislation might be necessary,'' he
said. ``There is a real ferment, and the question raised is, can
IRBs do what is expected of them _ that is, protect subjects of
experiments.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said it was too early to tell what action the office would
take as a result of the investigations. After all, his office
itself has few investigators and staff members and for years has
worked with university officials largely through cooperation and
cajoling.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been pressure building to change the system in
some way, at least to expand the number of review boards and give
them more resources. The toughest critics suggest that more
fundamental reform is necessary, because reviews of the system have
found significant problems.
</P>
<P>
   One of the keys to IRB operation, and a common source of
trouble, is the informed-consent statement that patients must sign
to indicate that they have been told the risks of the experiments
and are still willing to participate. The Office of Protection from
Research Risks has frequently found that informed-consent papers
understate or misstate the risks.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst cases, such as the Tuskegee syphilis experiment,
subjects were not told that treatment would be withheld so that
researchers could observe the course of the disease. In more recent
experiments, patients have not been told that the purpose of a
study was to induce symptoms and monitor them. Instead, they have
been told only that they might suffer symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``While factually correct, that is a blatant
misrepresentation,'' said Leonard Glantz, a professor of health law
at the Boston University School of Public Health, and a longtime
IRB member.
</P>
<P>
   Among the groups that have found the system in need of reform
have been the President's National Bioethics Advisory Committee,
the President's Committee on Radiation Experiments, the Department
of Health and Human Services Inspector General, Congress' General
Accounting Office and the Institute of Medicine at the National
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   As the Journal of the American Medical Association said in an
1996 editorial after an federal investigation of past wartime
radiation experiments and of current IRB practices, ``never before
has such a pressure-cooker atmosphere prevailed within the IRB
system, leading government officials, university administrators,
research sponsors and IRB members to wonder whether the IRB system
will crack or reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no one keeps track officially, the General Accounting
Office has estimated that 16,000 to 20,000 experiments on an
unknown number of people are conducted in the United States each
year. And the number and complexity of studies, which might involve
dozens to thousands of participants, appear to be rising sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers Association
reports that in the late 1970s, 30 separate human trials were done
for each new drug application sent to the Food and Drug
Administration. A trial is a study in which a new drug is tested
against an existing drug in varying numbers of patients.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, 68 trials were conducted per drug application. The
number of patients in the experiments has also shot up _ from about
1,600 for each drug application filed in the late 1970s, to 4,250
per application by 1995.
</P>
<P>
   And these numbers do not include all the other scientific
research involving human subjects, such as psychiatric or
behavioral studies, which may account for half of all human
research.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In the Duke case, federal investigators found, for example, that
some informed-consent documents had failed to give subjects full
information about what they would undergo. They found that the IRB
did not follow up to see if any harm had come to patients. They
found meetings convened and votes taken without a quorum present,
and found that two of the board members were top officers of the
university's grants and contracts office _ officials who have a
vested interest in approval of the research. In all, 20 violations
were found.
</P>
<P>
   The response to the growing burden on institutional review
boards has varied from place to place. At Duke, until federal
investigators stepped in, the burden just kept growing. There was
no full-time administrator or staff to review 2,000 experiments.
But at a far smaller research center, the University of Texas at
San Antonio, the board has a full-time administrator and four staff
members to help it review only 300 to 400 studies per year, said
Dr. Herman Wigodsky, a former chairman of the IRB there.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Protection from Research Risks, which has been in
operation since May 1974, carries a caseload of 80 to 120
investigations at a time. That is about four times the number it
handled in its first year of operation. Many more cases might be
opened as complaints about abuses continue to stream in _ some from
patients but most from medical center staff members _ especially
after highly publicized incidents like the suspension of research
at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency has the equivalent of only three full-time
employees to monitor 16,000 to 20,000 human experiments _ a
workload that Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., called ``pathetic''
in congressional hearings on IRB's last year.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, more than just the number of human experiments
has increased. There has also been an increase in complaints,
debates and public scrutiny. The biggest attention-getting event,
one that produced a flood of reports to investigate, said Ellis,
was the work of the President's Commission on Human Radiation
Experiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that people had a lot of complaints about
radiation,'' Ellis said, ``but people just became aware that they
had a place to turn.'' He said his office was ``experiencing a
25-year peak in interest and action regarding the protection of
human subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   As scientists face the bad publicity associated with the
discovery of ethics violations, there has been debate about whether
the problems found are largely ``administrative housekeeping'' or
are a signal that patients are being harmed.
</P>
<P>
   Since there is no actual compilation of patients hurt by
experiments, the amount of harm _ from side effects of drugs to
death caused by experimental methods _ cannot accurately be
assessed. Very few harmful events are reported to the Office of
Protection from Research Risks. ``They appear to be considerably
underreported,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   The system depends not on tracking harm, but on devising
well-planned experiments that assure reasonable safety. That means
record-keeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some discussion about whether what happens in
some of these instances is just housekeeping or is serious,'' Ellis
said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, rules require that at least one nonscientist be
present for every IRB action. ``If the IRB meeting minutes don't
show the presence and voting of that member, then there is just no
way to know whether this requirement has been satisfied,'' he said.
``That is more substance than housekeeping, I'd say.''
</P>
<P>
   Korn of the American Association of Medical Colleges
acknowledged that there was much chagrin on the part of medical
researchers about rules that seem overly burdensome and apparently
unnecessary. ``But we have no choice,'' he said. ``If we want
people to trust us, and if we want to be able to carry on with this
work, we must do this right. It is the way the system is set up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
