<HEADER>
A9348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUST-NOVEL-1600(2TAKE     05-24 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUST-NOVEL-1600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARD JUST REFLECTS ON THE DELUSIONS OF PEOPLE AND NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ No place is more gray than Berlin in winter, a layered
gray that begins in the sky, permeates the air, penetrates the
buildings and gathers with bottomless intensity in the city's
lakes. It is a grayness that Ward Just, the novelist, calls ``an
atmosphere,'' and in atmospheres lie the germ of his imaginative
voyages.
</P>
<P>
   One recently began here as Just gazed at the metal-gray waters
of the Wannsee. An icy wind was blowing over the lake. On the far
shore, just visible, was the villa where SS officers led by
Reinhard Heydrich gathered in January 1942 to decide the ``final
solution'' _ the extermination of European Jews. Out on the lake
two middle-aged men were furiously rowing a double scull against
the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what do you make of that?'' the author said, pulling an
unfiltered Camel from a packet in the breast pocket of his rumpled
tweed jacket and lighting it slowly. ``Colder than hell. Drizzle
coming down. Never seen a gray like it. That sinister villa. Two
German guys, aged 50 or so, battling the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Just smiled: he likes such conundrums. ``That's enough for me _
a situation, an atmosphere, a vision. I never begin with a plot.
The hell with a plot. But with time, with patience, the thing
reveals itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing does indeed. After 12 novels, reflections on the
delusions of people and nations and the sometimes permanent damage
they suffer, it is safe to say that Just will draw much from that
image of the dogged rowers. On the pain of Germany, its midcentury
catastrophe, its ineluctable battle with memory, its sullen
determination and belief in itself, its discipline, its Romantic
attraction to nature's unassuaged forces, its eternal mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Characters will appear out of all this, a story, even a plot of
sorts, that trace how the wounds of place and personality overlap
at Europe's bitter heart.
</P>
<P>
   Just, who is 62, has just left Berlin after a winterlong sojourn
to be in the United States for the publication this month of his
most recent novel, ``A Dangerous Friend'' (Peter Davison/Houghton
Mifflin). It is set in Vietnam, where Just worked as a
correspondent for The Washington Post from late 1965 to mid-1967,
discovering the themes of love, duty, honor, loyalty,
self-delusion, chaos and uprootedness that have since obsessed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was useless for journalism after Vietnam,'' he said simply.
``I knew I was not going to do any better work.''
</P>
<P>
   But the experience of Vietnam stayed with him after he quit
newspapering a few years later, informing his novels. As he wrote
in ``The Translator,'' his own favorite work, published in 1991:
``Every man had to test himself, and if he was courageous and lucky
he found maturity. That was all the reward you could ask for, or
were entitled to: growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Life is a game for adults in all of Just's work, serious
business. He tackles the big themes. War, of course, but also the
other battles _ for power (be it in Chicago's Loop or the Cold
War's corridors), for money and for some balance between passion
and love. His approach is disarming. Simple sentences build
inexorably to pin the reader, with a shocking abruptness, in a
charged web. There is something of the soldier's implacability in
Just's prose, something of the military man's taste for the ambush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just admired the hell out of a lot of the soldiers I met in
Vietnam,'' Just said. ``It was not for me. Hell, no. But the good
ones had a sense of loyalty, and the best ones had a real sense of
the limits of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Limits, and the terrible things that lie beyond them for people
and states, are central preoccupations of Just. Hence Vietnam;
hence Berlin. In both places, of course, the cold war's battles
were fought with great intensity. Their way of pushing people to
the outer edges of experience makes them natural settings for
Just's work.
</P>
<P>
   In the Vietnam War, the United States, with ``its industry, its
restlessness and sprawl, its impatience, its confidence, its anger
and its desire,'' went a step too far, driven in part by the egos
of men like Dicky Rostok, the antihero of ``A Dangerous Friend,''
whose faith in American power is almost limitless. Such faith is a
necessary basis for so farfetched an idea as building a nation in
the American image in a faraway place. But, Just suggests, it may
also be a form of blindness, and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Rostok, personal ambition and political passion mesh,''
Just said. ``But passion tends to go wrong so often.'' One of his
characters puts a similar thought about Rostok more bluntly in ``A
Dangerous Friend'': ``I have always believed that a mountainous ego
resulted from an absence of conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Just is deeply concerned with conscience. His ``atmosphere'' or
vision for ``A Dangerous Friend'' also emerged near the water, this
time on Martha's Vineyard, where he lives most of the year. He saw,
in his mind's eye, a man sitting on rickety pier, sketching and
resketching the same scene. This man, a survivor of Vietnam, had
withdrawn from the world, concluding that the only answer to chaos
was repetition.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear enough that the discipline of habit is also
attractive to Just, who is always at his battered typewriter for an
eight-hour day and always comfortably disheveled. Grief, he has
written, is the other face of grace; his graciousness is
unmistakable.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the old journalistic curiosity continues to drive him from a
settled life out into the world; and a darker side, a stormy
undertow, has persistently drawn him to Germany and Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family came from Darmstadt to Chicago about 150 years ago,
and I've been interested by Germany for a very long time,'' Just
said. ``Interest grew to obsession through the paintings. There's
that great Max Beckmann portrait of the man in a tuxedo _ square
face, head down with a cigarette, just a majestic portrait, and
that led me to all the Expressionists, Kirchner, Schmidt-Rottluff,
Dix, and something provocative stayed in my mind forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Another image or atmosphere dear to Just, this one from a visit
to a German beach: a beautiful topless girl playing volleyball with
two boys, watched by old women dressed completely in black.
</P>
<P>
   For Just, so much was there: the perverse German state, broken
in two by Hitler's murderous madness, full still of bitter spies
and reproach, chronically divided, but alive still with the
vitality that, for Just, makes it ``the most talented nation in
Europe, even if it is the most burdened.''
</P>
<P>
   He came to Berlin as a visiting fellow at the recently opened
American Academy _ a ``gastarbeiter,'' or guest worker, as he puts
it, with his gentle, often self-mocking smile. For many years,
sojourns in Europe had meant sojourns in Paris with his wife, Sarah
Catchpole, but he felt it was time for a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Germany is a feast of the mind, not the eye,'' he said. ``I
have not seen a single vista in Berlin that can compare favorably
to a commonplace sight in Paris. But the conversation, the quality
of introspection, the openness are fifty-fold what I found in
France.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that conversation, inevitably, has been about the
Holocaust, and some of it left Just breathless with its frankness
and pain. ``They are not forgetting,'' he said. ``It is with them
every minute of every hour of every days. My heart goes out to
those who bear no responsibility and think of what happened so
constantly.''
</P>
<P>
   He was at one Berlin dinner when a man started talking about his
father. A father much loved. A father later discovered to have been
a Nazi. Tears started to flow: a grown man talking about his father
and sobbing as he described how inexplicable it was that so good a
father could have embraced such evil.
</P>
<P>
   At another dinner, somebody remarked that Auschwitz would always
stand in the way of Germany's being a nation like any other. The
host said that was a ridiculous notion. Germany would be normal
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have asked: Why was it ridiculous to think that
Auschwitz would always prevent Germany from being normal?'' Just
said. ``I should have asked what normality meant to the host. But I
was silent.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems reasonable to assume that from that silence some of the
themes of Just's next novel will emerge. Germany has been in his
books for some time. ``As a nation,'' he once wrote, ``it resembled
Chicago, central to its region, a furious engine that advances on
its own inner logic, closed in on itself, with resentments enough
to fill the couches of Vienna _ yet beneath the surface there was
faith, patience and an implacable sense of destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   This European colossus will now move from backdrop to the front
of the stage. And what of Germany's being back at war, in Kosovo,
alongside the United States?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cold War is over, and Kosovo is not really about anything
larger than itself,'' Just said. ``I feel no point of comparison
with Vietnam, and no surprise or concern at Germany's role. We have
a responsibility now to the Albanians who lost their homes, and we
should take them back to their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Just said he would not be a direct witness of this European
struggle. ``There is no way I'd go back to war, no way I would get
a quotation straight today. Many of the things that make you a good
journalist have to be discarded to make you a good writer. Forget
the research. In a novel, every fact is a rock thrown in the hull,
and the boat sinks a bit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
