<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SELFHELP25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Comic pair turns tables on gurus of self-help
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're two of the hottest actors around _ Ben Stiller starred
in ``There's Something About Mary'' and Janeane Garofalo's resume
includes TV's late, lamented ``The Larry Sanders Show.''
</P>
<P>
   But now they're showing us something else: depth. With a
definite smirk. In ``Feel This Book'' (Ballantine, 224 pages,
$22.95), Stiller says, they attempted to write ``an
all-encompassing self-help book that touched on a lot of different
areas, but specialized in nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   They also attempted to describe their long-ago romantic
dalliance _ with predictably hilarious results. Following are
excerpts from an interview with the pair.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can you offer that other self-help gurus can't?
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo: We offer the wisdom that comes from doing series
television, from having your name above the title of a film.
</P>
<P>
   Stiller: And also the experience of not ever having really had
one successful long-term relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Despite your short, ill-fated relationship, you're still
friends. What's your secret?
</P>
<P>
   Stiller: Just get together with somebody who feeds into all of
your neuroses and you feed into all their neuroses and
insecurities.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo: Right. You have to have somebody whose dysfunctions
dovetail perfectly with your own.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Any truth to the talk that you made the relationship seem
like something more than it was?
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo: I have photos of me trying to seduce him in a
mechanical bear costume.
</P>
<P>
   Stiller: And I have the dirty sheets. No, we had a little thing,
a long time ago, and then, you know, all humor kind of springs from
a little nugget of truth. Hopefully, a tree of comedy grows.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Janeane, your ``Blame the Family'' chapter felt especially
impassioned. When's it time to finally let go?
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo: I don't think there is a good time to give up a
grudge. Especially with your family, because they're with you for
life. So I think it's an important show of internal strength and
inner fortitude to hang onto the grudge.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And Ben, you had some fun at other self-helpers' expense:
Tony Robbins, Deepak Chopra, etc. Anyone you purposely stayed away
from?
</P>
<P>
   Stiller: I think L. Ron Hubbard's grasp is further than we know.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you decide who got top cover billing?
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo: It was decided for us somehow. For some reason, it's
everyone's inclination to say ``Ben Stiller and Janeane Garofalo,''
instead of the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Ben?
</P>
<P>
   Stiller: I had lawyers working behind the scene so that I stayed
clean.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
