<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Father's Day comes once a year and Esquire makes the most out of
it
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Esquire ($3) puts together a thoughtful and entertaining
Father's Day issue packed with all kinds of Fathers, including the
priestly variety (in an improbable fashion spread) and more secular
Dads, such as Mike Tyson. Along with Tom Junod's portrait of the
fatherly Tyson (and his youngest son, Amir), is a heartbeaking tale
of Tommy Nothing Fancy, the Navajo boy doomed to live six short
years, and the adoptive father who teaches him to love fishing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SHE SAID, HE SAID: In Perspectives, Newsweek ($3.50) offers an
amusing pair of quotes. From GOP presidential hopeful Elizabeth
Dole, after her husband Bob said he might support rival John
McCain: ``I told him I loved him. I told him he was in the
woodshed.'' And from McCain, asked whether he'd spoken with Dole
since the flap: ``They haven't installed a phone in his woodshed
yet, so I haven't had a chance to speak with him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE OTHER SERBS? Basketball star Vlade Divac should be
sleeping, preparing for the fifth game of the playoffs against the
Utah Jazz, but at 3 in the morning he is up watching CNN and
dialing his homeland to find out which Serb relatives in Kosovo
have been killed by NATO bombs. According to Sports Illustrated
($2.95) columnist Rick Reilly, the Sacramento Kings center is no
fan of Slobodan Milosevic _ last summer he protested against the
Yugoslav leader in the streets of Belgrade _ but now is the target
of hate mail from those angry with Milosevic's genocidal policies.
Reilly presents the other side of the Kosovo story.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  DEPRESSED TEENS: Along with the other newsmagazines, Time
($3.50) uses the shootings at Heritage High School in Conyers to
renew a discussion of youth violence, and to post a list of warning
signs that a young person may be headed wrong. Time also reports a
revival among evangelical teens, inspired by Cassie Bernall, the
Columbine High School student who was slain when she confessed, at
gunpoint, her belief in God.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE KINGDOM IS AT HAND: ``God called my father to the world's
big stadiums, and called me to its ditches,'' says Franklin Graham,
son of Billy Graham, one of the greatest preachers of modern times.
``I resented paying for my father's fame,'' Franklin once told a
reporter. ``All my life I suffered for it.'' In George ($2.95),
Elizabeth Kaye writes of the rising son, preparing to take over his
father's well-connected empire.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  DYLAN GOES ELECTRIC: A big, fat, fun-to-borrow issue this
week, Entertainment Weekly ($3.95) boasts almost 100 pages devoted
to the 100 greatest moments in rock 'n' roll, from the Beatles'
appearance on ``The Ed Sullivan Show'' to the tragic departure of
Ginger from the Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  EVERYONE'S A CRITIC: Who are those Internet mavens who divulge
plot lines, post secret movie scripts and fuel positive and
negative buzz? Yahoo! Internet Life ($3.99) introduces this
influential new breed of film geek, in particular Harry Knowles,
the outspoken (and well-padded) Austin, Texas, Web critic. Also in
this issue: a guide to the sites that made the new ``Star Wars:
Episode I _The Phantom Menace'' movie the Net's biggest event since
the Pathfinder landing on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SEX AND THE SINGLE GIRL: Since Bonnie Fuller departed
Cosmopolitan ($2.95) and arrived at Glamour ($2.99) the latter
woman's magazine has tended toward celebrity covers and such Helen
Gurley Brownish story ideas as ``How to make him worship the ground
you walk on'' and ``Get Moregasmic!'' This month's issue uses two
covers to gauge reader interest in more celebrity cover-girls:
copies with pop singer Shania Twain on the front will go to homes
in the South, Midwest and Canada; those with model Josie Maran will
go to both coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
