plea to her to return as president of party as they prepare for
elections in the fall. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HARASS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules, 5 to 4,
that school boards can be sued for student-on-student sex
harassment. Associate Justice O'Connor, in the majority opinion,
notes that sex harassment in schools is serious, and that when a
school district is on notice that a student's education is impaired
and does nothing it can be sued. In the view of the minority, this
decision opens the way for the federal government to get involved
in such things as student desk assignments. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MEDIA (Washington) _ Police violate the 4th Amendment
when they bring the media along to a home for a search and arrest,
the Supreme Court rules. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CONTINGENCY (Undated) _ Once stuck on the ``do later'' part
of the Year 2000 agenda, contingency planning is suddenly in full
swing. After months of weighing options, businesses and governments
are being forced to decide just how much they will invest in
preparing for Year 2000 turmoil. By Barnaby Feder.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-VOLPE (New York) _ Justin Volpe, the police officer
accused of torturing a prisoner inside a Brooklyn stationhouse,
will change his plea to guilty on Tuesday, his lawyer has told a
federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-PROFILING-DISMISS (Hackensack, N.J.) _ In a new legal
ramification of racial profiling by the New Jersey State Police,
state authorities have moved to drop drug and weapons charges filed
against 21 individuals, most of them black and Hispanic, by two
troopers now under indictment. On Friday, the Middlesex County
prosecutor, Glenn Berman, filed a motion for dismissal of the
indictments, after apparently deciding that the indictments against
the troopers, John Hogan and James Kenna, had seriously undermined
the cases. A court hearing is scheduled for Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-LOBBY-RIFT (Washington) _ The congressional battle over gun
control has exposed deep fissures in the gun lobby. Mounting
tensions between the National Rifle Association and the nation's
largest gun makers have weakened the NRA's political clout in
Washington, helping gun control advocates score several victories
in the Senate last week with the passage of the first gun control
measures since the Republicans took control of the Congress in
1994. It could also make it harder for the NRA to beat back similar
measures in the House. By James Dao.
