<HEADER>
A9371 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITIAN-ARTS-2TAKES-N     05-24 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITIAN-ARTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETERMINED TO PRESERVE HAITIAN ARTS IN MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When Dade County approved the renaming of several blocks
of Northeast Second Avenue, in the Little Haiti section of the
city, in honor of Felix Morisseau-Leroy, the revered Haitian poet
who died last fall, the planning of the ceremony in the
neighborhood fell to a man named Jan Mapou, who runs the parking
operations at Miami International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   It's a more sensible choice than it may sound, for Mapou is
probably Miami's leading advocate for the Haitian arts.
</P>
<P>
   Parking chief is his day job. In the evenings he can be found on
Northeast Second at Libreri Mapou, the bookstore he owns. It serves
as headquarters for Sosyete Koukouy, an organization of Haitian
painters, dancers and actors whose purpose is to strengthen and
perpetuate Creole, the Haitian patois, in particular and Haitian
culture in general. The name means Society of Fireflies. ``We
lighten up the darkness,'' Mapou said.
</P>
<P>
   In the back of the bookstore the other day, Mapou, 57, a man
whose genial manner doesn't entirely hide a sense of entitlement,
discussed invitations to the renaming ceremony with some society
members. They listed arts groups, Haitian business leaders and,
finally, members of local government, choosing two county
commissioners, the mayor and the Haitian consul.
</P>
<P>
   ``We forgot Clinton,'' someone said. And Mapou responded, ``We
have to stay away from the politicians completely.'' It was a joke,
but it was telling. Home to some 40,000 people, Little Haiti is a
tiny pocket of culture in this cacophonous multicultural region,
and a place where the local feeling is one of neglect, a perception
not generally disputed.
</P>
<P>
   Even a cursory drive-through shows that the neighborhood is a
poor one, not nearly festive enough to draw the tourism that many
of the denizens would like. The colorful Caribbean storefronts,
with pictographs of their wares painted on them; the streetside
vendors peddling mangoes and sugar cane; the botanicas, with their
voodoo elixirs and religious paintings _ they're all here, but
sprinkled amid ordinary urban squalor.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny but stubborn in the center of it sits Libreri Mapou. It
isn't the only focus for Haitian culture in the city (the
restaurant Tap-Tap, in South Beach, with its hand-painted tables
and impromptu musical performances, is better known), but in this
neighborhood it is an isolated phenomenon; the term cultural oasis
is appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Mapou,'' said Lavarice Gaudin, who owns a shipping
company in Little Haiti and is an officer of Ve Ye Yo, an advocacy
group concerned, among other things, with the fate of Haitian
refugees. ``He is doing good things to keep Haitian culture alive.
We need more places for our culture here. His is all we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy St. Legere, the society's dance director, said the Mapou
bookstore was a haven for the Haitian artists in Miami. ``This is
where we gather,'' said Ms. St. Legere, who works as a school
speech pathologist but lives an hour and a half away, south of
Miami, near Homestead. ``But it's a little sad, because I don't
think enough people realize how important it is to our community.''
</P>
<P>
   The store sells books about Haiti and by Haitian authors in
English, French and Creole. ``I can tell you I sell more books in
Creole to non-Haitians than to Haitians,'' Mapou said. ``When I ask
why, they say, `I want to communicate with you, in your musical
language.' It's very easy, you know. Three thousand words, and
that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   The store is also home to readings by Caribbean authors
(upstairs, inscriptions by writers like Edwidge Danticat and Dany
Laferriere adorn the walls), scholarly lectures and small art
shows. In the courtyard out back, the Sosyete dancers rehearse; as
Mapou spoke, the troupe, under Ms. St. Legere's direction,
practiced rara and congo dances, accompanied by drummers, whose
syncopated rhythms resounded in the back of the store.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The society, an outgrowth of an advocacy group called Movement
Creole Haitian (though the pronunciation is French), was founded in
Haiti during the autocratic reign of Francois (Papa Doc) Duvalier,
who insisted on French as the nation's official language even
though only a minority of Haitians spoke it.
</P>
<P>
   Creole had developed orally and had a scant written tradition,
and the Movement, of which Mapou was a founding member, was trying
to create written materials _ dictionaries and texts _ to
legitimize it. Sosyete Koukouy (pronounced SO-syuh-tay koo-KOO-yuh)
included Movement artists who performed in the Creole language and
drew on the traditions, in dance and song, of native folklore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government didn't like our group,'' Mapou said,
understating the case. He had been working as a banker, but he and
the rest of the group, he said, were accused of being Communists,
and eventually, in 1969, he and five other Movement members were
imprisoned. He spent four months and six days in the infamous Fort
Dimanche, hastening his expatriation.
</P>
<P>
   He left Haiti for New York City in 1971 and began spreading the
Creole gospel to the Haitian diaspora. ``In New York, there was
another problem,'' he said. ``The English language prevails. People
were not only neglecting the Creole language; they were neglecting
their culture.'' He spent more than a decade in New York; the
Sosyete chapter he established there remains.
</P>
<P>
   The Creole orthography was finally standardized in 1979; in
1987, a year after the Duvalier dynasty fell, Creole was
recognized, along with French, as an official language. A
literature began to explode. As president, Jean-Bertrand Aristide
``went to the U.N. and he spoke Creole; the pope went to Haiti and
he spoke in Creole,'' Mapou said. ``Now Creole is accepted, and we
are very proud we have played a role.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1986 Mapou began the Miami chapter of the Sosyete with
several other New Yorkers who had moved here. The headquarters were
initially elsewhere; but in 1990 Mapou opened his bookstore, next
door to its current location, little more than a stall, really, in
what remains the neighborhood's most distinguished building.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Caribbean Marketplace, it was designed by Charles
Harrison Pawley in emulation of Haitian gingerbread architecture,
with its wooden turrets and colorful facades, and with the idea of
bringing tourists to the neighborhood to shop for Haitian goods.
</P>
<P>
   As a measure of Little Haiti's despair, the building is less
than a decade old but is already slipping into decrepitude. Its
owners went bankrupt two years ago, and it was taken over by the
city, which, lacking funds for a proper restoration, ceded it to
the county. The county's cultural affairs department has allotted
$15,000 for an engineering assessment, after which it hopes to form
a public and private partnership to transform the building into an
arts center.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, this is what Mapou wants: a place to expand, a place
for Haitian painters and sculptors to exhibit their work and a
place for his dancers and actors to rehearse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had an arts showroom next door, do you know how many
tourists would come here?'' he said. This is a subject that gets
his dander up. ``In another neighborhood, a building like that
would never be allowed to go down the drain.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime the Sosyete is operating on limited resources.
The county provides a small annual grant. Other than that, Mapou
squeaks by on bookstore earnings and donations generated by good
will.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he supported the group and the bookstore building, he
responded in Creole. ``Gres kochon kwit kochon,'' he said. Then he
translated: ``The fat from the pig cooks the pig.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
