</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9378 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-POLITICS-ART-2T     05-24 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEEKING TO LEAD INDIA, SONIA GANDHI CHALLENGES THE NOTION OF WHO
IS INDIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ On Friday, the eighth anniversary of former
Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's assassination, his widow, Sonia,
canceled all her speeches, donned a white sari bordered in black
and made a sorrowful visit to the memorial where he was cremated.
</P>
<P>
   Her very public withdrawal into private grief deepened the gloom
of her bereaved political supporters. For days they had gone on
hunger strikes, burned her critics in effigy and even tried to
immolate themselves, all to convince ``Madam'' to come back as
president of the country's most venerable political party.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Mrs. Gandhi gave them what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   This enigmatic woman, who was raised a Catholic in a small town
in Italy and who rose to power through marriage into India's
founding dynasty, sent word to Congress Party officials that she
will lead them once again.
</P>
<P>
   Surely one of the most improbable of political leaders, Mrs.
Gandhi, 52, had abruptly resigned a week ago, saying she was deeply
wounded that three party leaders had revolted against her candidacy
for prime minister because of her foreign birth and political
inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   An emergency meeting of party members from all over the country,
which had been called for Tuesday in a last-ditch attempt to woo
her back, is now likely to turn into a coronation of the regal,
charismatic Mrs. Gandhi as the party's unquestioned leader and its
candidate for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The remarkable events of the past week have upended the politics
of India, the world's biggest democracy, just months before
national elections are to be held.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party, whose aging leaders have openly admitted
that they are abjectly dependent on Mrs. Gandhi to win elections,
has been saved from disintegration by her return.
</P>
<P>
   But last week the party, which had been poised to make electoral
gains against the Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, split
over the emotionally charged issue of Mrs. Gandhi's Italian
origins. The three party leaders who rebelled against her were
expelled on Thursday. They have vowed to start a rival political
force that could bring together a formidable alliance of regional
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a nation struggling to lift hundreds of millions of its
citizens from dire poverty, to make peace with neighboring Pakistan
and to manage its status as a new nuclear power, the dominant issue
of the September election is likely to be whether an Indian citizen
born and raised elsewhere should be allowed to serve as prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   It is a question that goes to the heart of the nation's idea of
itself. Does a person have to be born on Indian soil to be a true
patriot? Or can someone who believes in India's pluralistic
democratic ideals and who chooses to become an Indian become a
citizen equal to any other?
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the captivating melodrama is Mrs. Gandhi
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi, who survived her family's tragic, blood-soaked saga
with queenly reserve, has given only one interview in her life, and
that was 14 years ago to a Hindi-language weekly. Clues to her
character must come instead from her close friends and colleagues,
and a review of memoirs and histories about this most public of
families.
</P>
<P>
   What emerges is a portrait of a passionate, headstrong woman who
is capable of making startling, independent choices but who has
nevertheless been swept into the tumultuous, no-holds-barred
political life of India by forces larger than herself.
</P>
<P>
   The most fateful of her choices was that of a mate.
</P>
<P>
   The romance began in 1965: Fetching Italian teen-ager with long
chestnut hair chances to meet dark-eyed scion of Indian political
dynasty in homey Greek restaurant and falls in love.
</P>
<P>
   Rajiv Gandhi was then studying at Cambridge University. Sonia
Maino was an 18-year-old student at an English-language school in
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   She had been raised in a conservative home near Turin and had
only ``a vague idea that India existed somewhere in the world, with
its snakes, elephants and jungles,'' she has written.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   She knew nothing of Rajiv's family and the central role it had
played in the monumental struggle to wrest India's independence
from the British empire.
</P>
<P>
   Rajiv's grandfather, Jawaharlal Nehru, a patrician lawyer, spent
years in prison during the freedom movement and served as India's
first Prime Minister. Rajiv's mother, Indira Gandhi, a petite woman
with a ruthless instinct for power, become Prime Minister herself
in 1966 and dominated Indian political life for almost two decades.
(The family is not related to Mohandas K. Gandhi, the Mahatma, the
most prominent opponent of British rule.)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, shortly after Sonia turned 21, her father reluctantly
allowed her to move to India to wed Rajiv, an airline pilot.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Indian way, friends say, Sonia also married her
husband's family. She and Rajiv lived with his mother and her other
son, Sanjay, and his family. Sonia became the ideal bahu, an
obedient, devoted daughter-in-law. She attended to the comforts of
her mother-in-law, selecting elegant silken saris for her and
cooking her favorite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, after Indira Gandhi was thrown out of office by the
voters and thrown into jail by Parliament on charges of abusing her
official powers, it was Sonia who carried home-cooked meals to her
every morning and evening.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout these years, Rajiv and Sonia Gandhi led a
determinedly private life, content to leave politics to the brash,
imperious Sanjay, whom Indira Gandhi was grooming to be her
successor.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1980 Indira Gandhi, in an extraordinary political
comeback, once again became prime minister. Months later, Sanjay
died in a plane crash and Rajiv became the heir apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Gandhi has written that she fought ``like a tigress'' to
keep her husband out of politics. In a memoir published by Penguin
Books India the year after he was assassinated, she says she
remembers feeling ``every minute drawing us closer to the abyss.''
</P>
<P>
   But her husband accepted his obligation to his mother and became
a member of Parliament. His wife continued to look after the home
and took a course in the restoration of oil paintings. In 1983, 15
years after moving to India and 10 years after she became eligible
for citizenship, she became an Indian. She was 36.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the fates again intervened.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of Oct. 31, 1984, while Sonia Gandhi was bathing,
she heard a sound like firecrackers popping in the garden, followed
by screams. She rushed outside to discover that her mother-in-law,
the prime minister, had been shot by her own security guards. Sonia
Gandhi took Indira Gandhi's bullet-riddled body to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later Rajiv arrived and he and his wife sequestered
themselves. When P.C. Alexander, the prime minister's principal
secretary, burst in on them, a weeping Sonia was begging her
husband not to become prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Gandhi was sworn in that same day. He and his wife immediately
withdrew their two children, Rahul and Priyanka, from school
because of fears they would be vulnerable to attack. For the next
five years the children, studying with private tutors at home, were
``virtually imprisoned,'' their mother wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband won a landslide electoral victory later that year on
a wave of sympathy. The Nehru-Gandhi family, with its almost mythic
status, still exerted a hold on the people's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   But Gandhi's term was blighted by never-proven charges of
corruption, and he lost his bid for re-election in 1989. In 1991,
as he campaigned again, a suicidal terrorist detonated a bomb that
was strapped to her waist, ripping his body apart.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb also shattered the Congress Party. For years Indira
Gandhi had squelched dissent and undermined potential rivals.
Immediately after the assassination of Rajiv Gandhi, the family
loyalists turned to the grief-stricken Sonia to take over, but she
flatly refused.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Rajiv wasn't even cremated and those Congress oldies asked her
to be Congress president,'' said Mrs. Gandhi's longtime friend
Rupika Chawla, an art conservator. ``They were as vulgar as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi withdrew from political life to head the Rajiv
Gandhi Foundation in New Delhi and dedicate herself to promoting
girls' education and employment for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a stream of party leaders courted her. She listened, but
said little. Some called her the Sphinx.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   By late 1997 the faction-ridden party, led by an octogenarian,
seemed to be in its death throes. And so, after years of resisting
the tidal pull into politics, Mrs. Gandhi agreed to campaign for
Congress in the 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Chawla said she believes her friend became more
self-reliant after her husband's death. She was not pushed into
heading the Congress Party. She chose it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a legacy,'' Mrs. Chawla said. ``And there was no one
left, really.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi began the campaign in Sriperumbudur, where her
husband was assassinated, and barnstormed across the nation. She
presented herself as a traditional Indian widow dedicated to her
husband's memory and only in politics to save the family legacy and
to battle the Bharatiya Janata Party, which she believed was out to
destroy the nation's secular heritage by setting Hindu against
Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by her two children, she struck a deep emotional chord
with adoring crowds who flocked to hear her wooden reading of
speeches in Italian-accented Hindi.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, she agreed to be president of the party and set
out to rebuild its support among Muslims and the poor. She elevated
younger leaders, persuaded Congress to require that a third of its
officials be women and became its purposeful, public face.
</P>
<P>
   In November Congress roared to victories against the Hindu
nationalists in state elections.
</P>
<P>
   But then came the calamitous bid last month to topple the Hindu
nationalist-led coalition and form a new government headed by Mrs.
Gandhi. Congress succeeded, barely, in bringing down the
government, which lost a confidence vote by a single vote, but
failed miserably to create a new majority.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened critics began to say Mrs. Gandhi was a power-hungry,
incompetent politician, not the self-sacrificing widow her handlers
would have the public believe. Her credibility as a winner was
heavily damaged by her erroneous boast that she had the votes to
form a new government.
</P>
<P>
   Elections were called for September and October.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setbacks, thousands of people continued to flock to
Mrs. Gandhi's home to wait for hours in 105-degree heat for the
chance of a word with her. Twice a week, they passed through
intensive security checks to enter the grounds and array themselves
behind a metal fence built around a lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi recently spent almost two hours in the sweltering
heat, earnestly working her way around the fence. As usual, she was
impeccably dressed in an understated sari. Her dark hair was in its
trademark, shoulder-length flip.
</P>
<P>
   As the afternoon wore on, large sweat stains appeared under her
arms, but she did not quit until she had reached every last person.
To most, she just pressed her hands together in the prayerful Hindu
greeting. But many handed her crumpled pieces of paper with
scribbled requests for jobs, or medical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   But her prominence has brought strong criticism as well as
feudal adulation.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   She has not yet responded herself to questions about whether she
retained both her Indian and Italian citizenship, as Italy allows
and India forbids. Instead, surrogates say that such questions are
an insult and that of course she renounced her Italian citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   As proof of her Indianness, her friends and colleagues cite her
role as the traditional Indian daughter-in-law and widow, as well
as her superb taste in handloomed saris, her ease in eating with
her fingers and her use of cardamom and cloves to freshen her
breath.
</P>
<P>
   But their insistence betrays a fear that the issue of her
Italian birth may resonate. A recent poll for Outlook magazine
found that almost half those surveyed said her foreign origin
should disqualify her from being Prime Minister.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, when hundreds of Congress members from all over the
nation gather in New Delhi, Mrs. Gandhi is expected to give an
emotional speech that stakes her claim to be a committed Indian who
has already sacrificed her beloved husband for the greater good of
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chose India as my country,'' she declared in her letter of
resignation. ``I am Indian and shall remain so till my last
breath.''
</P>
</TEXT>
