A9385 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE25-COX     05-24 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE BACKS SUBSIDES FOR RELIGIOUS GROUPS DOING SOCIAL WORK
 &HT;    550&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Vice President Al Gore proposed Monday that the
government subsidize religious organizations so that ``the unique
power of faith'' can combat social ills.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, speaking at an adult rehabilitation center run by the
Salvation Army, embraced an idea first offered by Republicans as he
called for ``a new partnership'' between church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faith- and value-based organizations'' have already shown ``a
muscular commitment'' to facing the nation's social problems, Gore
said, and a partnership with government would allow them to have an
even greater impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen the difference faith-based organizations make,''
Gore said, citing the experiences of his wife, Tipper, in working
with the homeless at Christ Church in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the lesson to the nation is clear: in those
instances where the unique power of faith can help us meet the
crushing social challenges that are otherwise impossible to meet,
... we should explore carefully tailored partnerships with our
faith community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was introduced by Bradford Culpepper, a resident of the
rehabilitation center who marveled that he had the opportunity to
stand on the same platform with the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also shared the podium with Atlanta firefighter Matt
Mosely, whose daring rescue of a man trapped on a burning crane
mesmerized viewers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Gore proposed expanding the so-called ``Charitable Choice''
provision of the 1996 welfare reform law that allows states to
enlist ``faith-based'' organizations to provide basic services to
help move people from welfare to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must dare to embrace faith-based approaches that advance
our shared goals as Americans,'' he said. To do so would usher in
``a new era of civil society collaboration.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a former divinity student at Vanderbilt University, said
that approach should also be used for other social services, such
as drug treatment, homelessness and the prevention of youth
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that some civil liberties experts object that such
support could breach the constitutional wall between church and
state, Gore said there should be ``clear and strict safeguards''
against the government promoting a particular religious view.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president made a veiled reference to former President
Bush's emphasis on volunteerism, rather than expanded government
programs, in addressing social ills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some past national political leaders have asked us to rely on
a fragile patchwork of well-intentioned volunteerism to fee the
hungry and house the homeless,'' he said. ``That approach,
optimistic though it was, was not adequate for the problems too
many Americans face. It left too many American children behind to
suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, the vice president traveled to Conyers, where
he met privately for more than 45 minutes at Rockdale Baptist
Church with the families of students who were wounded in last
week's shootings at Heritage High School. Security was tight at the
meeting, and media were kept at a distance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore then returned to Atlanta for a reception and private dinner
that were expected to net some $350,000 for his campaign for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal to provide government subsidies to religious
charities is remarkably similar to welfare reform provisions
sponsored in 1996 by Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., and to initiatives
currently pushed in Texas by Gov. George W. Bush, the front-runner
for the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   His embrace of the ideas was ridiculed by the national chairman
of the Republican Party, Jim Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a welcome change of heart for someone who gave just $353
to charity in 1997, and whose best-known participation in a
not-for-profit religious organization was to hold a campaign
fund-raiser at a Buddhist temple,'' Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   The address, which his campaign promoted as a major statement on
values, came as the vice president began a three-day campaign swing
through the South.
</P>
<P>
   Gore struck similar themes earlier in the day in Orlando at a
luncheon that netted his presidential campaign an estimated
$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment industry should show ``more restraint'' in the
production of violent and sexually explicit entertainment, he said
from the stage of the Hard Rock Cafe next to the Universal Studios
theme park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Images affect behavior,'' he insisted, or there would be no
advertising industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``number one solution'' to the problems facing children
today is that ``parents need to do a better job,'' Gore added.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was flying late Monday night to Texas, where he plans two
more days of events.
</P>
<P>
   According to a news release provided by his press office, Gore
planned Tuesday to announce a regulation reassuring families that
enrolling for government benefits would not affect their
immigration status.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new regulation will improve the health of our families by
addressing widespread confusion that prevents legal immigrants from
signing up for health insurance, school lunch, child care and other
essential programs,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
