<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, May 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably cool air will cover the interior Northeast and
Great Lakes states Tuesday as a powerful storm cuts off from
upper-level steering winds over southern Ontario. The front marking
the leading edge of the cooler air will pass through Maine during
the morning, accompanied by heavy rain and thunderstorms.
Meanwhile, a chill rain will fall on the low's western flank in
upper Michigan and northern Wisconsin as a conveyor of moisture
remains over the area.
</P>
<P>
   To the south, several spokes of upper level energy rotating
around the storm will ignite scattered showers punctuated by peals
of thunder from the southern Great Lakes to the northern
Appalachians. Some of the showers will be accompanied by small hail
and gusty winds.
</P>
<P>
   Ample sunshine will occur from southern New Jersey to Florida.
It will be breezy and noticeably less humid in much of the Piedmont
as the moist air mass of Monday has been replaced by much drier
Canadian air.
</P>
<P>
   Slow-moving showers and thundershowers will form in parts of
Texas, Oklahoma and the southern Rockies as moist air is forced to
ascend the sloping terrain. Localized flooding is possible,
especially along mountain streams in southern Colorado and northern
Mew Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, bright sunshine will grace areas from central
California to the northern Plains as high pressure from the surface
to 18,000 feet drifts slowly eastward. Readings will be quite mild,
with the exception of the immediate Northwest coast where onshore
breezes and low clouds will keep temperatures in the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Hot and Cold
</P>
<P>
   The mercury topped out Sunday at 91 degrees in Portland, Ore.,
tying the record high for the date. In fact, much of the Pacific
Northwest and Northern California have experienced great warmth
lately. A northward retreat of the jet stream has prompted offshore
breezes across the region, limiting the cooling effect of the
Pacific Ocean. Often, when the Northwest gets very warm, portions
of the Northeast turn cool. True to form, a return to chillier
weather will arrive across the Northeast early this week behind a
strong cold front that moved off the Atlantic seaboard Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9397 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-OIL-ART-NYT &LR;      05-24 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-OIL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DESPITE NATO EFFORTS, MILOSEVIC KEEPS HIS FLOW OF OIL AND
CASH (Exclusive)  
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As part of the campaign against President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia, the Clinton administration and NATO have
tried to cut off his oil supply and his bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   It is a campaign that has not gone well, American and NATO
officials say. Barges are filled with oil in Ukrainian ports and
cross the Black Sea to chug up the Danube River through Bulgaria
and Romania. To pay for it, Milosevic is using money he secreted in
banks in Cyprus during the earlier period of sanctions against
Yugoslavia, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration and European governments have appealed to
Ukraine to shut down the trade and they have asked Cyprus to freeze
Milosevic's bank accounts, American and NATO officials say, but to
no avail.
</P>
<P>
   During his visit to Washington last week, Gen. Wesley Clark,
NATO's commander, raised alarms about the oil shipments traveling
up the Danube and said that action needed to be taken to stop them.
He said this route was increasingly being used because NATO had
been somewhat successful in choking off the supply coming into
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   American officials say that they do not have a good fix on the
volume of oil Milosevic is getting through this route _ he is still
getting some from ships unloading at Montenegrin ports _ but they
say that it is Russian oil. The deals are being arranged by
middlemen who are making a tremendous profit because of the risks
involved, the officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how much oil Milosevic was getting, one administration
official said, ``All he needs.'' Another official said that was an
exaggeration, but he conceded that the Serbian leader was getting
enough oil to keep his military machine going. A third official
replied, simply, ``Too much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and NATO have tried to deal with the
matter quietly, fearing that making it a public issue could
backfire.
</P>
<P>
   When an oil embargo was last in effect against Yugoslavia, from
1992 until the signing of the Dayton peace accords in 1995,
Bulgaria and Romania were major conduits for oil in violation of
the sanctions. (Greek and Italian oil companies were major
suppliers, with most of their oil moving through Albania, a route
that has now been largely shut down.)
</P>
<P>
   But Washington and European capitals expect to have more success
now. The governments in Bulgaria and Romania have become more
stable and have better-trained law enforcement agencies; above all,
they have moved from their Communist pasts, expressing a strong
desire to get into NATO and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bulgaria and Romania have not been as cooperative as the
administration would like.
</P>
<P>
   The governments argue that they cannot interfere with traffic on
the Danube because it is an international waterway covered by the
Danube Convention of 1948, which calls for free movement of ships.
But American officials dismiss those assertions, noting that the
convention was signed by the Danube riparian states when they were
part of the Soviet Union; West Germany was the one Danube state
that did not sign.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, American and NATO officials say, the major problem is
Ukraine, which is the source of the oil transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week during meetings in Brussels, Belgium, Boris Tarasyuk,
Ukraine's foreign minister, was cordially but firmly told that his
country must stop the barges from loading up with oil in the
Ukrainian ports, a NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
   Tarasyuk countered with complaints about the economic damage
Ukraine was suffering because of the war against Yugoslavia. He
said that it had cost his country $220 million in lost trade, that
Ukrainian ports alone had lost $12 million, and that a Danube
shipping company in Ukraine was losing $313,000 a day. Who was
going to compensate Ukraine for that, he demanded of the NATO
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and NATO are not confident that they
will prevail upon the Ukrainian government. Nearly 90 percent of
the Ukrainian population is against the NATO bombing, according to
recent polls there, an American official said. It is for this same
reason that the administration does not feel that it can make a
public issue out of Ukraine's lack of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   In Cyprus, too, the Clinton administration is worried about
upsetting the government and so has not said anything publicly, but
it is not happy that the Cypriots have refused to close the bank
accounts belonging to Milosevic and to the Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
   With its secretive banking laws, Cyprus has become a major
money-laundering center, especially for Russian organized criminal
operations, American and European law-enforcement officials say.
European law enforcement officials say that many of the continent's
cigarette-smuggling operations use Cyprus, including an operation
in which one of Milosevic's sons is involved.
</P>
<P>
   American officials say they do not know how much Milosevic has
in these accounts, in part because finding his assets had never
been a priority of the CIA, several officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But however much is in them, the Cypriots argue that there is no
basis for seizing the bank accounts because there are no United
Nations sanctions against Yugoslavia. Most of the sanctions against
Yugoslavia that were imposed in 1992 were lifted after the Dayton
peace accords in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But back when the sanctions were in effect, Cyprus did not
cooperate either.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always found loopholes,'' an American official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9398 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-ANGEL-COX     05-24 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-ANGEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Venture capitalists 'angels' in disguise?
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Venture capitalists and ``angel'' investors get a lot
of attention for funding private company deals. But a report on
small business financing shows they aren't as generous as popularly
believed.
</P>
<P>
   They provide just over seven percent of the financing for
private U.S. companies with 20 or more employees, a former
economist with the Securities and Exchange Commission concludes.
Susan Woodward, now chief economist with the San Francisco
investment bank OffRoad Capital Corp., based her findings on two
government reports: The Federal Reserve Bank's National Survey of
Small Business Finance and its Call Report data. The Call report
contains mandatory monthly filings from banks regarding their
assets. The Fed's survey is based on 1993 data but Woodward also
used the change in bank loans to businesses between 1993 and 1998
to estimate the change in all small business financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised,'' Woodward said. ``Venture capital gets a
huge amount of attention in the press. It's so sexy and exciting.
Their offices are so opulent. They're so well paid. And the buzz is
that they earn spectacular returns.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, venture capitalists provided half of what private
individual investors or angels gave. Part of the reason venture
capitalists get so much attention, Woodward surmises, is because
they tend to give money for many business that wind up doing
initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of small business financing comes from
traditional sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``They mortgage their houses, God bless 'em. Then they get money
from family and friends,'' she said. Or it's debt financing from a
bank or trade credit.
</P>
<P>
   The findings illustrate ``a crying need'' for investment banks
to help investors and entrepreneurs find each other, Woodward said.
</P>
<P>
   One promising trend is the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is going to make a huge difference,'' Woodward
said. ``It's going to be the vehicle that will make it much easier
to get investors and entrepreneurs together.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco-based Hambrecht and Wit Capital of New York are
examples of two online investment bankers. And it's not as scary as
some might think.
</P>
<P>
   Says Woodward: ``It's much less scary than just plain trading
over the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   There are roughly 5 million small businesses in this country
with payrolls. They have more than $2.7 trillion in book assets,
according to data from The Fed and the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Joyner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9399 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-MEDIA-HNS &LR;      05-24 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-MEDIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE CAN'T BRING PRESS ON RAIDS OF PRIVATE HOMES, COURT RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Police are violating privacy rights protected by
the Fourth Amendment when they let TV camera crews and other
journalists accompany them on so-called ``media ride-alongs'' into
private homes to observe arrests or searches, the Supreme Court
ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a violation of the Fourth Amendment for police to bring
members of the media or other third parties into a home during the
execution of a warrant when the presence of the third parties in
the home was not in aid of the execution of the warrant,'' Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist wrote for the court in unanimous
decisions in cases from Montana and Maryland
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth Amendment allows law enforcement officials to enter
private property and homes to conduct a search or seizure only
after a warrant has been signed by a judge _ unless the police are
in active pursuit of a criminal suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows officers to bring along a third party only in
situations where the person is acting ``in aid of'' law enforcement
_ such as an informant to identify a suspect, a translator if
necessary, or someone who can identify stolen goods.
</P>
<P>
   News media lawyers have argued that reporters on assignments
with police do aid law enforcement by publicizing the government's
efforts to combat crime, facilitating accurate reporting on law
enforcement activities and protecting suspects from abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But in Monday's opinion, Rehnquist disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely, the possibility of good public relations for the
police is simply not enough, standing alone, to justify the
ride-along intrusion into a private home,'' Rehnquist said. ``And
even the need for accurate reporting on police issues in general
bears no direct relation to the constitutional justification for
the police intrusion into a home in order to execute a ...
warrant.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision means that from now on law enforcement
officers can held liable to pay monetary damages for violating the
Fourth Amendment's ban on unreasonable searches and seizures.
</P>
<P>
   But the court, by an 8-1 vote, also ruled that the law on
whether the media had a right to accompany police was unclear in
1992 and 1993 when the incidents that led to the two cases took
place. Therefore, the justices ruled, the Montana and Maryland
police who allowed the press to come along were immune to the
lawsuits against them.
</P>
<P>
   Only Justice John Paul Stevens voted to let both lawsuits
proceed to trial. He said the constitutional violations were clear
back in 1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union said Monday that the rulings
mean police must be guided by the Fourth Amendment, not by the
demands of the ``infotainment'' industry.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Dratel of the National Association of Criminal Defense
Lawyers, added that ``the government is not allowed to make a
display of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Richard Cordray, who represented the police officers in
both cases, said the rulings still will allow media to accompany
police officers as long as the journalists stay outside when
officers enter private homes.
</P>
<P>
   But attorney Lee Levine, representing the Associated Press and
other news organizations who sided with law enforcement officers,
said the rulings may discourage police from allowing the media to
accompany them even for permissible purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad for the public in the sense that the public won't get
to see, through the press' eyes, that important aspect of the
government's work,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision comes at a time when some police
departments are restricting news media access during police raids.
For example, Los Angeles Police Department guidelines, issued in
March, bar TV camera crews from entering homes and other private
property without owners' permission.
</P>
<P>
   In the Maryland case, Montgomery County sheriff's deputies and
deputy U.S. Marshals were accompanied by a Washington Post
photographer and reporter when they entered the Rockville home of
Charles and Geraldine Wilson the morning of April 16, 1992, in
search of the couple's son, Dominic. He was wanted on felony
charges of robbery, theft and assault with intent to rob.
</P>
<P>
   After entering the Wilsons' home, the photographer took several
pictures, although they were never published. Dominic was not in
the house when police arrived, but at his parents' request, he
surrendered later that day.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilsons sued the police, claiming their Fourth Amendment
rights had been violated. An appellate court agreed that the media
should not have accompanied the police but dismissed their suit
saying the law on the issue was unclear. On Monday the Supreme
Court agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In the Montana case, about 20 federal agents accompanied by a
CNN camera crew arrived at Paul Berger's sheep and cattle ranch
near Jordan on March 24, 1993, to search for evidence that Berger
was poisining eagles. At his trial, Berger was acquitted of all
charges except improper use of a pesticide, a minor offense.
</P>
<P>
   CNN eventually used footage of the raid in a story about
government efforts to protect endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco ruled
that Berger could sue the federal authorities who organized the
raid and allowed the television crew to come along. ``The record
... suggests that the government officers planned and executed the
search in a manner designed to enhance its entertainment, rather
than its law-enforcement, value,'' the appeals court said. The high
court agreed with that reasoning but said the lawsuit should not
proceed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
