<SLUG> BC-FBC-CARTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carter cleans out baseball locker _ for now By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Quincy Carter does not plan to return to the
Chicago Cubs farm team in Daytona Beach, Fla. this summer, but the
Georgia quarterback said he has not closed the book on his
professional baseball career.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, an outfielder for the Cubs' Class A affiliate, cleaned
out his locker and left the baseball team before a game Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been going at it in two sports for such a long time now,
I just felt I needed some rest,'' Carter said Monday. ``Since the
end of last season, I've been going to class, hitting the books,
going through winter workouts, going through spring (football)
practice. I spent my spring break at spring training. I'm just
physically and mentally drained.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said the Cubs ``have been very understanding.'' The team
placed him on the temporary inactive list and told him to take all
the time he needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at it as that big an ordeal,'' said Jim Hendry,
the Cubs director of scouting and player development. ``Basically,
he told me he mentally and physically needs a blow, which is
understandable considering what he's done the last year. But he
hasn't closed the door on baseball. And there's no doubt in our
minds he can be a major-league baseball player. It doesn't hurt his
status with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, a sophomore, said he plans to move back to Athens today
and spend the rest of the summer ``resting my body and getting
ready for football.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's departure from the baseball team fueled speculation
that he was leaning toward a football-only career and possibly an
early exit into the NFL. He recently left agent Lonnie Cooper, who
specializes in baseball contracts, and signed on with agent Eugene
Parker, who represents Deion Sanders, another two-sport star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still love baseball, and I still want to play it,'' Carter
said. ``I just want to take some time off this summer to evaluate
myself as a two-sport athlete.'' Carter hit .215 in rookie league
in 1996 and .211 at Class A Rockford (Ill.) in 1997. He went 0 for
3 in his only appearance at Daytona. In football, Carter was named
SEC Freshman of the Year after throwing for 2,484 yards and 12
touchdowns. Georgia is touting him as a Heisman Trophy candidate
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
