<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OWNERS-MEETING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moment of truth for Redskins franchise while consequences of
raising expansion fees await owners
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a setting appropriate to their mission, NFL owners
in the next two days will huddle at a hotel, raise the ante on
franchise fees and reinforce the league's status as the strongest
and best-positioned in sports history.
</P>
<P>
   Probably before lunch today, the owners will approve the sale of
the Washington Redskins to Bethesda, Md., businessman Daniel Snyder
for a record $800 million. That amount exceeds by more than 50
percent the $530 million fee Al Lerner paid last year for the
resurrected Cleveland Browns franchise.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the session adjourns Wednesday evening, however, the
bar could be pushed even higher, particularly if owners agree on a
minimum fee for the expansion franchise targeted for Los Angeles in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the expansion committee met Monday evening to hear
presentations from businessman Eli Broad and entertainment mogul
Michael Ovitz, the two prominent suitors for the Los Angeles
franchise. League officials are expected to announce today that
they are endorsing Ovitz's plan for refurbishing the Los Angeles
Coliseum. Despite his original plans for a shopping, sports and
entertainment complex in suburban Carson, Ovitz has fallen in line
with the league's preference for a revamped Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz offered the design to the NFL for free and without
strings, meaning that the league could adopt the concept but still
award the franchise to a different bidder. however, the owners
probably won't overlook that display of largess, especially
considering that they covet Ovitz's entertainment connections and
his ability to connect the league to a younger and hipper audience
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Using several buzz-phrases adopted by the league, Ovitz told the
Los Angeles Times that his plan ``is dedicated to making it a
fan-friendly day'' at a game.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz faces a couple of potential hurdles. While his group is
prepared to finance a $298 million stadium, it will require public
monies for five to seven parking garages, which will provide 27,000
spaces on site and are central his plan. And Broad, who commands
political support in Los Angeles and is committed to funding the
stadium, is claiming special and exclusive rights to bring NFL
football to the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old Snyder, who survived an ill-fated partnership
with Howard Milstein, apparently faces no opposition to his
Redskins deal. The finance committee last week unanimously
recommended his bid, assuring the culmination to a long and
occasionally acrimonious process that began with the death of late
Skins owner Jack Kent Cooke.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL also will brief owners on plans for a new stadium for
the New England Patriots and on Wednesday will present the upgraded
system for the return of instant replay. The system features
digital tape and touch-pad technology.
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
