<HEADER>
A9404 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-NUMBERS-TAKE1-     05-24 1736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-NUMBERS-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We've got your number: From 00 to 100, there are numbers linked
to great figures and events of sports
 &HT;    (EDS: IN TWO TAKES _ TAKE 1)
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sometimes, a great notion comes in a comfortable,
inspirational setting. Like many of the great revelations of the
20th century, this idea took flight in a virtual think tank. In a
press box, during a rain delay.
</P>
<P>
   In Turner Field last October, while the Braves and Padres waited
for the rain to stop and Game 1 of the NLCS to begin, three minds
spent nearly two hours pondering one of life's eternal mysteries:
Who's the best athlete, for each number, 1-99? Or your favorite
athlete _ or sports memory, or year _ inextricably tied to each
number? Wait. Make that 0 _ no, 00 _ to 100.
</P>
<P>
   There was Marty Noble, baseball writer from Newsday. There was
the lovely and talented Janet Ward, a magazine editor who also
works Braves games for SportsTicker and is, even better, my wife.
And I was the third. Like both of them and most of you, I identify
certain numbers with certain athletes.
</P>
<P>
   What's in a number? Almost everything, if you're into sports.
You say 8, I say Yogi, some guy in Athens says _ Buck Belue? Well,
yes. You say 23, we all say Michael. On some numbers, we can agree
that they are the one and only. For most others, we have our
personal preferences, or rank them 1-2-3. Gold, silver and bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Noble calls it his sports DNA. Numbers say a lot about our
sporting makeup: who we are, where we grew up, our ages and
stations in life. I'm 48 and was born in New York, where I spent
most of my life before moving to Atlanta in 1983. That explains a
lot about my list: the early New York influence, the
Atlanta-come-lately stuff, the dearth of current NBA bricklayers.
</P>
<P>
   This is a subjective list. That's part of the beauty of sports.
Who was better, Bird or Magic? And it doesn't include just
Hall-of-Famers and All-Stars. While we associate greatness with
specific numbers, some numbers also evoke sporting moments and
milestones, favorite athletes or unforgettable teams. These are
numbers we mark our lives by.
</P>
<P>
   This is the sort of thing sportswriters do while waiting for the
skies to clear. Hey, look. The rain's stopped. Play ball! Here's my
list. By the numbers, 00-100. What's yours?
</P>
<P>
   00 Jim Otto, the Raiders center, was an even better blocker than
a palindrome. And Johnny Vander Meer, the only pitcher to throw
back-to-back no-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   0 Johnny Olszewski was literally ``Johnny O,'' his nickname and
number while a Redskins' fullback in the '50s and early '60s. Nolan
Ryan never wore zero but should have; he fired seven no-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   1/8 The uniform number worn by Eddie Gaedel, Bill Veeck's
short-lived, pinch-hit midget who had a fraction of a career. On
Aug. 19, 1951, the 3-foot-7 Gaedel walked in his only at-bat before
AL president Will Harridge banned him the next day.
</P>
<P>
   1 John Wooden finished No. 1 with UCLA 10 times. Pee Wee Reese,
No. 1 in your program, was No. 1 in Brooklyn's hearts and the
little leader of the original, the real Dodgers. No one, not even
Pee Wee, fielded like the Wizard of Oz, Ozzie Smith.
</P>
<P>
   1A Muhammad Ali's draft classification.
</P>
<P>
   1.12 How do you define domination? Bob Gibson's earned-run
average in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   2 Nellie Fox, chaw bulging in his left cheek, turning two for
the White Sox. The $2 window at the track. And Ernie Banks, Mr.
Cub, who wore No. 14 but always suggested, ``Let's play two!''
</P>
<P>
   3 Babe Ruth. Period. No one else belongs here. (Sorry, Murph.)
</P>
<P>
   3:59.4 To Sir with admiration. Long before he was knighted,
Roger Bannister broke the four-minute mile barrier on May 6, 1954.
</P>
<P>
   4 Lou Gehrig. The Iron Horse was the Babe's cleanup hitter and
the pluckiest man on the face of the earth in the face of death.
Bobby Orr, bad knees and all, was hockey's nonpareil defenseman. In
the '50s, New York debated the merits of its three future Hall of
Fame center fielders: Willie, Mickey and The Duke _ Edwin Snider,
the Duke of Flatbush.
</P>
<P>
   5 Joe DiMaggio. Joltin' Joe has left and gone away but will
forever be 5. End of debate. Yet in the interest of marital bliss,
let's not forget my wife's favorite O, Brooks Robinson. And I can
still see Paul Hornung running the Packer sweep.
</P>
<P>
   6 Bill Russell revolutionized basketball defensively and was
most responsible for the Celtic dynasty. Stan Musial was the Man,
Julius Erving the Doctor.
</P>
<P>
   7 The Mick. Mickey Mantle. But there's room in seventh heaven
for John Elway. Even Mark Spitz, who swam to seven Olympic gold
medals in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   7 7/8 Bear Bryant's houndstooth hat size.
</P>
<P>
   8 Yogi Berra. He is 8. Said so right on his back when he
squatted behind home plate. No 8 was as steadfast as Cal Ripken,
though, and Carl
</P>
<P>
   Yastrzemski was a great 8, too.
</P>
<P>
   9 By any name _ The Splendid Splinter, Teddy Ballgame _ Ted
Williams was No. 9. Yet this hockey holy trinity left crowds on
Cloud 9: Gordie Howe. ``The Golden Jet,'' Bobby Hull. And Maurice
``Rocket'' Richard.
</P>
<P>
   10 Even 29 years after giving Brazil its third World Cup, Pele
remains soccer's greatest star (1,281 goals in 21 years and World
Cups in 1958, '62 and '70). Whether as Walt Frazier or his alter
ego ``Clyde,'' the Knicks guard glistened on and off the Madison
Square Garden court. Nadia Comenici and Mary Lou Retton were
perfect 10s when it mattered most.
</P>
<P>
   11 Phil Simms, the near-perfect (22-for-25) MVP of Super Bowl
XXI. And a Messiah and an Isiah: Mark Messier hoisted Lord
Stanley's Cup five times, and Isiah Thomas made the Pistons' Bad
Boys of the late '80s watchable. Barely.
</P>
<P>
   12 Joe Namath. I guarantee it. So did Broadway Joe, in Super
Bowl III. As a kid, I went to Philadelphia to see Roger Staubach
and Navy beat Army, long before he became Roger the Dodger in
Dallas. When Jim Thorpe, already a two-time football All-American,
won the decathlon and pentathlon at the 1912 Olympics, Sweden's
King Gustav V crowned him, ``The greatest athlete in the world.''
Thorpe's reply? ``Thanks, King.''
</P>
<P>
   13 Wilt the Stilt. Wilt Chamberlain was nigh-unstoppable
everywhere _ but the foul line. Nobody's thrown it better than Dan
Marino.
</P>
<P>
   14 Every kid wears a certain number for a certain hero. Mine was
14, for Y.A. Tittle, who passed the New York Football Giants to
three NFL Championship Games in a row in the early '60s. Alas, I
didn't have Y.A.'s arm. Fortunately, I don't have his hairline.
Yet. The Big O, Oscar Robinson, wore 14 for most of his career.
Pete Rose hustled a hit or two wearing 14, too.
</P>
<P>
   15 Bart Starr swung the baton for Lombardi's Packers. As a
Bullet and a Knick, Earl Monroe was ``The Pearl'' personified.
Thurman Munson, a terrific catcher and even better father, died far
too young.
</P>
<P>
   16 Joe Montana. QB XVI might be the best quarterback of all
time. Whitey Ford was the original Mr. October. George Blanda
played football until age 48 and went out kickin'.
</P>
<P>
   17 Ted Turner. As in, WTBS, Channel 17. When the Braves signed
Andy Messersmith, baseball's first free agent, Turner turned
tailor. While other Braves had their last name sewn above the
number on the back of the jersey, Turner ordered that Messersmith
be replaced with ``Channel.'' Baseball quickly canceled Channel 17,
the uniform. In Boston, John Havlicek never stopped moving, or
winning.
</P>
<P>
   18 Father and son, Archie and Peyton Manning. Martina
Navratilova and Chris Evert won 18 Grand Slam singles titles each.
</P>
<P>
   19 Johnny Unitas. If not Montana, then Johnny U _ backpedaling
in hightop black cleats _ was the best QB. Willis Reed dragged his
injured right leg onto the court in 1970 and promptly hit his only
two shots to ignite the Knicks' Game 7 rout of L.A. for their first
NBA championship. Tony Gwynn is the premier hitter of the age.
</P>
<P>
   19.32 Michael Johnson's world record time in the 200 meters at
the 1996 Olympics. The Man with the Golden Shoes became the first
male to double in the 200 and 400.
</P>
<P>
   20 Frank Robinson is the only man to win the MVP in both the
American and National Leagues. Who's a better runner, Lou Brock or
Barry Sanders? And Sergey Bubka raised the pole-vaulted ceiling to
20 feet, and higher.
</P>
<P>
   21 Roberto Clemente was a complete player and a complete person.
Every multi-millionaire ballplayer is indebted to Curt Flood; if
Flood had fought baseball's reserve clause even earlier, imagine
how much money another 21 _ Warren Spahn _ would've made. And
'Nique, our own human highlight film, Dominique Wilkins.
</P>
<P>
   22 Elgin Baylor, who begat Doctor J, who begat Michael. Dave
DeBusschere once played ``DEE-fense!'' and hit the open man when
Red Holzman's Knicks made beautiful string music together. Run,
Emmitt Smith, run.
</P>
<P>
   23 Michael Jordan, the one and only 23, the most rarefied Air of
all.
</P>
<P>
   24 Willie Mays. Say ``Hey'' for the man some now consider the
greatest living baseball player. Ken Griffey Jr. may be his heir.
</P>
<P>
   25 No one did more to help Bobby Cremins build Georgia Tech
basketball than Mark Price. In the mind's eye, Fred Biletnikoff,
forearms taped in white, is still catching passes.
</P>
<P>
   26 Some numbers are more popular than others. Herb Adderley, one
of the few memorable 26s, was a great All-Pro defensive back with
the Green Bay Packers in the '60s. Who ended Pete Rose's 44-game
hitting streak? No. 26, Gene Garber.
</P>
<P>
   27 The 1927 Yankees of Ruth and Gehrig, baseball's best. Carlton
Fisk, before he exchanged his Red Sox for White and reversed his
number to 72. And Navy's Joe Bellino, who won the 1960 Heisman
Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   28 Steve Blass. Long before there was Mark Wohlers, there was
Blass, who went from 1971 World Series hero to mysteriously losing
his control, and career.
</P>
<P>
   29 John Smoltz, who's got grit and great stuff galore, back in
Cy Young form. Few swings are/were sweeter than Rod Carew's, hitter
extraordinaire.
</P>
<P>
   29-2 1/2 Bob
</P>
<P>
   Beamon. At the 1968 Olympics in Mexico City's altitude, in the
single most extraordinary feat in track-and-field history, Beamon
obliterated the long jump record by nearly two feet.
</P>
<P>
   30 In 1930, Atlanta's Bobby Jones became the only golfer to
capture a recognized Grand Slam by winning the U.S. and British
Opens, and U.S. and British Amateurs. Maury Wills, the first to
steal 100 bases in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
