<HEADER>
A9405 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-NUMBERS-TAKE2-     05-24 2087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-NUMBERS-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We've got your number
 &HT;    (EDS: TAKE 2 OF 2)
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   30-30 Bobby Bonds, the 30-homer, 30-steal prototype.
</P>
<P>
   31 A thoroughbred and a Doggie. Secretariat's 31-length victory
in the 1973 Belmont Stakes made Big Red the first Triple Crown
winner since Citation in '48. Greg (Mad Dog) Maddux is the best
pitcher of his time. And Jim Taylor was Hornung's lead blocker and
the most bruising fullback this side of ...
</P>
<P>
   32 Jim Brown, football's finest running back and arguably its
greatest player. Sandy Koufax, too briefly baseball's greatest
left-hander. And Magic Johnson, who transformed the point. With
apologies to such 32s as Elston Howard, Bill Walton, Steve Carlton,
Karl Malone and Cookie Gilchrist (but not O.J.) at the most
log-jammed number of all.
</P>
<P>
   33 Kareem Abdul-Jabbar. No NBA player ever had more points or a
more lethal shot than Kareem's Sky Hook. Larry Bird did everything,
all the time, playing the game the way it was meant to be played.
By any pronunciation, Tony Dorsett could run the ball.
</P>
<P>
   34 Anywhere else, it's Sweetness. Here, it's Herschel Walker,
then Walter Payton, finally Bo Jackson (pick a sport; I'll choose
Auburn football).
</P>
<P>
   35 Follow the bouncing ball. Phil Niekro and Knucksie's
fluttering knuckler.
</P>
<P>
   36 Jesse Owens' four gold medals in the 1936 Olympics infuriated
Hitler. Meadowlark Lemon was the Harlem Globetrotters.
</P>
<P>
   37 Casey Stengel won big with the Yankees, birthed the Amazin'
Mets and spoke in hilarious tongues. The late, great Doak Walker,
whom Ricky Williams honored last season.
</P>
<P>
   38 The flip sides of 38: Gary Anderson, wide left from 38 yards
out in the fourth quarter of the 1998 NFC Championship Game. And
Morten Andersen, perfect from 38 in overtime to put the Falcons in
Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   39 Zonk and Campy. Larry Csonka was Don Shula's battering ram,
Roy Campanella Brooklyn's beloved backstop.
</P>
<P>
   40 Gale Sayers, both before and after the knee, ran like the
wind. Theron Sapp, ``The Drought Breaker,'' whose touchdown beat
Georgia Tech 7-0 in 1957 and ended Georgia's eight-year losing
streak against the Jackets. In 1978, Tech's Eddie Lee Ivery rushed
through the snow for a then-NCAA record 356 yards at Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   41 Eddie Mathews, power hitter and Hall of Famer. Tom Seaver,
power pitcher and Hall of Famer. Matt Snell, power fullback on the
Super Bowl Jets.
</P>
<P>
   42 Jackie Robinson. Thank you, for everything.
</P>
<P>
   42L Connie Mack's suit size. Essential for a man who never
managed in a uniform.
</P>
<P>
   43 Richard Petty. The King in the 43 car. Mark Wohlers, all of
it: the final out of the '95 World Series; the hanging slider to
Jim Leyritz; the too-painful-to-watch loss of control. And Carl
``Spider'' Lockhart, the late, pretty-great safety of the New York
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   44 The great Henry Aaron. The one and only Hammer. (With
apologies to Zeke from Cabin Creek, Jerry West.)
</P>
<P>
   44.2 _ Pistol Pete Maravich's career scoring average at LSU.
</P>
<P>
   45 Archie Griffin, the only two-time Heisman Trophy winner.
Homer Jones, one-time New York Giants receiver who invented the
celebratory touchdown spike.
</P>
<P>
   46 Jack Nicklaus' age in 1986, when he became the oldest winner
of the Masters. His sixth Masters title gave Nicklaus a record 20th
win in a major.
</P>
<P>
   47 Tom Glavine. The mantle of Mr. Brave has been passed with
care, from Aaron to Niekro to Dale Murphy to the little
left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   48 Oklahoma's try for a record 48th consecutive football victory
under Uncle Bud (coach Bud Wilkinson) ended in a 7-0 loss to Notre
Dame in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   49 Joe Louis' career KOs in 66 fights. Ron Guidry was Louisiana
left-handed lightning for the Yankees, Bobby Mitchell a blur out of
the backfield in both Cleveland and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   50 In 1950, City College of New York became the only school to
win the NCAA and NIT tournaments in the same season. And that
right-hander on your 1950 Boston Braves? No. 50, Ernie Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   51 Dick Butkus, the true monster of the Midway. And Russ Hodges'
radio delirium in 1951: ``The Giants win the pennant! The Giants
win the pennant!'' after Bobby Thomson's bottom-of-the-ninth homer
off Brooklyn's Ralph Branca gave the Giants the pennant.
</P>
<P>
   52 His were banker's hours. As Keith Wilkes at UCLA, he learned
to bank wing jumpers under Wooden; as Jamal Wilkes in the NBA, he
banked nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   53 The 53 Defense, so named for linebacker Bob Matheson's jersey
number with the 1972 Miami Dolphins, the only team in NFL history
to go 17-0.
</P>
<P>
   54 The number of years the New York Rangers wandered hockey's
wasteland before finally winning the Stanley Cup in 1994, their
first since '40.
</P>
<P>
   55 Who's a Bum?! At blessed last, Brooklyn wins its first World
Series over the hated Yankees in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   56 Joe DiMaggio's epic 56-game hitting streak, baseball's
unbreakable record.
</P>
<P>
   57 Jeff Van Note, once the vintage Falcon. In 1957, North
Carolina's triple-overtime upset of Wilt Chamberlain and Kansas in
the NCAA final.
</P>
<P>
   58 Jessie Tuggle, now our vintage Falcon. Jack Lambert, the
saber-toothless tiger in the middle of Pittsburgh's Steel Curtain.
Bill Bradley's 58 points off Wichita State in the 1965 NCAA
consolation game, still a Final Four record.
</P>
<P>
   59 Al Geiberger's PGA record low round of 59, since tied by Chip
Beck and David Duval, who shot 59 in the final round last January
to win the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic.
</P>
<P>
   60 Tommy Nobis, the first and fiercest Falcon of all.
</P>
<P>
   61 Roger Maris, 61 in '61.
</P>
<P>
   62 Charlie Trippi, the Georgia halfback who some consider
Georgia's greatest all-around athlete. Trippi was runner-up to
Army's Glenn Davis in the 1946 Heisman Trophy voting but won the
Maxwell Award that year as the nation's best player.
</P>
<P>
   63 Just days after President John F. Kennedy was assassinated on
Nov. 22, 1963, NFL commissioner Pete Rozelle had the league play
its Sunday games as scheduled. A young Bulls guard named Michael
Jordan scored 63 against Boston in the 1986 playoffs, still an NBA
playoff record.
</P>
<P>
   64 Green Bay right guard Jerry Kramer, leading Bart Starr's
sneak into the end zone in the final seconds to beat Dallas 21-17
in the Ice Bowl, the 1967 NFL title game.
</P>
<P>
   65 Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium opened in 1965 as the home of
the Atlanta _ Crackers. The beloved minor-league club left Ponce de
Leon Park to play its last season in the big ballyard in the round.
Tiger Woods shot 65 in the third round of the '97 Masters enroute
to his record-setting 270, 18-under victory.
</P>
<P>
   66 Sammy Sosa's 66 homers in '98. The skill of Mario Lemieux,
the brutality of Ray Nitschke. And 1966, Bobby Dodd's last season
as head coach at Georgia Tech, several months after all-black Texas
Western's 72-65 triumph over Adolph Rupp's all-white Kentucky
Wildcats in the most significant NCAA final.
</P>
<P>
   67 In 1967, Vince Lombardi's third NFL championship in a row
with Green Bay and fifth in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   68 Tommie Smith and John Carlos raise their black-gloved fists
in protest after winning the gold and bronze medals in the men's
200 meters at the 1968 Olympics in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   69 The Miracle Mets, whose pitching kiddie corps shut down
Baltimore to win the '69 World Series. Somewhere, Gil Hodges is
still smiling.
</P>
<P>
   70 Mark McGwire's 70 homers in '98. Now a stretch of I-70 in St.
Louis is named in Big Mac's honor.
</P>
<P>
   71 Elgin Baylor's then-NBA record point total against the Knicks
on Nov. 15, 1960, in the old Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   72 The 1972 Munich Olympic massacre of 11 Israelis by Arab
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   73 David Thompson's point total against Detroit in 1978, second
only to Wilt.
</P>
<P>
   74 The D-line: Bob Lilly. Merlin Olsen. And Alex Karras, who
talked an even better game.
</P>
<P>
   75 More D: Mean Joe Greene. David ``Deacon'' Jones. And John
Wooden's 10th and last NCAA title, in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   76 When Indiana topped Michigan for the 1976 NCAA championship,
the Hoosiers finished 32-0 _ the last Division I team to go
undefeated and win the national title. Big Daddy Lipscomb, RIP.
</P>
<P>
   77 ``The Galloping Ghost,'' Red Grange. John McEnroe won 77
singles and 77 doubles tennis titles.
</P>
<P>
   78 Eddie Robinson was 78 in 1997 when he coached his 55th and
last season at Grambling, where Coach Rob won a record 408 games.
</P>
<P>
   79 The 1979 Magic-Bird, Michigan State-Indiana State NCAA final
remains the most-watched NCAA title game in TV history.
</P>
<P>
   80 No one was meaner, badder or better than Georgia's Junkyard
Dawgs of 1980, the national champions. Jerry Rice is the best
receiver ever. Wayne Chrebet? Hofstra guy.
</P>
<P>
   81 Mr. End Zone Dance Fever himself, Billy ``White Shoes''
Johnson. And two old Italian stallions: defensive ends Gino
Marchetti and Andy Robustelli.
</P>
<P>
   82 Raymond Berry, who ran the most precise routes ever. The
Braves' record 13-0 start en route to the 1982 NL West title.
</P>
<P>
   83 The last of the New York Islanders' four straight Stanley
Cups came in 1983 at the expense of Edmonton. In the NFL's best
quarterback draft ever, six were taken in the first round,
including three sure Hall of Famers: Elway, Marino and Jim Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   84 Forty-eight years hence, Carl Lewis duplicates Jesse Owens'
Olympic record by taking four gold medals at the Los Angeles Games
in the 100, 200, long jump and 400-meter relay.
</P>
<P>
   85 Del Shofner (``Tittle _ to Shofner _ touchdown!''). And Ol'
Red Eyes, Max McGee.
</P>
<P>
   86 Through the wickets of Bill Buckner and the Mets, truly
amazingly, win the '86 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   87 Claude Humphrey, rushing the passer in Atlanta-Fulton County.
</P>
<P>
   88 Lynn Swann, the Baryshnikov of the post pattern. Alan Page,
an NFL MVP defensive tackle with the Vikings' Purple People Eaters,
now a Minnesota Supreme Court judge. And UCLA's 88-game winning
streak, stopped in '74 on a jumper by Notre Dame's Dwight Clay.
</P>
<P>
   89 Mike Ditka, who played tight end with a single-bar facemask
and singular ferocity. Otis Taylor, the Chiefs fleet wideout,
personified the AFL's wondrously wide-open style.
</P>
<P>
   90 1990, the year of Georgia Tech's co-national football
championship; if Colorado hadn't had five downs against Missouri,
the Jackets would've won it outright. And Mr. 90 Feet himself,
Abner Doubleday.
</P>
<P>
   91 1991, the best Braves season ever. From worst to first.
</P>
<P>
   92 Francisco Cabrera in the 1992 NLCS. Or, as Skip told us, ``A
lot of room in right-center. If he hits one there, we can dance in
the streets. The two-one. Swung. Line drive! Left field! One run is
in. Here comes Bream. Here's the throw to the plate. He
isssssssssssss _ safe! Braves win! Braves win! Braves win! Braves
win!'' Pause. ``BRAVES WIN!!!'' Jackie Joyner-Kersee, the finest
female athlete, won her second Olympic heptathlon in Barcelona in
'92.
</P>
<P>
   93 Distance of the most famous touchdown pass in Georgia history
and Buck Belue's life, the last 20 yards of which Larry Munson
described thusly before falling off his chair: ``Lindsay Scott!
Lindsay Scott! LINDSAY SCOTT!!!''
</P>
<P>
   94 In baseball's darkest moment since the Black Sox scandal, the
disgraceful cancellation of the 1994 World Series, because of the
players' strike and owners' intransigence.
</P>
<P>
   95 At long last, your 1995 Atlanta Braves, World Champions.
Who's next? Goldberg, No. 95 as an undersized defensive lineman
with Georgia and the Falcons, now the larger-than-life king of WCW
Wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   96 When the world truly came to Atlanta. The 1996 Centennial
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   97 The number of pitches thrown by Don Larsen in Game 5 of the
1956 World Series. That 2-0 win over Brooklyn is the only perfect
game in Series history.
</P>
<P>
   98 The 1998 world champion New York Yankees, whose 125 total
wins are the most ever in a season.
</P>
<P>
   98.84 The percentage of votes Tom Seaver received in the 1992
Hall of Fame balloting, the highest in the voting for Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   99 The Great One, Wayne Gretzky. (Sorry, George Mikan.)
</P>
<P>
   100 Wilt the Stilt. On March 2, 1962, in Hershey, Pa., Wilt
Chamberlain scored 100 points against the Knicks. It's the most
ever scored in an NBA game and in the Hershey Arena. More than
ever, unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   Disagree with Jack Wilkinson's choices? Got some numbers of your
own to add, or subtract? Let us know what you think. By telephone:
404-222-2031. By mail: P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta 30302. By e-mail:
sports(AT)AJC.com. Please include your full name and city.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
