<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN, FEINGOLD SHARE COURAGE AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The long and mercurial bid of US Senators John McCain
and Russell Feingold to reform campaign finance netted Monday the
first Profile in Courage Award to be shared by elected officials of
opposite parties.
</P>
<P>
   The senators, who united to press for legislation to limit the
impact of so-called soft money on federal elections, said at the
ceremony in the John F. Kennedy Library that they are confident the
bill will pass this year.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, both men stood by the principle of
fund-raising reform, putting their political careers in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold and McCain ``are two courageous men who have nothing to
fear before the courts of history,'' said Caroline Kennedy
Schlossberg, who helped judge the 10-year-old contest named for her
father, President John F. Kennedy, for his 1957 Pulitzer
Prize-winning book ``Profiles in Courage'' about elected officials
who risked their political careers for their beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The awards come with $25,000 stipends, which McCain and Feingold
said they plan to donate to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold, a Democrat from Wisconsin, nearly lost a reelection
challenge from Republican Mark Neumann after the incumbent swore
off private donations.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold kept his word even after the bipartisan bill died last
September when its supporters could not muster the 60 votes needed
to break an opposition filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative McCain, an Arizona Republican, said his policy
priorities differ sharply from those of Feingold and Senator Edward
M. Kennedy, who participated in the awards ceremony. But he said he
considered reform worthy of bucking his party leadership last year
and again this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we abolish soft money, Americans will never have a
government that works as hard for them as it does for the special
interests,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold said he does not interpret the award as a personal pat
on the back for his decision to limit fund-raising in his own
campaign. ``The award is the ideal way to spur us on to get the
last few votes . . . and put an end to this system of legalized
bribery that has overtakn our democracy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Senator Kennedy said he is a strong supporter of
the bill, but declined to seize the occasion to forswear soft money
donations to his 2000 reelection campaign. He said he will conform
with established laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm hopeful we'll have it passed by then,'' Kennedy said
after the ceremony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
