<HEADLINE>
JAMES E. DOWD, WAS PRESIDENT OF BOSTON STOCK EXCHANGE; 77 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending, fixing lede; a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- James E. Dowd, former president of the Boston Stock
Exchange, died of cancer Sunday in the Lahey Clinic in Burlington.
He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Dowd was president of the Boston Stock Exchange from 1969 to
1982. During his tenure he organized the New England Securities
Depository Trust Co., a subsidiary that offers a computerized book
entry system for members, and established BOSECO (for Boston Stock
Exchange Co.), which offers members access to the world's major
stock exchanges through associate member seats held by the Boston
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Dowd, of Concord, was born in Cambridge. He interrupted his
studies at Boston College to serve in the Army during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the Irish-looking face,'' as he said in a story
published in the Globe on Jan. 13, 1966, he became an interpreter
of Italian. He was then sent to the Pacific Theater ``to get the
best use of my training,'' he told the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Following the war, he graduated from Boston College and its law
school.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to becoming president of the Boston Stock Exchange, Mr.
Dowd was responsible for preventing abuses in the securities
industry as New England regional administrator of the Security
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the fact that New Englanders have the reputation of
looking at both ends of a nickel before they spend it,'' he said in
1966, ``a lot of money has been taken out of New England
fraudulently.''
</P>
<P>
   After stepping down as president of the Boston Stock Exchange,
Mr. Dowd was a consultant to the American Stock Exchange and a
director of Federated Investors Inc., the Dresdner R.C.M. Europe
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Marguerite (O'Donoghue); a daughter, Anne E.
Goodhue of Concord; two sisters, Alice I. Dowd of Arlington and
Grace E. Shea of Hyde Park; and two granddaughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
