<SLUG> BC-GORE-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TO ANNOUNCE POLICY CHANGE TO HELP IMPROVE HEALTH OF LEGAL
IMMIGRANTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore will announce Tuesday in
Texas a new Department of Justice regulation reassuring legal
immigrants that their application for some government benefits will
not affect their residency status.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, joined by President Clinton, will host the fifth annual
White House Community Empowerment Conference at the University of
Texas-Pan American at Edinburg to highlight the success of creating
jobs in hard-pressed areas such as South Texas. He also will raise
campaign money Wednesday in Dallas and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's office said the new regulation would clarify a
misconception that deterred some legal immigrants from applying for
Medicaid or a series of children's services, such as school lunch,
child care services and the new Children's Health Insurance
Program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new regulation will improve the health of our families by
addressing widespread confusion that prevents legal immigrants from
signing up for health insurance, school lunch, child care and other
essential programs,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the new regulation may meet some opposition in
Congress, where some lawmakers believe it will send the wrong
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans believe that immigration policy should bring people
to our country who will work hard and contribute, but these rules
will increase the number of immigrants on welfare who will be able
to bring in more immigrants to go on welfare and are an insult to
all Americans _ native born and immigrant,'' said Rep. Lamar Smith,
R-San Antonio and a Republican pointman on immigration issues.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, an unannounced candidate for president, also will make the
announcement in the heavily Hispanic area of South Texas. The
Hispanic vote is expected to be critical in the 2000 election
cycle, especially in states such as Texas and California.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush's capture of more than 40 percent of
the Hispanic vote in his re-election campaign last year _ a record
high for a Republican in the state _ is one of the factors that has
made him the front-runner for the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's statement said the 1996 immigration reform law and the
welfare reform law generated confusion among many legal immigrants
that an application for certain public benefits would deem them a
``public charge'' and subject them to deportation and denial of
permanent residency status.
</P>
<P>
   It cited a 1998 Urban Institute study that found a 21 percent
drop in Los Angeles County in the number of legal immigrants
applying for available programs between January 1996 and January
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Eligible legal immigrants can receive, without fear of
jeopardizing their immigration status, health insurance, which
includes Medicaid and Children's Health Insurance Program, access
to immunization, testing and treatment of communicable disease,
access to nutrition programs and other support programs, such as
child care services, housing assistance, energy assistance,
emergency disaster relief, foster care, adoption assistance,
transportation vouchers, educational assistance and job training
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also will direct federal agencies that oversee those
programs to send the new guidelines to their field offices, program
grantees and community organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will raise campaign money at a lunch in Dallas and a dinner
in Houston, where supporters must contribute at least $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
