<HEADER>
A9441 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-HARASS-1STLD-WR     05-24 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-HARASS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS MAY BE SUED OVER STUDENT-TO-STUDENT SEXUAL HARASSMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (EDs: ADDS 6 grafs of reaction after 8th graf starting Title IX
...)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ School systems around the country were put on
notice Monday that they must stop students from sexually harassing
their classmates or face the possibility of paying costly damages
to the victims.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-4 decision, the Supreme Court ruled that teachers and
school administrators who fail to stop student-to-student sexual
harassment may be violating a federal anti-bias law known as Title
IX.
</P>
<P>
   The court said a school district that accepts federal funding
can be held financially responsible for the sexual harassment of a
student if officials with the authority to help the child knew
about the harassment but were ``deliberately indifferent'' to it.
</P>
<P>
   In defining the harassment the court said it must be so
``severe, pervasive and objectively offensive'' that it prevents
the victim from learning or taking part in school activities.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' ruling was similar to a high court decision last
June that school districts can be held responsible when teachers
sexually harass students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recipients of federal funding may be liable for subjecting
their students to discrimination where the recipient is
deliberately indifferent to known acts of student-on-student sexual
harassment and the harasser is under the school's disciplinary
authority,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote for the court
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling reversed a 7-4 decision by 11th Circuit Court of
Appeals saying that Title IX never applies to student-on-student
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Title IX of the Education Amendments of 1972 bans sexual
discrimination in any educational institution that receives federal
money. The Supreme Court has long treated sexual harassment as a
form of illegal bias.
</P>
<P>
   The decision triggered sharply divided reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The National Education Association, representing more than 2.4
million teachers and school administrators, said the ruling will
help children attend school in an environment free of harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson here is that school districts should work to
prevent harassment from occurring in the first place through
education and training programs for students and staff,'' NEA
President Bob Chase said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lisa Brown, who wrote a friend-of-the-court brief for the
National School Board Association, predicted the decision will lead
to more lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see teachers and administrators spending more
and more time in court and with their lawyers,'' she said, adding
that the ruling will also give courts more control over the
day-to-day running of classrooms. ``Federal courts will slowly but
surely begin to make guidelines that will have to be followed by
teachers and principals,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia D. Greenberger, co-president of the National Women's Law
Center, a Washington-based group promoting women's legal rights,
said, ``This ruling extends to students basic protections against
sexual harassment that prevents them from getting the education
they deserve and have a right to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's case centered around LaShonda Davis, who was a
fifth-grade student at Hubbard Elementary School in Forsyth, Ga.,
in the 1992-1993 school year.
</P>
<P>
   Over a five-month period, a classmate of LaShonda, known only as
G.F., made her life unbearable. Whenever the chance arose, he tried
to grab her breasts, rub against her in the hallway or say sexually
explicit remarks, such as he wanted ``get in bed'' with her. One
day, G.F., whose desk was next to LaShonda, put a doorstop in his
pants and gestured suggestively.
</P>
<P>
   LaShonda and her mother, Aurelia Davis, repeatedly told her
teacher about G.F.'s behavior. They were assured that the principal
had been informed and that something would be done to stop G.F. But
nothing was done, and G.F. continued to taunt and grope.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, LaShonda's mother went directly to the principal,
who said he would look into the matter. But again, nothing
happened.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Aurelia sued the Monroe County School Board in federal
court, claiming that teachers and school administrators had not
done enough to protect her child from sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, a U.S. District Court dismissed the Davis
lawsuit, saying, ``The sexually harassing behavior of a fellow
fifth-grader is not part of a school program or activity.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the 11th Circuit Court upheld that decision, ruling
that while Title IX authorizes suits for sexual harassment, its
coverage did not extend to harassment by one's peers.
</P>
<P>
   However, the appeals court's decision in the Davis case appeared
vulnerable after the Supreme Court's ruling last June. The high
court said then, also in a 5-4 decision, that monetary damages
could be granted if a school official who had authority to do
something about harassment of students by school employees ``has
actual notice of or is deliberately indifferent'' to the
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday O'Connor was joined in her opinion by Justices John
Paul Stevens, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G.
Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Anthony M.
Kennedy, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas dissented.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the four, Kennedy said, ``We can be assured that
like suits will follow _ suits, which in cost and number, will
impose serious financial burdens on local school districts, the
taxpayers who support them and the children they serve.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at (202) 298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
