<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CHINA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Details of China's spying `frightening'
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An explosive 700-page congressional report
documenting China's efforts to obtain sensitive U.S. technology and
military secrets will be released today with an unusual stamp of
bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   The original mission of the special House investigatory
committee was to uncover possible campaign fund-raising and export
policy abuses by the Clinton admin- istration.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the nine-member panel headed by Rep. Christopher Cox
(R-Calif.) has uncovered an aggressive spy network that spans two
decades and both Democratic and Republican administrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an investigation of the Clinton administration,''
Cox said. ``This is an investigation of the espionage by the
People's Republic of China.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The spying is pervasive and it is frightening to see how much
they stole,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Cox was appointed by former House Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.)
last summer to investigate whether Clinton had compromised national
security by approving export licenses for American satellite makers
who had given generously to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The report finds that Chinese officials used a variety of
approaches to acquire U.S. military technology including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Using 3,000 so-called ``front companies'' operated by Chinese
nationals living in the United States to obtain information on
commercial satellites and other sensitive technology made here.
</P>
<P>
   _ Illegally diverting ``dual use technology,'' technology with
both commercial and military capabilities to solely military
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Applying pressure on U.S. companies to share sensitive
technology in joint ventures such as commercial satellite launches
in China.
</P>
<P>
   _ Engaging military personnel to engage in spying at nuclear
laboratories throughout the country, including Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory and Los Alamos Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The report also finds that interagency conflicts among the
Justice Department, CIA and Energy Department led to delays in
probing espionage at the nuclear facilities.
</P>
<P>
   After briefing senators last week about the report's findings,
lawmakers suggested over the weekend that Attorney General Janet
Reno consider resigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the Justice Department is adrift,'' said Sen.
Richard Shelby (R-Ala.), chairman of the Senate Intelligence
Committee on CBS's ``Face the Nation'' on Sunday. ``I believe it's
time, considering her role or lack of role.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelby's committee recently released its own report on China's
efforts to obtain military secrets, alleging that lax monitoring of
satellite exports has enhanced Beijing's ability to develop highly
sophisticated missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli (D-N.J.), a staunch supporter of the
administration, appeared to agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something wrong when the United States Congress on a
bipartisan basis has so little confidence in the chief law
enforcement officer of the United States,'' said Torricelli,
appearing on the same television program.
</P>
<P>
   The White House supported Reno, saying it would be
``inappropriate to prejudge'' the attorney general before the
report is released.
</P>
<P>
   As for the allegations that valuable nuclear secrets have been
stolen, White House Spokesperson Joe Lockhart said Monday that the
administration is ``under no illusions'' about the spy operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do try to acquire technology that, for whatever reason,
they can't produce indigenously,'' Lockhart said. ``And that has
gone on . . . for 40 years and probably longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
