<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-NASA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTDOWN BEGINS FOR SHUTTLE MISSION TO SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a lengthy hiatus in shuttle missions and a bleak stretch
for U.S. military and commercial rocket launches from Cape
Canaveral, Fla., NASA is poised to help lift the nation's space
program from the doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle Discovery and a crew of seven are to blast off at
6:48 a.m. EDT Thursday from NASA's Kennedy Space Center. The
countdown for the 10-day mission to the unstaffed international
space station began Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters predicted a slight chance that fog would delay
liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   The flight will mark the first shuttle launch in nearly six
months. It comes on the heels of a disastrous several weeks for the
Lockheed Martin Titan 4 and Boeing Delta 3 unmanned rockets
launched from the Cape Canaveral Air Force Station that adjoins
Kennedy. Last week, the situation prompted President Clinton to
order a sweeping probe of the seemingly unrelated incidents as the
losses surpassed $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency will forge ahead with Discovery's launching,
claiming it has staved off concerns that its shuttle work force has
grown rusty because of the unusually long hiatus in missions _ the
longest since the fatal 1986 Challenger accident suspended flights
for 32 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team definitely feels prepared,'' said NASA test director
Doug Lyons, who supervised Discovery's countdown activities Monday.
``We do have confidence in ourselves and the hardware.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent shuttle flight blasted off Dec. 4. Its crew
joined the first two components of the new station several days
later.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle flight rate has sunk to its lowest annual total
since 1989. No more than five shuttle sorties are planned for 1999,
the same as last year.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the shuttle's role now is dedicated to assembly of the
U.S.-led international space station. The temporary decline in
flights is attributable primarily to a 19-month delay in Russia's
launching of the new outpost's habitable service module. The
module's launching is tentatively targeted for late November from
Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The service module's arrival at the new station should unleash a
flurry of shuttle missions with a backlog of U.S. station
components.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't noticed any rustiness, but it's something we need to
be cognizant of,'' said veteran astronaut Kent Rominger,
Discovery's commander.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's flight was delayed one week so that shuttle
technicians could repair damages caused to the shuttle's fuel tank
by a recent hail storm.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the training by the astronauts as well as by lead flight
director Wayne Hale's mission control teams in Houston and the
launch control teams at Kennedy involves the rehearsal of elaborate
flight plans with realistic ground simulations.
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday, the Air Force successfully launched a massive,
unmanned Titan 4 with a classified reconnaissance satellite from
Vandenberg Air Force Base, Calif. Though most details of the
mission are secret, it apparently broke the run of Titan mishaps
from Cape Canaveral that prompted the White House investigations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those included losses April 9 and April 30 of Titan 4s with
Defense Support Program missile early warning and Milstar
communications satellites. The string of losses from Florida began
Aug. 12 with the explosion of a Titan 4 with another classified spy
satellites 40 seconds after lifting off from Cape Canaveral.
</P>
<P>
   On May 4, Boeing's new Delta 3 expendable rocket suffered its
second mishap with a commercial communications satellite after
lifting off from Cape Canaveral. The first Delta 3 mishap from the
Florida launch complex occurred last Aug. 26 as the rocket lifted
off with another commercial communications satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery pilot Rick Husband sees no link to the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of those are unmanned vehicles,'' he said. ``They are not
required to have the same level of safety as the manned vehicles
are supposed to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've seen talking to the folks at Kennedy and the
folks (at Johnson) they seem very professional in their approach
and very thorough in the preparations. I'm impressed in the pride
they take in their work,'' Husband said. ``This really hasn't
generated any additional concern for me or my family or friends.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's crew arrived late Sunday at Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Rominger and Husband, they include fight engineer
Ellen Ochoa, mission specialists Tammy Jernigan and Dan Barry,
Canadian astronaut Julie Payette and Russian cosmonaut Valery
Tokarev.
</P>
<P>
   After docking with the new station, the shuttle crew will
transfer nearly 2 tons of supplies for the first resident crew that
is slated to arrive early next year as well as to make repairs to
the power and satellite communications systems.
</P>
<P>
   Jernigan and Barry plan a spacewalk of almost seven hours during
which they will install U.S. and Russian made cargo cranes on the
outside of the outpost.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
