<HEADER>
A9446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-NYT &LR;      05-24 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., La.)  
 COURT RULING KEEPS TWO AVENUES OPEN IN DISABILITY CASES  (jw) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday examined two federal
laws aimed at protecting disabled workers and concluded that,
contrary to a lower court's view, there was no inevitable conflict
between them.
</P>
<P>
   One was the Social Security Act, which provides benefits to
people whose disabilities are so severe that they cannot ``engage
in any substantial gainful activity'' for at least 12 months. The
other was the Americans With Disabilities Act, which protects
workers with disabilities from discrimination as long as they can
perform the job's essential functions, with ``reasonable
accommodation'' if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Some lower courts have ruled that because someone who has
applied for or received Social Security disability benefits is by
definition unfit for employment, such a person is either barred
from suing for disability discrimination or faces special judicial
hurdles in pursuing a disability lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous opinion Monday by Justice Stephen Breyer, the
court disagreed. The two laws appear ``divergent,'' Breyer said,
but in context, they ``do not inherently conflict'' and ``can
comfortably exist side by side.'' He said the Social Security
program, receiving more than 2.5 million claims for benefits every
year, necessarily made broad determinations without a fine-tuned
examination of an individual's situation _ for example, whether
employees who cannot work without accommodations can return to work
if their special needs are addressed.
</P>
<P>
   The decision overturned a grant of summary judgment won by a
company that had dismissed a woman who tried to come back to work
after a stroke. The employer would not give her the extra time and
special training she said she needed. She applied for and received
Social Security benefits, at the same time suing the employer for
failing to accommodate her under the Americans With Disabilities
Act.
</P>
<P>
   In ruling for the employer, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in New Orleans held that the application for or receipt of
Social Security disability benefits had created the presumption
that a worker was not entitled to bring a discrimination suit
against the employer. Only in ``some limited and highly unusual set
of circumstances'' could the two laws not be seen as ``mutually
exclusive,'' the appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion Monday, Cleveland vs. Policy Management Systems
Corp., No. 97-1008, Breyer said it was common in the legal system
for people to pursue two alternative theories at once. When there
is an apparent inconsistency in the disability context, he said,
courts should not erect special burdens but should simply require
the plaintiff to explain the inconsistencies.
</P>
<P>
   He indicated that the explanation could be as simple as a
medical condition that had changed over time. The case now goes
back to the lower courts to give the plaintiff, Carolyn Cleveland,
a second chance at her discrimination suit.
</P>
<P>
   Beatrice Dohrn, legal director of the Lambda Legal Defense Fund,
a gay rights organization that filed a brief in the case, said the
decision could be particularly beneficial to people with the virus
that causes AIDS. With drug therapy, she said, people with HIV
often ``move in and out of being able to work'' and often face
discrimination on the job when they do work. The decision ``broke
down a barrier that people with HIV needed to get past,'' Ms. Dohrn
said.
</P>
<P>
   The court's other rulings Monday included these:
</P>
<P>
   --Nonprofits. The Federal Trade Commission has jurisdiction to
prevent certain nonprofit organizations, in this case a state
dental association, from engaging in unfair competition or
deceptive practices, the court ruled unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission Act, which dates to 1914, gives the
commission authority over the business practices of ``persons,
partnerships or corporations,'' with a corporation defined as an
organization ``which is organized to carry on business for its own
profit or that of its members.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the trade commission found that the 19,000-member
California association unreasonably restricted trade by placing
strict limits on the types of advertising dentists could use. The
nonprofit association challenged both the commission's jurisdiction
and its findings, both of which were upheld by the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In an opinion by Justice David Souter, the Supreme Court agreed
Monday on the jurisdictional question. Souter said it was
sufficient that members received economic benefits from the
association, such as favorable insurance rates as well as lobbying,
public relations, and other activities.
</P>
<P>
   But, Souter said, the Court of Appeals made too cursory an
analysis of the advertising restrictions before concluding that
they had an anti-competitive effect. The case, California Dental
Association vs. FTC, No. 97-1625, was sent back to the appeals
court for a new, more searching analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on that section of the opinion was 5-4. Breyer, joined
by Justices John Paul Stevens, Anthony Kennedy and Ruth Bader
Ginsburg, said the Court of Appeals properly found that the
restrictions on advertising prices and quality claims had deprived
consumers of useful information.
</P>
<P>
   --Property rights. The court ruled 5-4 that a property owner
suing a local government for depriving him of his right to develop
his property was entitled to have the case tried by a jury rather
than solely by a judge.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, City of Monterey vs. Del Monte Dunes, No. 97-1235,
affirmed a ruling by the 9th Circuit and was a victory for
developers, who view juries as more sympathetic than judges in this
type of case. The developer in this case spent years trying to get
permission to build houses on 37 acres of ocean-front property in
California, eventually winning a $1.45 million award from a jury on
the claim that the protracted proceedings violated its
constitutional right to due process.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy wrote the majority opinion, which was joined by Chief
Justice William Rehnquist and by Justices Antonin Scalia, Clarence
Thomas and Stevens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
