<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9449 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-SKOL-HARASS-CO     05-24 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-SKOL-HARASS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Supreme Court says school systems responsible for sexual
harassment complaints
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ School systems can be held liable and ordered to pay
damages to victims if educators ignore student complaints of sexual
harassment by classmates, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling drew mixed reactions from school officials and
lawyers who represent school systems. Some said similar policies
are in place or being drafted anyway, while others predicted
schools would act without trying to distinguish between harassment
and teasing.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-4 decision, the court sided with Aurelia Davis, a
Forsyth, Ga. woman who sued the Monroe County Board of Education,
claiming school officials did nothing to stop repeated sexual
harassment of her fifth-grade daugher by a male student at the
elemantary school they attended.
</P>
<P>
   The high court said parents such as Davis can sue a school board
under a federal law known as Title IX, which bans sexual
discrimination in any educational institution that receives federal
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited because this ruling is not just for me, it's
for parents of all schoolchildren,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling will require school boards to adopt sexual harassment
policies for students and make them known to teachers and students,
said Davis' lawyer, Verna Williams of the National Women's Law
Center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Although Monroe County allegedly had no such policy in 1992,
policies against students sexually harrassing other students are
becoming commonplace, if not universal. Large school districts in
the metro area, for example, all point to existing policies
prohibiting student-on-student harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling is so important, because the Supreme Court is
saying that schools can't turn their backs on student-to-student
sexual harassment. Up until today, that was an open question. Now
it's the law,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for a national group of school administrators
worried that the ruling will result in schools trying to protect
themselves by imposing harsher discipline for seemingly minor
incidents, such as last year's suspension of a first-grader in
North Carolina who kissed another student.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to hope the court has not taken flexibility out of
the hands of the officials who have to enforce discipline in our
schools,'' said Bruce Hunter of the American Association of School
Administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, writing for the majority, sought to
limit the scope of the decision, saying school districts can be
found liable only if educators knew about a student being sexually
harassed and did nothing. The legal standard of ``deliberate
indifference'' is a high threshold for plaintiffs to clear, but it
is the same standard the court adopted last year when it ruled in a
Texas case that school districts can be held liable when teachers
sexually harass students.
</P>
<P>
   In her ruling, O'Connor also said the alleged sexual harassment
must be so severe and so pervasive that it impedes a student's
ability to learn. ``Damages are not available for simple acts of
teasing and name-calling among school children...even where these
comments target differences in gender,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, this is not saying that kids can't be kids, she
said, directing courts to keep in mind that schools are unlike the
adult workplace and that ``children may regularly interact in a
manner that would be unacceptable among adults.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a scathing dissent, Justice Anthony Kennedy said the
decision inflicts the federal government on the nation's school
rooms and imposes ``potential crushing financial liability'' on
school districts already overwhelmed by violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can be assured that like suits will follow _ suits, which
in cost and number, will impose serious financial burdens on local
school districts, the taxpayers who support them and the children
they serve,'' Kennedy wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy also criticized the majority for failing to give more
precise direction to school districts about what type of limits can
be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``After today, Johnny will find that the routine problems of
adolescence are to be resolved by invoking a federal right to
demand assignment to a desk two rows away,'' wrote Kennedy, who
took the unusual step of reading at length from his dissenting
opinion in open court.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor responded in court by saying concern for ``little
Johnny'' should not drive ``little Mary'' from the classroom in
tears.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Underwood, general counsel for the National School Boards
Association, sought to downplay the ruling's significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it means thousands of lawsuits will be filed,''
she said. ``School boards can be held liable only if they actually
knew and did nothing. I think that's going to be a rare occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Allbritten, Georgia Association of Educators director,
expressed concern over the time and money schools might have to
spend defending against frivolous lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there wil be a rash (of suits) for awhile,''
Allbritton said. ``Then, once common sense prevails, it'll be
something that's just intergrated in an appropriate way into
character education and student codes of conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Georgia, he said, any weaknesses in current
policies will be addressed by a student discipline law recently
signed by Gov. Roy Barnes. It requires all180 systems to have a
code of conduct, reflecting community viewpoints, and requires
character education, or moral lessons, at every grade.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Hartley, a Gainesville, Ga.-based attorney whose firm has
represented more than 100 Georgia school systems, said he believes
districts are doing exactly what they should be doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``For quite some time, school systems have been aware of the
issue,'' Hartley said. ``Frankly, I don't know of anything more, on
a day-to-day basis, school systems really could do.''
</P>
<P>
   But he worried that the ruling will encourage unwinnable
lawsuits against schools, costing taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very simple to make an allegation in a lawsuit that
would meet these standards,'' he said. ``From the time (parents)
file a lawsuit to the time you can prove enough to get the judge to
throw it out can cost the school system a great deal of money.''
Atlanta and the large county systems in Fulton, Cobb, Gwinnett and
DeKalb all have policies against sexual harrassment by students. In
Atlanta, for example, an offense can be an off-color joke or
unwelcome touching of a body part; it can be a pattern of behavior
or one serious act. Students can charge other students anonymously,
but are subject to discipline for intentional false reports.
Punishment ranges from counseling to expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've started viewing any kind of harassment as bullying,''
said Garry McGiboney, who oversees student security and discipline
in DeKalb County. ``We handle it under the violence section that
deals with making verbal threats.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin and Doug Cumming write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
