<SLUG> BC-THERMO-RESTRUCTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERMO ELECTRON DETAILS RESTRUCTURING MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thermo Electron Corp., the equipment and instruments maker, said
Monday it plans to further reduce the number of its publicly traded
subsidiaries and make other restructuring moves to shore up its
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it will take a $450 million pretax charge and
put up for sale business units with annual sales of $350 million.
The sales are expected to generate about $200 million in cash for
share buybacks or other investments, the company added.
</P>
<P>
   An unspecified number of jobs will also be cut as Thermo
Electron reduces the number of publicly traded subsidiaries to 11
from 23.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it expects the changes to improve results by
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Thermo Electron was once seen as a technology incubator, known
for its unusual strategy of spinning out subsidiaries into publicly
traded companies while retaining majority control. But lately, the
company's profitability and share price have sagged amid growing
Wall Street concerns that its spinout strategy may have gone too
far.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently tapped a new chief executive, Richard F.
Syron, to lead a turnaround, succeeding founder and longtime CEO
George Hatsopoulos.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Thermo Electron said it would cut the number of its
public subsidiaries to 15.
</P>
<P>
   The Waltham, Mass. company's stock sagged as low as 12 11/16 on
April 15. Before the announcement Monday, it fell 1/4 to close at
$19 3/8 a share, less than half of the level of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a large shareholder, Franklin Mutual
Advisors, criticized Thermo Electron management and began to press
the company to step up a share repurchase program and to shed
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Syron, who will become Thermo Electron's chief executive on June
1, said Monday that the latest changes were ``in the spirit of what
Franklin was raising questions about.'' But he said the changes
were already contemplated before Franklin's criticized the company.
Thermo Electron hasn't decided whether it will repurchase more
shares, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Syron said, Thermo Electron will be able to concentrate on
its most profitable operations. ``There's a variety of motivations
for doing this, like some units that have insufficient returns,''
Syron said. ``Others detract from our focus on operating
businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   With partial ownership in businesses ranging from surgical eye
lasers to paper-recycling equipment to clean fuels, Thermo Electron
has operated as a confederation of units with a total revenue of
$3.9 billion among two dozen companies and 26,000 employees
worldwide, including 3,627 in Massachusetts and about 2,000 more in
the rest of New England.
</P>
<P>
   The original spinout strategy was meant to provide funding for
managers who wanted to start up their own ventures. But many became
esoteric and less profitable. ``It worked up to a point, but they
pushed it to an excess,'' said Goldman Sachs analyst Deane Dray.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Thermo Electron said it will absorb four of its public
subsidiaries _ ThermoLase Corp., ThermoTrex Corp., Thermo Ecotek
Corp. and Thermo Vision Corp. _ by exchanging shares or cash for
all outstanding stock of the four companies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Thermo Electron said it will take about $450
million in charges for the second quarter ended July 3. The charges
include: $125 million for the planned sale of clean-fuel facilities
at Thermo Ecotek; $105 million for restructuring of ThermoLase
Corp. and Trex Medical Corp.; and $65 million for the sale of oil
recycling facilities and other actions by Thermo TerraTech Inc.
</P>
<P>
   For its second quarter a year ago, Thermo Electron reported net
income of $61.79 million on sales of $947.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and observers greeted news of the latest changes with
cautious optimism. Among them was perhaps the company's most vocal
critic, Peter Langerman, chief executive of Franklin Mutual in
Short Hills, N.J., who said Monday's announcement was ``consistent
with what one would expect'' from the company. Michael Hutchison,
senior analyst at Barrington Research Associates in Chicago, said
he approved of the plans at first glance. ``Although $450 million
sounds like a big number, and it is, I think this is in the best
interests of the company,'' he said. ``All of these businesses
they're divesting very likely will have a positive impact on their
earnings, because they're only marginally profitable or are losing
money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, Thermo Electron also named to its board
of directors Samuel Bodman, chairman and chief executive of Cabot
Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
