r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-PATAKI-TEX     05-24 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PATAKI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK GOVERNOR JUMPS ONTO GEORGE W. BUSH BANDWAGON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New York Gov. George Pataki jumped on the George W.
Bush bandwagon Monday, joining a growing list of Republicans who
want the Texas governor to be their party's next presidential
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Putting aside his own White House ambitions, Pataki hailed Bush
as a candidate who can expand the Republican base by drawing more
votes from women and minorities. Bush welcomed the high-profile
endorsement in a live satellite hookup to Pataki's New York news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's blessing is the latest in a steady stream of
endorsements that have helped make Bush the clear front-runner for
the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has not made a single campaign trip or even declared
his candidacy, Bush has collected expressions of support from 16 of
the nation's 31 Republican governors, 8 of the 55 Republican
senators and 99 of the 222 Republican House members.
</P>
<P>
   Delegations of state legislators from at least 21 states,
including more than half of the Republicans in the California
Assembly, have also urged Bush to seek the nomination. Bush
campaign aides have scheduled daily endorsement announcements every
day for at least the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It's an impressive lineup, but political experts say the value
of endorsements varies widely.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some instances, it could be real _ real money and real
organizational support. In other cases, it's just another headline
that scares the opposition,'' New York pollster John Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush's opponents are scared by his backers, they don't let it
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time will tell whether it makes a difference,'' said Ari
Fleischer, a spokesman for GOP hopeful Elizabeth Dole. ``The
establishment wants to close ranks behind one candidate. They all
like Elizabeth Dole, but they've decided to rally around one
candidate, and that candidate is George W. Bush. After Elizabeth
Dole becomes the nominee, she's going to welcome them all back into
the fold.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fleischer also acknowledged that the Republican governors
could be vital allies for Bush because of their home-state
connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these governors have winning organizations in their
states,'' said John Truscott, a spokesman for Michigan Gov. John
Engler, an early Bush backer. ``They are governors who know how to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Engler, a possible Republican vice presidential candidate,
called on 30 of his wealthy supporters help Bush raise more than
$392,000 in Michigan in the first three months of this year. The
total made the state Bush's third biggest source of donations,
behind Texas and California.
</P>
<P>
   In another testament to Engler's clout, Detroit beat out Los
Angeles on the city ranking of donations, according to the Center
for Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan organization that monitors
political contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Truscott said Engler and his allies have nearly doubled the haul
for Bush in the second quarter of the year, which ends on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Engler has done a lot of phone calls and personal
visits,'' Truscott said. ``Over the years, he's put together a
great team that's extremely loyal to him. So when he asks for the
help, they line up quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers say Pataki may be able to do the same thing with his
Wall Street connections. The New York governor was joined at his
news conference by former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, another prodigious
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pataki is tight with Wall Street, and that's where the money
is. He and D'Amato can raise unlimited dollars, and I mean almost
unlimited,'' Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Spitzer, a political science professor at the State
University of New York in Cortland, said Bush's endorsements also
help foster the impression that the Texan's campaign is ``a train
rolling downhill at ever greater speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed to catch that spirit as he welcomed Pataki aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to count on you in the state of New York,'' he said,
dropping any pretense that he is merely exploring the possibility
of a campaign. ``You understand New York politics as well as
anybody. You've proven you can win, and I intend to win New York.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
