<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      05-24 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT RULING CURBS JOURNALISTS' WITNESSING POLICE ACTIVITY IN
HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court ruled unanimously Monday that the
police violate ``the right of residential privacy at the core of
the Fourth Amendment'' when they take journalists and photographers
into people's homes to witness searches or arrests.
</P>
<P>
   The decision sharply curbs the popular, but increasingly
disputed, practice in which journalists accompany the police into
private homes and get dramatic coverage of law enforcement in
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely the possibility of good public relations for the police
is simply not enough, standing alone, to justify the ride-along
intrusion into a private home,'' Chief Justice William Rehnquist
wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling does not apply to situations in which journalists
ride along with police to report on activity in a public place,
such as a street-corner drug raid. Its application to private
property that is not actually inside a residence is not clear. The
court did not address the liability of news organizations
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled in two cases, one in which a joint federal and
local law enforcement task force invited the Washington Post to
send a reporter and photographer along on an operation to arrest
fugitives in the Washington area, and one in which federal wildlife
agents brought a CNN camera crew along on a search of a Montana
ranch. In both cases, the homeowners sued on the ground that the
media presence violated their Fourth Amendment rights against
unreasonable searches.
</P>
<P>
   None of the law enforcement officers involved in either case
will face personal liability. The court found they were entitled to
immunity because it was not clear at the time _ 1992 for the
incident in Rockville, Md., and 1993 for the Montana search _ that
the actions were unconstitutional. Under the court's doctrine of
``qualified immunity,'' public officials are not liable for
constitutional violations unless the right at issue was ``clearly
established'' at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The constitutional question presented by this case is by no
means open and shut'' and had not been ruled on by any court at the
time, Rehnquist said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice John Paul Stevens dissented from the immunity portion of
the ruling, saying that the court was not announcing a new rule but
simply ``refused to recognize an entirely unprecedented request for
an exception to a well-established principle'' that police cannot
bring outsiders into a private home to witness the execution of a
warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens observed that the unusual fact that all nine justices
were in agreement on the underlying Fourth Amendment question
``certainly lends support to the notion that the question is indeed
`open and shut.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the Washington-area case, Wilson vs. Layne, No. 98-83, the
police and their journalist companions arrived at the wrong
address; the home was not that of the fugitive, but of his parents,
who were roused from their sleep to find, in addition to the
officers, a photographer taking pictures and a reporter taking
notes. The Washington Post never published an article about the
incident, and was not sued by the parents, who were represented by
the local affiliate of the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   Its director, Arthur Spitzer, said Monday that as a result of
the ruling, ``law enforcement agents should now have no doubt that
their conduct is governed by the Bill of Rights and not by the
demands of infotainment.'' His clients are also suing the
government under the Federal Tort Claims Act, which does not
contain an immunity defense.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit, in Richmond,
Va., had dismissed the suit on immunity grounds without deciding
the Fourth Amendment question.
</P>
<P>
   In the Montana case, Hanlon vs. Berger, No. 97-1927, the U.S.
Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit, in San Francisco, rejected
the agents' immunity claim and found the search violated the ranch
owners' Fourth Amendment rights. In addition, the appeals court
found that CNN, which was also a defendant, had through its joint
participation become a ``government actor'' and shared the agents'
liability.
</P>
<P>
   The justices never acted on the network's appeal of that ruling,
CNN vs. Berger, No. 97-1914, which remains pending before the
court. There are a number of factual issues about the nature of the
search to be resolved in the Montana case, so the court is not
likely to examine CNN's liability before the Ninth Circuit has a
chance to reconsider the whole case in light of Monday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   New organizations said that the decision would not have a direct
effect on their work because the earlier rulings had already caused
them to adjust their procedures. However, John Langley, executive
producer of a Fox network program, ``Cops,'' said his program would
continue as a ``pure ride-along show'' next season as it has since
1989. He said the program had always received releases from anyone
shown on camera, even people under arrest. ``Most of what we show
happens on the street or in cars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion in the Washington area case, Rehnquist noted that
the police had defended the ride-along practice as assisting law
enforcement in various ways. ``Were such `law enforcement
objectives' themselves sufficient to trump the Fourth Amendment,''
he said, ``the protections guaranteed by that amendment's text
would be significantly watered down.'' He said that outsiders could
join the police for specific purposes, giving the example of
property owners who come to identify stolen property.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
