<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9463 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENTANGLED-WHALE-BOS &LR;      05-24 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTANGLED-WHALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUERS RUSH TO FREE RIGHT WHALE   OFF NANTUCKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An animal rescue crew was recalled from training exercises in
South Carolina Monday to attempt a daring open sea disentanglement
of a rare Northern right whale that has become dangerously snarled
in fishing gear.
</P>
<P>
   The whale, swimming 60 miles off Nantucket, Mass., where gale
warnings and up to 12-foot seas were reported, has three buoys
floating near its head, and fishing line around its body and
trailing behind. Already, Charles ``Stormy'' Mayo of the Center for
Coastal Studies has placed a satellite tracking device on the
animal to allow rescuers to monitor its movement.
</P>
<P>
   But rough seas and fog prevented Mayo and his crew from
attempting to free the animal Monday, and National Marine Fisheries
Studies officials said the weather may prevent a rescue again
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we might have said this type of event isn't our
highest priority,'' said Center for Coastal Studies spokesman Scott
Landry, noting that the whale seems to be feeding normally. ``But
we've learned that even the most innocuous entanglement can turn
into something pretty grotesque pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry said the main concern is that fishing lines around the
45-foot-long whale's middle will grow tighter as the whale fattens
up at its summer feeding ground in the Bay of Fundy off Nova
Scotia. That, in turn, could interfere with feeding.
</P>
<P>
   Since there are only about 300 Northern right whales left in the
world, Landry said his Provincetown, Mass.-based organization did
not want to take a risk. Instead, two center officials who normally
work with Mayo on whale rescues were called back from South
Carolina where they were training others.
</P>
<P>
   The whale is one of three Northern right whales reportedly
entangled in fishing gear off the Massachusetts coast right now,
the first time that Landry could recall that more than one right
whale was in danger. Unfortunately, he said, observers have lost
track of the other two animals.
</P>
<P>
   Entanglements with fishing gear are the second leading
human-induced cause of death _ behind ship collisions _ for the
right whales, a species that has failed to recover more than 60
years since the end of whale-hunting. Already, lobster traps and
other fixed fishing gear are banned in Cape Cod Bay during certain
times of year to prevent even more entanglements.
</P>
<P>
   The drama began last weekend after an environmental organization
spotted an entangled whale 80 miles east of the island of
Nantucket, but lost the animal in the fog. A federal surveillance
plane found the animal again, and Mayo flew out by helicopter to
the Coast Guard cutter Diligence to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to reach the entangled whale on Saturday night,
Mayo approached the animal on Sunday morning in a hard-bottomed
inflatable raft, and attached the satellite tagging device. Now,
the center is using the tag to track the whale's movements on its
Internet homepage, www.coastalstudies.org.
</P>
<P>
   Once the weather clears, Mayo and the crew will return to the
whale, this time to cut away the fishing lines.
</P>
<P>
   The entanglement off Nantucket comes six weeks after the death
of another right whale, nicknamed Staccato, off Cape Cod when it
was apparently struck by a ship. The loss of Staccato, the mother
of at least six whales, was painful, since she was one of the most
prolific breeders left in the species.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the National Marine Fisheries Service were hoping
for a happier ending with the entangled whale off Nantucket, which
may be identified by its nickname once aerial photos of its
markings can be studied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
