<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9466 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIMES-DIGITAL-BOS &LR;      05-24 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMES-DIGITAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES CO. CREATES UMBRELLA ON-LINE SUBSIDIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times Co., owner of The Boston Globe, said Monday
it will consolidate its Internet holdings into a new business unit
called Times Company Digital.
</P>
<P>
   ``By aggregating our portfolio of Internet assets into one
business unit, we will sharpen our strategic focus and gain the
flexibility to bring our digital future to scale,'' Arthur
Sulzberger Jr., chairman of Times Co., said in a statement. ``This
step significantly advances our ability to build a high-quality,
high-valued Internet presence and to respond even more quickly to
the fast-moving Web marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Times Company Digital will include The New York Times on the Web
(www.nytimes.com), which has 7 million registered users; the
Globe's boston.com (www.boston.com), the country's largest regional
gateway, with more than 29 million page views in April; New York
Today (www.nytoday.com), an on-line source of lifestyle and
entertainment news in New York City; and Wine Today
(www.winetoday.com) a site for news on the California Wine Country.
The division will comprise almost 50 Web sites in all, including
sites operated by Times Co.'s regional newspapers, magazines, and
broadcast group.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from Internet properties operated by Times Co. is
expected to total $24 million to $26 million this year, the company
forecasted. In 1998, new media properties accounted for $18 million
of Times Co.'s $2.9 billion in annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is probably not profitable for the New York
Times, but it is a growing business and if they wanted to spin it
out as a separate company, it makes it easier to do now,'' said
Mary Ann Winter, media analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman.
</P>
<P>
   A Times spokeswoman said the company is always looking at ways
to increase shareholder value, and that management has explored and
will continue to examine various options.
</P>
<P>
   The Times is not the only media company reorganizing its on-line
offerings. Last week, Tribune Co. announced that it will create
Tribune Interactive, a unit for the on-line sites of its four
newspapers, 17 television stations, and other Internet-related
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Sulzberger announced that Martin A. Nisenholtz, president of the
New York Times Electronic Media Co., will become chief executive of
Times Company Digital.
</P>
<P>
   Times Co. stock closed Monday at 34 3/4 on the New York Stock
Exchange, down 5/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
