<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9477 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-1STWRITETHRU-COX     05-24 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-1STWRITETHRU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore makes call for faith-based solutions in violent society
 &HT;    (EDS: 1st writethru _ adds grafs 8-10. MOVING IN (W) Washington
and (A) General news categories.)
 &HT;    By Scott Shepard
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Vice President Al Gore came to Atlanta on Monday and
proposed that the government subsidize religious organizations so
that ``the unique power of faith'' can combat social ills.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, speaking at an adult rehabilitation center run by the
Salvation Army, embraced an idea first offered by Republicans as he
called for ``a new partnership'' between church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faith- and value-based organizations'' already have shown ``a
muscular commitment'' to facing the nation's social problems, Gore
said, and a partnership with government would allow them to have an
even greater impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen the difference faith-based organizations make,''
Gore said, citing the experiences of his wife, Tipper, in working
with the homeless at Christ Church in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the lesson to the nation is clear: In those
instances where the unique power of faith can help us meet the
crushing social challenges that are otherwise impossible to meet
... we should explore carefully tailored partnerships with our
faith community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, the vice president went to Conyers, where he
met privately for more than 45 minutes at Rockdale Baptist Church
with the families of six Heritage High School students who were
shot last week by a fellow student.
</P>
<P>
   Security was tight at the meeting, and media were kept at a
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Malarney, the Rockdale school board chairman, said the Gore
took off his coat, put his foot up on a chair and told the
students, ``You tell me how you feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Malarney said the vice president talked with each of the 50
people present individually during the one-hour stop at the church,
about 5 miles from Heritage. The 152-year-old church is the
namesake for the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an opportunity for (Gore) to meet in private with the
families,'' said Chris Lehane, a spokesman for the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   At the rehab center earlier, Gore was introduced by Bradford
Culpepper, a resident of the rehabilitation center who marveled
that he had the opportunity to stand on the same platform with the
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also shared the podium with Atlanta firefighter Matt
Mosely, whose daring rescue of a man trapped on a burning crane
mesmerized viewers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Gore proposed expanding the so-called ``Charitable Choice''
provision of the 1996 welfare overhaul law that allows states to
enlist ``faith-based'' organizations to provide basic services to
help move people from welfare to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must dare to embrace faith-based approaches that advance
our shared goals as Americans,'' he said. To do so would usher in
``a new era of civil society collaboration.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a former divinity student at Vanderbilt University, said
that approach should also be used for other social services, such
as drug treatment, homelessness and the prevention of youth
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that some civil liberties experts object that such
support could breach the constitutional wall between church and
state, Gore said there should be ``clear and strict safeguards''
against the government promoting a particular religious view.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president made a veiled reference to former President
Bush's emphasis on volunteerism, rather than expanded government
programs, in addressing social ills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some past national political leaders have asked us to rely on
a fragile patchwork of well-intentioned volunteerism to feed the
hungry and house the homeless,'' he said. ``That approach,
optimistic though it was, was not adequate for the problems too
many Americans face. It left too many American children behind to
suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   After the trip to Conyers, Gore returned to Atlanta for a
reception and private dinner that were expected to net about
$350,000 for his campaign for the Democratic presidential
nomination. Gore's address, which his campaign promoted as a major
statement on values, came as the vice president began a three-day
campaign swing through the South.
</P>
<P>
   Gore struck similar themes earlier in the day in Orlando at a
luncheon that netted his presidential campaign an estimated
$250,000. The vice president was flying late Monday night to Texas,
where he plans two more days of events.
</P>
<P>
   His press office said Gore planned today to announce a
regulation reassuring families that enrolling for government
benefits would not affect their immigration status.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
