<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KAPLAN-AD-COLUMN-NYT     05-24 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAPLAN-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: KAPLAN THALER GROUP TO BE ACQUIRED BY MACMANUS
GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The agency responsible for that much-discussed
Clairol Herbal Essences campaign in which women simulate sexual
ecstasy now has some excitement of its own: a new owner.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan Thaler Group, a creatively focused independent
advertising and entertainment shop in New York, has reached an
agreement in principle to be acquired by MacManus Group, which owns
agencies including N.W. Ayer &AMP; Partners and D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP;
Bowles Communications. Financial terms of the deal, to be formally
announced today, are not being disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan Thaler, founded in September 1997 by the creative veteran
Linda Kaplan Thaler, estimates its billings for this year at $145
million from clients including the American Red Cross and the
United Jewish Appeal, as well as the Bristol-Myers Squibb &UR;  &LR; Co., for
Herbal Essences and five other Clairol brands and for corporate
branding programs and pharmaceutical projects.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan Thaler joins a lengthening list of small and midsize
agencies that are being engulfed and devoured, as Mel Brooks would
say, by the Madison Avenue giants. MacManus is the world's
10th-largest agency group, with estimated billings of $7.6 billion
from such clients as the Coca-Cola &UR;  &LR; Co. the General Motors &UR;  &LR; Corp.,
Mars &UR;  &LR; Inc. and the Procter &AMP; Gamble &UR;  &LR; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Other recent examples of this widespread consolidation trend
include the purchases of the New York agencies Avrett Free &AMP;
Ginsberg and Berenter Greenhouse &AMP; Webster by the Bozell Worldwide
unit of True North Communications; the acquisitions of Citron
Haligman Bedecarre in San Francisco and Jordan McGrath Case &AMP;
Partners in New York by the Euro RSCG Worldwide unit of Havas
Advertising, and the sale of a majority stake in Mullen Advertising
in Wenham, Mass., to the Lowe Group unit of the Interpublic Group
of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grew a zillion times more fast than we thought,'' Ms.
Kaplan Thaler, president and chief executive at Kaplan Thaler, said
during a breakfast interview yesterday. ``The clients coming to us
are big clients.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a couple instances in the recent past when we
wanted desperately to pitch business, but we knew it required media
capabilities, research capabilities,'' she added. ``Now I can talk
about how we have media capabilities, research capabilities,
worldwide capabilities,'' through MacManus.
</P>
<P>
   MacManus plans to operate Kaplan Thaler as a freestanding,
autonomous unit, reporting directly to Roy J. Bostock, chairman and
chief executive at MacManus in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Linda and I do our jobs well, that independence will be
maintained and hopefully enhanced,'' said Bostock, who joined Ms.
Kaplan Thaler for the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have significant confidence we're smart enough to make sure
that continues,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaplan Thaler agreed, declaring that it would be
``counterproductive to do anything other than continue doing what
we were doing'' at Kaplan Thaler.
</P>
<P>
   For MacManus, Bostock said, owning Kaplan Thaler ``enables us to
compete for the kinds of businesses we're not able to without Linda
and her talented group of people.'' The agency has 35 other
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows Linda is a world-class talent,'' Bostock said.
``And that's obviously what this business is all about, talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaplan Thaler, 48, is a former comedy writer and performer
who worked at the big J. Walter Thompson and Wells BDDP agencies
before founding Kaplan Thaler. She is known for campaigns for
brands like Herbal Essences, Eastman Kodak &UR;  &LR;  and Toys ``R'' Us &UR;  &LR; 
that seek to make emotional connections with consumers using
tactics ranging from spicy humor and celebrities to heart-tugging
schmaltz and uplifting music.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as Ms. Kaplan Thaler showed a reel of her work, Bostock
tapped his coffee cup against a table to the beat of a tune during
one commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Bostock said he anticipated ``a lot of cross-fertilization''
between Kaplan Thaler and units of MacManus, which include Blue
Marble Advanced Communications Group, specializing in interactive
advertising; Manning, Selvage &AMP; Lee, public relations, and
Mediavest Worldwide, media services.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Mediavest is involved in television programming
and Kaplan Thaler has produced films and television programs for
clients, including an hourlong special about the Red Cross that ran
on CBS in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about creating ways to promote clients' brands whatever
they may be,'' Ms. Kaplan Thaler said, ``whether a TV commercial, a
TV special, a book or a CD-ROM.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaplan Thaler said that her decision to sell Kaplan Thaler
predated the agency's loss in March of the creative portion of the
account of Toys ``R'' Us, with billings estimated at $50 million.
Kaplan Thaler was eliminated from a review for the creative duties,
which were reassigned May 10 to the Leo &UR;  &LR; Burnett &UR;  &LR; Co. in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to grow the way we want,'' Ms. Kaplan Thaler said,
``this kind of partnership is absolutely essential.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
