<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BY-DESIGN-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY DESIGN: DANCING WITH MULES
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two current trends in footwear _ ballerina flats and
mules _ have converged for summer as the (unfortunately named)
ballet mule. In solid colors or with contrasting toes, the new
mules are trimmed with the little bow-tied loops that mark dancers'
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Klein's ballet mules ($145) are in all-black with patent
toes at Bloomingdale's, in all-black or in beige with black toes at
Bergdorf Goodman and in all-black or in white with black toes at
Macy's. Cynthia Rowley's version ($160) comes in all-white or
all-black at Bloomingdale's; in black, white or pale gray at
Macy's.
</P>
<P>
   Bergdorf Goodman also has Sigerson Morrison's mules ($198) in
black or white and Rebecca Moses' mules ($290) in pale blue, peach
or dark purple, all with contrasting bows.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's also has two slightly different ballet shoes: Joan
Halpern's with flat bows on the front ($275) and BCBGs takeoff on
point shoes, satin mules that have squared-off toes ($148).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9482 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-REOPENS-COX     05-24 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-REOPENS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students return to school following shooting
 &HT;    By Leon Stafford
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ Heritage High School students _ together as a
school for the first time Monday since last week's shootings _
hugged, signed yearbooks and said their goodbyes to the 1998-99
school year.
</P>
<P>
   They came in droves, filling the student parking lot by 8:10
a.m. and streaming off school buses. Some walked arm in arm,
preceding as if it were an ordinary day. One student held a sign
that read, ``We will survive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never had so much school spirit until this happened,''
said senior April Sargent, 17. She said the buzz among her
classmates was that they wanted everyone to know how proud they
were to be associated with Heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Principal Lowell Biddy said Monday's attendance was 90 percent,
a number that included four of the six students shot _ Brian
Barnhardt, Ryan Rosa, Jason Cheek and Drake Hoy. Cania Cullins had
said earlier that she would not be at school Monday. Stephanie
Laster was still hospitalized in Atlanta on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy, who had not spoken to the media since the shootings,
recounted early Monday a brief conversation he had with suspected
gunman, 15-year-old T.J. Solomon, after the Heritage sophomore
surrendered to administrators about nine minutes after he fired
into a crowd of fellow students last Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was quite hysterical,'' Biddy said. ``I was asking him if
he was OK. And then I asked the big questions. I asked if those are
blanks, and he said no. Then I asked if he had acted alone, and he
said yes. And then he started sobbing, and he said, `Mr. Biddy, I
don't know why I did this. I just don't know why I did this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Several students said they came back because they wanted to get
their yearbooks, which administrators had planned to release last
Thursday. The homeroom period was extended to almost two hours so
that the students could get the books signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just real happy to see everybody was alright and were
back,'' said Linda Ayala, 16, a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   However, most left after the first class period, opting to go
home early and start their summer vacations. School officially ends
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Jacquelyn Whalen, 15, said she was a little apprehensive about
returning to school, but wanted to say goodbye to her friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is okay,'' the freshman said of the atmosphere.
``It's practically normal, just a lot of police.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockdale County Sheriff's Department had about 20 deputies
on the scene patrolling the grounds and inside the building.
Another six Georgia State Patrol troopers directed traffic onto the
campus. Parents also were patrolling the hallways in an effort to
keep students safe.
</P>
<P>
   The news media, whose numbers have dwindled significantly from
last week when a horde descended on the school, was kept at bay and
not allowed on campus to talk to students.
</P>
<P>
   Rockdale Schools Superintendent Don Peccia praised the student
turnout, saying that normally it would not have been that high the
last day of classes.
</P>
<P>
   For Jenni Buchanan, the option given students to skip exams if
pleased with their final grade was a blessing in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if I took my economics exam I would be here taking
class this summer,'' the 17-year-old graduating senior said as she
left school for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Stafford writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
