u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESIDENT-SALARY-HNS &LR;      05-24 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENT-SALARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS TOLD PLAN TO DOUBLE PRESIDENT'S SALARY ISN'T ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former top White House officials told lawmakers
Monday that a House plan to double to the president's salary to
$400,000 annually doesn't go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   The figure should be $500,000, according to Kenneth Duberstein,
who served as chief of staff to President Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the compensation of the leader of the free
world, not about the salary of the chief of a small startup company
or the head of a third world country,'' Duberstein said.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before a House government reform subcommittee, six
other former White House officials agreed that a $500,000 annual
salary would be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   They were John Sununu, chief of staff to President George Bush;
Alexander Haig, chief of staff to President Richard Nixon and
secretary of state under Reagan; James R. Jones, special assistant
to President Lyndon Johnson; Robert Hartmann; counsel to President
Gerald Ford, Samuel Skinner, another Bush chief of staff, and
Thomas ``Mack'' McLarty III, former chief of staff to President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress isn't likely to accept a $500,000 figure. Last week
a House Appropriations subcommittee approved a plan to raise the
president's salary from $200,000 to $400,000 beginning Jan. 20,
2001. Clinton would not be affected by any pay boost.
</P>
<P>
   The president's salary has been the same since 1969 when
Congress raised it from $100,000 to $200,000. Richard Nixon was
then president.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the $200,000 salary, Rep. Stephen Horn, R-Calif.,
chairman of the government reform panel, said, ``I am sure to most
Americans, a salary of that amount seems to be a lot of money and
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   But Horn pointed out that ``it is the pay for one of the most
difficult, demanding and important jobs on the face of the earth''
and added that he supports the House appropriations panel's plan to
double it.
</P>
<P>
   Haig and the other former officials noted that the pressures on
the president have greatly increased over the last 30 years with
the rise of instant communication and around-the-clock news.
</P>
<P>
   ``People demand answers almost instantaneously to every domestic
and international crisis,'' often forcing the president to make
snap decisions rather than thinking things through, Haig said.
</P>
<P>
   If the 1969 salary were adjusted to 1998 dollars, it would be
$888,283, according to the Congressional Research Service (CRS), a
research arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   When George Washington took office in 1789, Congress established
a salary of $25,000 a year, according to CRS. If adjusted for a 2.5
percent inflation rate, Washington's salary would be worth more
than $4 million today, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's salary was increased from $25,000 to $50,000
when President Ulysses Grant began his second term in 1873 and
again in 1909 to $75,000 when President William Howard Taft took
office. In 1949 it was raised to $100,000 when President Harry
Truman, who took office in 1945 after the death of Franklin
Roosevelt, began his first full term. There was no other increase
until 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Sununu said Congress should also consider reviewing the
president's salary every eight or 12 years to better keep up with
cost of living changes.
</P>
<P>
   By law, Congress may alter a president's salary only between
terms. If it doesn't raise the pay before 2001, when Clinton leaves
the White House, the next opportunity won't come until 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, if Congress doesn't raise the president's salary,
the amount paid the vice president, the chief justice of the United
States and the House speaker could outstrip the president's sum by
2004.
</P>
<P>
   These officials currently earn $175,400, but their salaries,
like those of most other federal employees, are adjusted annually
to reflect cost-of-living changes.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone testifying at Monday's favored an increase in
presidential pay.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Ruskin, director of a nonprofit, watchdog group called the
Congressional Accountability Project, said $200,000 is a ``great
sum of money.'' Ruskin's organization receives funding from
consumer advocate Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   Ruskin noted that the president lives rent-free in the White
House, gets free travel expenses, leaves office with a $152,000
annual pension ``plus a near-certain prospect, if desired, of
becoming a multi-millionaire'' afterward.
</P>
<P>
   An opinion poll released Monday finds the idea of a presidential
pay raise has lukewarm support among the public. When told that the
president's salary has not been raised since 1969, 49 percent
favored a pay boost while 39 percent opposed it, according to the
survey conducted by the Pew Research Center for the People and the
Press.
</P>
<P>
   But when people were also told the president now earns $200,000
and gets housing and travel expenses, 41 percent of people favored
a pay raise and 55 percent opposed it, the poll showed.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at (202) 298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
