<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9485 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      05-24 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN ENVOY SEES PROGRESS IN KOSOVO TROOP QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Russian envoy to the Balkans claimed Monday to
have bridged one of the central gaps in peace negotiations between
NATO and Yugoslavia, convincing Western powers of the importance of
letting some Yugoslav forces stay inside Kosovo even after the
bombing stops.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Chernomyrdin, who is scheduled to meet with US Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott Wednesday, also repeated his plea
for NATO airstrikes to end, saying the attacks were complicating
the negotiations and eventually ``may spell catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials did not immediately react to Chernomyrdin's
claim, although a White House spokesman said Monday the demand is
still that ``all troops have to withdraw.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks coincided with a grim report from UN official Sergio
Vieira de Mello, who led a three-day fact-finding mission into
Kosovo, and emerged from the province Monday describing what he saw
there as ``a lot worse than we expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Serb forces blocked the team from certain areas of
Kosovo, they still managed to interview large numbers of displaced
ethnic Albanians, many of whom were in dire need of humanitarian
aid and military security, he said. At the same time, survivors
indicated that the region had been destroyed by widespread ``ethnic
cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen enough evidence and heard enough testimony to
confirm that there has been an attempt at displacing internally and
externally a shocking number of civilians,'' said de Mello, who is
the UN undersecretary-general for humanitarian affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Chernomyrdin's remarks, Talbott has said nothing about
a shift in policy since his meeting with the Russian envoy last
week, and Monday, as the third month of airstrikes began, NATO
officials gave every indication their campaign was continuing as
planned. In the past, officials have insisted that all Yugoslav
troops be withdrawn from Kosovo _ except, possibly, from the areas
around holy sites _ before the bombing is halted.
</P>
<P>
   But Chernomyrdin, who plans to fly to Belgrade Thursday for
further talks, said he had managed to convince NATO of the need to
let some of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's troops stay
inside the province. More than 40,000 Yugoslav troops have been
posted in Kosovo since March 24, and another 10,000 are said to
have been sent there in the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has taken two or three weeks to convince our counterparts _
the United States and NATO countries _ that while withdrawing the
(Yugoslav) troops, it's necessary to leave some of them behind,''
Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Monday:
</P>
<P>
   --Yugoslav media reported black-outs in large sections of the
country and a dwindling water supply, following another night of
severe NATO attacks.
</P>
<P>
   NATO said it was targeting military sites only and reported
hitting a radar site and a command center inside Yugoslavia on
Sunday night. At least one tank, nine artillery positions, seven
armored vehicles and 12 mortar positions were hit, according to
NATO spokesman Maj. Gen. Walter Jertz.
</P>
<P>
   --Crowds in the Serbian communities of Krusevac and Alexandrovac
gathered in protest against the local draft, rallying in groups as
large as 2,000 people. Anti-war leaders in the town of Cacak were
stopped for questioning, according to a news agency in neighboring
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   --NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana marked the end of two
months of airstrikes with an announcement that Milosevic ``is
cracking.'' Solana said there was increasing evidence of dissent
inside Yugoslavia, so NATO should stay the course with airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to maintain the strategy at this very moment, which is
producing results rapidly. Therefore we don't want to give the
impression that we are going to change the strategy,'' Solana said
in an interview in Brussels with Associated Press Television News.
</P>
<P>
   --Serb media reported that NATO airstrikes killed as many as 100
people when a jail in Istok was hit Friday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   --Twenty more US warplanes were on their way to join the fight.
The F/A-18 attack jets, flying from their base South Carolina, were
expected to bring the number of NATO planes involved in the
conflict to more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   --Hashim Thaci, the populist leader of the Kosovo Liberation
Army, offered words of comfort in a speech to thousands of refugees
in Kukes, Albania, near the southwest border of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we are not alone in our fight. The whole world is
helping us win our freedom,'' Thaci told the cheering crowd. ``We
are now reorganized. We are a better, more efficient force.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NATO members continued to push for a diplomatic
solution to the crisis, looking with cautious optimism toward this
week's meetings in Europe and Belgrade, where Chernomyrdin hopes to
find an end to the military conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But it was by no means clear that any solution was imminent.
According to White House officials, the withdrawal of Yugoslav
troops remained a requirement of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no particular breakthrough, but we continue to work
with Mr. Chernomyrdin and'' Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari ``to
find a way to meet the NATO conditions'' to end the conflict, White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is all troops have to withdraw, including
military and paramilitary,'' said David Leavy, spokesman for
national security adviser Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger. ``Once
there's a peace agreement, whether there can be a discussion about
having small numbers of troops come back to protect Serb holy sites
under the supervision of peacekeepers, that's something we'd look
at ... down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek echoed the
firmness of US officials Monday. Speaking to Globe editors, he
warned that NATO should be careful not to let war fatigue cause too
many compromises in working out a peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   Geremek, whose nation is one of NATO's newest members, said the
alliance must continue to demand the withdrawal of Serb forces from
Kosovo and the return of all refugees, although the alliance might
give ground in accepting Serb guard units to patrol Kosovo's
borders with Macedonia and Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the war is worth it _ to see that a dictator at the end
of the century cannot impose his will on the international
community,'' said Geremek. ``The Kosovo war is preparing us for the
21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Yemma of the Globe staff contributed to this article from
Boston. Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
