<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK BEGINS TASK OF WELDING COALITION GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ Amid bitter debate over whether an ultrareligious
party should be brought into his coalition, Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak started talks Monday aimed at forming a broad government
to tackle some of Israel's most formidable problems.
</P>
<P>
   With just 26 seats in the 120-seat parliament, Barak's One
Israel alliance must first decide who it wants as its second
largest partner: the Likud Party with 19 seats, or the
ultrareligious Shas Party with 17 seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a big coalition, and that means bringing in Shas or
Likud. Otherwise you end up with too many small parties and that's
not good for implementing policies,'' said Ra'anan Cohen, a member
of Labor, which dominates the alliance and is headed by Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, elected with 56 percent of the vote, has said he wants to
form as wide a coalition as possible to ensure strong backing when
he renews peace talks with the Palestinians and tries to implement
his promise to withdraw Israeli troops from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The country also faces a bitter internal debate over the role of
religion in the Jewish state and Barak has said he will take steps
to ensure that religious school students do not get a blanket
exemption from compulsory military service.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the campaign debate before the May 17 elections centered
on accusations that religious parties like Shas were trying to turn
Israel into a religious state.
</P>
<P>
   But voters did not give Barak's alliance a majority, leaving him
to figure out which of the other 14 parties in parliament will make
good coalition partners. Barak has until mid-July to form a
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his own party members have called on him to avoid
joining up with Likud, which until recently was headed by Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. Over the three years that the
Likud-led coalition governed, the peace process with the
Palestinians stalled and relations with all Arab countries
worsened.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many voices raised against a coalition with Shas,
which is liberal when it comes to peace with the Palestinians but
very tough when it comes to demanding further implementation of
Jewish religious law.
</P>
<P>
   Detractors of Shas, which gets most of its support from
working-class Israelis whose origins are in North Africa or the
Middle East, say the party is a danger to democracy because of its
fundamentalist religious views, which are spreading thanks to the
party's state-funded school system.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's victory speeches have been interrupted by chants of
``Just no to Shas'' while his office has been flooded with tens of
thousands of emails and faxes calling on him to keep the party in
the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The liberal Meretz Party, which has 10 seats in parliament and
usually serves in Labor-led coalition governments, has said it
opposes a coalition government that would include Shas, although it
also would prefer not to be in a coalition with Likud.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I prefer neither, but it is impossible to have Shas as
part of the government, although it will also be difficult to sit
down with Likud,'' said Ran Cohen, a Meretz member of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The new Shinui Party, which has six seats and a platform that
opposes religious interference in personal matters, has also said
it cannot imagine governing in a coalition with Shas. The Russian
immigrant party, Yisrael B'Aliyah, with six seats, has only said it
does not want Shas to be in charge of the Interior Ministry.
Barak's other likely partner, the Center Party headed by former
Likud party member Yitzhak Mordechai, has six seats and does not
have a set position on Shas.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, whose One Israel alliance includes the Orthodox Meimad
faction, has not made it clear where he stands. Last week, Shas
overcame one obstacle when Aryeh Deri, convicted of bribery and
fraud, resigned as the party's political leader and from the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Some political analysts and even members of Barak's own party
say it is important to include Shas in a coalition because many of
its supporters already feel alienated from the system and
discriminated against.
</P>
<P>
   Shas has been in and out of governments since it was formed in
the early 1980s and, when in, it usually has managed to control the
Interior Ministry, giving the party good access to state funds for
its social programs and schools and helping it win new supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find much of what Shas stands for as unappealing but a true
politics of inclusion calls for understanding the root causes of
Shas' anger and frustration,'' wrote political scientist Shlomo
Avineri in the Jerusalem Post.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the black garb of the ultra-Orthodox Jews, he wrote,
``there exist real people who have real problems of poverty and
alienation, of identity and marginalization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
