<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-SERVICES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC FILES LONG-DISTANCE PLAN FOR BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Bell Atlantic filed its Monday application to start
selling long-distance service in Massachusetts early next year,
touching off a high-stakes debate about whether the company has
done enough to open its local phone market to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like MediaOne, RCN, AT&AMP;T, and MCI-WorldCom said they
would fight Bell Atlantic's long-distance proposal. They said the
company hasn't cracked open its local phone network, a regulatory
bar the company has to clear if it wants to break into the
long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators at the state Department of Telecommunications and
Energy reacted cautiously Monday to Bell Atlantic's 15,000-page
filing, which was delivered in 28 boxes. They declined to say how
they would proceed, other than to say that Bell Atlantic's claims
would be scrutinized closely. Approval of the Federal
Communications Commission also is required.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is the second market where New York-based Bell
Atlantic has sought permission to offer long-distance services. The
company filed its first application last year in New York, and
another is expected shortly in Pennsylvania. Analysts say none of
the other six regional phone companies across the country is as far
along as Bell Atlantic in the regulatory process.
</P>
<P>
   Long distance is the key missing ingredient in the efforts of
Bell Atlantic and the other regional phone companies to offer
customers a rich stew of telecommunications services on one bill.
But the federal Telecommunications Act of 1996 authorizes state and
federal regulators to treat the $80 billion long-distance market
like a carrot, withholding it from the regional phone companies
until they open their markets to competition.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bell Atlantic officials were vague about what consumer
benefits they would bring to the already-crowded long-distance
market, they were insistent that they had met or exceeded all of
the 14 items on the local-competition checklist established by
Congress in the Telecommunications Act.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said 98 companies are now vying to provide local
phone service in Massachusetts and consumers can easily switch
carriers and keep their existing phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any company that says it can't compete with us simply doesn't
wish to do so,'' said Wayne Budd, Bell Atlantic's group vice
president for New England.
</P>
<P>
   But companies that are actually trying to compete against Bell
Atlantic say dealing with Bell Atlantic is not easy, with customers
all too often losing their dial tone as a customer is transferred
from Bell Atlantic to a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   RCN and MediaOne, the two companies vying for residential local
telephone customers in Massachusetts, said they have experienced a
host of problems in connecting their networks with Bell Atlantic's.
MediaOne, in fact, reached an impasse with Bell Atlantic on several
issues last month, and both companies have asked the DTE to step in
and arbitrate.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Jenkinson, MediaOne's spokesman, said Bell Atlantic's
market is open only on paper. ``It's nice to have interconnection
agreements signed, but the experience of the one facilities-based
company competing against Bell Atlantic in the residential market
is that they have not proven themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In its dealings with Bell Atlantic, Mike Mahoney, president and
chief operating officer of RCN, said his company has experienced
billing problems, delays in gaining access to Bell Atlantic
telephone poles, and difficulties in transferring a customer
numbers from Bell Atlantic to RCN.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to determine whether these things are
happening because of incompetence or sabotage, but the end result
is the same,'' Mahoney said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic officials said the regulatory process in
Massachusetts should proceed smoothly because the company has gone
through a rigorous review in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Public Service Commission hired an outside
consulting firm to test Bell Atlantic's computer systems to see
whether they mesh easily with those of competitors. Bell Atlantic
passed 90 percent of the tests, but is still working to pass the
others.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic officials said most of the same systems deployed
in New York are also in use here, which means regulators here could
easily piggyback on the New York review.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and MCI-WorldCom both said the lack of local phone
competition in Massachusetts is proof enough that Bell Atlantic has
not opened up its market sufficiently.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bell Atlantic's filing, less than 30,000 customers
have had their numbers ``ported'' to a competitor, while 138,000
lines have been purchased for resale. Most of Bell Atlantic's
competitors target the business market because that's where the
biggest profits are. Bell Atlantic officials said Monday they did
not know how many residential customers have defected to a
competitor. The company serves a total of four million business and
residential customers in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bell Atlantic has 99 percent market share in Massachusetts.
That is not evidence of competition by any definition,'' said
Robert Lopardo, regional director for public policy at
MCI-WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   But Budd said Bell Atlantic doesn't have to show that
competitors control a certain percentage of the Massachusetts
market. It only has to demonstrate that the market is open to
competition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic shares rose 1/16 Monday on the New York Stock
Exchange to close at 55 9/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
