<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHERS-BONUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
63 TEACHERS ACCEPT SIGNING BONUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When Lois Hedberg was diagnosed with breast cancer
five years ago, she used her education to research the disease, ask
doctors informed questions, connect with other patients and write
about it in a journal as therapy.
</P>
<P>
   What struck the church secretary as she went through
chemotherapy treatments and recovered from a mastectomy was how
much more excruciating the illness was for people less literate,
not as well-schooled.
</P>
<P>
   And so, her cancer acted as a muse, guiding her to teaching as a
new vocation so she could help others help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Hedberg, 53, was one step closer to the classroom as she
_ and 62 other new Massachusetts teachers _ accepted a $20,000
signing bonus from Senate President Tom Birmingham and state
Department of Education Commissioner David P. Driscoll.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made me want to teach was seeing people with this disease
who were poor and could not read and did not know what they were
dealing with,'' said Hedberg, of Wilbraham. ``I thought, `I want to
be the one to say, `You can do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A former college English teacher who has a master's degree from
Cornell and is a longtime school volunteer, Hedberg represents 41
percent of the recipients who are mid-career professionals between
the ages of 30 and 60.
</P>
<P>
   At a State House press conference Monday, Birmingham called the
recipients diverse and impressive and noted the bonuses were a way
for the state to lure people who had been flirting with education
as a career _ but hesitated because of the $26,000 starting salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should go into teaching to get rich,'' said Birmingham,
who devised the bonus program. ``But you shouldn't have to be rich
to afford to be a teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would support an increase in the $60 million Teacher
Quality budget item that supplied the funds this year, to help
entice more teachers next year. The bonuses will be given out in
four annual payments, the first is $8,000, to be used at the
teacher's discretion.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll called the bonus program ``a tremendous success story''
built on Birmingham's vision, and serving to uplift education at a
time when ``things looked fairly bleak.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is the only state offering bonuses in its teacher
recruitment campaign. To spread the word, DOE officials visited
cities and college campuses nationwide last year.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6,000 responses flooded into the DOE; 800 applications
were accepted. Of those, 120 finalists were selected based on class
rank (top 10 percent or better), grade-point averages (a minimum of
3.5), writing samples, recommendations and, for mid-career
professionals, work experience.
</P>
<P>
   All had to pass the state-mandated Educator Certification Test,
present a sample teaching lesson and interview one-on-one. The 62
chosen recipients agreed to teach in urban schools and will be
teaching in summer schools to prepare for their classroom debuts in
the fall. The new teachers also will be matched up with veteran
teacher-mentors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teaching is not something you learn totally, you have to bring
something deep down inside you to the profession; you must be
called to it,'' said Taiwo Stephenson, 31, a former biological
researcher at Harvard University Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson left a potential career in medicine in 1995 to
substitute-teach at Lowell High School, and now will begin his more
formal teaching career. ``You must enjoy children and love people
and bring that to the classroom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bonus recipients come from 10 states nationwide and one
foreign country, Romania. They have attended Ivy League colleges,
state universities and technical schools and have graduate degrees
in education, law, and civil engineering.
</P>
<P>
   The mid-career professionals have worked in business, research,
journalism and public health, among other professions. Forty-four
percent of the recipients are men, 56 percent are women, 23 percent
are minorities and 48 percent have strong backgrounds in math and
science, areas that need bolstering in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of bonus recipients, however, are soon-to-be
college graduates, like 22-year-old William Triant of Wellesley,
who will graduate June 10 from Harvard College with a 3.75 GPA and
a degree in American history and literature.
</P>
<P>
   Triant, who will teach physics and chemistry at a Boston public
high school, said he was inspired by instructors at Roxbury Latin
High School, who ``didn't just teach me things, but taught me how
to be myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about encourging kids to have their own thoughts
and expressions,'' Triant said. ``I know it will be a little
strange to have such a young teacher in front of them, but I think
I will bring a lot of energy into the classroom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
