<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUBURN-SUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Passed-over Oliver sues Auburn
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. _ In these parts, where life tends to revolve
around little more than college football, Bill Oliver has been
labeled a defensive guru by Auburn and Alabama fans, alike. The
faithful know him not just as coach Oliver but as ``Brother''
Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   And now, they can call him by another title _ plaintiff in a
potentially nasty court tussle that might expose Auburn's dirty
laundry for public airing.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver filed a civil lawsuit Monday in Lee County Circuit Court,
citing Auburn athletics director David Housel, influential
university trustee Robert E. ``Bobby'' Lowder and the university
itself. The eight counts include breach of contract, fraud and
deceit.
</P>
<P>
   A who's who of college football coaches and administrators could
parade across the Plains for depositions by summer's end, from
ex-Auburn coach Terry Bowden to Florida coach Steve Spurrier.
Auburn previously drew criticism for its handling of the Bowden
situation and for later backing out of a contract to play Florida
State, coached by Terry Bowden's father, Bobby Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the Oliver case is his contention that Housel
promised him the position of head coach, as a condition for
replacing Bowden on an interim basis last October. Oliver's
attorney, Kenneth Ingram Jr. of Alexander City, said Monday that
Oliver was later ```blindsided'' upon learning the job was offered
to former Mississippi coach Tommy Tuberville.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, assuming that he had the job, turned down an offer to
serve as Spurrier's defensive coordinator, Ingram said.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Housel led him to believe he would be the next head
coach,'' Ingram said. ``He assured him of it. . . . It was things
like: `You're the man. You're gonna get it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There was never a written agreement, however.
</P>
<P>
   As early as the summer of 1997, Ingram said, Lowder widely cast
as the man behind the hiring and firing of Auburn coaches
approached Oliver about the replacement of Bowden. Oliver had
joined Bowden's staff as defensive coordinator in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby Lowder said, `Brother, I'm not pleased with Terry Bowden
as our head coach,' '' Ingram said. `` 'I want you to be ready to
step in at anytime. In fact, that may happpen before this season
even starts.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lowder, founder of Colonial Bank in Montgomery and chairman of a
$9.5 billion holding company, could not be reached for comment
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Housel referred inquiries to university attorney Lee Armstrong,
whose office declined comment. Likewise, Ingram has advised Oliver
not to discuss the lawsuit. Oliver was out of state Monday to
prepare for the birth of a grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   During a 30-minute news conference Monday, Ingram, dressed in a
dark blue suit, charged that the university should be run by its
board of trustees, not by one man ``who obviously has anointed
himself as some monarch over what he considers to be his kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Ingram said Auburn is named in the suit only as a means to
recover more than $100,000 in principal that Oliver owes on a loan
he took out when he was hired in 1996. The suit seeks unspecified
damages, but Ingram said his firm will donate any fees it earns to
the university's general scholarship fund. Terry Bowden has been
identified as the first to give a deposition, here beginning next
month. Oliver's attorneys are expected to make Bowden a key witness
in its argument that Housel, as the university's representative,
had agreed that Auburn would pay off a loan of $136,000 over five
years that the coach took upon being hired as defensive
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   As a condition for coming to Auburn, Oliver had asked Housel to
add the almost nine years in pension monies that he had accumulated
in out-of-state coaching jobs into the Alabama State Retirement
Fund. Instead, the suit alleges, Housel encouraged Oliver to take
out a loan for the amount with Colonial Bank and promised that the
athletic department would cover the principal and interest with
five annual payments to Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   The verbal agreement was reached in a meeting attended by Oliver
and his attorney, Ricky Davis, Bowden and Housel. According to
Ingram, the university made only partial payments. and Oliver still
owes more than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Housel told everyone in that room, and I believe they'll
testify to it,'' Ingram said, ``that he had run this by Bobby
Lowder and (that) Bobby Lowder had agreed to it . . . I want
damages for what this man has been put through.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fish writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
