<SLUG> BC-LAW-FIRM-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK AND LONDON LAW FIRMS PROPOSE FIRST OVERSEAS MERGER
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Senior lawyers at Rogers &AMP; Wells in New York and
Clifford Chance in London have voted to join forces in what would
be the first overseas merger of large law firms.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger, which would create the world's
second-largest law firm in terms of revenue, must still be voted on
by all partners at the two firms, said a lawyer involved in the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the union could touch off a flurry of mergers
between law firms in the United States and Britain, which are
scrambling to expand their global reach to better serve
multinational clients. The law firms also feel threatened by the
giant accounting firms, which have jumped into the legal business
by hiring thousands of lawyers and merging with whole law firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Undoubtedly, there will be more of these mergers,'' said Joel
F. Henning, senior vice president at Hildebrandt International, a
consulting firm that advises law firms. ``In a world where
Daimler-Benz merges with Chrysler, where European banks are
acquiring American banks and where BP acquires Amoco, it would be
peculiar if the major law firms advising those companies were not
looking to grow correspondingly.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger would mean the end of the New York institution known
as Rogers &AMP; Wells, which has roots that date back 128 years. The
firm's partners include William P. Rogers, 85, who served as
secretary of state in the Nixon administration and attorney general
in the Eisenhower administration.
</P>
<P>
   With 400 lawyers, Rogers &AMP; Wells would be dwarfed by its
potential mate. Clifford Chance, with 2,000 lawyers, is Britain's
largest law firm.
</P>
<P>
   The new law firm would be known as Clifford Chance Rogers &AMP;
Wells in the United States, the lawyer said, and as Clifford Chance
in the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   But for the 400 lawyers at Rogers &AMP; Wells, a marriage with the
British giant brings global opportunities. Clifford Chance has
offices in 26 cities worldwide and has been aggressively expanding
its practice, intending to be the world's largest law firm.
</P>
<P>
   The British firm has long had its eye on large law firms based
in Manhattan. By joining Rogers &AMP; Wells, Clifford Chance gains
access to Wall Street and its booming market of corporate financial
deals. The lucrative legal fees associated with those deals are
helping New York's top law firms earn record profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to be a good match-up,'' Henning said. ``But no
merger is easy.''
</P>
<P>
   And, for this union to work, the two law firms must adapt to
each other's culture. Most significantly, the partners must agree
on how to split their profits.
</P>
<P>
   At Rogers &AMP; Wells, like most American law firms, partners'
salaries are based largely on what lawyers call the ``eat what you
kill'' approach: Those who bring in more clients and bill more
hours get paid more than those who do not. But at Clifford Chance
and most other British law firms, partners get paid based on their
seniority and the number of years they have worked for the firm, in
a system known as ``lockstep.''
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyer who has been involved in the talks says that the
two firms' leaders think they can work through the compensation
issues because the average partner at each firm earns the same,
about $650,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The partners must also work through some client conflicts that
would be created by a merger. In one case, the law firms represent
clients on both sides of a lawsuit that is scheduled for trial
soon, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The partners at the two firms are expected to vote on the merger
by the end of June. If approved, it would be effective on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey by The American Lawyer magazine, Rogers &AMP;
Wells, which had gross revenue of $187.5 million in 1997, was
America's 43rd-largest law firm. According to a similar survey of
global firms in 1998, Clifford Chance was the world's third-largest
law firm with $629 million in revenue. Only New York's Skadden,
Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom, with $826 million in revenue, and
Baker &AMP; McKenzie in Chicago, with $696.5 million, were larger.
</P>
<P>
   But even those law firms are small compared with the five
largest accounting firms. The Big Five are years ahead of the law
firms in creating global practices that offer ``one-stop shopping''
in a myriad of services to their corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting firms are already practicing law in many European
countries but have been limited in the United States by laws that
prevent lawyers and accountants from sharing fees. A committee at
the American Bar Association is reviewing those rules and
considering changes that may make it easier for the accounting
firms to practice law and the law firms to hire accountants and
consultants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
