<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABERHAGEN GETS A CHANCE TO WORK OUT ARM IN AKRON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rain will keep the Red Sox in New York for one night
longer than they expected, as Monday's postponement was rescheduled
for Thursday night, giving Roger Clemens an extra day's rest before
he faces his former mates for the first time in pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   There's one Sox player who won't be sticking around for the
occasion: Bret Saberhagen, who won his first Cy Young Award one
year (1985) before Clemens won his, intends to be in Akron, Ohio,
where he is scheduled to pitch Thursday for Class AA Trenton
against the Aeros, minor-league affiliate of the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen is on what he hopes will be a short rehabilitation
assignment before he rejoins the Sox rotation. It is six weeks
since he won a game for the Red Sox, five weeks since he pitched as
many as six innings, and three weeks since he was stashed on the
disabled list, done in by a strained muscle in the back of a
reconstructed right shoulder that held up remarkably well last
season.
</P>
<P>
   If he is able to throw around 70 pitches, Saberhagen said, he
expects to be able to rejoin the Sox rotation by the following
week. If not, the muscle strain threatens to make hash of what had
been a remarkable comeback story.
</P>
<P>
   A story known well to David Cone, the Yankees' righthander who
not only counts Saberhagen among his closest friends in the game,
but scripted his own storybook comeback from an aneurysm in his
pitching shoulder two years ago, winning 20 games at age 35, a
decade after he'd won 20 games for the Mets in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one pulls for him as much as I do,'' Cone said in the
Yankees' clubhouse. ``He's been to hell and back with his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough. He'll come back. But it's disappointing to see him
struggle with it.''
</P>
<P>
   At 35, Saberhagen is 15 months younger than Cone, with whom he
first became friends as prospects in the Royals' system before
being reunited with the Mets in 1992. It's regrettable, Cone said,
but inevitable that for as long as Saberhagen continues to pitch,
he'll have worries about his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The type of surgery he had was so (radical), he'll have to be
careful the rest of his career,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Red Sox) did a great job of handling him last
season. Jimy (Williams) handled him as well as I've ever seen an
injured pitcher handled.''
</P>
<P>
   What many fail to realize, Cone said, is the toll extracted from
Saberhagen each time he pushes himself to come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you pick up a baseball and throw, you've got to
work through the pain,'' Cone said. ``The pain wears you down. The
pain itself is fatiguing. I know that every time I threw, it would
take me 15 minutes to get loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constant fight, dealing with the pain. And it's a
different type of pain, a very sharp, deep type of pain when you
have a shoulder operation. And the meter's still running. It's not
one of those things when you wake up one morning and it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   So, why not concede the fight, count up your big-league wins
(157), your all-star appearances (three), your Cy Young Awards
(two), your World Series ring and Series MVP, and spend the rest of
your afternoons on a golf course someplace warm?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to walk away when there's still a chance you can do
it,'' Cone said. ``He's still a great pitcher. He can still pitch
with the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great tandem they have, Pedro (Martinez) and Sabes
when he is right. Sabes has a feel for pitching; you saw what he
did last year. He used to have the best fastball in the American
League, he and Roger. He doesn't throw 95 anymore, but he can still
throw hard, and he doesn't have to throw 95 to be successful,
because he knows how to pitch and change speeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night in Canal Park in Akron, far from Yankee Stadium
in the Bronx, Saberhagen will ignore the pain one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I anticipate he'll be back,'' Cone said. ``He knows what he
needs to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
