<SLUG> BC-BOMBARDIER-ORDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBARDIER GETS NEW YORK ORDER
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Metropolitan Transportation Authority of New York
has ordered 192 electric rail cars from Bombardier Inc. to replace
commuter trains on the Long Island Rail Road, the company announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The initial contract is worth $445 million, but if options for
808 additional cars are exercised the total price for 1,000 cars
would be $1.85 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Bombardier, a Montreal-based company that has become a global
leader in mass-transit equipment, will build stainless steel bodies
for the trains at La Pocatiere, Quebec, and install the drive
systems and interior fixtures at its United States plant in
Plattsburg, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The contract requires that at least 30 percent of the value of
the work be done in New York, said Kim Fischer, a Bombardier
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Electric of Japan and Supersteel of New York have a
joint-venture company that will make the electric drive systems.
</P>
<P>
   Deliveries to the LIRR are to begin in the second quarter of
2002 and continue for a year. If additional cars are ordered, some
will go into service on the Metro North Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Founded as a maker of snow-moving equipment in 1942, the main
business of Bombardier, has evolved into the construction of subway
cars, trains, airplanes and other motorized vehicles to a broad
range of international clients that range from the New York City
subway system to Shandong Province in China. The company's $8
billion in annual business has been growing at a rate of 20 percent
a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
