<SLUG> BC-SOCTUS-HARASS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Eds., subs to add a 2nd take, of new material)  
 DIVIDED SUPREME COURT HOLDS SCHOOLS LIABLE FOR SEX HARASSMENT BY
STUDENTS  (rm) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ School districts can be liable for damages under
federal law for failing to stop a student from subjecting another
student to severe and pervasive sexual harassment, the Supreme
Court ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-to-4 decision, with a majority opinion by Justice Sandra
Day O'Connor, found the court bitterly divided over the role of
federal law in the public school classroom. The ruling opened
school districts to liability for sexual harassment by students on
essentially the same grounds that a Supreme Court decision a year
ago set for liability when teachers harass students.
</P>
<P>
   What O'Connor, the author of both decisions, described Monday as
a statutory weapon against sex discrimination so severe that it
impairs a victim's ability to learn was labeled in Justice Anthony
M. Kennedy's dissenting opinion as an unwarranted federal intrusion
into ``day-to-day classroom logistics and interactions,'' a
judicial overreaction to ``the routine problems of adolescence.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority opinion was joined by Justices John Paul Stevens,
David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer. Chief
Justice William Rehnquist joined Kennedy's dissent, along with
Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusually direct rejoinder from the bench, O'Connor
concluded her announcement of the decision by addressing the
dissenters who, she said, maintained that the ruling would ``teach
little Johnny a perverse lesson in federalism.'' Rather, she said,
the majority believed the decision ``assures that little Mary may
attend class.''
</P>
<P>
   In her opinion, O'Connor emphasized that ``damages are not
available for simple acts of teasing and name-calling among school
children'' but rather for behavior ``so severe, pervasive, and
objectively offensive that it denies its victims the equal access
to education'' guaranteed under Title IX of the Education
Amendments of 1972. School officials must have known of the
harassment and, acting with ``deliberate indifference,'' failed to
take reasonable steps to stop it, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Resolving a dispute among the lower federal courts, the decision
overturned a ruling last year by the federal appeals court in
Atlanta that Title IX, which bars sex discrimination in schools and
colleges that receive federal money, simply did not apply to
student-on-student harassment. The case will now go back to the
appeals court for an application of the test the court set Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The case was brought by the mother of a girl who, as a
fifth-grader in Forsyth, Ga., complained that she was subjected to
months of sexual advances, taunting and unwanted touching of her
breasts and genital area by a boy who was eventually charged and
convicted in juvenile court of sexual battery against her. The girl
said, among other complaints, that the boy put a door stop in his
pants and acted in a sexually suggestive manner toward her in a gym
class.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and school administrators refused to respond to
complaints brought by the mother, Aurelia Davis, and by her
daughter, LaShonda, who sat next the boy in class and kept begging
to have her seat changed. Unable to concentrate in school,
LaShonda's grades dropped and she wrote a suicide note. The suit
seeks $500,000 in damages.
</P>
<P>
   While the court did not reach a conclusion on the Monroe County
Board of Education's liability, O'Connor's graphic recitation of
the details of the harassing behavior made clear that the school
district does not face an easy task in the next phase of the case.
O'Connor emphasized that schools exercise significant control over
student discipline, particularly in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat surprisingly, in light of the vehemence of Kennedy's
dissent, the National School Boards Association was supportive of
the decision. ``The standard has been set so high that it's a
standard we can live with and in fact are living up to already,''
Julie Underwood, the association's general counsel, said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the situation the court was addressing was, in a
sense, ``anachronistic'' because in the six years since this
lawsuit was filed, ``school districts have really worked hard to
have policies against sexual harassment and to help children
understand sexual harassment.'' Monroe County had no formal policy
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Greenberger, co-president of the National Women's Law
Center, which represented the Davis family, said she was satisfied
with the decision as well. She said the court had drawn ``a line
that makes sense,'' adding that the decision ``puts
student-on-student harassment on a proper footing with the rest of
Title IX.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's dissenting opinion, at 34 pages half again as long as
the majority opinion, took issue with the majority's premise that
``sex discrimination'' or ``sexual harassment'' was the proper way
to describe what he called at various points ``immature, childish
behavior'' and ``inappropriate behavior by children who are just
learning to interact with their peers.''
</P>
<P>
   In the workplace context as well as, more recently, in the
schools, the cCourt's precedents have treated sexual harassment as
a form of sex discrimination. But Kennedy said the court now had
taken that analysis too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``The norms of the adult workplace that have defined hostile
environment sexual harassment are not easily translated to peer
relationships in schools,'' he said, ``where teen-age romantic
relationships and dating are a part of everyday life.'' He added,
``a teen-ager's romantic overtures to a classmate (even when
persistent and unwelcome) are an inescapable part of adolescence.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said that while the majority described its test as
narrow and limiting, it was ``in fact, so broad that it will
support untold numbers of lawyers'' and lead courts and juries ``to
second-guess school administrators in every case.'' The result, he
said, would be ``a climate of fear that encourages school
administrators to label even the most innocuous of childish conduct
sexual harassment.'' He cited recent incidents in which schools had
suspended young children for kissing classmates of the opposite
sex.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor replied with a warning of her own. ``We trust that the
dissent's characterization of our opinion will not mislead courts
to impose more sweeping liability than we read Title IX to
require,'' she said, adding that to meet the court's test, the
behavior would ordinarily have to have a ``systemic effect'' rather
than reflect a single incident.
</P>
<P>
   But it was on the ground of federalism that the real battle in
this case, Davis vs. Monroe County Board of Education, No. 97-843,
appeared to have been fought.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said, ``Perhaps the most grave, and surely the most
lasting, disservice of Monday's decision is that it insures the
court's own disregard for the federal balance soon will be imparted
to our youngest citizens.'' He continued, ``Federal influence will
permeate everything from curriculum decisions to day-to-day
classroom logistics and interactions.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, until now, had been a reliable ally on the states'
rights side virtually any time a case raising federalism issues was
before the court. In the teacher harassment case last year, Gebser
vs. Lago Vista Independent School District, it was O'Connor and
Monday's dissenters who formed the 5-to-4 majority that set a high
hurdle for students to meet in suing school districts for
harassment by teachers; the four more liberal justices who joined
the majority Monday complained then that the test was too strict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
