<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURTING EWING KEEPS HOPING FOR THAT CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fourteen years removed from his Georgetown days and
five years removed from his only appearance in the NBA Finals (a
painful coulda/shoulda/woulda seven-game loss after being up, three
games to two), Patrick Ewing labors mightily for the New York
Knicks these days.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a pretty sight.
</P>
<P>
   It is now a cliche to label him a ``warrior.'' You'd think it
was on his birth certificate. But let's not go there. Just call him
a proud professional who wants desperately to win a championship,
and who hopes he doesn't get in the way while healthier and younger
men (Herb Williams excepted) bring more tangible assets to the
table.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks won Sunday's third game against Atlanta with their
captain making a minimal contribution. He had two baskets in 12
attempts. He never went to the line. He had no assists. He did grab
seven rebounds, and that often is his major contribution. He
blocked no shots. He only played 24 minutes, and it is almost a
given that his team would have won had he not played at all. His
backup, Chris Dudley, put up playoff career highs of 14 points and
12 rebounds and he, not the aging All-Star center, got a standing O
when he fouled out with 1:06 left.
</P>
<P>
   There have been much better times to be Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for all this is known to everyone who cares. It's not
simply a case of him being less than three months shy of his 37th
birthday. Or maybe it is. The reason he looks 136, and not merely
36, is that he is injured. Or is the reason he is injured because
he is a worn-out 36? We may not know the answer until next season,
when the Knicks are obligated to pay this man in excess of $14
million.
</P>
<P>
   He's got the textbook bad knees, but what 36-year-old center
doesn't? All that asphalt pounding as a youth and all that running
up and down the floor _ and, oh, how Patrick Ewing could run _
takes an inevitable toll. Now he also has a damaged left Achilles'
tendon. His best friend, more often than not, is a bucket of ice.
</P>
<P>
   He is probably too heavy, if you want to get right down to it.
He never was able to get in shape, at least not the kind of shape
he is accustomed to. He is now paying a fearful price for his
countless hours as a Players Association leader. Time that would
ordinarily have been spent working out was given over to hours
logged in a suit plotting the future of his fellow players. And in
the end he was discarded, as a deal many believe to be harmful to
the players was cut. He was not pleased.
</P>
<P>
   Time really does fly by, doesn't it? We are, after all, talking
about our Patrick Ewing, arguably the best Greater Boston high
school product ever. This is the Patrick Ewing of Cambridge Rindge
&AMP; Latin, who emigrated from Jamaica at age 11 and who grew up to be
the leader of multiple state champions. He took his services to
Georgetown, where he played in three NCAA title games in four years
and where he won a championship in 1984, when he and Michael Graham
terrorized Sam Bowie and Mel Turpin in an unforgettable semifinal
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   He was an extraordinarily shy young man who was not comfortable
outside his circle of close friends, but who was said to be a
delightful companion to those he knew best. The rest of us couldn't
see it then, but we can see it now. He is a poised man, entirely
sure of himself. He has a killer smile. He can be as elusive as the
next guy when it comes to granting interviews, but when he is in
the mood he is charming, engaging, and informative. As an adult, he
has always been good for a few surprises. I mean, who would have
thought that the No. 1, guaranteed, mortal lock, go-to-dinner
companions on the dream team would have been Larry Bird and Patrick
Ewing, or, as they were known for those seven weeks, ``Harry and
Larry?''
</P>
<P>
   Molded by Mike Jarvis to be a facsimile Bill Russell, and
further trained by John Thompson to treat offense as an
afterthought, he has turned out to be one of the great offensive
centers of all-time. When the short list of Most Reliable Moves of
all-time is compiled, sure to be included is Patrick Ewing's
patented baseline turnaround jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Relying primarily on that shot, Ewing averaged between 20 and
28.6 points a game for his first 13 NBA seasons. After missing 51
games in his first two seasons because of injury he became a
classic clock-punching machine, missing but 20 games over the next
10 seasons before missing the final 56 games of the 1997-98 season
with a freak wrist injury that could have happened to some
21-year-old kid as easily as to a 13-year veteran.
</P>
<P>
   But an assortment of ailments kept him out of 12 games this
year, and it's pretty obvious that as soon as the playoffs are over
he will go to bed for about a month. He is really, really hurting.
He struggles to get up and down the floor, looking like a '49
Studebaker attempting to keep up with a bunch of Porsches.
</P>
<P>
   But Patrick Ewing has a fierce heart, and he wants to be in
there. You can feel very comfortable attaching the word
``inspiration'' to his name.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
