<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PENTAGON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ATTACKS DISRUPT ELECTRICITY, WATER SUPPLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite poor weather, NATO planes attacked
electrical transformers throughout Serbia early Monday in an
attempt to cut off the Yugoslav military communications and supply
links to Kosovo, Pentagon and NATO officials said.
</P>
<P>
   By striking at the power complexes, the air campaign disrupted
daily civilian life, cutting off both electricity and the water
supply, since water pumping stations rely on electrical power.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said Monday that their intention was to undercut
the military effort in Kosovo, not to hurt civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not targeted the water system,'' said Peter Daniel, a
NATO spokesman in Brussels, Belgium. ``The difficulties with water
supply relate mostly to the difficulties that exist with the supply
of electricity.''
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon official said that despite the problems caused to
civilians, targeting the electrical grid system is a legitimate
objective, since the military operation of President Slobodan
Milosevic depends upon electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aware this will have an impact on civilians, but we are
in the midst of a military operation against Slobodan Milosevic,''
said a Pentagon official. ``Compare that to the consequences
suffered by the civilian population of Kosovo who have been driven
from their homes and have neither shelter, heat, water or food.''
</P>
<P>
   When NATO began hitting electrical plants earlier this month,
blacking out Belgrade and other cities, human rights groups
questioned whether the military benefits outweighed the harm they
caused to civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is that in a modern society, the electrical grid
is critical to providing essential services, especially the water
system, which has serious consequences for civilian health,'' said
Dinah PoKempner, deputy general counsel of Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said that the allied warplanes had attacked power
transformers at Nis, Drmno and Novi Sad early Monday, to disrupt
the military's command system, the air defense systems and
propaganda transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   William Arkin, the military consultant to Human Rights Watch,
objected to the bombing. ``Didn't the Air Force learn its lesson
from Iraq?'' he asked. ``You cut off electricity and the water
supply, you undermine public health and undermine your own
objectives of not only achieving your military mission but winning
the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   As the air war entered its third month, NATO and Pentagon
officials said the campaign was undermining the ability of
Milosevic to supply and maintain soldiers in Kosovo. Even though he
has been able to send replacements to Kosovo, the Pentagon said,
these troops have gone in without the usual equipment or supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marching in with troops without equipment probably makes them
feel good from the numbers standpoint, but it doesn't make them
effective from a standpoint of a very sophisticated military,''
said Air Force Major Gen. Charles Wald.
</P>
<P>
   Wald said there was evidence that the Yugoslav troops in Kosovo
are so low on fuel that they are taking gasoline from cars left
behind by fleeing refugees. Basic stocks are low, forcing soldiers
to forage for food.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not to the point where they're not effective,'' said
Wald. ``But it will be hard to sustain them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon announced the arrival of 20 fighter bombers, the
F/A-18D, at airbases in Hungary. Four more planes were expected to
arrive this week.
</P>
<P>
   After several days of training, the official said, the planes
will begin operations against targets in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   This month NATO officials expanded the basing of planes to
Hungary and Turkey to allow the air campaign to operate around the
clock. Without the introduction of ground troops, NATO is flying
more low-level missions over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's fleet of aircraft now numbers more than a thousand,
including 723 American airplanes and 281 aircraft from other
allies. This is more than twice the number originally committed in
March.
</P>
</TEXT>
