<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH-PATAKI TICKET NO DONE DEAL DESPITE ENDORSEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARA JAKES and JAMES M. ODATO  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gov. George Pataki became the 17th Republican state
chief executive Monday to endorse Texas Gov. George W. Bush for
president, setting up renewed speculation that the New Yorker was
positioning himself to become Bush's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Pataki dreams of a date in November 2000 with Bush _
a prospect he refused to discuss Monday _ political analysts were
divided over whether he would be tapped from the long list of names
on Bush's dance card.
</P>
<P>
   And Democrats said that even with Pataki on the ticket, New York
was unlikely to fall into the Republican column in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   With GOP loyalists behind him on the podium of a Manhattan hotel
and several dozen reporters looking on, Pataki turned to a
10-foot-high video screen, where Bush appeared via satellite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're here this morning not to talk about me, but to talk
about ideas,'' Pataki said. ``And that's why I am very proud this
morning to join with my colleagues in saying that not just me, but
New York state, is going to work to make sure that the next
president of the United States is my friend, the great governor
from Texas, Gov. George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid cheers, Bush said, ``The goal is much bigger than `The Two
Georges.' The goal is restoring dignity to the White House, and the
goal is to make sure America is better for everybody as we head
into the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   With its 33 electoral votes _ the second-largest bloc in the
country, behind California _ New York is a crucial state to win in
a presidential election. Pataki backers say his presence on a
national ticket would sweep the Empire State for the Republicans, a
feat that has eluded the party since Ronald Reagan's 48-state 1984
landslide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think George Pataki makes perfect sense for Bush,'' said New
York-based GOP strategist Jay Severin. ``When you look at a
Texas/New York axis, when you begin to calculate what it means to
Democrats if they're denied Texas and possibly New York, the math
becomes very daunting.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether Pataki could deliver New York for the GOP is, at
best, questionable. Democrats carried 52 of the state's 62 counties
in 1996. Pataki won a second term last fall with only 53 percent of
the vote against a significantly outspent Democrat, Peter Vallone.
And Democrats say the possible presence of Hillary Rodham Clinton
on the ballot for an open U.S. Senate seat now held by Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat, could draw votes to their ticket.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Party spokesman Matthew Hiltzik, pointing to
polls showing Pataki's approval rating has slid 17 points over the
last four months, said New Yorkers would be less likely to vote for
a national ticket that includes Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Some political observers said Monday that Pennsylvania Gov.
Thomas Ridge, for example, was a more likely pairing if Bush wins
the GOP nomination and seeks a moderate Republican governor. ``He's
pro-choice, he's a Vietnam vet and he's better looking,'' one
Democratic Party leader said.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates mentioned by Republicans Monday included
Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson or Michigan Gov. John Engler. Both
fit Bush's need for a moderate Republican from a big state far from
Texas, said Michael Edelman, a GOP analyst from Westchester County,
who also pointed to Arizona Sen. John McCain, a presidential
hopeful, as a potential vice presidential candidate if Bush is the
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   But as Bush weighs such factors as ideology, reputation and
geography, Edelman said, a Northeast governor like Pataki could
help him win.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki would not acknowledge that his endorsement could
translate into a vice presidential nomination, and he did not
answer when asked twice if he would be willing to give up the
governorship midway through his four-year term to join Bush in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Many at the event, however, said they were sure Pataki would
seize the vice presidential nomination, if offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely. Without equivocation,'' said Rep. John Sweeney,
R-N.Y., a close Pataki political adviser. ``While that isn't one of
the primary goals that the governor based his (Bush endorsement)
decision on ... we're hoping that'll happen. It's incumbent upon us
to make this a success and do the good things that have to be done
for Governor Bush so Governor Pataki has a better opportunity at
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But state GOP Chairman Bill Powers, referring to the vice
presidential nomination, noted, ``You don't run for that. And if
you do, you don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pataki has scheduled political speeches this summer in
Detroit, California, Washington state and Montana _ engagements
Powers said the governor should keep in order to continue espousing
Republican themes of tax cuts, reducing welfare and crime control
and what Pataki called ``passionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said Bush must first make his
final decision to run for president _ a decision that won't come
until after May 31, when the Texas Legislature adjourns _ before he
starts thinking about running mates. ``It's too early to
hypothesize about that,'' she said, when asked if a `George-George'
ticket was possible for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of Republican Party unity that the governor touted
Monday, however, apparently did not extend to fellow Republican
Rudolph Giuliani, the mayor of New York City, who was not invited
to the endorsement event.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, a political rival of the governor's, is widely
considered the party favorite running for the Moynihan seat.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Pataki on the ballroom stage Monday was Rep. Rick Lazio,
a Long Island Republican, a yet-unannounced candidate for the same
Senate post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
