<HEADLINE>
PATTERNS: ROUNDING UP STARS TO LEND GLAMOUR TO FASHION AWARDS SHOW
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
STARS OF THE SHOW  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What would an awards ceremony be without celebrities? Lacking in
glamour, most people seem to think. So the Council of Fashion
Designers of America is working hard to corral Hollywood
personalities to participate in its annual awards show on June 2,
now called the American Fashion Awards. No matter that the only
clear connection may be that the performers wear designer clothes
(usually borrowed) at other awards ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who will be presenters are Chris Rock, who will give
Calvin Klein the men's wear designer of the year award, and Joanna
Margolies, who will fittingly cite In Style magazine for ``putting
the spotlight on fashion and Hollywood.'' Bette Midler and Martha
Stewart will give Simon Doonan of Barneys New York a special award
for his ``window on fashion.'' Rita Wilson, along with Donna Karan
and Klein, will bestow posthumous honors on Elizabeth Tilberis, who
was the editor in chief of Harper's Bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   Two actresses will be co-hosts of a television show, produced by
the council, that will precede the June 13 telecast of an edited
version of the awards ceremony on the E! cable network. The job
will be shared by Sela Ward, who won an Emmy for ``Sisters,'' and
Caroline Rhea, who plays Sabrina's aunt on ``Sabrina, the Teen-Age
Witch.''
</P>
<P>
   Other confirmed presenters, celebrities in the fashion world,
will be Donatella Versace, who will give the Eugenia Shepard award
for fashion journalism to Elsa Klensch of CNN; John Fairchild, the
former publisher of Women's Wear Daily, who will give the lifetime
achievement award to Yves Saint Laurent, and Andre Leon Talley of
Vogue, who will present the international award to Yohji Yamamoto.
</P>
<P>
   Not learning from last year's fiasco with Christine Baranski as
host, the council is negotiating with another actress to fill that
post but would not confirm the name.
</P>
<P>
   And there is still some question whether the biggest potential
stars of the evening _ Sophia Loren, who will be cited by the
council for a lifetime of glamour, and Cher, cited for her
influence on fashion _ will actually be at the ceremony. Last year,
a major dose of glamour was provided by Elizabeth Taylor, who
sparkled in dangling jeweled earrings and a silver-beaded white
dress that set off her white hair. She was honored for _ what else?
_ a lifetime of glamour.  &QL; 
FROM DAY INTO EVENING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After 36 years of making jewelry, 15 in his own business, Pedro
Boregaard refuses to be type-cast. His designs range from punklike
oxidized silver chains with menacing spikes, to rings with sawtooth
edges, to pretty little eggs and hearts inset with diamonds or
colored stones.
</P>
<P>
   ``My idea is to do jewelry in a modern way,'' he said the other
day in his Manhattan atelier, ``so the woman can put it on in the
morning and go out at night in the same jewelry. To create jewelry
with a glamorous luster is old hat. You have to do it for today's
woman.''
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate his 15th anniversary this year, Boregaard, who was
born in Germany and learned his craft at a renowned Munich jeweler
called Hemmerle, was looking for a streamlined shape. He found it
in an unexpected place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was observing moths,'' he said, ``and I saw that when moths
sit they create a triangle. It's a very aerodynamic shape, like a
stealth fighter almost.''
</P>
<P>
   So he designed a collection of sleek moths with folded wings,
ranging from inchlong pins of oxidized silver and gold ($660) to a
two-and-a-half-inch-long mosaic brooch of three different golds set
with 11 carats of colored diamonds in shades of brown and beige
($65,000).
</P>
<P>
   His jewelry may be viewed by appointment: (212) 826-3660.
</P>
</TEXT>
