<SLUG> BC-HONDA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Honda snub has Georgia asking 'Why not here?'
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia likes to crow about its economic successes,
but car makers apparently remain unimpressed even as they have
scoured the Southeast for new factory sites.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Georgia recruiters have begun a hunt to find out what the
problem is. They plan to ask auto manufacturers what they can do
better.
</P>
<P>
   The latest hit came from Honda, which earlier this month
announced that it will employ 1,500 people and build a $400 million
assembly plant near Lincoln, Ala. Georgia officials were surprised.
They had never been told by company representatives that a site the
state offered northeast of metro Atlanta was no longer in the
running.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia offered Honda a free site, more than $20 million worth
of road improvements, a new worker training center, tax breaks and
encouragement from the governor and other top state officials. But
Honda didn't even talk directly with Georgia officials about their
offer.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in the 1990s, an automaker had chosen to
bring new jobs and money to a neighboring state. And for the third
time, Georgia didn't appear to be close in the competition.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, BMW selected a site in Greer, S.C., for a new plant.
Georgia apparently wasn't even in the running. A year later,
Mercedes-Benz announced it would take its considerable name and
clout to Vance, Ala., to build a $300 million assembly plant west
of Birmingham, Ala. Georgia, by some estimates, came in fourth. In
earlier years, other automakers came to the Southeast. Toyota went
to Kentucky, and Nissan and Saturn settled in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia economic recruiters say they aren't sure what's been
lacking in the state's offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does make you pause and say, `What is it?' '' said John
Malone, a manager in economic development for Georgia Power. ``It's
a large project. You don't enjoy not at least being strongly
considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Georgia Department of Industry, Trade &AMP;
Tourism; Georgia Power; NationsBank; and other companies involved
in economic development say they will try to meet with Honda
officials, their site selection team and perhaps Mercedes
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all been reflecting on it,'' said Mike Lott,
NationsBank's vice president for economic development in Georgia.
``We need to find out some after-the-fact information.''
</P>
<P>
   Several recruiters aren't so sure Honda officials will agree to
sit down and talk candidly. There would be little benefit to the
company to highlight Georgia's shortcomings, recruiters say.
</P>
<P>
   That may leave the state's recruiters exactly where they are
now: Guessing why Georgia hasn't landed a new auto assembly plant
since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Cardoza, the commissioner of Georgia's Department of
Industry, Trade &AMP; Tourism, says he believes the presence of large
Ford and General Motors assembly plants in metro Atlanta was a
factor in Honda's decision. Both plants have unions. Cardoza said
that may scare off automakers who may fear unionization efforts at
new plants.
</P>
<P>
   Economist Jeff Humphreys from the University of Georgia says car
makers worry less about union demands for higher wages but more
about the flexibility they fear they would lose in a unionized
factory.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is that Georgia traditionally does not offer
financial incentives as rich as those in neighboring states. While
Georgia officials never placed a value on the incentives they
offered to Honda, they said it fell well under the $158 million
pricetag that Alabama reported on its offer. Georgia also offered
far less than Alabama when that state attracted Mercedes with over
$250 million in enticements.
</P>
<P>
   Honda spokesman Jeffrey Smith said the company was ``leaning
very strongly toward Alabama'' even before financial incentives
were discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also said the presence of unions in existing auto plants
``is not really a factor'' in the placement of Honda's new assembly
plant. Instead, Smith said, Alabama emerged as a strong contender
early on because of issues such as its climate, transportation
network and large pool of available workers.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiters also say Georgia has not felt the need to be as
aggressive as Alabama in the hunt for assembly plants. Georgia has
been able to rely on a healthy economy. Even in terms of
manufacturing jobs, Georgia has seen growth while the rest of the
nation has slipped.
</P>
<P>
   Car plants also raise air pollution issues. Metro Atlanta's air
pollution problems put limits on industry, and that could restrict
car makers, who have been most interested in the northern part of
the state.
</P>
<P>
   The state has also put some of its focus on other areas, such as
high-tech companies that may show more promise for growth.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Power's John Malone said that when Honda made its
announcement about Alabama, he was more concerned about the
similarly timed decision by Dell Computer Corp. to build a new
plant in Nashville that would employ 3,000. Georgia apparently was
not a top contender for Dell's facility, Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia officials say they will continue to compete for auto
plants. They could get extra tools for that effort soon. Some state
officials are pushing for money to buy or reserve large sites to
offer to large employers, such as assembly plants. And Georgia Gov.
Roy Barnes has said he intends to review the state's incentive
options this year to see if improvements are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Malone offers some ideas on how Georgia could bolster its
chances to attract auto makers: Be ready with broad and very
flexible incentive options. And, he said, create a team to include
the governor and the commissioner of the Department of Industry,
Trade &AMP; Tourism to court auto makers personally.
</P>
<P>
   Form a team, he said, ``that aggressively attacks this and
doesn't quit until they get a plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kempner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
