A9537 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-BIAS-BOS &LR;      05-24 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-BIAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT OPENS WAY FOR PEER HARASSMENT SUITS IN SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Addressing a different school-safety issue and
expanding the definition of illegal gender discrimination, a
sharply divided Supreme Court told the nation's schools Monday that
they can be sued for student-on-student sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-4 decision _ its first on the issue of peer harassment in
schools _ the court ruled that educational institutions receiving
federal funds would be liable for monetary damages if they are
``deliberately indifferent'' to student-on-student harassment ``so
severe, pervasive, and objectively offensive'' that it interferes
with the victim's education.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling had the immediate effect of reviving a lawsuit
brought in 1992 by Aurelia Davis, who had unsuccessfully argued
that the Monroe County (Ga.) Board of Education had not done enough
to protect her fifth-grade daughter, LaShonda, from the persistent
and unbearable sexual advances of a 10-year-old male classmate
identified in court records as ``G.F.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's advocacy groups generally hailed the Davis decision as
an important milestone in the interpretation of the laws barring
gender discrimination. Marcia Greenberger, co-president of the
National Women's Law Center, which argued the Davis case before the
high court, called it ``a very important win for women and girls in
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision also sent chills through the country's elementary
and secondary schools as well as colleges and universities that
receive federal funds. Julie Underwood, general counsel for the
National School Boards Association, said schools could take some
comfort that the court had set ``an awfully high standard'' for
liability. ``It is one we can live with,'' Underwood said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``deliberately indifferent'' standard is identical to the
one the court set last year in the case of a Texas teacher who had
a secret, sexual affair with a student. The court ruled that under
Title IX of the 1972 Education Amendments, the victim could not
recover damages because the school district was not aware of the
harassment and therefore not liable for it.
</P>
<P>
   In the Davis case, the majority found, the Monroe County school
board remained idle in the face of knowing a student was harassing
another student in its schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having previously determined that `sexual harassment' is
`discrimination' in the school context under Title IX, we are
constrained to conclude that student-on-student sexual harassment,
if sufficiently severe, can likewise rise to the level of
discrimination actionable under the statute,'' Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor wrote for the majority.
</P>
<P>
   But in a biting dissent, the court minority predicted the ruling
would both set off ``runaway litigation'' by parents who mistake
childish conduct for harassment and unduly burden schools with new
costs and policing obligations. In an unusual turn, Justice Anthony
Kennedy read from the dissent in open court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of defending against peer sexual harassment suits
alone could overwhelm many school districts,'' Kennedy wrote.
``Some schools lack the resources even to deal with serious
problems of violence and are already overwhelmed with disciplinary
problems of all kinds.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, chided the court
majority for being ``oblivious to the fact that almost every child,
at some point, has trouble in school because he or she is being
teased by his or her peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girl who wants to skip recess because she is teased by
boys is no different from the overweight child who skips gym class
because the other children tease her about her size in the locker
room, or the child who risks flunking out because he refuses to
wear glasses to avoid the taunts of `four eyes,' '' Kennedy wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The court majority, including Justices John Paul Stevens, David
H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, and Stephen Breyer, called those
comparisons ``misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the school setting, students often engage in insults,
banter, teasing, shoving, pushing, and gender-specific conduct that
is upsetting'' but not discrimination, O'Connor wrote. ``Damages
are only available where the behavior is so severe, pervasive and
objectively offensive that it denies victims equal access to
education.''
</P>
<P>
   LaShonda Davis and her mother reported numerous incidents of
grabbing, groping, and suggestive talk by G.F., but school
officials did not discipline him. The boy eventually pleaded guilty
to charges of sexual battery after Mrs. Davis complained to the
county sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Alzapiedi is executive director of the Title IX
Advocacy Project, a nonprofit education organization that monitors
sexual harassment in middle and secondary schools in the Boston
area. She said serious harassment is often minimized as harmless
teasing, when in fact it is widespread and can have a ``devastating
impact'' on victims who experience depression, anxiety, and even
miss school because of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my hope that today's decision will be a wake-up call to
school officials who do not respond to complaints of peer sexual
harassment and to those officials who have ignored the sexual
harassment that they have witnessed between students,'' Alzapiedi
said.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Rodriques, an employment lawyer with the Boston firm of
Sullivan &AMP; Worcester, said universities could be at high risk for
liability because of the age of the college population, its social
freedom, and the typical hands-off attitude of college
administrators toward students' personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put yourself at Harvard,'' Rodriques said, ``and how much do
officials know, or want to know, about sexual harassment in a
mixed-up environment where students are studying, playing, going to
class, and sleeping together?''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled last year that employers can be held
liable in a sexual harassment suit if they do not enforce policies
preventing misconduct by managers and supervisors. The standard is
higher for school administrators _ they can't be sued for what they
did not know _ but ``the bar being high doesn't mean schools won't
get sued, and it won't be a pain in the neck,'' Rodrigues said.
</P>
<P>
   W. Warren Plowden Jr. of Macon, Ga., who represented the school
board, said he was ``disappointed'' with the high court ruling but
believed having to prove school officials are ``deliberately
indifferent'' would still be difficult for plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Davis v. Monroe County Board of Education, 97-843.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
