A9538 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALMPILOT-VII-COX     05-24 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALMPILOT-VII-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Palm VII buyers get early Web link
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Monday morning, 150 versions of the new Palm VII that
had been sold in metropolitan New York were _ wirelessly _
activated.
</P>
<P>
   Although the device's formal launch was not until 4 p.m.at the
Rainbow Room, those who bought the Palm VII earlier were able to
register and connect to BellSouth's national wireless network
within minutes, linking to the Internet as they walked, drove or
sat and watched the pigeons in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been working on this for almost three years,'' said
William F. Lenahan, president and chief executive of BellSouth
Wireless Data. ``I think this is a breakthrough kind of product.''
</P>
<P>
   Those first purchasers of the hand-held Palm VII are likely not
impulse buyers, since the device costs about $600.
</P>
<P>
   Made by Palm Computing, a subsidiary of 3Com, the Palm VII is at
its heart like the popular predecessor Palm Pilots, a personal
organizer.
</P>
<P>
   But built into the Palm VII is the ability to connect to the
Net, and those signals _ both upload and down _ are carried on the
same network used for BellSouth's interactive paging service.
</P>
<P>
   To make it work quickly enough, a Palm user has access to only
stripped-down Web sites. But perhaps more likely to draw users is
the ability to do financial transactions, send messages or receive
stock prices all day long.
</P>
<P>
   Others _ notably Psion and Microsoft _ are mounting their own
challenges with wireless devices aimed at the same market as Palm
VII. But Palm has something of a headstart.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3 million people use the Palm Pilot. ``If only 10
percent of them upgrade, that would be hundreds of thousands of
users. We see it as a significant impact on BellSouth's Wireless
Data network,'' said Lenahan.
</P>
<P>
   Users choose a monthly plan from $10 up, paying Palm Computing,
which in turn pays BellSouth for use of the network. ``By the end
of the year, I think (the revenue) from this will be significant.''
</P>
<P>
   While the devices are for sale now only in New York, Connecticut
and New Jersey, they are to be sold nationally by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   But they work on the national network right away, so a buyer can
use their Internet access anywhere in the country that BellSouth's
system works.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
