<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEMINIST-PROF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES AGAINST FEMINIST PROFESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A feminist theologian who has refused to admit men to
her classes lost a crucial early round Monday in her fight to keep
her teaching job at Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Middlesex Superior Court Judge Martha B. Sosman said BC has
adequate cause to fire Mary Daly, citing Daly's defiance of college
policy that all courses be open to male and female students.
</P>
<P>
   The judge refused to bar BC from distributing a catalog next
month that omits courses taught by Daly or from telling people Daly
had retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston College made a strong showing in support of its
contention that Daly did in fact agree to retire,'' Sosman said, in
denying Daly's request for a preliminary injunction.
</P>
<P>
   Rulings on preliminary injunctions are often seen as a harbinger
of how lawsuits will fare when they go to trial. Daly's suit
follows repeated clashes with college administrators over her
exclusion of men from her classes.
</P>
<P>
   Daly's attorney, Gretchen Van Ness, said she is looking at
possible grounds for appeal of Sosman's decision, but Daly
nevertheless plans to take her case to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always more facts and more law to be developed over
the course of the trial,'' Van Ness said. ``We are still optimistic
we will have a full and fair hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge found that after senior Duane Naquin threatened to sue
BC over his exclusion from a course taught by Daly, the school told
Daly she could not prevent or try to dissuade males from taking her
classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daly took the position that she would rather resign than admit
male students to her class,'' Sosman said.
</P>
<P>
   Daly and the college began negotiating a severance package,
although no final agreement was ever signed.
</P>
<P>
   Daly, 70, who has taught women-only courses at BC for a quarter
century, said she only agreed to take a leave of absence this
spring and planned to return to teaching this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no formal hearing and no formal notice to
her,'' said Van Ness. ``She has been simply erased from the course
catalog. All the rights that she has as a tenured professor have
been trampled on by Boston College.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sosman ruled that even if ultimately Daly's ``oral promise
to resign'' isn't found to be legally binding, ``there is no
question that the school has adequate cause to terminate Daly'' due
to her ``vehement and very public defiance'' of the school's
non-discrimination policy.
</P>
<P>
   BC spokesman Jack Dunn said college officials have reprimanded
Daly on five occasions over the past two decades for refusing to
let males into her class.
</P>
<P>
   Daly, whose books include ``Gyn/Ecology: The Metaethics of
Radical Feminism'' and ``Quintessence . . . Realizing the Archaic
Future: A Radical Elemental Feminist Manifesto,'' has said her
courses lose their impact if men enroll, because women become
inhibited when men are in the room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 2031EDT &QL; 
