A9545 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-SCHWEPPES-COX     05-24 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SCHWEPPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke scales down Cadbury deal
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co., bending to European antitrust
regulators, has scaled back its proposed purchase of Cadbury
Schweppes' brands outside the United States by eliminating most
European markets from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies said Monday that the revised $1.1 billion
agreement for Dr Pepper, Canada Dry, Crush and Schweppes brands now
covers 106 countries, including the United Kingdom, Ireland and
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   The original deal announced last December was valued at $1.85
billion and covered 126 nations, including Germany, Italy and
Spain. Those three countries have been dropped, along with 17 other
European nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies have now concluded that regulatory resistance in
certain countries within the European Union would probably result
in unacceptable delay,'' Cadbury said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury Chief Executive John Sunderland told reporters it was no
longer fruitful to keep ``banging our heads against a regulatory
brick wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola was more measured in its comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sincerely believed that the original deal was a good one
for all parties, and that the transaction and notifications were
sensitive to all relevant legal requirements,'' Coca-Cola Chairman
and Chief Executive M. Douglas Ivester said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we may have disagreed with some of the conclusions that
were reached, we continue, as always, to have complete respect for
the regulatory processes,'' Ivester added.
</P>
<P>
   But several industry analysts said Coca-Cola may have mishandled
the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question arises: Was Coke prepared from a regulatory
standpoint?'' said Deutsche Bank analyst Scott Wilkins. ``Did they
do their regulatory homework? ... It's usually not positive when
the shape of a deal is changed in midstream, and this deal is still
not consummated.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts said the companies made a pragmatic move, given
the unanticipated regulatory obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is trademark Ivester,'' said John Sicher, editor and
publisher of Beverage Digest. ``It's coming up with the best
solution in a set of circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the biggest deal announced by Coca-Cola since Ivester
took the helm from the late Roberto C. Goizueta in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators in Australia and Mexico _ key markets _ also have
opposed the initial deal as anti-competitive. The companies have
submitted a revised proposal in Australia in hopes of winning
regulatory approval the second time around. They hope to do the
same in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The companies' decision in Europe comes after EU Competition
Commissioner Karel Van Miert chastised Coca-Cola for trying to
bypass EU antitrust review by dealing with the regulators for each
country.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola and Cadbury argued that the EU did not have
jurisdiction in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium's regulators already have rejected the deal, and Germany
was reportedly poised to do the same. France has never been part of
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The European pullout means the total deal, if completed in its
present form, would add nearly 500 million cases to Coca-Cola's
annual volume. The original deal covered more than 600 million
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Both Coca-Cola and industry analysts expect the volume figures
to rise considerably when the Cadbury brands are put into
Coca-Cola's vast distribution network around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cadbury Schweppes brands give us growth opportunities in
flavor segments where we currently don't have products,'' said
Coca-Cola spokesman Robert Baskin.
</P>
<P>
   While the new deal allows Cadbury to sell its European brands
not covered by the deal to other companies, including Pepsico,
Cadbury said it planned to continue to operate them for the
``foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   A few analysts even speculated that Coca-Cola would take another
swipe at Cadbury's European brands in a few years, if the
regulatory climate changes.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico spokesman Jeff Brown said he would not speculate on what
his company might do in the wake of the new deal.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the agreement will be completed in stages. The
companies hope to close the deal in about half the countries in
July, with many other closings by end of the third quarter. It
could be a longer process in several countries, possibly the United
Kingdom, Mexico and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's shares fell $1.18 3/4 Monday to close at $66.81 1/4
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the European countries excluded from the revised deal
between Coca-Cola and Cadbury Schweppes 1:
</P>
<P>
   Andorra
</P>
<P>
   Austria
</P>
<P>
   Belgium
</P>
<P>
   Denmark
</P>
<P>
   Finland
</P>
<P>
   France
</P>
<P>
   Germany
</P>
<P>
   Gibraltar
</P>
<P>
   Iceland
</P>
<P>
   Italy
</P>
<P>
   Liechtenstein
</P>
<P>
   Luxembourg
</P>
<P>
   Malta
</P>
<P>
   Monaco
</P>
<P>
   Norway
</P>
<P>
   Portugal
</P>
<P>
   San Marino
</P>
<P>
   Spain
</P>
<P>
   Sweden
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland
</P>
<P>
   Netherlands
</P>
<P>
   1 The U.S. and South Africa also are excluded from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Cadbury Schweppes
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
