<SLUG> BC-CADBURY-COKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COKE PURSUES SCALED DOWN CADBURY DEAL
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the face of resistance from regulators around the world, the
Coca-Cola Co. scaled back its agreement yesterday to buy the
soft-drink brands of Cadbury Schweppes PLC.
</P>
<P>
   The companies had announced a $1.85 billion deal in December in
which Coca-Cola agreed to buy Cadbury's brands worldwide, but
regulators in Australia, Mexico, Belgium and the European Union
have rejected or expressed concern in recent weeks about the
purchase, usually because of the increased market dominance it
would give Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to preserve as much of the deal as possible, Coca-Cola will
pay $1.1 billion to control brands like Dr Pepper, Schweppes and
Crush except in most of the European Union countries. The deal is
expected to close by July in most of the countries and will be cut
back further if certain countries do not approve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Coke would not have wanted this to happen, and
neither would Cadbury,'' Jennifer Solomon, a beverage analyst for
Salomon Smith Barney, said. ``It's a disappointment to both
parties, but I don't think it's a shock to investors. Everyone was
starting to get nervous about the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Baskin, a Coca-Cola spokesman, said the revised agreement
came about because of ``regulatory resistance in certain countries
within the European Union, and they would have resulted in
unacceptable delays.''
</P>
<P>
   Baskin said the new agreement would mean about 500 million cases
of additional annual volume for Coca-Cola compared with 600 million
under the original plan. ``It's still a good strategic move for
us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest effect would seem to be on Cadbury's plans. When the
sale of its international brands was first announced, Cadbury
executives made much of the fact that the sale would free them to
concentrate on a fresh strategy: expanding their global
confectionery business as well as building up their bottling
network and running their soft-drink business in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new terms, Cadbury will continue selling its brands in
19 countries in Western Europe, including Belgium, Germany, Italy,
Spain and Switzerland, but not in Britain, its largest market. The
company will also retain Norway and Sweden, for what a spokeswoman
called ``geographic completeness.'' The company will also continue
to sell its brands in France, which would have been true under the
original plan as well.
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury will also give up its business in Ireland and Greece,
said the spokeswoman, Dora McCabe. The company's chief executive,
John Sunderland, insisted in a statement that its strategy remained
intact. ``We will still receive a significant cash sum whilst
retaining our strong European soft drinks business,'' he said.
``What we are doing removes uncertainty for our employees, for our
bottlers and our shareowners, and ensures a swifter conclusion to
the transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, because it is keeping most of its European beverage
operations, Cadbury will be forced to hold onto about half of its
bottling plants, worth about $800 million. The company had eagerly
anticipated selling them in a separate transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Coca-Cola fell $1.1875 Monday, to $66.8125, while the
American depository receipts of Cadbury fell 62.5 cents, to
$55.375.
</P>
<P>
   Talks regarding a revised deal began in earnest just more than a
week ago, Mrs. McCabe said. There were indications earlier,
however, that both companies might have been rethinking their
plans.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to reporters at a beverage conference on May 13,
Cadbury's global managing director of beverages, John T. Brock,
said the European Union's opposition was the result of
anti-American sentiment stemming from other trade issues, including
beef and bananas. ``The relationship between the U.S. and the E.U.
right now is not at an all-time high,'' he said, adding that ``it
is a political issue at least as much as a regulatory issue.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same meeting, Brock said he was ``convinced that there is
a deal to be done that will be value-creating for both Coke and
Cadbury.'' He added, ``If at some point we and Coke concluded it
made sense not to do this deal, there are other deals we could
do.'' He called the agreement one that ``made sense at the time but
it is not a deal that is critical to our future.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing chorus of criticism was hard to ignore, analysts
said, and both Coca-Cola and Cadbury wanted to avoid having their
agreement delayed further. Coca-Cola may have been worried about
the specter of another bureaucratic stalemate like the one the
company is still trying to resolve in France regarding its purchase
of the Orangina brand from Pernod Ricard SA. That purchase has been
pending since it was announced in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have given up many small countries in which their share
was small anyway,'' said Michael Bellas, chief executive of
Beverage Marketing, a research and consulting firm for the beverage
industry. ``The big countries are still in place. This
restructuring won't affect them, and it will probably appease the
European group.''
</P>
<P>
   The question remains as to whether Cadbury will seek a new buyer
for its brands in Europe. Some industry experts think Coca-Cola
will end up owning them eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never say never,'' said John D. Sicher, publisher of Beverage
Digest, an industry newsletter.
</P>
</TEXT>
