<SLUG> BC-NEWCARE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Long-term care firm planning to restructure
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ NewCare Health Corp., an Atlanta-based long-term care
company, announced a restructuring Monday that includes contracting
with a Massachusetts-based firm to manage its operations.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring is to reduce operating losses, NewCare said in
a press release. The company also said it recently sold five
facilities to reduce debt. NewCare operates 38 nursing homes,
assisted-living centers and independent-living facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Lenox Healthcare, a privately held Pittsfield, Mass.-based
company, will take over operations of NewCare starting June 1.
Lenox will appoint two members to NewCare's board and will acquire
an undisclosed number of shares of common stock and warrants.
</P>
<P>
   NewCare executives could not be reached for comment on the
changes. Shares of NewCare rose 12 1/2 cents to close at 87 1/2
cents in Nasdaq trading Monday.
</P>
<P>
   NewCare lost $5.5 million on revenue of $19.4 million in the
first quarter of 1999, ending March 31. For the 1998 year, it lost
$7.8 million on revenue of $66.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   NewCare linked the need for restructuring to recent reductions
in Medicare reimbursements. Last year Medicare switched to a system
that pays fixed daily fees for patients according to illness,
instead of reimbursing nursing homes for their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Citing that payment change, Atlanta-based Mariner Post-Acute
Network, which also operates nursing homes, last week reported a
second-quarter loss of about $79 million and announced it was
laying off 7,300 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
