<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANNIE-LOANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    $12 billion to aid Atlanta area housing
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fannie Mae will invest $12 billion over the next five
years to help 160,000 low- and moderate-income families in Clayton,
Cobb, DeKalb, Fulton and Gwinnett counties buy their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money will be used for down payment assistance to
get families into their own houses.
</P>
<P>
   The successes of previous initiatives and Atlanta's vibrant
housing market prompted the new efforts, Fannie Mae's chairman and
chief executive officer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see this at Summerdale Commons, Techwood/Centennial
Place, City Plaza and the Park at Briarcliff,'' Franklin D. Raines
told a crowd of about 200 gathered in Mechanicsville, a
neighborhood two blocks southeast of Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street on Ralph David Abernathy Boulevard are 16 two-
and three-bedroom townhomes, part of the 48-unit development Ware
Estates.
</P>
<P>
   Nearing completion now and priced between $95,000 and $120,000,
they sold out within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase of the project has 50 buyers on its waiting
list.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae invests directly in multifamily housing projects and
uses bond programs to enable eligible families to buy homes with
below-market interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Ware Estates is being developed by the Urban Residential
Development Corp. and Summech, a nonprofit community development
corporation in the Mechanicsville, Summerhill and Peoplestown
neighborhoods that span some 40 blocks south of I-75/85 and east of
I-20.
</P>
<P>
   Although the area is enjoying renewal activity now was recently
full of dilapidated houses and, as Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell
said, ``ravaged by the success of the (Atlanta) Braves and Braves
fans' parking and trash.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was among dozens of city, state and federal officials
attending Raines' presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Raines said the $12 billion, with Ware Estates as its catalyst,
would revitalize neighborhoods located in other parts of the
five-county area, not just downtown.
</P>
<P>
   It will fund a market study to determine specific housing needs
for the target counties.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the new HouseAtlanta initiative will include new
underwriting plans and the continued rejuvenation of Auburn Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae's cooperating partners include the Atlanta
Development Authority, SunTrust, Capital City Bank, Wachovia,
Citizens Trust Bank, Enterprise Social Investment Corp. and
foundation, Atlanta Neighborhood Development Partnership and United
Way.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSEATLANTA (cq) INITIATIVE
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae: The congressionally-chartered public company is the
nation's largest source of funds for home mortgages. If you meet
Fannie Mae's guidelines, it will guarantee your loan
</P>
<P>
   Mortgage limits: Through its regular and special programs,
Fannie Mae will guarantee mortgages up to $240,000.
</P>
<P>
   Income limits: Fannie Mae's programs do not necessarily have
income requirements. Borrowers wishing to buy under some of those
programs have to show good employment and credit histories and
perhaps meet other criteria.
</P>
<P>
   How to apply: Call 1-800-732-6643 Monday-Friday, 9 a.m.-5p.m.,
for a list of participating mortgage lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harte writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
