<SLUG> BC-Y2K-RX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Health care industry lags on Y2K bug, experts say
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The health care industry trails other sectors in
preparing for Y2K problems and is scrambling to catch up, experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret about the vulnerability of the whole health
care industry, and hospitals in particular,'' Lew Yeouze of
consulting firm William M. Mercer said Monday. ``In a hospital, so
many things are used to keep people alive,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But many hospitals had not addressed this as a big issue until
recently, Yeouze said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Pearson of GHA, an association of Georgia hospitals,
declined to comment on a recent Senate report on how health care is
running behind other industries on Y2K readiness. But he said
hospitals in the state are aggressively tackling the issue.
</P>
<P>
   GHA has been holding information sessions with its members and
has developed a list of contingency plans for hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not predicting problems,'' Pearson said, adding, ``This
is an unprecedented event.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Georgia Insurance Commissioner John Oxendine, to head
off a potential Y2K problem, ordered health insurers to allow
consumers to buy a three-month supply of life-saving prescription
drugs in advance of Jan. 1. That would ensure adequate supplies
through March 31. Insurers typically pay only for a 30-day supply,
according to Oxendine's office.
</P>
<P>
   The order would pertain to life-sustaining medication such as
insulin and heart medicine. The order does not apply to Georgians
covered by employer plans that are self-insured.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem arose because computer programmers, as a
shortcut, used a two-digit code to represent the year. Unless
software is adjusted, a 00 date could mean 1900, not 2000. If not
corrected, those computers could shut down or produce incorrect
information, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Among health care organizations, hospitals have the biggest
challenge in addressing the computer bug.
</P>
<P>
   Besides their financial transactions, and their physical plants,
hospitals depend on a maze of computer systems. And computer chips
help run a variety of high-tech equipment used in medical services,
ranging from infusion pumps and respirators to CT scans and
defibrillators. Electricity and water supplies are vital as well.
</P>
<P>
   Patient care is where many hospitals have started their Y2K
work, Pearson said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited a survey by the American Hospital Association to
indicate hospitals are well on their way to completing their
readiness.
</P>
<P>
   In that February survey, 85 percent of respondents said they
expect their information systems will be ready or won't be a
problem by year end, 90 percent expect their medical devices will
be ready, and 72 expect their physical plant will be compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Georgia, the state's largest
health insurer, is spending more than $15 million over 2 1/2 years
on Y2K preparedness. ``We will be ready by year end,'' said Charlie
Harman, a Blue Cross vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's Medicaid program recently failed to meet state and
federal deadlines for Y2K testing. But the Department of Medical
Assistance has improved its status with federal officials, said
Mike Hale, project manager for the Year 2000 Project for the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved from a high-risk to a medium-risk category,'' he
said. Medicaid should be doing systems testing in July, Hale said.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
