<HEADLINE>
ASIA, SLOWING RECOVERING STILL OFFERS BARGAINS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the economies of most Asian nations appearing to be slowly
on the mend, the region's airlines and hotels are no longer
practically giving away their services, as they were less than a
year ago. Nevertheless, there are still lots of travel bargains to
Asia, and travelers whose plans can accommodate midweek departures,
Saturday stays and other restrictions can save money, or at least
enjoy an array of extras.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the bargains are also beneficial to countries in the
region. ``Tourism is actually helping to stimulate economic
recovery and growth in destinations including South Korea, Thailand
and Bali,'' said Joseph A. McInerney, the chief executive of the
Pacific Asia Travel Association in Bangkok. ``In Thailand, for
example, tourist arrivals from the U.S. reached 361,705 in 1998 _ a
16.3 percent increase over 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest bargains, as usual, are those offered by the
airlines, which typically arrange package deals with tour operators
and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines, for example, is offering a Bangkok package
that includes air fare and five nights in a hotel for $669 for West
Coast departures, and $717 from New York, Boston, Chicago, Detroit,
Memphis and Minneapolis/St. Paul.
</P>
<P>
   After June 30, prices rise to $809 and $845, for travel through
Aug. 31. Other Northwest packages are available for travel to Hong
Kong, Singapore, Beijing, Shanghai and Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines' tour branch, United Vacations, is offering a
$999 package for travel through Dec. 31 that includes air fare
between the West Coast and Hong Kong, five nights at one of two
Mandarin Oriental hotels there and 5,000 bonus miles in United's
frequent flier program. From New York the price starts at $1,059.
</P>
<P>
   Cathay Pacific's $999 All Asia Pass is back, allowing passengers
to fly from New York, San Francisco or Los Angeles to Hong Kong,
then to as many as 15 other cities. The pass, available only
through travel agents, is valid for 21 days, but passengers who
register at www.cathay-usa.com receive an additional 10 days.
Travel is valid between Aug. 22 and Nov. 16; for travel now through
Aug. 21, add $200.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia Airlines has a package starting at $700 a person
including air fare from Newark or Los Angeles to Kuala Lumpur or
any of six other destinations in Malaysia. Designed for two or more
passengers traveling together on the same reservation, the package
includes three nights in a hotel and daily breakfast. It must be
booked by June 30 and travel completed by July 10.
</P>
<P>
   Thai Airways' specials include a $999 round-trip package from
Los Angeles to Bangkok, Chiang Mai and Phuket with eight nights'
hotel and sightseeing. From New York, the price is $350 higher. The
package, valid for travel through Sept. 30, costs $299 extra for
travel June 1 through Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Air New Zealand has two specials through Aug. 31: $899 between
Los Angeles and Auckland, New Zealand, with five nights'
accommodations, and $999 between Los Angeles and Sydney, with five
nights' accommodations, breakfast and airport transfers.
Reservations: Newmans South Pacific Vacations, (800) 421-3326.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers on Singapore Airlines can stay in Singapore for as
little as $60 a night for two in a first-class hotel (such as the
Excelsior) or for $142 for two in a Marriott or similar hotel. The
package includes discounts for shopping, dining, sightseeing and
rental cars, as well as admission to six attractions including the
Singapore zoo and Jurong Bird Park.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to counter the past year's low occupancy rates, which
plummeted below 50 percent in many major cities, many Asian hotels
still offer bargain rates or a slew of enhancements.
</P>
<P>
   From Tuesday through Aug. 31, the Mandarin Oriental Hotel Group
_ with properties in eight Asian cities, including the Oriental in
Singapore and Bangkok, and the Mandarin Oriental in Hong Kong and
Jakarta _ is offering double occupancy at the single rate, with
free use of hotel health equipment and breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Through Oct. 31, 90 Holiday Inn and Crowne Plaza hotels in 15
Asian countries are offering a free night to guests who stay one to
three nights at a participating hotel and pay with a Visa card.
</P>
<P>
   Peninsula Group hotels, which include the Peninsula Bangkok,
Peninsula Manila, Peninsula Hong Kong and The Palace Hotel in
Bangkok, offer an array of discounts, upgrades and other amenities.
Through August, the rate at the Kowloon Hotel in Hong Kong is $168
a night, rather than the usual $310. Also included are a daily
American buffet breakfast and 500 miles with either United Airlines
or Japan Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Marriott Hotels are lowering rates, at least through September,
and are making more of amenities packages. In addition to ground
transportation to and from the airport, a daily newpaper and free
use of the health club, the Marriott Royal Garden Riverside Hotel
in Bangkok is offering a 50 percent discount on tennis lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton Hotels in Singapore, Tokyo, Bangkok, Taipei and Beijing
have also trimmed prices modestly and added upgrades,
transportation, breakfasts and other perks. Most of the hotels will
offer the promotions at least through September.
</P>
</TEXT>
