<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYA RALLIES, BUT CHANG CAN'T AVOID THE EXIT
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ On the opening day at the French Open, the clay was a
slippery place to conduct business.
</P>
<P>
   A surfeit of past and present men's champions, a couple of them
doomed to dueling each other in the first round, scrambled through
a difficult first round Monday at Roland Garros, where the balls
soaked up so much humidity that players felt as if they were
hurling bowling balls across the net.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Moya, the men's defending champion, found himself mired
in a two-sets-to-none trough before he eventually woke up and
rallied.
</P>
<P>
   The most daunting assignment was that given to Michael Chang,
ranked 50th and a creaky version of the relentlessly resilient
17-year-old who outlasted leg cramps, Ivan Lendl and Stefan Edberg
here in 1989. A decade later, Chang was not up to the task of
getting past Yevgeny Kafelnikov, currently No. 1 in the world, and
for the first time in his career failed to reach the second round
in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov, the 1996 French Open champion and the reigning
Australian Open champion, put an embarrassing string of six
opening-round losses out of his mind and kept focused for the
nearly three hours he needed to dismiss Chang, 6-2, 5-7, 6-0, 7-6
(10-8).
</P>
<P>
   Chang did not leave without a fight, but after saving three
match points, he was floored by a forehand volley.
</P>
<P>
   Chang admitted he has been mulling over missionary work as his
most appropriate post-tennis profession but said he is not ready to
turn in his sneakers and turn tail on a career that has brought him
more than $17 million but never a No. 1 ranking like Kafelnikov's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest thing has been to pick myself back up after
losses like this, but my time's not up yet,'' the 27-year-old Chang
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Muster, the 1995 champion, who has slipped to No. 47,
also failed to survive the opening round, losing to Nicolas
Lapentti of Ecuador, 2-6, 6-1, 6-2, 7-6 (7-4).
</P>
<P>
   During his near three-hour brush with early elimination, Moya
had visions of failing to defend his title, a fate also suffered by
Boris Becker at the 1997 Australian Open and Roscoe Tanner in
Melbourne in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   But after taking only four games from 92d-ranked Markus Hipfl in
the first two sets, the fourth-seeded Moya rediscovered his poise
and his topspin and persevered for a 3-6, 1-6, 6-4, 6-2, 6-4
comeback. Moya improved his five-set record at Grand Slams to 8-1,
but it was only his second reversal of a two-sets-to-none deficit.
His other recovery came at Chang's expense at the 1998 United
States Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I was playing, I didn't see any way to escape from
this match,'' Moya said. ``But I just kept fighting. I run at all
the balls. What can you do when you're losing so badly? You just
have to do your best and pray, and that's what I did and it worked
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Moya next faces Petr Korda, last year's Australian Open
champion. Korda has been accused of steroid use by the
International Tennis Federation and, pending the outcome of an
appeal at the Court of Arbitration for Sport, this could be the
31-year-old Czech's final French Open.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi, a scant month after receiving his divorce decree
from the actress Brooke Shields, stormed into the second round with
a 3-6, 7-5, 7-5, 6-3 comeback against Franco Squillari of
Argentina. Always a fan of the grand gesture, the 13th-seeded
Agassi finished off the match with three consecutive aces.
</P>
<P>
   On the women's side, the defending champion, Arantxa Sanchez
Vicario, breezed by Croatia's Mirjana Lucic, 6-2, 6-2, and both
Williams sisters reached the second round with similar ease. The
fifth-seeded Venus trounced Alexandra Fusai, 6-1, 6-1, and the
10th-seeded Serena overpowered Laurence Courtois, 6-4, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Top-seeded Martina Hingis, who is eager to correct the fact that
she has won every Grand Slam event except the French Open, downed
Amanda Hopkins, 6-1, 6-4, to set up a second-round match with
Amelie Mauresmo of France.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a dangerous player; I'll take her serious,'' Hingis said
of the 18th-ranked Mauresmo, the player she defeated in the final
of the 1999 Australia Open.
</P>
<P>
   After Mauresmo announced in Melbourne that she is gay, Hingis
blithely referred to her as ``half a man.'' The French teen-ager
got her revenge a month later at the Paris Indoors, a defeat Hingis
played down as ``not a huge loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauresmo said the sting of the comments about her personal life
made by Hingis had not worn off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since people are still talking about it, it still exists,''
Mauresmo said. ``My motivation will be at a maximum. Now I know
that I can beat her. I have no pressure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
