</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Japan: Military Pact Approved
</P>
<P>
   The upper house of Parliament approved contentious legislation
strengthening military cooperation with Washington. The law will
make it easier for Japan to back American military forces in any
confrontation with North Korea or other military crises in the
region. China, which has been nervous about steps to improve
Japan-U.S. military ties, announced it was ``deeply concerned''
about the legislation.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Information Bill Introduced
</P>
<P>
   The government introduced a delayed and diluted freedom of
information bill that for the first time would give the public the
right to records held by the police, government departments and
local courts and agencies. A campaign promise of the two-year-old
Labor government, the measure exempted broad areas like commercial
interests and public safety.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Premier Shrugs Off Threat
</P>
<P>
   Four days after a government adviser was killed by terrorists
claiming to be members of the Red Brigades, the emblem of the
extreme left-wing group, a five-pointed star, was found painted on
the wall of Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema's rented apartment in
southern Italy. D'Alema shrugged off its significance. ``I think
these are unpleasant aspects of the times we live in,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Corsica: 4 Confess To Role In Slaying
</P>
<P>
   Four Corsican nationalists have confessed that they played a
role in the 1998 killing of Claude Erignac, the top French official
on the island, the police said. They said a fifth man, the
suspected gunman, is still on the run. The announcement comes as
Corsica is still in turmoil over the arrest earlier this month of
Erignac's successor on charges of ordering illegal acts.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Colombia: Rightists Kidnap Senator
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's main right-wing paramilitary group has claimed
responsibility for the kidnapping of an opposition senator in
Medellin. Sen. Piedad Cordoba, head of the chamber's human rights
commission, has been active in efforts to bring about peace talks
with left-wing rebel groups. But in a statement, the leader of the
death squads said she had put herself ``at the service of guerrilla
diplomacy'' and demanded that his group take part in the talks,
scheduled to begin soon.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Jailed General Moved
</P>
<P>
   A dissident army general serving a 28-year jail sentence has
been transferred involuntarily from a military to a civilian
prison. Gen. Jose Francisco Gallardo was convicted by a court
martial last year of destruction and theft of army property, but
Amnesty International and other human rights groups say he has been
persecuted for criticizing the military. The officer's supporters
suspect he was transferred to end any contacts with military
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Drive Against Child Labor
</P>
<P>
   The International Labor Organization is expected to adopt a
convention aimed at banning the worst forms of child labor. The
pact would require countries signing on to take immediate action
against slavery, forced labor, sexual exploitation, child
trafficking and hazardous work involving children under 18. The
agency estimates that in developing countries some 250 million
children between 5 and 14 work, about half of them full-time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
