u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERRILL-INTERNET-NYT     05-24 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH TO USE INTERNET FOR ADVISING CLIENTS AND BOND
TRADING
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Merrill Lynch, criticized for a go-slow approach to
online trading for consumers, is trying to stay ahead of the
Internet curve when it comes to its core corporate and
institutional clients.
</P>
<P>
   The securities firm has created a new group, called Direct
Markets, that will distribute Merrill's research and investment
advice over the World Wide Web. Clients will be able to trade some
bonds on the Internet, and Merrill says online underwriting is not
far off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the attention in the Internet world is directed toward
the retail side,'' Thomas W. Davis, an executive vice president who
heads the firm's capital markets group, said in an interview. ``But
as we look at the landscape, we see technology creating
considerable change on the institutional side as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill's online push is intended to ward off competition from
upstarts that promise lower costs and more direct ways for large
fund managers, like mutual and pension funds and corporations with
big investment pools, to trade stocks, bonds and options through
the Internet. Merrill also has taken stakes in companies like
Optimark, a stock trading service for institutional investors, and
Tradeweb, a similar service for bond traders, Merrill officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are approached once a day by some organization that's the
latest and greatest facilitator of market activity,'' said G. Kelly
Martin, who heads Merrill's debt operations. ``We think we have a
lot to offer these people. As these markets mature, we anticipate
playing a bigger role in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as stock trading by individual investors has exploded, the
biggest stock and bond traders, who tend to be sensitive to how
well their trade orders are executed and the benefits they get from
close ties to an investment bank, have been slower to embrace new
trading companies. But Merrill seems eager to prevent the
defections it had from its consumer client base when rivals like
Charles Schwab and ETrade began offering a full array of brokerage
services at much lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to meet and exceed competitive offerings,'' Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill has begun offering electronic trading and research
services for some products. They include online tools for managing
clients' commercial paper, United States government and agency
bonds, and repurchase agreements. Information and trading of stock,
bond and commodity derivatives is already available. Select clients
will also have electronic access to Merrill's offerings of new debt
issues, the firm said in an internal memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   The offerings seem more evolutionary than revolutionary. Some
big Merrill clients say they have long received research on line.
Trading through the Internet can be useful for small buy and sell
orders, some said, but most clients want brokers to walk them
through placement of larger orders, particularly in volatile
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some of the smaller orders, on line is great _ less
nuisance, lower cost,'' said Barbara Kenworthy, a bond fund manager
for Prudential Securities. But, she said, bond markets other than
for United States Treasury bonds are too unstable to execute large
trades automatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are trying to trade sizable blocks, you need to really
get the flavor of the market,'' she said. ``For that, you need that
relationship with your banker.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
