<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENEALOGY-WEBSITE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    400 million ancestors hit Web as Mormons go online
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The hunt for your ancestors may have just gotten
easier.
</P>
<P>
   The Mormon Church on Monday introduced FamilySearch, a World
Wide Web site that contains nearly 400 million names. Internet
users can search the site for records of their relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Online resources such as this one have helped popularize
genealogy by making information more readily available. There are
many online databases that can help researchers trace their family
trees, but the Mormon site has far more names, says April Helm,
co-author of ``Genealogy Online for Dummies'' (IDG, $24.99).
</P>
<P>
   FamilySearch contains information drawn from a century of record
gathering by the church, which possesses the largest genealogical
database in the world. Previously, researchers could search those
records only at local family history centers _ there are 14 in
metro Atlanta _ or at the Family History Library in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The FamilySearch site attracted more than 200 million hits
during a two-month test, and it bogged down in heavy traffic as
word spread Monday. Some visitors weren't able to visit the site,
which had drawn 30 million hits as of 11 a.m. The site will be
expanded to accommodate 100 million hits per day, said Elder Monte
J. Brough of Lilburn, a former executive director of the church's
Family History Department. Brough conceived the project five years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Access to the site is free for everyone, Mormon or not. ``I
don't care where you come from or what your background is, I think
we've got something you can use and enjoy,'' Brough said.
</P>
<P>
   The church spent an undisclosed amount of money to put its
records online. In the next two years it plans to add more names,
bringing the total to 1 billion people in 110 countries, Brough
said.
</P>
<P>
   The site also offers access to the Family History Library in
Salt Lake City and records of some 32 million people with pedigrees
_ information on several generations of relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The church _ formally known as the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints _ encourages members to trace their family roots
so they can baptize ancestors by proxy. Mormons believe that the
dead can choose their faith in the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   The church unveiled the Internet site at press conferences in
Atlanta, Washington and Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   FamilySearch: www.familysearch.org
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
