</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-ART-words(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A RIVER RUNS THROUGH IT
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   So here's my question for the day: Why is it (beyond issues of
personal character) that Mikhail Gorbachev, Bill Clinton, Benjamin
Netanyahu and Tony Blair engender so much passion, hatred and
adulation from their supporters and detractors?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, I would suggest, has to do with the fact that during
the 1990s the world shifted from one international system to
another. We have moved from a Cold War system, built around
division and walls, to a globalization system built around
integration and Webs. For every major country, moving between these
two systems involves crossing a Rubicon, and one of the reasons
that Gorby, Bibi, Tony and Bill have gotten under people's skins so
much has to do with the controversial strategies they each used to
cross this daunting river.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, they all share reputations for being dishonest
(Blair the least of all, but then he's just getting started!),
earned in part because the political coalitions they used to come
to power at the tail end of the Cold War system had to be
jettisoned in favor of different coalitions required for governing
in the new system.
</P>
<P>
   The man who faced the widest Rubicon was Gorbachev. The gulf
between the Communist Cold War system and the free-market
globalization system was the mother of all Rubicons. ``The only
reason Gorbachev was able to manage that transition as long as he
did, as peacefully as he did, was because he didn't realize how
wide the Rubicon really was,'' remarked Michael Mandelbaum, a Johns
Hopkins University foreign policy specialist. ``Gorbachev thought
he could cross the river in one leap, and when he discovered that
wasn't possible, he thought he could walk on water.''
</P>
<P>
   Once it became apparent how much change would actually be
required, Gorbachev found himself without friends _ his old
Communist allies despised him for doing too much, and his natural
allies, such as Boris Yeltsin, dismissed him for doing too little.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu came to power riding a coalition of people who were
wary of the Oslo peace process, but he soon discovered that he
could not govern without advancing Oslo. Too many Israelis didn't
want to live in a world of walls, but wanted to be integrated in
the broad trends of both the region and the globe, which the Oslo
process represented. Bibi's strategy was to swim laps in the
Rubicon. He crossed the river in some important ways by signing the
Hebron and Wye agreements, but then crossed back, when he
confronted the wrath of his original right-wing constituency. He
never stayed on one bank long enough to be trusted by either his
right-wing core or the centrist coalition supporting Oslo _ and he
never really tried to build a bridge between the two.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton's strategy was to cross the Rubicon by filling in
most of the river. That is, he absorbed the best of Republican
ideas _ welfare reform, deficit reduction, free trade, missile
defense _ and then left the Republicans with being anti-abortion
and pro-guns. (He left the GOP as the party that is ready to defend
the life of every unborn child, but willing to risk the life of
every born adult.) So the Rubicon between Democrats and Republicans
is now mostly filled in, but the remaining divide is very deep.
Clinton roams around with ease, while the Republicans sit over on
their bank stewing at him and trying to figure out how to widen the
river again.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Blair's Rubicon between the Cold War and globalization is
whether to bring Britain into the European Monetary Union, which he
clearly seems inclined to do, even though this is a hugely divisive
issue. For now, Blair is dog paddling in his Rubicon, postponing
the decision on joining Europe until the next election, after which
he will probably hold a national referendum _ in hopes that this
will be his bridge from one side of the river to the other. One
reason for Blair's tough stance on Kosovo may be to highlight
British leadership and his own nationalist credentials at a time
when he may be preparing to obscure both by merging Britain into
Europe. The more Blair prepares to abandon the British pound, the
more he speaks like Winston Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Gorby, Blair knows his Rubicon cannot be crossed in one
leap, and unlike Bibi, he actually has a strategy for bridging the
two sides. But this river between Britain and Europe is a roiling
one, and Blair best not make Gorby's mistake of thinking that he
can walk on water.(BOX)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
