</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM'S GRAFT TRIALS DAZZLE THE PUBLIC, BUT GRAFT REMAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam _ Just before a huge corruption trial
began here this month with 77 defendants, including powerful
bankers and business executives, local reporters were taken aside
and handed envelopes of cash worth more than a month's pay.
</P>
<P>
   According to one reporter, who wrote about the incident in his
newspaper, Tuoi Tre, a top official of a bank that employs 16
defendants gave each reporter the equivalent of $150 and suggested
they limit their articles to narrow accounts of court testimony.
</P>
<P>
   In two years the government has been engaged in a major
anticorruption drive, highlighted by a series of ever-larger trials
that have resulted in 12 death sentences. The cases are the talk of
the country. Overflow crowds are gathering to hear testimony over
loudspeakers outside the current trial.
</P>
<P>
   But the cash envelopes raised few eyebrows. Far from being
capital crimes, such gestures are simply part of day-to-day life.
As in a number of neighboring countries, the tortuous and
multilayered bureaucracy of Vietnam and its low-paid public workers
and police officers provide fertile ground for a culture of
payoffs. ``It's the weak point of our system,'' a schoolteacher who
is following the trials said. ``It's an illness of Southeast Asia,
to try to get rich on the back of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   A doctor who insisted on anonymity said: ``I'm not sure how much
effect trials like this will have because corruption is all around
is. It's a way of life. Everyone knows that if you need some
documentation or need to get something out of customs, it will cost
a little something. Parents pay to get their children into good
schools. Some hospitals expect something on the side to treat
patients. On rural roads, you see trucks lined up waiting to pay
off the police, so they can go on their way.''
</P>
<P>
   As the economy has opened over 10 years, opportunities for big
payoffs have multiplied, part of the unbridled capitalism that has
surged through other newly open economies like Russia's.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign executives report having been told they would have to
pay six-figure or even seven-figure bribes to secure major
contracts. It is common for foreign companies to hire local
``consultants,'' whose chief asset is personal connections to
important officials.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Communist Party leader, Le Ka Phieu, expressed
his concern, saying, ``Wasteful behavior, embezzlement and
corruption are not merely economic, but ethical issues that become
political.''
</P>
<P>
   High-profile corruption trials have picked up their pace this
year. In one, 74 defendants were convicted, and two were sentenced
to death, for being in a national smuggling ring.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, 35 people, including 29 local officials, were
sentenced to up to 20 years in prison for a logging swindle.
</P>
<P>
   The trial that started on May 10 involves a shell game in which
two companies, Minh Phung and Epco, are said to have colluded with
bankers to obtain huge loans using phantom collateral. Prosecutors
say the scheme cost the government up to $280 million, more than
budget revenue for Ho Chi Minh City last year. The scope of the
trial is enormous, involving 54 defense lawyers, nearly 300
witnesses and an indictment that took four days to read.
</P>
<P>
   Along with company executives, the defendants include 18 former
officers of state banks, as well as six public officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9566 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SENATE-HNS &LR;      05-24 0027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY STUMPS IN NEW YORK, RAISES CASH FOR SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9567 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SENATE-HNS &LR;      05-24 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY STUMPS IN NEW YORK, RAISES CASH FOR SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton launched preparations for a
possible Senate campaign in New York on Monday, raising more than
$1 million for the Democratic candidate who will seek to succeed
retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady laid out the broad themes of her own would-be
Senate campaign and praised Rep. Nita Lowey, the Democrat who has
vowed to seek the Senate seat if Clinton does not.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, while not directly addressing her own political plans,
talked about education, child care and leadership. Leadership, she
said, ``comes through persuasion'' and efforts ``to bring people
together rather than things that push us apart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of all the progress we have made, we cannot be
complacent,'' Clinton told some 500 guests who paid $1,000 each to
benefit Lowey's campaign in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton recounted her experience visiting Kosovo refugees in
Macedonia last week and her visit with President Clinton to
Littleton, Colo., the site of a school shooting that left 15 people
dead. ``We have work to do at home as well,'' the first lady
declared. ``Too many children have seen too much violence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to more to help every child,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton raised the money during a whirlwind evening that
included an appearance at a book party for Matilda Cuomo, wife of
former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, and receipt of an award from
Americans for the Arts, an advocacy organization.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aides said the first lady's ninth visit to the Empire
State since Jan. 1 is the latest step in her effort to reach a
decision by mid-June on establishing an exploratory committee for a
Senate campaign _ the first by a sitting first lady in American
history.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the fund-raiser for Lowey, Clinton mingled at a private
home in Manhattan with more than 50 guests who had paid $10,000
each to raise more than $500,000 for the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee to be used by the party's candidate for Senate
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud to march forward shoulder to shoulder with my
friend, Hillary Rodham Clinton,'' Lowey said. ``We are united and
we are confidant that on Nov. 7, 2000, New York will elect its
first woman to the United States Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know yet who will lead our march,'' she said, ``but I
do know the road. I am proud to walk it with Hillary and with each
of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowey has promised to leave her six-term seat in Congress
representing well-to-do Westchester County, north of New York City,
and run for the Senate if Clinton foregoes the race.
</P>
<P>
   Lowey could use the money raised at the fund-raiser either for
re-election to the House or for the Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you one thing, the next senator from New York will
be a woman,'' Lowey said in a broadcast interview Sunday. ``If
Hillary Clinton runs, she will win. If I run, I will win.''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan, a Democrat, is retiring next year at the end of his
fourth term in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance at the Lowey fund-raiser appeared designed
in part to soothe private grumbling by some local Democrats who
have quietly raised concerns about the impact that Clinton's
flirtation with a Senate race is having on the fortunes of
Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Lowey defended Clinton's gradual exploration of a Senate bid in
an interview on ABC News' ``This Week.'' Lowey said she believed
New Yorkers would be more concerned about the substance of a
Democratic Senate candidacy than the person's origins.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was born in Illinois, educated at Wellesley College in
suburban Boston and Yale Law School in New Haven, Conn., and became
active in politics during her husband's 12 years as governor of
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think New Yorkers care what you stand for, rather than where
you're from,'' Lowey said, defending the first lady's possible
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's arrival in New York coincided with fresh evidence that
she will have a tough fight on her hands for a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate exploratory committee of New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani welcomed the first lady with a message on the campaign's
Web site, www.HillaryNo.com, saying: ``Hillary can't stay away from
New York City.'' The statement added: ``The U.S. Senate is a place
for proven leaders, not a proving ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., said in a broadcast interview on Sunday
that he was ``inching closer and closer'' to challenging Giuliani
for the Republican nomination for the Senate. Lazio, who has
represented a Long Island congressional district for eight years,
criticized both Clinton and Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have somebody in New York representing New York
interests who is looking for this as a platform for power and not
watching out for New York. ... We need to have a New Yorker
represent New York,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said Giuliani was ``a reluctant Republican'' who had
endorsed Mario Cuomo over Republican challenger George Pataki in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's comments raised the possibility of a bitter GOP primary
fight for the Senate nomination, a contest that could strengthen
Clinton's chances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
