u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-PROFILING-DISMISS-     05-24 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-PROFILING-DISMISS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS SEEK TO DROP CHARGES BROUGHT BY TWO N.J. TROOPERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rm) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ Acting in what they called ``the interests of
justice,'' prosecutors have moved to drop drug and weapons charges
filed against 21 drivers by two New Jersey state troopers who have
been accused of lying about the race of other drivers they had
stopped and searched.
</P>
<P>
   In a motion filed last Friday in New Brunswick, the Middlesex
County prosecutor's office said the 21 cases should be dismissed
because they were undermined by an April 19 indictment that charged
that the troopers, John Hogan and James Kenna, falsified records to
cover up the fact that they were targeting black and Hispanic
drivers for stops. Of the 21 drivers whose cases could be
dismissed, at least 19 are either black or Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Robert A. Longhi of New Jersey Superior Court has
scheduled a hearing on the motion Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If, as expected, he throws out the cases, it would represent one
of the most dramatic results of the state attorney general's
ongoing investigation into charges that some state troopers have
for years singled out black and Hispanic motorists for stops,
particularly on the New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers say that the state's willingness to drop these
cases, in which all the drivers were stopped or arrested by Hogan
and Kenna, could lead to challenges to overturn dozens of past
convictions of minority motorists who were arrested by the two or
by other troopers who may have practiced profiling. At the time
Hogan and Kenna were indicted, state investigators said that as
many as 10 other troopers could face criminal charges of falsifying
records.
</P>
<P>
   William Buckman, a Moorestown lawyer who has helped lead the
legal fight against profiling, said he believed the attorney
general's office has an ethical and legal obligation to share with
defense lawyers any new evidence of discriminatory stops that led
to conviction of black or Hispanic motorists. Buckman also said he
expected those convicted in the past will file appeals on grounds
the state withheld evidence of profiling or their lawyers did not
raise the issue during trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Buckman cautioned that overturning convictions is difficult
in New Jersey. ``Some judge are more hostile to re-opening
convictions than others,'' Buckman said. ``That's the wildcard
that's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan and Kenna made the 21 arrests in the months before April
1998 when they opened fire on four young black and Hispanic men
riding in a van they had stopped on the turnpike. Three of the
van's passengers were wounded. A state grand jury is considering
filing criminal charges against the troopers for the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a different grand jury accused the two troopers of
falsifying official documents and reporting that black and Hispanic
drivers they had stopped were white. Both were suspended from the
state police without pay immediately after the indictment. They
face arraignment on those charges Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the motion filed last Friday, Lawrence R. West, first
assistant Middlesex County prosecutor, said the two troopers were
``necessary and essential witnesses'' against the 21 individuals.
West said the charges they had lied on official records prompted
his office to seek dismissal of the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Davis, a spokesman for the attorney general's office, said
officials there agreed with the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the primary witnesses in each case, and they would
have lacked any kind of credibility,'' Davis said of Hogan and
Kenna.
</P>
<P>
   The move to dismiss the cases comes nearly six months after the
attorney general's office convinced state judges to suspend
prosecution of these 21 individuals and 9 others who had been
either stopped or arrested by Hogan or Kenna.
</P>
<P>
   The state asked that the cases be suspended after a Trenton
lawyer, Robin Kay Lord, started a court fight in Mercer County to
obtain Hogan's personnel file and any evidence that he had engaged
in profiling. Ms. Lord wanted the material to help defend two black
men whom the two troopers arrested on drug charges in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The state argued that surrendering the documents would
jeopardize the ongoing grand jury investigation of the van
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Two judges granted the state's motion, and suspended prosecution
of Ms. Lord's two clients in Mercer County and 28 others in
Middlesex County from Dec. 11 to April 11. The state allowed the
suspension period to lapse about a week before the trooper
indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, judges in Mercer County dismissed drug
charges against Ms. Lord's two clients.
</P>
<P>
   Seven defendants in the 28 Middlesex cases are not involved in
the current dismissal motion. West said that some pleaded guilty
during the suspension period and that troopers other that Hogan and
Kenna will testify against the others.
</P>
<P>
   The 21 people whose cases not may be dropped in New Brunswick
include a television producer, Michael G. Moye, whom Hogan charged
with illegal weapons possession after stopping his van on the
turnpike in early 1998. Moye said the weapons, two handguns and a
shotgun, were legally purchased and registered and part of a
collection he was transferring from his home in California to his
home in Greenwich, Conn. He said he told Hogan about the guns but
was arrested because two were loaded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
