<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-SUSPECT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE IN TEXAS SEEK SUSPECT IN SERIES OF SLAYINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Calif., Fla., N.M.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PATTY REINERT  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEIMAR, Texas _ A suspect in the slaying of a Houston-area
doctor was named Monday as a suspect in the killings of a Weimar
minister and his wife after authorities linked evidence at both
crime scenes, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, a 38-year-old Mexican national who has
a 20-year criminal record in Texas, California, Florida, New Mexico
and other states, is now wanted for questioning in the murders of
the Rev.
</P>
<P>
   Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic, 46, and his wife, Karen, 47. The couple
was found beaten to death with a sledgehammer in the parsonage
behind the Weimar United Church of Christ when they failed to show
up for services May 2.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez also has been charged with burglary and is a
suspect in last December's sexual assault and murder of Dr. Claudia
Benton, 39, a Baylor College of Medicine physician who was found
dead Dec. 17 in her home in West University Place, a Houston
suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Her body was found on the floor in an upstairs bedroom. A bloody
kitchen knife from the home was near the body. The autopsy report
showed that she had suffered three stab wounds and at least 19
blows to the head with a heavy statue, and had been sexually
assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez became a suspect in the West University case
when his fingerprint was lifted from pieces of a broken steering
column from Benton's Jeep Cherokee, which had been stolen and later
recovered in San Antonio. Last week, workers at the Texas
Department of Public Safety Crime Lab analyzed samples from the
West University crime scene and linked them to those from the
Sirnics' home in Weimar, a town of 2,050 about 90 miles west of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Weimar authorities plan to issue warrants for Resendez-Ramirez's
arrest today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it's imperative that we locate this individual as soon
as possible,'' said Weimar Police Chief Bill Livingston.
``Hopefully someone will have some idea where he may be.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston and West University Police Chief Gary M. Brye said
similarities between the two cases prompted them to compare
physical evidence, but they declined to say what specific evidence
made them suspect Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the victims were attacked in their homes at night,
with the killer entering through a garage or carport. All the
victims were beaten to death in their bedrooms and the murder
weapon was left at the scene. And both homes were located near
railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The West University police description of Resendez-Ramirez
notes: ``Suspect may be living as a transient working odd jobs and
riding the rails.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this seems a little far-fetched and you wonder, `How
did you guys get together?''' Livingston said. ``But we were
following every clue through to the hilt. Any similarity, any tie,
we were checking out.''
</P>
<P>
   DPS officials worked all weekend to compare the physical
evidence in the two cases and found it consistent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez is described as 5-foot-6, 150 pounds, with
brown eyes and black hair. Brye said he has used numerous aliases
throughout his criminal career, which has included arrests for
property crimes, auto theft and criminal trespass.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also are still searching for the Sirnics' 1998 red
Mazda pickup, with Texas plates 2DK-J47, which was stolen from
their driveway the weekend they were found dead in their bed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
