<HEADER>
A9574 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEREGULATION-COX     05-24 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEREGULATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taft claims Ohio 'at disadvantage' when bidding for large jobs
 &HT;    By Michael Wagner and William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ A lot of states would have loved to snatch away
the new $300 million diesel engine factory and its 700 jobs from
the Dayton, Ohio area last year.
</P>
<P>
   Moraine was always considered the front-runner to land the
project from the General Motors Corp. and Isuzu Motors Ltd., but it
wasn't a done deal until the auto giants finished adding up their
big-ticket costs.
</P>
<P>
   Labor, material, and equipment were the biggest costs, but so
too was the plant's expected electric bill.
</P>
<P>
   Moraine won the bid, but Gov. Bob Taft and other backers of a
bill that would deregulate Ohio's $11 billion electric industry say
Ohio is now at a disadvantage when competing for large industrial
projects. That's because several other states already have
deregulation and potentially cheaper power costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Electric and all utility costs are a huge factor when
companies like GM or Delphi Automotive are considering building or
relocating plants,'' said David Cole, director of the University of
Michigan's Office for the Study of Automotive Transportation. ``The
cheaper the electric bill the better chance a community like Dayton
has to keep or expand its automotive job base.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft will be in Dayton today to speak to the Dayton Area Chamber
of Commerce about the importance of deregulation and its potential
impact on regions such as the Miami Valley that rely heavily on
large energy users.
</P>
<P>
   Large users could see a significant energy savings under the
bill as written, and the governor expects deregulation to be a big
factor in retaining jobs.
</P>
<P>
   His visit comes in the middle of what Senate President Richard
Finan, R-Cincinnati, called the ``fifth inning'' of efforts to
enact legislation deregulating the state's electric industry. The
Senate approved the legislation last week and the House is now
considering the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (deregulation) is the largest single economic development
issue for the governor,'' said Scott Borgemenke, Taft's chief
policy adviser. ``It's kind of a new marketplace across the country
and nobody knows how the deregulated marketplace is going to shake
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Delphi and GM, which operate nine plants with about 18,000
workers in the Miami Valley, spend about $50 million annually on
utility costs with a sizeable portion going for electric power.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide they pay $130 million annually for electricity. Under
deregulation, they would shave $10 million to $15 million of that
annual cost, according to Delphi officials.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason GM, Delphi and the state's other large
industrial customers appear to be faring well in the political
fight for deregulation in the Ohio General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The deregulation bill would allow Ohioans to pick their electric
suppliers as of Jan. 1, 2001. For residential customers, it
provides a reduction of about 2 percent off their electric bills,
as well as the hope competition will further lower their monthly
bills.
</P>
<P>
   The savings would be much greater for large industrial users. In
an open marketplace, the big customers could buy power from the
cheapest supplier, technically anywhere in the nation. The current
bill provides big business with advantages that include:
</P>
<P>
   A flat tax that's applied to their total electric bill, while
other customers would still have to pay the more expensive per
kilowatt tax. The flat tax is expected to save large industrial
operations millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The chance to choose their electric supplier from the first day
of deregulation while residents wait until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The option of renewing special-rate contracts for up to 10 years
at the same electric cost or shopping the market for an even
cheaper electric supplier.
</P>
<P>
   The state's privately owned utility companies oppose the
deregulation bill, and say its benefits for big business will be
paid for by residential and small business customers, and by
utility shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfortunate that the legislative process for this bill
has consistently catered to the demands of large industrial energy
users. Utility costs are a factor, but not the biggest factor in
locating a business in Ohio,'' said Robert Snyder, executive vice
president of the Ohio Electric Utility Institute which represents
the state's major, private utilities, including Dayton Power &AMP;
Light Co.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the utilities say the bill limits their ability to
recover ``stranded costs'' _ state-approved investments they made
decades ago in nuclear power plants and other expensive projects.
The recovery would be in the form of a customer tax.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would give the Public Utilities Commission of
Ohio authority to determine how much money each utility can get
back. Statewide, stranded cost estimates have been as high as $14
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups who are also opposed to the current legislation
say industry and utilities' gain will be converted into a loss for
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point there is nothing good for consumers,'' said
Jennifer O'Donnell, spokeswoman for Ohio Citizen Action. ``They
threw in this nickel-and-dime rate cut which would evaporate
quickly in exchange for handing over billions and billions to
utilities and give them a deregulated monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell said the bill contains language that lets consumers
form buying groups to negotiate for lower costs. However, the
language requires local governments that want to form a buying
group to recruit members ``one by one.'' This approach has already
failed in California and Pennsylvania, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A better approach would be to let a local government declare
itself a ``buying group'' and all residents are members. Individual
residents could withdraw if they did not want to participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to fight tooth and nail,'' O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial legislation is now going through the Ohio
House Public Utilities committee and could reach the House floor by
the second week of June. House Speaker Jo Ann Davidson,
R-Reynoldsburg, doesn't expect the lobbying from industry, the
utilities and consumer groups to go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure will come from all sides,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Wagner and William Hershey write for the Dayton Daily
News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
