A9576 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DDN-WILKINS-COX     05-24 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DDN-WILKINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court sends Ohio fraud lawsuit back to Columbus for trial
 &HT;    By Steve Bennish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A U.S. appeals court in Cincinnati Friday
reinstated a lawsuit accusing state officials of defrauding the
government by not reporting the abuse of federal anti-poverty
funds.
</P>
<P>
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals returned fired state
employee Terry Wilkins' lawsuit to the U.S. District in Columbus,
which had dismissed it in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins, a former top administrator for the Ohio Department of
Development, said state officials overlooked poverty agency
misspending _ including local alleged misdeeds at the now defunct
Montgomery County Community Action Agency _ to keep federal money
flowing to Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 Dayton Daily News series found agencies around Ohio
misspent hundreds of thousands of dollars in taxpayer funds on
luxury autos for executives, complex real estate deals that put
properties in private hands and programs that did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   With the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals' decision, the case
returns to federal judge Joseph P. Kinneary in Columbus. Wilkins,
who headed the Office of Community Services, said his First
Amendment rights were violated when he was fired in 1993 after
pursuing persistent problems at the agencies. Kinneary now has the
option of scheduling the case for a jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruling said that a Wilkins' lawsuit filed in
1993 was dismissed on purely technical grounds without a ruling on
its actual merits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been six years,'' Wilkins' attorney Sandy Spater said
Monday. ``We'd like it to go to trial so we can have our day in
court. It's extremely important. The merits of the case have never
been considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Beougher, a spokeswoman for the Attorney General's
office, said the office had just received the appeals court opinion
and is considering options.
</P>
<P>
   One estimate placed MCCAA's unpaid debts at $3 million when it
folded in October 1997, including $1.1 million claimed by the U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-05-24-99 1856E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
