A9580 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-HARASS-HNS &LR;      05-24 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-HARASS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES RULE SCHOOLS CAN BE HELD LIABLE IN STUDENT HARASSMENT
CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE LASH  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A divided Supreme Court ruled Monday that school
boards can be held liable under federal law for ignoring severe
sexual harassment of one student by another.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-4 decision, the high court said Title IX of the 1972
Education Amendments requires school administrators to take action
when they discover ``severe, pervasive and objectively offensive''
harassment that interferes with a student's ability to learn. The
dissenting justices, however, assailed the court for potentially
turning adolescent sexual teasing into a federal case and
subjecting schools to costly and protracted litigation.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the case was whether Title IX, which requires
schools receiving federal funds to provide equal education
facilities for boys and girls, demands that administrators take
steps to prevent students from sexually harassing fellow pupils at
school.
</P>
<P>
   The court revived a lawsuit brought by Aurelia Davis, the mother
of a fifth-grade girl who claims the Monroe County, Ga., Board of
Education violated Title IX by refusing to stop a fifth-grade boy
from groping and makInn lewd comments to her daughter, LaShonda.
The mother said that she and her daughter told teachers of the
alleged harassment but that the instructors did nothing and in one
instance required LaShonda to sit next to the boy.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, agreeing with a trial
court, ruled that Title IX does not apply to sexual harassment
between students, even when teachers know of the malicious
behavior. The justices, overruling the 11th Circuit, sent Aurelia
Davis' lawsuit back for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Groups representing school boards and teachers hailed the high
court's ruling, saying it will safeguard students from harassment
while protecting administrators from liability, so long as they
don't ignore harassment in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``School boards across the country have developed or are in the
process of developing tough and clear sexual harassment policies
that demonstrate that such action will not be tolerated,'' said
Anne Bryant, executive director of the National School Boards
Association. ``Today's court ruling shows that if school officials
implement these guidelines, children should not be vulnerable to
harassment, and schools, with limited public funding, should not be
vulnerable to huge monetary damages.''
</P>
<P>
   The NSBA's reaction to the decision is in contrast to its
arguments to the court before the case was heard in January. In a
legal brief urging the justices to interpret Title IX narrowly, the
association said the statute does not apply to sexual harassment
between students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liability for damages under Title IX hinges on the existence
of gender discrimination by the grant recipient (school) _ not on
whether schools are successful in responding to allegations of
student misconduct,'' NSBA wrote in a legal brief to the justices.
</P>
<P>
   National Education Association President Bob Chase, whose group
represents 2.4 million teachers, called the court's decision a
``lesson ... that school districts should work to prevent sexual
harassment from occurring in the first place through education and
training programs for students and staff.''
</P>
<P>
   The case, Davis vs. Monroe County Board of Education, is similar
to one the justices decided last year in which they held that a
school near Austin, Texas, could not be held liable under Title IX
for a teacher's sexual harassment of a student. The court, in
Gebser vs. Lago Vista Independent School District, said schools can
be held liable for harassment only if they knew of the misbehavior
and showed ``deliberate indifference'' by failing to take action.
</P>
<P>
   Citing that decision, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote in the
court's majority opinion Monday that schools can similarly be held
liable for ignoring the pleas of a student being so sexually
harassed that it interferes with her or his ability to receive an
education. To avoid liability, a school must take action to remedy
the harassment, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the historical duty and freedom of schools to discipline
students, the court said administrators have leeway to decide how
to stop the harassment. The school's response, rather than having
to meet the common legal standard of being reasonable, must be just
``not clearly unreasonable,'' O'Connor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The court also went to great length to distinguish illegal
sexual harassment that prevents learning from mere sexual banter
that is a staple of teen-age discourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is understandable that, in the school setting, students
often engage in insults, banter, teasing, shoving, pushing and
gender-specific conduct that is upsetting to the students subjected
to it,'' O'Connor wrote. ``Damages are not available for simple
acts of teasing and name-calling among schoolchildren, however,
even where these comments target differences in gender. Rather, in
the context of student-on-student harassment, damages are available
only where the behavior is so severe, pervasive and objectively
offensive that it denies its victims the equal access to education
that Title IX is designed to prevent.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining O'Connor's opinion were Justices John Paul Stevens,
David H.
</P>
<P>
   Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Anthony M. Kennedy registered his displeasure with
the court by taking the extraordinary step of reading parts of his
biting dissent from the bench. Kennedy, joined by three other
justices, assailed the court for what he called its improperly
broad interpretation of Title IX that will have federal judges _
rather than parents and teachers _ setting school disciplinary
policies regarding harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Litigation will increase as schools, parents and judges will
struggle to clarify the confusion the court has created by failing
to define clearly what constitutes illegal harassment under the
federal law, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the court seems ``oblivious'' to the widespread
teasing that goes on at school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girl who wants to skip recess because she is teased by the
boys is no different from the overweight child who skips gym class
because the other children tease her about her size in the locker
room; or the child who risks flunking out because he refuses to
wear glasses to avoid the taunts of `four eyes'; or the child who
refuses to go to school because the school bully calls him a
`scaredy-cat' at recess,'' Kennedy wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most children respond to teasing in ways that detract from
their ability to learn. The majority's test for actionable
harassment will, as a result, sweep in almost all of the more
innocuous conduct (that is) a part of school life.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Kennedy's dissent were Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
