<HEADER>
A9583 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-REDS-NEAGLE     05-24 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-NEAGLE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neagle goes on DL; weakness in rotator cuff the diagnosis
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ On that memorable day last Wednesday in Denver when
the Cincinnati Reds played ring-around-the-bases with 24 runs, 28
hits and six home runs, there was one frown in the postgame
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Denny Neagle was the only one who thought the food was
lousy and the beer was flat. Given a 6-0 lead in the first inning,
Neagle couldn't cruise. By the second inning, it was 6-6 and Neagle
was in the clubhouse showering nearly two hours before the game
ended, soaping up with a 0-3 record and a swollen 8.17 earned-run
average over six starts.
</P>
<P>
   Something is amiss and has been since Neagle reported to spring
training with a weak shoulder after the mid-winter trade with
Atlanta for All-Star second baseman Bret Boone.
</P>
<P>
   So, as expected, the Cincinnati Reds placed Neagle on the
disabled list Monday and are expected to fill his roster spot
before tonight's game against the Los Angeles Dodgers and pitcher
Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Jim Bowden was not assuaged by Los Angeles Dr.
Ralph Gambardella's diagnosis of weakness in Neagle's rotator cuff
after an examination Friday. Copies of an MRI have been sent to Dr.
Stanley Ho at Stanford University and Dr. James Meranus in
Cincinnati for evaluations and Neagle will be examined Wednesday by
noted sports physician James C. Andrews in Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``The medical information we have been provided is not
consistent with our baseball evaluation,'' Bowden said. ``There is
no point continuing on a path that has not allowed the strength in
Denny's shoulder to improve. If surgery is not recommended, we must
find a better way to strengthen his rotator cuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds, fresh off a 6-1 trip to Denver and San Diego, are home
for three games against the Dodgers before bolting town again for
stops at Florida, New York and interleague games at Kansas City and
Minnesota _ a testy stretch of 18 road games and three home games.
</P>
<P>
   Infielder Carlos Baerga, leading the International League at
Triple-A Indianapolis with 52 hits entering the weekend, was the
top choice to join the club today, but a meeting Monday between
Bowden and manager Jack McKeon may have changed it.
</P>
<P>
   It could be infielder Aaron Boone or outfielder Mark Sweeney,
players who began the season with the Reds but were optioned to
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds want Boone to play every day, but Mark Lewis is manning
third base well and hitting .280. An extra outfielder isn't needed,
nor is a left-handed pinch-hitter, even though Sweeney had six
pinch-hits, including two pinch-hit home runs before he left.
</P>
<P>
   Baerga can play third base and second base and, as manager Jack
McKeon said, ``I'm not tub-thumping for Baerga, but he is a veteran
who knows how to play, is a switch-hitter and is a good guy in the
clubhouse.'' Baerga signed his first professional contract with the
San Diego Padres when McKeon was general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Baerga also would give McKeon a chance to rest shortstop Barry
Larkin, who has started all 40 games and missed only two innings.
Second baseman Pokey Reese, who signed as a shortstop, can move
back to short and Baerga can play second on days Larkin rests.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jeff Branson can play second, short and third and he
is hitting .280 at Indianapolis, but is another left-handed hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Also needed to be addressed is a fifth pitcher to go with Steve
Parris _ tonight's starter against Brown _ Brett Tomko, Pete
Harnisch and Steve Avery.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon indicated that Jason Bere was out of the rotation after
another shaky start last Tuesday in Colorado _ one-plus inning, two
runs, three hits, three walks.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds, though, came back to win that game, 5-3. Amazingly,
although his earned-run average is 6.61 and he has given up 40
hits, 27 runs and 28 walks in his 31.1 innings, Bere is 2-0 and the
Reds are 6-2 in his eight starts, 5-0 over his last five.
</P>
<P>
   Bere was skipped once in the rotation last week and pitched a
simulated game Saturday in San Diego as pitching coach Don Gullett
tinkered with his mechanics. Indications are that Bere will start
Saturday in Florida when a fifth pitcher is needed, although
bullpenners Gabe White and Ron Villone have been mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
