<HEADER>
A9584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-HASEK-NYT     05-24 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-HASEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH HASEK, THE QUESTION IS STARTING, NOT STOPPING
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Darcy Regier understood the unspoken implication of
the question. Regier, the general manager of the Buffalo Sabres,
was being asked about the injury to Dominik Hasek, his star goalie,
who missed Game 1 of the Eastern Conference finals with a groin
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek missed practice Monday because he was back in Buffalo,
visiting doctors for extensive testing. And Hasek could miss Game 2
against the Toronto Maple Leafs on Tuesday night in Air Canada
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a happy surprise if he were in there,'' Regier
said.
</P>
<P>
   But some players play with pain and some do not, a reporter
said, adding, ``Do you have to swallow a little bit here and just
say, `This is what Dom wants and so this is the way we have to
approach it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Regier replied quickly and bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Regier said. ``If the question is, `Do we think he
should play with this injury?' Absolutely not. Not where he is
right now. He wanted to play very badly. When you see his eyes
welling up, you don't question what some people want to question. I
don't question it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Hasek's absence on Sunday, the Sabres beat the Maple
Leafs by 5-4 as the backup Dwayne Roloson made 28 saves in the
opening game of the four-of-seven-game series. The winner will meet
Dallas or Colorado in the championship round.
</P>
<P>
   Sabres Coach Lindy Ruff said Hasek went to Buffalo for magnetic
resonance imaging and for a bone scan, after a doctor from Lansing,
Mich., was flown in to treat Hasek on Saturday night. Other
physicians were treating him in Buffalo Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek missed 12 games late in the regular season with this
injury and began to suffer from it again during the second round
against Boston. Two years ago, when a knee injury kept Hasek out of
some playoff games, some people doubted the severity of the
problem, and there were hard feelings toward him from both inside
and outside the team.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said that ``the injury has been there all along'' and
``it's just the pain factor right now.'' He said Hasek is taking
pain medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think one or two days is going to make a lot of
difference,'' Ruff said. ``It's painful, and we have to get that
pain eased. That is Dom's mentality. He's got to get it to a level
where he feels comfortable that he can perform his acrobatics. They
are going through every precaution with him. It's the pelvic area
and the bone there where the muscles are attached.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres also played Game 1 without Miroslav Satan, their
leading scorer in the regular season, who is out with a foot
bruise. Satan skated well Monday and could return sometime this
series.
</P>
<P>
   After practice Monday, the Leafs held a long team meeting and
said afterward that they would concentrate on their checking and
try not to allow the Sabres as many chances as they did in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Joseph, Toronto's star goalie, gave up five goals on
Buffalo's first 19 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph said he was not pleased with all the Buffalo traffic in
front of his goal crease, creating distractions and blocking his
views of shots.
</P>
<P>
   But Buffalo's Ruff vowed, ``When we come out of the gates
tomorrow, we're coming with a full-court press again.'' Although
the Sabres were credited with a 52-35 edge in hitting, Ruff said
they could do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can hit more,'' Ruff said. ``We swung off a few
times. We've got to finish. It's something we've really stressed.
We've got some good hitters on the team. We'd like to take it one
level higher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
