<HEADER>
A9586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-INDY-SAFETY-COX     05-24 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-SAFETY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRL outlines safety procedures for Indy 500
 &HT;    By Dave Lance
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ In light of the spectator deaths at Lowes Motor
Speedway on May 1, Indy Racing League officials outlined details of
a safety system Monday that will be required on every car competing
in the Indianapolis 500 Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   IRL executive director Leo Mehl hopes the new Suspension &AMP; Wheel
Energy Management System will reduce the chances of wheel
assemblies becoming detached during accidents. SWEMS takes
approximately two hours to install and Mehl said the 33 Indy cars
will be outfitted with the system by Carburetion Day on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The cars' chassis and suspension will be attached with multiple
restraints made of Zylon, which has a breaking strength of 5 tons.
</P>
<P>
   SWEMS is similar to tethers, which Formula One began using this
season. But Mehl said the two are slightly different, although they
both are designed to keep loosened suspension parts and wheels
connected during crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think tethers is the right term,'' he said from
Indianapolis Motor Speedway. ``This is a system that has several
Zylon cables, not just one rope as when you hear the word tether.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can imagine we've been working hard on this since (the
deaths). We've had a series of meetings with Dallara, G Force and
Riley &AMP; Scott (Indy car constructors).''
</P>
<P>
   Three spectators were killed at Lowes in Charlotte, N.C., when a
tire and other debris from a three-car pileup flew over a 15-foot
fence and into a grandstand. It was the second time in nine months
fans were killed as the result of an open-wheel car crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every (racing series) must react to this situation,''
Mehl said. ``I don't think any of us are sure what's going to
happen when you hit a wall at (over 200 mph), but we feel this is a
step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But how will it affect drivers during crashes? The major
complaint with tethered wheels and parts is that they might bounce
back and hit the drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis Motor Speedway was closed Monday and drivers were
unavailable for comments. But team managers voiced their opinion on
SWEMS
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to make every effort to make open-wheel racing as
safe as it can be,'' said Thomas Knapp, Greg Ray's team manager.
``The initial impression is it probably has got a good design, but
unfortunately we can't design an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart's manager and car owner Larry Curry also thinks
SWEMS is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything they can do in the way of safety, I'm hugely
supportive of,'' Curry said. ``It's a problem we need to address
and not put off until tomorrow. I think it's absolutely necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a quality driver out there not concerned with the
possibility of a fan getting hurt. Anything that helps the fans,
Tony Stewart is going to be a big supporter of.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehl does not believe SWEMS will have a negative effect on
drivers during crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel this is a good thing for the driver,'' he said. ``The
more we can keep attached to the car is better for the driver. The
less wheels and suspension around the track to run into is better
for the fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing everything possible to make sure the race is as
safe for the fans as it can be.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Lance writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
