<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9590 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLORIDA-FLOODING-COX     05-24 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-FLOODING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plans for Everglades, Florida waterways endangered
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When dirty water pounded the St. Lucie
River last year and the Lake Okeechobee dike sprang leaks, water
managers said part of their difficulty stemmed from a flood-prone
community about 100 miles to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Their solution: Buy and remove the community, unclogging a
drainage bottleneck that has plagued the lake, the river and the
Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   But now those plans are in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Agencies that offered to put up part of the money haven't.
Opponents are attacking in court. Some congressmen are openly
hostile.
</P>
<P>
   The board of the South Florida Water Management District may
have to decide as early as next month whether to proceed with
buying the community known as the 8 1/2-Square-Mile Area, just east
of Everglades National Park. They also could seek a compromise that
would leave most of the area's 400 homes intact while restoring
natural flows into the park's northeast corner.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the district's board is investigating
accusations that its staff illegally discussed the buyout in secret
or bullied residents into selling.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the momentum is on their side.
</P>
<P>
   ``The walls are starting to come tumbling down,'' said Joette
Lorion, a consultant for the Miccosukee Indian tribe, which accuses
the buyout's supporters of an irrational obsession with eradicating
the community. ``They're going to risk the entire Everglades
restoration for this.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters say this isn't the time to flinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation needs some leadership,'' said Charles Lee,
senior vice president of the Florida Audubon Society. He said the
district should buy the homes even if it has to go it alone.
</P>
<P>
   The district's board voted in November to begin the buyout, long
advocated by the park's staff and almost all environmental groups _
as long as the U.S. Interior Department and Miami-Dade County pay
part of the $55 million to $124 million costs. They estimated they
would be finished in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, district Land Director Bill Malone says more than a
quarter of the community's roughly 1,200 landowners have expressed
an interest in selling. But only the board can decide, perhaps as
early as June, whether to close on any of the sales.
</P>
<P>
   Little else seems to have worked out as planned:
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Department says it can't provide any money until it
finishes an environmental study that won't be done until early
2000. Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt didn't mention that snag
Nov. 12, when he offered to pay half the costs and said some of the
money could be available this year.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Miami-Dade County has put off its decision
indefinitely. Meanwhile, nearly a third of the county commissioners
have recused themselves because they own land in the community or
have other conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   A federal-state advisory group last week removed the area from a
list of land purchases that the Interior Department should pursue.
Buyout supporters say the action was only temporary.
</P>
<P>
   Hostile congressmen heaped scorn on the buyout last month at a
hearing packed with homeowners and tribe representatives. ABC News
later cited the controversy as evidence that ``no one is really in
charge'' of the Everglades restoration.
</P>
<P>
   The buyout also is facing scrutiny from a new set of water
managers, whom Gov. Jeb Bush appointed in March with marching
orders to respect property rights.
</P>
<P>
   The new board has hired Boca Raton lawyer Robert Rivas, an
expert on the state's Government-in-the-Sunshine law, to
investigate whether the staff broke the law. District employees
have denied that accusation, contained in a lawsuit from the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's top Everglades adviser, Allison DeFoor, said he's
awaiting the results of that investigation, too.
</P>
<P>
   Water managers also have ordered their inspector general to
investigate accusations that employees intimidated residents or
falsely told them that the district has the power to condemn their
land. Malone denies it.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than buy the community, the tribe advocates building
pumps and levees to protect it from flooding, as Congress
authorized in 1989. But park scientists say leaving the community
intact would inevitably lead to more dense development and an
outcry for more aggressive flood control, draining the park dry.
</P>
<P>
   The 8 1/2-Square-Mile Area story began decades ago, when
landowners began erecting homes _ many apparently without permits _
in a largely agricultural enclave just west of the dike that
separates the Everglades from the populated coast.
</P>
<P>
   Water managers say they can't restore natural flows into the
park without worsening flooding in the neighborhood. They said the
blocked flow contributed to a disastrous water glut in early 1998,
when the corps said it had no choice but to empty a full Lake
Okeechobee into the St. Lucie River. Even so, the dike surrounding
the lake sprang leaks.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe blames the delay on government's indecision.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has taken on a Cold War tone, with some Cuban exiles
in the community comparing the water managers to Fidel Castro.
Miccosukee attorney Dexter Lehtinen even accused the
environmentalists of being ``socialists.'' ``They are a dangerous
group,'' he said. ``They are upset that people can own private
property in America.'' Lee countered that letting the residents
stay would mean squandering public money on pumps, levees and other
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have is a very small number of people who are in an
untenable situation, and they're asking the rest of society to
subsidize their existence,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. King writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
