</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARGENTINE `DOMINO EFFECT' ON BRAZILIAN STOCKS 
(PREVIOUSLY SKEDED AS: BRAZIL-DEBT)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla.)   (jw) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ When news of pressure on the Argentine peso
started to scroll down the computer screens on trading floors here
last week, traders mainly chuckled, stoking the historic rivalry
between Brazil and its neighbor to the south.
</P>
<P>
   They're not chuckling anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The Bovespa stock index for the Sao Paulo stock exchange plunged
nearly 4.89 percent Monday, its largest one-day percentage drop
since the country's currency devaluation crisis in mid-January, as
concern over Argentina's economic policies pushed the index to its
lowest level in nearly a month.
</P>
<P>
   The decline was deeper than similar drops in stock markets in
other Latin American countries, Argentina included. Worries over
the return of a small tax on foreign investment in Brazilian
securities and of higher interest rates in the Unites States
contributed to the decline.
</P>
<P>
   The pullback in the market, mainly because of factors abroad
beyond the control of Brazilian policy-makers, is denting a newly
found optimism among investors, though it is not a surprise. In a
conundrum that has often applied to Brazil in recent years, the
country has often been among the first to pay for bad news coming
from other emerging markets, or the United States, the largest
source of Brazil's foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon is due mainly to the size of Brazil, Latin
America's largest country, and the relative sophistication of its
financial system. Because there are so many Brazilian stocks and
bonds in comparison with other developing countries, and because
these securities are the most liquid, they are often the first to
be sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The domino effect is back,'' said Marcelo Cestari, the chief
equities trader at Banco Mercantil do Brasil. ``Everything seems
negative again and there doesn't seem much we can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the decline in markets here came on a day when the
economy received a vote of confidence. Brazil abandoned a plan to
swap billions of dollars of corporate debt for less risky
securities supported by the government, because investors shunned
the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Although the scrapping of the deal is not positive for Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co., the investment bank that designed it, it is positive
as a measurement of restored faith in Brazil among foreign
investors. The main reason for the swap not going forward is a
general perception among investors that the chances are minimal for
a wave of corporate bond defaults.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a moment when panic reigned and people would have
taken anything for Brazilian bonds,'' said Jonathan Binder, the
senior investment strategist at Americas Trust Bank, a Miami-based
institution with a varied portfolio of Brazilian debt. If the
transaction engineered by Goldman, Sachs had been introduced a few
months ago, in the aftermath of the currency devaluation in
mid-January, Binder said, it may have succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Investors agreed to exchange only about $680 million of an
eligible $19.6 billion of foreign debt issued by Brazilian
companies for securities sold by an offshore company linked to the
country's development bank. That was shy of the $1 billion bankers
deemed necessary for the transaction to proceed. At the end of last
week, officials from the development bank, known by its initials
BNDES, said they were confident of swapping at least $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, the government's aim with the deal, which was to
facilitate Brazilian borrowing, is slowly materializing. A few
top-tier banks such as Banco Bradesco and Banco Itau have succeeded
in refinancing their own borrowings in international markets. These
institutions, in turn, have begun lending again to large corporate
clients.
</P>
<P>
   With overnight interest rates still high, though, at 23.5
percent, such financing doesn't come cheap. Even Brazil's largest
companies pay an estimated 27 percent domestically on a one-year
loan, compared with a rate of roughly half that amount if the
financing is secured in more liquid international borrowing
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with investors betting that most Brazilian companies will
find a way to honor their obligations, the bond swap, although
scrapped on paper, may have succeeded psychologically. ``The deal
calmed markets by showing that government support was there,'' said
Binder of Americas Trust Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Such support is not a novelty. For several companies facing debt
difficulties earlier this year, such as the railroad MRS Logistica,
the government stepped in and engineered subtle bailouts through
the use of pension funds for state-controlled companies and
state-controlled banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There somehow seems to be this intervention and problems are
resolved,'' said Anne Milne, the head of emerging markets debt
research at ING Barings in New York. She compared this strategy to
that of neighboring Argentina, where the government has done little
to help.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, there have been six Argentine debt defaults,
compared with two in Brazil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
