s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV30-NYT     05-24 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST IN HAWAIIAN WATERS  
 STOPPING CHARTRES  
 A CHOICE OF HORSE SHOWS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL FREIREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Hawaiian Waters &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Could you tell me what inter-island surface
transportation is available in the Hawaiian Islands other than
cruise ships? (Air transport misses the feel of the area.) _ J.
Douglas Miller, Katonah, N.Y.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Traveling between islands by boat is the exception in Hawaii.
The only such passenger service operating daily, according to the
Hawaii Visitors and Convention Bureau, links Maui, the second
largest of the six major populated islands, and Lanai, the
smallest.
</P>
<P>
   A journey of 45 minutes to an hour takes passengers from Maui,
which is bustling with beachfront hotels and resorts, to Lanai,
home to about 3,000 residents and the former site of sizable
pineapple fields.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle _ actually a powerboat that carries up to 80
passengers _ is run by Expeditions, Post Office Box 10, Lahaina,
Hawaii 96767, (808) 661-3756, fax (808) 661-0544. It operates
between Lahaina harbor, across from the Pioneer Inn, and Manele
harbor on Lanai. The fare is $25 one way and $50 round trip; for
children 2 to 11, it's $20 one way, $40 round trip. Add 4.166
percent state tax to all fares. Reservations required.
</P>
<P>
   Boats depart five times daily in each direction. The first and
last leave Maui at 6:45 a.m. and 5:45 p.m., respectively, and Lanai
at 8 a.m. and 6:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   An Expeditions package covers an overnight stay on Lanai at the
Manele Bay resort or the Lodge at Koele as well as the ferry and
transportation between the dock and the hotel. The total cost for
two is $339 plus 11.42 percent in state and hotel taxes. Or you can
stay at the Hotel Lanai, (808) 565-7211, for $95 to $200 a night
plus tax; that's for the hotel alone.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a tent, there's a campground, with showers and
bathrooms, about 100 yards from Hulopoe Beach, (808) 565-3982;
that'll be $5 per person per night plus a onetime $5 registration
fee.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday and Saturday, an excursion leaves Lahaina for
Kaunakakai, the main city on Molokai. It is run by Lin Wa Cruises,
113 Prison Street, Lahaina, Hawaii 96761, (800) 275-6969 or (808)
565-8218, and takes an hour and a half. Passengers set out at 6:15
a.m. and head back from Molokai at 2 p.m. The trip, aboard a yacht
that carries 149 passengers, is $69, $35 for children, plus a 4
percent tax and a 2 percent harbor fee. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stopping in Chartres &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)We are going to France in the fall and would like to
pick up a car at Charles de Gaulle Airport and drop it off at the
train station at Chartres. Is there somewhere we can leave our
luggage while we tour the city? _ Carol A. Greene, Loudon,
Tenn.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Unfortunately, there are no lockers or baggage rooms in the
Chartres train station. Because of the fear of terrorist bombs,
most lockers and baggage rooms in France have been closed for about
five years. In an emergency, the chef de quai, who is in charge of
the station, can accept suitcases for a short while in his office,
but he is not obliged to do so.
</P>
<P>
   If you rent from Avis, you can drop your car off at the station
and leave the keys in a designated box since Avis and the French
railway system have an agreement making such dropoffs possible at
most French rail stations.
</P>
<P>
   Another solution may be to leave your suitcases in a rented car
(not exposed, of course), visit the cathedral and then return the
car just before taking the train to Paris. Or you can simply make
Chartres a day trip from Paris, unencumbered by a car or concern
about luggage.
</P>
<P>
   You may have the good fortune to be in Chartres between Easter
and November. That is when Malcolm Miller, a guide who since 1958
has been helping visitors grasp the meaning of medieval
iconography, is there. To Miller, the cathedral is ``a remarkable
library of human knowledge.'' ``In a world where few could read or
write,'' he once noted, ``the pictures in the glass and the
statuary provided almost everything the medieval man or woman
wanted to know about the world here and the life hereafter.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's tours, which run an hour and a quarter, are conducted
daily except Sunday at noon and at 2:45 p.m. Participants meet near
the gift shop in the cathedral. Tours are $6.50, $3.25 for
students, at 6.2 francs to the dollar. Information: (33-2)
37.28.15.58, fax (33-2) 37.28.33.03.
</P>
<P>
   The first train for Chartres departs Montparnasse station in
Paris at 6:24 a.m., the last return leaves Chartres at 9:06 p.m.
The trip takes 45 to 90 minutes; round trip fare is $23 second
class, $34.80 first class. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Choice of Horse Shows &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I would like to take my granddaughter to a national
horse show to celebrate her 13th birthday. Can you suggest some? _
Naomi Singer, Pepper Pike, Ohio(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Here are some shows in Ohio and Michigan during the summer,
with a sprinkling of highlights. Major events usually take place on
Friday and Saturday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Motor City Horse Show, from June 16 to 20, and the Detroit
Horse Show, from June 22 to 27, are both held at the Bloomfield
Open Hunt Club, 405 East Long Lake, Bloomfield Hills, Mich. 48304;
(248) 644-9411, fax (248) 644-3958. Only general admission seats
are left for both shows, and they are $5. Highlights: children and
adult amateur owners take part in both hunter and jumper events on
Fridays. In the grand prix events, held on Saturday evenings, horse
and rider compete against the clock on a course with 10 to 12 jumps
over obstacles at least 4 feet 6 inches high and 5 to 6 feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan All Morgan Horse Show, July 7 to 10, Michigan State
Fairgrounds, Woodward and Eight Mile, in Detroit. The restored
1940s fairgrounds, just off I-75, are on the city limits. No
admission fee, parking $4. Information: (810) 793-4583 or (248)
437-5757. Morgan horses are known for their versatility as these
highlights suggest: carriage driving with a single rider; hunters
judged on walk, trot and canter; pro-am class events, in which
professional and amateur riders ride hunters, Western and English
pleasure horses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State Fair Horse Show, July 23 to Aug. 22, at the Ohio Expo
Center, on 17th Avenue near I-71, in Columbus. When the fair opens
on Aug. 6, admission will be charged: $7 for ages 13 to 59, and $6
for ages 5 to 12 and 60 and above; parking is $4. Information:
(614) 644-4035. Highlights: July 23 to 25, reining; July 30 to Aug.
1, cutting (taking a calf away from the herd); Aug. 2 to 5, 4-H;
Aug. 6 to 8, rodeo for riders in kindergarten through 12th grade,
with the younger participants riding sheep; Aug. 9 to 13, draft
horses; Aug. 15 to 20, Saddlebred, Hackney, Shetland and Morgan
horses; Aug. 21 and 22, Paint and Arabian.
</P>
</TEXT>
