<HEADLINE>
USC'S DAVIS LEAVES HIS MARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jerome Davis of USC closes out his collegiate
career in next week's NCAA track and field championships, but it
will be difficult for the defending national 400-meter champion to
top his performance in the Pacific-10 Conference finals at Arizona
State on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Davis won an unprecedented fourth Pac-10 title in a
lifetime-best 44.95 seconds _ the fastest time in the nation this
season _ and turned in a stunning 43.8 anchor to lift the Trojans'
1,600 relay of LeRoy Jordan, DeJon Joyner and Felix Sanchez to a
come-from-behind victory over UCLA in a collegiate-leading and
Pac-10 meet-record 3:02.68.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also won the 200 in 20.58 and combined with Charles Lee,
formerly of Cleveland High and Valley College; Miguel Fletcher, a
freshman from Alemany; and Sultan McCullough on USC's victorious
400 relay that timed 39.46.
</P>
<P>
   The four Pac-10 titles brought Davis' career total to 10. In
addition, Davis became only the sixth athlete in conference history
to win the same event four years in a row, an elite list that
includes Trojans long jumper Randy Williams, the 1972 Olympic
champion; USC hammer thrower Balazs Kiss (1993-96), the 1996
Olympic champion; and the late Steve Prefontaine, who won the
3-mile from 1970-73 at Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling to put a mark in history, but it is hard
to believe that I have done it,'' said Davis, who called his first
and last 400 titles the most challenging. ``I didn't try to focus
on it, I just tried to put in perspective as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   USC, buoyed by Davis, won its second Pac-10 title in three years
with 164 points to avenge a one-point loss to UCLA in the annual
cross-town dual meet May 1. UCLA was second with 136 points and
Stanford was third with 105.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA women _ boosted by junior Seilala Sua, winner of the
hammer, shot put and javelin, and sophomore Michelle Perry from
Quartz Hill, who won the 100-meter hurdles in 13.37 _ captured
their third consecutive title with 160 points.
</P>
<P>
   USC finished second with 140 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
