<SLUG> BC-BALTIMORE-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAACP CHIEF RULES OUT RUNNING FOR MAYOR OF BALTIMORE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Ending months of uncertainty over his future, Kweisi
Mfume said Monday he would forgo running for mayor of Baltimore to
remain as president and chief executive of the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   While the decision thrust Lawrence A. Bell III, the City Council
president and Mfume's second cousin, into the role of front-runner,
it disappointed an array of city and state leaders who had urged
Mfume to jump into the Democratic primary to succeed Mayor Kurt L.
Schmoke, a three-term Democrat who decided not to seek another four
years in office.
</P>
<P>
   State leaders favored Mfume for mayor so much that they changed
Maryland law to require that a Baltimore mayoral candidate live in
the city only six months before the election, rather than a year,
because Mfume only recently changed his residency to the city from
Baltimore County. In addition, a group of 200 prominent
Baltimoreans, including three former mayors, formed a draft
movement last month to rally support for him.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Mfume said, he could not turn his back on the
NAACP, the nation's oldest civil-rights organization, just three
years after he left a safe seat in Congress to lead it, signing a
five-year contract that pays more than twice the mayor's annual
salary, $95,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``A plethora of inequities cry out for advocates of social
justice to get involved and stay involved,'' he said at at the
NCAAP national headquarters here. ``I cannot walk away from that
fight at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   His deliberations effectively chilled the mayoral race for
months. Besides Bell and Carl Stokes, a former city council member,
several other Democrats are running. But none have been able to
ignite much excitement, let alone raise the money needed to sustain
a campaign through the September primary and November general
election.
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore, an overwhelmingly Democratic city, the winner of
the party primary is virtually assured of victory two months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has not been an enviable position,'' Mfume said of
ambivalent feelings that did not dissipate, he said, until Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume said he reached his decision after getting in touch with
his ``inner voice, a voice I always listened to and that always
guided me correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   In essence, he said, the voice told him to finish what he had
started, seeming to answer what he described months ago as his
fundamental consideration: ``Where could I do the most for the
greatest number of people?'' He offered no additional reasons
Monday for his decision.
</P>
<P>
   With Mfume out of the mayoral race, Bell is expected to rev up
what has been a rather quiet campaign. Yet he will do so without
the support of many Baltimore luminaries, including William Donald
Schaefer, a four-term mayor, a two-term governor of Maryland and
one of those leading the effort to encourage Mfume to run.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Mfume indicate whether he would support his cousin. He
said he routinely did not endorse candidates until the filing
deadline passes, July 6, in this case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
