<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCOTUS-HARASS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: STUDENTS AND SEXUAL HARASSMENT  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, May 25:
</P>
<P>
   A bitterly divided Supreme Court on Monday affirmed the legal
obligation of schools to protect students from severe and pervasive
sexual harassment by other students. The 5-4 decision marked an
important turning point for education and for civil rights. Most
significantly, it recognized that student-on-student sexual
harassment not only disrupts a victim's ability to learn but, in
egregious cases, may also amount to a violation of Title IX of the
Education Amendments of 1972, the law that bars sex discrimination
in schools and colleges receiving federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   The case involved a fifth-grade girl in Georgia who was
subjected to months of taunting and unwanted touching by a male
classmate who was eventually convicted in juvenile court of sexual
battery. Despite repeated complaints, school officials refused to
take action. Overturning a ruling last year by the federal appeals
court in Atlanta, the court declared that Title IX covers
student-on-student harassment. It then held that school districts
can be held liable for the student's misconduct, applying
essentially the same stringent standard the court adopted last year
for cases of student harassment by teachers. ``Recipients of
federal funding,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote for the
majority, may be liable ``where the recipient is deliberately
indifferent to known acts of student-on-student sexual
harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   The court also said that the behavior at issue must be severe
and pervasive _ a clear and appropriate effort to draw a line
between illegal harassment and everyday playground behavior. By
contrast, the dissenters _ Chief Justice William Rehnquist and
Justices Anthony Kennedy, Clarence Thomas and Antonin Scalia _
seemed to view such harassment as a normal rite of adolescence.
They further criticized the majority for meddling in school
disciplinary decisions. Ms. O'Connor's unusually sharp rejoinder
from the bench got it just right. Far from teaching ``little Johnny
a perverse lesson in federalism,'' as the dissenters alleged, the
majority was simply trying to ensure ``that little Mary may attend
class.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
