<HEADLINE>
ESPN AND BASEBALL LAWSUITS ARE A LEGAL FOOD FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits are being lobbed so rapidly between Major League
Baseball and ESPN that Bat Track technology may be required in
federal court to determine who slugs harder, Bud Selig, the
baseball commissioner, or George Bodenheimer, the ESPN president.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Selig triggers his hitch in time, he gets his bat up to 93
miles per hour,'' Joe Morgan might say. ``Bodenheimer has a quick
swing, hits to the opposite field and if he's not fooled by a
slider, he can swing like Bud.''
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be no room for compromise, as the battle rages
over the propriety of ESPN's shifting three Sunday night baseball
games in September to ESPN2 to make room for early-season National
Football League telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL contract costs ESPN $600 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN says the contract permits the shift, but baseball calls it
a breach that will let it terminate the deal after this season and
seek a new cable partner.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN sued baseball on May 4, saying baseball had unfairly put an
end to the deal. In a countersuit filed last Friday, baseball
charged, ``In entering into the NFL agreement, ESPN deliberately
breached its contract with baseball in order to pursue increased
revenue for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball produced language from the contract (but not the
contract) that it says obligates ESPN to keep the September games
on ESPN, which has 76.6 million subscribers, and boot the NFL games
to ESPN2, which has 64.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   This is a case about bruised feelings. ESPN did not inform
baseball of its plans 17 months ago to buy rights to the first half
of the NFL season, so that it could carry games that were formerly
TNT's. Baseball has been incensed ever since.
</P>
<P>
   This case may turn on contractual language that, baseball
insists, mandates that ESPN not sign any deals that conflict with
its ability to show every Sunday night game on ESPN (but not
ESPN2). More likely, this legal food fight between former friends
may become an exercise in semantics, which probably won't be as
interesting as ESPN's carrying the National Spelling Bee.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN argues that Sunday games can be pre-empted for ``events of
significant viewer interest.'' ESPN determines this through
ratings: its NFL games last season averaged an 8.1 Nielsen cable
rating; its baseball games averaged a 1.8.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's view is different. First, it notes that the contract
says ``an event of significant viewer interest,'' not ``events.''
Does that make a difference? You bet. The singular, to baseball,
connotes something really big, something really special, like the
Olympics, which ESPN doesn't have.
</P>
<P>
   (To baseball, the Sept. 12 Milwaukee-Colorado game will always
mean more than the competing Steelers-Browns matchup, essentially
because its contract came first. This may be the wrong year to
argue significance.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense is silly semantics,'' said Dick Glover, an
executive vice president of ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   To baseball, NFL games fail miserably to meet the significance
test, no matter their ratings. To baseball, substituting another
sport's ``regularly scheduled programming'' misuses the
significance threshold.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, baseball has approved switches of regularly scheduled
events on Wednesday nights. Wednesday night, baseball will go to
ESPN2 in favor of Game 3 of hockey's Dallas-Colorado Western
Conference final series; next Wednesday, Game 6 of the
Toronto-Buffalo hockey series will pre-empt baseball on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts work against their argument,'' Glover said. ``They
feel the criteria for Wednesdays and Sundays are different, but
they're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Glover said documents exist to prove that baseball officials
have been aware that ESPN wanted to acquire the NFL rights it did
not have and would, if necessary, move the Sunday night baseball
games in September to ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has rejected ESPN's remedies, and ESPN has spurned what
it contends was a demand by baseball for $350 million to accept the
Sunday night shifts (which baseball denies demanding).
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, baseball says ESPN is carrying too many
baseball clips on ``Sportscenter.'' While baseball is arguing to
get off ESPN, Glover said, sounding amazed, ``They're also
complaining about too much coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   What to do? Short of a settlement or a drawn-out trial, this
could end up with baseball selling its Sunday night rights to TNT,
which has 76 million viewers, and its Wednesday night rights to
ESPN. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
