<SLUG> BC-THERMO-REORG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERMO ELECTRON PLANS TO SELL OR SHUT SEVERAL BUSINESSES
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No longer will the Thermo Electron Corp. operate a network of
spas that offer hair removal by laser. Gone will be its
once-promising Wyoming plant that scrubs coal to make it burn more
cleanly. And the company will jettison a European business set up
to convert contaminated petroleum into usable oil products.
</P>
<P>
   In a tacit acknowledgment that a number of its far-flung
ventures have failed to produce the expected returns, Thermo
Electron said Monday it would sell or shut down several businesses,
write off $450 million of assets and reduce its publicly traded
subsidiaries to 11 from 23. It had previously said it would cut the
number to 15.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements come just two weeks after a leading
shareholder urged the company, which is based in Waltham, Mass., to
accelerate its reorganization and three days before Thermo Electron
executives are expected to face vigorous questioning at the
company's annual meeting. Thermo Electron's stock has lost 44
percent of its value in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   The new reorganization plan is likely to depress earnings for
the second quarter and much of the rest of the year, said Richard
F. Syron, a director who will become Thermo Electron's president
and chief executive on June 1. He declined to elaborate on the
reorganization's effect on earnings, but he said that the company
expected to reap about $200 million in cash from the sale of
various businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to do a lot of things,'' Syron said. ``I think
we will have a difficult second quarter and it will be a very
challenging year over all.''
</P>
<P>
   Syron said that Thermo Electron executives met last week with
representatives of Franklin Mutual Advisers, the mutual fund
management company owned by Franklin Resources that urged the
company in a letter on May 7 to move more aggressively in
overhauling the board and the company's structure and operations.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the new reorganization moves were already in the
works before the company received the letter from Franklin, which
at the start of the month owned about 2 percent of Thermo Electron.
``I believe this announcement goes in the direction they were
suggesting,'' Syron said.
</P>
<P>
   David E. Marcus, a senior vice president at Franklin, called the
reorganization plan ``a step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to address some, but not all, of our issues,'' he
added. ``We do intend to explore further steps with the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Thermo Electron also said Monday it had named Samuel W. Bodman
3d, chairman and chief executive of the Cabot Corp., a specialty
chemicals and energy company, to the Thermo board. In addition, the
company formed a new corporate governance and nominating committee,
which is responsible for reviewing director performance and
nominating future directors.
</P>
<P>
   According to the new reorganization plan, four publicly traded
subsidiaries will be reabsorbed into Thermo Electron. Shareholders
of three of those _ Thermolase, Thermotrex and Thermo Ecotek _ are
to receive Thermo Electron shares in exchange for their shares,
while shareholders of the fourth, Thermo Vision, will receive cash.
</P>
<P>
   Thermo Electron said the amounts of shares or cash would be
determined in consultation with investment bankers. The plans are
subject to shareholder approval.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it would sell businesses that have
combined annual sales of about $350 million. Syron called those
operations, which were once promoted as important parts of the
company's strategy and expansion, ``outside our core
competencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Among them are the Wyoming coal-scrubbing plant and the European
oil-processing operation. In addition, the company will sell a
power electronics and test-equipment business _ part of the
company's Thermedics subsidiary _ and its Thermolyte unit, which
was trying to develop propane-powered lighting products for
recreational use.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the $450 million of charges is $105 million related
to the closing of the hair-removal spas, the write-off of the
lasers used in the hair removal procedures and closing of two
manufacturing plants.
</P>
<P>
   Syron said that the company did not plan to reconsider a
five-year, $2.5 million consulting agreement with John N.
Hatsopoulos, the former chief financial officer and brother of
George N. Hatsopoulos, the company's founder and chairman. That
agreement has been severely criticized by the Franklin managers,
who questioned whether John Hatsopoulos would make future
contributions worth that amount.
</P>
<P>
   The company's current proxy statement describes the agreement as
an ``ongoing consulting relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   But Syron said, ``I think you do have to look at a substantial
component of that as payment for how much John Hatsopoulos has
added to the company over the entire span he has been working
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
