<SLUG> BC-GORE-CHURCHFUNDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE BACKS FEDERAL MONEY FOR CHURCH SOCIAL SERVICE PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At a campaign stop in Atlanta Monday, Vice President
Al Gore said churches and other religion-based groups should be
eligible in certain instances to receive federal money to help
fight homelessness, substance abuse, youth violence and other
social ills.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, while lacking details, was an intriguing departure
for a Democratic candidate because the party is typically
associated with support for a strict separation between church and
state. Indeed, the closest existing program _ a 1996 provision that
allows government financing of religion-based welfare-to-work
initiatives _ was championed by Republicans in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, considered the leading contender for the Democratic
nomination in 2000, took pains in his speech at a Salvation Army
center here to say that that he believed strongly in the separation
of church and state, which he said had been ``good for all
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also said that national leaders had been trapped in a
dead-end debate about the role religion should play in solving the
country's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some on the right have said for too long that a specific set
of religious values should be imposed, threatening the founders'
precious separation of church and state,'' Gore said. ``In
contrast, some on the left have said for too long that religious
values should play no role in addressing public needs. These are
false choices: hollow secularism or right-wing religion. Both
positions are rigid. They are not where solutions lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that if elected president he would propose expanding
the welfare-to-work program, known as Charitable Choice, as long as
certain safeguards defined what he said would be ``carefully
tailored partnerships.''
</P>
<P>
   Government, he said, must never promote a particular religious
view or try to force anyone to receive faith. There must always be
an alternative choice of high-quality secular programs. Direct
proselytizing would be prohibited as part of any publicly financed
effort. And Gore said that the government would demand financial
accountability of churches just as it does of other social service
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore said he had been persuaded that faith is often
``essential to spark a personal transformation and to keep that
person from falling back into addiction, delinquency or
dependency.'' And he added that if he is elected President, ``the
voices of faith-based organizations will be integral to the
policies set forth in my administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry W. Lynn, the executive director of Americans United for
Separation of Church and State, said that his group was considering
challenging the charitable choice concept in a lawsuit and warned
that Gore's proposal raised ``serious constitutional issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Taxpayer dollars should not be used to pay for programs that
promote religion or allow discrimination in hiring,'' Lynn said.
``Charitable choice does just that.''
</P>
<P>
   While in Atlanta, Gore met privately with most of the victims of
Thursday's school shooting in nearby Conyers, as well as with their
families and school officials. He was endorsed by Gov. Roy E.
Barnes at a campaign fund-raiser here Monday night that was
expected to generate $350,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
