<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY SHARES LEAD A BROAD MARKET SELLOFF
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices staged a broad, steep selloff, led by big declines
in Internet and technology issues. It was the third consecutive
decline for stocks, and some analysts said the market, which has
charged ahead for much of the year, might be in the midst of a
correction.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 174.61 points, or 1.6
percent, to 10,654.67. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell
23.64 points, or 1.8 percent, to 1,306.65. The Nasdaq composite
index dropped 66.48 points, or 2.6 percent, to 2,453.66.
</P>
<P>
   LATE TRADING COULD START IN SUMMER
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange, which had been planning to expand
its trading hours next year, is accelerating its timetable and
could start evening sessions as soon as this summer, the exchange's
chairman said.
</P>
<P>
   AVIS TO BUY CENDANT FLEET BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   Cendant agreed to sell its automobile fleet unit to Avis Rent a
Car in a deal that raises the company's stake in Avis to 34 percent
from 19 percent. Avis, the nation's No. 2 car rental company after
Hertz, will pay $1.44 billion in cash and $360 million in
convertible preferred stock and assume $3.2 billion in Cendant debt
for the fleet business. Shares of Avis fell $7.375, to $28, while
Cendant rose 68.75 cents, to $19.875.
</P>
<P>
   THERMO ELECTRON TO SELL UNITS
</P>
<P>
   In a tacit acknowledgment that several of its far-flung ventures
have failed to produce the expected returns, Thermo Electron said
it would sell or close some businesses, write off $450 million of
assets and reduce its publicly traded subsidiaries to 11 from 23.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL CATERS TO BIG CLIENTS ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, criticized for a go-slow approach to online
trading for consumers, is trying to stay ahead of the Internet
curve when it comes to its core corporate and institutional
clients. The securities firm has created a new group that will
distribute research and investment advice over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   GM SET TO SPIN OFF DELPHI UNIT
</P>
<P>
   When General Motors spins off its auto parts maker, Delphi
Automotive Systems, on Friday, it will create the nation's
36th-largest company in terms of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   3 INVESTMENT FIRMS BUY INTO DATEK
</P>
<P>
   Three prominent venture capital firms have agreed to jointly buy
a minority stake in Datek Online Holdings, which owns the country's
fourth-largest brokerage service as well as a computer-based
stock-trading system, for a total of $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   MORE MERGING ON MADISON AVENUE
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan Thaler Group, an independent advertising and
entertainment shop in New York founded in 1997 by Linda Kaplan
Thaler, has reached an agreement in principle to be acquired by
MacManus Group. Financial terms of the deal, to be announced
Tuesday, are not being disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE TELEKOM HURT IN BATTLE
</P>
<P>
   Although it is still Europe's biggest telephone company and
seems intent on spending billions of dollars on acquisitions,
Deutsche Telekom lost more than just a takeover battle when
Olivetti trumped its bid to acquire Telecom Italia. The proposed
deal all but destroyed Deutsche Telekom's alliance with France
Telecom, and Olivetti's victory greatly strengthens a formidable
rival, Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
   REFCO TO SETTLE CASE FOR $8 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   Refco, a futures brokerage firm, will pay $8 million to settle
allegations of record-keeping violations involving a California
financial adviser. Refco will pay $7 million to the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission and $1 million to the Chicago Board of
Trade.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK ORDERS 192 RAIL CARS
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Transportation Authority of New York has
ordered 192 electric rail cars from Bombardier to replace commuter
trains on the Long Island Rail Road. The initial contract is worth
$445 million, but if options for 808 additional cars are exercised,
the total price for 1,000 cars would be $1.85 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
