<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LATIN-PRESS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: UNDERMINING THE LATIN PRESS  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, May 25:
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been a champion of freedom of the
press in Latin America. So it is dismaying to see Washington
sponsoring a declaration in the Organization of American States
that would endorse limits on media freedoms. The draft declaration,
which seems to be a fumble by the administration rather than a
policy reversal, has been approved by the ambassadors of the 34
member nations. It should be withdrawn. When hemisphere foreign
ministers meet next month, they should not be asked to approve a
declaration that would give governments license for further
restrictions on Latin America's besieged journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The draft was written and introduced by the American mission to
the OAS last year and then was modified by some of the governments
most hostile to press freedom, including Mexico and Peru. Press
freedom groups were not consulted. The declaration also contains
many points that retreat from previous strong statements on press
freedoms signed by hemisphere governments.
</P>
<P>
   The draft condemns some kinds of prepublication censorship, but
accepts others. It also states that press freedoms can be limited
``under domestic law.'' But in many countries, the most serious
threat to press freedom comes from restrictive laws. Seventeen
countries, for example, make it illegal to show contempt for public
officials. These laws are used to prosecute and jail journalists
who publish information about official corruption and abuses _ even
when the information is true.
</P>
<P>
   The draft also seems to endorse laws that let governments set
standards for fairness and truth in reporting. That invites
intimidation and control. Latin American journalists increasingly
face lawsuits and jail when they do aggressive reporting. The
Clinton administration and the OAS should fight for them, not make
their job harder.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
