<HEADLINE>
NYSE PLANS TO BEGIN EXPANDED TRADING HOURS THIS SUMMER
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Stock Exchange, which had been planning
to expand its trading hours next year, is accelerating its
timetable and could commence evening sessions as soon as this
summer, the exchange's chairman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman, Richard Grasso, has said for several months that
the Big Board would probably move to extend its trading hours by
the summer of next year, allowing the exchange and its member
institutions time to safely navigate the Year 2000 date change. But
at a news conference Monday, Grasso said, in response to questions,
that ``it is very clear to me that our timetable has got to be
accelerated.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the issue will ``clearly be discussed'' at the exchange
board's meeting on June 3, with the board asked to give its formal
authorization to the proposal ``as early as July of this year.''
Typically, the board does not meet in July and August, but Grasso
said that the extraordinary array of competitive issues now facing
the exchange could well require summer meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Those competitive pressures include a proposal by the Nasdaq
market, run by the National Association of Securities Dealers, to
add evening sessions to its trading hours. That plan is expected to
be discussed by Nasdaq officials this week, for possible enactment
by midsummer.
</P>
<P>
   Also scheduled for introduction in the coming months is Indivex,
an after-hours trading service for individual investors operated by
Eclipse Trading. The fledgling service has already signed on
Discover Brokerage, a unit of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter; Dreyfus
Brokerage Services, an affiliate of Mellon Bank, and some large
Nasdaq market makers, including Herzog Heine Geduld.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Instinet, a unit of Reuters Group PLC, has said
recently that it is considering opening its institution-only
trading system to individuals who want to trade when traditional
markets are closed. Instinet is the oldest and by far the largest
of the alternative trading services now in operation.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso said Monday he and his staff still have significant
concerns about whether there would be sufficient trading volume
during evening hours to make such sessions attractive to investors.
``We have to consider whether consumers are going to be helped or
hurt'' by trading when volume is reduced, he said.
</P>
<P>
   By accelerating his pursuit of a decision on longer trading
hours, Grasso adds to an agenda that already includes another
crucial competitive decision facing the exchange: whether to
develop an alternative trading service of its own to compete with
the growing roster of private electronic communications networks,
or ECNs, which now account for nearly a third of all trades in
Nasdaq stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso said Monday that a number of ideas remain under study,
including the possible creation of a ``super ECN,'' a
computer-based trading system with ``an open architecture'' that
would allow other ECNs to participate.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected the exchange to reach a decision on an ECN
arrangement ``in the next few months.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
