<HEADLINE>
FEW ASSURANCES IN TRIP INSURANCE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Wash.)   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Builders warn that there is no standard-sized window. There is
likewise no standard trip-cancellation insurance policy. Recent
events have raised questions that expose widening differences among
the popular policies sold to protect travelers against lost
payments if they cannot take a trip, tour or cruise.
</P>
<P>
   The American Airlines pilots' 10-day sickout in February
affected 600,000 travelers by the airline's count, and caused many
people to miss connections to cruises and tours. Trans World
Airlines similarly canceled 200 flights over Christmas, including
90 on Christmas Day, when flight attendants called in sick. Were
these job actions strikes as defined in cancellation policies, and
did the insurance underwriters refund any or all of the
policyholders' lost payments?
</P>
<P>
   The conflict over Kosovo has had a multiple impact in areas far
removed from the warfare. First, it is causing cruise and tour
companies to alter itineraries in the Adriatic and on European
river cruises. Then, when the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade was
bombed, the United States Embassy in Beijing and consulates
elsewhere in China were subject to violent demonstrations,
Americans were harassed and United States businesses there damaged.
</P>
<P>
   On May 9, the State Department issued an official warning
advising against travel to China; this was rescinded on May 13. How
did the insurance companies respond to policyholders who canceled
under these circumstances?
</P>
<P>
   And what about an event for which there is no precedent? Travel
companies of all sorts have been selling high-priced packages for
the end of the millennium: cruises, hotel stays in Paris or New
York, global air trips. The sellers are linking their higher prices
to much tighter cancellation deadlines and severe penalties for
later cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   Many hotel packages provide for no refund at all in the event of
cancellation. How are insurance companies dealing with exposure to
losses over as many as 15 months?
</P>
<P>
   Although these situations represent only part of what
trip-cancellation insurance may cover _ or not _ the message is to
research insurance as soon as you are ready to pay a deposit for a
major travel expenditure. Timing is important. If there is a chance
that a family member's existing medical problem may cause a change
in plans, insurance must be bought promptly after the first
deposit; the window periods are specified on the fliers.
</P>
<P>
   Then read the small type carefully because the administrator of
the insurance policy will normally take the narrowest possible
interpretation of the language. If the language says ``broken
leg,'' it does not mean broken arm, hip or rib.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of hewing to the line became a big issue some years
ago when several large tour operators shut their doors and decamped
with their customers' deposits. Some insurance companies would not
pay their policyholders because the insurance provided benefits
only if the defaulting company declared bankruptcy, and most never
did. After the burst of defaults, many insurance companies changed
the policy language to encompass a company's cessation of
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Results of a quick survey of six companies show the wide
differences in small-type language and in its interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley Finkle, president of one of these companies, Trip Mate,
discussing the China questions, said the policies his company
prepares for tour operators generally did not pay benefits to
policyholders who canceled their trips because the State Department
issued a warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the situation is bad enough,'' he said, ``the operator will
change the itinerary or give refunds.'' State Department warnings
come in many modulations, he said, and other government cautionary
notices may be reports of disease outbreaks from the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkely Group, according to Christina E. Hopper, a vice
president, does not write its policies to cover cancellation for a
government travel warning. Travel Insured also does not cover this
circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   One acceptable _ ``covered'' _ reason for canceling a trip, as
described in Travelex's literature, is couched in this opaque
language: ``Terrorism in a country which is part of the Covered
Trip which causes the United States Department of State to issue a
travel warning that You should not travel within that country for a
period of time that would include the Covered Trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Ambrose, a vice president, said this meant that
losses of money would be covered if a traveler canceled a trip to
China during the period of the warning or before the warning was
issued if the trip included the May 9-13 period.
</P>
<P>
   While Travel Guard will pay benefits in the event of
``documented terrorism'' in the destination country, Dan McGinnity,
a spokesman, said that this did not apply in the China case. This
company's terrorism definition says, ``Terrorism does not include
general civil protest, unrest, rioting, or an act of war,'' and it
relies on sources like The Wall Street Journal to report its
existence. Travel Insured also does not pay in the event of civil
disturbances even if there is a government warning issued on a
country.
</P>
<P>
   Access America, according to Beth L. Godlin, senior vice
president, was covering losses in cancellations because of a State
Department travel warning, although its language does not
specifically say it. Ms. Godlin said that it was covered by
implication because the insurance says that cancellations for the
State Department's less serious travel advisories, bulletins or
alerts are specifically not covered.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about changes of itinerary in the Adriatic, insurance
officials said they did not recall receiving many claims. Most
travel and cruise companies' contracts reserve the right to change
an itinerary _ although not usually substantially _ without making
refunds. If a traveler was taking the trip specifically to visit
someone in Dubrovnik, and that port of call was eliminated, the
insurance experts said the traveler probably should be talking to
the cruise line.
</P>
<P>
   When the Adriatic port changes were first announced after the
NATO bombing began, some companies _ for instance, Euro Cruises _
offered refunds directly, or offered to let customers select a
later cruise.
</P>
<P>
   For those who change their mind about a trip for any reason,
Travel Guard provides a modest benefit: up to $250 against lost
payments, regardless of the reason for cancellation. To get this,
the traveler must buy the coverage within seven days of paying an
initial deposit.
</P>
<P>
   The American Airlines and TWA labor actions were a classic
sticky wicket. In the American pilots' action, Travel Guard refused
to pay because its language refers to ``an unforeseen organized
labor strike'' and Travel Guard initially said this did not cover
the 10-day sickout.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Myers, owner of Tickets and Travel in Houston, had 10
Austin high school clients making a ski trip on Feb. 11; six of
them arrived in Colorado a day late and four never got out of Texas
because of American's cancellations. They held Travel Guard
policies, and the next day, when the company would not pay, Myers
wrote the company to protest, sending a copy to Travel Weekly, a
trade publication. On Feb. 17, Travel Guard issued a press release
saying it would make an exception and reimburse the policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   John Noel, the chief executive officer of Travel Guard, said:
``We stepped in to make sure that they are compensated for
nonrefundable travel expenses that other companies are refusing to
cover.'' McGinnity emphasized that this was an exception.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Access America's language says it covers losses when ``strikes,
natural disasters or bad weather'' result in the complete cessation
of services by an airline or tour operator for at least 24 hours.
Initially, it also refused to pay claims for the American sickout,
including one from Bernard and Barbara Willett of Jericho, N.Y.,
who missed a Panama Canal cruise booked through ABC Tours of
Bloomfield, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Willett was particularly outraged because the couple going with
them did collect through Travel Insured.
</P>
<P>
   The Willetts' lawyer wrote the New York State Insurance
Department, citing law-dictionary definitions of ``strike.'' Access
America is paying on these claims, Ms. Godlin said, and last
Monday, Willett said he had received a check for $1,693, the price
of the cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Berkely policies usually cover such events under the ``trip
delay'' provision, Ms. Hopper said. Trip Mate, Finkle said, pays
when there is a formally called strike or lockout, not job actions.
Travelex, according to Sally Dunlap, a vice president, decided that
because the American sickout was of such long duration, it would
pay claims for those who had no alternative route.
</P>
<P>
   None of the experts remembered paying any claims as a result of
the TWA sickout. TWA said that it accommodated travelers any way it
could on other lines, with tickets for later flights and with
vouchers, and that it believes that many of its customers held only
airline tickets, not tour packages or hotel reservations, because
they were trying to get home for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium reservations business is a unique situation.
Agencies, operators, expensive hotels and exotic locales are
furiously marketing all sorts of unusual travel to mark the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   One traveler was thinking about a millennial cruise as far back
as 1997, his travel agent said. After an early false start, this
traveler, Louis H. Barnett of Fort Worth, made a new choice in the
summer of 1998: a family cruise to celebrate his wife's 75th
birthday on Dec. 31, 1999. On July 24, he paid a $13,000 deposit on
seven cabins on the Statendam of Holland America Lines, which
leaves Dec. 23 this year on a 16-day cruise from San Diego to
Hawaii and back.
</P>
<P>
   The Barnetts are long-time cruise-takers, and Barnett, 80, an
investor, called his regular travel agent, Jay Silberman of Cruise
Consultants in San Antonio. The total for the trip, Silberman said,
was imposing: the six cabins for 11 family members were $19,500
each, and the suite Barnett reserved for himself and his wife was
$28,000.
</P>
<P>
   Silberman said that he suggested buying the Holland America
Cancellation Protection Plan, which is actually a waiver of
penalties in the event of cancellation, rather than insurance. This
is not inexpensive: Silberman said the plan's cost for the suite
alone would have been $1,400 _ $700 for each of the senior
Barnetts. They turned this down.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 15, 1998, 14 months before the cruise, the deadline for
cancellation passed, according to the line. On Nov. 16, Barnett
canceled the reservation, having discovered, he said, that some of
the grandchildren would not have time for a 16-day cruise, and that
others wanted to go elsewhere. Silberman said he spoke to the line
``probably 20 times,'' but the deadline was immutable.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett proposed that the line apply the deposit to some other
cruise. Silberman said that his client also proposed giving the
money to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Cole C. Quinn of Holland America's executive office in Seattle
wrote to Barnett on Feb. 1 that although the situation was
``unfortunate, our cancellation policies are clearly stated, and
apply to everyone equally.'' On May 20, a spokesman for the cruise
line said that the line stood by its position on the matter, saying
that 200 cabins on this cruise remained unsold.
</P>
<P>
   Although insurance was not an issue here _ Barnett could have
also bought cancellation insurance if he had wished _ the insurance
officials all said that the penalties for canceling reservations
for millennial events were very severe, even in relation to usual
penalties on Christmas-New Year's cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   Finkle said that the cost of the insurance was running about
double the average. The premiums, as filed with most state
insurance departments, cannot be raised for the occasion _ $5.50
for each $100 of coverage is usual _ but the costs of the trips are
high and the cancellation penalties are being enforced swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   Cruises at premium prices are selling briskly for the December
holidays. Cancellation insurance is probably a good course, whether
you buy direct from the company or from a travel agent or take a
policy offered by the tour or cruise organization. But you will
have to make your best guess as to which part of the policy will be
the important one if you miss your trip. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Six insurers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the companies whose officials were interviewed about
their trip-cancellation policies:
</P>
<P>
   Access America, of Richmond, a division of World Access, sells
policies under its own name and also prepares policies for travel
operators' labels. Its underwriter is the BCS Co.; (800) 284-8300.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkely Group, Garden City, N.Y., sells policies under the
brand name Carefree and administers policies for travel operators
and cruise companies, including Carnival, Abercrombie &AMP; Kent and
Mountain Travel-Sobek. Its main underwriter is the National Union
Fire Insurance Co. of Pittsburgh, a division of American
International in New York; (800) 323-3149.
</P>
<P>
   Travel Guard, Stevens Point, Wis., a division of the Noel Group,
sells under its own name and also provides policies for operators
and travel-agent consortiums to put their own names on. Cigna is
the underwriter; (800) 826-1300.
</P>
<P>
   Travel Insured, East Hartford, Conn., is underwritten by the
Travelers Insurance Co.; (800) 243-3174.
</P>
<P>
   Travelex, which was Mutual of Omaha before it was bought by a
currency exchange company, is still in Omaha. The underwriter is
TIG Insurance; (800) 797-4515.
</P>
<P>
   Trip Mate, Kansas City, Mo., prepares policies only for sale by
tour operators, including Globus Tours, Insight, Trafalgar and
Grand Circle. It uses several underwriters, including Monumental
General Casualty in Baltimore. It does not sell retail policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
