</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-VOLPE-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. POLICE OFFICER WILL PLEAD GUILTY TO ASSAULTING IMMIGRANT
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By ROBERT McFADDEN and JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Confronted with devastating testimony by fellow
officers and a crumbling defense, the police officer accused of
torturing a Haitian immigrant in the bathroom of a Brooklyn station
house in 1997 will plead guilty to all charges Tuesday and throw
himself on the mercy of the court, his lawyer told a federal judge
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With an overwhelming case against him and with prosecutors
rejecting any plea bargain, the officer, Justin A. Volpe, appeared
to have no choice but to admit that he rammed a broom handle into
the rectum and then into the mouth of the handcuffed man, Abner
Louima, in a fit of rage. Volpe could be sentenced to a prison term
ranging from 25 years to life without parole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to enter a plea tomorrow,'' Officer Volpe's
lawyer, Marvyn M. Kornberg, told Judge Eugene H. Nickerson in
federal court in Brooklyn in a quiet conference of defense lawyers
and prosecutors at the bench Monday afternoon, signaling that his
client had abandoned all but the hope of leniency.
</P>
<P>
   While the trial of four other officers accused in the case was
expected to continue, a guilty plea by Volpe would end his
involvement in the most explosive New York police brutality episode
in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Monday night that he would withhold
comment until the plea was entered, and Police Commissioner Howard
Safir also declined to comment. The mayor and the commissioner,
often outspoken in their defense of police officers, have been
silent in the Louima case.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the other defendants indicated that they were
prepared to go on with the trial. Kornberg declined to comment on
whether Volpe would testify for the prosecution, or whether, in
offering his plea, he would implicate any of the others. Other
lawyers in the case said it was not likely that he would testify,
and what he will disclose in his plea appeared to be up to the
judge.
</P>
<P>
   As a condition of pleading guilty, legal experts said, Volpe
would be required to detail his actions on the morning of Aug. 9,
1997, when, officials charge, he and Officers Charles Schwarz,
Thomas Wiese and Thomas Bruder beat Louima in a patrol car before
taking him to the 70th Precinct station house, where Schwarz
allegedly held him down while Volpe sodomized him.
</P>
<P>
   The extent to which Volpe will tell his story _ whether the
actions of other officers will be detailed or even cited, for
example _ will be up to Judge Nickerson, lawyers said. But legal
experts said that to ensure that the continuing trial of the other
officers would not be tainted, the judge was not likely to require
any statements by Volpe of their involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Volpe's statement in open court, which will take
place in the absence of the jury, could amount to a dramatic
confession of his own purported brutality, a story that has already
been told in testimony by Louima, 32, who suffered severe rectal
and bladder injuries and underwent several operations and months of
hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   By pleading guilty to violating Louima's civil rights in a
sexual assault, Volpe, 27, would expose himself to a maximum
sentence of life in prison without possibility of parole. But under
complex federal sentencing guidelines, Nickerson, by applying all
provisions for leniency including Volpe's acceptance of
responsibility for his actions, could impose a term of as little as
25 to 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts noted that the judge would have wide discretion in
sentencing. Prosecutors were expected to argue against leniency on
the ground that Volpe decided to plead guilty only after he saw the
overwhelming case against him as fellow officers in the past week
told of hearing him brag of the assault and seeing him brandish the
stick stained with blood and feces.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Technically, Nickerson could reject a guilty plea if he thought
it served the interest of justice, but lawyers said that was not
likely in view of the testimony in recent days by Sgt. Kenneth
Wernick, Detective Eric Turetzky and Officers Mark Schofield and
Michael Schoer.
</P>
<P>
   Turetzky last week testified that he saw Volpe lead a handcuffed
Louima, whose pants were down at his ankles, to the bathroom of the
station house, and later that he saw Volpe, disheveled and sullen,
swinging a stick around ``like a sword and hitting it against a
wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Schofield testified that he, too, saw Volpe with a stick and
said he had borrowed a pair of black leather gloves before the
alleged attack and later gave them back, covered with blood.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg, who had said at the outset of the trial that Louima's
injuries had been caused by consensual sex at a nightclub before a
melee that led to his arrest, and other defense lawyers vigorously
attacked the credibility of both police witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But the defense appeared to be taken by surprise last Wednesday
when Wernick testified, in an account that had not been made public
previously, that Volpe had bragged about the attack, saying ``I
took a man down tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant said Volpe told him he ``took a stick and put it
five or six inches up (Louima's rectum), took it out and put it up
to his mouth and teeth area, kind of like showing it to him.'' He
said Volpe also showed him the section of broomstick, two to three
feet long, in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   After first saying he intended to cross-examine Wernick,
Kornberg reversed himself and asked no questions. He also did not
cross-examine Schoer, who testified that Volpe had taunted him by
putting the excrement-tainted stick near his face.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
