<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9617 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CHECKETTS-LIE-NYT     05-24 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CHECKETTS-LIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECKETTS NOW ADMITS HE MET JACKSON AND LIED ABOUT IT
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A conciliatory Dave Checketts acknowledged Monday
that he met with Phil Jackson nearly six weeks ago, after denying
on Sunday that he had made contact with the former Bulls coach for
exploratory talks about potentially coming to the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts, the Madison Square Garden president, also said that
he met with the Knicks' coach, Jeff Van Gundy, earlier in the day
and apologized to him for making misleading statements about
meeting with Jackson. Speaking at a news conference before Game 4
of the Eastern Conference semifinal at the Garden Monday night,
Checketts appeared contrite and remorseful about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   But he also did not quell the speculation surrounding Van
Gundy's status as coach, saying he and Van Gundy agreed to discuss
the matter after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took over with eight games left to go in the regular
season, my goal with the Knicks team and the coaches was to
eliminate the distractions I felt were getting in the way of the
team accomplishing what it could accomplish,'' said Checketts, who
reassigned Ernie Grunfeld, general manager and team president, on
April 21. ``And I've tried very hard to do that. But when we were
21-21 and having lost four in a row, I reached out through an
intermediary and contacted Phil Jackson, and I set up a meeting
with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did meet. We met for a couple of hours. There were no
offers exchanged. There was nothing that came out of the meeting,
other than getting acquainted with a guy that I felt was a
tremendous option for us, if in fact we continued the season the
way it was going and didn't make the playoffs and we needed a new
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I did meet with him. I regret that I lied about that, that
I misled the press and Jeff Van Gundy about that.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, during the nationally televised game between the
Atlanta Hawks and Knicks, Checketts denied a report in The New York
Times that morning that Checketts had met with Jackson in
mid-April. After the game, through a spokesman, he continued to
deny the meeting but acknowledged contacting Jackson through an
intermediary.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson could not reached for comment. His agent, Todd
Musburger, who also attended the meeting with Checketts, declined
to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
