SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Massachusetts Home For Contemporary Art &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years in the making, MASS MoCA, a campus for
contemporary art in North Adams, Mass., is set to open Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   MASS MoCA, which calls itself the largest center for
contemporary visual and performing arts in the United States, plans
to focus on artists charting new territory, works that blur the
line between visual and performing arts, and works that have seldom
been seen because of their size or material.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-acre site includes 27 disused factory buildings, though
so far only 6 have been renovated. Dating from the 19th century,
the complex once belonged to the O. Arnold and Co. print works and
later to Sprague Electric Co. Listed on the National Register of
Historic Places, the red-brick structures are joined by bridges,
viaducts and elevated walkways to form an elaborate system of
interlocking courtyards, an architectural vision in itself. They
occupy nearly a third of North Adams' downtown business district.
</P>
<P>
   Transformed, the buildings are now home to 19 galleries with
more than 100,000 square feet of exhibition space, including one as
long as a football field; a 650-seat theater; an outdoor cinema
with a 50-foot-wide screen; two performance courtyards; an art
workshop, and fabrication facilities, including areas that allow
visitors to watch artists create.
</P>
<P>
   For its opening MASS MoCA has scheduled a broad range of
programs; most are scheduled to run for at least several months.
Among them: a group exhibition of works by Robert Rauschenberg,
Joseph Beuys, Mario Merz and other artists; a new commissioned work
by Tony Oursler, the video artist; a large-scale installation by
Natalie Jeremijenko; and ``Ghostcatching,'' which uses digital
motion-capture technology to multiply the dancing of Bill T. Jones
into an interactive ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   There is also an animation series, which on July 10 features a
Walt Disney Pictures project in development, and an exhibition that
brings together drawings by the dancer Trisha Brown and the painter
Terry Winters, among others. Christina Kubisch has created a sound
work for MASS MoCA's clock tower.
</P>
<P>
   MASS MoCA, at 87 Marshall Street in North Adams, is about three
hours by car from both New York and Boston. The center is open
daily; admission is $8. For more information: (413) 664-4481. On
the Internet: www.massmoca.org.
</P>
<P>
   Judith H. Dobrzynski &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelin Teams Mexico With Belize, Guatemala &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelin has published its first combined tourist guide to
Mexico, Guatemala and Belize. Mexico had a Green Guide of its own,
last reissued in 1990, and the two smaller countries until now had
none. The new volume, in the familiar paperback pocket-width
format, devotes some 310 pages to Mexico, 26 to Guatemala and 18 to
tiny English-speaking Belize.
</P>
<P>
   The book rates attractions in Michelin's usual way: one star for
``interesting,'' two for ``worth a detour'' and three for ``worth
the trip.'' Belize's reefs and Lamanai archeological site rate
three stars, as do the Tikal archeological zone and the ancient
capital of Antigua in Guatemala. Mexico has many three-star spots.
</P>
<P>
   Advice on safety is sparse; it mostly concerns the hazards of
nature and the sun, although the United States Embassy's precaution
against hailing taxis on the streets of Mexico City is noted.
</P>
<P>
   The book, with a large number of small maps and modest color
pictures, is published in English, Spanish or French and costs $20.
Michelin outlet information: (800) 223-0987. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the Hanoi Hilton To the Hilton Hanoi &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hilton Hanoi Opera hotel has opened, a few blocks from Hoa
Lo, the infamous ``Hanoi Hilton'' where American prisoners were
held during the Vietnam War. (The few remaining cells of that
prison have been preserved as a museum.) The seven-story classical
facade of the new hotel resembles its more immediate neighbor, the
newly restored 1911 French colonial Hanoi Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood is within walking distance of the city's
central business district. Guest rooms, furnished with lacquered
cabinets and Vietnamese art, have individually controlled
air-conditioning, data ports and television with international
channels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a fitness center, whirlpool, sauna and massage, and the
outdoor pool has its own bar. Dining choices include a cafe, a bar,
a brasserie with French specialties and a Cantonese restaurant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hotel has 269 rooms and suites. A special promotional rate
of $111 for a double (you must book at least three days in advance)
is good through Sept. 15; the standard rate is $155. Tax of 15
percent is extra. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hilton Hanoi Opera, 1 Le Thanh Tong Street, Hoan Kiem, Hanoi,
Vietnam; telephone (84-4) 933-0500, fax (84-4) 933-0530.
Reservations: (800) 445-8667 or www.hilton.com.
</P>
<P>
   Luba Vangelova &QL;
</P>
