r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON &LR;      05-24 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 When a Stock Sale Is Short or Long Term  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I worked for a privately held company until last October
1. The month before I left, I exercised my right to buy some stock
in the company. I was granted the right in December 1997, but
didn't have the money at that time. The company says that it will
go public soon. Once it does, I intend to sell my shares. My
question is: What is my purchase date for determining whether my
sale is long term or short term? Is it the grant date, or the date
when I paid for the shares, or the date when the stock goes public?
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  It isn't the grant date, because you didn't own the
shares at that time. It isn't the date the stock will go public,
because you bought the shares before then. The date on which you
actually bought the shares is your purchase date for tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, you are not entitled to long-term capital gains
treatment, because it is less than 12 months since you bought the
shares. If you bought the shares, say, last September 15, then the
earliest date for a long-term sale would be September 16, 1999. If
you are in the 28 percent bracket, you would pay a 28 percent tax
on your gain with a short-term sale, compared with 20 percent if
the sale is long term. All other things being equal, you would do
much better to sell long term.
</P>
<P>
   However, other things have a tendency not to stay equal. It
could be unwise to time your sale based on tax considerations
alone.
</P>
<P>
   You have to decide whether the prospects for the stock are good
enough to justify waiting to sell.
</P>
<P>
   For example, suppose the stock shoots up after the initial
public offering _ as stocks often do _ and you find yourself with a
short-term gain of $30 per share. If you then sold the stock, you
would pay a capital gains tax of $8.40 per share. If the stock
stayed at $30 until you qualified for long-term treatment, your tax
would be $6 per share.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the stock were to fall several points before
September? In that case, you would have outsmarted yourself. You
would have been better off taking a short-term gain.
</P>
<P>
   More on Roth IRAs
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a recent column you stated that a taxpayer who contributes
the full $2,000 annual amount to a Roth Individual Retirement
Account cannot contribute anything to traditional IRAs that same
year. But what if the traditional IRA is a nondeductible type? Can
I contribute to that and also contribute $2,000 to my Roth?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: I'm afraid not. The tax law explicitly states that the
$2,000 limit on your Roth contribution will be reduced by whatever
you contribute that same year to any traditional IRAs. So if you
max out your Roth, there's no room left for other contributions.
</P>
<P>
   I can understand why you posed the question. Since you pay taxes
up front on the money you contribute to a nondeductible IRA, you
are wondering why the government is so tight-fisted about the
amounts you can contribute.
</P>
<P>
   The reason _ you can decide for yourself whether it is a good
one _ is that your earnings on the money you contribute to a
nondeductible IRA will accumulate tax-deferred. The government
doesn't want too much tax-deferred income sitting out there,
because it has to raise enough money each year to finance the many,
wonderful federal services and programs that benefit us all.
</P>
<P>
   Tax on Gift of Stock
</P>
<P>
   Q: I own some stock that has gone up in value since I bought it,
and I am thinking of giving some of it to my children. What cost
basis will they use if they ever decide to sell?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: When you give stock to your children, you escape the
obligation to pay tax on your capital gain. As you indicate, that
obligation is transferred to the children _ but they don't have to
pay until they sell the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Their cost basis will be the same as yours, and they also will
use your purchase date to determine whether their sale is long term
or short term. (It will be long term if they sell the stock at
least a year and a day after you bought it.)
</P>
<P>
   When you give your children the stock, don't forget to also give
them the transaction slips, brokerage statements or other documents
that confirm the purchase date and price. They will need the
information for their tax records, and they might have to produce
the documents if the Internal Revenue Service poses any questions.
</P>
<P>
   You don't mention the amount of money involved. Bear in mind
that if you plan to give stock with a current value of more than
$10,000 to any one child, you will have to pay a federal gift tax.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
