<HEADLINE>
FOR SCHOOL ADMINISTRATORS, ANXIETY AND ASSURANCE AFTER RULING 
</HEADLINE>
  (With SCOTUS-HARASS) 
(mk) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Educational administrators, exhausted by weeks of focus on
school safety and discipline after the shootings in Littleton,
Colo., worried Monday that the Supreme Court's decision on student
sexual harassment would be yet another burden.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, their lawyers pointed to the high legal
standard required by the court for a school to be held liable and
said the ruling should not cause great concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``School administrators are reeling after Littleton,'' said Paul
Houston, executive director of the American Association of School
Administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am afraid they will pick up their papers tomorrow morning
and find that the Supreme Court has handed them one more job, which
is preventing kids from harassing each other,'' Houston said.
</P>
<P>
   But Julie Underwood, general counsel to the National School
Boards Association, said, ``The court stated that school districts
would only be held liable if they were deliberately indifferent to
known and pervasive harassment. These are rare occasions.'' Ms.
Underwood added, ``If the standard had been lower, then we would be
very concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   The school boards association had filed a brief urging that the
court not use the lower standard of civil rights law, which makes
institutions liable if they knew or should have known about a
problem, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony Kennedy's concern that the 5-4 ruling would lead
to an avalanche of litigation was unfounded, Ms. Underwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Yurek, general counsel for the National Association of
Secondary School Principals, said the court had reaffirmed what his
organization had been telling its members: that they must be
actively involved in protecting their students and promoting
appropriate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of boys will be boys and girls will be girls are long
gone,'' Yurek said. ``The school needs to address all elements of
the school environment and teach core values, including respect.
There won't be liability if you are proactive and out there
teaching kids about appropriate behavior. It really is important
that values be taught in schools as well as in homes and
churches.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, the administrators' association director, said he
agreed. But such education would require more teacher training and
there is the potential cost of fighting litigation. He said he was
concerned how the ruling would affect pupils in special education
with emotional or behavioral problems.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Pipho, senior fellow at the Education Commission of the
States, based in Colorado, said some states were already
strengthening education that promotes mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole Columbine situation has moved us further along in
the acceptance of the fact that schools have got to do something in
this arena,'' Pipho said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
