<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHALLENGE OF THE CLINTON PRESIDENCY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a special issue on ``A Century of Style,'' the menswear
periodical DNR deconstructs the suits of  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; , ``the
first Baby Boomer to be elected president. Quickly, he changed his
image of a sloppy jogger in too-short shorts to a Dapper Dan in
crepe pinstripe suits in the European style.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ironically,'' reports the magazine, ``ties _ not suits _ will
be Clinton's legacy.'' The story describes  &UR; Hillary Rodham &LR; 
 &UR; Clinton &LR;  buying her husband  &UR; Jerry Garcia &LR;  ties and notes that
 &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; , ``herself a tie salesperson while in high school
and college, would present him with a $100  &UR; Ermenegildo &LR; 
 &UR; Zegna &LR;  tie. As Lewinsky told the grand jury: `Ties were a big issue
with us.'
</P>
<P>
   ``As we enter the 21st century, politicians continue to seek the
formula for looking presidential. Image is part of the package but
takes a backseat to issues, which is probably as it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ After  &UR; Bob Dole &LR;  expressed some positive thoughts recently
about the presidential aspirations of Senator  &UR; John McCain &LR; ,
R-Ariz.,  &UR; Elizabeth Dole &LR;  joked that she was angry at him. Former
Rep.  &UR; Susan Molinari &LR; , R-N.Y., went a little further in a question
quoted in Roll Call: ``After this interview, is Bob Dole going to
need Viagra?''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Caroline Maneatis &LR; , co-owner of the San Francisco clothing
store Cara Mia, ran three blocks last week in pursuit of  &UR; Gwyneth &LR; 
 &UR; Paltrow &LR; , who'd left her hot pants behind. Paltrow was in the store
for about an hour, buying nearly four figures' worth of stuff, but
had forgotten the shorts when she left for an appointment a few
blocks away. Exercising superhuman self-control during the great
chase, Maneatis didn't yell, ``Gwyneth,'' but she noticed that
heads were turning anyway.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tricycle: The Buddhist Review and three separate Buddhist
centers sponsoring Change Your Mind Day _ June 5, &LR; from 12:30 to
5:30 p.m. in Pioneer Meadow in Golden Gate Park _ have much more in
mind than which side of the bed to sleep on or whether Cherry
Garcia beats Rainforest Crunch.
</P>
<P>
   _ The departure gate was changed twice when  &UR; David Cassell &LR;  flew
Alaska Airlines from Portland, Ore., to Oakland, and then the
destination was changed from Oakland to San Francisco (with a
shuttle to Oakland). When prayer cards were distributed with the
meal, he writes, he got worried.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
