<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9637 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-COLBASE-COLUMN-LA     05-24 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-COLBASE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIONS LOOK FORWARD TO CARDINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Two days after winning its second consecutive West Coast
Conference baseball championship, Loyola Marymount received
surprising news.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions, who beat Pepperdine for the WCC championship on
Saturday, were rewarded with a trip to Stanford and a first-round
game against the top-seeded Cardinal when the NCAA playoffs start
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   LMU was expecting to stay in Los Angeles and play in the
regional hosted by USC. Head coach Frank Cruz, who guided the Lions
(33-26) to five wins in six games against Pepperdine this season,
was diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were going to be at one or the other,'' said Cruz,
whose team upset Stanford last year in a regional opener. ``It's
like, `Pick your poison.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The players were more candid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We flat-out beat Pepperdine,'' LMU shortstop Curt Fiore said
on Saturday. ``There were no flukes there.'
</P>
<P>
   Dick Rockwell, the NCAA selection-committee chair, said less
thought was given to LMU's being sent to Stanford and more was
given to Pepperdine's (43-14) receiving the No. 1 seed at USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in the best interest of college baseball if you move
some teams out of (L.A.),'' Rockwell said. ``We think Fullerton is
very good. Pepperdine beat Fullerton twice. I think (the Waves)
deserved a No. 1 seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``About Loyola Marymount, that was probably a more geographic
move than anything else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 12th-ranked Waves, who were ranked as high as No. 3 earlier
in the season, were seeded first in a regional for the second time
in school history. Rockwell said the Waves deserved to be seeded
over USC, which finished second in the Pac-10 and went 1-1 against
Pepperdine this season.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA (30-29) received an at-large bid and plays Oklahoma State
in the regional hosted by Wichita State. Rockwell was asked about
the Bruins' selection on Monday's ESPN telecast of the playoff
pairings and again during a conference call later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That UCLA question probably took up an hour and a half of our
time,'' Rockwell said. ``(The Bruins) played everybody. They played
21 teams in the Top 50. If we were at 48 teams, I don't think UCLA
would have gotten in. (But) they have a reasonable chance to
compete for the national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   __ To the rescue: Jason Lane and Barry Zito had All-American
seasons for USC. Eric Munson, the Trojans catcher, is considered
college baseball's top hitter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Trojans' most valuable player this season is Dominic
Correa, a senior second baseman. Correa, who started only 12 games
as a junior, is batting .343 with 12 home runs and 48 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-11, 185-pound Correa also is a reliable relief
pitcher, going 1-1 with a 2.31 ERA and one save. He talked his way
into a pitching role early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Correa) has been extra valuable,'' USC coach Mike Gillespie
said. ``He's been largely responsible for the success we have had.
It's really a great story.''
</P>
<P>
   USC needed a starting second baseman when Kevin Schultz
unexpectedly quit the team a month before the season. After playing
left field to start the year, Correa became the starter at second
and flourished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I had spot time,'' Correa said. ``I felt I had to do
well to stay in the mix. This is by far the most fun I've had. I
picked a good year to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ No experience needed: The highlight of LMU's championship
season was the play of freshman Tommy Perez, who earned the
starting third-base job less than a year after graduating from
Burroughs High.
</P>
<P>
   Perez enters the playoffs batting .294 with 11 homers and 48
RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``My power numbers are decent,'' said Perez, who started 54 of
the Lions' 56 games in the regular season, ``but my average can be
a little higher. I'm happy. I've put together some good numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez wasn't selected in last year's draft until the 45th round.
Despite batting .488 with 12 homers and 48 RBI for the Indians, he
was the 1,332nd player picked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew that scouts had a negative opinion about me,''
Perez said. ``These (LMU) coaches gave me a chance. They didn't
really change much. They let me do what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   __ No `I' in Curt: Curt Fiore wanted to be Loyola Marymount's
starting third baseman this season. Instead, he started at first
base. Then he moved to shortstop in late April when Jack Brooks
went down with a shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   Even while moving around the infield, Fiore, a senior, only
committed eight errors. He leads the Lions in batting average
(.366) to go with eight homers and 44 RBI. Fiore's latest homer
came in the seventh inning of LMU's 7-6 win over Pepperdine
Saturday in the decisive third game of the WCC championship series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my last year and I want to do what's right,'' Fiore
said. ``I want to do what is best for the team. If shortstop is the
place to be, that's where I'm going to play.'' &QL; 
PLAYOFF BOUND
</P>
<P>
   Six Los Angeles-area teams earned bids to the 64-team NCAA
college baseball playoffs, which start Friday: &QL; 
__ Pepperdine. Seeded No. 1 at regional hosted by USC. First-game
opponent: Harvard. &QL; 
__ USC: Seeded No. 2. First-game opponent: Virginia Commonwealth. &QL; 
__ UCLA: Seeded No. 3 at Wichita State regional. First-game
opponent: Oklahoma State. &QL; 
__ Loyola Marymount: Seeded No. 4 at Stanford regional. First-game
opponent: Stanford. &QL; 
__ Cal State Fullerton: Seeded No. 1 at Notre Dame regional.
First-game opponent: Michigan. &QL; 
__ Long Beach State: Seeded No. 2 at Texas A&AMP;M regional. First-game
opponent: Mississippi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
