Institution's National Museum of American History. Using technology
as new as space age fabrics and as ordinary as the chemicals from
the corner dry-cleaning shop, scientists and historians at the
museum have taken on the job of cleaning and preserving the flag
that flew over Fort McHenry in Baltimore in 1814, so that it might
last at least another 185 years. (Richard W. Strauss/Smithsonian
Institution/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- May 24, 1999 -- SCI-FLAG-PRESERVE-3, 5-24
-- Suzanne Thomassen-Krauss, the cheif conservator at the
Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of American History,
discusses the details of the work to be done on the Star-Spangled
Banner at the museum. Using technology as new as space age fabrics
and as ordinary as the chemicals from the corner dry-cleaning shop,
scientists and historians at the museum have taken on the job of
cleaning and preserving the Star-Spangled Banner, the flag that
flew over Fort McHenry in Baltimore in 1814, so that it might last
at least another 185 years. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- May 24, 1999 -- SCI-FLAG-PRESERVE-2-B&AMP;W, 5-24
-- A magnified sample of dust removed from the Star-Spangled Banner
during vacuuming in 1994 shows clay particles, vegetable matter,
synthetic fibers, linen, and cotton linters. Using technology as
new as space age fabrics and as ordinary as the chemicals from the
corner dry-cleaning shop, scientists and historians at the
Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of American History have
taken on the job of cleaning and preserving the Star-Spangled
Banner, the flag that flew over Fort McHenry in Baltimore in 1814,
so that it might last at least another 185 years. (Mary
Ballard/Smithsonian Institution/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BOSTON -- May 24, 1999 -- SCI-FLAG-PRESERVE-1, 5-24 --
The first known photograph of the Star-Spangled Banner, taken in
1873 at the Boston Navy Yard. Using technology as new as space age
fabrics and as ordinary as the chemicals from the corner
dry-cleaning shop, scientists and historians at the Smithsonian
Institution's National Museum of American History have taken on the
job of cleaning and preserving the Star-Spangled Banner, the flag
that flew over Fort McHenry in Baltimore in 1814, so that it might
last at least another 185 years. (Smithsonian Institution/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- May 24, 1999 -- SCI-WEIGHT-MORPH, 05-24 --
Former New York City mayor turned T.V. personality, Ed Koch with a
``body-morphing station'' used to promote the weight-loss drug
Xenical at a Manhattan news conference. The morphing station, which
is available only at news media events, may eventually find its way
into malls. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- May 24, 1999 -- SCI-WEIGHT-REBOUND, 05-24 --
Russell M. Lomando, at top, lost 50 pounds. Below, in 1987, Lomando
weighed 210 pounds. ``I was 39 years old and I was walking up the
train stairs in Brooklyn huffing and puffing,'' he says. ``You just
have to change your life style.'' (below: courtesy of Russell
Lomando, top: Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BLACE, Macedonia -- May 24, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-3,
5-24 -- An elderly man is carried onto a bus transporting refugees
