<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9645 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS &LR;      05-24 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREMIUM SEAT SALES AT PATRIOTS STADIUM 50% OFF GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- On the day Massachusetts officially anted up $70
million to help the New England Patriots build a new stadium in
Foxborough, business representatives admitted they have fallen
short of their stated goal of selling $15 million in premium
seating, a key source of financing for the project.
</P>
<P>
   As Governor Paul Cellucci signed the stadium bill on Beacon Hill
Monday, Paul G. Kirk Jr., one of the civic leaders who waged the
successful campaign to keep the Patriots from moving to Hartford,
Conn. said: ``I think, at this point, that we have commitments for
about roughly half of that, about $7.5 million worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I'm delighted with where we are,'' Kirk added.
``We've won our fight with the skeptics and this is now reality.
We're just going to continue to go on until the job is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Specialists in sports business say the group's initial target
was overly aggressive. They predict that sufficent premium seating
will eventually be sold to get the stadium off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Robert Kraft, in Atlanta for a meeting of National
Football League owners, praised the bill's signing but did not
comment further Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's great. That's step one,'' said Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft said he would not say more because the NFL owners would
not meet until Tuesday to approve the league's contribution to the
stadium finance package, part of a new policy designed to prevent
teams from deserting big-city markets for smaller cities offering
lucrative stadium deals. However, sources said Kraft also remained
tight-lipped to avoid giving Connecticut any fodder for the lawsuit
it threatened to file after Kraft pulled out of an agreement for a
Hartford facility.
</P>
<P>
   Attending the signing ceremony were Senate President Thomas F.
Birmingham and House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, whose long
opposition to higher levels of state financing had blocked
construction of the stadium here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a happy day for all of the taxpayers in the Commonwealth
of Massachusetts, whether they're sports fans or not,'' said
Birmingham, who raised both arms in a touchdown signal when he
walked to a podium to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, when Kirk and other civic leaders put the issue of
the Patriots stadium back on the agenda in Massachusetts, they said
they would follow through with a campaign to obtain commitments
from corporations to purchase a big portion of the 100 to 120
luxury suites and about 6,000 club seats planned for the facility.
</P>
<P>
   The civic leaders said the ticket drive was part of the business
community's commitment to the stadium, a private-sector complement
to the state's agreement to fund $70 million in improvements to
roads, sewers, and other infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Civic leaders said they wanted to have the commitments lined up
to present to the NFL owners at this week's meeting. At the time,
it was possible that both the Connecticut and Massachusetts stadium
offers could be on the table for the owners to review.
</P>
<P>
   But Kraft, citing concern that the Hartford stadium could not be
ready by 2002 as promised, pulled out of the deal at the end of
April. That took some of the pressure off the Bay State drive to
line up seating commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft briefed the NFL owners' finance committee Monday. Owners
are expected to approve a plan Tuesday, even with the seating
commitments running behind target.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the lesson is that one needs to be careful saying
publicly how high the bar is raised,'' said Larry Moulter,
president of Woolf Associates. ``These are expensive properties,
and the companies don't make their decisions that quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they will sell, across time,'' Moulter said, adding
that if the stock market remains at the 11,000 level until the
stadium is built, it will make for an easier sale to businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Caporale, of the investment banking firm Game Plan LLC,
said that obtaining $7.5 million in commitments in less than a
month is actually a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought from the start that their goal was overly
ambitious,'' Caporale said. ``If they've achieved that number in
that short a period of time, I think they've done well.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of both the Boston Red Sox and the FleetCenter, which
both have premium seating, have said that the Boston market will
probably sustain new stadiums for the Red Sox and the Patriots, as
well as re-selling the seating at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Competition with Red Sox management, which signaled its
impending approach to the premium-seating market when announcing
plans for a new Fenway Park 10 days ago, has not played a major
role in slowing businesses' commitments to the Patriots, Kirk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard an isolated story here and there, that one company
is holding back while they weigh the Red Sox situation, too,'' said
Kirk. ``But, overall, no, I don't think it has been a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, trailer park residents on the Foxboro Stadium site,
who under terms of the $70 million stadium bill have six months to
vacate, said Monday that they are soliciting support from
Foxborough officials and voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sorry we're in the way,'' said Jackie Sewell, who lives
in a mobile home on land owned by Kraft. ``We want to be moved to
another location. We don't want to stop progress for our state. We
just want Mr. Kraft to move us to another location.''
</P>
<P>
   The residents have formed the Route One Mobile Home Tenants
Association to fight any plan that would move them off the site.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kraus, a Plymouth attorney hired by the residents, has
formally notified Kraft's real estate company that the tenants will
wage a legal fight to stay somewhere on the stadium site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tina Cassidy and Thomas Farragher of the Globe staff contributed
to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
