<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9650 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-ASSESS-2TAK     05-24 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: WITH VOLPE PLEADING GUILTY, NEW PROBLEMS FOR REMAINING
DEFENDANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They acted as if he were not even in the same
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   They did not say good morning to him, they did not pat him on
the back, they barely looked at him at all.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, four officers who grudgingly shared a defense table
with Officer Justin A. Volpe worked hard to convey to jurors a
simple message: He is not one of us.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Volpe's sudden decision to admit he rammed a stick
into Abner Louima's rectum, their wish will come true: Volpe will
vanish from the defense table, left to await his sentence while
under house arrest at his parents' home in Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   For the remaining officers on trial, the effect of Volpe's
guilty plea creates several new questions for their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors almost surely will not be told of Volpe's pleading
guilty to violating Louima's civil rights in a sexual assault.
Because of fears of prejudicing the jury, the judge will likely
point out Volpe's absence but instruct the jurors to draw no
inference from it. But will jurors _ who are not sequestered _
learn about the guilty plea anyway? And if they do, will it taint
their views of the remaining officers?
</P>
<P>
   Volpe is not expected to testify for the prosecution, because he
has not made a deal with prosecutors, who have indicated they do
not consider him a reliable witness. But will his absence focus the
jury's attention on the conduct of the other four who up until now
have largely escaped notice?
</P>
<P>
   Judge Eugene Nickerson of U.S. District Court has instructed
jurors not to hold the remaining four accountable for the actions
described in some of the most damaging testimony to date, but will
federal prosecutors, freed of the need to build a case against
their most prominent defendant, now bear down on them?
</P>
<P>
   The complications were immediately apparent Monday, moments
after Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn M. Kornberg, asked for a private
conference with Nickerson to announce his client's intent to plead
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen C. Worth, a lawyer for Officer Charles Schwarz, asked
the judge to withhold from the public any mention of Volpe's change
of heart until he entered his plea in open court.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it will be what took place in court,'' Worth said,
``and not the wild, wild and crazy speculation that's going to go
on now because of the press' misunderstanding of what's happening
here, which is that he simply, as I understand it, is entering a
plea of guilty on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   But moment later, after consulting with ``my
soon-to-be-remaining co-counsel,'' Worth suddenly reversed course
and withdrew his request that Nickerson keep secret Volpe's plans
to change his plea
</P>
<P>
   Of all the defense lawyers still in the case, Worth may have the
most to be concerned about. Only his client faces charges in
connection with the sodomy of Louima in the bathroom at the 70th
Precinct. Schwarz is accused of holding Louima down.
</P>
<P>
   Two other officers, Thomas Wiese and Thomas Bruder, are accused
of beating Louima in a police car. The fourth, Sgt. Michael
Bellomo, is charged with covering up the assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for all four have repeatedly asked Nickerson to sever
their cases from Volpe's trial on grounds that evidence against him
would automatically prejudice jurors against all the officers.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, most of the evidence presented so far has focused on
Volpe. He is the only officer Louima has been able to identify as
being involved in the attack. He has been the trial's central
character, a muscular, 27-year-old who sat at the defense table,
silent but often glowering, as day by day, witness by witness, the
evidence piled up around him, like shovels of sand on a coffin.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, it was a trauma surgeon who did the shoveling,
telling jurors how lacerations on Louima's rectum and bladder lined
up perfectly with one another, making his injuries consistent with
trauma from a blunt object.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe slumped deeper in his chair, scribbled a few more notes on
his legal pad, and watched himself be buried by an efficient team
of federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday afternoon, Kornberg acknowledged what was becoming
increasingly obvious to those who lined up each morning to get a
courtroom seat at U.S. District Court in Brooklyn: That the
allegations against his client are true, that Volpe's denials have
been lies, that Louima, handcuffed and bloodied and face down on
the urine-splattered floor of a police bathroom, suffered through
one of the worst instances of police brutality on record.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Kornberg's announcement that his client intends to
plead guilty came primarily because four more of Volpe's colleagues
in the 70th Precinct shattered the legendary wall of silence that
traditionally serves and protects police officers who do wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The extent to which the wall crumbled surprised even Kornberg _
one of New York City's top trial lawyers _ to such a degree that he
abandoned his intention to cross-examine two of the officers who
testified against his client.
</P>
<P>
   One officer described how Volpe casually brandished a
foul-smelling stick even as Louima lay in agony on the floor of a
holding cell, blood trickling into his abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   Another described how he boasted of breaking a man down.
</P>
<P>
   Another described how his uniform was disheveled, how Volpe's
name tag had been removed from his shirt, and how his mood seemed
oddly muted and detached that August morning.
</P>
<P>
   Another described how Volpe borrowed a pair of gloves and
returned them covered in blood like it was no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony was so strong that Volpe surely seemed headed for
conviction, and if found guilty by a jury, would face life in
prison. By admitting guilt, he may receive a lesser sentence from
the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the trial, Louima took the stand and quietly gave his
account of what happened the night he was arrested outside Club
Rendezvous in the Flatbush section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony was restrained and dignified, but Kornberg and the
defense lawyers for the four other police officers on trial tried
to savage Louima's credibility. They jumped at every opportunity to
mention his $150-million lawsuit against the city. They forced him
to confess to all the lies he told about that night, starting with
his whopper about how his attackers boasted ``It's Giuliani time.''
</P>
<P>
   The cross-examination raised doubts about Louima's account --
until Volpe's brethren began their joyless parade to the witness
chair.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Kornberg attacked them with the same vigor he attacked
Louima. He went so far as to suggest during a sidebar conference
with Nickerson that the first officer to testify, Detective Eric
Turetzky, was doing so because he once had a crush on Volpe's
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   But when the third officer marched to the stand, the fight was
starting to ebb from Kornberg. His initial line of defense _ that
Louima's injuries were caused by consensual gay sex _ was in a
shambles, and not only because prosecutors pointed out that Louima
is married, has two children and a third on the way.
</P>
<P>
   The medical testimony Monday cast strong doubt on Kornberg's gay
sex theory, as did descriptions of a healthy, dancing, club-bopping
Louima, seen shaking hours later with the onset of shock.
</P>
<P>
   And so, when the third officer, Sgt. Kenneth Wernick, finished
his story of Volpe walking stick in hand toward a dumpster,
Kornberg clearly signaled the coming white flag by saying he had no
questions. In case anyone missed the signal, he did it again when
prosecutors were finished with the fourth officer. ``No
questions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters he was changing tactics, and he dangled hints
of some grand master plan to rescue Volpe. But the only plan, it
now turns out, is for Volpe to throw himself on the mercy of
Nickerson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
