<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-MENTALHEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PATAKI'S PUBLIC SAFETY FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, May 25:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki portrays himself as a law-and-order
politician who makes public safety a top priority. The governor is
very vocal about his desire to keep even nonviolent prisoners in
jail for longer periods of time. But meanwhile, on his watch,
mentally ill people with histories of violent behavior are being
sent to live in the community without adequate supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Goldstein, who is charged with pushing 32-year-old Kendra
Webdale to her death in front of a subway last January, was a
textbook example of how New York state's policies can threaten not
only the former patients left to fend for themselves, but also the
public at large. As reported by Michael Winerip in The New York
Times Magazine on Sunday, Goldstein had attacked at least 13 other
people in the previous two years and had compiled a 3,500-page
psychiatric file that indicated ``high risk for violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein kept asking to be hospitalized. But the system, which
is fixated on getting people out of institutions in the cheapest
way possible, kept spitting him back out onto the streets. He wound
up in a rooming house, and when he stopped taking his medication
and going to his assigned mental health clinic, he was sent a form
letter warning that his case was going to be closed. Shortly
thereafter, he wound up in the subway station where he is accused
of pushing Ms. Webdale to her death.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki administration officials are not allowed to talk about
patients' case histories, but they note that New York spends more
than $4 billion a year on mental health services. Nevertheless,
there are about 5,000 fewer beds in state psychiatric hospitals now
than when Pataki took office, and only a few hundred additional
community slots that provide both shelter and round-the-clock
supervision. Even though all former mental patients do not need
that kind of expensive care, the numbers suggest that there is a
large gap.
</P>
<P>
   The state is now down to its last 6,000 mental hospital
patients, many of whom have criminal records, histories of violence
or long periods of institutionalization. Pataki should halt further
bed reductions until he can assure the state that the people being
sent back to their communities will get the supervision they need.
He should also expand the disappointingly puny program he proposed
to provide new housing for the chronic mentally ill in New York
City, and demonstrate concern for patients who leave the rapidly
shrinking state psychiatric hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, many of them wind up in subsidized beds in glorified
flophouses, with no one to check to make sure that they take their
medication and go to their appointments with a therapist. The
results are an increase in the number of delusional homeless people
on the streets and in the shelters _ and a tragedy like the one
that befell Ms. Webdale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
