<HEADLINE>
3 VENTURE CAPITAL FIRMS TAKE STAKE IN DATEK ONLINE HOLDINGS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three prominent venture capital firms, including one financed by
Paul G. Allen, a co-founder of the Microsoft Corp., have agreed to
jointly purchase a minority stake in the Datek Online Holdings
Corp. for a total of $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Datek owns the nation's fourth-largest online brokerage service
and is the parent of Island ECN, a computer-based stock-trading
system that is seeking regulatory approval to operate as the
nation's newest stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The investment, to be formally announced Tuesday, is to be made
by Vulcan Ventures, Allen's venture capital organization in
Bellevue, Wash.; TA Associates, a Boston-based venture fund whose
investors include major university endowments and corporate pension
funds, and Group Arnault of Paris, the private holding company run
by the French businessman Bernard Arnault. Group Arnault, which has
recently become active as an investor in online commerce, controls
LVMH Moeet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, the luxury-goods merchandiser.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, arranged by Credit Suisse First Boston, calls for
Group Arnault to contribute $170 million, with TA Associates
investing $75 million and Vulcan contributing $55 million.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Datek nor the venture capital firms would disclose the
exact size of the minority stake being purchased. But Kenneth T.
Schiciano, a principal with TA Associates, said the funds'
investment ``values the company in excess of $1 billion,'' which
suggests that less than a third of Datek's equity is changing
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Edward J. Nicoll, president of Datek Online Holdings, said that
the company's six-member board of directors would be expanded to
nine members to accommodate representatives from each of the three
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The money will help finance an expanded marketing program,
improved computer technology and recruitment of new personnel,
Nicoll said. ``This is a transformative event for our firm,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Datek's online brokerage service was fined and
sanctioned by Federal regulators for using as much as $50 million
from customer accounts to settle other customers' trades and to pay
company bills. The company said it had improved its financial
controls since the incidents cited by regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Island ECN has applied for regulatory permission to
operate as a stock exchange, an expensive undertaking that will
require it to develop some way of policing its own operations and
members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
