<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-KING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW KING OF JORDAN ASSERTS SYRIA WANTS PEACE WITH ISRAEL
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ King Abdullah of Jordan, ending his first visit to
America since ascending the throne, said Monday he believed Syria
was ready to make peace with Israel and that once Israel's new
government was installed, there would be ``quick movement'' toward
peace.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, the key to a stable, peaceful and prosperous
Middle East remained in reinforcing peace between Israel and its
Palestinian neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have peace with Syria at the expense of Israelis and
Palestinians without having their problems solved will only create
more of a difficulty,'' the king warned.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old king discussed the need for peace and economic
development in the region and at home in Jordan in a meeting with
the editorial board of The New York Times. He spoke on his second
day of a visit to New York and the final day of his 10-day trip to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was was ``very happy'' with the election results in
Israel, in which the Labor Party leader, Ehud Barak, scored an
impressive victory, the king said that the contest was not just an
election of an individual, but a referendum on whether Israel
should continue the peace process. ``This is a new beginning,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Syrian leader, Hafez al-Assad, had resisted many
previous peace overtures from Israel, the atmosphere in Damascus
had changed, Abdullah asserted. ``I think Syria realizes that it's
missed the boat on several occasions and now here's an opportunity
to start again,'' the king said. ``And I don't think that another
opportunity will come up again.''
</P>
<P>
   During his recent visit to Damascus, he said, Syria was
``particularly forthcoming'' in its desire to move forward with
Israel, as were other Arab states. ``The Arab world wants peace
with Israel,'' Abdullah declared.
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked whether Barak would give back to Syria the
Golan Heights, which Israel has occupied since the 1967 war, the
king said he usually replied to that question with a question:
``Isn't it better to give up the Golan and conquer the rest of the
Arab world? You give up on one side but there is so much to gain on
the other.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he added, while it was easy to seek a ``quick
fix, or a quick reward'' by concentrating on Syria at the expense
of the Israeli-Palestinian issue, focus had to be maintained on
resolving the ``original'' conflict, he said. ``You can very easily
be blinded by the prize that a Syria-Israeli peace might afford and
forget about the original problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an impassioned appeal shortly before he headed back to his
capital, Amman, the king also urged the United States and its NATO
allies to stay the course in Kosovo and insure that the refugees
can return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are doing this not just for Kosovo; you're doing this for
the world,'' said the king, who has spent the last 10 days seeking
economic help for his country and political support in Washington
and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Much depends on how the Balkans conflict is resolved, he said.
On Monday and earlier in his visit, he said that how the conflict
in Kosovo ended would be an indicator of American resolve
throughout the world and would ``set the rules'' for other
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming king in February after the death of his father,
King Hussein, who had been admired in Washington, Abdullah has
tried to ease tensions with countries with which Jordan has had
occasionally tense relations, including Syria and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   President Mohammad Khatami of Iran, Abdullah said, had ``time on
his side'' and was ``breaking down barriers'' and creating a
``sense of hope for the moderates.'' But, he added, toning down
some of his earlier optimism about his turbulent region, moderating
Iran ``might take a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The young king, who was raised largely in England and who was
partly schooled in the United States, comfortably fielded often
skeptical questions at meetings Monday and Tuesday with Jewish
organizations, policy groups and the news media. Reiterating his
view that economic development was key to a politically stable,
peaceful region, he vowed that Jordan would reform and liberalize
its economy to attract foreign and domestic investment within two
years.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to have succeeded in winning many American hearts and
minds, and was hopeful that he had made some progress in securing
the debt relief which he said Jordan desperately needed. ``This is
our one big chance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After a dinner on Sunday night, former Secretary of State Henry
A. Kissinger, who spent years mediating peace agreements between
Arabs and Israelis, said he was ``very favorably impressed'' by
Abdullah, who he said exhibited ``a certain strategic sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Salberg, the chairman of the Conference of Presidents of
Major American Jewish Organizations, with whom the king met Monday
morning, said King Abdullah was a ``very open, direct person who
I'm certain will advance peace.'' And, Salberg added, ``I believe
he's tough enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
