u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PATAKI-BUSH-ART-NY     05-24 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-BUSH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI, LAYING OWN DREAMS ASIDE, ENDORSES BUSH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gov. George Pataki on Monday became the 16th
Republican governor to endorse the candidacy of Gov. George W.
Bush, the Texas Republican who is viewed by many party leaders as
the front-runner for the presidential nomination. With his
announcement, Pataki effectively abandoned his own flirtation with
running in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki made his endorsement at an elaborately staged rally at a
midtown Manhattan ballroom, surrounded by Republican leaders who
had traveled from across the state to join the governor for what
had been advertised as a major political announcement. For all the
mystery Pataki had attached to the event, it came as something less
than a surprise, given Bush's already broad support among national
Republicans, and seemed unlikely to significantly alter the state
of play on the presidential field.
</P>
<P>
   Bush listened by a satellite hookup from Austin, Texas, as
Pataki described Bush as the leader in a class of Republican
governors who had pursued the party's policies of reducing
government regulation, taxes and welfare rolls. In effect, Pataki
applied to Bush the same rationale he had offered for himself in
raising his own national profile earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an inclusive Republican who has reached out with his
doctrine of compassionate conservatism and in the process built a
party that has supported him with overwhelming votes from the
Hispanic community, from women, from African-Americans across
Texas,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement at the Sheraton New York Hotel and Towers was
organized as a political show of force, intended to portray Pataki
to Bush as a powerful force in New York politics. Pataki has left
little doubt that he would like to be considered as a vice
presidential candidate by Bush, though he declined to address the
question directly on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's advisers did their best to stimulate interest in the
event. Blue spotlights formed a glowing backdrop for Pataki as he
spoke; Bush's face was beamed onto a huge video screen. Guards
barred reporters who arrived late, apparently out of concern that
they might distract from the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the absence of true drama in the event was evident the
moment Pataki took the stage, notwithstanding the 23 video cameras
that recorded the event. As the governor began to talk, state Sen.
Roy Goodman, R-Manhattan, flipped open his cell phone and began a
whispered conversation from his perch near Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding the turnout, the absence of one major Republican
_ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York City, who has signaled that he
is likely to endorse Bush as well _ was evidence of the divisions
that remain between the governor and Giuliani. By contrast, U.S.
Rep. Rick Lazio, R-Long Island, who has said he will challenge
Giuliani if he seeks his party's Senate nomination next year, was
afforded a prominent spot on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he was not concerned that he had not been invited.
``I think the focus was on trying to get as much attention for the
presidential race as possible. And it obviously wasn't about a
possible Senate race or anything else, so I have no problem with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki ignored questions shouted by reporters about whether
Giuliani had been invited. His political adviser, Zenia Mucha,
responded to the same question by saying: ``Who? Pardon me? I can't
hear you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
