<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITESSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VITESSE TO ACQUIRE `NETWORK-ON-A-CHIP' FIRM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMARILLO, Calif. _ In an effort to increase its presence in the
growing Internet processor market, computer chip maker Vitesse
Semiconductor Inc. said it will acquire a small Northern California
firm for $65 million.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of high-speed, gallium arsenide chips used in the
telecommunications industry said it will buy Santa Clara-based
XaQti Corp., a 35-employee maker of ``network-on-a-chip'' products
used to direct the flow of data across the Internet. The purchase
will be financed entirely with stock of Vitesse, based in Camarillo
in Ventura County northwest of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts greeted news of the merger positively, saying the
companies' strengths should complement each other. ``I like the
acquisition,'' said Arun Veerappan, an analyst at BancBoston
Robertson Stephens. ``It's a step in the right direction for
Vitesse.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors also appear pleased, bidding up Vitesse stock $1.375,
or 2.7 percent, to $52.625 on a day when the technology-heavy
Nasdaq exchange fell 66.54 to 2453.66.
</P>
<P>
   The XaQti purchase will be accounted for as a pooling of
interests and is expected to have no material impact on Vitesse's
financial results, the company said. The transaction is expected to
be completed by the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at both companies said the acquisition should broaden
their potential customer base. Vitesse had 1998 sales of $175
million, mostly to the telecom industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great deal of synergy in technology between Vitesse
and XaQti,'' Alak Deb, co-founder and chief technology officer of
XaQti said in a written statement accompanying the announcement.
``The merged companies will bring together complementary core
competencies to develop high-performance and cost-effective data
communications solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Potential new customers include Internet backbone companies and
Internet service providers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990524.0484 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9677 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-SCHOOL-AUDIT-COX     05-24 1752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-SCHOOL-AUDIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio school system to react drastically to unfavorable audit
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dayton public school officials will seek to close
as many as five schools, lay off an undetermined number of
employees and privatize some transportation services to respond to
a state audit that estimated the district could be as much as $14
million in the red within five weeks, school officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The ``performance audit'' conducted by the state auditor's
office revealed the extent of the district's financial shortfalls,
criticized school officials for earlier financial projections that
auditors concluded were far too rosy and detailed sloppy
record-keeping by the district. The audit also concluded the
district spends a disproportionate amount of money on
administration and other support services at the expense of
instruction. The report's 170 recommendations, if implemented,
could result in potential annual savings of $25 million to $42
million, Auditor of State James Petro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This school district's financial condition is treacherous,''
said Petro, who announced the audit's findings Monday in a joint
news conference with Superintendent James Williams. If no action is
taken, the school district could face an accumulated deficit of
$39.8 million in four years, Petro warned. The district's annual
budget is about $184 million.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he did not get good information from the
treasurer's office and should not be blamed for the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not taking this beating,'' the superintendent said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted the shortfall could rise to $19 million without cuts in
the district's $184 million general fund budget.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning audit results shocked schools administrators, board
members and union officials, who wondered how a district thought to
be in good financial shape could end up with such a huge deficit.
Board members ended the day snipping at each other during a secret
session some deemed inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   The report on the Dayton public schools is one of 21 such
``performance audits'' Petro's office is conducting on Ohio's
largest-enrollment school districts at the request of state
legislators. The Ohio General Assembly in 1997 mandated performance
audits for the 21 largest districts that share a special allocation
of state funding, and Petro's office has found similar financial
shortfalls and practices to criticize at other school districts. In
Cincinnati, for example, Petro's audit projected a deficit of
$260.3 million within five years and recommended $53 million in
annual cuts to teaching staff, transportation, technology and
facilities. In Parma, a district about half Dayton's size, a
performance audit projected a $45 million deficit by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, Dayton school officials must develop an
``economy and efficiency plan'' within six months to respond to the
performance audit. Williams said he will appoint business leaders
and other community members to a task force to help craft that
plan. The superintendent said he expects the efficiency plan to
embrace some of the 170 recommendations while challenging others.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams isn't waiting for the task force report before
taking action. Although the performance audit calls for the
district simply to analyze building capacity and consider whether
school closings are justified, Williams said he would recommend
closing five school buildings as a first step toward erasing the
projected deficit. The superintendent said he has identified the
five buildings targeted for closure, but he declined to name them.
</P>
<P>
   Board President Ed Hickman said he believed the board would look
favorably on Williams' proposal. The school closings, Hickman said,
``will have to happen'' because of declines in enrollment and
steeper declines on the horizon due in part to competition from
charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he would also recommend the board cut 20
administrative positions, hire another firm to bus more than 1,600
private- and parochial-school students the district now transports,
and conduct a review of staffing needs among the teaching and
clerical ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The audit suggested that the school district could trim between
590 and 744 jobs by bringing its staffing levels to a level that
compares with similar districts. And the audit said the district
could eliminate up to 41 teaching positions if all teachers were to
teach the amount of minutes called for in their union contract with
the school district, a finding that appears in similar fashion in
other performance audits around the state as well.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Fulwiler Shawhan _ president of the Dayton Education
Association, the union representing the district's teachers _
called the audit's projected deficits ``devastating,'' in part
because they came as a surprise. Board president Hickman
acknowledged the size of the potential deficit did ``sneak up on''
him and fellow board members.
</P>
<P>
   Shawhan said school officials should ensure that budget cuts are
made in a way that has the least impact on students in the
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he wanted to spare teachers of kindergarten
through third grade from any cuts, noting the school district's
announced goal of having a student-to-teacher ratio of 15 to 1 in
those grades. That would focus any cuts to the teaching staff to
grades 4-12, though Williams also noted he would have to negotiate
such details with the teachers' union. The DEA's current contract
with the school district expires June 30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent said he would like to close and consolidate
offices now located in the former Roosevelt High School to save
money and would use enrollment data as a primary criteria to target
school buildings for closure. WHIO-TV Channel 7 reported the five
targeted schools are the Longfellow Center, Jane Addams Elementary
School, Residence Park Elementary School, Whittier Elementary
School and Fairport Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the schools targeted for closure might be
converted into charter schools, which would operate privately and
would be free of some state rules and restrictions in return for
improving academic achievement. Williams said he would seek to
invite community groups to apply for the school board's approval to
convert the schools to charters.
</P>
<P>
   Declining enrollment is to blame for much of the pessimistic
projections, Williams said. While the district has lost on average
a few hundred students each year the last few years, to about
26,000, school officials estimate they'll lose another 2,000 to
3,000 students next year, as charter schools take a bite out of the
district's enrollment base.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the district has been slow to respond to the
enrollment projections.
</P>
<P>
   The performance audit found some school district's practices
worthy of praise, including its development of a strategic reform
plan, which has been used as a model for other districts in Ohio;
for pursuing lower prices for goods and services through a
purchasing co-op; and for providing comprehensive training for
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   But the overall tone of the inch-thick, 448-page report is
critical. For example, auditors said:
</P>
<P>
   The school district supplied inaccurate and unreliable
information to state officials' education database, reporting no
salary for the superintendent in 1997-98 and reporting the annual
salaries of many professional positions in two digits such as $28
and $29.
</P>
<P>
   School officials furnished state officials with three different
figures to reflect the number of full-time-equivalent employees
ranging from 3,317 to 3,929. The information was ``inconsistent and
could not be fully explained, which raises questions about the
district's ability to truly manage and budget for their largest
expenditures.''
</P>
<P>
   The district's underestimation of 1998 salaries and benefits by
$4 million to $5 million resulted in the school district canceling
some bill payments to help avoid a year-ending deficit.
``Departments will be expected to pay for prior-year obligations
out of current-year budget. These situations make it more difficult
to ascertain the true financial condition of the district,'' the
audit said
</P>
<P>
   The school district's transportation department ``is not
operating effectively or efficiently,'' with higher costs compared
to other districts.
</P>
<P>
   School officials attempted to provide auditors with an updated
financial projections in March, but auditors did not incorporate it
into the report ``because certain projected amounts are unrealistic
and are not supported by written assumptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the performance audit took the school district to task
for sloppy record-keeping and oversights, it also included a
reference to one of the Dayton area's largest employers as ``AT&AMP;T
Global Information.'' AT&AMP;T spun off the former NCR, which dropped
its Global moniker in favor of its original name, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton School Board met later Monday afternoon, and the
Dayton Daily News protested when the board voted unanimously to go
into a secret meeting to discuss ``personnel'' _ after the district
said the meeting would be open.
</P>
<P>
   Before the meeting. Hickman had said the board planned to meet
in closed session not to discuss personnel, but to talk about what
the district needs to do as a result of the audit. The Daily News
complained, citing the state's open meeting law, and the schools
said the meeting would be open after all. But shortly after the
start of the 5 p.m. meeting, the board went into secret session.
The closed session lasted about an hour, and then the board meeting
was quickly adjourned.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Nellie Terrell, who requested the session, later
said the board discussed the ``behavioral problems of our
superintendent.''
</P>
<P>
   Hickman acknowledged that the members argued about whether they
should be meeting secretly to discuss the audit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that this happened,'' he said. ``I'm praying
to God the board gets its act together. (We should) make sure we
focus on this (deficit), instead of some little nitty gritty that
doesn't amount to a hill of beans.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the board said it went into executive session to
discuss employment matters, but at the end of the five-hour meeting
said it met to prepare for Monday morning's press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
