<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-GUNMAKERS-500(2     05-24 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GUNMAKERS-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA CITIES TO SUE GUN MAKERS OVER SALES METHODS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mich., Ill., N.Y., Mass., Ga., S.C., Fla.)   (jw) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two groups of California cities, led by Los Angeles and San
Francisco, will file suit against gun manufacturers on Wednesday in
a novel use of a sweeping state business law that government
officials and gun-control advocates hope will force the
manufacturers to change the way they market firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits will accuse the manufacturers of providing weapons
to disreputable dealers, and to dealers in areas with lax controls,
knowing that these people were likely to sell guns to criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Nine other cities, plus Wayne County, Mich., have already filed
suit against the gun industry since November, but gun-control
advocates say they expect the California lawsuits to be especially
threatening to the gun makers because of the number of cities
involved, their size and the broad nature of the state
business-practices law under which they are bringing suit.
</P>
<P>
   The California business-practices law allows cities and
individuals to sue over accusations of broadly defined ``unlawful,
unfair and deceptive business acts and practices'' and to collect
large fines and a share of the defendants' profits.
</P>
<P>
   James Hahn, the city attorney for Los Angeles, said of his
city's lawsuit, ``We think it sends a big, important message to the
gun industry that there are a number of cities in California that
have had to deal with the cost of human suffering from guns and
that we are united.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Hahn said, ``It's not about the money; it's about changing
the way they do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Louise Renne, the city attorney of San Francisco, concurred,
saying that what made the California lawsuits different from the
previous ones was that the goal of Los Angeles and San Francisco
``is not so much money but reform of the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Delfay, the president of the Sporting Arms and Ammunition
Manufacturers Institute, the largest gun industry trade
association, said evidence for the accusation of deliberately
supplying guns to the illegal market was ``nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how you could do it if you wanted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Delfay, whose group was to be named as a defendant in both
suits, along with 28 manufacturers and distributors and two other
trade organizations, said: ``There is no way for a manufacturer to
know a specific firearm is going to be used in crime. If there was,
I'm certain all manufacturers would sacrifice that sale in a New
York minute.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry would be more threatened by financial penalties
than the tobacco industry was to similar threats because the gun
industry is much smaller. Sales of handguns, rifles, shotguns and
ammunition combined were only $1.4 billion in 1997, compared with
sales of $48 billion for the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   Several cities have felt that while they have been blocked from
getting meaningful gun control in Congress and state legislatures
by politicians friendly to the National Rifle Association, they
would have a much better chance in court in front of an urban jury
familiar with the costs of gun violence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With the experience of the states' multibillion-dollar
settlement with the tobacco companies in mind, the cities feel they
do not have to actually win a lawsuit but rather bring enough suits
to threaten the gun manufacturers and make them ready to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Rand, a lawyer for the Violence Policy Center in
Washington, a group that does gun-control research and advocacy,
said the California lawsuits were significant because ``these are
the biggest cities in the biggest state, and for the first time a
group of cities are coordinating.'' Moreover, Ms. Rand said, ``They
will have a big advantage because the California law is very broad,
a kind of super consumers protection law.''
</P>
<P>
   James McCall, a professor at the Hastings College of Law in San
Francisco, part of the University of California system, said the
law being employed by Los Angeles and San Francisco had become a
sweeping tool that had been broadly interpreted by the California
Supreme Court and provided for judges to award large amounts of
money. But the attack on the gun makers is a novel application of
the law, McCall said.
</P>
<P>
   To make their case, he said, the cities will need to show a
violation of state or local law and prove a conspiracy to sell guns
to criminals and juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento, Oakland, and Berkeley are expected to join in the
San Francisco suit, to be filed in state court in San Francisco,
and Compton and Inglewood are expected to join with Los Angeles in
filing suit there, officials said. San Diego and Long Beach may
join in the Los Angeles suit, and some counties in Northern
California have discussed joining the San Francisco suit.
</P>
<P>
   The suits charge that the gun makers have created a distribution
system to deliberately ``insulate themselves from any
responsibility'' for whom the guns end up with, Hahn said.
``Basically, the gun makers supply the illegal underground market
by flooding the legal market with far more guns than it can
absorb.''
</P>
<P>
   This view, similar to accusations made in lawsuits by Chicago
and Detroit is based on information compiled in recent years by the
federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms as it has traced
the flow of guns used in crimes back to the manufacturers and then
the wholesalers and down to the dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The firearms agency has found that large numbers of guns used in
crimes in cities like New York, Boston or Chicago, with restrictive
gun-control laws, were originally sold in states with lax
gun-control laws like Georgia, South Carolina or Florida to illegal
gun traffickers. Many of these guns used in crimes, perhaps half,
are sold new in stores to criminals or straw purchasers acting on
their behalf, and gun control advocates and many law-enforcement
officials now believe the gun makers must be to some degree aware
of what is happening.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for this belief is that when the firearms agency
traces a crime gun, it goes back to the manufacturer to start the
tracking process, a clear clue to the company that the gun has been
involved in questionable acts.
</P>
<P>
   The California suits also charge that the gun makers have failed
to incorporate sufficient safety devices in their products, like
child safety locks or gun technology that would only allow the
legal owner to fire the gun. Similar accusations have been made in
lawsuits by other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Under the business law, the cities cannot collect damages, Hahn
said, but they can collect fines, of $2,500 per count, and
``disgorgement'' of profits. This could amount to millions of
dollars, he said, because the cities say each gun sold illegally is
a separate count.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
