u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-DOCS-UNION-NYT     05-24 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-DOCS-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NLRB DENIES BID BY DOCTORS TO UNIONIZE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a setback to doctors' efforts to unionize, the National Labor
Relations Board's regional office in Philadelphia ruled Monday that
more than 500 New Jersey doctors working for a health maintenance
organization were independent contractors _ not employees _ and
therefore could not form a union.
</P>
<P>
   As labor unions have sought to persuade thousands of doctors
nationwide to unionize, the New Jersey case was widely viewed as an
important test case because it concerned whether doctors
contracting with an HMO should be considered employees and thus
have the right to form unions.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second time that the doctors had made their case to
the labor board's Philadelphia branch. But last August, after the
local board rejected the doctors' arguments, the national board
overturned that ruling and ordered a hearing to get a ``fuller
picture'' of the relationships between doctors and HMOs. It was the
first time the board had heard testimony on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The union the doctors sought to join, the United Food and
Commercial Workers, argued that the doctors were employees of the
HMO, the Amerihealth Corporation of New Jersey, because Amerihealth
controlled many of the details of their work, such as the maximum
wait for patients, the size of their waiting room and whether
patients should undergo surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting the union's argument, the labor board's regional
director, Dorothy L. Moore-Duncan, concluded that the doctors were
independent businessmen because they ran their own practices, were
free to contract with other HMOs and worked at their own offices.
In addition, she noted that Amerihealth had little control over the
doctors because its patients represented just a small fraction _
normally 4 percent _ of their overall practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physicians lack the close economic relations and
integration with Amerihealth that would support a finding of
employee status,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   With Monday's decision, Ms. Moore-Duncan rejected a petition by
Local 56 of the United Food and Commercial Workers to hold an
election in which 515 primary care physicians and specialists in
Atlantic and Cape May Counties were to vote on whether to join the
union.
</P>
<P>
   Robert F. O'Brien, the union's lawyer, said the union was still
debating whether to appeal the decision to the labor board's main
office in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision contains pages and pages of facts that strongly
point to these doctors' employee status,'' O'Brien said, ``but then
it wrongly concludes that they're entrepreneurs, which flies in the
face of the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Several officials from other unions said the Amerihealth
doctors' situation represented an unfavorable set of circumstances
for a test case. These officials said unions would have been better
off to have asked the national labor board to examine a case
involving an HMO that maintained far more control over their
doctors than Amerihealth did and accounted for far more _ perhaps
50 percent _ of the doctors' caseload.
</P>
<P>
   G. Fred DiBona Jr., chairman of Amerihealth, said in a statement
that Monday's ruling ``clarifies a question of considerable
importance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The NLRB decision agrees with virtually every point we have
made over the past 18 months,'' DiBona said, ``including the facts
the doctors own their own businesses, compete with each other,
contract with a large number of insurers, make their own hours and
are the sole beneficiaries of their successes.''
</P>
<P>
   But the United Food and Commercial Workers repeatedly insisted
that the doctors were tantamount to part-time employees because the
HMO controlled so many details of their practice. For instance,
Amerihealth requires that the doctors' offices maintain certain
records, be open a certain number of hours each week and allow
visits by Amerihealth inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moore-Duncan concluded that the doctors' extensive
independence from Amerihealth outweighed the amount of control the
HMO had over them.
</P>
<P>
   Labor experts estimate that 35,000 of the nation's 700,000
doctors are in unions. The recent acceleration of efforts to
unionize doctors have focused on salaried staff physicians at
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, when private-practice physicians have sought to
bargain collectively with HMOs over reimbursements or other
matters, the doctors have been accused of violating antitrust laws,
charged with being independent businessmen conspiring to restrain
trade. Many private-practice doctors are urging Congress to enact
an antitrust exemption that would let them bargain with HMOs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
