</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-POOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Governor likely to sign colonias bill
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Senate on Monday approved and sent to
the governor a bill that would help the poorest of the state's
poor, who live in substandard border-region neighborhoods called
colonias, obtain modern water and sewer services. The measure also
would crack down on the development of new neighborhoods without
basic sanitation.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, who shaped the legislation through his
secretary of state and border liaison, Elton Bomer, indicated he
would sign it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very strong piece of legislation,'' Bush said. ``It
will give the state more tools to stop the spread of colonias and
improve conditions for people living there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had directed Bomer to make colonias his top priority after
a series of articles last year in the Austin American-Statesman
drew attention to the slow pace and other problems with the
water-sewer program. In some cases, households had not been hooked
up to water and sewer lines installed years earlier. And in one
colonia in the Lower Rio Grande Valley, a toddler fell into an
outhouse and drowned at a time when local government officials were
squabbling over which city or water district would serve that
neighborhood. The measure builds on a 10-year-old, $579 million
sanitation program financed jointly by the federal government and
the state. It injects a modest amount of additional money _
$331,000 a year for a six-person team of troubleshooters _ into the
program and grants new enforcement powers, planning tools,
regulatory oversight and flexibility to state and local agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Senators, who concurred with minor changes by the House, said
the bill offers new hope to the roughly 400,000 people living in
colonias. These neighborhoods, which span the Texas-Mexico border
from El Paso to Brownsville, constitute the largest concentration
of people living without basic sanitation in the United States.
Despite the troubling conditions, the residents have a strong ethic
of home ownership and often build their houses one room at a time
as they earn money from migrant labor, retail positions,
construction and other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For too long, colonia residents have put up with substandard
water, sewer, electricity and other services,'' said Sen. David
Sibley, R-Waco, vice chairman of the Special Committee on Border
Affairs. ``I commend the authors of this bill for their leadership
in passing legislation that will continue to improve the standard
of living for these hardworking Texans.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the third time that state lawmakers have enacted major
legislation concerning colonias. First, in 1989, they set the
water-sewer aid program in motion. In 1995, they tightened
development rules to curb the construction of new colonias.
</P>
<P>
   The latest bill reflects bipartisan cooperation between a
Republican governor and Democratic Senate and House members
representing the border region. The primary author was Sen. Eddie
Lucio Jr., D-Brownsville, chairman of the border panel. Democratic
Sens. Judith Zaffirini of Laredo, Carlos Truan of Corpus Christi
and Eliot Shapleigh of El Paso co-authored the bill, and Rep. Henry
Cuellar, D-Laredo, sponsored the measure in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think never before in history, in Texas, have we witnessed
such bipartisan and nonpartisan support for colonias,'' Bomer said.
``I expect a good helping of improvements for people along the
border who don't have access to water and sewer lines.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks and months, Bomer and the Texas Water
Development Board, which administers the program, have launched new
initiatives intended to hook up thousands of households to water
and sewer lines.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph K.M. Haurwitz writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
