<HEADER>
A9692 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-WILDFIRE-COX     05-24 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-WILDFIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wildfire blankets coast with smoke
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A behemoth, 12,000-acre wildfire burning
in the far reaches of western Palm Beach County smothered three
counties in smoke Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The fire, ignited by lightning Friday in the northern half of
the Rotenberger wildlife preserve, quickly spread from just 1,200
acres about 11:30 a.m. Sunday when Division of Forestry rangers
were first called to battle it, said Dave Utley, chief of the DOF's
Everglades District. With winds blowing from the west, a steely,
gray blanket of smoke and hot, dry air cloaked the coast from
Delray Beach to Fort Pierce for most of Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a fire that large, it puts up huge volumes of
smoke and when you've got the wind direction that's favorable _ or
not favorable to you all _ you're going to feel the effects,''
Utley said. ``Unfortunately, the wind direction is interfering with
the tactics we'd like to use to extinguish it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire in the 27,000-acre preserve went unnoticed for two days
because winds from the east fanned smoke west into uninhabited
wilderness. But on Monday, winds swung to the west, sending rolling
clouds toward civilization and alarming hundreds of residents on
the Treasure Coast who still anxiously watch the skies following
terrifying fires last month that destroyed 43 homes in a single
night.
</P>
<P>
   One Martin County dispatcher logged 142 calls during a single
hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is still concerned and I don't blame them,'' said St.
Lucie Fire District spokesman Lt. Ron Parrish.
</P>
<P>
   Winds shifted when a high pressure ridge in the Atlantic drifted
south, the National Weather Service said. Usually, the ridge rides
further north over Bermuda during the summer and blows sea breezes
along the east coast. Meteorologists even have a name for it: the
Bermuda High. It is this ridge that creates our all too familiar
soggy summer trade winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not in the summer yet, so it's not unusual to get
the ridge to the south,'' said meteorologist Tom Warner. ``It's
just a stroke of bad luck, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The winds will continue from the west through Wednesday, bad
news for rangers who had hoped to protect a string of electrical
lines near the fire's northern edge that supply power to the west
coast, Utley said. The fire is burning about two miles from the
towers, an uncomfortable, but not yet dangerous distance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still two miles from the lines, but there's no break that
would prevent it from burning down to the lines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the fire strikes the energized lines, it would act like a
circuit breaker, triggering ``a blackout somewhere.'' Utley said
the fire, fueled by saw grass and trees, is surrounded on three
sides by canals that should help contain it: the Miami Canal to the
east, a levee on the Hendry County line to the west and the L-4
canal on the south.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday and Monday, eight rangers on all-terrain vehicles tried
to control the flames, but the fire was burning too intensely. If
winds shift to the southeast, rangers will use a helicopter from
Fort Meyers, loaded with explosive plastic balls, to ignite
backfires, Utley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually this time of year, we get lightning strikes that burn
a couple of acres and go out. But with the dryness of the
vegetation and soil,'' he said, ``it's going to keep going until it
runs out of fuel.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, forestry officials worried that spring would
plunge the state, still recovering from wildfires that scorched a
half million acres last year, into a dangerous drought because of
La Nina conditions. In recent weeks, rain has increased but much of
the state, particularly wilderness areas in the heart of South
Florida, remain parched and ready to ignite. In addition to Port
St. Lucie's April fires, 3,611 fires have burned 274,581 acres
across the state.
</P>
<P>
   A 600-acre fire grew tenfold Monday in the Osceola National
Forest and jumped a highway into the 400,000-acre Okefenokee Swamp.
</P>
<P>
   After frantic callers insisted the Treasure Coast was burning
Monday, the Martin County Sheriff's Office sent a helicopter to
search out flames, Parrish said. Only two relatively small fires _
a 100-acre fire in the western part of Martin County and one about
36 acres on the Indian River and St. Lucie counties line _ were
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Still, health officials in Palm Beach, Martin and St. Lucie
counties urged people with respiratory problems to stay indoors
with their air-conditioners on. Meteorologists predict the smoke
will continue today, with the wind blowing at about 10 mph from the
west.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Staletovich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. Brian Crecente and Jill Taylor contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
