<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS SWEEP HAWKS AMID CHANTS FOR THEIR COACH
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Knicks' remarkable transformation from a
team teetering on collapse a month ago to a group with a chance to
turn its season into something special continued Monday night as
they emphatically claimed Game 4 to sweep the Atlanta Hawks and
take their second-round playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   Relentless in their barrage of the thin Hawks, the Knicks eased
away for a 79-66 victory and earned the right to play the Indiana
Pacers in the Eastern Conference finals, with Game 1 on Sunday at
Market Square Arena in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Chants of ``Jeff Van Gundy'' filled the Garden in the last three
minutes of the game, a show of support for a coach who has received
no assurance that he will be back next season. And yet, this is the
first time the Knicks have been in a conference finals since 1994
and the third time in the 90s. The eighth-seeded Knicks, who did
not clinch a playoff spot until the second-to-last game of the
season, were led by Allan Houston (19 points), Patrick Ewing (17)
and Latrell Sprewell (11), against the worn and frustrated Hawks,
led by Steve Smith (14 points), Dikembe Mutombo (11) and Mookie
Blaylock (7).
</P>
<P>
   With five days off before the next round, Ewing's sore Achilles'
tendon will have a chance to rest before he faces the Pacers, who
eliminated the Knicks in the second round last year and needed just
five games to do so. After Ewing missed four months after wrist
surgery, he tried to save the Knicks by gallantly returning in Game
2 but failed in his comeback attempt.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Knicks are a much more balanced team.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, who came out and treated the Hawks as if they were a
sheet of paper to charge through in order to get to the Pacers,
were the aggressors from the beginning and continued their assault
the instant the second unit, led by Sprewell, Marcus Camby and
Chris Childs, came into the game.
</P>
<P>
   They were an intimidating group. And the sagging Hawks had to
tremble just a bit as Sprewell and his partners turned steals into
dunks and misses into fast-break opportunities that resulted in a
48-37 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   That edge was not squandered when Houston and Ewing started the
third quarter with a flurry of jumpers and helped put the Knicks
ahead, 66-51, to start the fourth. Ewing was making a mockery out
of Mutombo's wingspan by floating jumpers over his college friend.
</P>
<P>
   Everything that made up the Hawks' personality _ stingy defense,
Mutombo's menacing presence, deadly 3-point shooting _ was
vanishing beneath the determined Knicks, who quickly built a 56-40
lead with 7:33 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   That lead increased to 65-47 with 2:00 left in the third
quarter, and the chants of ``We want Reggie, we want Reggie'' were
ringing out in a crowd savoring the opportunity to see Reggie
Miller in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks played like they wanted him. Instead of being
complacent with their 3-0 lead in the series, the night began with
Houston and Charlie Ward popping 3-pointers and Ewing finding a
groove, which escaped him in Game 3, by hitting 5 of his first 8
shots, bringing misery to his crestfallen Mutombo with every high
arching baseline jumper.
</P>
<P>
   After the Knicks grabbed a 25-18 first-quarter lead, the old
then made way for the new. Sprewell tore off his warm-ups and
stirred up a crowd somewhat bored by the Knicks' dominance of the
Hawks. Sprewell changed all that when he stepped in front of a pass
to Smith and darted to the basket with a two-handed dunk and
two-fisted flex as he ran back down the floor with 6:50 left in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Fearlessly, Sprewell just preyed on the Hawks' interior defense,
flying inside to either score on a dunk or draw a foul. He went to
the free-throw line six times in the first half and left Mutombo
shaking his head at all the foul trouble he had found himself in
courtesy of Sprewell and an aggressive Camby.
</P>
<P>
   Though hampered with back spasms, Camby stuck his neck out on a
couple of occasions and even absorbed a flagrant foul on his way to
the basket with 10 minutes left in the first half. He hit two free
throws to give the Knicks a 29-18 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the ragged Hawks, depending on the will and desire of Smith,
came back and cut the Knicks' lead to 6 points after a foolish play
by Childs. As Mutombo went up for a dunk, Childs wrapped him up and
pulled him to the floor. This might have been Childs' comeback to
the elbow he took from Mutombo on April 9, a blow that knocked out
a front tooth.
</P>
<P>
   He vowed revenge at that time. He didn't need a hard foul to get
it the way the Knicks were blasting away at the Hawks. Still,
Childs was called for the foul and a technical that resulted in 3
points for the Hawks and pulled them to within 6, at 38-32, with
4:33 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the Knicks these days, they had a feisty counterpunch
in them. Childs came back and hit a 19-foot jumper. Three
possessions later, he swiped a steal and was off on a fast-break
layup that broke the Hawks down and gave the Knicks a 44-32 lead
with two minutes left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks were clinging to life, down by 11 points at the half,
but seemed hardly capable of mounting a comeback. The Hawks
finished the first half shooting 33 percent with Smith hitting 4 of
14 from the field and Blaylock giving his team a 2-for-9 effort.
The combination of the Knicks' ability to send fresh bodies at the
Hawks and play suffocating defense had their opponent in a frazzled
state. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
