<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS PITCHERS OFF TO ROCKY START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kevin Brown, Chan Ho Park and Ismael Valdes were
to create an imposing, if not intimidating, trio of starting
pitchers. Carlos Perez, the lone lefty, and Darren Dreifort would
complement them to form what could be the most formidable starting
rotation in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Clink. Clank. Clunk.
</P>
<P>
   You don't win without solid starting pitching, and in case that
was forgotten, the Los Angeles Dodgers are here to remind everyone.
A quarter of the way into what's so far a disappointing season, the
Dodgers starting rotation is the primary culprit.
</P>
<P>
   The starters do not pitch deep into games, they give up runs
early and they have trouble protecting leads in the middle innings.
It's causing an already fragile bullpen to burn out and is putting
a strain on Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only guy doing his job on a consistent basis is Brown,''
Dreifort said.
</P>
<P>
   The modest standard by which pitching is graded these days is
the quality start _ three earned runs or less in six or more
innings. The Dodgers (22-21) have 13 quality starts in their last
26 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Pitching coach) Charlie (Hough) and I, it's our job to
straighten the pitching out,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``It's location, like in real estate. Movement helps and pitch
selection helps. It's a funny game. The middle (of the plate) is no
good. Outside is no good. It's just a little area on each side,
(and) if you do that, you'll be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Dodgers haven't found the outside portions of the
plate enough. They completed a three-game series against the St.
Louis Cardinals in which Valdes, Dreifort and Perez went 1-2 with a
6.75 ERA and averaged 51/3 innings per start.
</P>
<P>
   Notorious for his rigorous between-starts work ethic, which
includes throwing on the side twice and taking ground balls in the
infield, Brown is averaging more than seven innings per start and
has allowed one run in each of his last three starts. The only
other starter averaging more than six innings per start is Valdes
(4-2, 3.77 ERA). He got off to a quick start, but he lasted just
41/3 innings in his last start.
</P>
<P>
   When Brown signed his seven-year, $105-million contract, general
manager Kevin Malone spoke repeatedly about his influence on a
pitching staff. It's been evident off the field, but in two months
it hasn't translated the way the Dodgers hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly brings something special out there,'' Hough said.
``Most of it is competition, the level he competes at. He's got the
go-get-them kind of personality. I think it's going to get better.
You'll see his influence more and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but Park (3-3, 4.78 ERA) spent the first month of the
season with contract negotiations hanging over his head and hasn't
shown confidence in his fastball at crucial stages of game.
Instead, Johnson has criticized him for throwing too many offspeed
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Perez (1-6, 6.39) signed a three-year, $15-million contract in
the offseason and has rewarded the Dodgers with an awful start. His
52/3 innings of four-run ball against St. Louis on Sunday was one
of his better outings.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort (5-2, 4.98) is tied with Brown for the team lead in
wins, but his ERA is second highest among the starters. Although
he's had just two quality starts, he's benefited from terrific run
support. In the 47 innings Dreifort's pitched, the Dodgers have
scored 38 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a collection of a lot of little things we're going
through as a team,'' Brown said. ``You have to have an active role
in making things better. Even when you're doing well, you have to
continue to work to be better and not be satisfied. I don't think
that's a problem. It's finding the right thing, and what they have
to be doing to get in a groove.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ongoing process. It's a matter of hitting your stride.
This is not a unique situation. Staffs go through it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers staff wasn't supposed to experience such an
elongated slump, which has been prevalent most of the season.
Johnson met with the Dodgers pitchers earlier in the season and
stressed the importance of not trying to be too fine with their
pitches. That didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   The pitchers had another meeting before Saturday's game with St.
Louis to discuss how to remedy the mind-numbing problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always the little things that turn into big innings for
other teams,'' Dreifort said. ``You walk a guy, leave a pitch up, a
guy hits a two-run homer. It's just kind of the way it's been. It's
something you have to go out and pitch through. That's the way you
build confidence and get yourself on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown takes a 5-2 mark and his 2.54 ERA into tonight's game in
Cincinnati. The concern isn't how Brown will pitch, but what will
happen the next four days in what is a circle of inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   By National League standards, the Dodgers are successful. Their
starters are second in wins (19), fifth in ERA (4.28), fourth in
innings pitched (265) and sixth in earned runs (126). But so much
more is expected because their expectations are so high. The
Dodgers talked about challenging the Atlanta Braves to be the best
starting five in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers don't even have the best starting five in the NL
West. That belongs to Arizona, which ended the week with a 4.21 ERA
from its starters and a league-best 2942/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good talent. I believe we'll do better,'' Hough said.
``When you look at what the rest of the staffs in the big leagues
are doing, that's how many runs are being scored. There's guys all
over the place pitching with 6 ERAs. When this thing is done with,
this staff is going to be pretty good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
