<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: VAN GUNDY COULD FEEL THE TRUTH
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jeff Van Gundy probably did not need to be told it
was true, that Dave Checketts had been talking to Phil Jackson. Van
Gundy could feel it, right between his shoulder blades, from the
lack of enthusiasm at the top of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night Checketts informed the world that Van Gundy is ``a
great, great coach.'' Of course, it took being caught in a lie for
Checketts to issue any kind of support for the coach, who has been
twisting, twisting the spring away, in a vacuum while Checketts
checked out his options.
</P>
<P>
   As far as can be determined, Van Gundy twists still, even though
the Knicks swept their series with the Hawks with a 79-66 victory
Monday night and will play the Indiana Pacers in the Eastern
Conference finals, beginning Sunday in Indianapolis. Checketts said
he would take care of the issue after the season, but he fell far
short of any concrete praise for Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   If one wanted to trust raging instinct, it would almost seem
that Checketts has already decided that Jackson is his kind of
big-time guy, and that by bringing in Jackson to run the Knicks
next year Checketts could virtually assure that Patrick Ewing would
finish his career back home in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick has the right to say whatever he wants,'' Checketts
said rather coldly Monday night, when reminded that Ewing has said
he adamantly refuses to play for Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ewing's strong and uncharacteristic stand, Checketts met
with Jackson in mid-April, and soon afterward dismissed Ernie
Grunfeld as team president and general manager. When Mike Wise
reported the meeting with Jackson in The New York Times on Sunday,
Checketts at first denied it, but in a news conference Monday night
he admitted that the meeting had indeed taken place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that I lied about it,'' Checketts said. ``I misled
the press. I misled Jeff Van Gundy.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts spoke with Van Gundy before the game. The coach would
not discuss what was said, but he seemed to be in a controlled
sense of purpose, holding in his true feelings _ anger, contempt,
sadness.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most pathetic things Checketts said Monday night was
that he did not know Van Gundy very well and wanted to observe him
up close for the rest of the season. Checketts is, after all, the
president and chief operating officer of Madison Square Garden and,
as he reminded everybody Monday night, ``I was a general manager in
this league; I know a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he did not know the coach of his own team very well and
felt the need to meet with somebody who was a visible burr to his
own captain, and then, in his own words, lied about the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I erred on the side of trying to protect everybody,''
Checketts explained.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to fault Checketts for planning for major
contingencies. That is what chief executive officers must do.
However, the new people who currently own the Knicks cannot
appreciate the spectacle of their top executive bringing them such
ugly publicity. If Van Gundy is still on probation for next season,
what does that say about the status of Checketts?
</P>
<P>
   The new people might ask why Grunfeld and Van Gundy were
squabbling so divisively, and why Checketts didn't bang their heads
together and say, ``Get it together, you knuckleheads.''
</P>
<P>
   And the new people might ask whether Phil Jackson was a wise
alternative even a month ago, when the Knicks were in the doldrums.
Jackson is far from the self-styled maverick who worried that his
counterculture image would work against his ever getting hired as
an assistant coach in the league.
</P>
<P>
   After dealing with people as diverse as Michael Jordan, Jerry
Reinsdorf, Jerry Krause, Scottie Pippen and Dennis Rodman, Jackson
has developed the thick hide of a survivor.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks employed a similarly massive ego a few years back. It
all ended badly with charges that Pat Riley was an ambitious and
duplicitous careerist who used a fax machine to announce his
departure from the happy little family of the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Dave Checketts could have made Van Gundy
feel good about the prospect of remaining with this organization.
That prospect may have faded.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy is young and healthy, not totally naive or helpless,
and further ahead professionally than he might ever have expected
for a point guard from Nazareth College. Plus, as Lenny Wilkens,
who has coached all over the map and made the Hall of Fame, put it,
``There's always another job.'' The crowd chanted ``Jeff Van
Gundy'' toward the end Monday night but the prospect of another job
might appeal to Van Gundy right about now. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
