<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE OWE DEL HARRIS AN APOLOGY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I want to take this opportunity, on behalf of Jerry Buss, Jerry
West, malevolent radio sports talk show hosts, myopic sportswriters
and athletic followers throughout Southern California, to offer my
most humble apologies to Del Harris.
</P>
<P>
   You were right all along, Del, and we were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   You were cruelly sacrificed as coach of the Los Angeles Lakers
at mid-season supposedly because you no longer were able to
communicate with your players.
</P>
<P>
   Well, in light of the unpleasant events that have swirled around
the Laker orbit since your involuntary departure that climaxed
Sunday with the team being swept out of the playoffs by the San
Antonio Spurs, you have been totally vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   The Laker players also refused to listen to your successor, Kurt
Rambis, who vainly preached teamwork, who vainly tried to get
Shaquille O'Neal to concentrate on defense, who vainly tried to put
some restraints on Kobe Bryant, who vainly tried to alter his
interim coaching status with tactical moves that continually turned
out to be disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Lakers this season wasn't Del Harris, who
actually knows how to coach, or even Kurt Rambis, who doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who knows a moving screen from a John Stockton flop can
tell you that the Lakers' two top players, Shaquille O'Neal and
Kobe Bryant, haven't the faintest idea of how basketball is
supposed to be played at least team basketball.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen selfish, egotistical jocks with wildly inflated views
of their self-worth across the seasons, but I'm not sure any can
surpass Bryant, a nice enough young chap with a pleasant
personality who displays about as much discipline on the hardwoods
as a 4-year-old does at a day care center.
</P>
<P>
   If I could, I'd like to lift Bryant upside down from his
sneakers, shake some sense into his noggin, and force him to repeat
after me, ``I'm not Michael Jordan and I'm not going to take
anymore wayward shots and, instead, I solemnly promise I'm going to
start looking to pass to open teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   I put my palms over my ears when naive people keep telling me to
be patient with Kobe Bryant because he is only 20 years old and
still is learning the game.
</P>
<P>
   I keep telling such Bryant propagandists that, as John Wooden
constantly has insisted, basketball isn't that difficult a game to
learn, that Bryant stubbornly has refused to play within a team
framework, that Bryant isn't nearly as good as he thinks he is, and
that Magic Johnson had mastered the sport to such a dizzying level
by the time he was Bryant's age that he led the Lakers to a world
title.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way any team is going to win an NBA title, much less
even make it to the Western Conference finals, when it possesses a
player as self-centered as Bryant, who hogs the basketball with a
scandalous disregard for teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is no way a team can even avert a four-game
playoff impalement when its so-called superstar center, Shaquille
O'Neal, isn't in proper physical shape, plays erratic defense,
doesn't know how to pass out of double teams, and becomes such a
terrible offensive liability that he's better off on the bench in
the closing minutes of tight games because of his horrid free throw
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   As a loser, Shaquille O'Neal makes Wilt Chamberlain, affixed
with such a label throughout his career because of his annual
post-season flameouts to Bill Russell's Boston Celtics, look like a
rousing winner.
</P>
<P>
   If I were Jerry West, I'd give O'Neal a tape of Tim Duncan's
exploits against the Lakers and force O'Neal to spend three hours a
day in the off-season studying it.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers and Spurs still would be playing had O'Neal been able
to make, oh, half of his free throws, which he was unable to do
during the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   If Shaq was only able to display the same zest for practicing
foul shots that he does for eating he can stand to drop those 50 or
60 unflattering pounds that have impacted his defensive quickness
then I'm sure he would no longer humiliate himself almost every
time he lumbers haplessly to the free throw line.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bryant, O'Neal, who's 27, still hasn't learned the deft
subtleties of his sport, as evidenced by the mere two assists he
managed during the series with the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   How could a guy like O'Neal who's constantly engulfed by
defenders wind up with such a meager total in four games?
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious O'Neal needs a Klieg light to spot an open
teammate. Wilt Chamberlain once actually led the NBA in assists.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a more self-indulgent player on the Lakers than Kobe
Bryant and I'm not sure that's humanly possible it would have to be
Shaquille O'Neal, who takes just as many indiscreet shots as Bryant
and doesn't exactly seem passionately stirred by competitive
juices.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, one can point to more reasons for the Lakers' latest
unraveling than the shoddy antics of Bryant and O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers still don't have a first-rate point guard, although
at least Derek Fisher isn't timid about playing hard-nosed defense,
which makes him unique on this pacifistic Laker team.
</P>
<P>
   They also could use a power forward able to consistently grab
rebounds and hold his own with the likes of Tim Duncan. J.R. Reid
tries, bless him, but he's simply not very good.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice is a good shooter, but the Lakers, true to form, never
were able to find him enough open looks.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry and Rick Fox also are talented players, but their
skills were thoroughly squandered on perhaps the stupidest Laker
team I've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what those two lovable Jerrys, Messrs. Buss and
West, will be able to do in the upcoming months to prevent another
post-season Laker collapse next spring.
</P>
<P>
   You have a serious dilemma when your two marquee performers,
Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, not only don't understand even
the most basic fundamentals of basketball, but also aren't
particularly fond of each other.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a strong-willed coach like Chuck Daly, who resigned from
the Orlando Magic Monday, is the answer.
</P>
<P>
   But, remember, Del Harris also was strong-willed, and look what
happened to him during another disappointing Laker season in which
the beleaguered Harris at least is left with the last cackle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
