<HEADER>
A9839 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUIMA-VOLPE-650&AMP;ADD-     05-24 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-VOLPE-650&AMP;ADD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. POLICE OFFICER WILL PLEAD GUILTY TO ASSAULTING IMMIGRANT
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS to add 700 words starting with 8th graf after optional trim,
beginning: Volpe's decision.)  (rm) 
 By ROBERT McFADDEN and JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Confronted with devastating testimony by fellow
officers and a crumbling defense, the policeman accused of
torturing Abner Louima in the bathroom of a Brooklyn station house
in 1997 will plead guilty to all charges Tuesday and throw himself
on the mercy of the court, his lawyer told a federal judge Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With chances of an acquittal all but gone and prosecutors
rejecting any plea bargain in a case that stunned the city and the
nation, the officer, Justin Volpe, appeared to have no choice but
to admit that he rammed a broom handle into the rectum and then
into the mouth of the handcuffed Haitian immigrant in a fit of
rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to enter a plea tomorrow,'' Volpe's lawyer,
Marvyn Kornberg, told Judge Eugene Nickerson in U.S. District Court
in Brooklyn. The request took place during a quiet conference of
defense lawyers and prosecutors at the bench at 3:45 p.m.,
signaling that his client had abandoned all but the hope of
leniency.
</P>
<P>
   While the trial of four other officers accused in the case was
expected to continue, a guilty plea by Volpe would end his
involvement in the most explosive New York police brutality episode
in decades. Its horrors have been compared and contrasted to those
of Amadou Diallo, the unarmed West African immigrant slain by four
officers in a hail of 41 shots last February.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Monday night that he would withhold
comment until the plea was entered Tuesday, and Police Commissioner
Howard Safir also declined to comment. The mayor and the
commissioner, often outspoken in their defense of police officers,
have been silent in the Louima case.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the other defendants indicated Monday that they were
prepared to go on with the trial. Kornberg declined to comment on
whether Volpe would testify for the prosecution, or whether, in
offering his plea, he would implicate any of the others. Other
lawyers in the case said it was unlikely that he would testify, and
what he would disclose in his plea appeared to be up to the judge.
</P>
<P>
   By pleading guilty to violating Louima's civil rights in a
sexual assault, the 27-year-old Volpe would expose himself to a
maximum sentence of life in prison without possibility of parole.
But under complex federal sentencing guidelines, Nickerson, by
applying all provisions for leniency, including Volpe's acceptance
of responsibility for his actions, could impose a term of 25 to 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts noted that the judge would have wide discretion in
the sentence. Prosecutors were expected to argue against any
leniency, on the ground that Volpe decided to plead guilty only
after he saw the overwhelming case against him. Last week, fellow
officers had testified about hearing him brag of the assault and
seeing him brandish the stick stained with blood and feces.
</P>
<P>
   As a condition of pleading guilty, legal experts said, Volpe
would be required to detail his actions on the morning of Aug. 9,
1997, when, officials charge, he and Officers Charles Schwarz,
Thomas Wiese and Thomas Bruder beat Louima in a patrol car before
taking him to the 70th Precinct station house, where Schwarz
allegedly held him down while Volpe sodomized him with a broom
handle.
</P>
<P>
   The extent to which Volpe will tell his story Tuesday _ whether
the actions of other officers will be detailed or even cited, for
example _ will be up to Nickerson, lawyers said. But to insure that
a continuing trial of the other officers not be tainted, legal
experts said the judge was not likely to require any statements by
Volpe of their involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Volpe's statement in open court, which will take
place in the absence of the jury, could amount to a dramatic,
blow-by-blow confession of his own alleged brutality. That has
already been told in testimony by Louima, 32, who suffered severe
rectal and bladder injuries and underwent several operations and
months of hospitalization.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In theory, Nickerson could reject a guilty plea if he thought it
served the interest of justice, but lawyers said that was not
likely in view of the testimony in recent days by Sgt. Kenneth
Wernick, Detective Eric Turetzky and Officers Mark Schofield and
Michael Schoer.
</P>
<P>
   Turetzky testified last week that he saw Volpe lead a handcuffed
Louima, whose pants were at his ankles, to the bathroom of the
station house, and later that he saw Volpe, disheveled and sullen,
swinging a stick around ``like a sword and hitting it against a
wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Schofield testified that he, too, saw Volpe with a stick, and
said he had borrowed a pair of black leather gloves before the
alleged attack and later gave them back, covered with blood.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg, who had said at the outset of the trial that Louima's
injuries had been caused by consensual sex at a nightclub before a
melee that led to his arrest, and other defense lawyers attacked
the credibility of the police witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the defense appeared to be taken by surprise last Wednesday
when Wernick took the stand and said that Volpe had bragged about
the attack, saying, ``I took a man down tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant said Volpe told him he ``took a stick and put it
five or six inches up,'' and that then he ``took it out and put it
up to his mouth and teeth area, kind of like showing it to him.''
He said Volpe also showed him the section of broomstick, two to
three feet long, in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   After first saying he intended to cross-examine the sergeant,
Kornberg reversed himself and asked no questions. He also did not
cross-examine Schoer, who testified that Volpe had taunted him by
putting the excrement-tainted stick near his face.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe's decision to plead guilty came on a relatively routine
day, in a trial dominated by prosecution witnesses whose shocking
evidence had made daily headlines. The defense had not even begun
to present its case.
</P>
<P>
   There was testimony Monday by prosecution witnesses about
Volpe's allegedly falsified report of the circumstances in which
Louima and a second Haitian immigrant, Patrick Antoine, were
arrested on the streets around a Flatbush nightclub called the
Rendez-Vous.
</P>
<P>
   Police had been called there after a melee broke out outside the
club. In that melee, Volpe was struck by someone _ it is unclear
who _ and the enraged officer apparently mistook Louima for that
assailant.
</P>
<P>
   Antoine had not been involved in the melee, but was seized
walking home several blocks away; Volpe's report put him in the
middle of the melee. Antoine, like Louima, was beaten, but their
injuries were listed in the Volpe report as having been sustained
in the melee.
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses who testified Monday included a surgeon who told
of injuries to Louima's rectum and bladder, and of having operated
on Louima at Coney Island Hospital. Federal agents and police
investigators also told of blood spots and blood found in the
police car where the officers were said to have beaten Louima.
</P>
<P>
   But as the testimony droned on, reporters at midafternoon were
told privately that a major break was imminent, that Volpe had made
a decision to plead guilty to all the charges against him:
depriving Louima and Antoine of of their civil rights, conspiracy,
obstruction of justice and witness tampering. The last charge arose
because Volpe allegedly told Louima after the bathroom attack that
he would kill him if he ever told about it.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, Wiese and Bruder are charged with violating Louima's
civil rights by beating him in the patrol car en route to the
station house. In addition, Schwarz was accused of participating in
the sexual assault of Louima by holding him down in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth defendant, Sgt. Michael Bellomo, is charged with trying
to cover up the beating in the police car, and of arresting Antoine
on false charges to cover up his beating.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:45 p.m. Monday, after a series of huddled conferences
involving the defense lawyers and prosecutors led by Alan Vinegrad,
the chief of the criminal division of the U.S. attorney's office in
Brooklyn, Kornberg asked Nickerson for a conference at the bench
and disclosed his client's intent to plead guilty Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In view of the plan to enter a guilty plea, Vinegrad asked that
Volpe, who has been free on bail pending the outcome of the trial,
be placed under house arrest. Under that arrangement, he was
allowed to return Monday night to his parents' home on Staten
Island, where he has been living, and would return to court Tuesday
in the company of Kornberg.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe might have entered his plea Monday, but was said to have
wanted to spend a last night with his parents. His father, Robert
Volpe, is a retired New York City police detective who was renowned
as an investigator of art fraud and art thefts. Volpe's bail was
expected to be revoked after his plea.
</P>
<P>
   No court session had been planned for Tuesday because the wife
of one defense lawyer was expected to give birth. The jury had been
given Tuesday off; had that not been the case, Nickerson would have
had to send the jury out during Volpe's plea, so that its judgment
about the other defendants would not be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the jury have been instructed not to read or listen
to news accounts of the case, and they are expected to arrive in
court Wednesday unaware of any plea. They would see only an empty
chair where Volpe sat. The judge would instruct them that the case
against one officer has been disposed of, and that they were not to
consider that in judging the case against the others.
</P>
<P>
   Vinegrad had no comment Monday. Stephen Worth, the lawyer for
Schwarz, said he had no intention at the moment of calling for a
mistrial. Joseph Tacopina, Stuart London and John Patten, the
lawyers for Wiese, Bruder and Bellomo, respectively, said they
intended to go ahead with their clients' defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
