<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE SPREWELL PUZZLE IS THE OPPOSITE OF EASY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The moment comes soon enough, and it belongs to
Latrell Sprewell, and no one else. The coach calls his name
sometime during the first quarter, and the building erupts as soon
as he stands up. Sprewell does not start the game at Madison Square
Garden. He restarts it, and jams it into the highest possible gear.
</P>
<P>
   This much-debated deployment that Jeff Van Gundy settled on for
Sprewell _ part by circumstance, part by choice _ not only gave a
team-in-progress much clearer focus, it offered New York fans a
direct voice line to the player so viscerally and forgivingly
adopted as the replacement for the most popular Knick of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   John Starks once resisted coming off the bench, but ultimately
came around to the energizing buzz, to the electric moment that
belonged to him. Sprewell is not likely to embrace this position,
no matter how much farther in these playoffs it carries him and the
Knicks. If we know anything about this explosive talent beyond his
hyperactive capacity to break down the defense, it is his ability
to convince himself that any decision rendered by others is a
direct affront to the one he makes for himself.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the man has a persecution complex the size of
Pittsburgh, which is no easy way to go through a season, or life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latrell,'' Chris Childs profoundly stated last week in
Atlanta, ``is the opposite of easy.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the Atlanta Hawks and the Eastern Conference
semifinals were concerned, it was easy, over and out Monday night,
the Knicks sweeping with a 79-66 no mas victory, setting their
sights on the conference final and their matchups for the Indiana
Pacers. After the paper-thin Heat and handicapped Hawks, here comes
an opponent that has as much roster definition as it has depth.
Here come Antonio Davis, Jalen Rose and Derrick McKey, all arms,
legs and disruption, charging on call off Larry Bird's bench.
</P>
<P>
   Here comes the only team left in the playoffs, Western
Conference included, with the defensive components to
simultaneously challenge Sprewell and Allan Houston, to put the
new, improved Knicks to the in-your-face acid test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd be in this position,'' Sprewell said, in
one of those moments when he comes off reasoned and willing, and
his comeback story is one to embrace.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the best spot of his basketball life, the grand stage
of a conference final, in New York City, against Reggie Miller and
his cast of odd-shaped pieces which form a most beguiling
basketball puzzle. Sprewell could not have imagined a better spring
for himself as he waited out the lockout, in limbo, for the
inevitable trade from Golden State. And despite this run, his first
taste of playoff success, there is the mind-boggling issue of what
Van Gundy and the team has asked of him.
</P>
<P>
   There is yet another coach, like every other Sprewell has played
for, who has dared to impose his unwelcome will.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't always see eye to eye,'' Van Gundy had to admit after
Sprewell cursed him and his substitution scheme during Game 2 in
Atlanta. This choice of words evoked memories of Anthony Mason, on
the Knicks' bench, avoiding eye contact with Pat Riley, at all
costs. For all his talent, Mason's unacceptable flaw was his
incessant need to prove himself right. And that is Sprewell, who
choked his coach and sued the league and blamed his agent and then
has the temerity to curse Van Gundy three months after the Knicks
brought him to New York to remake his career.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here is not just a very good player who wants to
start. It is the circumstances _ in a supposed redemptive season
cut short by 32 games and further reduced by his injured foot _
under which Sprewell has let his displeasure be known, with his
minutes and the coach. Forget compromise. This is his American
Dream. These are his terms.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell has certainly earned his cheers, but the last thing he
needs to hear is a defense of his bench-role blues because he
happens to be the best player on the team. Maybe next season _ if
there is a next season for him in New York _ he will have a better
case against Van Gundy or some other coach. Then again, maybe
Sprewell never gets another chance to play this deep into spring.
These runs are fickle. That ball that rolled off Terry Porter in
Miami, Game 5, could have rolled off Sprewell instead. Athletes can
always leverage themselves into more money and minutes, but
Sprewell has been granted a chance to jam the Knicks into a gear
that even the Pacers might not match, right on into the
championship round.
</P>
<P>
   He just has to wait a few minutes to restart the game, as Jalen
Rose does for Bird. For this truncated season, Van Gundy made the
right team call. Hopefully, for his sake, Sprewell can enjoy this
role, this stage, and those clamorous moments when Van Gundy calls
his name and the Garden responds.
</P>
<P>
   These should be the best times of his basketball life, far from
the opposite of easy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
