<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS MIGHT SEE OFFSEASON SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Stoic expressions and resigned tones filled
the Lakers' quickly emptying locker room in the wake of another
sweep from the playoffs. Underlying all their carefully chosen
words was the harsh realization that another quick exit has
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Jones, Nick Van Exel and Del Harris couldn't win a
championship soon enough and they were sent packing. Who's next?
The Lakers don't know yet, but as they packed up their belongings
Monday, a day after being swept from the conference semifinals by
the San Antonio Spurs, they braced for a different kind of clean
sweep.
</P>
<P>
   The coach might not be retained, several starters might not be
back and even the executive vice president won't guarantee he'll be
here when the Lakers open the 1999-2000 season at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West deferred any answers on interim coach Kurt Rambis or
the state of several players' contracts but did imply he'll be the
one deciding those issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell you I fully intend and I hope to complete my four
years here,'' West said, referring to the contract that starts next
season. ``I don't want that to be any more of a story than it has
been in the past. But to say that I don't get frustrated would not
be the truth. It really is how to manage the stress and frustration
of the job.''
</P>
<P>
   So West will try to deal better with the strain, attempt to
stave off further meddling from owner Jerry Buss _ who signed
Dennis Rodman over West's objections _ then return to the task of
trying to put the Lakers in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   First, he has to settle on a coach. And then, who will return to
play for that coach.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis' fate is unclear and West declined to give a timeline for
that decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll have more responses for you people in a
couple of weeks, after I meet with Jerry Buss and the other people
on our staff to determine where we're headed,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis believes he's earned the chance to prove himself during a
normal season _ i.e., not a compacted 50-game slate that included a
change in coaches, the Rodman drama and a major trade. ``A crazy
season,'' as Robert Horry put it.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of players declined to endorse Rambis, and certain
influential players clearly had problems with him, but a few
offered praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned,'' Rambis said. ``I made some mistakes, but I
learned. I think I did a good job. Basically, no one had to go
through the type of season that I had to go through, so there's
nothing to really compare it to. . . . I wish things would have
worked out differently, but given the circumstances, the cards I
was dealt, I thought I did a very good job.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Lakers mull that decision, the clock is ticking for
sharpshooter Glen Rice. The Lakers have until July 1 to either
exercise a $7.1 million one-year option or give Rice the
multimillion-dollar extension he wants. If they take no action,
he'll join a long list of Lakers free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Starters Derek Fisher and J.R. Reid and reserves Rick Fox and
Ruben Patterson are free agents as of July 1. And Derek Harper, a
part-time starter, might retire.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the small matter of Shaquille O'Neal's option to
terminate the remaining four years of his contract. Opting out
would mean sacrificing millions because of the league's new labor
deal, but O'Neal has stopped short of guaranteeing he'll return.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he dodged the issue entirely by skipping the
postseason team meeting _ as he's done every season here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to win and he'll do it at all costs,'' said Fisher,
who thinks O'Neal will be back. ``He doesn't have any financial
concerns. Whatever decision he makes, it will be about winning a
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher and Fox want to return. Reid is noncommittal. Harper is
taking a wait-and-see approach. And Rice, frustrated over his role
in the offense, nevertheless wants to be a Laker for the long term.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers don't trade Rice, and O'Neal stays, they will
again form a dangerous, if volatile, core with Kobe Bryant on a
team that will again be favored to contend for a title. And maybe
all the Lakers really need is not a wholesale makeover but a real
training camp and full 82-game schedule to become a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have the pieces,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a terrible basketball team,'' West admonished.
``We have a talented basketball team here, and we're competing
against our past success. . . . We lost in four straight games to a
team with the best record this year. And those are the things that
we will be remembered for, but I will tell you this is a pretty
darn good team. If we can retain the parts that we want to retain
and maybe add a couple players that will provide us a little bit
different look on our bench, we think we're very, very
competitive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-99 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
