</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PLOT-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS OF 14-YEAR-OLD CONSPIRATOR CLAIM TEXAS AUTHORITIES
OVERREACTED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MARCOS, Texas _ The parents of one of four Wimberley boys
who admitted to participating in a plot to attack their local high
school say prosecutors railroaded the youths through the justice
system, ignoring signs that the boys were basically big talkers
with a fondness for firecrackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be naive parents,'' said Stella Armstrong,
the mother of one of the 14-year-olds. ``But they made something
small into something very, very big.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the four boys pleaded ``true,'' the juvenile court
equivalent of guilty, to charges of conspiracy to commit arson.
Prosecutors say the boys planned to arm themselves with explosives,
take over Wimberley High School in the year 2001 and hold the
campus hostage for $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most dangerous explosives seized by law
enforcement agents during searches of the boys' homes a month ago
were rifle shell casings stuffed with firecrackers. Police records
show that authorities also confiscated a film canister with BBs in
it and atop it, a smoke bomb, in addition to a clear plastic
container filled with gunpowder.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Armstrong said the container, taken from his son's room, is
the type that comes out of a gumball machine rather than a
Tupperware container. Stella Armstrong said the explosives, all
fireworks, were left over from a family New Year's party.
</P>
<P>
   Other evidence included instructions on how to assemble a pipe
bomb downloaded from the Internet and a computer disk, apparently
with a school report on the atomic bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were they going to bring the roof down in the next 15
seconds?'' said Hays County District Attorney Michael Wenk. ``No.
But they were actively engaged in the planning of a criminal act
and they crossed the legal threshold.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Armstrongs describe overzealous law enforcement
officers, mean-spirited prosecutors and a judge who they say called
their son ``a monster'' in court. Despite their strong objections,
they say officials interrogated their son and the other three boys
for eight hours without a lawyer or a parent present.
</P>
<P>
   When the couple protested, they say they were told by assistant
District Attorney Patrick Keaveny, ``These boys have no rights.''
Keaveny did not return calls from the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Until late Friday, County Court at Law Judge Howard Warner had
placed a gag order on the case, meaning those involved in it were
forbidden to speak and documents were sealed. Warner said the
search warrant affidavits, among other documents, would remain
sealed.
</P>
<P>
   One defense attorney released some of the information to the
Chronicle on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the boys, including the Armstrong's son, were sentenced
to two years probation after a three-month boot camp at the Hays
County Juvenile Detention Center. The fourth boy was given two
years probation. The Armstrongs said their son pleaded guilty
because prosecutors threatened to charge him as an adult and lock
him up until he turns 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be the rest of his childhood,'' said Stella
Armstrong. ``I wasn't going to take the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of a plot to attack a Wimberley school broke three days
after the April 20 massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo. Those familiar with the case say an eighth-grader at
Wimberley Junior High School told his parents about a plan for some
sort of similar assault, and his parents told him to tell school
officials.
</P>
<P>
   School officials contacted law enforcement authorities, turning
over two spiral notebooks and a sheet of notebook paper from three
of the boys, which included notes by one of the three about killing
people by stabbing them with pencils and ink pens.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities then wired the eighth-grade informant
electronically, using him to ferret out those believed to be behind
the plan. The informant was among five boys detained, but law
enforcement officials later released him.
</P>
<P>
   The four Wimberley boys were held on charges of conspiracy to
commit murder, conspiracy to commit arson and conspiracy to
manufacture explosives.
</P>
<P>
   According to police reports the informant told authorities the
boys were asking other students what they thought of the Littleton
killings, in an effort to find recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the person that was asked said that it was cool or neat,''
the informant said, ``they would be told that there was a group of
students that was going to do the same thing at Wimberley, and
would be asked to join the group.''
</P>
<P>
   The informant said the boys picked the spring of 2001 to carry
out their plan because ``they'll be in high school by then and also
have driver's licenses.'' As an afterthought, he added that the two
years preparation would also give them time to learn the layout of
the high school. The boy also apparently gave authorities an
unwritten hit list.
</P>
<P>
   Though prosecutors believe this evidence to be strong, the
Armstrongs say words like ``neat'' and ``cool'' and talk of
driver's licenses are red flags for 14-year-olds whose bark is
clearly bigger than their bite. One parent whose son is a friend of
one of the boys who was detained says the two still play with Legos
and Ninja Turtles.
</P>
<P>
   Though their son was in trouble with school officials last year
for possession of marijuana, the Armstrongs describe him as
generally a good kid. Unlike the Colorado killers, the Wimberley
youths were not on the fringe. Instead they were represented on the
honor roll, in team sports and in school government.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son is devastated,'' said Stella Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said Keaveny, the assistant district attorney, tore up
confessions written by her son three times during his questioning,
saying it was not what he wanted. The couple said their son and the
other three boys were essentially talked into admitting a
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could convince a 14-year-old he lived on Mars if I had eight
hours,'' said Bob Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   The couple said Judge Warner told their son at the time of his
sentencing that ``there are a lot of people in the community that
think you are a monster.''
</P>
<P>
   They quoted the judge as saying, ``I suggest you crawl yourself
into that little hole you dug, stay in for a while and work
yourself out of it to prove to the community you are not the
monster they think you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner declined to discuss the case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
