<SLUG> BC-WICKENBURG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OLD WICKENBURG' MAY FADE, RESIDENTS OF RETIREMENT HOT SPOT FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICKENBURG _ As the cowboy ambled to the counter to pick up his
store-bought lariat, the sweet smell of leather and oil wafted
through the warm air of Ben's Saddlery shop.
</P>
<P>
   Old Wickenburg. That's what longtime boot and saddlemaker Arlene
Hefner calls it.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of place where ranchers would gossip for hours among
the boot racks during a rainstorm. Where prospectors couldn't get
enough of gold fever milking the mother lode at the nearby Vulture
Mine.
</P>
<P>
   The Old West atmosphere spawned a cottage industry of dude
ranches. ``Out Wickenburg Way'' became the local Chamber of
Commerce hook for tourists. City officials still emboss their
business cards with stagecoaches and galloping horses. The local
museum displays original works of famed Western artists Frederic
Remington and Charles Russell.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Hefner said, Old Wickenburg is an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   She looks out the front door at the modern, suburban-style City
Hall that ``looks like it should be somewhere in Scottsdale.'' The
new pink sidewalks ``give pause to any real (cowboy) walking on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most disturbing sign came last week, Hefner said. That's
when Wickenburg made the top five list of most desirable towns for
retirees in this year's edition of ``Retirement Places Rated''.
</P>
<P>
   `` '' That led to mentions on the ``Today'' show and in ``USA
Today,'' and to a wave of telephone calls to the chamber. More than
100 information packs went out to prospective residents.
</P>
<P>
   `` '' Not that it was unexpected. Senior citizens with money and
different ideas about the town's future have been moving here with
great regularity in recent years. And city officials estimate that
about 60 percent of the town's 6,000 residents are of retirement
age.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Which is just all fine and dandy, says Richard Conklin, a
retired barber from Iowa who has lived in Wickenburg for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old-timers here think things are going to pot,'' Conklin
said. ``But I think the town is doing a mighty fine job of
planning. They are doing everything they can to retain its flavor
and all the new developments here are nice.''
</P>
<P>
   But the problem of retirees altering the way things used to be
will only get worse, say Hefner and co-workers Karen Lamontagne and
L.A. Francis. They believe they are on the verge of becoming the
true Sun City West.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun City Grand project near U.S. 60 and Loop 303 means that
sprawl in the northwest Valley has now crept to the halfway point
in the 58 miles between Wickenburg and downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   An extended section of two-lane road on U.S. 60, which turns
into U.S. 89 near Wickenburg, has kept many from traveling to
Wickenburg in the past. But the state's construction timetable
calls for the highway to be all four lane in little more than three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Lamontagne said it doesn't take an Einstein to figure out what
will happen next: a corridor of senior citizens from Sun City to
Wickenburg.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Stricklin, Wickenburg's planning director, says he can't
dispute that analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Sun City began, that set the geographical direction for
retirement living,'' Stricklin said. ``Then it moved west to Sun
City West and now Sun City Grand to connect the Grand Avenue
corridor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a major economic effort on the part of the state
to attract retirees because they are good for the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricklin said Wickenburg is in an annexation mode _ hoping to
annex enough to preserve its lifestyle, because ``we can't have
Phoenix growing up to our door.''
</P>
<P>
   But Buckeye has annexed property within 12 miles of Wickenburg.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Stewart, a Wickenburg hardware store owner, said he thinks
the high cost of developing land along U.S. 89 southeast of town
will prevent an actual corridor of retiree subdivisions between the
Valley and Wickenburg.
</P>
<P>
   But the high cost of land and housing within the town, along
with an absence of good jobs, also mean that well-heeled retirees
have the upper hand on purchasing land in Wickenburg.
</P>
<P>
   Todd ``Paco'' Corbet, a 30-year-old local Realtor who was raised
in Wickenburg, said he recently moved to the Valley because he
could buy a house for $40,000 less than for a comparable house in
Wickenburg.
</P>
<P>
   And the older, newer people in And the older, newer people in
Wickenburg are flexing their muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who moved to Wickenburg 11 years ago from Idaho, said,
``It's not our idea for this town to look like Tombstone. Our idea
is for it to be a combination of the Old West and period
architecture of the 1950s.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget about the '50s, said Francis, who fashions saddles at
Ben's Saddlery. Francis said he chose to leave Jackson Hole, Wyo.,
after its ``destruction by the Californians'' and move to the
Wickenburg area because of its frontier charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now,'' he said, ``all the old people are destroying all of
that here, too.'' &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at (602) 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
