<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRINGHAUSEN DETOURED IN PITTSBURGH ON HIS LONG ROAD BACK
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ There were flashes Mondy night, quick glimpses of
why Jason Isringhausen was once considered the future of the New
York Mets' pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   There were also reminders, however, in the Mets' 7-4 loss to the
Pittsburgh Pirates that Isringhausen's long road back from
disappointments and injuries is still far from complete.
</P>
<P>
   In Isringhausen's first major league appearance in 20 months, he
gave up five runs, seven hits (including two home runs) and four
walks in six innings, with seven strikeouts. But he fit right in
with the other Mets' starters, who have a 5.49 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   Isringhausen pitched through the rain, and he pitched in the
cold. But even though Isringhausen left with the Mets trailing by
5-3, it was likely worth the wait for him.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets could not get Isringhausen off the hook because they
squandered opportunity after opportunity, leaving 11 runners on
base. The most frustrating moments came in the eighth, when the
Mets left runners on second and third with one out after Brian
McRae's run-scoring double had cut the deficit to 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Sprague hit a two-run homer off Turk Wendell in the bottom of
the eighth to put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates' bullpen kept the Mets at bay. Jose Silva, a
right-hander with a 7.67 ERA, came on in the fourth inning and shut
down the Mets into the eighth in relief of the starter, Francisco
Cordova. Then a former Mets farmhand _ Scott Sauerbeck, a
27-year-old left-hander whom the Pirates had plucked this winter in
the Rule V draft _ entered the game in the eighth with the tying
and go-ahead runs in scoring position and struck out Benny Agbayani
and Jermaine Allensworth.
</P>
<P>
   Isringhausen's last major league outing had also been against
the Pirates on Sept. 23, 1997, at Shea Stadium. He had fought back
from surgeries on his shoulder and elbow, a broken wrist and
tuberculosis to pitch that year. But on Jan. 13, 1998, Isringhausen
had reconstructive elbow surgery, and he did not pitch at all last
season.
</P>
<P>
   This year Isringhausen was 3-1 with a 2.53 ERA at Class AAA
Norfolk as he waited for the call back to the majors.
</P>
<P>
   It came on Sunday. But as if a year and a half was not long
enough, the 26-year-old right-hander had to wait another 21 minutes
as rain delayed the start of the game.
</P>
<P>
   On Isringhausen's first pitch, Al Martin slapped a double down
the left-field line past a diving Robin Ventura, who was playing in
at third base to deny Martin an easy bunt.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious that Isringhausen was pitching on adrenaline. His
fastball had life in the first and was consistently clocked at 96
miles an hour. On Isringhausen's second pitch, Warren Morris bunted
back to him, too hard for Martin to advance, and Isringhausen had
an out.
</P>
<P>
   Isringhausen froze the next batter, Brian Giles with a crisp
knuckle curve on a 1-2 pitch. For a moment, he was resembling the
23-year-old Isringhausen who had gone 9-2 as a rookie in 1995.
Soon, though, he looked more like Isringhausen who had struggled
through a 6-14 sophomore season in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Young fought him for a full-count walk. Out went Mike
Piazza to try to settle Isringhausen down. It did not work. His
next pitch was a 93-MPH fastball that Jason Kendall blasted over
the fence in left-center field for a three-run home run, and the
Mets were down, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored a run in the third on Piazza's sacrifice fly
with the bases loaded, but they left two runners on base. And then
Morris homered to lead off the Pittsburgh third and make it 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets responded with a two-out rally in the fourth, knocking
out Cordova on Allensworth's two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   Isringhausen's velocity, meanwhile, was down in the 90-93 MPH
range.
</P>
</TEXT>
