<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6 `WIZ' KIDS, 150 WHIZZES AT BEING KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The happy dance was the best part.
</P>
<P>
   During that segment of the audition, the kids were no longer
would-be actors trying for parts. They were just kids again,
throwing their hands into the air, twirling and laughing while
singing, ``Ding dong, the wicked witch is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a song that sticks easily and firmly in your head every
time you hear it. With more than 150 kids trying out for six roles
as munchkins in a touring production of ``The Wizard of Oz'' that
will play at Gammage Auditorium next month, it must have been
permanently carved into the brains of the people picking the
pint-size performers for the show.
</P>
<P>
   Not every kid who showed up at Wells Fargo Arena on the Arizona
State University campus last week to audition carried a
professional resume and glossy glamour shots, but enough did to
remind you that just because the roles were diminutive didn't mean
the ambitions were.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Klein, 9, waited three hours to be first in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a marine biologist or a pediatrician,'' she said
as she affixed an adhesive badge with a ``1'' on it to her
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   What? Not an actor?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that would be if I didn't become an actor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle's dad, Michael, is a rare bird at this kind of thing _
he's honest about his role in the process. &QL; 
PARENTS IN THE WINGS
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an admitted stage parent,'' he said. ``I take her around
to all the auditions and pictures, you name it. Somebody's got to
take her.''
</P>
<P>
   Good for him. Those words _ ``stage parent'' _ are pure poison
to most people, dredging up visions of a claw-fingered harpy
shoving a reluctant, crying child out from behind the curtain and
into the spotlight toward reflected fame and glory.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't how Klein portrayed himself, and, frankly, it wasn't
how he seemed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to talk her out of it,'' he said, referring to acting,
``but she refused. She's a little ham.''
</P>
<P>
   Again with the honesty. Which is not to say others lied about
their children's ambitions or, more to the point, their own. Lisa
Stark brought Kurt, 11, to the audition because ``he saw it on the
news and wanted to do it.'' No resume, no photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his deal, not mine,'' she said. Like the rest of the
kids, Kurt had dutifully memorized the wicked-witch song.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have his song memorized now,'' Lisa Stark said. No doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Acting experience _ and ambition _ varied among the kids waiting
to go on. Marcus Vizzerra, a 9-year-old dressed sharply in a vest,
gave a simple reason why he would make a good munchkin:
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I'm short.''
</P>
<P>
   (Marcus, too, had the song down cold. As did his mother,
Melissa. ``I was singing that song in my sleep last night,'' she
said.) &QL; 
THINKING CAP
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Hofferth, meanwhile, sported a green leprechaun hat, which
suggested a munchkinlike look, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use it . . . just to get more in the feel of acting,'' the
12-year-old said of his hat. ``And to get people's attention _ like
yours.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the room where the kids auditioned was where the biggest
differences were found. Allison Queal, a munchkin, citizen of Oz
and flying monkey in the touring company, taught the children a
simple dance step, which they performed in groups of five while
singing the witch song.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, any kid singing, ``Wake up you sleepy head/Rub
your eyes, get out of bed'' while clomping around (the happy dance)
is cute. But some moved uncomfortably and awkwardly, as if they
were wearing wet clothes. Others wore the steely eyed glint and
professional grins of seasoned pros as they moved fluidly.
</P>
<P>
   None of the kids you've been reading about made the final cut.
But that's OK. They looked positively gleeful doing the happy
dance.
</P>
<P>
   Which is more important anyway. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
