A9854 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEMEPARK-AZR &LR;      05-24 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEMEPARK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTTSDALE MAYOR WANTS MASSIVE CULTURAL THEME PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEXA HAUSSLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   heels of a stadium district victory, Scottsdale Mayor Sam
Campana wants voters' blessing for another massive redevelopment
project: a cultural theme park.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to ask voters Sept. 7 if developers can keep sales
taxes to help pay for a proposed $1 billion mall of museums in
downtown Scottsdale along the Arizona Canal's south bank.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, voters would be deciding whether the project _
billed as a cultural mecca anchored by a Smithsonian-affiliated
museum _ should fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottsdale City Council is to decide tonight whether to put
the theme park question on the ballot, along with another question
involving a financing plan for desert preservation.
</P>
<P>
   The theme park vote will be ``similar to what we did with Los
Arcos,'' Campana said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Scottsdale voters overwhelmingly approved forming a
special taxing stadium district to help finance a proposed $624
million hockey-entertainment complex at Los Arcos Mall.
</P>
<P>
   The theme park election would come two months before another Los
Arcos election to approve a financing plan for that project and six
months before the city's mayoral and council election.
</P>
<P>
   The cultural theme park, called the Canals of Scottsdale, would
be built by a group of developers on a 27-acre site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this project stands on its own,'' said Fred Unger, a
partner in the development group. &UR; ``This is an opportunity to bring
in a cultural component that very few cities in the world have.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for downtown property owners called the news
``wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that we'll have a chance to vote on it, it's the way
it should be,'' said property manager Tom Giller, president of
Scottsdale Focus, an advocacy group for downtown property owners.
</P>
<P>
   Some downtown business and property owners have objected to the
size of the project and plans to buy or condemn about 30 businesses
in the city's arts, craft and Western-theme shopping district.
</P>
<P>
   A state legislative committee agreed in July to let the
developers use a now-defunct 1994 law that was originally designed
to help Gilbert lure an amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows cities to organize a theme park district and use
sales tax revenue _ equaling up to 30 percent of the project's
total cost _ to pay off bonds used to finance the project's
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Canals developers would get to keep up to $300
million in state, city and county sales taxes collected within the
project to build roads, parking garages and other public facilities
including renovations to the Galleria, a failed high-end shopping
center. They have pledged to funnel voter-approved preservation and
transportation taxes back to the city.
</P>
<P>
   The developers, which include Galleria owner Excel Legacy Corp.,
would pick up the rest of the project's estimated $1 billion tab.
</P>
<P>
   But they cannot use the theme park financing tool without
voters' approval because of wording in the legislation and the
city's charter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not increasing any taxes, it's changing how they are
used, and you need to go to a vote of the people to approve that,''
Unger said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Campana also wants to ask voters to approve a plan
for the McDowell-Sonoran Preserve that would use preserve tax
dollars to secure financing to protect the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale already has acquired 80 percent of the McDowell
Mountain foothills slated for preservation, using money from a
voter-approved 0.2 percent sales tax increase. But the city still
wants to purchase about 3,000 acres in undeveloped desert to add to
the preserve.
</P>
<P>
   Using expected revenue from the preserve tax to finance the
purchase of private property will allow the city to ``move more
quickly to acquire that,'' said Art Decabooter, chairman of the
McDowell Sonoran Preserve Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really smarter use of the dollars coming in . . . to have
the money available before the prices continue to inflate,'' he
said. &QL; 
Alexa Haussler can be reached at (602) 444-7481 or at
alexa.haussler(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
