<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9858 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      05-24 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COURAGE' IN SAME PIT AS `HERO' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is John F. Kennedy's daughter Caroline on the
``Today''show Monday morning talking to Katie Couric and
denigrating herself and the memory of her old man.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline and her brother, who used to be called John-John, are
on the show to promote the Profile in Courage Award presented each
year by their father's presidential library to politicians who
stick to their principles despite fierce opposition and even
danger.
</P>
<P>
   The award is 10 years old now, and Couric is asking Caroline in
a joking-but-not-quite way if the folks at the Kennedy library are
having a tough time finding politicians with real courage.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline laughs and flashes that famous Kennedy smile and says
that's what people told them when she and her brother began the
awards program.
</P>
<P>
   However, she says, they've found many, many bold and valorous
elected officials out there.
</P>
<P>
   After which I expect her to pause, then say, ``Just kiddin'!''
</P>
<P>
   But she doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   LEAP INTO ABYSS &QL; 
Caroline appears to believe what she is saying, teetering on the
edge of this quaintly naive opinion until she leaps into the abyss
of absurdity by announcing this year's winners:
</P>
<P>
   Sens. John McCain and Russell Feingold.
</P>
<P>
   The senators are being honored for sponsoring federal
legislation that would reform campaign finance laws by severely
restricting the money politicians collect, particularly the
unlimited ``soft money'' donations made to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   The bill didn't pass.
</P>
<P>
   Both senators were up for re-election last year. McCain faced a
political novice with no chance of unseating him in a heavily
Republican state like Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The risk he faced was zero.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even that didn't keep McCain from raising millions of
dollars in campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   He crisscrossed the country collecting cash for himself and
other candidates, thinking ahead to his current run at the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold, at least, had a well-financed, well-known opponent to
contend with, and he almost lost, mostly because he refused to
accept soft-money donations.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd rather lose than compromise his beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   On the ``Today'' show, John-John Kennedy said McCain's big risk
was going against the will of his party.
</P>
<P>
   (Another joke at which no one laughed.)
</P>
<P>
   For his presidential campaign, McCain has drawn to his camp the
kind of high-priced advisers whom conservative columnist Arianna
Huffington describes as ``fixtures in the Washington nexus of
lobbying, political action committees and soft money
contributions.'' &QL; 
TALKING THE TALK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These days, courageous means only talking the talk, not walking
the walk.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedys could have presented their award to someone who
displayed actual bravery, someone other than a couple of high-paid
dilettantes whose greatest danger was loss of parking privileges at
the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, McCain and Feingold could have turned down the award,
saying adherence to principles is the least we should expect of
people, not the most.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, everyone took the politically correct way out.
</P>
<P>
   And why not?
</P>
<P>
   It was only a matter of time before ``courage'' became as
meaningless a word as ``hero,'' which now defines everyone from
wealthy giants who play basketball to GIs who stumble into a Serb
ambush and get captured without firing a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Some years ago, John McCain was locked up in a place where
staunch adherence to principles could have cost him his life.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't waver.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough when the rest of us concoct phony definitions
for things like courage and heroism.
</P>
<P>
   It's different, and much sadder, when someone who's known for
the real thing, like McCain, goes along with us. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
