<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL PUTS THE `ME' INTO LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ L.A. is a nice place to clinch a Western
Conference Finals berth. But San Antonio forward Sean Elliott
wouldn't want to play here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of individualism, a lot of `Me,' '' Elliott said
after the Spurs' Western Conference semifinal series-clinching win
over the Lakers Sunday at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott was talking about the city, but he could have been
describing the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille ``I've got this team just the way I want it'' O'Neal.
Kobe ``I've never seen a double team I didn't think I could score
on'' Bryant. Glen ``I need plays called for me'' Rice. They're as
L.A. as oxygen bars, road rage and plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is the team captain, but for the second year in a row he
couldn't be bothered to attend the Lakers' morning-after team
meeting. Maybe he ran into a scheduling conflict with Billy Blanks'
Tae-Bo class and couldn't get from Sherman Oaks to Inglewood in
time.
</P>
<P>
   The players who did come to clear out their lockers Monday made
a big deal of saying it was no big deal that O'Neal was a no-show
at the last official team gathering. But of course. They're inured
to O'Neal's ways by now. They know that if they don't expect too
much from him, they might not be let down.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal ought to have been there, if only to say his so-longs to
players who've had his back who might not be  &UR; !ital! &LR; coming back.
Guys like Rice, J.R. Reid, Derek Fisher, Derek Harper, Rick Fox and
Ruben Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   They deserved a few nice parting words from their leader. But
who's going to explain that to Shaq? He pays people good money to
shield him from potentially unpleasant confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal refers to the Lakers as if it's just another one of his
possessions, like a seventh car or a second child. ``My guys played
hard,'' he said after the Lakers' 118-107 loss to the Spurs in
Sunday's deciding Game 4 of the Spurs' series.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' downfall this season, O'Neal said, was ``we never
learned to play together, play smart.''
</P>
<P>
   How keen of him to recognize it. Of course, that's the easy
part. The hard part is rectifying it.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott was right, it  &UR; !ital! &LR; is hard playing professional team
sports in L.A. (If it were easy, the city surely wouldn't be in the
midst of an 11-year championship drought.)
</P>
<P>
   Never mind all the deep tans and shallow mores, there's the
sheer geography of L.A. working against the teams. The city is so
spread out, it can swallow the players if they aren't careful. A
Laker could live in Pacific Palisades or Century City or Marina del
Rey or Manhattan Beach, practice in L.A. and play in Inglewood.
With that kind of spacing, a team's offense is bound to suffer. Its
defense, too.
</P>
<P>
   With players fanning out after practices and games, it's hard to
get tight. Show us players who car-pool to practice and share the
occasional meal afterward and we'll show you a team with
camaraderie and chemistry. There's nothing like a little bonding
off the court to bring players closer on it.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal wasn't seeing the cement for the sidewalk earlier this
season when he said, ``We don't have to go to the movies together,
eat dinner together and do all that. . . . When we're on the court
. . . everybody just has to do their part, period, whether we like
each other or not.''
</P>
<P>
   But had they done more things together, who knows? They just
might have found themselves growing fond of one another in spite of
themselves. It takes a bond to raise a championship banner. And
we're not talking about simply a shared wish and a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   But don't take our word for it. Listen to Lakers forward Robert
Horry, who was part of two NBA championships in Houston. Horry
said, ``The biggest thing in basketball is learning your fellow
man.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, wouldn't it be great to see O'Neal invite his
teammates _ whoever they end up being _ over to his crib for a
barbecue some day right after training camp breaks in the fall?
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be a step in the right direction if Bryant, instead
of shooting baskets for 90 minutes by himself after practice,
occasionally left the floor with his teammates and asked them if
they'd like to grab lunch, on him?
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers could win 34 of 57 games this year, imagine the
success they might have if they learned to really respect _ even
genuinely like _ one another. You don't need to imagine it. Just
look at San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys here are out for a common goal,'' Elliott said. ``Guys
aren't putting themselves first.''
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, so does this:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of talk about whose team this is,'' said Spurs
guard Mario Elie. ``It's our team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
