<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-REACT-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE ENDS NOT WITH A BANG, BUT A WHISPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-LOUIMA-VOLPE, NY-LOUIMA-ASSESS) 
(mk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sign of an end to a case alleging singular police
brutality came quietly late Monday afternoon, in a courtroom
whisper.
</P>
<P>
   But the whispers begot exclamations by nightfall, as many in the
city learned that Police Officer Justin Volpe planned to admit
Tuesday that he tortured a Haitian immigrant in a Brooklyn precinct
station house two summers ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and other city and police officials
declined to comment Monday night, saying that they would wait until
the burly officer officially entered his plea. And most of the
officers walking in and out of the 70th Precinct station house in
Brooklyn brushed aside questions about their colleague, whose
alleged brutality of Abner Louima had turned their workplace into a
symbol of the abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Brooklyn church where Louima worships, several
congregants spoke softly but firmly of justice done, and of their
hope that something good and lasting comes from the harm done to
their brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked for justice, we found justice,'' said Gastona
Morette, 48, who works as a cook in a nursing home. ``And now
everybody can enjoy it. This is not only for the Haitian people,
this is for all the people of New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Marvyn Kornberg, the usually voluble lawyer for Volpe,
who whispered the words that caused the evening ripples. At a
sidebar conference out of the earshot of courtroom spectators,
Kornberg told federal prosecutors and Judge Eugene Nickerson in
federal court in Brooklyn that his client ``would like to enter a
plea tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Although delivered in the formal language of the law, Kornberg's
words referred to a case of grotesque allegations, including that
Volpe had shoved a stick up Louima's rectum, rupturing vital
organs, while another officer held him down in a station house
bathroom. It attracted international attention, and transformed two
men into public figures: Louima, a black man so thin that the suits
he wore to the trial hung loose on his body, and Volpe, a white man
with the body of a weightlifter and the strut of a man who felt
wrongfully accused.
</P>
<P>
   After the sidebar conference, Kornberg and Volpe left the court
building and strode away under pallid skies, returning reporters'
questions with volleys of ``no comment.'' But minutes later, just
as those skies let loose a thunderous rain, the intentions of the
accused police officer became known.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Osborne, a video producer hurrying past Cadman Plaza
Park, savored both the shelter of his umbrella and the news. ``I
would have been surprised'' by a guilty plea three weeks ago, he
said, given the self-assuredness of Kornberg, who at that time was
suggesting that Louima, a heterosexual, had suffered his injuries
by having sex with another man on the night of his August 1997
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, several officers from the 70th Precinct have
provided devastating testimony against Volpe, he said, and the
officer's guilt became increasingly obvious. But Osborne, who is
black, said that he thinks Volpe was spurred to violence not by
racism but by a ferocious rage, tapped by a punch the officer
supposedly received outside a Brooklyn nightclub on the night of
the attack on Louima.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers are supposed to be trained for such encounters,
Osborne said. ``To somehow take it personally ...'' He did not
finish the thought.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Officer Rafael Collazo of the Latino Officers
Association finished the thought for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming this plea is made, it sends a strong statement that
the department may have officers who are possible loose cannons on
this job,'' Collazo said. ``The vast majority are good,
hard-working officers. But the fact that Volpe will admit to such a
heinous crime sends a message that the department should
re-evaluate problem officers on this job and do more to root them
out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton held a news conference Monday night at his
Harlem headquarters to praise the officers who testified against
Volpe _ ``They have given policing a good name in this city'' _ and
to decry what he called Kornberg's ``homophobic defense.'' He also
said: ``I'm very happy for Abner and his family.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was joy over the news at Louima's church, it was muted,
almost respectful. Congregants of the Evangelical Crusade of
Fishers of Men came Monday night to celebrate the church's 26th
anniversary, but several acknowledged that they had heard ``the
good news'' through radio and television reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not surprised,'' said Pastor Phillius Nicolas. ``We
believe in God, and we knew that no matter how they tried to hide
the truth, the truth would come out. And it came.''
</P>
<P>
   The pastor and others said that they felt vindicated by the
news, and they expressed hope that it would teach police a lesson
in respect. But Nicolas also said that the city's Haitians should
also draw a lesson from the story of Abner Louima. ``It should
teach people that no one is going to give you your rights,'' he
said. ``You have to claim them.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the congregation said that no portion of Monday
night's service would be set aside to celebrate the news. Instead,
they said, they would thank God in prayer and song.
</P>
</TEXT>
