<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY RAISES MONEY FOR CANDIDATE WHO MAY STEP ASIDE FOR HER
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Amid new indications that she is preparing to move to
New York to run for the United States Senate, Hillary Rodham
Clinton returned to Manhattan Monday night as the featured speaker
at a political fund-raiser for Representative Nita D. Lowey _ the
Westchester Democrat who is hoping that Mrs. Clinton does not run,
so that she can.
</P>
<P>
   Even for a year that is turning out to be one of the more
politically convoluted in recent New York history, Mrs. Clinton's
appearance at Mrs. Lowey's $1,000-a-head fund-raiser was an odd
event. The First Lady helped the 61-year-old Westchester Democrat
raise $1 million for a potential race for the Senate, a race that
Mrs. Lowey said she would forgo if Mrs. Clinton decided to seek the
seat herself. Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan is retiring at the
end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mrs. Lowey's aides acknowledge that it is increasingly
likely that Mrs. clinton will decide to run. The First Lady has
instructed representatives to begin looking for a home for her and
President Clinton in Westchester, according to a report that will
appear in The New York Times Magazine on Sunday. And Mrs. Clinton
told the CBS anchorman Dan Rather, in an interview scheduled to be
broadcast on ``60 Minutes II'' Wednesday night, that she planned
``to live in New York no matter what I end up doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, in the course of her remarks to a hotel ballroom
bustling with Democrats and television crews, did not allude to the
topic that had most of the tables buzzing. Instead, she offered an
effusive testimonial to Mrs. Lowey's record in Congress and never
once mentioned Mrs. Lowey's Senate ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Mrs. Lowey _ who has said she would run for a sixth
term in the House if Mrs. Clinton runs for the Senate _ made
humorous reference to their situation, and then noted the unusual
fact that it is state Republicans, rather than Democrats, who are
feuding these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the Republicans in this state turn their backs on one
another, I am proud to march forward shoulder to shoulder with my
friend, Hillary Rodham Clinton,'' Mrs. Lowey said. ``We are united
_ and we are confident that on Nov. 7, 2000, New York will elect
its first woman to the United States Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Mrs. Clinton's ninth visit to the state this year, and
inevitably reinforced a belief among Democrats here and in
Washington that in the end she will run for the seat that Mrs.
Lowey would like.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has told friends that she is likely to form an
exploratory committee _ it would be the first step toward running _
but has yet to make a final decision about actually running.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has said before that he and Mrs. Clinton, who
are expected to set up more than one residence after his term
expires, would like to live in New York. Mrs. Clinton's friends
told The Times Magazine that her representatives were looking at
potential locations in Westchester, raising the prospect that Mrs.
Clinton could have Mrs. Lowey as her congresswoman.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing places to live after the White House, the Clintons
are known to be considering both security and proximity to golf
courses, which is presumably what nudged Mrs. Clinton to look north
of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's itinerary Monday allowed her to attend to both
New York and national political concerns. She showed up at a book
party for Matilda Raffa Cuomo, the wife of Mario M. Cuomo, at Le
Cirque 2000. She attended an awards dinner sponsored by Americans
for the Arts at Lincoln Center, and she also appeared at a
closed-door fund-raiser for the Democratic Senate Campaign
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   At the fund-raiser for Mrs. Lowey, she praised the
representative's record on abortion rights and gun control, among
other issues. ``With Nita it is not about back-room deals or how
many special interests you can satisfy,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``It's
really about whether or not she can make a contribution to the
well-being of her constituents and her state and her country.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's press secretary, Marsha Berry, said that because
about half of what Mrs. Clinton did Monday was considered official
business, half the cost of the trip was billed to the White House
and the rest would be billed to the political committees that
benefited from her appearances.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons that Mrs. Clinton is moving to forming an
exploratory committee is that she has come under increasing
criticism for making trips to New York at White House expense; an
exploratory committee would allow her to raise money to finance the
trips.
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Lowey was at all annoyed about how Mrs. Clinton's
political ambitions were overcoming her own, she and her aides did
not show it last night.
</P>
<P>
   The representative matched Mrs. Clinton, compliment for
compliment. Her press secretary, Howard Wolfson, smiled gamely when
he learned that the First Lady might be house-shopping in his boss'
district
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be absolutely delighted to welcome the First Lady to
Westchester,'' Wolfson said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
